<SLUG> BC-BKW-ROBERTSON-COLUMN </SLUG>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
In face of real adversity, Cooper comes through like a champion
<TEXT>
<P>
   By DALE ROBERTSON
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   Never underestimate the heart of a champion. Even the broken
heart of a champion.
</P>
<P>
   The Comets haven't fully come to grips with Kim Perrot's death
from cancer last week. They're still hurting, and none more so than
Perrot's best friend, Cynthia Cooper. But Cooper, showing herself
to be the consummate professional, put her grief on hold Sunday
afternoon and let hoops set her free.
</P>
<P>
   Temporarily anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I prayed, and I prayed, and I prayed,'' Cooper said. ``I'm
still not out of the woods yet, but I felt more like my old self
today.''
</P>
<P>
   In an 83-55 season-saving Comets rout, Coop scored 22 points, 12
coming on timely 4-of-7 shooting from 3-point range. She handed out
nine assists and was ferocious on defense, too, perhaps more
ferocious than she had been all year. If this wasn't the game of
her remarkable, late-blooming career, it came close, certainly
graded on the curve these bizarre and tragic circumstances merited.
</P>
<P>
   ``That it happened when it did was hard for us,'' Cooper said of
Perrot's death. ``If it had occurred even a month ago, maybe we
wouldn't be having this conversation. But it's on everyone's minds,
and you can't just block it out because you have a big game.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, as the two-time Most Valuable Player of the WNBA,
Coop feels a strong sense of duty and obligation to her team. She
must lead the Comets by example. Showing sadness, however honest
and obviously heartfelt the sentiment might be, is a bad example
during the money season.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, she had to find her way out of that deep, deep funk she
was in Thursday night, when her shots wouldn't drop and the Comets
would be hammered by the Sparks in Los Angeles. The ugly,
uncharacteristically tepid if not altogether unexpected defeat _
75-60 _ left the only champions the WNBA has known confronting the
reality of a possible early elimination.
</P>
<P>
   Coop's faith has been sorely tested by the events of the last
year. First, it was her mother who died. Now Kim. But prayer is how
she bolsters her resolve, and this was no time to change a winning
game plan.
</P>
<P>
   When morning broke, she did not fear in the least for the
Comets' future, and that was good. Coop's positive vibes filled the
locker room beforehand and then spilled out onto the court.
</P>
<P>
   Houston's rowdy fans took care of the rest. By tip-off, the
Comets' karma was intact. As coach Van Chancellor said, ``I could
tell we were a different team. I thought were were ready to play,
and we were.''
</P>
<P>
   None more so than Cooper. Although she missed two of her first
three shots _ the Comets started 1-for-10 _ there would be no
residual damage. Coop swished two treys to pull the Comets even at
11, and they wouldn't trail again. A six-point lead at halftime had
ballooned to 19 less than 10 minutes into the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kim wouldn't have been pleased with the way I played Thursday
night,'' Cooper said. ``I was emotionally spent, and honestly, I
let my team down. So it was really important for me to refocus, to
play the kind of ball I know I'm capable of playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like I'm going to suddenly stop thinking about my
mother or Kim. I'm not. Their deaths will stay with me for a long,
long time. But when you have a job to do ''
</P>
<P>
   Another beckons tonight. Sunday was about surviving, and so is
Game 3. The only difference is Los Angeles must confront the same
all-or-nothing scenario.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, we'll see how they can handle some adversity,'' Cooper
said. ``But I think we'll have to play an even better game
ourselves. It's going to be pretty intense, because everybody's
backs are against the wall.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for Houston, the wall helps hold up the Compaq
Center roof. The Sparks have never won here, and the Comets have
lost but twice at home over the past two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our fans don't just support this team,'' Chancellor said.
``They love this team. Believe me, they do help us.''
</P>
<P>
   When you are as fatigued as the Comets must be, any extra source
of energy is a boon. Since a week ago Thursday, they have traveled
to LA twice, Sacramento and Lafayette, La., where Perrot's private
funeral was. They have played four games while having to bury a
special teammate, a spunky woman who was quarterbacking their
offense and inspiring their defense one year ago.
</P>
<P>
   That's a lot to ask.
</P>
<P>
   Had the Comets rolled over Sunday, they would have been
deserving of our affection and sympathy just the same. Instead,
following Cooper's lead, the point became moot. They reduced the
Sparks to mere embers in short order. Hence, anybody dumb enough to
believe women are the inherently weaker sex is not paying
attention.
</P>
<P>
   If you are out there, I would love to introduce you to Cynthia
Cooper and her friends. They are amazing people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
