<SLUG> BC-TEN-HAMLET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORMAN SHOWS HE CAN ALSO WIN ON HARD   COURTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JENNY KELLNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   COMMACK, N.Y. _ Down a break in the third set of his Hamlet Cup
semifinal against Jason Stoltenberg on Saturday night, Magnus
Norman faced two possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   If he came back to win, he would face second-seeded Alex
Corretja in just over 12 hours in his first career hard courts
final. If he lost, he would get to pack up his things, travel to
Manhattan and hook up with his fellow Swedish tennis players at the
Roger Smith Hotel for a party before the U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   The party waited.
</P>
<P>
   Norman came back to defeat Stoltenberg, and Sunday, on a hot and
breezy afternoon, he won his fourth title this year _ tying him
with Pete Sampras for the ATP tour lead _ with a 7-6 (7-4), 4-6,
6-3 upset of Corretja. The first three titles came on clay in
Orlando, Fla., Stuttgart, Germany, and Umag, Croatia.
</P>
<P>
   ``You say, `Pete Sampras and Magnus Norman _ who's Magnus
Norman?''' the 6-foot-2-inch right-hander said with a laugh. ``I
don't know if I deserve to be up there. I know I have won four
titles, but I haven't won Wimbledon.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hamlet Cup victory did continue a rather extraordinary
streak that began after Wimbledon: Norman has won 22 of his last 26
matches. Norman, who is expected to move to No. 26 from 34 when the
new ranking is released Monday, credited his new coach, Fredrik
Rosengren, with whom he has been working since January, for the
turnaround in his game.
</P>
<P>
   ``This summer I had been so negative _ I said I don't want to
play in two hard court tournaments before the Open because I am no
good on hard courts,'' said Norman, who made it to the third round
in Indianapolis last week. ``He made me realize I could do it. This
is the biggest week for us as a team because we've been working
very hard on my hard court game.''
</P>
<P>
   That was obvious against the Spaniard Corretja, whose hard court
performance has also improved substantially over the last few
years. In the first set, with both players' serves plagued by
swirling winds, Norman squeaked by in the tiebreaker, going up by
4-1 when Corretja double-faulted and then sent an easy backhand
sailing past the baseline.
</P>
<P>
   After falling into Corretja's rhythm of long baseline rallies in
the second set, Norman went on the attack in the third. Rushing the
net repeatedly, he got the break in the sixth game. At deuce, he
sent a backhand sizzling down the line, and he then laced a volley
crosscourt to go up by 4-2.
</P>
<P>
   A pumped-up Norman served out the match at love, letting out a
whoop of delight when Corretja's backhand return floated wide.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end, he played much more aggressive and hit harder,''
Corretja said. ``He deserved to win at the end because he was going
for the points and I was sitting back, waiting.''
</P>
<P>
   Corretja said he felt confident heading into his first-round
match at the Open against the left-handed Australian Wayne Arthurs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was good to play five matches _ it helped my confidence,''
Corretja said. ``I did not play my best tennis today, but now I
will rest and prepare myself for the Open. If I am mentally strong
and ready to go I think I can do well.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman, whose confidence was bolstered even more by beating a
top player Sunday, was also looking forward to the Open, where he
will face No. 17-seeded Felix Mantilla of Spain in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to keep my game going for the next few weeks,'' said
Norman, who earned $46,000 for the victory. ``I am not going to be
satisfied with this _ I have more goals. The guys who play me in
the Open know they're going to have to play well.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
