<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-INJURY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIANTS STARTING CENTER MAY MISS THE SEASON OPENER
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tests Sunday on the knee injury of Giants center Brian Williams
in Saturday night's loss to the Jets provided the team with better
news than expected, but the valuable, veteran lineman may still
miss the regular-season opener Sept. 12 at Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Based on a doctor's preliminary examination after the game, the
Giants had been preparing to play without Williams for a month.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Jim Fassel of the Giants said that there was no timetable
for Williams' return, but he acknowledged that an early
interpretation of a magnetic resonance imaging test on Williams'
left knee indicated there was no damage to ligaments and that the
injury should not require a lengthy recovery.
</P>
<P>
   But even if Williams missed the team's first game, it could be a
significant absence for the Giants, who also lost their backup
center, Lance Scott, to a knee injury in practice last week.
</P>
<P>
   When Williams left the field early in the second quarter of the
16-10 loss, the effect on the team was chilling.
</P>
<P>
   It did not carry the devastation familiar from a year ago
against the Jets, when Giants cornerback Jason Sehorn limped off.
It took only minutes last August to understand that Sehorn was out
for the season, and indeed he has yet to return.
</P>
<P>
   But with Williams on the sideline, the Giants' offense, so
poised and potent in the two previous preseason games, immediately
played as if panicked and powerless. It is not called the center
position without reason. Without Williams, the Giants looked
rudderless.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, the notion that Williams could miss any time
during the regular season distressed an already disheartened locker
room.
</P>
<P>
   The mood in the locker room may be a bit brighter when the team
reconvenes Monday morning. Fassel was cautious, if optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are waiting for another opinion,'' said Fassel, adding that
Dr. Russell Warren, the team surgeon, had not examined the test
results. ``We aren't saying anything definitive. But the people who
have looked at this so far feel like it'd be a short-term thing.''
</P>
<P>
   After Saturday's game, Fassel said that there was no structural
damage to the knee but suggested there might be a cartilage
problem.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear how the injury was sustained.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who returned to the Giants after missing two years
with an eye injury, has had a dramatic impact on the Giants'
quality of play this year.
</P>
<P>
   He is the team's most senior player in terms of time of service
(11 years) and age (33). His leadership has been plainly evident on
what was the National Football League's youngest team the past two
seasons. His ability to elevate the line's pass protection skills
and his ability to get the line to play more cohesively _ the most
important component of good line play _ has been one of the more
impressive stories of the Giants' preseason.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who was considered one of the best centers in the NFL
before his eye injury, has also implored the offense to play
tougher and with more confidence, something notably missing in
recent seasons. The dropoff in the Giants' production _ as well as
the team's equilibrium in the face of a blitzing opponent _ was
obvious when Williams left Saturday's game.
</P>
<P>
   The effect of Williams' absence was exacerbated by Scott's
injury. Scott, who tore a knee ligament last week, had been the
starting center for most of the past two years. He had shifted to
left guard since Williams' return, but figured to be a highly
experienced backup at center.
</P>
<P>
   The center duties on Saturday instead fell to Derek Engler, a
third-year player. Engler, 25, is a valued reserve who played
capably as a rookie starter in 1997 until he broke his ankle. Since
then, Engler has not started a game. He could easily play well for
Williams, but he has big shoes to fill, especially because Williams
had created such a comfort level for the line.
</P>
<P>
   And should Williams miss any extended time, it could stunt the
development of rookie Luke Petitgout, who is starting at left guard
because Scott is out.
</P>
<P>
   Petitgout would normally be lining up shoulder to shoulder with
Williams, who could counsel the rookie on line calls and other
decisions. Naturally, it never hurts a rookie to be playing between
two seasoned linemen like Williams and left tackle Roman Oben.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
