<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Monday, Aug. 30. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABORTION (Phoenix) _ The Arizona Supreme Court on Sunday cleared
the way for a 14-year-old girl to fly toKansas for a late-term
abortion by overturning a state appeals judge's ruling that had
temporarily blocked it. Arizona Gov. Jane Hull and other state
officials declined comment, but law experts say state appeals may
be exhausted. Late Sunday, it was unclear when the 14-year-old ward
of the state would leave for Kansas, where abortion laws are more
liberal, or whether she was already there. Story by CHRISTINA
LEONARD and JANELLE COWGILL. Story will move in the ``A'' category.
</P>
<P>
   ROBINSON (Phoenix) _ Ken Robinson, a career minor leaguer but
someone who had a future with the expansion of the Arizona
Diamondbacks, died this past spring training in an auto accident in
Tucson. Five months later, his widow in Jacksonville, Fla., tells
The Republic how she has coped with the loss of Ken, who was a hero
to a lot of people. By KENT SOMERS. Story will move in the ``A''
category.
</P>
<P>
   TV-GOODY (Undated) _ Combine a Kathie Lee-less Regis Philbin, a
reworking of a British game show and the third-place network in the
dead of summer television and what do you get? A ratings monster. A
return to the nostalgic days when game shows fared well in prime
time. Or further proof that people will watch just about anything
you put in front of them in August. Depends upon your point of
view. Whatever your answer, look for Who Wants To Be a Millionaire
to return. By BILL GOODYKOONTZ. Story will move in the ``E''
category.
</P>
<P>
   NEW&AMP;NOTABLE (undated) _ Anne Stephenson's capsule book reviews.
By ANNE STEPHENSON. Story will move in the ``E'' category. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
