<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 00:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3897 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-METS-DIAMONDBACKS-NYT     08-30 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-METS-DIAMONDBACKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POOR PITCHING AND SLOPPY FIELDING UNDO THE METS IN LOSS TO
DIAMONDBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Mets pitcher Al Leiter fidgets so much and so
routinely on the mound _ adjusting his cap, swiping the dirt in
front of the pitching rubber with his right foot, tugging on the
belt of his pants, rubbing the ball furiously _ that it is hard to
tell sometimes if he is distressed by something that is happening
in the game or if he even realizes what he is doing.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason for Leiter's mannerisms, it's safe to assume
he wasn't thrilled with his role in what amounted to a pitchers'
duel in reverse Sunday night. This game evolved as if he and
Arizona's starter, Andy Benes, went 20 paces and then fired water
pistols at each other. Their aim wasn't great then, either.
</P>
<P>
   In a game as ugly as a mosh pit, that included poor pitching
(the teams used nine pitchers, and the Mets relievers gave up two
runs) and erratic fielding, the Diamondbacks outlasted the Mets,
8-4, to win 2 of 3 from a potential playoff opponent.
</P>
<P>
   The loss dropped the Mets 3 1/2 games behind the National League
East-leading Atlanta Braves, who beat St. Louis, 4-3.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter and Benes each struggled with his control from the first
batters he faced. But Benes, who allowed a leadoff single to Rickey
Henderson, never settled down after escaping the first inning
without a run.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter did. He gave up four runs in an abysmal first inning in
which it seemed he would never retire a batter. He walked the first
two batters he faced, gave up a double that dropped between
Henderson and center fielder Darryl Hamilton in left center when it
appeared Hamilton called for the ball, then backed away at the last
moment.
</P>
<P>
   That allowed the first run to score. Then Matt Williams laced a
first-pitch double down the left-field line that bounced against a
pole at the bullpen fence and rolled away from Henderson to give
Arizona a 3-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   A Greg Colbrunn comebacker rolled to the right of the mound and
Leiter threw wildly to John Olerud, allowing Williams to advance to
third. Bernard Gilkey then flied out to almost exactly the same
spot as Luis Gonzalez's fly ball, scoring Williams for the fourth
run of the inning. Leiter was wiping his foot in front of the
rubber so furiously every time he had the ball that a trough was
probably forming.
</P>
<P>
   As terrible as Leiter's start was, Benes was almost worst. When
he threw strikes, the Mets hit them or had worked Benes deep into
the count. The Mets scored three runs in the second, led off when
Roger Cedeno singled and moved to second on Todd Pratt's groundout.
He scored when Rey Ordonez, who has been hot at the plate on this
road trip, sent a single up the middle.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter sacrificed Ordonez to second and he scored when Henderson
got his second single of the night to make the score 4-2. Henderson
stole second and came home for the third run when Edgardo Alfonzo's
double drove him in and the Mets trailed by 4-3.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks and Mets each added another run and then, just
as the fans were reaching for their pillows and blankets to settle
in for a long night, the teams stopped scoring. Benes was gone
after the fourth, having thrown 103 pitches and allowing nine hits.
Leiter forged on a bit longer and his sixth inning was his finest.
He struck out two and got Tony Womack to fly out.
</P>
<P>
   But Bobby Valentine's gamble to leave his ace in for the seventh
backfired. He began the inning with 102 pitches and, after getting
Jay Bell to fly out, Gonzalez hit an 0-1 pitch over the right-field
wall. It was Leiter's 110th pitch and his last. He left with the
the Mets behind by 6-4 after allowing six runs on seven hits and
walking six.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter has been a vastly improved pitcher since he beat the
Yankees at Yankee Stadium on the day after three Mets coaches were
fired in June, but this outing was one of his worst of the season.
It dropped him to 10-9, and was reminiscent of how he pitched in
the first two months, when he struggled in almost every outing got
just two victories in his first 10 starts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
