<HEADLINE>
YANKEES SWEEP MARINERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Yes, the New York Yankees have a good team. They are
31 games over .500, they've won two of the last three World Series
and there's little they don't do well.
</P>
<P>
   Mariners manager Lou Piniella did not think it necessary to
expand on that Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really want to talk about their pitching, their
hitting, their defense, their speed,'' said Piniella, after the
Yankees stomped the M's, 11-5, to complete a three-game sweep at
Yankee Stadium. ``I have no interest in talking about it _ none,
zero, zilch, nada, nil, you can name it in whatever language you
want.
</P>
<P>
   ``That team beats you seven games in a row, it gets a little
frustrating, too. It's not much fun to sit there and be on the
other side of it.''
</P>
<P>
   It did not look like much fun for Piniella, who was ejected from
the finale of the Yankees' four-game sweep three weeks ago at
Safeco Field. He stuck this one out, enduring a gruesome afternoon
in which the Mariners made three errors, allowed an inside-the-park
home run, a bases-loaded walk and leadoff base runners in five of
the past six innings.
</P>
<P>
   The manager's only notable on-field appearance came in the
sixth, when Todd Williams, brought in to keep the Mariners' deficit
at 6-4, walked leadoff hitter Joe Girardi and fell behind the next
hitter, Chuck Knoblauch. Piniella came to the mound _ with a brief,
emphatic message for Williams _ then returned to the dugout to
watch an embarrassing play unfold.
</P>
<P>
   The lumbering Girardi broke for second, apparently on a missed
hit-and-run. Catcher Dan Wilson's throw bounced off shortstop Alex
Rodriguez for an error, and by the time Rafael Bournigal recovered
it, he was in short right field. Girardi faked toward home, and
while Bournigal said he knew Girardi wasn't running, he felt he had
to throw home in case he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he decides to go, and I hesitate, then I might have a
problem throwing him out from that far away,'' Bournigal said.
</P>
<P>
   The throw hit the cutout where the grass meets the dirt in front
of the plate, skidded past Wilson, and with Williams backing up
third and not home, Girardi scored easily to give the Yankees a 7-4
lead.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Sinclair came in, walked Paul O'Neill, and surrendered a
two-run homer to Bernie Williams that made it 9-4 New York.
</P>
<P>
   It said something that Piniella praised the next reliever, Tom
Davey, who gave up two runs on three hits and a hit batsman but
issued no walks.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got hit a little bit, but that's OK, I don't mind that,''
Piniella said. ``But Williams walked (one), Sinclair walked (two) _
you can't get it done up here like that. Especially against a good
team like the Yankees, they're going to take advantage of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Piniella was asked if that's part of the learning process for a
staff that came into this series with six rookies among its 12
pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know about the learning process,'' Piniella said.
``What it shows you is we're outmanned, plain and simple. If
there's a lesson to be derived, it's that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners finished their season series with the Yankees with
one win in 10 games. The M's have won only eight of 29 games
against the American League's first place teams.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees not only exploited the struggling Mariner hitters,
they also shut down Ken Griffey Jr., Rodriguez and Edgar Martinez,
who have been hitting well. The Mariners' 3-4-5 hitters batted .194
in this series (6-for-31), with no runs batted in.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to point at anybody, because I look in the mirror
and I haven't gotten the job done,'' said Rodriguez. ``You can't
make mistakes over and over again and try to beat this team. You
have to play flawless baseball to compete. The effort was there, we
just didn't get the job done. They really put it to us this year.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners led, 2-0, doubling their run total from the series'
first two games on Wilson's two-out, two-run double in the second
inning. It was the Mariners' first hit this series with runners in
scoring position, and gave Paul Abbott a lead.
</P>
<P>
   But Abbott was not sharp. He allowed three consecutive singles
to start the third, the last one bringing in a run. O'Neill then
slapped a grounder to third, but Russ Davis, shifting to get in
position for a would-be third-to-first double play, couldn't field
the ball. It went for an error and brought in a run, and the
Yankees took a 3-2 lead when Abbott walked Ricky Ledee with the
bases loaded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just got behind hitters, and I had to make pitches that you
don't want to make,'' said Abbott (5-1). ``I just gave them too
many looks at too many pitches, and they're way too good a team to
do that to.''
</P>
<P>
   For Abbott, the final blow came in the fifth, again with Ledee
hitting. With two outs and a runner at first, Ledee crushed a pitch
deep to center. Griffey gave chase, leaped and missed _ ``Once it
hit the wall, I didn't see the ball,'' he said _ and Ledee circled
the bases for a stand-up inside-the-park homer.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first inside-the-park homer at Yankee Stadium since
Deion Sanders did it against the Kansas City Royals _ beating
fellow two-sport star Bo Jackson's throw to the plate _ in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Tyler Kepner can be reached at 206-448-8004
</P>
<P>
   or tylerkepner &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
