<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-NOTEBOOK-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIT-STARVED IBANEZ HUNGRY FOR SOLUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Raul Ibanez's first hit after the All-Star break was
a grand slam, so maybe he had nowhere else to go.
</P>
<P>
   But Ibanez never thought the second half would continue as it
has. The Mariners outfielder/first baseman, who was hitting .333 at
the break, has just 11 hits in 68 at-bats since, for a .162
average.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to helping the team more than I have,''
Ibanez said. ``I've struggled this whole second half, but I think
I've found something.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Saturday's game, hitting coach Jesse Barfield worked with
Ibanez on staying closed in his stance, and the adjustment worked
immediately. In his first at-bat, Ibanez homered off the New York
Yankees' Orlando Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're searching and searching and searching, and then when
you find something, it's like you've learned to hit all over
again,'' Ibanez said. ``We all know what we're doing wrong, but the
thing is, how do you stop it? You have to be able to execute.''
</P>
<P>
   Ibanez was hitless in his last two at-bats Saturday, and popped
up with the bases loaded Sunday as a pinch hitter against Yankees
closer Mariano Rivera, ending the inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a quick hip going right now, and from a hitting
standpoint, that's suicide,'' said Barfield, adding that Ibanez has
struggled with outside pitches. ``He understands that, and he's
working hard to alleviate it. If it's all up to work ethic, he's
got a great chance, because he works extremely hard and he's
confident.''
</P>
<P>
   Ibanez still has a month to raise his stock as the Mariners
prepare for the offseason. The 27-year-old could figure in at a
number of positions that might be available next year, including
first base, left and right field. He has made 16 starts since the
All-Star break _ after making just 10 starts the whole first half _
and that has been an adjustment.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're pinch hitting, you just have one at-bat, and it's
a tough thing to do,'' he said. ``But your level of concentration
only has to be intense for one at-bat, just a few pitches. When
you're playing more, you have to readjust and spread out your focus
to more at-bats. But it's way better to play more than pinch hit.''
</P>
<P>
   As for his chances of playing his way into next year's lineup,
Ibanez said he's narrowed his concerns to the Mariners' wild-card
pursuit. And there is opportunity to correct his own troubles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that there's time left to turn everything around,'' he
said. ``I'm very confident that I'll be able to. I know I'm a
better hitter than I've been, so I'm not really worried about it.''
</P>
<P>
   BLOWERS SIGNED: The Mariners signed 34-year-old Mike Blowers to
a minor league contract over the weekend. Blowers made his debut
for Class AAA Tacoma Saturday, starting at first base and going
0-for-4.
</P>
<P>
   The UW product, who hit .251 with 10 homers and 43 runs batted
in this year for the Hanshin Tigers of Japan's Central League,
batted .237 for Oakland last year and .293 for the '97 Mariners.
The M's have used seven first basemen since trading David Segui
last month and are expected to make Blowers the eighth sometime in
September.
</P>
<P>
   EXTRA BASES: Because they used three relievers Sunday, the
Mariners will send down a pitcher and promote right-hander Ken
Cloude to start the second game of today's doubleheader in Chicago.
... With the offense sagging, manager Lou Piniella rearranged his
lineup Sunday, putting Russ Davis in the leadoff spot. The last
time Davis batted there? ``Probably Little League,'' Davis said. He
had batted no higher than sixth this season. ... David Bell's home
run in the fifth inning was his second since June 12. ... When Paul
Abbott walked Ricky Ledee to force in a run in the third inning, it
was the Mariners' 24th bases-loaded walk of the year, the most in
the majors. ... Yankees third baseman Scott Brosius left the team
to travel to Oregon to be with his cancer-stricken father ...
Players from Little League World Series finalists Osaka, Japan, and
Phenix City, Ala., were honored before the game.
</P>
</TEXT>
