<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-FOLEY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEAHAWKS WIN SPELLS RELIEF FOR FOLEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIRKLAND, Wash. _ It might have been only a second-half stint in
a preseason game, and a short one at that, but the importance of
his performance was not lost on Glenn Foley.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was pressure on me tonight _ pressure like I hadn't felt
in over a year,'' Foley said after the Seahawks' 41-7 romp over the
Arizona Cardinals at the Kingdome on Saturday night. ``But I've
always played pretty well under pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   Foley completed only 4 of 5 passes, but two went for touchdowns
as he directed the Seahawks' second-string offense to three TDs in
his three series.
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly numbers that will get him into Canton any time soon,
but the necessary effort to keep him in Kirkland.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure Foley spoke of, and had worn like a hair shirt for
the past two weeks, was self-generated. The Seahawks had worked a
trade in March with the New York Jets to obtain Foley as insurance
because Jon Kitna was still untested and about to test drive the
complex offense of new coach Mike Holmgren.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Foley's play has made him look more like a liability.
</P>
<P>
   In the preseason opener, he threw two interceptions and lost a
fumble to set up 21 Buffalo points in an embarrassing 24-10 loss to
the Bills. On the training-camp practice fields in Cheney, Foley
further tested Holmgren's already fiber-optic-thin patience by not
playing well and not seeming to be affected by it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was happy for Glenn, because he really didn't play up to his
expectations or mine in the first game,'' Holmgren said Sunday,
before reviewing the videotape of his first victory as coach of the
Seahawks. ``(Saturday) night, he was better. Clearly better.''
</P>
<P>
   Redemption was a long time coming for Foley. He did not play in
the second preseason game at San Francisco. He spent the 14 days
between stints watching and learning, but also wondering.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was frustrating because I didn't get to play in the second
game. So it was a long two weeks for me _ the longest two weeks of
my life,'' he said. ``Playing as poorly as I did in the first game,
I was itching to get back. But I just waited my turn and got two
more weeks of what the offense is all about, what it's like on game
day, after watching Jon and Brock (Huard, the No. 3 quarterback) do
it for a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that helped me a lot,'' he said. ``But I put a lot of
pressure on myself this week to show everybody what I could do.''
</P>
<P>
   Foley was not without his foils and his friends Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   His second TD pass _ a 15-yarder to fullback Oscar Gray _ was on
the same play he threw for one his interceptions against the Bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time he did kind of what I asked him to do,'' Holmgren
said. ``I said, `See, it works.' So I can teach to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Foley's first TD pass _ a 23-yarder to Michael Jackson _ came
with an emotional and physical lift from the veteran wide receiver.
</P>
<P>
   ``Glenn needed this game. We talked about that in the huddle
before the play because there was a TV timeout,'' Jackson said. ``I
told Foley, `Just put air under it and I'll find a way of getting
it somehow.' He was feeling pressure, so I told him, `Give me a
little of it. Let's share it. My shoulders are broad enough.'''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson used those broad shoulders, not to mention his long arms
and route-running savvy, to make a nice adjustment on the pass,
twisting from right to left and taking it over his shoulder behind
the Cardinals' rookie cornerback Coby Rhinehart.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great throw by Glenn,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great catch by Mike,'' Foley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was pressure there for Glenn, we all knew it,''
offensive tackle Grant Williams said. ``But he stepped up like a
champ. He was more lively and having fun in the huddle.''
</P>
<P>
   And, for the first time in two weeks, able to smile about
something he had done on the field.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
