<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONG SEASON FOR COLLINS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A person would have to be pretty heartless to not empathize with
Terry Collins.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine spending every moment of your life trying to fix all
that is wrong with the Anaheim Angels, investing every ounce of
your energy into this impossible task because you don't know how to
do it any other way.
</P>
<P>
   Some Angels players may shrug off loses, but Collins can't. He
doesn't know how.
</P>
<P>
   Some Angels may snipe at their manager behind his back, but he
can't let that get in the way of who he plays. That's a luxury for
the few managers with job security.
</P>
<P>
   Some fans may say the Angels are cursed, but he can't indulge in
potions or bad karma.
</P>
<P>
   So Terry Collins resides in his own personal dungeon, a lonely
place where the frustration never ebbs for long.
</P>
<P>
   Before heading to Boston and three losses to the Red Sox,
Collins sat in his claustrophobic office at Anaheim Stadium and
tried to find different ways to answer questions that have lost
their meaning.
</P>
<P>
   Part of this personal hell is to be reminded every day that all
is lost. ``You can't keep talking about,'' said Collins. ``There's
only so many ways you can be negative. It gets old.''
</P>
<P>
   Cam he at least go home and talk out his frustrations? ``There's
no one there to talk to,'' said Collins, who has no wife, no
roommate, no pets.
</P>
<P>
   Friends? Long walks on the beach? Books? Relaxation tapes?
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, I'll go to a movie, or go out to dinner,'' said
Collins. But the frustrations usually return before he digests his
dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is part of the business, part of the game,'' he said.
``There are good times, and there are crappy times, and we're in
the middle of a crappy time. But if you can't deal with it, you
shouldn't be here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not the kind of person (who can just tune it out). I'm
always thinking about the next game. Baseball can be a grind on the
major-league level. You play 162 games, and you're expected to play
162 games hard. When the season's over, you can leave it, but not
until it's over.''
</P>
<P>
   There is ample evidence that many Angels metaphorically ended
their seasons in July. The Angels were on a modest 12-7 run before
the All-Star break and, despite being under .500, were only 6{
games behind the Texas Rangers in the A.L. West.
</P>
<P>
   They won their first game back, then promptly fell off the
planet. They lost 11 straight games, the biggest chunk of a hideous
4-23 run. Since July 16, the Angels are a feckless 9-33.
</P>
<P>
   With just 51 wins (only Detroit and Florida have fewer), the
Angels are on pace to eclipse franchise lows set by the 1980 team -
just 65 wins, a .406 winning percentage, and 30 games under .500.
</P>
<P>
   This will likely be the 11th Angels team in 38 years to finish
20 games or more under .500 and six of the last seven precipitated
managerial changes, either at midseason or the following year.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not Collins suffers the same fate as Bobby Winkles,
John McNamara, Buck Rodgers and Marcel Lacheman remains to be seen.
Disney Sports extended his contract, but it was that subject which
sent the clubhouse into hysterics and the team on its descent.
</P>
<P>
   A case can be built against Collins. He's intense and projects
nervous energy, which can be a real negative in the dugout. He
wants his players to hustle in a nonchalant era of baseball. He
shares some
</P>
<P>
   micro-managing bad habits with other managers, and one has to
search the data base hard to remember a game he's won through
managerial skill. His recent decisions to use closer Troy Percival
in the eighth inning are examples of a manager lunging for answers.
</P>
<P>
   But Collins doesn't deserve the resentment he receives from many
players. He may not be a great manager, but this is his first
losing season on any level since 1986.
</P>
<P>
   How different might things have been in 1997 if Tony Phillips
isn't busted? How different might things have been last year if
Bill Bavasi deals for a much-needed pitcher down the stretch? The
Angels led the A.L. West as September began.
</P>
<P>
   How different would 1999 have been if Mo Vaughn doesn't hurt
himself in the top of the first inning of the
</P>
<P>
   season's first game?
</P>
<P>
   One really needs a tour of the Angels clubhouse to understand
why a critic might side with Collins.
</P>
<P>
   Disney's refurbishment of the stadium included a gorgeous new
clubhouse that is spacious and well-appointed: Two massive big
screen TVs, a deluxe CD system, and subdued lighting like that of a
posh hotel bar.
</P>
<P>
   But no one is ever there. Seriously. You can find a few players
watching other sports events before or after games, but there is no
camaraderie. Many players hide out in the player-only dining lounge
or trainer's room. And when you do see players in the clubhouse,
they are often gathered in little cliques and whispering among
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   If I'm Tony Tavares, the president of Disney Sports who OK'd a
lush locker room despite believing ballplayers are spoiled, I close
the private lounge, rip out the carpet and track lighting, and put
in some nuclear illumination.
</P>
<P>
   Collins meets his fate daily in his little office with the 200
watt lights, and then takes it home with him, which is more than
one can say for the players. At the very least, you wish his misery
had more company.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-99 0029EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
