<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 00:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3903 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-HURRICANE-RDP-2NDLD-W     08-30 1161
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-RDP-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM CAROLINAS TO NEW YORK, STORM'S SHADOW PRECEDES IT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: Updates throughout   with storm moving further out to sea.) (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Map is being
sent to NYT graphics clients. Non-subscribers may make individual
purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By ANDY NEWMAN and EMILY YELLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The fringes of Hurricane Dennis began lashing the Carolina coast
with gusts and rain Sunday, prompting the pre-emptive evacuation of
more than 30,000 vacationers and residents from North Carolina's
barrier islands and forcing swimmers out of the water as far north
as Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night the storm began turning east, away from land, when
it was still 150 miles off Wilmington, N.C. And forecasters did not
expect the center of the storm, with its 105-mile-an-hour winds, to
get within 75 miles of the coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like the hurricane-force winds are going to remain
offshore,'' Tom Addington, a spokesman for the National Weather
Service in Wilmington, said at 10:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   But winds of 60 miles an hour were predicted for the coast
overnight, accompanied by tides several feet above normal. Up to
five inches of rain is expected to fall on the Carolinas Monday.
And a hurricane warning remained in effect for the North Carolina
coast from the South Carolina state line to Oregon Inlet, near Nags
Head.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina's governor, James B. Hunt Jr., bracing for the
worst, declared both a state of emergency and a state of disaster
Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Further north, Virginia Beach and two beaches on Long Island's
South Shore closed to swimmers, and more rescues of swimmers than
usual were reported in rough waters off Ocean City, Md. A tropical
storm warning extended from Oregon Inlet north to Chincoteague,
Va., and south as far as Savannah, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Because of possible storm surges, which can cause flooding and
block roads, more than 20,000 people were evacuated from Ocracoke
and Hatteras, the delicate barrier islands of the Outer Banks north
of Wilmington. Closer to Wilmington, more than 10,000 people were
evacuated from Carolina Beach, Wrightsville Beach, Kure Beach and
Figure Eight Island, emergency officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Up and down the Carolinas, residents and business owners went
through the familiar drills of boarding up houses and stores.
Thousands of tourists who had hoped to spend the second to the last
weekend of the summer season at the beach packed up their cars and
reluctantly headed home, taking their money with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a bunch of cancellations today and we've lost ten to
twelve thousand dollars,'' Keli Black, a hotel employee in
Charleston, S.C. _ where half an inch of rain fell Sunday _ told
CBS News.
</P>
<P>
   Some businesses in North Carolina complained that the state was
overreacting by ordering the evacuations, but Robert Carver, a
spokesman for the division of emergency management, said officials
would rather be safe than sorry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody knows exactly where this storm is going,'' Carver said.
``We are trying to find a happy medium between overreacting and not
reacting appropriately.''
</P>
<P>
   For Mike Murphy, a state environmental program manager in
Virginia, it was the second straight year that a storm forced the
family to evacuate during a vacation in North Carolina. Last year's
culprit was Hurricane Bonnie.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very disappointed,'' Murphy, 45, said as he and his wife
and twins arrived in Wilmington after being evacuated from Topsail
Island, about 30 miles to the north. Around noon Sunday, their
rental company called and said they had to be off the island by 8
p.m. While Murphy and his wife packed, the children watched videos.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did this last year, so they know what to expect,'' Murphy
said. ``I guess they're hurricane veterans now.''
</P>
<P>
   In Virginia, red flags prohibiting swimming flew over Virginia
Beach, although the beaches stayed open, the police said. The
authorities also canceled a fireworks display that is a regular
fixture at the beach in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Ocean City, Md.'s beaches remained open Sunday, but Lt. Mike
Stone of the Ocean City Beach Patrol said rough water had kept the
patrol busier than usual, with more than 200 rescues.
</P>
<P>
   In the New York metropolitan region, the sun was out, but the
combined forces of Hurricane Dennis and Hurricane Cindy, which is
400 miles east of Bermuda, caused waves big enough to prompt the
State Parks Department to close two Long Island beaches _ Jones
Beach and Robert Moses State Park _ to swimmers, although
sunbathing was allowed.
</P>
<P>
   By 1 p.m., five- to seven-foot swells had calmed enough that
some beaches allowed wading up to the waist, but no farther, said
George Gorman, a director of recreation services for the Parks
Department.
</P>
<P>
   High tides also washed out a beach road used by fishermen at
Democrat Point in Robert Moses State Park, Gorman said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the restrictions, the crowds were actually about 10
percent to 20 percent above normal for this time of year, Gorman
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put up signs at the toll plazas warning people, but they
didn't turn around,'' he said. ``It turned out to be a great beach
day.''
</P>
<P>
   In North Carolina, two county-run emergency shelters were opened
at 3:30 p.m. Sunday in Wilmington. All city and county offices,
courts and all public schools will be closed today in the
Wilmington area.
</P>
<P>
   Shelters opened in northern South Carolina coastal counties
yesterday as well.
</P>
<P>
   In Litchfield, S.C., south of Myrtle Beach, a property manager,
Bobby Warner, oversaw precautionary measures at the Litchfield By
the Sea resort. Workers were busy boarding up buildings and
securing outdoor furniture.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are being very careful,'' Warner said. ``We have been
through this many times before and have learned to err on the side
of caution. We've pretty much got this down to a science.''
</P>
<P>
   Caution was also the watchword of the day at Alligator Adventure
in North Myrtle Beach, S.C., where workers hurried to reinforce a
fence surrounding the park with steel to make sure the 800
alligators inside stayed inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst-case scenario,'' said the alligator park's manager,
Matt Burmeister, ``is that some may get out of their individual
pens, but they are not getting out of our park.''
</P>
<P>
   For a crew of students from Clemson University, driving four
research vans to Wilmington, the object was to get close to the eye
of the storm. Their vans were pulling trailers carrying towers that
they hoped to place in the hardest-hit areas on land to measure the
wind speed of the strongest part of the hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to get an accurate measure of wind speed on the
ground,'' said Don Key, 22, a civil engineering student.
``Typically, winds are measured at high levels, but we are trying
to see the wind speeds at house level so we can write more accurate
building codes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-99 0033EDT &QL; 
