<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING HOPING HAPPY WORKERS NOW WILL MEAN BETTER PRODUCTIVITY
LATER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAUL NYHAN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Boeing Co. and its top union are optimistic they
have forged a three-year contract that will win ratification from
the Machinists on Wednesday _ and boost worker productivity and the
company's performance for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing and the International Association of Machinists base
their optimism on the fact that Boeing addressed many union demands
in the contract, which was unveiled on Saturday, including a
generous wage increase and improved pension benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The union's hopes are also built on what the company didn't
offer, such as alterations to the workweek or new health care
premiums.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing executives seem to be betting they can improve operations
by cooperating with Machinists rather than trying to squeeze
concessions from them during a labor dispute, say some financial
analysts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a major turn in the company's strategy _ making a bet
that a happier work force will hopefully lead to better
productivity,'' said Peter Jacobs, an analyst at Ragen MacKenzie
Group Inc., a Seattle-based investment firm. ``That's where the
real risk is in this.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing's desire to avoid a fight with its largest union _
especially in a year when it's scheduled to deliver a record 620
airplanes _ became evident when Chief Executive Officer Phil Condit
entered the talks on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are truly at a crossroads. With ratification, we can go
forward together to build a more secure future,'' Condit wrote in
an open letter sent to employees represented by the Machinists
union.
</P>
<P>
   While Boeing must wait until Wednesday for its employees to
vote, investors will render their verdict on Monday _ in the
trading of Boeing stock _ on whether they think the contract will
hurt or help the company's performance. Wall Street's opinion is
important because the company is trying to recover from two years
of production problems and bolster its image in the eyes of
investors.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Whitlow, who tracks Boeing for Safeco Asset Management,
said Monday's reaction was likely to be modest.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that they didn't strike is a plus,'' Whitlow said.
</P>
<P>
   If union members endorse the contract, Boeing will be able to
claim it negotiated 36 consecutive contracts, without a strike
during the last two years, according to the company.
</P>
<P>
   So far, many union members have a positive view of the company's
strategy and offer, according to Steve Vergala Sr., a union
steward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the general consensus is, `Yeah I like this,'''
Vergala said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, some employees are upset and ratification is far from
guaranteed. For example, older Boeing workers are disappointed the
contract only offers a 25 percent increase in monthly pension
benefits, according to other union members. The company can also
abuse proposed language that is designed to protect union jobs,
according to David Clay, who works at Boeing's Everett plant.
</P>
<P>
   Under the contract, Boeing pledged there would be no layoffs due
to subcontracting or offloading, although other layoffs are
possible. In addition, a joint committee will review subcontracting
or offloading 180 days before any action.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no teeth'' in job security provisions, Clay, who
opposes the contract, said.
</P>
<P>
   The Machinists will have the final say on Wednesday when they
cast their ballots at union halls spread throughout Washington,
Portland, Ore., and Wichita, Kan. The contract covers 44,000 Boeing
workers.
</P>
<P>
   The ballot will have two parts. A Machinist must check one box
to ratify the proposal or another to reject it. Then a workers must
vote to either reaffirm or reject the union's authority to strike.
</P>
<P>
   Even if a majority of those voting reject the offer, the
contract is accepted unless two-thirds vote to strike. The current
contract expires at 12:01 a.m. Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   While Boeing officials are hopeful their ``best and final
offer'' will be accepted, they realize they won't know until late
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is now in the hands of each individual employee,'' said
Peter Conte, who has been Boeing's primary spokesman during the
intense two weeks of negotiations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
