<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS MAKING SURE PEREZ READY TO RETURN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Carlos Perez will not be called up immediately
when rosters are expanded Wednesday. Instead the Los Angeles
Dodgers' troubled left-hander will make one more minor-league start
Friday before the team returns him to the starting rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Pitching coach Claude Osteen said Perez, who allowed six hits
and four earned runs in six innings in a victory over Omaha, will
pitch in September to see if he has improved his speed and
location.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not as concerned with the numbers because he is throwing
mostly fastballs trying to get his velocity up,'' Osteen said.
``He's around 90 right now, which is a big jump from earlier this
season, when he was around 83.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to make sure he is consistent there. That is why we're
giving him another start.''
</P>
<P>
   Arm's just fine: Struggling left-handed reliever Pedro Borbon
faced one batter Sunday and allowed a sacrifice fly to Mark Grace.
</P>
<P>
   Borbon entered the game after allowing seven runs in his last
three appearances, but said his elbow _ which was surgically
repaired two years ago _ is sound.
</P>
<P>
   ``Physically I'm fine,'' he said. ``But mentally I'm pretty
tired and I've made some mistakes out there. I've been in 61 games
this year and I've never done that before.''
</P>
<P>
   Borbon was 2-1 with a 1.64 ERA at the All-Star break. But since
then he has allowed 14 runs in 12 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to spot him with just a batter or two the rest of
the way,'' said manager Davey Johnson. ``His fastball still looks
very good.''
</P>
<P>
   Quick hits: Eric Gregg, worked home plate Sunday night in what
could be his last game as a major-league umpire. Gregg, one of 22
umpires whose resignations were accepted by Major League Baseball,
could have worked through Wednesday's game but he is taking a
vacation for the rest of the week. The umpires are appealing....
Eric Young's hitting streak ended at 10 games when he went hitless
in four at-bats.... Catcher Todd Hundley threw out Sammy Sosa at
second base in the fourth inning, the first runner he has gotten
since Aug. 16. Hundley has thrown out 15 of 104 runners trying to
steal (14 percent).... Gary Sheffield, who had 17 RBI in his
previous eight games, was 0 for 3, ending a streak of six
consecutive games with an RBI.... Starting pitchers Darren Dreifort
and Kyle Farnsworth both were born in Wichita, Kan., but Farnsworth
grew up in Georgia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
