<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-MARTIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETS EXHALE AS MARTIN BREAKS INTO THE OPEN
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It counted in Curtis Martin's mind, and that's what matters.
</P>
<P>
   He had played more than 80 games _ preseason, regular season,
and post-season _ in his National Football League career, but until
Saturday night against the Giants he had never run 80 yards for a
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   So in the afterglow of the Jets' 16-10 victory, Martin
understood the importance of what he had done, especially since all
last week everyone had expected him to make something happen, to
break out of a preseason slump in which he was averaging 2.5 yards
a carry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The significance of it, for me it's saying, `Everything's
OK,''' Martin said. ``It gives you hope. A running back needs to
know what he's capable of doing. This game I feel more like
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Bill Parcells, who had chided Martin last week for not
breaking a big run, agreed Sunday. ``It's called demonstrated
ability,'' said Parcells, who believes moments like that imprint
themselves on a player and make him believe he can do it again.
``This kid runs well and improved his pass-receiving skills
tremendously since his rookie year. He's just a good back _ not the
greatest back I've ever seen, but he's a high-quality back. He's
dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   And he is even more so now with help from the rookie right guard
Randy Thomas, who threw two blocks for him during the 80-yard run.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, everything seems OK with the Jets' offense, which has been
impressive on almost every drive this preseason. Parcells, whose
team improved to 2-1 in the preseason, admitted he is concerned,
however, because the Jets do not have a classic fullback to be a
lead blocker for Martin.
</P>
<P>
   But the Giants' defense had held opposing runners to less than
three yards a carry in the team's first two preseason games, and
none had scored a touchdown. But Martin barreled across the goal
line twice _ his other touchdown capped the opening drive, which
was directed by Ray Lucas. Martin averaged 18.1 yards a run
Saturday night with 127 yards on seven attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Martin is the leading ballcarrier in the NFL this preseason,
while Vinny Testaverde is the top-ranked quarterback in the
American Conference. He trails only the Giants' Kent Graham for
leaguewide honors.
</P>
<P>
   Martin leads in rushing yardage with 170 yards on 24 carries for
a 7.1-yard average. That is more than double his regular-season
average in 1998. He also leads the league with 207 yards from
scrimmage this preseason.
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde's 9-for-15 passing against the Giants was worse,
percentagewise, than his first two games. He has completed 73.8
percent of his passes (31 for 42) with two touchdowns and one
interception. He has not been sacked.
</P>
<P>
   This is how good the Jets' first-string offense has been in the
preseason: On 14 drives, it has scored four touchdowns and three
field goals. That offense, in the equivalent of less than a game
and a half, has scored 36 points. The Jets' first-team defense has
yielded only 23.
</P>
<P>
   After the Jets' first team scored a field goal and a touchdown
in two drives against the Packers in the first preseason game, an
Eagles advance scout said he thought the Jets were sensational.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Glanville, the former head coach and now a television
analyst, still was impressed the next day. As he waited in the
Green Bay, Wis., airport with his CBS counterpart Phil Simms,
Glanville said of those two series: ``The Jets are ready to play
now. I'd rest them now for the regular season.'' And Simms spent
much of the plane ride back to New York talking about ``all the
weapons Vinny has.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells would never speak so glowingly of his own team.
Instead, the coach said Sunday, what he liked about the offense was
the fact that it committed only six mental errors in 50 plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was obvious our concentration was better,'' he said.
Sometimes, telling an entire team that he can find better players
in a bus station _ as Parcells did last week after a close victory
over Philadelphia _ will do that.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Parcells was unhappy about Dedric Ward's drop of a
fourth-quarter pass from Testaverde that probably would have
resulted in a touchdown. ``We could have put the game away,'' he
said. And there was a missed extra point and a missed field goal by
John Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Missed extra points are unacceptable,'' Parcells said. ``You
should go a whole season without one.''
</P>
<P>
   He has come closer to making a decision on Lucas, who did
everything asked of him in his only drive. He completed all four of
his passes for a total of 26 yards. None traveled more than six
yards in the air, but he successfully executed a comfortable game
plan. Now he sits and waits for Parcells to officially tell him he
has made the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think,'' Lucas said, ``I might have a good chance.''
</P>
<P>
   As Lucas was reveling in a post-game news conference, Parcells
poked his head in and shouted to the former Rutgers quarterback,
``Just like playing against Temple.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
