<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-BROSIUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEYRITZ TRIES NEW ROLE AS THIRD-STRING THIRD BASEMAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Scott Brosius left the Yankees Sunday to be with his
father, Maury Brosius, who has been gravely ill at his Oregon home.
Scott Brosius may rejoin the team later in the week, depending on
his father's condition.
</P>
<P>
   Brosius is the everyday third baseman, and usually the
utilityman Luis Sojo would play in his place. Sojo, however, is
covered with a rash that has left him feeling ill. Last week in
Texas, Sojo attempted to treat a skin problem with some lotion and
apparently had a reaction to the lotion, with rashes breaking out
over much of his body.
</P>
<P>
   So Jim Leyritz, who has played catcher and first base most of
his career, started at third base Sunday. It just so happened that
the left-hander Andy Pettitte _ who generates an inordinate amount
of ground balls with his sinking fastball and cut fastball _
started for the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   But Leyritz, who played third in one game for San Diego last
year, did not have a ground ball chance for the first four innings
yesterday, and he noticed that Pettitte was pitching almost
exclusively outside to right-handed hitters _ which would be one
way to diminish the chances of the ball being hit to the left side.
``You're working away a lot,'' Leyritz said to Pettitte. ``That
have to do with me?''
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte replied, with a smile, ``That just happens to be the
game plan.''
</P>
<P>
   In the fifth inning, Leyritz fielded a grounder and threw the
ball away for an error, but in the eighth, he made one easy play
and later dived to his left to spear another grounder, before
throwing for the out at second base. ``He did fine,'' said Joe
Torre, the Yankees' manager.
</P>
<P>
   Torre said Sojo could have played yesterday if he had been
desperately needed, and he is hoping Sojo will be able to play
tonight, when the Yankees start a four-game series against the
Oakland Athletics. The Yankees will be able to expand their roster
on Wednesday, and it is very likely that Clay Bellinger, who can
play any position, will be recalled from Triple-A Columbus, along
with the outfielder Darryl Strawberry and a pitcher, in the first
wave of promotions.
</P>
<P>
   Maury Brosius has been battling colon cancer, and in recent
months, doctors have concentrated on diminishing his pain. He and
his son have talked nightly, after games, and early last week Scott
Brosius said that his father's voice had strengthened, that he
sounded good.
</P>
<P>
   Late Saturday night, Brosius received word that he was needed at
home. ``We're all thinking of Scott and his father,'' Pettitte
said. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
