<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CAB-CRASH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TAXI CRASH CLAIMS A LIFE AND ENDS A LOVE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Minn.)  (lb) 
 By BARBARA STEWART   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mary McGrath was barely out of high school when she
left her home in the Midwest and embarked on a love affair with New
York that lasted nearly 30 years, and ended Friday when she was
killed in a taxi crash on 42nd Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her favorite date was Little Italy on the weekend,'' said Jim
Bitros, who met her in a Manhattan singles bar and married her in
1976 in Tarrytown. ``Or we'd go to a cafe around here and bring the
dogs and sit there people-watching.''
</P>
<P>
   But she was just as content to stay home at night, ordering
dinner in and renting old Bette Davis or Barbara Stanwyck movies,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like being with an old buddy when you're 15 years old,
but you're married to her,'' he said of their relationship.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, Ms. McGrath _ who changed her name to Mara Bitros
after her marriage _ created a life with her husband that combined
the coziness she remembered from Minneapolis with the eclecticism
and electricity of the streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``She loved holidays,'' said Bitros, in their apartment on East
77th Street. ``From now until New Year's was her favorite time of
year.'' The living room where he was sitting was filled with
holiday knickknacks like a Santa carving on the side table and
framed photos of Casey and Murphy, the couple's pet Shih Tzus, on
Santa's lap. She started her Christmas shopping last month and had
already ordered a holiday wreath from a catalog, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Bitros, 46, left Minneapolis after briefly attending a
community college there. James McGrath, her father, who died in
1980, owned a high-end haberdashery, and Rosalia, her mother, died
when Mrs. Bitros was a child. Her first job in New York was at B.
Altman's, the venerable department store, where she and the
childhood friend who came with her from Minneapolis found jobs as
security detectives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody ever suspected her _ this pretty blond girl,'' said
Dennis McGrath, her brother, who works in public relations in
Minneapolis. ``She caught a lot of shoplifters that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, she found work matching home-care nurses with elderly
clients and selling weight-loss programs. She tried executive
headhunting for a while, but it did not suit her, said Bitros.
``Too barracudalike.''
</P>
<P>
   Her latest job was as a counselor for Career Blazers, an
employment agency and job-training company in midtown. There she
worked with people who lacked job skills and who were difficult to
place because of past alcohol and drug-abuse problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``She would get excited when she was able to get somebody who
was having a hard time finding work a good $20,000-a-year job,''
said Bitros. ``She got involved with her clients. She would say: `I
want you to go home and wear a blue suit at that job interview.'
Once she borrowed one of my blue blazers and gave it to a student
for an interview.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Mrs. Bitros was supposed to take last Friday off, she
went to work to meet with a company representative who had job
openings for her clients. She hated riding the subway, and was
mugged once on a platform, said Bitros.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted her to take cabs to work,'' he said. ``I thought it
was safer.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Bitros was taking a taxi on her way home from work Friday
afternoon when Joseph Cemeus, the driver, lost control of the car.
It jumped the curb and smashed into a building. Her head slammed
against the Plexiglas partition, injuring her severely and causing
cardiac arrest. The police, who are investigating, have not filed
charges against Cemeus, whose leg was broken in the crash.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Bitros was not wearing a seat belt. Bitros said that his
wife made a habit of buckling her belt, and speculated that she had
not had time to buckle when the crash occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Her funeral is scheduled for 10 a.m. on Wednesday at St. John
the Baptist Church on the Upper East Side. Bitros said he wanted
taxis to change the Plexiglas partitions to a more flexible
material.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe that will help, if I can get something good out of
this,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
