<HEADER>
A3942 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-CLINTON-FUTURE-N     08-30 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CLINTON-FUTURE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL OBSERVER: BILL CLINTON _ AFTER THE WHITE HOUSE, WHAT? 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DUDLEY CLENDINEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The closer President Clinton gets to that awkward next stage of
life _ the ex-presidency _ the better former President Jimmy
Carter, white-haired and wrinkled, looks to him.
</P>
<P>
   The two have had a prickly relationship through the decades, but
also much in common. Fellow Southerners, former governors, fellow
Southern Baptists and men of supreme self-confidence, they were
each dark-horse candidates who drove Republican presidents from the
Oval Office, and then had sharply mixed experience in it
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Carter was defeated in 1980 amid the general feeling that he may
have been a moral success, but was a failure as a leader. For Bill
Clinton, the more gifted politician, re-elected but unable to
resist temptation, it is the reverse.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will leave the White House with the same nagging needs
that Carter had _ to come to terms with his own record and
character, and to redeem himself in the public eye.
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton stood with Jimmy and Rosalynn Carter this month, to
award each of them the Medal of Freedom, the nation's highest
civilian honor, for their work in combating disease and brokering
peace efforts around the world, his admiration for the way the
Carters have spent a generation beyond the White House was clear.
Together, he said, ``they have done more good things for more
people than any other couple on the face of the earth.''
</P>
<P>
   Those words are a long way from the don't-call-us-we'll-call-you
treatment the Carters got when the Clintons moved into the White
House. But impeachment, the shrinking time left to him in the Oval
Office, Hillary Rodham Clinton's own ambition for a New York Senate
seat and Carter's success in creating the Carter Center in Atlanta
as a base from which to do good works have all focused the
president on the sea of time that looms past the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   He will only be 54 when he leaves the White House in January
2001, the youngest ex-president since Theodore Roosevelt, and the
first to watch his wife seek office as he departs.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton cannot, like Roosevelt, lose himself on safari in Africa
for 10 months after walking out the door. He needs to be supportive
to his wife. He needs a position in life. He also has a home to
buy, lawyers' bills to pay from years of being investigated by
Kenneth Starr and a $125-million Clinton library and museum in
Little Rock, Ark., to build.
</P>
<P>
   Some earlier presidents took real jobs. Theodore Roosevelt
worked as a contributing editor for a magazine. William Howard Taft
taught law as a professor at Yale and became chief justice of the
Supreme Court. Woodrow Wilson established a brief law practice in
New York City. Calvin Coolidge became a paid spokesman for an
insurance company.
</P>
<P>
   But ex-presidents have not worked salaried jobs for some time.
Instead, pensioned and provided with office expenses and Secret
Service protection, they solicit money to build presidential
libraries and become personalities and presences, paid to write, to
speak, to advise and appear.
</P>
<P>
   Some, like Ulysses Grant, Richard Nixon and Carter, have written
books for income or redemption. Herbert Hoover, who established the
first great modern example of postpresidential good works,
published more than a dozen, and coordinated efforts on war relief,
world famine and the reorganization of the federal government in
his 31 years out of office.
</P>
<P>
   Others, like Gerald Ford, Ronald Reagan and George Bush, have
become wealthy _ or wealthier _ from fees for speeches, appearances
and service on corporate boards.
</P>
<P>
   It has been speculated that Clinton, who loves Hollywood, might
become a partner in some firm like Dreamworks. But that sounds more
like a bad movie script than a real life choice _ and Clinton's
choices and qualifications are challenging enough.
</P>
<P>
   People find his future fascinating to guess at. Impeached by the
House, acquitted by the Senate, held in contempt of court by a
federal judge and despised by conservative Republicans in Congress,
he seems an intriguing but unlikely candidate for the United
Nations, the World Bank, the Supreme Court or some university
presidency _ positions that his global experience and his
background as a Rhodes scholar and former law professor might
otherwise suggest. Considering his gregarious talents, appointive
jobs seem somehow too constrained.
</P>
<P>
   But he can speak. He can write. His political goals, before
leaving office, are to install Al Gore as president and a
Democratic majority in Congress. The voters will decide. Beyond
that, he said at a dinner for his wife in Nantucket, Mass.,
recently, it is Hillary Clinton's turn to lead for the next 20
years, and his to follow. It will be interesting to see just what
that means.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
