<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-BOX-OFFICE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SIXTH SENSE' TOPS BOX OFFICE FOURTH WEEKEND IN ROW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Horror continued to dominate late-summer
moviegoing at the nation's multiplexes as the fourth weekend of
``The Sixth Sense'' easily led with an impressive $20.1 million at
2,688 theaters amid a moderate weekend overall at the box office,
studio sources said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sense,'' dropping off a mere 16 percent from last weekend,
became the first film since ``Saving Private Ryan'' to win four
consecutive weekends. The Disney release joined ``Titanic'' and
``Star Wars Episode 1: The Phantom Menace'' as the only movies to
top $20 million on four straight weekends.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we've joined some pretty good company,'' noted studio
distribution chief Chuck Viane, who projects a final gross of
around $225 million for ``The Sixth Sense.'' ``People keep going to
see it and bringing their friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Viane said repeat viewers for the tale of a boy beset by
supernatural forces currently comprise about 15 percent of the
movie's audience, far above rivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sense'' has now taken in $138.8 million in 24 days during a
period when moviegoing usually falls off sharply due to the start
of school. It now ranks 84th on the all-time list, displacing
``Good Will Hunting'' and just behind ``Sister Act.''
</P>
<P>
   The weekend's only other solid performance came from Disney's
opening of ``The 13th Warrior,'' a 10th century action-adventure
based on Michael Crichton's novel ``Eaters of the Dead.'' The
Antonio Banderas vehicle finished second with $10.3 million at
2,306 theaters, giving Disney the first one-two finish at the box
office since Paramount managed to achieve that distinction with
``Titanic'' and ``Grease'' in March 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Bucksbaum, president of the Reel Source forecasting
service, credited Disney with meeting a tough challenge in finding
an acceptable window for ``13th Warrior.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They got pretty good results in a genre that hasn't been doing
very well,'' he noted. ``This is usually a really bad time to open
movies because kids are focused on going back to school.''
</P>
<P>
   Holdover films took the next five slots, followed by a quartet
of new films that failed to generate much excitement. ``This
weekend's results are indicative of the strength of earlier films
and the weakness of new entries,'' industry tracker Arthur Rockwell
said. ``This is the time of year that studios often get rid of
their dogs.''
</P>
<P>
   Paramount's fifth weekend of ``Runaway Bride'' continued to show
strong legs with a respectable third-place finish as it took in
$6.9 million at 3,090 sites. Julia Roberts' ``Bride'' has taken in
$124.5 million to go with the $114 million gross of ``Notting
Hill,'' firmly establishing the star as Hollywood's most bankable
actress.
</P>
<P>
   Universal's third weekend of ``Bowfinger'' followed with $6.6
million at 2,732 theaters, topping Warner Bros.' second weekend of
``Mickey Blue Eyes'' with $5.5 million at 2,573 locations, MGM's
fourth weekend of ``The Thomas Crown Affair'' with $4.7 million at
2,095 screens and Artisan's seventh weekend of ``The Blair Witch
Project'' with $4.3 million at 2,332 theaters. ``Blair,'' the most
profitable movie ever with a $35,000 production cost, has grossed
$128.1 million to become the 103rd highest domestic grosser of all
time.
</P>
<P>
   Miramax's cop-action-adventure ``In Too Deep'' finished eighth
with a respectable $4.2 million at only 667 theaters to go with
$1.6 million it grossed in its opening days Wednesday and Thursday.
USA Films' ``The Muse,'' a Hollywood comedy with Albert Brooks and
Sharon Stone, came in ninth with a modest $4 million at 1,256
sites, followed by New Line's horror-thriller ``The Astronaut's
Wife'' with $3.6 million at 2,209 theaters and Universal's comedy
``Dudley Do-Right'' with $3 million at 1,802 locations.
</P>
<P>
   Warner Bros.' debut of family oriented drama ``A Dog of
Flanders,'' the fifth film version of the 19th century story,
flopped with a minuscule $870,000 at 1,267 theaters. The woeful
numbers underscore the difficulty of selling a movie targeted at
children, Bucksbaum noted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids just don't want to see a movie that's supposed to appeal
to them,'' he added. ``They want it to be something that's aimed at
teen-agers and adults.''
</P>
<P>
   The poor performance by ``The Astronaut's Wife'' was well below
Hollywood's consensus, given the generally strong market for horror
films, and probably reflected the surprisingly powerful drawing
power of ``The Sixth Sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Bucksbaum said ``Sixth Sense'' is likely to lead again during
Labor Day weekend, when it faces a pair of new films _ Warner's
action-adventure ``The Chill Factor'' with Cuba Gooding Jr. and
Miramax's prep school comedy ``Outside Providence.'' Both open
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Bucksbaum said the most powerful coming challenge to ``Sixth
Sense'' is likely to come from another horror-thriller, MGM's
``Stigmata,'' opening Sept. 10 with a first weekend that could hit
$17 million.
</P>
<P>
   Although this weekend's overall total of $94 million declined 9
percent from last weekend, the figure was 20 percent above the same
weekend last summer as the summer season continues its
record-setting run. Year-to-date business has gone past $4.9
billion and leads the 1998 pace by 8 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
