<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-NEC </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODS: MONEY PLAYER 
</HEADLINE>
 INVITATIONAL-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AKRON, Ohio _ This $5 million NEC Invitational was so lucrative
that Steve Pate, the 14th-place finisher, was handed a check for
$109,000 and Japan's Jumbo Ozaki, finishing last, as he often does
in America, was paid $27,000.
</P>
<P>
   And for Tiger Woods, a million dollars is still a million
dollars, but winning this elite tournament with 23 of the top 24
players in the world in the field meant so much more. Woods loves
to win, but winning is so much more meaningful when it comes
against the best.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning never gets old,'' said Woods, whose five-shot lead
entering the final round helped him cushion a surge from Phil
Mickelson. ``It feels good. Not only when you can win, but when you
can beat the best players. It gives you even more satisfaction to
beat the best.''
</P>
<P>
   And, at day's end, eight of the 12 golfers on the US Ryder Cup
team left the Firestone Country Club and boarded a plane to Boston
for a practice session Monday at The Country Club in Brookline,
Mass. Davis Love was a surprising late scratch from the passenger
list, skipping the practice round so he could receive treatment in
Georgia Monday for a sore neck ``that left my whole arm tingling
when I swung hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a tired group of European Ryder Cuppers headed home,
clearly needing rest after a frantic August. Another typical
American course, long from tee to green with rough heavy on the
sides, left the Europeans badly outplayed, the American Ryder Cup
team outshooting them by 80 strokes (The 12 US players scored a
cumulative 7 under par; the Europeans finished at 73 over par).
</P>
<P>
   Players on both teams said the lopsided advantage the US had
here means nothing. Strategy and tactics, of course, are radically
different playing stroke play for individual gain vs. the match
play for team glory of the Ryder Cup.
</P>
<P>
   The 80-shot differential, said the US's Payne Stewart, ``is not
relevant.'' No comparison or prediction should be made, said Woods,
``because this is a stroke play event and, quite honestly, we
really didn't care how we did against the Europeans.''
</P>
<P>
   Ryder Cup mania can wait as more glory is poured upon Woods,
whose birdie putt on the 17th hole held off Mickelson, who started
the day seven shots behind Woods but had charged within a stroke of
the leader on the 16th. That 15-footer on the 17th was huge because
Woods's putter had been balky here, a fact virtually unnoticed when
his drives were prodigious and his approach shots nearly impeccable
during that glorious 8-under round on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But on that 17th, Woods had to make a putt. Woods's caddie,
Steve Williams, said to Woods, ``Just keep doing what you've been
doing. Trust your stroke.''
</P>
<P>
   Easy for a caddie to say. ``Great advice,'' Woods remembered
thinking, ``but I needed to bury this one.'' And then Woods the
Golf Scientist took over, remembering the constant refrain of the
week on the practice greens ``that my tendency was not to let the
blade release, but to kind of hold onto it. And if you hold onto
it, the toe comes over pretty quick and starts the ball over left
with a little hook spin.''
</P>
<P>
   Easy for a scientist to analyze, even a Golf Scientist. Woods
still had to stroke the ball. ``And I said, `I don't care what
happens, but I'm releasing the blade.' I released it in my right
hand and it went in.''
</P>
<P>
   And Woods's perch atop golf's pedestal grew a bit more secure.
Woods Sunday tied Jack Nicklaus as the youngest player to win five
events in a season, tying him to the day (23 years, 8 months, 30
days) when Nicklaus accomplished the feat in the 1961 season.
</P>
<P>
   Even more, the victory was Woods's fifth in his last eight
tournaments as last year's ``hard work'' as Woods time and again
puts it _ when he and Butch Harmon, his guru, broke down his swing
and rebuilt it _ is paying off so clearly.
</P>
<P>
   Woods has won $4,266,585 this year, the first golfer to surpass
$4 million in earnings in one year. Finally, Woods had led or been
tied for the lead after 54 holes 10 times since turning pro three
years ago; he has won the last nine times he has been in this
position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you one thing,'' said Woods with a wide smile,
``I'm not against playing with a big lead.'' His Saturday round had
been spectacular, ``but it's always the hardest thing to come out
the next day and shoot a low number again.''
</P>
<P>
   But Woods made the putt he had to make, as the best must do, no
matter how they drive. And Woods won the cool million. And now
Woods's swing is trustworthy, ``the pressure is less now because
I've been through it,'' and the golf world is his.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
