<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-TRAILER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVIE TRAILERS KEY TO BOX OFFICE PROFITS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ ``I see dead people.''
</P>
<P>
   Those four whispered words by Haley Joel Osment, spoken at just
the right time in the trailer for ``The Sixth Sense,'' launched the
movie toward the box office stratosphere.
</P>
<P>
   It also underscored the growing importance of trailers, those
collections of images and catch phrases, lasting just one or two
minutes, shown in theaters before the main feature.
</P>
<P>
   True, trailers have been around since the early days of
Hollywood. But they have gained importance in recent years because
they can bring in huge crowds in the first weeks of a movie's
release, when studios now receive most of their box office grosses.
</P>
<P>
   Trailers also are shown, discussed and analyzed on the Internet,
a hotbed for whipping up the buzz about a movie even before it is
released.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trailers have become the No. 1 selling point for a movie,''
said Robert Bucksbaum, president of the Reel Source forecasting
service. ``The money studios spend on them is worth it. With `The
Sixth Sense,' the trailer was one of the best around because it
summed up a complex story and raised the hair on the back of your
neck.''
</P>
<P>
   Disney's ``Sixth Sense'' has been an unexpected late-summer hit
with close to $139 million in domestic box office grosses through
24 days.
</P>
<P>
   It easily led the box office for the fourth straight weekend
thanks to strong word-of-mouth and that creepy trailer.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Viane, the studio's distribution chief, said the film
benefited significantly from the trailer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It played in front of a variety of great early summer hits and
really whetted people's appetites,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The trailer for ``The Blair Witch Project'' may have been the
year's most influential because its costs were so low and the
movie's success was so unexpected. The decidedly low-tech trailer
managed to generate sensational response with a straightforward but
provocative approach: simply stating that three filmmakers had
disappeared in 1994 and their footage had been found a year later,
then showing 30 seconds of the trademark wobbly footage and ending
with the Web site address.
</P>
<P>
   Also impressive was New Line's decision to spoof ``Star Wars''
in its ``Austin Powers'' trailers, with Mike Myers' Dr. Evil as
Darth Vader and the voice-over: ``If you see one movie this summer,
see `Star Wars.' But if you see two movies, see `Austin Powers: The
Spy Who Shagged Me.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Craig Murray of Craig Murray Productions thought the ``Austin
Powers'' trailer was as important as the ``Blair Witch'' because
``it tapped into the audience's state of mind,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what you're trying to do: break through the clutter of
ads and do it in a way that respects the audience,'' said Murray,
who recently produced the Disney ``Tarzan'' trailer. ``Audiences
are much more sophisticated, so you have less time to capture their
attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Making that happen, though, is tricky. A trailer has to tell
enough about the movie to make it memorable, but not so much that
potential customers feel they've already seen the film.
</P>
<P>
   Further complicating the task now is that the key customers, the
free-spending adolescents and young adults often identified as
``The MTV Generation,'' have become far more image-oriented and
less patient with story development.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it had been five years ago, we would have done the `Tarzan'
trailer by saying first here's the movie, here are the songs, here
are the characters, and here's how you should feel,'' Murray said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Murray's trailer stressed such key elements as the way
Tarzan moved through the trees, almost as if surfing or
skateboarding.
</P>
<P>
   ``The movement really gave the movie a signature. The biggest
change is that stories are now told much more through images, so
we're no longer settling for the tried and true. The question we're
asking is, What kind of feeling and tone are we trying to impart?''
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood studios are willing to spend up to $500,000 with one
of more than a dozen specialty operations that produce only
trailers. Besides Murray's Burbank-based operation, which has 60
employees, other key players include CBO, Trailer Park, Ant Farm,
Kaleidoscope, Aspect Ratio, Creative Domain and Intralink.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a real art to trailers,'' said Drew Devlin, an
executive with Clark Film Buying. ``Sometimes they can be much
better than the movie. The major emphasis now is to come up with
something different.''
</P>
<P>
   And something shorter. The trend this summer has been toward
creating trailers that are far shorter than the maximum of two
minutes and 30 seconds set by the Motion Picture Association of
America.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing a lot more movement toward `get in and get out,'
'' Murray noted. ``They're used to a faster pace. We're looking to
generate an emotional response.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the move to shorter trailers may have stemmed from 20th
Century Fox's rule limiting total trailer time to eight minutes
before screening of ``Star Wars: Episode 1 _ The Phantom Menace.''
Studio executives still wanted to showcase a half-dozen projects
before ``Star Wars.'' They just shortened their trailers to
accommodate the rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the shorter trailers may have actually helped a lot of
the midsummer and late-summer films,'' Devlin said. ``People's
attention spans seem so short now that you have to grab them in the
first five or six seconds. Trailers can be a tremendous marketing
tool even if they don't reveal everything.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-99 0129EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
