<DOCNO> NYT19990830.0031 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 01:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3951 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ANALYSIS     08-30 1225
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSTANT BATTLE FOR PATRIOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA _ After watching the Tampa Bay Buccaneers manhandle the
Patriots Saturday night in steamy Raymond James Stadium, one had to
wonder one thing about New England's football future.
</P>
<P>
   Is there any?
</P>
<P>
   It seems like only yesterday that Drew Bledsoe was a rookie and
Bill Parcells was stalking the sidelines but it has been seven
years since they arrived and in the NFL seven years is a lifetime.
For several seasons during that stretch, the Patriots could boast
that they had superior talent, the best in the AFC East. That is a
boast they no longer can make.
</P>
<P>
   This does not mean the Patriots have degenerated in seven years
into also-rans, but what it does mean is that the rest of the
division has caught up to their talent, some of it now aging and
others of it never having come into full bloom. What is left is a
team that can beat anyone when everything is right. The problem
comes when everything is not right.
</P>
<P>
   Other than the 1996 season, when they unexpectedly went to the
Super Bowl, this collection of talent always has performed
erratically. When expected to win, too often it lost. When it
seemed the sky was falling, it often won. This makes for good
theater, but it does not make for a championship team.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout Pete Carroll's two-plus seasons in New England, his
teams have been consistently inconsistent, as they have continued
to be this summer. One game they appear to be unbeatable. The next
they embarrass themselves. Why this occurs is difficult to pinpoint
but it is undeniable.
</P>
<P>
   Look at their record and go by what you see. There's no telling
from one week to the next, one month to the next, or one season to
the next what this team will do. That is a character flaw that will
haunt it again this fall.
</P>
<P>
   With two weeks to go before the season opener, the 1999 edition
of the Patriots seems different from its predecessors in only one
regard. While it remains as prone to inconsistency as its forebears
it no longer is as talented. What that means is simple. It will not
win as many games.
</P>
<P>
   That is not to say this is a team without talent. There is rich
talent here in some areas, especially on offense, where it will
score explosively at times. But it is a team with a nearly 25
percent turnover in starters from a year ago and none have a track
record to rely on.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, the new recruits play running back, center, linebacker,
and safety. Those positions are the heart of a team. Where will
that leave them? In the same condition as their old coach,
Parcells. With heart trouble.
</P>
<P>
   A case in point is poor Tedy Bruschi. For too long Bruschi heard
the preachings of Parcells when he would tell his players they
needed to know their role to survive in the NFL. Bruschi always
seemed to.
</P>
<P>
   He is a valuable role player, a cat-quick pass rusher who can
come into a game in the right situation and be a force. What he is
not is an every-down outside linebacker who can take on blockers
who are wider than he is tall and taller than he is wide play after
play, especially if the defensive linemen in front of him are not
adept at protecting him from those blockers, as the present group
without departed Ferric Collons has proven to be.
</P>
<P>
   Yet that is the position Bruschi was put in when management
decided to dump Todd Collins for financial reasons last winter.
Collins was an always reliable if seldom spectacular anchor on the
edges of their defense and now that anchor, like those of Willie
Clay and Ted Johnson, is gone and the ship has begun to drift.
</P>
<P>
   Off what we've seen this summer, management's decision in just
this one area has made the team weaker in two spots and stronger in
none. If things don't improve, before the season is over Bruschi
will be unfairly criticized for not being what they should have
known he never was. He is not the only example of this, just the
latest.
</P>
<P>
   They ship out Jimmy Hitchcock and he intercepts seven passes for
a team that goes 15-1 while Chris Canty stays. They ship out Sam
Gash and he goes to the Pro Bowl while Tony Carter plays without
being noticed. They import a wall of young offensive linemen via
the draft and not a one shows the slightest sign of ever being
ready to play.
</P>
<P>
   They pass on drafting Sam Madison and Vonnie Holliday for Canty,
Tebucky Jones, and Robert Edwards. Madison is now considered one of
the best young corners in football, Holliday starts in Green Bay
and had eight sacks his rookie season at defensive end, while Canty
has been fired, Edwards probably never will play again after a
freak injury, and Jones remains much more in Carroll's eyes than he
is in the eyes of opposing coaches.
</P>
<P>
   What Tampa's shocking 45-14 dismemberment of the Patriots showed
Saturday night is that our worst fears about this team may be
realized. It is weak in the middle and weak at the top. Weak in the
middle of the offensive line, which Warren Sapp and the rest of the
Buccaneers readily broke down time after time. Weak in the middle
of the defense, which Mike Alstott and Warrick Dunn ran through
time after time. Weak in the running game and weak in the pass
rushing game. Weak, in other words, in too many places.
</P>
<P>
   That the Patriots have talent is obvious to anyone who spends
any time honestly evaluating them. Drew Bledsoe is among the best
passers in the league and Terry Glenn is one of the best wide
receivers in the AFC when healthy. Saturday night both were on
their games and single-handedly destroyed the Bucs' defense on one
scoring drive as Glenn caught three straight passes, the last for a
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Good as they were though, that touchdown made the score 14-7
Tampa, and soon it was 28-7, and then it didn't matter how good
Bledsoe and Glenn were because football is the one game that is
less about individuals and more about team. Ask the Lions, who for
years had Barry Sanders and Herman Moore and still couldn't win
anything.
</P>
<P>
   What Patriots management has done is sell out the whole for a
few of its parts. It has gone from a strong team to a team with
some strong, very well-paid parts, and that is not the same thing.
Where they are good they are very good but where they are not they
often are barely adequate and their backups are not even adept
enough to challenge those weaker links for a job.
</P>
<P>
   That is why New England's special teams have slipped the past
two years. It is not that Larry Whigham, that unit's leader, has
lost his enthusiasm. It's that the cast around him is not as good.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, six or eight stars do not make for a bright
constellation or for much of a football team. And an obsession with
dismantling what another man built just because you grew to despise
him is unsound at best and fatal at worst, but it has led to what
you saw Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   What remains behind seven years since Parcells came and three
years since he left is a dangerous team capable of slapping around
anybody on any Sunday but one just as capable of losing to anybody
at any time. It is a team that is not as good as it was a year ago
at center, middle linebacker, outside linebacker, safety, defensive
tackle, and probably running back.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at the other side of the coin, where is it better?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-99 0133EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990830.0032 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 01:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3952 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-TEN-USPROCHAMPIONSHIP     08-30 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-US </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAFIN SERVES UP STUNNING WN 
</HEADLINE>
 PRO CHAMPIONSHIPS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHIRA SPRINGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE _ Trophy presentations and the crowning of a new
winner normally create a charged atmosphere reserved for the last
day of a long competition. But Sunday afternoon at Longwood Cricket
Club there was a distinct difference.
</P>
<P>
   The 3,300 fans at the US Pro Championships final between Greg
Rusedski and Marat Safin witnessed an unusual occurrence. The
future of men's tennis served and returned his way to the first of
many titles. For all the attention paid Grand Slam events, the
smaller tournaments that comprise the bulk of the ATP Tour schedule
provide important plot points in a player's career.
</P>
<P>
   Safin will remember his triumphant week at Longwood as the rest
of his promising career takes shape. Even when his list of
accomplishments grows, it always will start with the No. 6 seed's
6-4, 7-6 (13-11) upset of top-seeded Rusedski. The 19-year-old
Russian earned 150 rankings points and $46,000 for the victory. And
when the new world rankings are released Monday, he will continue
his climb from No. 33.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to work hard to win. It's nice, but I'm still thinking
about (Pete) Sampras so it's not so nice,'' said Safin of the
opponent who awaits him in the first round of the US Open.
</P>
<P>
   The teenager, however, served notice to the No. 1 player in the
world with his performance. Safin defeated Rusedski with 16 aces,
solid returns, and occasional appearances at net, besting the
lefthander from London at his own game. Typically, Rusedski lets
his powerful serve set the tone of the match and makes returns
difficult, if not impossible. He managed just six aces against
Safin, who leaped at every opportunity to get his racket on the
speeding shots.
</P>
<P>
   Safin admitted after the match that returning a Rusedski serve
was all guesswork. Safin could not read his opponent's serves well
and simply selected a side to favor for the returns. On many
occasions, he had the right instincts. The Russian's ability to
catch up with Rusedski's serves improved as the match and points
went longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem was concentration,'' said Safin. ``It's difficult
to play against Greg because he plays serve and volley. You just
have to return and concentrate all the time on the return. No
matter if I'm doing good or bad, I had to return serve. After
returning the first serve, I had just to put the ball in play, but
all match there was a lot of pressure. I know if I don't win a
point, he will serve an ace the next point. You are always thinking
about his serve.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither player fell behind in a service game until the middle of
the first set. In fact, the pace of the opening games was so quick
that the ball boys and girls had trouble keeping up. Few points
went beyond a serve and return. Few games lasted longer than five
points.
</P>
<P>
   The first time the top seed faltered on his serve proved costly.
The longest rally of the match gave Safin a 0-15 lead in the
seventh game. At the time, the small opening seemed insignificant.
And Rusedski edged ahead, 30-15, before his backhand volley
deserted him. Safin got the break necessary to win the first set
when Rusedski's third volley in a row didn't clear the net.
</P>
<P>
   Once the Russian capitalized on his lone break point, he
confidently served through his next game, notching two aces. After
Rusedski held serve, Safin struggled to reach deuce and then used a
cross-court forehand to take the early set lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great player and that was probably his best match all
week,'' said Rusedski, the ninth-ranked player in the world who has
yet to win a title this year. ``He was just too good (Sunday). If
he consistently serves that well, he's going to be hard for anyone
to beat. I got my racket on a few serves, but not too many.''
</P>
<P>
   The second set went to a decisive tiebreaker, where Safin
squandered four match points and Rusedski let two set points pass.
The 13-11 outcome of the extra session marked the longest
tiebreaker in Longwood tournament history.
</P>
<P>
   The players battled back and forth for 20 minutes, mixing aces
and double faults, overhead winners, and missed volleys. Safin
double faulted on his fourth match point with the score 11-10. But
on the next two points, consecutive long volleys by Rusedski gave
away the match.
</P>
<P>
   Safin is just getting started. He lifted the winner's trophy
over his head as if it was the top prize awarded at Wimbledon or
Roland Garros.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to be a really good player in the future,'' said
Rusedski. ``He'll probably be in the top 10.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
