<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 01:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3953 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-HOLLEYCOLUMN-BOS &LR;      08-30 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-HOLLEY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEEKEND POSITIVELY HEAVENLY 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Red Sox should be hearing voices this morning. They
spent their weekend beating up on Angels, so now they have caught
the attention of the baseball gods. The gods are shouting. If the
Sox can't pick up the gist of the words they must be crazy.
</P>
<P>
   All of this began Sunday when the Sox beat the Motown Angels,
7-4, at Fenway Park. About an hour later, the A's lost to the White
Sox and began preparing for a four-game series in Yankee Stadium.
At the same time in Minneapolis, the Royals lost to the Twins and
started heading east to Boston.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just me. You hear that? The gods are screaming about
opportunities now.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox are practically being dared to solidify their postseason
status this week. Even if they aren't thinking about the Yankees as
much as they should, they still can stiff-arm the A's if they
simply do what everyone else in the American League has done: Beat
up the Royals. If they can't do that, then maybe they don't need to
be in the playoffs this season.
</P>
<P>
   I know Jimy Williams likes to give credit to every team in the
majors, but the Royals are terrible. I think Williams says nicer
things about them than they say about themselves. Kansas City is
the birthplace of bebop legend Charlie Parker. It is also the
Midwestern land where a baseball team frequently gets bebopped
upside the head. Think about this: The Royals were just swept by
the Twins. Their own media relations staff recently noted that the
Royals have lost ``60 of their last 90 contests.'' And that was
before Sunday's loss.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, the gods are playing air guitars and yelling like
thrash-metal vocalists.
</P>
<P>
   After their four games with the Royals, the Sox have a 12-game
road trip to Seattle, Oakland, New York, and Cleveland. So now is
the easiest time to pick up a couple of games on somebody, either
the Yankees or A's. If they don't do it now, the Sox will regret it
in September, an easy month for both New York and Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know Kansas City has struggled, but they've got some pretty
good hitters over there,'' Sox catcher Scott Hatteberg said. ``And
Jeff Suppan is pitching there now; he's having a good year.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Sox prospect Suppan starts Monday night. He and Jose
Rosado are the only KC starters in this series with earned run
averages under 6. Earlier this month, Suppan got a complete-game,
5-2 win over his former teammates. But the man opposing Suppan is
Pedro Martinez. So that means the Sox get to start a series with
their rotation set from the top, facing the worst team in the
league. There is also a chance that Ramon Martinez could start
Thursday's game, which will end the series.
</P>
<P>
   The gods are chanting, waving freshly printed playoff tickets,
and arguing over the brand of champagne the Sox should use when
they secure a postseason spot.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the Sox never would say anything like that on the
record. They speak safely when discussing the opposition. They need
an irreverent speaker, someone like Tim Belcher, who started Sunday
for the Angels. Belcher gave up seven runs in 5 1/3 innings.
Afterward, he gave an indication that he also hears the gods
talking to the Sox. He subtly ripped his teammates, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``They take an aggressive approach to hitting,'' he said of the
Sox. ``You don't see that from a lot of clubs. They swing at a lot
of strikes and spoil a lot of good pitches. That's why they're
where they're at and we're where we're at.''
</P>
<P>
   With Sunday's loss, the Angels are now 27 games behind
first-place Texas in the AL West. Predictably, Mo Vaughn was booed
each time he went to the plate. His summer ended with a 3-for-20
performance against his former team. Two of those hits came Sunday.
Vaughn swears that he has no regrets about leaving, but I am
convinced he wants to come back. If the Red Sox were like a
university and allowed players to take six-month sabbaticals, I bet
Vaughn would have leapt at that option. It is clear now that he
needed a break more than he needed to leave. He now finds himself
teamed with the Angels of Oz, surrounded by players with dazzling
potential and questionable hearts.
</P>
<P>
   Before Sunday's game, Dan Duquette chatted with a few reporters
and ``innocently'' asked if anyone had noticed Jose Offerman's
on-base capability. You may remember that the general manager was
mocked for that on-base quote last November, when he said Offerman
could replace Vaughn in that category.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought you weren't gloating,'' someone said to Duquette.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not gloating,'' he said. ``Just asking.''
</P>
<P>
   Duquette talking a little trash? The gods are hysterical,
whooping and high-fiving each other. Duquette was fully aware of
the on-base numbers, which are .384 for Offerman and .345 for
Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   Now all the numbers seem to be favoring the Sox. Bryce Florie
was shaky in the ninth, but Derek Lowe bailed him out in four
pitches and got the save. Trot Nixon had three hits. Pat Rapp gave
up a run. And if you listened closely in the sixth, you could hear
the divine whispers beginning then. That's when Donnie Sadler
scored from third on a short sacrifice fly to left field. He ran so
fast that you weren't sure if it was Sadler or his
computer-generated, animated likeness. There was a streak across
home plate, like dirt lightning, after Sadler slid past catcher
Matt Walbeck.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not many people would have scored there,'' said Williams,
shaking his head in amazement.
</P>
<P>
   You know what people say about speed like that, right? It's
God-given.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
