<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-MIAMI-OHIO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIAMI MAKES A STATEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
 STATE-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The message, if indeed the intention was
to send one, was more subtle than some Miami teams of the past had
sent.
</P>
<P>
   The strutting was held to a minimum, and while some of their
on-field antics suggested that the Hurricanes still were linked to
their past, the reaction to one of the school's biggest victories
in recent years Sunday was almost sedate.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, we're not back yet,'' said Miami coach Butch Davis
following a convincing 23-12 victory over No. 9 Ohio State in the
Kickoff Classic at Giants Stadium. ``But this was a step forward.
It is something that this team and this program can build on.''
</P>
<P>
   When Miami was winning national championships in 1983, 1985,
1987, and 1991, and was a traveling road show that attracted
national attention, a win in August, even over a team with the
credentials of Ohio State, only would have been a footnote in a
season filled with greater goals.
</P>
<P>
   But a three-year probation that cut the Hurricanes to Division
1-AA strength in terms of scholarships and quality players, has
lowered the bar slightly. The Hurricanes finally have gotten back
to a full scholarship level of 85, although 56 are either freshmen
or sophomores.
</P>
<P>
   Five years into a plan that still has not reached its peak _
``We're still probably a year away from being back completely to
the levels where we really want to be,'' said Davis _ the
Hurricanes look like a team that can and will compete against
anyone.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday was a case in point. Granted, Ohio State was not the team
that went 11-1 a year ago and was regarded in many quarters as the
best team in the country _ Florida State and Tennessee
notwithstanding.
</P>
<P>
   But the Buckeyes had enough people left to make them a top 10
team in some preseason polls. Aside from inexperience at
quarterback and wide receiver, Ohio State still looked like a team
that could compete for the Big Ten title, if not for the national
crown.
</P>
<P>
   But on a 90-degree afternoon, which made the Hurrianes feel more
like they were in Miami than in the Meadowlands, the Hurricanes
were better. They were quicker. They were more aggressive, playing
with the kind of intensity and enthusiasm that characterized Miami
teams of the past.
</P>
<P>
   They made a statement early in the first quarter, scoring in
just two plays on their first offensive series on a 44-yard run by
James Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first of a series of big plays by the Hurricanes on
offense and defense that set the tone for the game, giving the
crowd of 73,037 a glimpse of the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``They made big plays and we didn't,'' said Ohio State coach
John Cooper, a loser in his season opener for the first time in his
12 seasons in Columbus. ``They are a good football team and they
are going to win a lot of games this season.''
</P>
<P>
   Leading the way was a child of Miami's future. Sophomore
quarterback Kenny Kelly, making his first collegiate start, ran for
a touchdown, threw a touchdown pass, and completed 17 of 25 passes
for 245 yards.
</P>
<P>
   On the flip side, Kelly threw a pair of interceptions and
fumbled once.
</P>
<P>
   But with a defense that has some of the old Miami speed, as well
as swagger, correcting most of the mistakes, none of Kelly's errors
were fatal.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State responded well at first, taking a 9-7 lead at the end
of the first quarter, largely because of a 69-yard breakaway run by
tailback Michael Wiley, the Buckeyes' latest link to the great
skill-position players they have turned out in this decade.
</P>
<P>
   But after the first-quarter flurry, the Buckeyes could do
nothing offensively.
</P>
<P>
   Miami, however, was making just enough plays, whether it was
Jackson, who ran for a game-high 89 yards, or Najeh Davenport, who
picked up 81. Or tight end Daniel Franks, who made a pair of key
third-down receptions. Or wide receiver Santana Moss, who had only
three catches, but those were for 115 yards, including a 67-yard
grab of an underthrown Kelly pass that gave Miami a touchdown in
the final eight seconds of the first half.
</P>
<P>
   That was good enough to give the Hurricanes a 23-9 lead, which
was more than enough to win, especially when they reached the
fourth quarter with a still-solid 23-12 bulge.
</P>
<P>
   For Miami, it was only a small step. Ahead in the next month are
games against Florida State and Penn State, who are No. 1 and No. 2
in most people's minds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really good,'' said Kelly. ``We're very good. But for us
to be in the same league as the Miami teams of the late '80s, we
have to finish 13-0. If we finish 13-0 and I'm sitting in the
Louisiana Superdome (national championship game) with our same
guys, and we come out with a win, then I'll tell you we're back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
