NYT-08-30-99 0148EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990830.0036 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 01:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3957 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-RUN-WORLDCHAMPIONSHIP     08-30 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-WORLD </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US RELAY TEAM GETS GREENE LIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
 CHAMPIONSHIPS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEVILLE, Spain _ Going into the World Championships, the
spotlight was on the quest of Marion Jones for a historic four gold
medals. Coming out of them, it's on Maurice Greene, who
Sunday &UR;  &LR; night won his third when he anchored the US men's 4x100
relay to victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always believed I could be one of the best athletes in
the world,'' said Greene, wrapping up his busy week after earlier
winning the 100 and 200. ``I'm just glad I came here and performed
the way I could.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say Michael Johnson didn't earn his share of the
stage. In the last event of the meet, which ended Sunday &UR;  &LR; night,
Johnson wowed 51,142 screaming fans with a 43.50 anchor leg in the
4x400 relay to bring another gold to the US while earning his ninth
world championship gold medal, surpassing Carl Lewis for the most
in history. Johnson had tied Lewis earlier this week when he won
gold while breaking the 400-meter world record when he ran 43.29,
the only world mark to fall in the meet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a testament to what I've been trying to do my whole
career in being consistent in going to all the world championships
at the top of my game,'' said Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   In the long relay, Jerome Davis ate up the track running first
leg, giving Antonio Pettigrew a lead over Robert Mackowiak of
Poland. Angelo Taylor opened the gap, and when Johnson got the
stick the race was over.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, the 4x100 finally had come off without a hitch for the
Americans, a novelty after dropping the baton in the first round in
both 1995 and 1997. Jon Drummond got out strong in the first leg;
the exchanges were smooth all around to first Tim Montgomery and
then Brian Lewis; and by the time Greene got the stick Great
Britain's Dwain Chambers was only a step in front of him. That lead
soon evaporated as Greene turned on the jets to propel the US to a
win in 37.59 seconds, the fifth-fastest relay in history.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw Brian come around to me and I felt the baton in my
hand, I said `I got three gold medals,' '' Greene said.
</P>
<P>
   Great Britain ended up second in 37.73, with Nigeria getting
bronze in 37.91. Canada was absent, disqualified in the first round
for a late baton pass.
</P>
<P>
   The US women, hurt by the absence of Jones, didn't fare as well,
with the 4x400 picking up silver and the 4x100 falling into fourth
and out of the medals with a bad first exchange and a tired-looking
Gail Devers unable to make up the ground as anchor. Jones had
planned to run one of the relays before succumbing to back spasms
in her 200-meter semifinal and dropping out of the meet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish (Jones) could've been here, and it probably would've
been a different story,'' said Cheryl Taplin, who ran the first
leg.
</P>
<P>
   The most dramatic race of the night, if not the nine-day meet,
was the men's 800 meters, in which Wilson Kipketer of Denmark had
to nip South African Hezekiel Sepeng in a lean at the tape to win
his third world title. Kipketer, who raced little in 1998 after a
bout with malaria, said that despite trailing down the stretch, he
was never worried. Sort of.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, it probably didn't look like it on television, but I knew
I was going to catch Sepeng,'' said the 26-year-old
Kenyan-turned-Dane. ``The only trouble was that time was running
out and I didn't know if I would make it before the line.'' He did,
clocking 1:43.30 to Sepeng's 1:43.32, the closest championship 800
meters ever.
</P>
<P>
   In the women's 1,500, American Regina Jacobs took her second
straight silver medal, this time behind Olympic champion Svetlana
Masterkova of Russia. Elena Buhaianu of Romania took the race out
slowly in 1:03.87 for the first half, while the main group ran 10
meters behind. By 800 meters Jacobs, Masterkova, and Portugal's
Carla Sacramento, the 1997 gold medalist, were 1-2-3, but Jacobs
appeared to get boxed in with about 150 meters to go and Masterkova
kicked the final 100 to victory in 3:59.53 to Jacobs's 4:00.35.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's tremendous, especially for una vieja,'' said
Jacobs, 36, referring to herself as an old woman.
</P>
<P>
   Tenth was Marla Runyan, legally blind and running only her
eighth race ever at the distance. ``I'm just learning to run
back-to-back 1,500s,'' she said, never before having run rounds.
``I had a big PR Friday night and I felt it in my legs tonight.''
But Runyan was far from disappointed, adding: ``I am so honored to
wear a USA uniform and run in this stadium.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
