<SLUG> BC-BBA-ATHLETICS-RAPP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HE'S BEEN THROWING OFF HIS QUESTIONABLE RAP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The jury has been out for a long time on righthander
Pat Rapp. Now the evidence is piling up that the worst is over in
his short time with the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Rapp has found a groove that if it continues could make him the
second-best starter in manager Jimy Williams's never-a-dull-moment
rotation. When the Red Sox signed Rapp, who was 12-13 last season
in Kansas City, they hoped they had found a No. 2 man behind Pedro
Martinez. But he has struggled on and off the field, until
recently, and his timing couldn't be better.
</P>
<P>
   Rapp improved to 6-5 Sunday at Fenway Park after Boston's 7-4
victory over Anaheim. He's been going six innings or so and hoping
the bullpen can hang on, which it did in a 4-1 victory over
Minnesota last week. Since Aug. 2, Boston has won five of the six
games Rapp has pitched. He won't be winning the Cy Young Award this
season, but he's doing his part now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't take for granted what he's done,'' said pitching coach
Joe Kerrigan. ``For the last month he's pitched very well and has
done a hell of a job of focusing. His control is good. He now has a
good curveball that makes him very effective against lefthanders.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason Rapp has had to stay focused is he's been thinking
about his wife's rough pregnancy, although he knows there's nothing
he can do about that but pray.
</P>
<P>
   Rapp was so inconsistent to start the season he was banished to
the bullpen in late June and made 11 relief appearances. But he
returned to the rotation July 28 after posting a 2.66 earned run
average.
</P>
<P>
   And, magically, Rapp has been a different pitcher. A
tinkered-with motion has made his delivery more compact. Instead of
falling behind in the count, he's been getting ahead with his
fastball and throwing his curve and changeup for strikes. On July
28, Rapp went eight innings in an 8-0 victory at Toronto. He hasn't
lost since.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel a lot more comfortable out there and I hit my spots,''
said Rapp. ``I've simplified my mechanics and gotten rid of a lot
of wasted moves and turns. It's helped me keep myself in the strike
zone.''
</P>
<P>
   The change has been duly noted.
</P>
<P>
   ``You tip your cap to him,'' said manager Jimy Williams. ``He's
really done an outstanding job. I believe the stint in the bullpen
really helped him. It gave him a chance to work on some things. His
delivery has been simplified. I think that has helped him a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, at least on the diamond. With his wife, Rebecca, at home
in Sulphur, La., Rapp is living two lives: Baseball pitcher, and
nervous father awaiting the birth of his third child.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seems like the last couple of weeks I've blocked it out,''
said Rapp of the situation at home. ``It's actually helped me
concentrate a lot more on the job for as long as it takes and as
long as Jimy wants me out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerrigan has played a big part in the recent success.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe told me one day last month, `You're 32 years old and you
might have found the key to your success.' Maybe he's right,'' Rapp
said. ``I'm just trying to throw strikes, hit my spots, and get a
good read on the hitters the first time around so the second time
around I can make an adjustment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just in the last month I found some mechanics that have been
working. I throw a lot more strikes. The curveball has gotten
better so that I can use it almost any time I want to. I haven't
had to use my changeup too much. Seems like I'm getting ahead in
the count more this half of the season. Knowing that you can still
make quality pitches for a strike.''
</P>
<P>
   There is little chance that Bret Saberhagen, the veteran who has
been in the No. 2 slot, will return soon. His shoulder problems
continue and he has been scratched from Thursday's start. The Sox
have the option of bringing back Tim Wakefield on that day or
activating Ramon Martinez. Rapp is next scheduled to pitch Friday
in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of our starters are important,'' said Williams. ``But of
late Rapp has risen to the occasion and really given us a lift.
He's been very consistent in all of his starts the last month. He's
very durable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
