<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-CUBS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOSA HITS 54TH TO LEAD CUBS OVER DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ For Sammy Sosa, it was a night like so many
others. For Kyle Farnsworth it was the game of his young life.
</P>
<P>
   There are now 54 reasons why Sosa isn't sharing the spotlight
much these days, 54 homers that bring the crowd to its feet no
matter where he is playing.
</P>
<P>
   But just as special Sunday was the two-hit, 6-0 shutout
Farnsworth threw at the Los Angeles Dodgers, just the third
major-league victory for the struggling 23-year old right-hander.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa, who was cheered wildly throughout the three-game series,
received a standing ovation from the crowd of 47,411 at Dodger
Stadium after leading off the seventh inning with a homer off
Darren Dreifort.
</P>
<P>
   It was a 427-foot, opposite-field drive that landed deep in the
Cubs' bullpen. Dodgers right-fielder Raul Mondesi didn't even look
up.
</P>
<P>
   ``What for,'' he said. ``Sammy is just so strong.''
</P>
<P>
   But when Sosa caught Todd Hollandsworth's flyout to end the
game, he unwittingly tossed Farnsworth's momento into the stands.
</P>
<P>
   Not that anybody cared, except maybe Dreifort, who pitched well
but unraveled after the home run and the huge response from the
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   For Farnsworth, who is scheduled to pitch against the Dodgers on
Saturday at Wrigley Field, it was his first victory in his last 12
major-league starts.
</P>
<P>
   That win also came at Dodger Stadium on May 11. Since then he
also has been sent to the minors and pitched out of the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   But through eight inings, he had allowed just one hit, a bloop
single by Hollandsworth with one out in the furth inning that
should have been caught by left fielder Glenallen Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Although Mark Grudzielanek ended the what-ifs by bouncing
infield single to open the ninth, Farnsworth's performance did have
historical significance.
</P>
<P>
   The last Cubs pitcher to throw a one-hitter in Dodger Stadium
was Bob Hendley in September 1965, the same night Sandy Koufax
pitched a perfect game.
</P>
<P>
   ``This felt great,'' said Farnsworth, who came in wth a 6.17
ERA. ``This is a long time coming.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa is making a little history of his own.
</P>
<P>
   He is nine games ahead of his pace from last season when he hit
66. This year he is leading the Cardinals Mark McGwire, who had 70
last year. McGwire has 51, but is stuck in a 2 for 19 slump.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers were successful against Sosa in the first two games
in the series. But Sosa who came in 1 for 8, owns Dreifort. The
home run made him 6 for 12 lifetime. He also added two singles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last two games here they pitched me real well and I was
swinging at too many pitches out of the strike zone,'' Sosa said.
``But I went to the cage early today with my batting coach (Jeff
Pentland) and pretty much figured out what happened.``I came into
the game trying to be patient, which is part of my game. went up
there relaxed and it pretty much worked.''
</P>
<P>
   As Sosa circled the bases, the flashbulbs popped and the crowd
roared. When play resumed Mark Grace lined a double to right and
Hill walked.
</P>
<P>
   Tyler Houston came up in a bunt situation and rolled the ball
toward third base. Instead of breaking for the ball, Dreifort raced
toward the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman Adrian Beltre picked up the ball and made a wild
throw to first. Grace scored and Hill and Houston moved into
scoring position. Both scored on a base hit by Gary Gaetti.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he was upset by the home crowd's reaction to Sosa,
Dreifort looked sternly ahead and said, ``I really don't know what
to say about that.''
</P>
<P>
   He also was booed when he fell behind 2-0 to Sosa before the
home run. &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Manager Davey Johnson said Dreifort, who pitched brilliantly for
six innings, wasn't rattled. Grudzielanek disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I noticed right away that he wasn't the same,'' Grudzielanek
said. ``He had pitched so well to that point.''
</P>
<P>
   In additon to his ninth-inning single, Grudzielanek played a big
role in Farnsworth's night.
</P>
<P>
   He opened the sixth by hittng a line drive back to the mound.
Farnwaorth caught the ball, but it struck him on his pitching
hands.
</P>
<P>
   Play was halted for several minutes as Farnsworth tried to
restore the feeling in his hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't really it that well,''Grudzielanek said. ``We knew he
had a good fastball, but the scouting report was that he is more of
a thrower. Tonight, he was a pitcher, a very good pitcher.''
</P>
<P>
   After Hollandsorth's bloop single, Farnsworth retired the next
14 batters he faced. He got another run in the eight and even drove
one home with a ninth-inning single off rookie Matt Herges, his
first big league RBI.
</P>
<P>
   In the ninth, Grudzielanek opened with a high chopper that
bounced over the head of Gaetti at third. Farnsworth then balked
Grudzielanek to second, which cost him a double play when Gary
Sheffield grounded to short. Eric Karros flied to center and
Holandsworth flied to Sosa to end the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite a game,'' said Farnsworth, who threw 121 pitches. ``I'll
remember it for a long time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
