u s BC-ROW-WORLDCHAMPIONSHIP     08-30 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROW-WORLD </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US MEN'S EIGHT TAKES THIRD STRAIGHT ROWING TITLE 
</HEADLINE>
 CHAMPIONSHIPS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. CATHARINES, Ontario _ With a quarter of the race to go, the
US men's eight looked across Martindale Pond and saw the British
walking through them with wing-tipped shoes. ``There's a point
where you have to say, is the race over now?'' stroke Chris Ahrens
said later. ``Or are we going to dig down and find that extra
gear?''
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't some Sunday morning paddle, after all. This was the
world rowing championships. So the Yanks pushed the stick into
overdrive, blew past the Brits by half a length _ and made a little
history here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it's sunk in yet,'' said Ahrens, after he and
his mates had won the title for the third straight year and stamped
themselves as the clear Olympic favorite. ``It's a great thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Only the Germans (the East in 1975-77-78-79; the West in
1989-90-91-93) ever had won three in a row, but the Americans were
sure they were up to it, even if they hadn't rowed an international
race since they won in Cologne last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had confidence we were going to win,'' said 3-man Porter
Collins, after the US had prevailed in a stiff headwind that added
half a minute (6:01.58) to the race. ``We can row anybody
anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   The eight's victory, their fourth in the last five world
regattas, was the showpiece to a strong week by the resurgent US
flotilla, which ended up with 10 medals (six gold, three silver,
one bronze) in 24 events, one shy of the Germans. The men's coxed
four and women's lightweight pair and quad also grabbed gold Sunday
and the women's eight and lightweight double (with Worcester,
Mass., attorney Christine Collins in bow) both took silvers behind
the Romanians.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're no slouches,'' Collins testified, after Camelia
Macoviciuc and Constanta Burcica had pulled away to win by a
length. ``They've been rowing together for a long time. They didn't
win the Olympics for nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Hefty as the haul was, seven of the US medals came in
non-Olympic events. With the Sydney Games on the horizon the
Americans wanted to make sure they produced something that would
make the whole world watch next summer, particularly in the eights,
which is still the sport's glamour event.
</P>
<P>
   The women, who now have won medals in five of the last six
Worlds, thought they had a terrific chance at unseating the
Romanians, whom they'd only beaten once since the 1984 Olympics.
But the Yanks, who hadn't raced before they came here, gave up too
much ground early and the Romanians held off their late surge to
prevail by a quarter of a length.
</P>
<P>
   ``We let 'em get out too far, just like last year,'' said stroke
Amy Fuller, whose mates lost by the same margin in Cologne. This
time, the US had to come out of third at the quarter pole and spent
most of the race half a length behind.
</P>
<P>
   So cox Rajanya Shah called for the finish sprint early, hoping
to reel in the the scarlet-capped Romanians before they ran out of
space. ``Just before the launch we told ourselves, let's not say we
needed another 200 meters,'' said Fuller.
</P>
<P>
   For a moment, the US appeared to be drawing even. Then Romanian
stroke Dolna Ignat hit the gas and the Americans found themselves
on the award dock listening to the same old song _ made in
Bucharest. ``Next year is the year that counts,'' Fuller mused.
``I've gone into the Olympic year as the favorite. I'd rather be
the underdog.''
</P>
<P>
   The US males haven't won the Olympics since 1964 but they've
been hell in a shell ever since Atlanta, winning as many titles in
one quadrennium as they had in the previous 35 years.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans came hammering off the line, hoping to shake the
field. But with 500 meters to go the British, who hadn't won a
world medal since 1991, had them down by nearly half a length.
``(Cox Pete) Cipollone called us even,'' said Collins, ``but we
knew we were down.''
</P>
<P>
   Not for long. The US mashed the pedal to the floor and ripped
off a stunning sprint that left the British agape and astern. Fifth
gear is a wonderful thing to have. The Yanks just have to make sure
theirs clears Customs in Sydney next summer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-99 0155EDT &QL; 
