<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 02:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3972 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS &LR;      08-30 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME FOR PATRIOTS TO FACE UP TO LETDOWNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA _ There were more than 64,000 screaming fans in the
Buccaneers' state-of-the-art stadium Saturday night. It was warm.
The opposition was tough.
</P>
<P>
   There was every reason for the Patriots to be intense,
emotional, their adrenaline flowing. It was an exhibition game, but
an important one, the third of the preseason.
</P>
<P>
   New England also was playing in the city where it embarrassed
itself two years ago in the regular season, 27-7.
</P>
<P>
   Wouldn't the players want to show the fans of Tampa Bay and
their players that that result was a fluke?
</P>
<P>
   So how did a 45-14 thrashing occur? How was all the emotion,
intensity, and adrenaline left on the practice field? How did the
basics of tackling, rushing, blocking, catching, throwing, kicking,
covering suddenly seem so foreign? How did the Bucs, 8-8 last year,
seem so much quicker, faster, and stronger than the Patriots, who
were 9-7 and made the playoffs?
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't add up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt defensively we were playing at three different
levels,'' said Patriots nose tackle Chad Eaton. ``The line was
playing at one level, the linebackers at another, and the defensive
backs at another. It didn't feel right. The calls were great. The
communication was great. We were flying around. It just felt like
we weren't at the same stage we were last week. We need more heat
on the quarterback. There's more we need to come with. It was bad
and all, but at least it doesn't count. We have time to get it
together.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably one of the most embarrassing games I've played
in,'' said wide receiver Shawn Jefferson. ``I don't know how it
happened, but it happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everything looked horrible. Drew Bledsoe threw the ball well
except for an early interception and got his time in, like a
pitcher in spring training gets his innings in. Rookie running back
Kevin Faulk scampered for a 17-yard gain and netted 40 yards on
nine carries. Although the offensive line had real problems with
Warren Sapp and Brad Culpepper, rookie center Damien Woody appeared
to hold his own. Save for a fumble in the first quarter, Terry
Glenn made four very good and tough catches.
</P>
<P>
   But the Patriots' secondary and special teams were horrendous.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing special happened on special teams, and in fact, things
got worse. Rookie linebacker Andy Katzenmoyer wasn't as lost as he
was in his first game, but he wasn't as good as he was in his
second game. And the Tebucky Jones experiment at right corner had
another bad night.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no need to point fingers,'' said cornerback Ty Law,
who had one of his worst days as a Patriot. ``We win and lose as a
team. You can't single out one particular effort. You can't do it.
We have to ask ourselves what can we do as individuals to help this
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Law is right about the team concept, but his recently signed
huge contract makes him one of the leaders of this team. He is now
under a microscope. He can ask Bledsoe all about that; for years
Bledsoe had to live up to the expectations of his contract, and he
has done it. Law must do it as well.
</P>
<P>
   From now on Law will be expected to perform at an extremely high
level at a very visible position. Since he's now paid close to
Deion Sanders money, he'd better make that type of impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody's perfect,'' said Law. ``Just because we're veterans
we're still human beings. This is just a wake-up call. It's the
preseason, not the regular season. It's a very disappointing loss,
but we can go back and look at ourselves in the mirror and figure
out what each one of us has to do better. I love these guys around
here so I'm not gonna let them down.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Pete Carroll addressed the letdown straight on, but he's
had to make that speech too often during his tenure. By now
shouldn't there be some hint, something that lets him know that his
team isn't ready to play? And shouldn't he have a quick fix for
turning a flat team into an energetic one on the fly? That's what
he's paid $1 million per year to do.
</P>
<P>
   Coaches go by what happens during the week in practice. If the
sessions are fruitful, if everything on the checklist is
accomplished, then everything must be fine, they believe. But too
often everything has been fine and then at game time all that was
accomplished during the week is lost.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots have been off and on so far, they were out to lunch
against Washington, on their game vs. Dallas, and back to sleep
against Tampa Bay. In three days they visit Carolina, a team they
should dismantle easily if they are who they claim they are.
</P>
<P>
   It's time to start expecting consistency, or at least something
close to it. There aren't many teams in the NFL who offer such
consistency, but the good teams take the down periods and minimize
them. The Patriots have too many times when they don't click.
</P>
<P>
   None of this will be remembered in December if the Patriots are
vying for the AFC East title. But something has to be done about
this periodic amnesia _ when the players forget why they're among
the best in the world, and how they're expected to tackle, run,
block, catch, and cover at an intense, spirited, and productive
level.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
