<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-DEFENSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO STANDOUTS IN PATRIOTS' DEBACLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA _ Shawn Jefferson was at a virtual loss for words. Troy
Brown also searched for answers, and Drew Bledsoe sounded agitated.
The Patriots' three veterans conveyed a frustration and
disappointment that echoed throughout the locker room following the
team's humiliating loss to the Tampa Bay Buccaneers Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   But those veterans could take some solace from the 45-14
debacle. At least it won't affect their employment status.
</P>
<P>
   Others might not be so fortunate. Over the next week, NFL teams
pare their rosters twice: The first will come Tuesday, when each
roster must be cut to a maximum of 65 players.
</P>
<P>
   The second comes Sunday, when rosters must be cut to a maximum
of 53 players.
</P>
<P>
   Surely some Patriots rookies and free agents will endure a few
sleepless nights throughout that period.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night would have been a great time to shine, to put
forth a diamond-like effort amid 60 minutes of rough play by the
team as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, no player stood out. Because the poor performance came
so close to the season opener, one wonders how many more
opportunities players will get as the last exhibition game,
Thursday night at Carolina, looms.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the Tampa Bay effort would change his plans for the
Carolina game, coach Pete Carroll said, ``Yeah, most likely it
will.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't leave this as one of our last attempts. We'll play .
. . I don't want to say right now, because I have to figure it out.
But (Carolina) is much more important than it was.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if anyone played himself out of a job Saturday night,
Carroll said, ``I don't know that, but the word was out in the
locker room. I let it be known that guys playing without emotion,
just playing flat and not giving it up, are in trouble . . . making
this club. Just flat out, they're in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that some of the younger players didn't fill the statistics
sheet. It's just that nothing was sustained for long, by any
player.
</P>
<P>
   Even thrill-a-minute backup quarterback Michael Bishop wasn't
his usual self. The seventh-round pick had three rushes for 37
yards, but threw just three passes, completing two, while being
sacked for a 4-yard loss.
</P>
<P>
   Among the other draftees, Kevin Faulk, who is being groomed as
the team's go-to running back, had 40 yards on nine carries, but 17
of those yards came on one carry.
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Andy Katzenmoyer had four tackles, including one on
special teams. Safety Marcus Washington had three tackles, one on
special teams. Wide receiver Sean Morey didn't have any catches but
returned a kickoff 19 yards.
</P>
<P>
   In fact the only rookie who stood out Saturday night was safety
Tony George, who was ejected for throwing a forearm at Darnell
McDonald in the fourth quarter in retaliation for a blind-side hit
he suffered from the Bucs' rookie wide receiver.
</P>
<P>
   Before the ejection, George played solidly. He finished with
four tackles, one on special teams. But after the game, he was
apologetic, knowing he can't deny himself opportunities to shine.
</P>
<P>
   Asked where he felt he would fit in on the team long term, the
former standout from the University of Florida said, ``Definitely
as a special teams player. It's just like it was at Florida,
playing special teams and just make a mark, go out, and be excited
all the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're not excited to be out there in this league, the NFL,
then this is not the league for you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
