<HEADER>
A3987 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-TEN-USPRO-SAFIN-BOS &LR;      08-30 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-US </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAFIN PROVES HIMSELF AN ACE 
</HEADLINE>
 PRO-SAFIN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE _ As Marat Safin, a formidable juvenile hunk
resembling a fugitive tight end, crunched his 16th ace past the
equally long-reaching but short-circuited Greg Rusedski, a solitary
red-white-and-blue Russian flag was raised in the south grandstand.
</P>
<P>
   The flag-waver didn't look like Boris Yeltsin, the first hacker
and wayward president of Safin's country. But Boris probably wishes
he'd been sunbathing at Longwood Cricket Club Sunday instead of
trying to hold together the disintegrating homeland. He would have
been pleased to witness the efficient manner in which Safin, a
husky, 6-foot-4-inch Muscovite, carried the flag in formerly enemy
territory to disintegrate Rusedski and win the US Professional
Tennis Championship, 6-4, 7-6 (13-11).
</P>
<P>
   Another appreciative guy would have been one of Russia's first
tennis players, Leo Tolstoy, who also wrote books. Tolstoy, whose
faded court can be seen in outline on his Yasnaya Polyana estate,
might have thought of Safin as a sporting reincarnation of his own
embattled Pierre in ``War and Peace,'' somehow lugging the flag in
the war against Napoleon.
</P>
<P>
   And yet another countryman-with-racket, Czar Nicholas II, might
have decorated puissant Safin for winning the oldest of
professional tournaments. However, the US Pro wasn't launched until
1927, and poor Nicholas had been dead nine years, executed by Lenin
presumably for serving too many double faults.
</P>
<P>
   Safin didn't serve enough of them (six) to help the Czar of Zip,
Greg Rusedski, fastest server in the business. Rusedski, a
lefthanded fireballer holding the record, 149 miles per hour, found
himself uncomfortably in the fiery right hand of a boy bomber, and
hoisted by his own kind of petard.
</P>
<P>
   ``His serve was a joke,'' pronounced Rusedski, dealing in
gallows humor. ``I kept reaching and could never touch it.'' At
least 16 times anyway, plus eight service winners.
</P>
<P>
   Aces are supposed to be up Rusedski's short sleeve, but they
came streaming out of Safin's as though he were a magician or
somebody you wouldn't want to play poker (or tennis) with. Sixteen
dingers. One of every four points Safin won on his inviolable serve
was an ace. This kind of serving sorcery is hard to resist. Safin
served Rusedski blind _ the Englishman never saw a break point.
</P>
<P>
   Safin, 19, merely the third teenager to seize the crown (Aaron
Krickstein was 16 in 1984, Bjorn Borg 18 in 1974), did other good
things, too. He ran astoundingly, stealing points that Rusedski
thought were his. His low, skimming returns, particularly
double-fisted backhands, kept serve-and-volleying Rusedski hot and
bothered.
</P>
<P>
   As the No. 9 of the universe, a US Open finalist two years ago,
Rusedski figured to beat No. 33. But breaking Safin's serve was
about as easy as cracking George W. Bush's silence about youthful
fun and games.
</P>
<P>
   That 16th ace, prominently lifting the Russian flag, made it
10-9 for Safin in the excruciating 24-point tiebreaker that twisted
and turned for 14 minutes like a zonked-out snake. Rusedski was
dodging match points, Safin set points. Nothing so suspenseful had
concluded a US Pro finale.
</P>
<P>
   Safin's sixth double fault (the joke on himself) to 11-11 gave
Rusedski fleeting hope, but Greg was gone two points later, and the
Russian flag-flutterer halfway up the grandstand joyously flapped
while 3,300 patrons clapped.
</P>
<P>
   This match was about two guys starving for victory. Rusedski,
holder of seven titles, but none since last autumn, had said, ``It
sure would be good to take No. 8 out of here.''
</P>
<P>
   Safin? His career total was zero.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someday I have to win one. You never think about where. But
Boston is nice place. I have this good memory now.'' He was
breaking his maiden as they say at the racetrack, and he looks like
a fine horse for the Russians to ride in Davis Cup for a long time.
His someday in the winner's circle paid $46,000.
</P>
<P>
   Marat's journey to a first title went from Moscow with mother
love to Valencia, Spain, and through way stations across the world.
Mom, Raisa Islanova, a tennis teacher herself, packed him off to
Valencia six years ago to be schooled by coach Rafael Mensua. She
felt the weather and opportunity among the Spaniards was superior
to that of Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard. I was homesick. I had to learn Spanish fast,'' he
says. But the maternal get-outta-town treatment worked. His hunger
was momentarily abated, and as a reward he gets Pete Sampras to
gnaw on at the US Open.
</P>
<P>
   He'll remember Longwood forever for a couple of reasons. Aside
from the hunger that was checked by victory, he wasn't thirsty
enough Saturday. Failing to drink sufficiently during morning
practice, Safin got dehydrated and almost missed his semifinal date
with 1997 champ Sjeng Schalken, whom he beat after a slow, groggy
start, 5-7, 6-3, 6-1.
</P>
<P>
   Rehydrated in time by Dr. Rich Paul and trainer Bill Norris,
Safin learned a valuable lesson: Keep drinking. President Yeltsin
would agree, and advise vodka. Dr. Paul said water was just as
good.
</P>
<P>
   This was Safin's 38th pro tournament, perhaps confirming the old
Russian proverb, ``The 38th time never fails.'' It probably dates
back to the much-stabbed Rasputin, advisor to Czarina Alexandra,
who apparently succumbed on the 38th stroke.
</P>
<P>
   The flag that took over shortly after Rasputin, Czar Nicholas,
and Czarina Alexandra, the Soviet hammer and sickle, has also
succumbed. But the hammer is around, and named Marat Safin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-99 0207EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990830.0055 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 02:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3988 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS &LR;      08-30 0533
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARKES CAN'T STOP REVOLUTION FALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The Revolution have returned to their
customary place in the MLS standings. They are deep into a streak
of failures and desperately chasing a playoff berth.
</P>
<P>
   This is like a recurring nightmare for many of the Revolution
players, but it is a new experience for John Harkes. After a 2-1
loss to the Chicago Fire Saturday night extended the Revolution's
streak to nine games without a regulation-time victory, Harkes
seemed almost in a state of shock.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what to say anymore,'' Harkes said. ``We just
have to play basic soccer and be more of a team.''
</P>
<P>
   Harkes's clubs usually have been successful _ D.C. United went
to the MLS Cup final in the first three seasons of the league and
Sheffield Wednesday played in the FA and League Cup finals in
England. He seldom has been at a loss for words in his career.
</P>
<P>
   But there are few signs the Revolution are capable of
recovering, and Harkes's influence on the team has not been strong
enough to change its losing habits.
</P>
<P>
   Not only have the Revolution failed to win in regulation time
since a 3-2 victory over the MetroStars July 4, they have not taken
the lead against an Eastern Conference opponent since then. In the
last 810 minutes of play, they have taken the lead for a total of
48 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   This lack of success has taken a toll on the team's confidence
and revived memories of the nine-game losing streaks of 1997 and
'98. Nor have the Revolution displayed the resourcefulness or
attacking unpredictability that could rescue them.
</P>
<P>
   Management has shown signs of desperation by acquiring players
such as Jeff Baicher and Ariel Graziani, who was an influential
goal-scorer for nearly every team he played for in Latin America,
and found his form four minutes into his first game with Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Baicher nor Graziani, nor the trading of Graziani for
midfielder Leonel Alvarez, could be expected to solve the
Revolution's fatal weaknesses in defense, though. Walter Zenga is
still performing exceptionally well as a goalkeeper, but his
coaching tactics have been ineffective. There is simply not a
winning combination among the players.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution were humiliated by the Fire's first-half
performance. At this stage of the season, the team should be
galvanized but instead is filled with self-doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Harkes was especially upset by the way the Fire's first goal was
scored, as Jerzy Podbrozny easily shielded a defender about 25
yards from goal and found Frank Klopas with a short pass. Klopas
then penetrated to the penalty area and found Roman Kosecki, whose
finish was excellent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankie Klopas should never be allowed to chip a ball like
that,'' Harkes said. ``The defense needed to step up with Mike
Burns and put them offside. That's just basic soccer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Walter Zenga was making great saves but we weren't doing what
we are supposed to do. We are knocking ourselves down. We need to
have discipline, be smart, and use our heads. We need to work hard,
but work hard in the right places.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-99 0210EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
