<DOCNO> NYT19990830.0056 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 02:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3989 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-abortion-AZR &LR;      08-30 1041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-abortion-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA HIGH COURT LIFTS BLOCK TO 14 YEAR-OLD'S ABORTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINA LEONARD AND JANELLE COWGILL  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ The Arizona Supreme Court on Sunday cleared the way
for a 14-year-old girl to fly to Kansas for a late-term abortion by
overturning a state appeals judge's ruling that had temporarily
blocked it.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Jane Hull and other state officials declined to comment,
but law experts say state appeals may be exhausted.
</P>
<P>
   Late Sunday, it was unclear when the 14-year-old ward of the
state would leave for Kansas, where abortion laws are more liberal,
or whether she was already there.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone conference early Sunday, the high court voted 3-2
to overturn appellate Judge Michael Ryan's decision Saturday, which
temporarily blocked the foster child from aborting her 24-week-old
fetus.
</P>
<P>
   In making the decision, however, the court did not spell out its
reasoning, saying it would release a more detailed order later. The
order released Sunday concluded that the original trial judge who
ruled that the abortion could proceed had not ``abused his
discretion,'' nor was his ruling ``clearly erroneous.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether opponents of the decision have remaining grounds for
appeal is unclear.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney John P. Frank, an expert on constitutional law, said
that if the girl has left the state, the issue is dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``If she's gone, it becomes simple,'' he said. ``It becomes
zero.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way to lay hands on her.''
</P>
<P>
   However, if she's still here, the state could still take the
case to federal District Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's some side that wants to attempt to challenge
legally the state court order, they would have to find a way to get
to federal court,'' said attorney Marc Budoff, another legal
expert. &UR; ``A district judge would have to determine that there's a
federal issue involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Maricopa County Superior Court Judge William Sargeant
ordered that the girl be allowed to have the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Hull and the state attorney general questioned whether the fetus
was too advanced for an abortion.
</P>
<P>
   The state also questioned the girl's competency, and had asked
Sargeant to reconsider his ruling and allow a doctor to determine
whether the fetus could survive outside the womb.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday morning, Sargeant affirmed his earlier decision,
permitting the girl to seek an abortion. All the decisions have
been made in secret because the girl, who officials say was raped
or had sex with an adult, which is statutory rape, is a juvenile.
</P>
<P>
   The state immediately took the case to the Arizona Court of
Appeals, which ordered the temporary stay.
</P>
<P>
   Without releasing an explanation Sunday, the Supreme Court
vacated that decision.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Laura Knaperek, R-Tempe, and Rep. Jeff Groscost, R-Mesa,
say they are shocked that the Supreme Court sided with Sargeant's
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chiseled on the walls of the state Supreme Court are the
words, `Where law ends, tyranny begins,' '' Groscost said. ``With
today's 3-2 court decision, tyranny began and our hopes ended.
Tonight we pray for the little girl and her unborn child.''
</P>
<P>
   Knaperek said she was unhappy that the decision was made over
the telephone and, she believes, didn't get the scrutiny it
deserves.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears there wasn't enough time for Supreme Court justices
to make right choices based on information,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And Dr. Carolyn Gerster, chairwoman of Arizona Right to Life,
said she's outraged at the court's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``This baby is no longer a fetus, this is now a premature
baby,'' she said. ``What crime did this baby commit to be sentenced
to death? We have just begun to fight.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bruce Miller, director of Arizona Right to Choose, said that
the Supreme Court made the right decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have said, enough is enough _ this young woman had the
input of many more adults into her consideration of whether or not
to have an abortion than most teenagers do,'' according to a
release. ``We must respect her decision, and let her get on with
her life.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Sue Grace, R-north central Phoenix, said that the issue has
received due process, and that the state should accept that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to move on. What we need to move on to is
investigating the leak, and making sure this never happens again,''
Grace said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This girl's life has been devastated by this leak.''
</P>
<P>
   Chief Justice Thomas A. Zlaket and Vice Chief Justice Charles E.
Jones dissented. Both the majority and dissenters will release a
more detailed order explaining their arguments.
</P>
<P>
   Budoff said the court may not have made the decision based on
the abortion issue, but on procedural issues alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me that this is more of a philosophical and moral
news event than it is a legal news event,'' Budoff said.
</P>
<P>
   Frank added that the high court may not have ruled on abortion
at all, but instead looked at a person's ``right to travel.''
</P>
<P>
   But Budoff, who has practiced in Arizona for 25 years, said
although the case may not pose significant legal issues, it brings
up other interesting issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a lawyer's standpoint, you're interested to see the
tugging that goes on between legal and political and moral and
ethical issues,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials have planned to send the girl her to Kansas, where Dr.
George Tiller is the nation's leading practitioner of late-term
abortions.
</P>
<P>
   State attorneys reportedly focused their appeal, in part, on the
differences between Arizona's abortion law and the more liberal
guidelines in Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   Late-term abortions in Arizona are allowed only when the life or
health of the mother is in danger. An abortion is considered late
term if the fetus is able to survive outside the womb. In Arizona,
that determination is made by a doctor. No Arizona clinics
currently provide abortions after 20 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas, exceptions are allowed for late-term abortions if the
mother's life is in danger or if there is danger of major bodily
impairment or loss of function, which some, including Tiller, have
interpreted to mean the mental health of the mother. &QL; 
Republic writers Karina Bland and Chris Moeser contributed to this
article. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-99 0214EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
