</P>
<P>
   Without releasing an explanation Sunday, the Supreme Court
vacated that decision.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Laura Knaperek, R-Tempe, and Rep. Jeff Groscost, R-Mesa,
say they are shocked that the Supreme Court sided with Sargeant's
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chiseled on the walls of the state Supreme Court are the
words, `Where law ends, tyranny begins,' '' Groscost said. ``With
today's 3-2 court decision, tyranny began and our hopes ended.
Tonight we pray for the little girl and her unborn child.''
</P>
<P>
   Knapereksaid she was unhappy that the decision was made over
the telephone and, she believes, didn't get the scrutiny it
deserves.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears there wasn't enough time for Supreme Court justices
to make right choices based on information,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And Dr. Carolyn Gerster, chairwoman of Arizona Right to Life,
said she's outraged at the court's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``This baby is no longer a fetus, this is now a premature
baby,'' she said. ``What crime did this baby commit to be sentenced
to death? We have just begun to fight.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bruce Miller, director of Arizona Right to Choose, said that
the Supreme Court made the right decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have said, enough is enough _ this young woman had the
input of many more adults into her consideration of whether or not
to have an abortion than most teenagers do,'' according to a
release. ``We must respect her decision, and let her get on with
her life.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Sue Grace, R-north central Phoenix, said that the issue has
received due process, and that the state should accept that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to move on. What we need to move on to is
investigating the leak, and making sure this never happens again,''
Grace said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This girl's life has been devastated by this leak.''
</P>
<P>
   Chief Justice Thomas A. Zlaket and Vice Chief Justice Charles E.
Jones dissented. Both the majority and dissenters will release a
more detailed order explaining their arguments.
</P>
<P>
   Budoff said the court may not have made the decision based on
the abortion issue, but on procedural issues alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me that this is more of a philosophical and moral
news event than it is a legal news event,'' Budoff said.
</P>
<P>
   Frank added that the high court may not have ruled on abortion
at all, but instead looked at a person's ``right to travel.''
</P>
<P>
   But Budoff, who has practiced in Arizona for 25 years, said
although the case may not pose significant legal issues, it brings
up other interesting issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a lawyer's standpoint, you're interested to see the
tugging that goes on between legal and political and moral and
ethical issues,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials have planned to send the girl her to Kansas, where Dr.
George Tiller is the nation's leading practitioner of late-term
abortions.
</P>
<P>
   State attorneys reportedly focused their appeal, in part, on the
differences between Arizona's abortion law and the more liberal
guidelines in Kansas.
</P>
