<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 02:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3992 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-ROBINSON-AZR &LR;      08-30 1854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBINSON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEATH OF PITCHER MARS WINNING YEAR FOR ARIZONA DIAMONDBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KENT SOMERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ Every Sunday, Lorrie Robinson buckles her
2-year-old son, Chase, into his car seat and drives to what he
calls ``the park.'' She follows the narrow road past the tall, old
trees with moss draping from the branches to the newest section of
the Oaklawn Cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   On clear summer days, she can't help but think this is the
perfect final resting spot for her husband, Kenny: On a mound in
the bright sunshine.
</P>
<P>
   While the Diamondbacks pursue a pennant in just their second
year of existence, it's easy to forget that this season began with
tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   A one-car rollover on a dark Tucson road. One Diamondbacks
pitcher, Kenny Robinson, dead. Another, John Rosengren, charged
with manslaughter after tests showed he had a blood-alcohol level
of 0.162, above Arizona's legal limit of 0.10.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took two people's lives,'' Liz Robinson, Kenny's mother,
said of the Feb. 28 accident. ``It took John's life, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosengren was arrested on suspicion of second-degree murder and
released on $75,000 bail. A grand jury later indicted him on the
manslaughter charge. If convicted, he faces a prison term of seven
to 21 years.
</P>
<P>
   Rosengren, whose trial is set for Sept. 28, has been out of
baseball since the accident and is living with his parents near
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   The Robinson family had dreamed this would be a breakthrough
year for Kenny. His injured shoulder was returning to health and
the Diamondbacks were in need of relief help.
</P>
<P>
   No one seemed to care that Kenny wasn't the prototype major
league pitcher. On rosters, he was listed at 5-foot-9, but he was
really three inches shorter.
</P>
<P>
   ``But my heart is 5-9,'' he liked to say.
</P>
<P>
   Lorrie and Kenny hoped that at 29, Kenny's career would be
reborn in Arizona. Dreaming he would spend the year with the
Diamondbacks, calling her twice a day, just as he did every day
they had been apart in their 8-year marriage. Telling her of the
excitement of a pennant race, asking about Chase, laughing together
at their $500 monthly phone bills. Still building their days around
those calls.
</P>
<P>
   Lorrie Robinson still can't bring herself to erase Kenny's voice
from the answering machine at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the biggest thing I can't do yet,'' Lorrie said. ``I just
finally opened his suitcases from when they shipped them home.
That's been five months.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenny's parents, Liz and Ken Sr., hoped to travel to their son's
games or watch them on satellite. Instead of driving to games now,
they take weekend trips to try to fill lonely hours. &QL; 
Player distraught &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rosengren declined to comment, but he is distraught over the
accident, said his lawyer, Mike Piccarreta of Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   ``John felt it was inappropriate to discuss what he's going
through at this time, and that all thoughts and concerns should be
for the Robinson family,'' Piccarreta said.
</P>
<P>
   North Silverbell Road in Tucson is narrow and filled with gentle
curves and dips as it crosses desert washes. Running roughly
parallel to Interstate 10, which dissects the city, the road is
poorly lit in the 3000 block, where the accident occurred. It's not
a challenging drive, but it does require a clear, attentive mind.
</P>
<P>
   There are few details available about the events of that night.
The families aren't sure where the two men went, and authorities
won't say.
</P>
<P>
   What is known is that in the early evening of Feb. 27, Kenny
called Lorrie as usual. He said Rosengren was coming over that
night to watch the North Carolina-Duke basketball game and that
they would probably make an early night of it.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't.
</P>
<P>
   According to police reports, the players were southbound on
Silverbell, a two-lane road at that point, about 1:40 a.m. They
were less than a mile from Robinson's apartment when Rosengren's
'97 Explorer drifted off the east side of the road onto a dirt
shoulder. It was estimated to be traveling at 55 mph, 10 mph over
the speed limit. The Explorer then came back on to the road and
turned over on the driver's side.
</P>
<P>
   Neither player was wearing a seat belt, and paramedics had to
use an ax to break out the front windshield, so they could pull the
two men from the vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Robinson suffered a severe head injury and was pronounced
dead at the scene. He had a blood-alcohol level of 0.258, according
to the medical examiner's report. That figure surprised Robinson's
family and friends, who said he preferred staying home and playing
video games to drinking and night life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something that was very out of character,'' Lorrie
Robinson said. ``We didn't even go out or anything like that when
he was home.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosengren, who wasn't seriously hurt, smelled of alcohol and his
speech was slurred, according to police.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Expletive), I was the one driving and it's all my fault,'' he
told police that night, according to reports.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson and Rosengren weren't the best of friends, having known
each only a month or so, but they were bound by similar
circumstances. &QL; 
Coming off injuries &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Both were coming off arm injuries and hoped to make the
big-league roster. Both reported early to the Diamondbacks spring
training camp in Tucson to continue rehabilitation work.
</P>
<P>
   Now, they are forever tied by the events of one horrible night.
</P>
<P>
   When two Jacksonville police officers rang her doorbell that
Sunday morning, Lorrie Robinson's first thought was that something
had happened to her parents, who live just a few minutes away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is your husband Kenny Robinson?'' they asked.
</P>
<P>
   Her breath stolen away, Lorrie had one thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please tell me he's OK.''
</P>
<P>
   They told Lorrie that Kenny had been killed in a car accident.
They had no details. She called her parents, who were there when
Lorrie called Kenny's mom and dad, who live near Akron, Ohio, where
Kenny grew up.
</P>
<P>
   Six months later, the families still wonder about the events of
that night. Kenny was fanatical about wearing his seat belt, yet he
didn't have his on. He felt strongly about drinking and driving,
yet he was riding with an apparently impaired driver.
</P>
<P>
   At times, the Robinsons think they would like to talk to
Rosengren, to find out more about that night. Rosengren is
prevented by Arizona law from contacting the family until his case
has been adjudicated.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, Lorrie Robinson thinks, the family would only be
getting one side of the story. She wonders if the entire truth will
ever be known.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know him (Rosengren),'' Lorrie said. ``I just know how
I feel about drinking and driving. You could be the nicest person
in the world and still get behind the wheel of a car and something
happens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying Kenny was not at fault. Obviously, he got into
the truck. They could have called a cab. I just don't know. I'm
affected. He (Rosengren) is affected. We're both going through a
whole whirlwind of emotions. I can't say they are exactly the same,
but . . .''
</P>
<P>
   She would like people to know that Kenny was more than just a
journeyman pitcher and is hopeful that he will be remembered more
for how he lived than how he died.
</P>
<P>
   He was the kind of guy who called his parents five times while
driving across the country for spring training.
</P>
<P>
   ``What other 29-year-old man would do that?'' Liz asked.
</P>
<P>
   Ken once organized a baby shower for a minor-league teammate's
wife and thought nothing of covering a round of golf for a young
minor-league player strapped for cash. He could make people laugh
by imitating the checkout scanner at a grocery store, driving
clerks nuts in the process.
</P>
<P>
   Liz Robinson affectionately calls her son ``a momma's boy.''
Kenny called his parents several times a week and always after he
pitched, no matter the time. The family's social life revolved
around sports and the games played by Kenny and his younger sister,
Christi.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you this much, we lived Kenny's life with him, so
when he dies, that kind of dies too,'' Liz said.
</P>
<P>
   A big man &QL; 
Robinson was a rarity in baseball _ a short right-handed pitcher
who made it to the big leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Growing up, it was always the taller kids who were tried first
at pitcher, even though Robinson was begging for the chance.
Eventually, coaches would let the little guy throw and then realize
their mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``He always said, `I don't understand why all they want is
height, height, height,' '' Lorrie said. ``If somebody has the
talent, why does height have to factor into it?''
</P>
<P>
   When Robinson was in the minors, opposing fans could be brutal.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could just hear people jawing at him from the stands.
`Don't you need your step-stool?' Or ``Hey, Tattoo, where's the
plane?' That was a cute one.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Robinson began to pitch and the ribbing stopped. He had a
fastball that reached the mid-90s, and he spent parts of three
seasons in the majors, two with Toronto and one with Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks claimed him off waivers from Toronto in 1998
and had him targeted as a middle reliever or closer until he was
sidelined by a shoulder injury suffered in spring training.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he worked hard all year to come back from his injury,''
said Joe Garagiola Jr., the Diamondbacks' general manager. ``And I
guess that's the principal thing I take away from our association
and time with Ken _ his competitiveness, his determination.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he was hard-nosed on the mound, Robinson was soft-hearted
off of it. He would send his son flowers, balloons and chocolates
on Valentine's Day. He wrote poetry and short stories.
</P>
<P>
   Before important times in his life, he would write letters to
those close to him, telling them how much they meant to him.
</P>
<P>
   After the accident, some close friends cleaned out Kenny's
apartment in Tucson to send things back to Lorrie. On a closet
shelf, Diana found a letter that Kenny had written to Lorrie and
Chase before he underwent shoulder surgery in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   He wanted them to know how he felt should something go wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time you see Chase smile, please see me smiling, too,
because I'll be there watching over you.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you think about me, I want you to think one thing _ that
I was a good person who worked my ass off and never gave in or
quit.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last year of Kenny's life, he was able to do so many
things he never had before, Lorrie said. The surgery kept him out
of baseball in 1998, and he spent the summer at home for the first
time in years. He took pride in his yard, and Lorrie would tease
him when neighbors would ask for tips.
</P>
<P>
   Kenny attended his 10-year high school reunion, bought a
Corvette, saw an old friend for the first time in years, shook
hands with President Clinton during his visit to spring training.
</P>
<P>
   A Major League Baseball pension and a life insurance policy are
allowing Chase and Lorrie to live comfortably in the home the
couple bought in Jacksonville just over two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   She has a business degree from Florida State and plans to
returns to work once Chase is a little older.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
