<HEADLINE>
ABC STRIKES GOLD WITH `MILLIONAIRE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Combine a Kathie Lee-less Regis Philbin, a reworking of a
British game show and the third-place network in the dead of summer
television and what do you get?
</P>
<P>
   A ratings monster. A return to the nostalgic days when game
shows fared well in prime time. Or further proof that people will
watch just about anything you put in front of them in August.
Depends upon your point of view.
</P>
<P>
   If you're an ABC executive, the answer is clear. During the
first week of its 13-day run, ``Who Wants To Be a Millionaire?''
was the second-, fifth-, sixth-, 12th- and 18th-most popular show
on television. Ratings for the latter part of the run _ which ended
Sunday night _ will doubtless climb even higher. Numbers like that
guaranteed that the show would return in some form, and it will,
for November sweeps. (Why not? How many countries can they send
Drew Carey to?)
</P>
<P>
   Even though no one actually won $1 million, ``Millionaire'' is a
certifiable phenomenon, a water-cooler topic. Who among us hasn't
mentally trashed the knucklehead from Richmond, Va., for not going
for the $1 million question last week? Doesn't everyone know that
Jethro Tull won the first Grammy for heavy metal? Sure, his
$500,000 winnings would have been whacked to $32,000 if he'd
missed, but you know you'd have gone for it.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you also wouldn't have known Pope John Paul I's real
name, which this guy did to get to the $1 million question.
Details, details. This is television we're talking about.
</P>
<P>
   (A contestant on Thursday night missed a $64,000 question _
really _ when he thought the Keating Five was a group of bankers.
This bodes well for John McCain's presidential aspirations.)
</P>
<P>
   On the off chance that you recently defected to the United
States and have no idea what all the fuss is over, here's a quick
explanation (clip and save for the show's return):
</P>
<P>
   One contestant is chosen from a group of 10, who qualified for a
free trip to New York and the studio over the phone. Most had to
pay $1.50 for an area-code 900 call; lucky residents of nine states
(including Arizona) made free 800 calls.
</P>
<P>
   Once chosen, the contestant sits across from Philbin and answers
a series of questions, beginning at $100 and more or less doubling
in value every time. They also increase in difficulty.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds about as interesting as a root canal so far. But the
producers jack up the tension with a space-age set, smarmy music,
tricky lighting and annoying comments from Philbin, who squeezes as
much drama out of a trivia question as Bill Clinton does from an
apology. (But Regis doesn't cry.)
</P>
<P>
   Contestants see the question before deciding to continue. Plus,
they are allowed three ``Lifelines.'' They can eliminate two of the
four possible answers, giving them a 50-50 shot. They can ask the
audience for help (sort of an instant poll). Or they can make a
live phone call to a presumably smart friend, asking for the
answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just doubling the money, questions get a little more
intense,'' Philbin told TV critics earlier this summer. ``But the
production values surrounding this is what really is the icing on
the cake.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lighting gets a little more intense, the music gets a
little stronger, the guy gets up to a quarter million dollars,
suddenly you hear a heartbeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then he calls his friend . . . and asks him the question
with the four possible answers, and that second hand is ticking,
you're down to 16 seconds, the music comes in _ I tell you, it's
really terrific television.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Davies, the executive producer of the show, looked to an
old-time game-show host to explain the phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Monty Hall used to say that every great game show has one
moment where the contestant is going to win everything or lose
everything,'' Davies said. ``This program takes that moment,
heightens it with lighting and music and the intimacy of the set,
and plays that moment again and again and again. And it's a very,
very simple idea.''
</P>
<P>
   It really, really is. Much like the classic '50s game shows
were. Which is probably the real reason people watch the show _ it
seems so simple, you could see yourself winning. And answering
trivia questions is more work than buying a lottery ticket _ you
would feel like you earned your windfall.
</P>
<P>
   The simplicity is deceptive, of course.
</P>
<P>
   ``The questions are not impossible,'' Philbin said on a show
last week. ``It's the broad range that'll kill you every time.''
</P>
<P>
   Before you start naming your first-born son Regis, remember one
thing: It's August. ``Millionaire'' was up against the likes of
reruns of ``Jesse'' and ``Jag.'' That's not much of a test _ a
scrambled porno channel would probably do well in that competition.
</P>
<P>
   (Not to imply that anyone would really watch scrambled porno.
That was a hypothetical example. Besides, I was young.)
</P>
<P>
   So, in the spirit of the thing, when ``Millionaire'' returns,
will it: A) continue to kill in the ratings; B) suffer a huge drop;
C) torpedo ABC's season or D) send Regis scurrying back to Kathie
Lee with his tail between his legs?
</P>
<P>
   You have until November to answer. &QL; 
Reach Bill Goodykoontz at (602) 444-8974, or at
bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
