<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONDO-REVIVAL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONDOS MAKE COMEBACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Anna McDonald and her husband just put their
suburban Reseda condominium up for sale at $185,000, and they are
confident they won't have much trouble finding a buyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have talked to a few people who say the market is good right
now. I'm not in a hurry. If I don't sell this year I will just wait
until next year,'' she said on a recent Sunday while preparing the
tri-level, 1,600-square-foot unit for the parade of prospective
buyers she anticipates.
</P>
<P>
   Time and synergy could prove the McDonalds right.
</P>
<P>
   The buyers are definitely out there.
</P>
<P>
   And the longer the McDonalds wait to sell, the more money their
unit is likely to fetch.
</P>
<P>
   Locked in a slump from 1993 to 1997, the area's condominium
market has finally enlisted in the real estate recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to robust single-family home market _ in which both sales
and prices are rising _ condominiums are enjoying a renaissance of
sorts these days as well.
</P>
<P>
   While on average accounting for about one-third of all home
sales, the condominiums market now is showing the same trends
common for single-family homes.
</P>
<P>
   Sales and prices are rising on an annual basis. And condominiums
that are priced right and show well do not stay on the market for
very long.
</P>
<P>
   Consider that:
</P>
<P>
   _ During July, the most recent month for which figures are
available, escrow closed on 361 condominiums in the San Fernando
Valley, up 14.6percent from July 1998, according to the Southland
Regional Association of Realtors.
</P>
<P>
   The median price, the point at which half the homes sold for
more and half for less, was $127,000, or an annual gain of
3.3percent.
</P>
<P>
   Condominium sales have increased for five of the first six
months of the year on an annual basis.
</P>
<P>
   _ In the Santa Clarita Valley, condominium sales boomed last
month, soaring 50 percent to 117 units. The median price was
$133,000, a gain of nearly 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Fierce competition for single-family homes in Santa Clarita is
credited with fueling condominium sales. Of the 1,268 properties
listed for sale, 381 were condominiums.
</P>
<P>
   _ Realtors also report that condominium sales are brisk in the
Conejo Valley as well. Pat Evans, a broker at Coldwell Banker in
Thousand Oaks, said activity is picking up in the condo market,
which in the Conejo Valley can mean homes as inexpensive as $90,000
and as pricey as $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``The acceptability of that type of property has increased
dramatically in the last few years. More people are now willing to
consider (condominiums) as well as a single-family home,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   That's the case for Northridge residents Kristin and Matthew
Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   They are shopping for a condominium in the $175,000 price range
and focusing their search on the Simi Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Right now they believe they can get more house for their money
in buying a condominium.
</P>
<P>
   ``The quality of the home itself, if you are able to find it, is
much higher than the single-family home in the comparable price
range,'' Kristin Mitchell said.
</P>
<P>
   Their house hunting has been a little bit frustrating in that
they have been looking on and off for about four months. Meanwhile,
prices and interest rates have been rising.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing that the amount that are out there are decreasing
and the prices have been going up,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Mitchells are working with Prudential California Realty
brokers Judy and Gary Washburn, who say condominiums are moving
fast in today's market.
</P>
<P>
   ``A town home properly prepared for sale can be sold within the
first 45 days on the market if the price is good,'' Gary Washburn
said.
</P>
<P>
   Other Realtors say the sales pace can be even quicker.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Miller, a broker at Paramount Properties, recalls quick
buyer response to a unit at the Northbrook complex on Vanalden
Street in suburban Winnetka that had no trouble attracting buyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The minute the sign went in the window we had someone calling
making an offer on it,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   Why the sudden spike of interest _ and prices _ in the condo
market? Industry experts say that for much of the decade, condos
have trailed the single-family market at a greater pace than
normal.
</P>
<P>
   The recession of the early 1990s sent real estate into a tail
spin, with prices plunging along with sales. The median price for a
single-family home peaked at $245,000 three times 1989 but had
fallen to $155,000 by September 1997.
</P>
<P>
   That meant there were lots of homes on the market with prices
less than the median. Since single-family home prices were so low,
first-time buyers were able to jump into this market, leapfrogging
the condominium market.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, the local real estate market has finally returned
to normal, with condos positioned as a reachable stepping stone for
many first-time buyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a portion of the overall market, condominiums went into
decline and now they are back today to where their natural position
is within the market,'' said John Karevoll, an analyst with
Acxiom/DataQuick, a market research firm.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor helping the condominium market is the tight
supply of single-family homes for sale. During July, 4,778
single-family homes were listed for sale in the San Fernando
Valley, just 1 percent ahead of last year's number and well below
what experts believe is an ample inventory for a community the size
of the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   So consumers who have been sitting on the fence likely will find
themselves paying more today for less house, whether it's a
condominium or single-family home, than six months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are an awful lot of entry-level buyers who missed the
boat when it came to small homes so they are good candidates to buy
a condo,'' Karevoll said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-99 0258EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
