<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 03:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4002 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON     08-30 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 LIFE IS JUST A BOWL OF MOLECULES  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Woke up, got out of bed, dragged a comb across my head.
</P>
<P>
   But not in that order. Made a mental note to make myself a list
so I can get the sequence right next time, then forgot where I put
the note.
</P>
<P>
   Column not making sense yet? Good. It's supposed to be about
life, more or less, so if the column makes sense, something is
terribly wrong.
</P>
<P>
   I don't feel like eating this early, so maybe I'll just snort
some food-flavored molecules.
</P>
<P>
   At Crabtree and Evelyn in the Stanford Shopping Center, Daryl
Glen came across aerosal sprays for the kitchen, in flavors such as
``Fresh Salad'' and ``Patisserie.''
</P>
<P>
   I'd pick some up, but they might clash with my Fresh Flautas
aftershave and my Cheeze Doodles deodorant.
</P>
<P>
   The spray is a great idea for dieters, though. An aerosal blast
of Patisserie in each nostril and a shot of Salad, and who needs
lunch? Don't do it while riding Muni, though, or you'll have to
pass the can around, give everyone a hit. Don't bogart that
Patisserie, my friend.
</P>
<P>
   For a more substantial breakfast, you might find something on
the junk e-mail I received, a list of the worst convenience foods.
No. 6 is Armour Pork Brains in Milk Gravy, which is not yet
available in aerosal aroma form.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, brains are served scrambled with eggs, but I'm an
optimist, I like my brains sunny-side up. You are what you eat, so
I don't eat scrambled brains. And to enhance creativity, I eat only
the left brain.
</P>
<P>
   And when I finish my pork brains, I always say, ``Th-th-that's
all, folks!''
</P>
<P>
   AFTER inhaling breakfast, I picked up the newspaper and read
that ``The Blair Witch Project'' is under attack from witches.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The movie) defames us and makes us less human,'' says a
spokeswitch in Salem. ``We still get people asking us if we fly on
brooms. ... (The movie) both exploits and reinforces negative
stereotypes about witches.' ''
</P>
<P>
   (In a related story, sharks angry over their species' portrayal
in ``Deep Blue Sea'' have been picketing off Stinson Beach.)
</P>
<P>
   It's sad, really, the yuppification of witches. They had a look
that worked _ the broom, pointy hat and nose wart. Effective, and
commercial. Nobody wants Halloween cutouts of witches in hip
hairstyles and Honda Civics.
</P>
<P>
   Now instead of frightening us, witches just come off as cranky
chicks, although I reserve the right to change my opinion if I wake
up tomorrow as a green frog.
</P>
<P>
   ``THANKS,'' I said to the man on the sidewalk as I took a
quarter out of the cup he thrust at me. I had just come up from
BART, where the trains offer cars in three temperatures: Cool, Warm
and Turkish Prison.
</P>
<P>
   Some cars are so hot that BART should give out tree branches so
passengers could sauna-flog one another.
</P>
<P>
   Out on the street it was cool and gray, and one thing you can
say about San Francisco is that we do summer, but we don't overdo
summer. A couple days of lukewarm sun, then on to fall. Sometimes
the only outward signs of summer are the Macy's Christmas displays.
</P>
<P>
   At Fifth and Mission streets in San Francisco Sunday, motorists
were leading lives of noisy desperation, playing a hornish
symphony. I'm changing my view of road rage. It's a good, healthy
outlet for anger and frustration: Blow it out your horn, hurl
curses and gestures. Rageaerobics. Arrive at your destination
refreshed, as if from a bracing game of racquetball or squash, then
find there's no parking.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, I suggested alleviating the parking crunch, especially
when the Giants' new ballpark opens, by using mothballed aircraft
carriers for floating parking lots.
</P>
<P>
   One reader said that would be great, then if we get into another
war with Saddam, we could ship over a few carriers filled with our
SUVs and guzzle up all of his gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   Another reader also liked the carrier idea, with a twist: ``Fill
'em with cars, then sink 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, no,'' said Sue Kemp. ``Tow the carriers to the airport
between games so they can be used as those extra runways SFO says
it needs.''
</P>
<P>
   Flying commercial jets can get pretty boring, surely the pilots
would welcome the challenge and adrenalin rush of landing a jumbo
jet on an aircraft carrier. It would be a more exciting spectator
sport than baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Weirder still, it turns out that the idea of a carrier as
ballpark car lot was pitched to Mayor Willie Brown last year, and
reportedly he loved it and the idea is under study. The Navy would
be asked to donate a carrier to be converted to a naval museum and
parking lot for about 1,500 cars.
</P>
<P>
   So what's the point of presenting ludicrous ideas for their
alleged humor value when real life beats you to it?
</P>
<P>
   I'm making a mental note to forget the whole thing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
