<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 03:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4003 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r i BC-TRUFFLE-TARIFFS-SFCHR     08-30 0995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRUFFLE-TARIFFS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRADE WAR ENTANGLES TRUFFLES, OTHER EUROPEAN DELICACIES
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By KIM SEVERSON 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  By Thanksgiving, Roquefort cheese _ if you can find it _ will
probably double in price to about $30 a pound. That good French
mustard you like might be $6 a jar. And prized white European
truffles could cost a staggering $2,800 a pound.
<P>
   Damn politics.
</P>
<P>
   In July, the United States slapped a 100 percent retaliatory
tariff on selected imported European foods like Dijon mustard,
filled French chocolate bars, canned Italian tomatoes and foie
gras. And the United States is just beginning to feel its effects.
</P>
<P>
   The penalty was the latest chapter in a lengthy dispute over
beef. Since 1989, the 15-nation European Union has refused to
import U.S. beef treated with growth hormones. In July, the World
Trade Organization said the United States could collect millions of
dollars in customs tariffs on certain European food products as a
punishment.
</P>
<P>
   The tariff promises to double the price of luxury foods
gourmands hold near and dear and, some in the food business
predict, cause a run on certain items.
</P>
<P>
   Enough pretariff shipments of nonperishable items like raspberry
jam and Italian biscotti are already in American warehouses that
consumers won't feel the pinch for a few months, importers and
specialty store owners say. But prices of perishable commodities
are starting to climb.
</P>
<P>
   Roquefort, a blue cheese produced only in a certain region in
France and the only cheese on the hit list, is one of the first
items to reflect the tariff.
</P>
<P>
   Some importers quickly flew in as much as they could to beat the
tariff, and passed only the extra shipping cost on to cheese
sellers. The real price hike on the cheese, which is selling for
about $14 to $16 a pound retail, will come once the warehouses are
empty _ which could be as soon as November or as late as January,
depending on demand.
</P>
<P>
   Truffle lovers are particularly worried. The season for fresh
European white truffles - most prized among lovers of the fungus -
begins in October. Last year, black truffles were about $500 a
pound and the best white truffles cost $1,400 a pound. Since the
base price is driven by the abundance of the harvest, no one knows
if the price will double this year.
</P>
<P>
   For chefs trying to price and sell advance reservations for
special holiday dinners in which truffles traditionally play a
starring role, the uncertainty is maddening.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the millennium. People will be expecting foie gras and
truffles and caviar,'' says Roland Passot, owner/chef at La Folie,
one of San Francisco's top French restaurants, where 100 pounds of
truffles were consumed last season. He says that no matter the
price, he will buy truffles. But he doesn't know how it will affect
the price of the special New Year's Eve feast he has planned.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the items, like fresh or frozen pork and beef products,
are sent to meat processors and thus won't hit consumers as hard,
said Mike Conway, president of MJ Borelli and Co., a meat importer
in Emeryville that sells high-quality Italian pork and other raw
meat products to salami makers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just bought extra hoping things will blow over,'' he said.
``It's just sort of in the hands of the government now.''
</P>
<P>
   In other cases, some products simply aren't making it to store
shelves. Dean Wilkinson, purchasing manager for International
Delicacies in Emeryville, had $17,000 worth of Italian toast and
bread products on a barge heading across the Atlantic when the
tariff hit. The supplier ordered the ship to turn around because
the Italian company wasn't about to absorb the tax.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's grumbling about it,'' Wilkinson said of the
tariff. ``No one thought they'd do it. It could be years before
this thing is over.''
</P>
<P>
   Some importers predict that a strong dollar and deals by
European food manufacturers will combine to keep prices on some
items from doubling. And there's always good, old American
products. Some chefs say that the tariff will be a boost for
companies that process California tomatoes, domestic pork products
or the fatty goose livers called foie gras.
</P>
<P>
   But some things just can't be replaced, such as Italian or
French truffles or Roquefort cheese. And that's exactly why those
products were chosen, said Steve Gaddis, president of Pacific
Cheese in Hayward, the largest importer of Roquefort in the western
United States.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; `Highly Political'
</P>
<P>
   ``The selection of this cheese is highly political. The items
were selected to have an impact and help solve the problem as a
negotiation item.''
</P>
<P>
   Politics played a role in protecting another item from the list.
Prosciutto, a dense, salt-cured, air-dried ham made only in Parma,
Italy, and a constant in deli cases, was taken off the list after
intensive lobbying by importers.
</P>
<P>
   How long the tax will last is anybody's guess. Under the
agreement, the United States can only collect $116.8 million using
the luxury tariff. Some importers say the prices will drop once the
cap is reached. Others hope political pressure will force an
agreement sooner.
</P>
<P>
   Already, French farmers are fighting back. In the southwestern
region where Roquefort is produced, the local government earlier
this month imposed a 100 percent tax on bottles of Coca-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   And the French press reported that last week the farmers in the
same region dumped fruit, vegetables and manure in front of
McDonald's outlets. The protests began earlier in the month when
farmers from a region known for its foie gras occupied a McDonald's
in the town of Gers.
</P>
<P>
   That sort of pressure might actually make a difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see how it goes,'' said Henry Kaplan, president of De
Choix Specialty Foods, a company with offices in New York and San
Francisco. ``The Europeans are on vacation now. When they come back
and see how it affects their business they'll come to their
senses.''  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
