<SLUG> BC-DOMASH-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
INTERNET HELPS CHECK VALUE OF STOCKS &HT;    By HARRY DOMASH
 &HT;    c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It seems every time I see mutual fund managers
interviewed on television, they say that they only buy undervalued
growth stocks. That sounds great, but how do you know whether a
stock is undervalued or overvalued?
</P>
<P>
   You can use the Internet to find the answer.
</P>
<P>
   There are innumerable methods to measure a stock's worth. Most
calculate a fair value for the stock and then define companies with
share prices above fair value as overvalued, and those below fair
value as undervalued.
</P>
<P>
   One widely used approach involves comparing the company's
price-earnings ratio (stock price divided by annual earnings per
share) with its annual earnings growth rate, expressed in
percentages. Originally, the company's past earnings growth history
was used, but now most analysts use expected future earnings
growth.
</P>
<P>
   The Motley Fool (www.fool.com) packaged the concept into a
formula the company named the Fool Ratio _ a stock's PE divided by
the expected earnings growth rate. The idea caught on, but the name
didn't stick, and now it's called the PEG (PE divided by Growth).
</P>
<P>
   The Motley Fool defines fair value to be the price where the
earnings growth rate and the PE are equal, and the PEG equals 1.
For example, if a company's shares are trading at 20 times earnings
and earnings are expected to grow 20 percent a year, the stock is
fairly valued. But given the market's current exuberance, some
analysts say fair value is when the PEG is 1.5 or even 2.0.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKSELECTOR: StockSelector (www.stockselector.com) gives an
easy way to find fair value using a variety of approaches. Type a
stock symbol into the box labeled Ticker, select Valuations from
the drop-down menu, click on Submit and you're done.
</P>
<P>
   Seconds later, you'll see fair values determined by PEG and
several other valuation methods. StockSelector displays the fair
value price determined by each method, and the difference between
the fair value price and the closing price expressed in dollars and
in percentage.
</P>
<P>
   I tested StockSelector's valuation methods Tuesday (August 24),
using Airborne Freight (ABF) as an example. Airborne currently is
on the outs with many analysts, and Tuesday's closing stock price,
$24.94, was about 40 percent below its recent high. Airborne's
earnings for the June quarter were below the year-ago quarter and
also below the consensus estimate of analysts. Airborne attributed
the shortfall to a ``lack of growth in domestic shipments.''
</P>
<P>
   StockSelector's PEG Value calculator compares next fiscal year's
expected earnings with the estimated long-term earnings growth
rate. It came up with a fair value of $33.86 for Airborne, 36
percent above Tuesday's closing price.
</P>
<P>
   StockSelector's other fair value calculators include:
</P>
<P>
   StockSelector Value: Based on the idea that a stock tends to
trade around a consistent PE ratio, this program calculates a
five-year average PE for the stock and multiplies it by next year's
estimated earnings. This method valued Airborne at $42.16 per
share.
</P>
<P>
   Present Value: This is a conservative method that uses a
combination of book value and inflation-adjusted earnings
forecasts. The fair value for Airborne using Present Value was
$39.54.
</P>
<P>
   Industry Value: This system uses the average PE for the
company's industry _ in this case, air delivery/ freight services _
and next year's earnings forecasts for the company. The rationale
is that in the long term, that a company's PE will approximate the
PE ratio for its industry. This approach came up with a fair value
of $40.18 for Airborne.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; D &LR; ividend Value: This formula uses the company's five-year
average dividend rate. It came up with $16 for Airborne's fair
value.
</P>
<P>
   QUICKEN'S APPROACH: The Quicken site (www.quicken.com) recently
added an ``intrinsic value'' calculator, which uses estimated
future earnings to determine the present value. Benjamin Graham,
who is considered the founder of fundamental analysis, first put
forth the concept of intrinsic value. It is a favorite tool of many
value investors.
</P>
<P>
   You can find intrinsic value on Quicken by first getting a
quote, then clicking on Evaluator and lastly selecting Intrinsic
Value. Quicken's program came up with an intrinsic value of an
incredible $525 per share for Airborne Freight. Quicken says its
evaluator still is in the test stage and that its result for
Airborne indicates that either Quicken has more testing to do or
Airborne Freight's share price has terrific upside potential. I
suppose time will give us the answer.
</P>
<P>
   VECTOR VEST: You'll find another view of fair value at Vector
Vest (www.vectorvest.com). We described Vector Vest in our column
on second opinions a few weeks ago. Select the Free Stock Analysis,
enter the stock symbol and click Get Stock Info for a report.
VectorVest calculates fair value using a proprietary formula based
on earnings, financial performance and interest rates. The result,
shown near the top of the report, showed a value of $27.10 per
share for Airborne Freight.
</P>
<P>
   We found a range of opinions for Airborne's fair value, but most
were in the $27 to $40 per share range, considerably above the
current price.
</P>
<P>
   I don't recommend buying any stock based solely on mathematical
calculations, but it's a starting point for further research.
</P>
<P>
   UPDATE ON MORNINGSTAR: Morningstar has completely redesigned its
site at www.morningstar.com. The same information is there, but
it's in different places. If you've saved the columns on using
Morningstar to evaluate mutual funds, you'll find the links
mentioned in the columns no longer work. There are updated versions
of the columns at www.winninginvesting.com. Go to Basic Training
and look for Mutual Fund Evaluation _ The Basics.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-99 0334EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990830.0066 </DOCNO>
