 NEWS AND FEATURE SUMMARY -- No. 2570 -- August 30, 1999 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We are offering the following articles for sale. Please contact
us for availability your country. Best regards, Karl Horwitz
</P>
<P>
   1. THE MILOSEVIC GENERATION Welcome to Belgrade, the capital of
Serbia. Here bureaucrats with bodyguards and blood on their hands
have become private club dandies; middle-class professionals have
been forced to choose between poverty or criminality; and feigned
lunacy is a sane way to stay safe. Four lost wars, international
isolation and gangster economics have combined to make Belgrade
especially cruel to the young people who have come of age during
the 12-year reign of Slobodan Milosevic. By Blaine Harden. From The
New York Times Magazine. Full-length (7,700 words) + edited article
available.
_____________________________________________________________ 2.
CAN B. SMITH BE MARTHA? An icon of the black professional class is
hoping to cross over - by mounting a three-fronted attack on Martha
Stewart's living. Barbara Smith, the restaurateur and cookbook
author, host of a nationally syndicated TV show in the U.S. and
editor-in-chief of an upcoming magazine that will bear her
brand-like name, is already a star in the black community. By Julia
Reed. From The New York Times Magazine. Full-length (3,500 words) +
edited article available.
_____________________________________________________________ 3.
WARHOL : SUBVERSION THROUGHOUT SEDUCTION Andy Warhol was the
greatest designer of the second half of the 20th century. He
invented a style, made it fashionable, applied it to a wide range
of products, publicised it on a large scale and caused it to be
hugely influential. If there is such a thing as a Warholian
modernity, it resides in his conception of the artist as producer,
distributor, publicist and actor rolled into one. Warhol has never
before been given such an effective and representative
retrospective as the exhibition now on in Brussels, Belgium, until
September 19. The title of the show says everything : ``Andy
Warhol, a Factory.'' By Philippe Dagen. From Le Monde. 1,500 words.
(English translation available.)
_____________________________________________________________ 4.
THE TIME FOR WAR IS OVER: AN INTERVIEW WITH GADHAFI Nearly five
months after the United Nations suspended its sanctions against
Libya, following Libya's belated agreement to turn over two Libyan
suspects in the 1988 Lockerbie bombing for trial in the
Netherlands, Colonel Moammar Gadhafi has returned to the
international scene. In this exclusive interview, given under a
Bedouin tent in Tripoli, the Libyan leader whistles a somewhat
different tune than in the past. The time for war is over, he says,
and now is the time to work on national development. Increasingly
he is turning away from his erstwhile Arab comrades and toward
black Africa. By Pierre Prier. From Le Figaro. 2,750 words. English
translation available. (N/A France, Italy, French-speaking
Switzerland, French-speaking Canada, Spain, Japan.)
_____________________________________________________________ 5.
FROM PROSPECT MAGAZINE ( N/A U.K.)
</P>
<P>
   (a) NEXT TIME, SEND IN THE GURKHAS The West's reluctance to
sacrifice soldiers means it must rely on mercenaries if it wants to
intervene effectively. By Anatol Lieven. 1,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   (b) HOW MANY HOLOCAUST MUSEUMS Plans are well-advanced to build
a Holocaust museum in Manchester, England. Non-religious Jews
should not base their identity on the Holocaust, writes Valerie
Monchi. 1,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   (c) TEN YEARS IN EUROPE Ten years ago, the leaders of western
Europe set the wrong priorities. Instead of confronting the
challenge of the end of communism, they embarked on monetary union.
There is thus a direct link between Emu and ethnic cleansing. Half
the energy spent on the euro might have averted disaster in the
Balkans. By Timothy Garton Ash. 5,000 words.
_________________________________________________________ 6. FROM
NATURE NEWS SERVICE (N/A France and Spain. Embargo Sept. 1) A. GM
MAKES MENSA MOUSE?
</P>
<P>
   A new 'smart' mouse may shed light on how memories are made and
used, and even on how they might be improved. Sara Abdulla puts the
new breed of mastermind mice through the maze. 400 words. B. RIVER
DEEP, MOUNTAIN HIGH
</P>
<P>
   The growth of high mountains influences the Earth's climate by
affecting global patterns of air circulation. But does climate
change affect the height of mountains? By Paul Cooper. 400 words.
_____________________________________________________________ 7.
COMPUTER BOOSTING MIMICS HUMAN INTUITION Anyone who has been to the
racetrack knows that picking a winning horse is part art and part
science. Now a small group of researchers say that such intuition
can, at least in part, be duplicated by computers, using an
artificial intelligence technique called boosting. By Jennifer 8.
Lee. New York Times Science Times. 1,100 words.
