<DOCNO> NYT19990830.0079 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 09:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4109 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-R-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2TA     08-30 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 The Week in Review  
 (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   So Many Words, So Little Time &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The war of words in the ordinarily staid dictionary market
intensified with the publication of Microsoft's upstart new
reference guide, the Encarta World English Dictionary.
</P>
<P>
   London's underground was plastered with Encarta posters of a coy
topless model who was strategically covered by the weighty
dictionary. Rival publishers like Merriam-Webster Inc. in the
United States came out with more subdued full-page advertisements
in People and Time featuring a beaming college student in
sunglasses: ``Will your performance this school year be inspired or
ignominious?''
</P>
<P>
   But the real skirmishes were taking place behind the scenes with
rival publishers collecting examples of mistakes, omissions and
preachiness in the seven-pound print version of Encarta that labels
words like ``handicapped'' or ``harridan'' as offensive terms.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft insisted that all dictionaries have errors and any
mistakes would be corrected. But that didn't still the glee of
rivals who are so wary of Microsoft's financial resources that they
have turned to the weapons they know best: words.
</P>
<P>
   The competition whispered about the Encarta pronunciation of
Niagara Falls _ ``nigara falwz'' or Civil War general George Gordon
Meade, who was mistakenly described as a leader in the
Revolutionary War. There was the inclusion of a photograph of
Microsoft Chairman Bill Gates and the absence of a photo of John F.
Kennedy. And there was some bewilderment about the appearance of
Louise Veronica Ciccone, the pop singer, as the first definition of
Madonna, followed by the second, the Virgin Mary.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft editorial director Richard Bready noted that first
editions of dictionaries are known for errors. ``If you are a
lexicographer, it's possible to find this level of error in any
dictionary. This is not the result of haste to publish. This is the
result of publishing a dictionary.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By DOREEN CARVAJAL &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Unearthed, a New City of the Dead &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The tombs of ancient Egypt have by no means exhausted their
power to astonish.
</P>
<P>
   Years may go by without an eye-popping discovery, but then
archaeologists stumble on something like the 2,000-year-old
cemetery at an oasis 230 miles southwest of Cairo. They gave the
first detailed descriptions of one of the most spectacular Egyptian
discoveries in decades. In the buried tombs were rows of mummies
lavishly prepared for the afterlife with masks and waistcoats
covered in gold.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never before have such a number of mummies been found in a
single site in Egypt,'' said Dr. Zahi Hawass, director of the
excavations at Bahariya Oasis in what is being called the Valley of
the Golden Mummies.
</P>
<P>
   In the first four tombs explored, archaeologists counted 105
mummies _ men, women and children _ all from the Roman period of
Egypt in the first two centuries A.D. Looking at the painted masks,
Hawass said, ``The eyes of some gazed at me as if they were
alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Archaeologists were delighted to find they had beaten looters to
the scene. They estimated that the entire cemetery, extending over
two square miles, might yield 10,000 mummies. The remains will be
examined for information on what the people ate, the diseases they
suffered, causes of their deaths and estimates of life expectancy.
They should also provide important insights into the art, religion
and funerary practices of a community of affluent wine makers in
Roman Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JOHN NOBLE WILFORD
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
