<P>
   _ By JOHN NOBLE WILFORD
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Airline Employees Said to Run Vast Drug Ring From Miami  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Heroin in the coffee? Cocaine in the aisle carts next to cans of
ginger ale and beer? Hand grenades in the overhead bins?
</P>
<P>
   The arrests of more than 50 American Airlines ramp workers and
food contract workers, on a variety of drug and weapons charges,
gave a whole new meaning to flying high over Miami International
Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Federal investigators were first tipped off to the alleged drug
smuggling operation when a pilot was accidentally served a
coffee-heroin mixture in flight and complained that it tasted
funny. The workers also hid drugs in cargo holds and ceiling
panels, investigators said, and used Miami as a distribution point
to the Eastern seaboard for drugs coming from Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   _ By RICK BRAGG
</P>
<P>
   Lady Luck Regrets
</P>
<P>
   The California state Supreme Court dealt a bad hand to Indian
gambling tribes, ruling that a ballot measure to allow expansion of
the $1.4 billion tribal casino business violated the state
constitution's ban on Las Vegas-style slot machines and card games.
The tribes are already collecting signatures to put a
constitutional amendment on the ballot next year to exempt tribal
gambling from the ban, and are hoping to work out a compromise with
Gov. Gray Davis. But federal prosecutors have threatened to shut
down the disputed games in six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   _ By TODD S. PURDUM
</P>
<P>
   Revisions After Waco  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After six years of denials, Attorney General Janet Reno conceded
that pyrotechnic tear gas canisters were used at the Branch
Davidian compound in the 1993 assault that ended with the deaths of
some 80 Davidians near Waco, Texas. While the disclosure does not
alter experts' conclusions that the fire that killed many of the
members was set by them, Reno suggested that the FBI had misled
her. She ordered another inquiry into one of the worst law
enforcement debacles of modern times.
</P>
<P>
   _ By STEPHEN LABATON
</P>
<P>
   Beijing's Hard Line for Sect  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   China has reached the final stage of its campaign against Falun
Gong by revealing plans to prosecute the spiritual movement's top
leaders, who are expected to be charged soon with subversion and
sentenced to life in prison. The authorities are singling out 50 or
more leaders for punishment, while letting ordinary followers off.
The crackdown, intended as a sign of strong Communist Party
authority, is expected to wrap up before Beijing's huge Oct. 1
celebration of the 50th anniversary of Communist China.
</P>
<P>
   _ By SETH FAISON
</P>
<P>
   A Better Deal  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As a murderer, Samuel Sheinbein of Aspen Hill, Md., was an
amateur; after killing an acquaintance in 1997, the 19-year-old
left behind a handwritten note describing the murder plot. But in
manipulating the legal systems of two countries, he seemed like a
pro, fleeing to Israel and claiming citizenship on the basis of his
father's birth in British Palestine. Sheinbein worked out a plea
bargain to serve 24 years in prison, tough by Israeli standards. In
Maryland, he would have faced life in prison without hope of
parole.
</P>
<P>
   _ By PHILIP SHENON
</P>
<P>
   Blocking Vouchers  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The nation's first program to use public money to send children
to religious schools was blocked when a federal judge said there
were strong indications that the 4-year-old Cleveland program
violated the separation of church and state.
</P>
<P>
   The action _ an injunction pending a more thorough review _ came
one day before the start of school. Some 4,000 Cleveland children
were to attend 56 private schools using tuition vouchers paid for
by taxpayers. The order, watched by similar programs elsewhere, has
been appealed and the case may end up before the U.S. Supreme
Court.
</P>
<P>
   _ By PAM BELLUCK
</P>
<P>
   Do as They Say  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno has said, that under her
stewardship, the Justice Department would be more worker friendly,
but lawyers at the agency have filed a lawsuit accusing the
Department of knowingly cheating them out of millions of hours of
overtime pay. Internal documents show that even as officials told
lawyers they were ineligible for overtime, top personnel managers
knew otherwise. The Department even kept two sets of books: One
set, on which paychecks were based, credited lawyers with only the
official 40-hour work week; the other precisely tracked overtime
and was used to lobby Congress for bigger budgets _ but not to pay
overtime.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVID JOHNSTON
</P>
<P>
   Online Social Disease  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the first instance of its kind, public health officials here
have traced a cluster of six syphilis cases to a local chat room on
America Online.
</P>
<P>
   Some of men exposed since mid-June knew their sex partners only
by their online nicknames. Because America Online will not divulge
their identities, the officials have been warning scores of exposed
men using e-mail messages and postings in the chat room, San
Francisco Men 4 Men.
</P>
<P>
   _ By EVELYN NIEVES
</P>
<P>
   Things Change  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Chinua Achebe, the Nigerian author whose novel ``Things Fall
Apart'' has become one of the most widely read works of African
fiction in the United States, returned to visit his native country
after a nine-year absence.
</P>
<P>
   Achebe, 69, left Nigeria, which recently inaugurated its first
civilian government in 16 years, to seek medical treatment in
America after a car accident left him paralyzed from the waist
down. Though he is not considered an exile, Achebe's arrival was
seen as a positive development in a country whose military rulers
tolerated little criticism and became international pariahs in 1995
after hanging the writer and political critic Ken Saro-Wiwa.
</P>
<P>
   _ By NORIMITSU ONISHI
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
