<DOCNO> NYT19990830.0105 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 09:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4131 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-R-GOLD-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      08-30 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-GOLD-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS GOLD PRICES FALL, THE CACHET PREVAILS 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (The Week in Review)  
 (bl)  
 By DANA CANEDY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the price of gold hits a 20-year low, diehard gold bugs and
others are rushing in to buy the precious metal as a hedge against
the day the bear wakes from his prolonged hibernation on Wall
Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always advise our clients to invest a portion of their
portfolios in gold-related investments because gold is a contrarian
investment in that it has a negative correlation to stocks and
bonds,'' said Harry Bingham, president of Van Eck Institutional
Advisers in New York City, which has been urging clients to take
advantage of declining prices.
</P>
<P>
   That's fine for those dabbling in bullion or gold futures, but
what about the rest of America? Haven't the collective contents of
jewelry boxes taken a nose dive? The price an ounce has slid 11
percent since January alone. Wouldn't people be better off buying
Beanie Babies than bracelets and belly rings?
</P>
<P>
   The market value for gold has been declining for several years
as global economies have collapsed and central banks have sold off
tons of bullion in a time of low inflation. The Bank of England,
the latest to sell, in July unloaded 25 tons of 415 tons it plans
to sell to raise money to invest in U.S., European and Japanese
bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Gold once traded for nearly $500 an ounce, but the influx of
bullion on the market has depressed the price to about $255 an
ounce from $325 a year ago. Mine operators in South Africa and
elsewhere have shut down or laid off workers.
</P>
<P>
   Paradoxically, consumers' demand for gold is at an all-time
high. U.S. retail sales last year increased more than 8 percent to
$13.7 billion, according to the World Gold Council, which
represents the seventh consecutive year of revenue increases.
</P>
<P>
   Synonymous with status and self-expression for millenniums,
adorning the heads of royalty, the fingers of newlyweds and the
necks of fashion victims, gold historically rises and falls in
cycles like the stock market. When it comes to the price of jewelry
relative to gold values, consumers are ``just oblivious,'' said
Judith Langer, president of Langer Associates, a market research
and trend consulting firm in New York City. ``It's sort of like
fur. When fur becomes less expensive, consumers consider it an
affordable status symbol rather than thinking it's cheap and,
therefore, worthless.''
</P>
<P>
   Although jewelry accounts for 80 percent of the gold demand
worldwide, consumers won't see any devaluation soon. Retail prices
can take up to six months to reflect market fluctuations; merchants
may take that long to sell off their old inventories. This year's
holiday sale prices may be very low because retailers are
restocking at cheaper rates.
</P>
<P>
   But all that glitters is not not marked down. Craftsmanship
counts. ``It's kind of like weighing an Escada silk blouse and
saying `how much silk is in it,''' said Mark Seelig, vice president
of sales for Ourafin Llc., a large gold jewelry manufacturer and
importer.
</P>
<P>
   As an investment, ``gold is insurance against economic,
financial and political uncertainty,'' said Richard Scott Ram,
chief portfolio strategist at the World Gold Council, who has been
advising pension fund managers to include more gold as a part of a
diverse portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone, though, sees much value in purchasing gold for
more than its snob appeal. ``If somebody wants to have precious
metals in their portfolio, we want them to keep it at a small
portion,'' said Ray Russolillo, director of personal financial
services for PricewaterhouseCoopers. ``One of the big reasons is
there is no current income generated from it, there is often a cost
to holding the metal and typically it has been a long-term hedge
against inflation.'' Russolillo prefers cushions that are more
liquid.
</P>
<P>
   The debate over whether gold and gold futures are an investment
bargain these days may make stimulating conversation on the
cocktail circuit, but jewelry lovers, it seems, have little sense
of what all the fuss is about.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the research we've done about who knows about the gold
price, 15 percent state that they knew what the price was,'' said
Anne DiNuzzo, jewelry manager for the World Gold Council, ``and
half that 15 percent were wrong.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-99 0941EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
