<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 09:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3108 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-R-INDONESIA-TIMOR-REV     08-30 0514
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-INDONESIA-TIMOR-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TINY NATIONS, GRAND AMBITIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (The Week in Review)  
 (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ The East Timorese are voting Monday on whether
to sever ties with Indonesia, and if they opt for independence,
where would this brand-new country rank among the U.N.'s 188
members? For those Indonesians who argue that East Timor, occupying
only a half of one of Indonesia's 13,000 islands, is too small to
be viable, the facts may be surprising.
</P>
<P>
   East Timor, with 871,000 people and an area of 7,336 square
miles, is bigger in population and size than the three newest
members of the United Nations. The newcomers, which are expected to
take their seats in the General Assembly this fall, are all Pacific
island nations: Tonga, with a population of about 98,000 and 268
square miles of land; Nauru, with 11,000 people and 8.1 square
miles; and Kiribati, with 82,000 people scattered over 316 square
miles of islands.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, at least three dozen members of the United Nations,
many created in the decades of anti-colonialism that shattered
European empires after World War II, have populations smaller than
East Timor's. Most are island nations in the Caribbean, Pacific or
Indian Ocean, but there are also a few in Central and South
America, including Guyana, Suriname and Belize. Among older
countries, Iceland's population is smaller, as are those of
Liechtenstein and Luxembourg. So is the population of Brunei, with
its collection of oil wells at the edge of Borneo in the South
China Sea.
</P>
<P>
   Many small nations struggle because they do not have oil or
other money-earning natural resources. But there are believed to be
petroleum reserves in the ocean south of East Timor. A decade ago,
Australia and Indonesia agreed to explore the area jointly.
Political pressure on the Australian government could insure that
money earned there in the future flows at least in part to the East
Timorese.
</P>
<P>
   Nauru has thrived on something less often talked about: the
phosphates derived from the dung of sea birds. Other small nations
fight to stay economically solvent on fish. Or foreign aid.
</P>
<P>
   Portugal, which abandoned East Timor as a colony in 1974, has
offered to finance the nation's budget for five years, and other
countries have also offered aid. Independence will not be instant,
though, even if voters back it resoundingly. Indonesia will wait
for a new parliament and a new president to take office late in the
year before making a final decision.
</P>
<P>
   But other nations must be wondering: If East Timor makes it into
the United Nations, who's next? Other territories with aspirations
to independence _ among them Kashmir, Kosovo and Tibet _ are
watching closely this week as the United Nations, which is
organizing and monitoring the elections, helps East Timor take this
important step.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
