<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 10:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4174 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN01-CO     08-30 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Hamburgers embroiled in world politics
 &HT;    (For release Sept. 1, 1999.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The world's newest political prey is the hamburger stand,
principally McDonald's and Burger King. An outlash at McDonald's is
an outlash against American foreign policy, and a deep-rooted
battle in the Middle East has Burger King cringing.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than beefing up U.S. forces in front of our embassies,
perhaps they ought to be watching the drive-through line.
</P>
<P>
   Unconventional Gen. George S. Patton once fantasized World War
II being determined by a one-on-one battle between himself and
German Field Marshall Erwin Rommel. They never sat down and had a
hamburger together before shaking hands and heading off to their
respective tanks.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, however, there have been new ways created to settle
differences. When the U.S. bombs somewhere in the world, either
intentionally or accidentally, the hamburger joints in those places
take the brunt of the resident response.
</P>
<P>
   McDonald's, more than Burger King, has been targeted _ perhaps
because the Golden Arches have become some sort of gastronomic
symbol of American influence. Besides, if you can't shoot down the
plane doing the bombing, busting up an American hamburger stand
will suffice.
</P>
<P>
   Our errant projectiles in Yugoslavia, in the war to let
Albanians kill Serbs for a change, resulted in McDonald's
restaurants being attacked in Belgrade as well as in China.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. losses over Yugoslavia amounted to one plane shot down and
about 2,000 pounds of hamburger destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, when the hamburger chains are not being attacked
overseas, they pillage each other in American markets.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, both hamburger giants took nasty hits. Near Millau,
France, citizens there ransacked a still-not completed McDonald's
to protest U.S. tariffs and genetically modified food. (Aren't the
French the ones who eat snails and creamed brains? Yes, I thought
so.)
</P>
<P>
   Similar attacks took place elsewhere in France and even in
Antwerp, Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   Much like the democratic-leaning Russians did to Lenin's statue
in Moscow, the Millau protesters knocked Ronald McDonald off his
pedestal and onto his back amid a sea of apples dumped in front of
the shop. The French lead the world in unique protests and labor
actions. In the past, they have blocked the runways at airports,
left their produce out to rot, created immense traffic jams on the
expressways and shut down their museums during the height of
tourist season.
</P>
<P>
   Burger King, meanwhile, got its toes burned in the Middle East
when Palestinians discovered one of BK's new establishments was in
a Jewish settlement in the West Bank, considered by the
Palestinians to be occupied territory since 1967.
</P>
<P>
   The Arab League got in on this one by presenting a resolution,
to be voted upon next month, to boycott Burger King in Arab
countries if the hamburger giant did not back down. In the U.S., a
coalition of American Muslims called for a worldwide boycott of
Burger King. Also in the U.S., Jewish groups called for a boycott
of Burger King if it knuckles under. Much like any other Middle
East issue, emotion takes control of sensibility.
</P>
<P>
   Burger King has squeamed out of this one by withdrawing
franchise rights to the West Bank establishment, but also saying it
had no idea it was in a controversial Jewish settlement in the West
Bank. I cannot imagine Burger King granting a franchise anywhere in
the world without knowing where it was, but if you want to believe
that cop-out, have it your way.
</P>
<P>
   There is no support here of Jewish settlement in the West Bank.
Other than a determination on the future of Jerusalem, prevention
of Jewish West Bank settlements is the biggest issue between Arabs
and Israel. Putting a Burger King in the midst of it just begs for
overreaction.
</P>
<P>
   And it came.
</P>
<P>
   I only can assume that refusal by Burger King to accede to the
Muslim demands might have widened the War of the Edibles. While
Burger King is headquartered in Miami, it is owned by a British
corporation, one that also owns, among other worldwide products,
Haagen-Dazs ice cream, Green Giant foods and Smirnoff vodka; lots
to boycott.
</P>
<P>
   So elated was the terrorist group Hamas with the backing down of
Burger King that it issued a statement of praise for the company,
then likely went back to planning attacks on Israeli civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the fast-food chains ought to be asking for a seat on
the president's national security council. Getting tagged for U.S.
foreign policy is no way to have to sell hamburgers.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
