<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: School vouchers are unconstitutional and unwise
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   We're a long way from a definitive ruling on whether using tax
money to send kids to religious schools is constitutional, but the
finding by a federal district court in Ohio that there's probable
cause to suspect a church-state violation in Cleveland's program
may hint at what's to come.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of vouchers are reacting as if the very idea of
judicial review were novel to the point of abomination. Clint
Bolick, litigation director of the Institute of Justice, which
argued for the Cleveland program, called the ruling by Judge
Solomon Oliver Jr. ``an outrageous abuse of judicial power.''
</P>
<P>
   It is, instead, a perfectly ordinary, indeed predictable,
finding. It was inevitable that the constitutionality of vouchers
would be tested in federal courts, and Judge Oliver's ruling
follows one in Maine earlier this year that barred the use of
public money to pay tuitions at a Roman Catholic school.
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives, mainly, have rallied to vouchers not only as a
cure-all for any- and everything wrong with public schools but as
the sole allowable fix. Even a proposed national program to repair
dilapidated schools has flopped in Congress partly out of a dug-in
ideological dismissal of public education on the right.
</P>
<P>
   Hyped now as an educational nostrum, vouchers were created as a
political devise
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-99 1037EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990830.0114 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 10:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4183 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOX-$ADV29     08-30 0454
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOX-$ADV29 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ATTN COX EDs: Re-sending for those papers that have not used it
previously.
 &HT;    FOUR LEADING DEMOCRATS IN YUGOSLAVIA'S SERB OPPOSITION
 &HT;    With YUGOSLAVIA-BOX-$ADV29
 &HT;    For Use Sun. Aug. 29 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By LAURENCE JOLIDON 
 &HT;    c.1999 Special to Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VUK DRASKOVIC
</P>
<P>
   Leader of the Serbian Renewal Movement, Draskovic is a
well-known writer and crowd-rousing speaker at street protests who
has tarnished his reputation as a reformer by appearing to flirt
with the Milosevic regime, even joining the government during the
NATO bombing until he was booted out for urging negotiations with
the West. His party controls Belgrade's city government, which
lends him power and funding for his presidential aspirations. But
his surprise appearance at a big mid-August rally he had said he
would skip drew loud boos.
</P>
<P>
   ZORAN DJINDJIC
</P>
<P>
   Leader of the Democratic Party, traditional home for Serbia's
reform-minded intellectuals, former philosophy professor Djindjic
is the most telegenic opposition figure. An excellent stump
speaker, he attracts support from the West as well as Serbia's
middle-classes, but doesn't appeal to the masses like the
emotional, mercurial Draskovic. He and Draskovic conduct a running,
bitter public quarrel at the expense of democratic unity, which
turns off
</P>
<P>
   younger democrats. He has vowed to quit politics if Milosevic is
still in power next year.
</P>
<P>
   GEN. MOMCILO PERESIC
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia's former army chief, Gen. Peresic was fired by
Milosevic last year after accusing the government of pushing the
country into war with NATO and manipulating the army for political
gain. Not officially a candidate, Peresic retains close ties with
important military figures and is speaking out for democratic
changes. He is allied with the Movement for Democratic Serbia, an
umbrella for reformers and democrats formed only two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   He is seen as a thorough professional with little personal
ambition who talks of averting ``a new catastrophe'' _ meaning
civil war.
</P>
<P>
   VELIMIR ILIC
</P>
<P>
   The mayor of Cacak, a central Serbian city where Milosevic's
socialists have always been unpopular, ``Velja'' Ilic is a
firebrand from a family of ``Chetniks,'' World War II guerrillas
who felt betrayed when the West threw its support to Tito's
Communist partisans. Forced into hiding during the NATO bombing for
``treasonous'' statements criticizing the Yugoslav army, he has
founded his own political party, New Serbia, and is confident that
democracy's _ and his _ time has come to oust ``the last of
Europe's communists.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
