<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 10:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4189 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-KABAT-COLUMN31-COX     08-30 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KABAT-COLUMN31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Truth is plain to see
 &HT;    By Vicki Marsh Kabat
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ ``Disciples used to gather in the name of Christ
to nap . . .''
</P>
<P>
   As I boldly sang those words at church recently, my husband
stopped in mid-verse and stared at me.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's sup, not nap!''
</P>
<P>
   Either I've been spending too much time in the recliner, or
something is seriously wrong with my eyes. ``What about Peter? He
napped,'' I whispered back.
</P>
<P>
   Things didn't improve during the responsive reading, when I
confidently intoned, ``Create in us a clear part, O God, and renew
a fight spirit within us!''
</P>
<P>
   With that, my husband elbowed me in the ribs.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's clear heart and right spirit,'' he said. ``Put on your
glasses already.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, vanity of vanities. It's no secret I have terrible eyesight.
I have had since I was 8 years old.
</P>
<P>
   How mortified I was with that first pair of glasses. They were
terrible wing-tip, sparkly things that cursed a generation of
vision-impaired girls who grew up in the '60s.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever self-esteem I had managed to muster in those first
years of life slipped completely away when I put those frames upon
my freckled little nose.
</P>
<P>
   Today, children have wonderful choices in frames and can make a
serious fashion statement with their selection. But in my childhood
days, the only choices were ugly and uglier.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent trip to my childhood home, I pulled out the photo
albums. As I flipped through them, I came upon the pages where my
mother had put our school pictures every year. There they were, the
sparkly frames and then the black, dweeb frames. It was a sorry
succession of years that no one should have to remember, much less
have memorialized in a photo album.
</P>
<P>
   My youngest son came over to see what I was looking at.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who is that?'' he asked, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's your beloved mother,'' I said, my voice full of
warning.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly aghast, he looked from the album page to me and back
again, unable to believe this awful truth in his lineage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Geez, Mom. You had some pretty rough years in there, huh?'' he
said sympathetically.
</P>
<P>
   I got contacts as soon as I could and stayed in them for decades
to come. And I have contacts now. The truth is, though, at this
``certain age'' I now enjoy, the contacts alone can't do the job
when I'm reading.
</P>
<P>
   So I carry glasses with me, which I use constantly at work. But
when I'm in a public place, such as church or a restaurant, I still
like to pretend I can actually, you know, see.
</P>
<P>
   The problem isn't just in public, though. At home, I can't see
the washing instructions on tags in clothes or the baking
directions on boxes or the measurements in recipes. The
consequences can be disastrous: a silk blouse that now could fit a
Barbie doll; a solidified lump of stove-top stuffing that needed 1
1/2 cups of water, not 1/2 cup; inedible cookies that only needed
3/4 cup of sugar instead of the 1 3/4 cups I put in them . . .
actually, I did manage to eat those, just to avoid waste, you know.
</P>
<P>
   Pride is a terrible thing. How could I suddenly be looking down
my nose through magnifying glasses like my parents? I remember well
the jokes betwen them and their friends when we'd go out to eat at
a restaurant and one would hold the menu up across the table for
the other to read. Poor old geezers, I thought . . . just
yesterday, it seems.
</P>
<P>
   But on this Sunday morning, with my ribs bruised and tender from
my husband's admonitions, I sat mutely in the pew and took heart
from the only thing I could:
</P>
<P>
   If faith, as the Bible tells us, is believing in what we cannot
see, then my faith is growing abundantly.
</P>
<P>
   Vicki Marsh Kabat writes for the Waco (Texas) Tribune-Herald.
She can be reached online at VMKabat(at)aol.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
