<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mozart effect too good to last
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Any scientific theory that brings soft
music to nurseries, induces state legislators to praise the great
composers and moves classical music product off the shelves is a
good thing. Not necessarily a true thing, but a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   That's why I was sorry to read that scientists had debunked the
so-called ``Mozart effect.'' Perhaps someone will re-bunk it.
</P>
<P>
   The Mozart effect is the theory that listening to Mozart's music
can make folks smarter. It is based on a 1993 study that found
college students who listened to Mozart's music _ specifically
``Sonata for Two Pianos in D Major'' _ demonstrated improved
thinking skills.
</P>
<P>
   Combine those results with the idea that most of our learning
happens in the first three years of life and the result is a
widespread certainty that playing Mozart for infants and toddlers
makes them smarter.
</P>
<P>
   In no time schools, day care centers and state policy makers
responded. The Florida Legislature showed a surprising new
appreciation for improved thinking skills by requiring day care
centers to play classical music. Georgia Gov. Zell Miller had free
Mozart CDs sent to new mothers in that state. Other states followed
suit.
</P>
<P>
   Parents, anxious to give their children an intellectual edge,
searched out the classical music shelves of the CD stores,
abandoning Raffi and cute singing dinosaurs in favor of Mozart. A
quick search of Amazon.com finds 13 CDs with the phrase ``Mozart
effect'' in the title.
</P>
<P>
   The news spread faster than the allegro movement of ``Eine
Kleine Nachtmusik.'' For once, society seemed to be on the
threshold of realizing an impossible dream _ raising a batch of
kids that wouldn't turn out quite so dumb 15 years down the road.
</P>
<P>
   This discovery became known too late to help me with my kids.
Already entering elementary school, they were, developmentally
speaking, over the hill. Once again, I was behind the curve and a
failure as a parent. I had played Bach to them in the nursery, not
Mozart. My children would be doomed to low SAT scores, second-rate
universities and juvenile delinquency.
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, just as might have been predicted, no comforting
cantatas come from the CD players in their rooms these days. I
brace my bedroom door against the harsh electronic grind of Atari
Teenage Riot and the Beastie Boys. If only, if only I had known and
not let myself get stuck in the Baroque. But then, if I had played
Stravinsky, things might have turned out even worse.
</P>
<P>
   I can, however, take new comfort in a new study in the latest
issue of the journal Nature. It declares that Mozart listeners
don't get any smarter after all.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom-line message is that there is either no Mozart
effect or a very small Mozart effect,'' Harvard researcher
Christopher Chabris told the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Harsh words. He must have listened to Berg as an infant.
</P>
<P>
   But this reassessment shouldn't be too big a surprise. Although
I'm sure the new generation of Mozart-babies will be better in some
way for their exposure, the idea that you could buy your kids a
point or two of IQ for $12.99 in the record-and-tape section of
Wal-Mart does seem just a little too easy.
</P>
<P>
   We are a society that will mobilize its resources to put Mozart
in every nursery but six years later will plop the same bunch of
kids in front of the TV for hours at a time. And for good measure,
we will eliminate their junior-high school music program at the
first hint of a tight school budget.
</P>
<P>
   Our commitment to higher IQs through music begins to get iffy as
the cost rises above $15 and the kids get older than 10.
</P>
<P>
   Even if holding cribside Mozart concerts doesn't raise kids' IQ,
at least it doesn't hurt. And maybe it has other beneficial
effects, ones that don't show up on standardized tests. Perhaps it
makes little kids less grumpy, a little nicer. (Testing this would
require psychologists to develop a standardized Niceness Quotient.
High NQ children could be tested, identified and then hit up for
their lunch money.)
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps playing Mozart for toddlers does nothing more than keep
their parents from freaking out. If that's true, it would be well
worth $12.99. Even if the kids don't get any smarter.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lane is associate editor at The Daytona Beach (Fla.)
News-Journal. E-mail: marklane(at)n-jcenter.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
