<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Search engines refining `pathfinder' services
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ One of the big changes on the Web over the last few
years has been the addition of truly useful services.
</P>
<P>
   In the beginning, the World Wide Web was more of a curiosity _ a
pig that could sing _ but nowadays many of us use the Web in daily
life. Today, we'll take a look at some sites that can help you find
a good barber, locate the nearest grocery store or help you
navigate to a new friend's home.
</P>
<P>
   Let's travel to our first of these ``pathfinder'' sites. It's
called AltaVista Connections and is located at www.zip2.com/.
AltaVista, as you probably know, is one of the best known of the
search engines. But _ as is true of most of these places _ it has
diversified into other services.
</P>
<P>
   When you go to that page, you'll see a list of services and
businesses such as dining, home and real estate, health, and sports
and recreation. Clicking on any of these broad topics brings up
other lists of specific kinds of businesses. Once you select the
exact type of business you want to find, the search engine will ask
you for your home address.
</P>
<P>
   Now the site can really go to work. It'll give you a list of
businesses in that category _ let's say barber shops _ that are
near your home. You'll be told how far away each is, its address
and its phone number. If you wish, you can get a map and driving
directions to that location.
</P>
<P>
   The next site today is maintained by another search engine,
Yahoo, and it's located at yp
</P>
<P>
   .yahoo.com/. This site works very much like the one from
AltaVista. The mechanics of how you go about it are a little
different, but the end result will be the same sort of a list of
businesses, addresses and phone numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, one nifty thing about the Yahoo site may surprise you or
frighten you (since some people have an almost obsessive fear that
computers are somehow invading their privacy). The Yahoo site uses
a cookie (a tiny text file it sends to your computer) that will
identify you the next time you try the service. So, on subsequent
visits from the same computer, you can simply select the business
category and Yahoo will automatically assume that your home address
is the same as it was last time. It gets all that information from
the cookie.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Husted writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
