<SLUG> BC-MAC-REPORT31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SimCity 3000 more intellectually challenging than its
predecessors
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ ``SimCity'' always has been a thing of intellectual
beauty. This computer game is so well thought out, so full of
nuances in its understanding of modern urban life, that you can
play it again and again and still be surprised.
</P>
<P>
   This tradition continues with the latest version, ``SimCity
3000.'' The PC version has been out for more than a year. The Mac
version has now been released.
</P>
<P>
   ``SimCity 3000'' is even more sophisticated and complex than its
two predecessors, making game play not only addictive but much more
challenging. I built a city of 180,000 and watched it collapse in
financial ruin. You never can let your guard down in this version
of ``SimCity.''
</P>
<P>
   The first thing you'll notice about ``SimCity 3000'' is the
stunning new look. There are hundreds of new buildings, and you can
study them at street level. You'll see people walking your streets
and all kinds of traffic: buses, cars, firetrucks and police cars,
to name a few. In ``SimCity 2000,'' the only representation of
traffic was a flowing river of little blue dots.
</P>
<P>
   ``SimCity 3000'' has added lots of new special buildings given
as awards. For instance, if you reach a certain population level
you'll receive a university, a golf course, a medical research
complex and many more.
</P>
<P>
   The game includes replicas of scores of famous buildings from
around the world. There's the United Nations complex, Westin
Peachtree Plaza and Notre Dame, to name a few. You can add up to 10
of these landmark buildings in any city.
</P>
<P>
   With this additional detail comes added complexity. In addition
to traffic, development, power and water, you now must manage
waste. Left unmanaged, it will litter your streets and pollute your
water. This is a major new challenge to master in developing a
successful city.
</P>
<P>
   Another big new challenge is deal-making with neighbors. You can
sell them your garbage, for example, or take the garbage of others
for a fee.
</P>
<P>
   These added elements make ``SimCity 3000'' more difficult to
play and less forgiving of mistakes, even at the easiest levels. In
earlier versions, with a city of 180,000, I pretty much would have
been home free.
</P>
<P>
   While ``SimCity 3000'' is stunning, it does have a few
weaknesses. A big one is the huge amount of computing power needed.
You have to set virtual memory, for example, at a minimum of 128
megabytes to play.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the functions appear to need tweaking. It's very hard _
in some cases impossible _ to build bridges. Nor does the game
recognize basic Mac key commands such as Command W to close a
window.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, though, this is a great new version of a great game.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Haddad writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
