r f BC-NETWATCH-COLUMN31-COX     08-30 0953
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWATCH-COLUMN31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Music sales on net not same old song
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's always something when it comes to the new
frontier of downloading and paying for music from the Internet.
Atlantic Records put a bold foot forward and decided to market the
new Tori Amos song ``Bliss'' as a secure downloadable track for
sale over the Internet. About 10 minutes later, somebody hacked the
song so it could be downloaded for free. This is essentially the
online equivalent of shoplifting, and nobody's too happy about it.
</P>
<P>
   However, instead of the record companies blaming the Web and the
Web blaming the record companies, everyone seems to regard the Tori
experiment as a learning experience, and this is good news for
consumers. Instead of backing away, retailers and artists are
thinking hard not just about security but pricing and making
digital music something mainstream consumers will want to buy as
often as CDs from the local record store.
</P>
<P>
   All this is a far cry from the olden days of digital downloading
that existed about six months ago. Downloading music from the
Internet was confusing, complicated and often illegal. Web sites
blamed the record companies for not providing music. Record
companies blamed the Web. Many people in the record business see
the Web as an uncivilized, unethical and just plain nasty place
created for the sole purpose of ripping them off.
</P>
<P>
   Atlantic apparently took a hard look at the Internet and decided
that if you can't beat them, you might as well join them. The Tori
Amos single was priced at $1.59 and provided free to any retailer
on the Web that wanted to sell it. Some chose to give it away,
others priced it slightly higher, but the point was it was out
there, people would download it and if the gods are smiling,
Atlantic and Tori Amos might make some money selling music on the
Web.
</P>
<P>
   Atlantic Group co-Chairman/co-Chief Executive Officer Val Azzoli
applauded his label's fearlessness and vision in a press release:
``The time has clearly arrived for online downloads to become
another readily available retail format, alongside the familiar CD,
cassette and vinyl,'' he said. ``With the for-sale download release
of `Bliss,' we are taking another major step in the rapid
development of secure digital music distribution.''
</P>
<P>
   Also dipping its toe into the uncharted waters of digital music
is CDNow. Ted Hooban, the company's director of digital products,
says this is the first time CDNow is offering digital music for
sale. He says the challenge for any online retailer is to present
digital downloads in a user-friendly format.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's going to be a long time before record labels and
online music retailers walk off hand-in-hand into the sunset.
Although CDNow says its goal is to be the No. 1 destination for
downloading music over the Internet, the company admits almost too
many obstacles exist to bringing music downloads to great numbers
of consumers any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   Hooban says it's imperative for CDNow to understand all sides of
the digital download dilemma.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that in order for us to continue to be a leading
commerce site for music, we have to dive down and deal with all
these issues head-on,'' he says. ``What are the dominant formats?
Where are the record labels going? What do the artists want? We
have to work with them, but we have to build systems that are
friendly and make it something that is easy for consumers to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Both record labels and online retailers are concerned about
piracy, theft and security but don't know if they have the
technology or the industry clout to do anything about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This really turns everybody upside down,'' Hooban says.
``Everyone is trying to figure out how the world should look, and
the customer doesn't know how the world should look. You don't know
what customers will or will not do or what record companies will or
will not do. Everybody's in there trying to understand how to
manage all the copyrights and keep things secure.''
</P>
<P>
   One answer to the security debacle is to have songs that
eventually ``time out,'' or won't play after a certain date. ``We
have no data on how people react,'' he says, ``but from a consumer
perspective, any time you lose something like that _ and this is
just my theory _ you almost paid a price to get it. You downloaded
a player, you installed the player and you waited 20, 30 or 40
minutes to download the track. You did pay a price to get that
song. So I question the value of having someone take it away from
you. To leave it on the desktop will drive more sales than to have
it time out.''
</P>
<P>
   Hooban says the ins and outs of digital music distribution are
hard to explain because there are so many parties involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rules aren't written,'' he says. ``I don't think this
industry is going to make this easy for the customer.'' CDNow, as
one of the earliest online music retailers, understands the online
music-buying consumer and what he or she will and will not put up
with when it comes to buying music.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are doing our focus groups and an incredible amount of
research and looking at how people interact with digital downloads.
The stuff we have up there right now is a big experiment,'' he
says. ``We want to find out what people will go through and what
they will pay for a digital download. We want to make it a clean
and easy experience and figure out how to put marketing muscle
behind it. Right now it's a complicated process. We're just trying
to learn.''
</P>
<P>
   Frances Katz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
