<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 10:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4196 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-POWERUSER-COLUMN31-CO     08-30 1337
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POWERUSER-COLUMN31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POWERUSER: Springing for better monitor can be an eye-saver
 &HT;    (EDS: Can run with TECHNOBUDDY31.)
 &HT;    By Gerry Yandel
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Since the first time I ventured into a dungeon and
reduced a monster to a pile of fur and gore, I've had this
half-baked notion that it would be really cool to get one of those
60-inch TV sets, hook it to a computer, turn off all the lights and
scare myself silly playing a life-size version of ``Hexen.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, re-creating the putrid tones of the dank walls of
``Hexen'' or the eerie red glow of a ``Doom'' burial chamber in the
living room is much easier said than done.
</P>
<P>
   In my quest for the techno-chops to see what it would take to be
able to creep down a dungeon hallway on a giant-screen TV, I
learned a good deal about monitors, video cards and how they work
together.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first things I learned is that a computer won't work
very well with a TV set. Without getting too technically obtuse,
about the best resolution I could hope for, even using specialized
_ and expensive _ converter equipment, is 640 pixels by 480 pixels,
which would look terrible ... especially on one of those monster TV
sets.
</P>
<P>
   These days, with computer manufacturers practically giving away
their machines, it makes sense to build a system around your
monitor as opposed to the CPU. Especially for people who use their
machines primarily to surf the Net, send e-mail, write letters and
play solitaire.
</P>
<P>
   It's not going to make too much difference whether the computer
you buy for those uses is a 166-MHz or a 500-MHz machine _ unless
you are using some kind of whiz-bang 3-D solitaire game. But there
is a significant difference between a 15-inch, a 17-inch, a 19-inch
and a 21-inch monitor.
</P>
<P>
   It makes even more sense for heavy gamers and artistic types
using complex imaging software to invest extra in a monitor because
they will be spending even more time in front of a machine.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how you look at it, your eyes do most of the heavy
lifting when it comes to computers. In the long run, the money you
invest in a good monitor may save you the price of a pair of
glasses.
</P>
<P>
   Like most things related to computers, there is enough
information on monitors and video cards to fill several thick
books, but a good enough understanding of how video works to make
informed choices is not so hard to come by.
</P>
<P>
   The first thing to know is that two things are involved that
work together but should be considered separately: the monitor and
the video card.
</P>
<P>
   In a simplified explanation, the card tells the monitor what to
display. The monitor is responsible for the display quality _
sharpness, brightness, resolution and stability. The card transfers
the data between the computer and monitor.
</P>
<P>
   So you can buy the biggest, baddest, fastest video card out
there, but if your monitor is a piece of junk, the picture will be
poor. On the other hand, a high-end monitor used with a standard
video card would most likely yield pretty decent results for casual
home users.
</P>
<P>
   There's not a whole lot to the monitor side of things. What you
see, is, um, what you get. The primary considerations when
purchasing a monitor are the refresh rate and the screen size.
</P>
<P>
   Because of cost, the most common screen size was 15 inches as
recently as a year ago, when they cost between $300 and $350. But
17-inch monitors have since fallen to around $200 and are quickly
becoming the screen size of choice, and a 19-inch monitor now costs
what a 15-inch used to cost. Don't forget, too, that screen sizes
are measured diagonally. The viewing area on a 15-inch screen is
actually about 13 inches.
</P>
<P>
   The refresh rate is measured in megahertz _ standard speeds on
new monitors these days are around 65-75 MHz _ and it is the speed
the screen is redrawn, which happens every time the cursor blinks
or moves. A lesser factor is dot pitch _ a measure of the distance
between pixels _ but anything 0.28 mm or less is good, although the
lower the dot pitch, the better.
</P>
<P>
   The most common monitors are cathode ray tube (that's the
familiar picture tube, called the CRT) and liquid crystal display
(LCD) monitors, which use liquid crystals between two polarizing
plates. The flat-panel monitors use the LCD technology and are only
a few inches thick, but they are new to the market and still priced
extremely high. Consider a flat-panel screen if space or design is
a factor _ and you have a couple of hundred spare dollars _ but a
CRT should be sufficient.
</P>
<P>
   It's when you start playing games that video gets serious.
Upgrading a video card can enhance every aspect of your computer's
imaging processes.
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, your computer has a card that can handle 2-D
display (or else you wouldn't be able to see anything). Systems
from a year or two ago, like my Pentium 166, have cards that handle
2-D and 3-D, albeit in a limited capacity, with 1 or 2 megabytes of
video memory. New systems these days normally come with video cards
that handle 2-D and 3-D display and have at least 4 MB _ if not 8
MB _ of video RAM.
</P>
<P>
   The amount of RAM on a card serves two purposes: the number of
colors that can be processed _ i.e., 8-bit (256 colors) or 24-bit
(16.7 million colors) _ and the speed at which images can be
rendered. Some cards _ like the S3 ViRGE in my computer _ can be
upgraded simply by adding more RAM. Different types of RAM can be
used on video cards, so check the manufacturer's info on your card
to see what it takes. In other cases. it makes more sense to add a
3-D graphics accelerator card, either in addition to or instead of
your VGA card.
</P>
<P>
   The way accelerators work is fairly straightforward. A VGA card
has no processor on it, and all graphics commands to the monitor
come from your CPU. Video accelerators have processors built onto
the card that handle most of the graphics commands and leave your
CPU and video bus free to do other things. Obviously, the more
memory on your video card, the higher the performance. When I
bought my computer a year and a half ago, 1 megabyte of video
memory was cutting edge. Nowadays it's not unusual to see several
different cards available with 16 MB or 32 MB of RAM.
</P>
<P>
   It would be great if video accelerators were no more complex
than that, but, alas, that's not the case. (We are talking about
computers, after all.)
</P>
<P>
   The processors on video cards are proprietary, which means that
each has its own set of commands. Consequently, a game _ or any
other program _ used under one type of card may perform differently
under another video accelerator.
</P>
<P>
   Another quirk to consider: No matter how much you soup up your
video card, it is limited to the top speed of your computer's video
bus. Although there seems to be some debate whether the new video
bus _ called AGP for advanced graphics port _ is really that much
better than the older PCI bus, AGP has become the standard in new
systems.
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturers generally make video accelerators in both flavors
for those of us who have PCI graphics ports and don't have an AGP
slot on the motherboard. Naturally, AGP and PCI are not compatible.
</P>
<P>
   So it shouldn't seem like too big a deal to rig the TV to the
computer, right? Unfortunately, U.S. TVs are only capable of 525
vertical lines of resolution, hence the 640x480 I mentioned
earlier. The advent of HDTV, which will have about double the
resolution capabilities, undoubtedly will change the video picture
(sorry again).
</P>
<P>
   Then again, blowing the life-sized undead into little bits of
decayed flesh at that resolution might be a bit much to stomach.
</P>
<P>
   These sites contain information about video cards:
</P>
<P>
   comp.sys.ibm.pc.hardware.video
</P>
<P>
   www.lmn.pub.ro/(tilde)bytemare/graphics/index.html
</P>
<P>
   www.cs.columbia.edu/(tilde)bm/3dcards/3d-cards1.html
</P>
<P>
   Gerry Yandel writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
