<SLUG> BC-TECH-TOOLS31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nature: Virtual Serengeti a little brutal for children
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A new CD-ROM from Grolier, by way of the television
series ``Nature,'' entitled ``Nature: Virtual Serengeti,'' is aimed
at children, and it has a great many strengths. But it will require
a certain amount of strength from the youngsters who get into it.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than just link together a series of video clips or still
shots, the producers turned out a self-contained education package.
</P>
<P>
   The premise is that a researcher sent to the East African plains
has wandered off to study baboons, and your youngster is recruited
to take his place, finish his research and put together a film for
Nature magazine.
</P>
<P>
   This is less preposterous than it might seem, since from the
frequent e-mails and the stuff he wrote in the research journal,
the original researcher is no more than 10 years old himself.
</P>
<P>
   At any rate, the new researcher has a base camp, a Land Rover
and a plane to use in studying wildlife from the Mara River to
Amboseli.
</P>
<P>
   The all-important video is based on nodes in each area to be
visited. Each node allows a full 360-degree view by swinging the
cursor to one side of the screen or the other. By clicking on the
horizon or somewhere around it at the proper place, one moves to
another node.
</P>
<P>
   There are animals to be found at virtually every node, but they
aren't obvious. Their presence is indicated by sudden animal
noises, at which point you click around the screen until the view
zeroes in on the animal in question. The animal, and the behavior
observed, are recorded automatically in a long file. These records
can then be used to complete the research simply by connecting the
right picture to the right question.
</P>
<P>
   ``Virtual Serengeti'' is lavishly produced; the video and audio
are very good; and most of it really does shed interesting light on
the behavior and traits of the animals in question. But a major
slip seems to have occurred between the production and the
packaging.
</P>
<P>
   The program comes in a large, multicolored box, inside which is
the usual heavy cardboard stiffener box. When you open all this up,
all that falls out is one shrink-wrapped pasteboard CD-ROM jacket.
</P>
<P>
   There are no instructions, a rather unsettling state of affairs
that seems to be gaining momentum in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, this would be all right, because ``Virtual
Serengeti'' is not a difficult program, and it has a sort of
prelude to orient the user. Unfortunately, some of the finer points
of this prelude don't seem to be quite accurate.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, it indicates that when you see a forward arrow,
you can go forward. You can't. It says you're supposed to sweep the
cursor around each view and when animals are located, it will
change to a sort of box. In practice, animals can't be located
until they make noises, and then the cursor will turn into a box at
a dozen places on the screen, some of which take you to the beast
and some of which don't. In addition, there are about a half-dozen
other cursors that pop up that are entirely unexplained and that
don't seem to do anything most of the time.
</P>
<P>
   All this is going to require a certain amount of patience on the
part of kids.
</P>
<P>
   The second caveat I'm going to issue may or may not be a
problem, depending on your attitude. I don't see it as a problem,
but I tend to put a premium on realism. ``Virtual Serengeti'' is
realistic. Animals die, often violently, which is usually the way
death comes in this part of the world, where the food chain is
plain for all to see.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the nature shows on television now don't bat an eye at
this sort of thing, and kids who'd be interested in this program
have probably seen a lot of such shows. But you'll have to be the
judge of that.
</P>
<P>
   Virtual Serengeti costs $30, and if you can't find it locally
you can order it from gi.grolier.com.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Warner
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
