<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 10:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4201 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-TECHNOBUDDY-COLUMN31-     08-30 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNOBUDDY-COLUMN31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TECHNOBUDDY: Accelerator card, more RAM can make PC game-ready
 &HT;    (EDS: Can run in conjunction with POWERUSER-COLUMN about video
cards/gaming.)
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ I had a friend who claimed she quit school in the
third grade because of recess. She said: I don't play games.
</P>
<P>
   When I first began using computers _ back when the Appalachian
Mountains were young _ games fascinated me. The graphics in some of
the earliest games were literally little dots on the monochrome
screen. If there was sound at all, it was no more than a beep that
came from the PC's built-in speaker.
</P>
<P>
   I continued playing through the advent of the color monitor and
saw games become increasingly complicated. I saw the day when games
(as they are now) were the most demanding application run on most
home PCs. You need more processing power and better video
performance for ``Mutant Martian Unwed Mothers'' than for your word
processor, to check e-mail or even to mess with the
graphics-intensive Web.
</P>
<P>
   While my home computer is an OK machine (a 350-megahertz Pentium
II), it wasn't in shape to play games when I got the urge to try
them again. Finding a game was not a problem. Since I write about
computers, there are usually plenty of review copies to try. But _
for most new games _ I needed more oomph than my PC could deliver.
</P>
<P>
   Since I was determined to try a game, I spent some time (and
money) getting my PC game-capable. I pay my own way when it comes
to my home PC. I don't take free machines or hardware _ that would
create a conflict of interest when it comes to writing about the
various companies. So it was out of the question to buy a new PC
already up to the task. It also meant I couldn't wander the aisles
of the computer stores and ignore the price tags.
</P>
<P>
   Serious gamers will get nothing from my adventure. They use
top-of-the-line machines and spend hours reading about and
discussing the latest hardware. But if you are a typical home PC
user and just looking to play an occasional game, maybe what I
learned can help.
</P>
<P>
   The most important (and expensive) part of the game upgrade was
to replace my old plain vanilla video card with a 3-D accelerator
card. Since I'm writing this for the real PC novice, let's stop and
explain some things. The hardware device that connects your monitor
to the PC is a video card. Like your computer, it has memory chips
of its own. For most applications _ word processing, home finance
programs, Web browsing, spreadsheets and the like _ any video card
with 4 to 8 megabytes of RAM works fine. Most modern games profit
(and some require) a video card that uses a special accelerator
chip that makes game graphics come alive.
</P>
<P>
   You simply pull out your old video card and replace it with the
new one (the accelerator card will work fine for your regular
computing chores, too; you don't need both). Before you go
shopping, check your computer manual to see if your video card uses
the Advanced Graphics Port connection. That's a special slot in
your PC designed for these cards (they'll say AGP on the box). Get
the AGP video accelerator card if your computer supports that
standard, and get the regular one if it doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   If you're curious, I bought the Voodoo 3D card with 16 megabytes
of memory. There are plenty to choose from, and it would be smart
to read reviews in a computer gaming magazine before you buy. I
paid around $130 for the card. There are plenty that are much more
expensive and have twice that amount of memory. But those are for
heavy-duty gamers. My 16-megabyte card worked fine. And Voodoo is a
popular brand, so almost any game you find will work fine on that
card.
</P>
<P>
   Since my computer, probably like yours, already had a halfway
decent sound system, the only other upgrade I needed was memory.
Memory is a great investment. Adding RAM _ unlike an accelerator
card _ speeds everything you do. If you have 32 megabytes, you
definitely need to bump the memory up to 64 megabytes. I already
had 64 megabytes, and I upgraded to 128 megabytes and saw a
performance increase. But, if you are frugal, you can get by fine
with 64 megabytes.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a relatively modern PC, that's all you need to play
a game or two. I did everything for about $200. So, if you want to
play games, there is no need to quit school and get a job.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Husted writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
