<TEXT>
<P>
   If I Cross My Eyes, Will They Really Stick?
</P>
<P>
   By Jan R. Ledford
</P>
<P>
   C. 1999 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ You're eating in the school lunchroom. Everyone's
doing stunts. The kid across from you entertains the crowd by
bending his thumb back to his wrist.
</P>
<P>
   It's your turn.
</P>
<P>
   You cross your eyes in toward your nose. Everyone shrieks.
</P>
<P>
   But the teacher sees you. ``Stop it!'' she says. ``Your eyes
will stick like that!''
</P>
<P>
   Will they really?
</P>
<P>
   No. The muscles that move your eyes around are designed to move
smoothly. They are attached to the skull at the back of the eye
holes (called orbits). Then the muscles run forward and attach to
the eyeball. There's nothing for them to get stuck on!
</P>
<P>
   Then why are some people cross-eyed?
</P>
<P>
   The medical term for crossed eyes is ``strabismus.'' The most
common cause of strabismus is that a person is born with it. One
muscle might be too weak and is unable to pull the eye straight. Or
a muscle might be too strong and pull the eye out of line.
</P>
<P>
   A crossed eye might be turned in or out. It might not even be
crossed all the time.
</P>
<P>
   Strabismus in adults is often caused by a problem with a nerve
that goes to an eye muscle. A nerve is like an electric line that
runs from the brain to the muscle. The nerve tells the muscle what
to do. If the ``electric line'' isn't working right, then the
muscle can't work right, either. In that case, the muscle won't
pull when it should. Then it can't keep up with the other eye, and
crossing occurs.
</P>
<P>
   If you are talking to someone with a crossed eye, it can be hard
to tell if they're looking at you. But chances are, one of their
eyes is looking at you. Just look the person in that eye!
</P>
<P>
   How your eyes move
</P>
<P>
   Each eye has six muscles attached to it. Not only do your eyes
move side to side, they also move up, down and to every position in
between. But that's not all. The eye muscles also keep the eyes
from rotating when you tilt your head. You can watch this happen.
Have a friend sit facing you. Ask him to keep looking at an object
over your shoulder. Now tell him to tilt his head toward the right
shoulder. Now the left. Did you see that? The head moved, but the
eyes didn't. Cool!
</P>
<P>
   A crossing checklist
</P>
<P>
   Have a friend sit facing you. Ask him or her to look at items in
the following checklist. Do the eyes cross? Or not?
</P>
<P>
   Write YES or NO.
</P>
<P>
   1. Look over my shoulder at the farthest thing you can see.
</P>
<P>
   2. Look over my shoulder at something about 20 feet away.
</P>
<P>
   3. Look over my shoulder at something about 10 feet away.
</P>
<P>
   4. Look at my ear.
</P>
<P>
   5. Look at my finger. (Hold it about 12 inches away.)
</P>
<P>
   6. Watch my fingertip. (Slowly move your finger closer. STOP at
2 inches.)
</P>
<P>
   7. Look at my finger (hold it 12 inches away); now look over my
shoulder, far away.
</P>
<P>
   Did you notice that the eyes crossed more when they looked at
closer objects? It's normal for the eyes to cross inward when
looking at something close up. Such crossing usually starts once an
object is closer than 20 feet, although it may be hard to notice at
first.
</P>
<P>
   Jan R. Ledford writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
