<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New school? Don't panic! Follow our tips to make friends
 &HT;    By Theresa W. Giarrusso
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Walking into a crowded school bus or cafeteria is a
little scary for anyone. If you're at a new school, it can be extra
nerve-racking.
</P>
<P>
   This month, thousands of kids around Atlanta are trying to make
friends and get comfortable in new surroundings. We asked students
and teachers to tell us ways to break the ice. Here are their five
best tips:
</P>
<P>
   1. Look outside the classroom: Getting involved in your
neighborhood, church and clubs are great ways to meet kids from
your school.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Leverett, 13, tackled his first-day-of-school jitters on the
field. ``When I transferred to Marist last year, I was worried that
I wouldn't find any people I liked, so I wanted to meet some kids
with interests like mine.'' Jay joined the football team, which
started practicing before the school year began. ``So on the first
day I knew a bunch of people.''
</P>
<P>
   2. Concentrate on finding a buddy: Don't try to meet every
student at once. Home in on one or two kids who seem friendly and
hang with them on the bus or in the lunchroom _ both can be lonely
places.
</P>
<P>
   3. Just smile: ``It's hard to do when you're nervous,'' says
Dominique Hearnes, a seventh-grade teacher. But kids are more
likely to talk to you if you don't look like you'll bite.
</P>
<P>
   4. Be helpful to others: Offer to sharpen someone's pencil, push
them on a swing or wait with them in the lunch line. But don't take
it too far, advises Shelly Savage, a first-grade teacher. She found
a student lying on the ground, letting another student stand on her
back to reach the monkey bars. ``She was trying to be helpful.''
</P>
<P>
   5. Be curious: Hearnes says take advantage of the
get-to-know-you activities your teacher leads. Listen to what the
kids say they're into and ask them about it later. Ask about
favorite teams, Pokemon characters and video games. You can also
wonder aloud why the bus smells or offer a compliment, if it's
sincere.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, remember how it feels to be new. When new students
start in the middle of the year, offer to show them around. Be the
friendly face you'd wished for earlier in the year.
</P>
<P>
   Theresa W. Giarrusso writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga. Sarah Austin, 14, of Decatur
High School in Atlanta, contributed to this report. She
participated in the summer writing program at VOX, a newspaper for
teenagers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-99 1048EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
