<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Build Civilization that stands Test of Time
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Civilization'' is one of the most popular strategy computer
games of all time, and now a new version has been released. Called
``Civilization II: Test of Time,'' the latest release expands on
the original game by adding two new worlds. You can build your
civilization in a fantasy-based or sci-fi-based world. Or you can
use the original map of Earth. The game also has added new sounds
and special effects. ``Civilization II: Test of Time'' is available
only for PCs running Windows 95 or higher.
</P>
<P>
   Among the more popular education software has been Knowledge
Adventure's Blaster series of titles for reading and math. The
company has released two new titles in this series. One is aimed at
first-graders, the other at kindergartners. The titles work on both
Macs and PCs.
</P>
<P>
   In print
</P>
<P>
   The end of the year is fast approaching, and with it comes the
prospect that the millennium bug could cause problems for your
personal computer. Learn how to keep from losing files _ or even
your system _ in the September issue of PC World. The magazine
tests 15 software utility programs that claim to protect PCs from
the Y2K bug.
</P>
<P>
   The same issue of PC World offers tips on how to get the most
out of Microsoft Office. You'll find tips on how to use Word, Excel
and PowerPoint. You'll learn, for example, how to type anywhere in
a document, create hyperlinks and create two side-by-side pages on
one sheet.
</P>
<P>
   Online
</P>
<P>
   If you're interested in Jewish history, check out the new site
of the Museum of Jewish Heritage in New York. The museum focuses on
the history of the Holocaust. It has more than 2,000 photographs,
800 artifacts and 24 original documentary films. Much of this
material is posted online. You'll find this site at
www.mjhnyc.org/home.htm.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
