<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-REPORT31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dorms easily outfitted on site
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If you've spent any time in a Target or Wal-Mart or
Office Depot in the past few weeks, you probably have a decent idea
why CollegiateMall.com might get a few looks on the Web this year.
</P>
<P>
   The site is designed to be a place for college students to flesh
out their dorm rooms. Need a scallop-shaped trash can? How about a
bathrobe rack to hang over your bedroom door? Or maybe a nightstand
or a dresser or a backpack? CollegiateMall.com even has
partnerships with Amazon.com and VarsityBooks.com that let the site
sell music CDs and textbooks.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston-based site, started in 1998 by a Boston University
student, bills itself the one-stop college shop.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site even has a form to fill out for students interested
in becoming campus reps for CollegiateMall.com (which is also the
address for the site on the Web).
</P>
<P>
   Bankers, brokers vie for online trust
</P>
<P>
   One of the main things online bankers and brokerages hope to do
is become the place on the Web where you make your money decisions.
</P>
<P>
   The logic works something like this: If you trust one company to
handle your checking account online, you're more likely to trust
them with other financial decisions, such as buying insuranctrading stock.
</P>
<P>
   A study by Synergistics Research looks at the idea of
cross-selling from the customer's perspective. The study found that
the Web offers tremendous opportunities for banks to sell things to
their customers that they would not ordinarily sell.
</P>
<P>
   About one-third of people polled said they would be interested
in handling their investments and getting life, car and homeowners
insurance from the company that handles their checking account.
</P>
<P>
   Synergistics Research asked about 1,000 people in May. The
survey also found that younger people are more interested in the
idea. Most banks are not taking advantage of the interest yet, the
study found.
</P>
<P>
   Two more DVDs from Panasonic
</P>
<P>
   Panasonic Consumer Electronics has two more DVD products on the
market, starting in October.
</P>
<P>
   The Panasonic DVD-A7 sells for about $1,000, the Technics
DVD-A10 for about $1,200.
</P>
<P>
   Both devices can be incorporated into your home entertainment
system. The DVD players take conventional CDs.
</P>
<P>
   DVD-Audio recordings will be reproduced with higher quality
sound. When hooked up to a television, a DVD also can reproduce
video, including graphics, text and music videos. The audio DVD
player works with DVD video discs as well, which means you can play
DVD movies.
</P>
<P>
   The two-channel DVD-Audio uses a sampling frequency of 192
kilohertz, more than four times the frequency used by a CD, to
extend the playback response to 96 kilohertz.
</P>
<P>
   Higher frequency reproduction is expected to give the audio DVD
a much better sound quality than a CD.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Clothier writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
