<HEADER>
A4219 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-CONSUMER-Q-AND-A31-CO     08-30 0585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMER-Q-AND-A31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer Q and A
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving on (a) General news and (l) Lifestyle categories.)
 &HT;    By Jane Greig
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: The headlights of sport utility vehicles shine in my eyes!
Who do I complain to? _ G.P.A: The National Highway Traffic Safety
Administration at (800) 424-9393. Headlight standards were set more
than 30 years ago by the Society of Automotive Engineers. A height
margin of 22 to 54 inches above the road surface is allowed for all
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people say they (SUVs) are too big, too tall, and in
a crash, the short vehicle gets the worse of it,'' says NHTSA
spokesperson Liz Neblett. The NHTSA and SUV manufacturers have been
researching safety issues with special attention to the rollover
factor. In 1996, SUVs had the highest rate of fatal crashes
involving rollovers (37 percent).
</P>
<P>
   Q: What are the criteria for getting your name on the Hollywood
Walk of Fame and how do you find out the list of names? _ Barry
Winkle
</P>
<P>
   A: The walk is a program of the Hollywood Chamber of Commerce.
Criteria include longevity, professional achievement, community
contributions and a guarantee the star will attend the ceremony.
Want to nominate someone? Send a stamped, self-addressed envelope
to: Walk of Fame, Hollywood Chamber of Commerce, 7018 Hollywood
Blvd., Hollywood, CA 90028. To receive a complete roster (star
names, locations on the walk) send $4 to the same address.
</P>
<P>
   The first recipient? Joanne Woodward in 1960. Once a star is
selected, someone (the star, the nominator, an organization) pays
the chamber a sponsorship fee of $15,000 before the unveiling and
traditional print making.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Although I pay at least the minimum requested of my credit
card, I get every month an ``overlimit fee'' of $29 even when I
have made no other purchases in the transaction period. And they
call this $29 overlimit fee a ``purchase,'' the only one I made
during this period. Is this legal? _ P. Bailey
</P>
<P>
   A: Perfectly. Oh dear. It is legal to call the overlimit fee
(charged when customers exeed their approved credit card limit) a
purchase, says Steve Rhode, president of the nonprofit Debt
Counselors of America. To get off the merry-go-round, make more
than the minimum payment. For credit and debt counseling, contact
Debt Counselors of America at (800) 680-DEBT.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have never seen any information about when you can legally
stop using a car seat. At what point is it legal not to use a car
seat and use seat belts instead? _ Nannette Rodriguez
</P>
<P>
   A: Seat belts are designed for adults, not children.
</P>
<P>
   Car seats should be appropriate for a child's weight and size.
The National Highway Traffic Safety Administration recommends older
kids over 40 pounds ride in booster seat-- until lap and shoulder
belts fit correctly. Some booster seats are constructed for
children up to 70 or 80 pounds. The lap belt must fit low and snug
on their hips. The shoulder belt must not cross their face or neck.
Never put the shoulder belt behind a child's back or under his arm.
</P>
<P>
   For more information on car seats, contact the Safe Riders
Program at (800) 252-8255 and ask for a copy of ``Buckle Up and be
a Safe Rider.''
</P>
<P>
   Contact Jane Greig, author of ``Thanks for Asking,'' at P.O. Box
670, Austin, Texas, 78767; (512) 445-3697; E-mail:
jgreig(AT)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
