r v BC-COMMENTARY-BJT31-COX     08-30 0633
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMMENTARY-BJT31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE COMMENTARY BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These columns for release Tuesday, August 31, 1999 are moving
today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   WALKER-COLUMN _ LONGVIEW, Texas _ ``If you don't have anything
in your car, you don't have anything to worry about.'' That's what
a Texas state trooper told a friend of my daughter's after he was
stopped on Interstate 20 and for the third time in three months
told that an officer needed to search his car for drugs. (Walker,
Longview News-Journal). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES _ So, it turns out on closer examination,
listening to Mozart doesn't make you smarter, except a little bit
and maybe for a nanosecond. Mozart's music is merely a pleasure _
but for a long time. Isn't that good enough? (Rosenfeld, Cox News
Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GEEWAX-Y2K-COLUMN _ Marilyn Geewax's weekly column looking at
issues raised by the coming of 2000. (Geewax, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ GIBSONBURG, Ohio. Most mornings I take my first
cup of coffee and the laptop to the front porch and settle into the
old wicker swing, pretending to work. I manage to fool everyone but
myself. Folks walking by wave and ask if I'm writing about them. I
assure them their darkest secrets will be headlines by Tuesday.
They grin and keep going. (Schuett, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   KABAT-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ Oh, vanity of vanities. It's no
secret I have terrible eyesight. If faith, as the Bible tells us,
is believing in what we cannot see, then my faith is growing
abundantly. (Kabat, Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   LANE-COLUMN _ DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Any scientific theory that
brings soft music to nurseries, induces state legislators to praise
the great composers and moves classical music product off the
shelves is a good thing. Not necessarily a true thing, but a good
thing. That's why I was sorry to read that scientists had debunked
the so-called ``Mozart effect.'' Perhaps someone will re-bunk it.
(Lane, Daytona Beach News-Journal) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BUDGET INFORMATION FOR SUBSCRIBERS OF THE NYT NEWS
SERVICE
</P>
<P>
   Spot news budgets move daily at 2 p.m. and 6 p.m. Eastern.
Additionally, separate features and commentary budgets move at 10
a.m., and sports and business budgets at 6 p.m. Additional updates
are possible if news developments warrant.
</P>
<P>
   All times are Eastern unless otherwise noted. If stories will
move after 8 p.m., an ETA will be given.
</P>
<P>
   PHOTOS, LAYOUTS and GRAPHICS CoxNet layouts are for sale over
the web, through the New York Times News Service's PageExpress
service, at www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
</P>
<P>
   If a budget line or story is marked with photos or graphics,
those are available from the New York Times News Service at
212-556-4204. Or call CoxNet for more information at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   HOW TO REACH US
</P>
<P>
   Questions should be directed to CoxNet, the Cox News Service, in
Atlanta at 404-526-5456. We are staffed 8 a.m. to 10 p.m.
Monday-Friday, and 1-10 p.m. on weekends and holidays.
</P>
<P>
   The news manager is Paul Foutch, 404-526-5429,
pfoutch(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   The day news editor is Tom Oder, 404-526-5887,
toder(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   The night news editor is Todd C. Duncan, 404-582-7282,
tduncan(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Cox Washington Bureau:
</P>
<P>
   News editor Art Dalglish, 202-887-8338, artd(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Foreign editor Rick Christie, 202-887-8316, rickc(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Bureau chief Andy Alexander, 202-887-8334, andya(at)coxnews.com
</P>
