<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEATURES-BJT31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE FEATURES BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These feature stories are moving today to clients of the New
York Times News Service. Stories are for release Tuesday, August
31, 1999, unless otherwise embargoed.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BUDGET INFORMATION
</P>
<P>
   So specialty editors can focus on one day's budget, CoxNet
produces themed features budgets each day. Here is the schedule:
</P>
<P>
   TODAY: Technology
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday for Wednesday: Automotive, personal finance and home &AMP;
garden
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday for Thursday: Food, CD reviews, video reviews
</P>
<P>
   Thursday for Friday: Movie reviews, travel, books and fashion
</P>
<P>
   Friday for Saturday: Religion and science &AMP; health
</P>
<P>
   In addition, separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports,
business and commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. An ETA is given if a
story will move after 8 p.m. Eastern.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   LOOK ON THE WEB: Stories marked as a CoxNet layout are available
for purchase in paginated form: www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOLOGY
</P>
<P>
   TECH-INSTANT _ Until just a few years ago _ eons by today's
cyber standards _ teen-agers used to spend hours on the phone just
talking about nothing. Now they do the same thing on a computer _
with as many friends, near and far, as their young brains can
juggle at once without exploding. Teens today spend hours at a
sitting shooting the electronic breeze with online buddies,
sometimes five or six at a time, no matter if they're across the
street or across an ocean. ``It's hot beyond belief. Young kids can
be in touch with their group at any time. And they can be talking
to multiple groups at once,'' said Roger Carlsen, a University of
Dayton professor who is an instructor and consultant in educational
technology. (DeBrosse, Dayton Daily News) MOVED FRIDAY.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   INSTANT-SIDE _ Sidebar listing some shorthand used on instant
messaging and explainer of emoticons. (Dayton Daily News) MOVED
FRIDAY. WITH ILLUSTRATION.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET PTECH PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is the CoxNet PTECH page for the current week. This
layout is available Tuesday after 2 p.m. EDT. Art includes two
color photos, one photo illustration and one color illustration
</P>
<P>
   COXNET PTECH 0828 WALKMAN ANNIVERSARY _ Twenty years and
worldwide sales of almost 200 million units later, the Walkman has
triumphed beyond Sony's wildest projections. (McLeese, Austin
American Statesman) Art includes 3-column color photo illustration
of a man wearing a Walkman and a 18-point color photo of a Sports
Walkman.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOBUDDY _ If you worry that Microsoft dominates the
technology world so completely that other software companies don't
have a chance, let me give you something more important to worry
about _ Intel. (Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.) Art includes
1 column color sig of columnist.
</P>
<P>
   NETWATCH _ Personal information is rapidly becoming the Web's
gold standard. Everyone from Amazon.com to The New York Times knows
that information is the Internet's most valuable currency. (Katz,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution.) Art includes 6-pica color
illustration of a computer.
</P>
<P>
   GADGETS _ The Sharper Image is offering a CD Shower Companion,
which the company claims is the first and only water-resistant
stereo CD player made for use in the shower. (Cummings, Dayton
Daily News) Art includes 1-column color photo of the CD Shower
Companion.
</P>
<P>
   TECH BRIEFS _ The new online sensation is called ``The Dating
Game Online.'' During its premiere week on the Web in July, it
attracted some 75,000 players. (Staff, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.)
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOBUDDY_ ATLANTA _ Serious gamers will get nothing from my
adventure. They use top-of-the-line machines and spend hours
reading about and discussing the latest hardware. But if you are a
typical home PC user and just looking to play an occasional game,
maybe what I learned can help. (Husted, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   POWERUSER-COLUMN _ In my quest for the techno-chops to see what
it would take to be able to creep down a dungeon hallway on a
giant-screen TV, I learned a good deal about monitors, video cards
and how they work together. (Yandel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-TOOLS _ ATLANTA _ A new CD-ROM from Grolier, by way of the
television series ``Nature,'' entitled ``Nature: Virtual
Serengeti,'' is aimed at children, and it has a great many
strengths. But it will require a certain amount of strength from
the youngsters who get into it. (Warner, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NETWATCH _ ATLANTA _ It's always something when it comes to the
new frontier of downloading and paying for music from the Internet.
Atlantic Records put a bold foot forward and decided to market the
new Tori Amos song ``Bliss'' as a secure downloadable track for
sale over the Internet. About 10 minutes later, somebody hacked the
song so it could be downloaded for free. This is essentially the
online equivalent of shoplifting, and nobody's too happy about it.
(Katz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CYBERSCENE _ In the beginning, the World Wide Web was more of a
curiosity _ a pig that could sing _ but nowadays many of us use the
Web in daily life. Today, we'll take a look at some sites that can
help you find a good barber, locate the nearest grocery store or
help you navigate to a new friend's home. (Husted, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-MEDIA _ What the tech magazines are writing about. (Haddad,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MAC-REPORT _ ATLANTA _ ``SimCity'' always has been a thing of
intellectual beauty. This computer game is so well thought out, so
full of nuances in its understanding of modern urban life, that you
can play it again and again and still be surprised. This tradition
continues with the latest version, ``SimCity 3000.'' The PC version
has been out for more than a year. The Mac version has now been
released. (Haddad , Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-REPORT _ Tech briefs on new products and developments.
(Clothier, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   NFK-CHECKITOUT _ A brief on a new web site, TV show or event for
kids. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NFK-NEWSFLASH _ Tips on how not to be nervous at a new school.
(Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NFK-FEATURE _ This week: Will crossed eyes really stick? Answers
to that and other eye facts. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CONSUMERQ&AMP;A _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Consumer Q&AMP;A. (Greig, Austin
American-Statesman) (l, a) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   DIXIECHICKS _ A story that defines the who, what, where, why and
when of the country music trio the Dixie Chicks. A year ago, the
threesome was an unknown country act playing Six Flags Over
Georgia. As they prepare to release their new CD (today, 8/31),
they are Grammy winners and the hottest thing going in country
music. We talk to them, their producer, their wardrobe folks, local
country radio, industry folks and real people. (MLongino, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 30.
</P>
<P>
   NEWSSTAND _ Periodicals on the newsstands this week. (O'Briant,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE-MEDICINEAIDS-CONFERENCE _ ATLANTA _ News out of the
CDC's AIDS conference. Possibly two stories. One on new HIV test to
be unveiled and another on HIV epidemic among African-Americans.
(Kim, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
