 Monday, Aug. 30, 1999     
 Editors      The Hearst News Service will file the following for
Tuesday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.    (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all sluglines.)   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ARMY-ADS (San Antonio) _ The Army's famed jingle, ``Be all that
you can be,'' may be history. Army Secretary Louis Caldera said his
service will take a hard look at the future of slogan, which was
introduced in 1981. The slogan was listed by Advertising Age
magazine as the century's No. 2 commercial tune, beaten out only by
McDonalds' theme, ``You deserve a break today.'' By SIG
CHRISTENSON.
</P>
<P>
   BREWER-PROFILE (Bryan, Texas) _ Lawrence Russell Brewer, the
quiet son of fundamentalist Christians, became a thief. When he
landed in prison for burglary at age 19, and later returned for
cocaine possession and parole violations, he seemed to embrace
inmate life. This week, Brewer becomes the second man to stand
trial for the capital murder of James Byrd Jr., the black man
dragged to death last year in Jasper. Jury selection begins
Tuesday. By PATTY REINERT.
</P>
<P>
   CRIMES-TEXAS (Del Rio, Texas) _ A federal mandate to prosecute
more drug and immigration crime is straining the federal courts in
Texas and setting justice on a collision course with the
constitutional rights of the accused. There has been a 74 percent
increase in the number of criminal cases filed in the federal court
in the Southern District of Texas _ the bulk of which are petty
drug possession or illegal entry/re-entry into the country. By
DEBORAH TEDFORD.
</P>
<P>
   DESIGNER-DRUGS (Houston) _ In this day of premanufactured
pharmaceuticals there is still a need for medications made the
old-fashioned way _ with mortar and pestle. Called compounding,
this specialty is a small but growing field that's filling a
valuable medical service. By LISA DAVIS.
</P>
<P>
   PERFECT-STORM (Corpus Christi, Texas) _ Could Hurricane Bret
have been the ``perfect storm?'' Marine researchers think so. Major
tropical storms are the best way to unclog some of the Gulf coast's
silt-filled, brown-tide-damaged bays and estuaries. The storm,
which caused little damage and no deaths when it hit Texas, may
have helped restore the natural balance of fresh and salt water
necessary for many forms of coastal wildlife. By JAMES PINKERTON.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-STORM-REVIEW (Undated) _ A look at Erik Larson's book,
``Isaac's Storm,'' which tells the story of the 1900 hurricane that
destroyed Galveston, Texas. By BOB TUTT.
</P>
<P>
   AUDIO-BOOKS (Undated) _ Vince Flynn's ``Transfer of Power'' is a
significant improvement over his political thriller ``Term
Limits.'' Sure, ``Transfer'' contains some roll-your-eyes plot
developments and capitalizes on well-worn stereotypes. But Flynn is
clearly working harder this time out. By DOUG BLACKBURN.
</P>
<P>
   TV-REVIEW-PARKERS (Undated) _ Give UPN credit for launching one
of the few TV shows this season that has an African American cast.
Then subtract points for airing yet another sitcom that's as
predictable and rim-shot rote as they come. ``The Parkers'' is a
spinoff from one of UPN's longest-running hits, ``Moesha.'' But any
resemblance _ especially to quality _ ends there. By TIM GOODMAN.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-HOLLY-FLAP (Undated) _ A look at the flap over the annual
Labor Day music festival in Lubbock, Texas, honoring rock 'n' roll
legend Buddy Holly. His widow, Maria Elena Holly of Dallas, has
threatened to sue the visitors and convention bureau over linking
the event to Holly with licensing rights. By JIM HENDERSON.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-SPELLING-PROFILE (Undated) _ Tori Spelling of TV's
``Beverly Hills, 90210'' relishes showing a new side to people who
see her touchingly funny, scene-stealing performance in the movie
``Trick.'' By JOEY GUERRA.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-BLONDIE (Undated) _ Blondie is back. And the groups
enduring music _ and tour _ is hitting a chord with fans. By JOEY
GUERRA.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   AMPUTEE-INVENTOR (Brazoria, Texas) _ After losing a hand in an
industrial accident, Ron Farquharson got a prosthesis on that arm
with a hook on the end. But years of frustration at trying to use
tools and kitchen implements with the hook led him and a co-worker
to design and make a ``terminal device'' _ a receptor attachment
for the end of a prosthetic arm. All kinds of specially adapted
tools can be snapped onto the end and turned to 45-degree angles or
rotated 360 degrees. By STEVE OLAFSON. (Photo available on NYT
database).
</P>
<P>
   BARLOW-COLUMN (Houston) _ Cellular phones and driving just don't
mix. It's dangerous to drive while talking on the phone. A Toronto
study concludes that people who talk and drive are moving about as
well as someone who has quaffed the legal limit of alcohol. Three
countries _ Brazil, Israel and Australia _ have banned the use of
telephones while driving. Don't expect similar legislation in the
United States. By JIM BARLOW.
</P>
<P>
   CONVEX-MIRRORS (Troy, N.Y.) _ Convex mirrors became the fashion
in the late 18th and early 19th century. The mirrors, also called
``bull's-eye,'' were popular in the neoclassical era, the Federal
period and with Hepplewhite furnishings, which have graceful
curves. One type, the girandole looking glass, often features a
branched candleholder. By FRANCES INGRAHAM HEINS.
</P>
<P>
   TREASURES-JUNK (Houston) _ Van Goghs in the garage, Rembrandts
in the attic? Here's how to tell if your family's long-neglected
collectibles actually might be worth something in today's art and
antique market. By PATRICIA C. JOHNSON.
</P>
<P>
   BIKE-TRAILS-HOUSTON (Houston) _ Deep in the urban heart of
Houston _ a place known for its relentless flatness _ lies a
near-wilderness startling in its verticality. Now, the park and its
proper use are at the center of a shrill debate between thousands
of youthful off-road mountain bikers and the park's traditional
defenders, the Memorial Park Advisory Board. The 1,500-acre park is
a haven for weary city-dwellers. By ALLAN TURNER. (Photo available
on NYT database).
</P>
<P>
   DORM-TEXAS (College Station, Texas) _ Hart Hall, traditionally
an all-male bastion of stoics at Texas A&AMP;M University, is now coed.
The dormitory, the cheapest housing on campus, is also without air
conditioning. Now women can sweat it out with their male
counterparts. Oh boy! By PATTY REINERT.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ A reader asks, ``Branches are breaking
off the pecan trees in my neighborhood. The limbs do not seem to
have any insect damage and seem healthy. Is it because of the
earlier summer rains that are causing the limbs to be too heavy to
support the heavy pecan load? Is there anything that can be done to
prevent further damage to the trees?''Assorted Q&AMP;As. By KATHY
HUBER.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DRILLING-TECHNOLOGY (Houston) _ Deepwater drilling is on the
cusp of huge technological advances, says Marshall Adkins, an
energy service analyst in Houston for Raymond James &AMP; Associates,
an institutional research firm. Most technologies to date have been
evolutionary, according to Adkins. The revolutionary ones will be
in fiber optics, in deepwater drilling, underbalanced drilling and
in seismic data collection, he predicts. ``We are on the edge.'' By
NELSON ANTOSH.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COLUMN (Houston) _ He seemed perfectly sane when he
stopped by the office some time ago. Polite. Soft-spoken.
Articulate. Feet planted firmly on the floor. So why does Doug
Lansky insist on lassoing reindeer above the Arctic Circle in
Sweden? Playing underwater hockey in Australia? Participating in
the world's largest tomato fight in Spain? And why is he now on a
five-month honeymoon that began last week with stops in Uganda,
Rwanda and Kenya and will continue at sumo wrestling school in
Japan? By HARRY SHATTUCK.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-REDRIVER (Undated) _ In the Red River Valley, which hugs
the Texas-Oklahoma border, the legends are larger, the fish seem
bigger and the days are filled with delightful discoveries. When
not pausing to watch the light shimmer on an area lake, take time
to savor the nostalgia of an authentic town square. Here beside the
courthouse or on Main Street, the personality of the region _ and
its people _ is best defined. By SYD KEARNEY. (Photos available on
the NYT database).
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-REDRIVER-GIMMICKS (Undated) _ You gotta have a gimmick,
young Gypsy Rose Lee was advised in the popular musical ``Gypsy.''
Those words of wisdom ring true for tourist-hungry towns as well as
entertainers, and towns in the Red River Valley tout attractions as
diverse as an Eiffel Tower (in Paris) to a two-state post office
(in Texarkana). By SYD KEARNEY. (Photos available on the NYT
database).
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   OUTDOORS-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ California's best places in
the great outdoors are a mystery. Hell Hole Reservoir, set deep on
the west flank of the Sierra Nevada, is much like this. I became
transfixed by this long, narrow lake set in a granite gorge. The
lake was obviously remote, yet accessible by car, with a paved road
all the way in. By TOM STIENSTRA.
</P>
<P>
   RATTO-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ The story was floated deftly, so
that it would sort of stick to the back of your brain rather than
hit you flush in the face. Plus, there were no fingerprints to lead
the reader anywhere. The story was that there have been some
backchannel discussions among baseball executives about buying out
a few of the straggling teams, presumably to save their cities the
shame of having to tolerate underfunded baseball any longer. The
four cities mentioned were Minnesota, Kansas City, Montreal and
Oakland. By RAY RATTO.
</P>
<P>
   GLF-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Golf is an old game, but its fans
may be younger than ever. And one 23-year-old is sounding almost
fatherly in expressing concern about where this may lead. Tiger
Woods was talking specifically about next month's Ryder Cup in
Brookline, Mass., in light of the boisterousness of the fans during
his battle with Sergio Garcia at the PGA Championship two weeks
ago. By SUSAN FORNOFF.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Yet another newspaper columnist
was fired last week for allegedly making up people and quotes. Now
I've decided to come clean. After all, this column is nearly 12
years running; that's a tanker truck full of material that The San
Francisco Examiner could investigate and find bogus. By STEPHANIE
SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   ROBISON-COLUMN (Austin, Texas) _ It was almost refreshing last
week when the federal health experts at the Centers for Disease
Control and Prevention renewed debate over the tobacco settlements
negotiated by Texas and other states. The CDC's No. 1 concern is
whether Texas and other states are making the best possible use of
their tobacco dollars to fight smoking, the single most preventable
cause of death and disease in the United States and, supposedly,
the main reason the states sued cigarette companies in the first
place. By CLAY ROBISON.
</P>
<P>
   DYING (Medford, N.J.) _ Americans take dying much too seriously.
Death is serious, but dying is just a step on the way, a place
where you can choose, by the way you think, to be very much alive.
Unfortunately, once other people know you're dying, they think they
have to say things like, ``I'm so sorry,'' when what you really
wish they would do is tell you a good joke. By DALE O'REILLEY.
</P>
