<HEADER>
A4241 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN-COX     08-30 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Small steps across life's big intersection
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Most mornings I take my first cup of coffee
and the laptop to the front porch and settle into the old wicker
swing, pretending to work. I manage to fool everyone but myself.
Folks walking by wave and ask if I'm writing about them. I assure
them their darkest secrets will be headlines by Tuesday. They grin
and keep going.
</P>
<P>
   This morning a pretty blonde lady on an old balloon-tire bicycle
and her two young daughters, each on a miniature of mom's bike, are
out for an early ride. They have a system. Mom pedals up to the
intersection and raises her arm. The chicks lined up behind her go
for their brakes. Then, Mom wheels her bike to the middle of the
street, looks both ways before declaring it safe for the girls to
cross. She stays there, on guard, until the tots are out of harm's
way. They pedal on. The little girls are pleased about crossing a
big street. I can hear them chatter excitedly as they ride away.
</P>
<P>
   One spring afternoon, shortly after I'd moved here 15 years ago,
a very young boy climbed the big front stairs to my porch and asked
me if I wanted to buy some ``stuff'' to help out his ball team. He
wasn't sure what it was he was selling, but insisted it was really
good stuff and that I probably needed some. He was so cute and his
sales pitch so earnest, I purchase some just to be sure I never ran
out of ``stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   As I filled in the order form, I asked him how business was. He
looked at me, shook his head, and explained that it wasn't too bad
but would have been a whole lot better if only his mom would let
him cross the street. He was four.
</P>
<P>
   Years later, the young salesman was in one of my English
classes. Now he's a sophomore at the university, crossing big
streets and everything. Whatever his mama taught him worked.
</P>
<P>
   The year I began kindergarten, my mother walked me to and from
school every day because there were two streets to cross. They were
just little neighborhood streets, but the way my mother carried on,
you would have thought it was Chicago's Dan Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   By first grade I was feeling pretty grown up _ I had school
supplies _ pencils, paste, and a bag to carry it all in. I asked to
be allowed to walk to school with the other kids - without my
mother. No way!
</P>
<P>
   Second grade, I tried again and got the same answer. I argued
there was a war on and since gas was rationed there would be fewer
cars on the road. Mother reminded me that old Mr. Kelly had a ``B''
sticker and was still racing around the neighborhood in second gear
(he'd forgotten how to shift, Daddy said), and until he parked his
old Ford I was not crossing a street alone.
</P>
<P>
   Third grade the major threat to my safety was Herman Preefer, a
mean kid who wore striped T-shirts and corduroy knickers. Still, my
mother made ready to walk me to school. This time I had a fit and
sat my backside on the sidewalk insisting the only way she was
going to take me to school would be to drag me. So she did.
</P>
<P>
   That evening at dinner Mother described the scene to my father.
He frowned and made me eat peas. That's when I began to suspect my
mother would be walking me to school until I was old enough to
drive _ or vote _ whichever came first.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, my father was moved by logic _ when I explained his
wife was ruining my social life by not letting me walk alone with
my friends he suggested I let her follow at a distance. I was
adamant. He said we'd give it a try my way, but if ever I should be
observed behaving recklessly at a crossing, I would be tossed into
the car and driven to school for the rest of my life. I was
ecstatic.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, I took off on my own. First, I hid my green
leggings in the Bartel's hedge (big kids didn't wear those baby
things), then I joined my friends. Man, was I cool or what! Then
Arthur Corbett kissed me.
</P>
<P>
   I went screaming home, begging my mother to walk me to school
until Arthur got over it. She refused.
</P>
<P>
   That was when I began to suspect being grown up isn't all it's
cracked up to be.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or email: eschuett(at)nwonline.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
