<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-BOSTON-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON'S WATERFRONT COMES CLEAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN HOLDER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star   BOSTON _ It's cold. The wind is
blowing. And it has been raining, on and off, all morning. The kind
of morning when you wake up and say, ``What a great day to visit a
wastewater treatment plant!''
<TEXT>
<P>
   Deborah Burwick might have thought so, but most of her charges
didn't. They didn't show up.
</P>
<P>
   Only three students from Burwick's class for displaced workers
made it out to the Deer Island Treatment Plant in Boston Harbor.
They missed seeing the $3.8 billion plant and learning what an
important role it has played over the last few years in the
incredible cleanup of Boston Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never ate a lobster from Boston Harbor the last few years
because I knew the harbor was dirty,'' said tour guide Bernie
Devlin, an operations liaison for the Massachusetts Water Resources
Authority.
</P>
<P>
   That's no longer true. The harbor is safe again for lobsters and
other ocean life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hearing rumors of aquatic life they haven't seen in years
out there,'' Devlin said. Healthy lobsters. Harbor seals. And
people.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't so long ago that Boston Harbor was a laughingstock. In
the 1988 presidential campaign George Bush embarrassed rival
Michael Dukakis, Massachusetts' governor at the time, when he
called Boston Harbor the dirtiest in America.
</P>
<P>
   Now gleaming new hotels welcome well-heeled guests to the
waterfront. The Temptations, Willie Nelson and Donna Summer brought
yuppie suburbanites to a summer pavilion in the Seaport District. A
federal courthouse opened on Fan Pier last year, and plans call for
a $695 million convention center. Construction is everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Dawn Curtis, director of communications for the year-old Seaport
Hotel and nearby World Trade Center, points enthusiastically to
what will be.
</P>
<P>
   On Fan Pier, she said, two Hyatt hotels are to be built. Retail,
office and residential developments are in the works. Charter boats
and water taxis already launch from the area.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the concert series at the 5,000-seat Bank Boston
Pavilion, a Boston radio station sponsored a series of ``Smooth
Jazz'' cruises every Friday night this summer. And earlier this
month the Celebrate Seaport Festival brought people in for canoeing
and kayaking, antiques and a farmers market. A new line of the
``T,'' Boston's subway system, is under construction, leading to an
eventual Seaport station.
</P>
<P>
   ``The waterfront is the area for development,'' says Vivien Li,
executive director of the Boston Harbor Association. ``This mayor
(Thomas M. Menino) has decided that his legacy will be development
along the waterfront.''
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Harbor Association was founded in 1973 by the Boston
Shipping Association and the League of Women Voters. For the last
eight years, Li has been executive director of the group, now
primarily made up of business people.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the first years, cleaning was the key to us,'' she said,
pointing out that the state has spent $30 million on that effort.
</P>
<P>
   Beaches are monitored daily. ``The water is significantly
cleaner,'' she said. ``You can actually swim in it, unless it rains
more than half an inch.'' Even then swimmers can generally return
after 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Now cleanup is just one concern, evidenced by the abundance of
construction projects. The harbor area has proved an attractive
place to live for a lot of very successful people, Li said,
particularly empty nesters in their 50s and 60s. Condominiums in
the area sell for $450,000 and up.
</P>
<P>
   But that kind of success isn't what drives Li, a longtime
activist and environmentalist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our motto is a clean, alive and accessible harbor,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Accessibility is key to her. The harbor association has been
instrumental in the development of the HarborWalk, a half-completed
project that eventually will become a 43-mile continuous walkway
around the harbor.
</P>
<P>
   She points with pride to certain businesses that have been
particularly welcoming, and not just to paying clients.
</P>
<P>
   - On Rowes Wharf, for example, Foster's Rotunda in the Boston
Harbor Hotel is an elegant retreat, offering its space for free at
midday for people to sit and watch the harbor's activities through
its large windows.
</P>
<P>
   - The historic Marriott's Custom House, built in 1847, offers
free historical tours at 4 p.m. daily. You can peer into the inner
workings of the tower's famous clock, 221/2 feet in diameter. And
the observation deck offers a magnificent view from the 26th
floor..MDNM/
</P>
<P>
   - Even the Marriott Long Wharf hotel, which Li had long
criticized for its lack of public access, now offers public
restrooms and tables, seating for public use and water
transportation connections.
</P>
<P>
   Access will be crucial to the long-term success of the harbor as
a destination. Right now it's tough even to get there because of
the Big Dig, a $10.8 billion project that, among other things, is
sending 71/2 miles of Boston's Central Artery underground. Eight to
10 lanes of expressway will be hidden below 27 acres of new park
land.
</P>
<P>
   That's still five years away. And even though Bostonians are
used to congested and busy roads, traffic can be a nightmare if
you're anywhere close to the harbor.
</P>
<P>
   Go anyway. The promises of what the harbor will be shouldn't
deter you from seeing what's already there. You might even start at
the Big Dig.
</P>
<P>
   Just across from the New England Aquarium, the Big Dig Visitor
Center puts everything in perspective. Displays help explain the
reasons behind the project _ 200,000 cars a day. They tell what has
already taken place and what's happening now, and a model of the
project puts everything into perspective. The kids can even dig
into a mini-construction site.
</P>
<P>
   If the Big Dig center is a brief diversion, the aquarium on
Central Wharf is a destination. It centers on a four-story, 200,000
gallon circular tank surrounded by a penguin rookery. As you walk
the spiraling ramp to the top, watch out for the sand tiger sharks,
moray eels, sea turtles and hundreds of tropical fish. Check out
the Aquarium Medical Center, a working animal care laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   Boston advertises itself as America's Most Walkable City, and
it's especially true along the harbor.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes south of the aquarium, just across the Congress
Street Bridge, you'll see a huge inflated Arthur, the cartoon
aardvark. He's welcoming kids to the Children's Museum. Inside,
they'll find more of ``Arthur's World,'' plus a giant's desktop and
an 800-gallon replica of the Fort Point Channel scene outside the
museum.
</P>
<P>
   Next, stop at the Boston Tea Party Ship &AMP; Museum, on the
Congress Street Bridge, where you might think you've wandered into
a comedy club.
</P>
<P>
   The history is serious here, aboard a replica of the Brig
Beaver, one of three ships from which patriot tax protesters dumped
342 crates of tea from nearby Griffin's Wharf in December 1773. But
this place also recognizes the potential for silliness. As an
actress explains how the tea party came about, she encourages
visitors to shout ``Fie!'' on taxes and ``Dump the Tea! Into the
Sea!''
</P>
<P>
   Willing participants can re-enact the tea party, wearing
``simple but effective'' day-glo blue ``Mohawk'' feathers. They can
even dump crates into the harbor (don't worry, they're roped to the
ship). Best of all, perhaps, is a cup of tax-free tea.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you'd want to, it's virtually impossible to ignore the
history in Boston. Head north along the harbor past Christopher
Columbus Park, and you'll quickly find yourself in the North End,
one of Boston's oldest working neighborhoods and among the most
historic.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a good chance to wander inland just a few blocks (OK,
maybe we're cheating, but the North End is too good to pass up).
See that red painted line snaking along the sidewalk? It means
you're on the Freedom Trail, which connects 16 historic sites
throughout the city.
</P>
<P>
   One stop is Paul Revere's house, built in 1680 and one of the
few pieces of 17th-century architecture remaining in Boston. Here
you'll learn that Revere's midnight ride was partly myth. He didn't
ride through the streets yelling, ``The British are coming!''
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1774 we had not declared independence, so technically
everybody was British,'' a guide says. Moreover, to avoid arrest
``most likely he stopped at individual doors to alert people.''
</P>
<P>
   It's comforting to learn, then, that your schoolbooks were a
little more accurate when it comes to the Old North Church, an
active Episcopal congregation a few blocks away. A plaque in front
of the 1723 building reads: ``The signal lanterns of Paul Revere
displayed in the steeple of the church April 18, 1775, warned the
country of the march of the British troops to Lexington and
Concord.''
</P>
<P>
   Historic or not, the North End is a fascinating place to spend
an afternoon. It's the kind of neighborhood where old men sit on
benches, chewing on cigar stubs, and white-haired women lean out
their windows, watching the cigar-chewing men (and the tourists).
Where Mom-and-Pop groceries and Italian restaurants nestle among
the apartment buildings and the churches and ball fields.
</P>
<P>
   But the harbor calls. Just a few blocks and you're back on the
water, across the Charlestown Bridge from the USS Constitution,
which first launched in 1797 and gained its nickname, ``Old
Ironsides,'' in the War of 1812.
</P>
<P>
   Although it's still a commissioned warship (with a crew of 71
officers and seamen), the Constitution is more of a museum than
anything else these days. Sailors offer free guided tours, during
which you'll learn, among other things, that ``Old Ironsides'' is a
misnomer; the ship got its nickname because of the strength of its
oak sides.
</P>
<P>
   The Constitution also offers a pretty good place to survey the
Boston skyline. Peer past that ship's masts, and you can see the
American history. Keep looking and you can see city's future.
</P>
<P>
   Out on Deer Island, Bernie Devlin sees it every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three years ago,'' he said, ``I could count the number of
boats in the harbor. Now I guarantee you won't be able to count
them all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
