<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-BOSSIDE-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOING TO BOSTON, GREAT THINGS TO DO IN BOSTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN HOLDER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GOING TO BOSTON Getting there
</P>
<P>
   Round trip airfare between Kansas City and Boston recently ran
from about $250, with restrictions. By car it's a 1,400-mile trip.
Getting around
</P>
<P>
   With or without the Big Dig, Boston is not a driver-friendly
city. But public transportation is inexpensive and plentiful. A
one-way fare on the ``T,'' Boston's subway system, costs 85 cents.
Passes also are available for one day, $5; three days, $9; and
seven days, $18. Call (800) 392-6100. Where to stay
</P>
<P>
   Hotel bargains are rare. Unless you're prepared to stay far away
from the city center, don't be surprised to pay more than $200 a
night.
</P>
<P>
   - Boston Milner Hotel, 78 S. Charles St. The rooms are tiny, the
water pressure was nearly nonexistent, but the location and price
were right. Near Boston Common and the theater district. Prices
start at $70, including continental breakfast. Call (800) 453-1731
or visit www.milner-hotels.com.
</P>
<P>
   - Seaport Hotel, 1 Seaport Lane. This 427-room hotel opened last
year in the Seaport District, across from the World Trade Center.
Weekend rates begin at $139. Call (617) 385-4000 or visit
www.seaporthotel.com
</P>
<P>
   - Marriott Long Wharf, 296 State St. Right on the harbor, near
the aquarium and Fanueil Hall. Rates begin about $300. Call (617)
227-0800.
</P>
<P>
   - Boston Harbor Hotel, 70 Rowes Wharf. Charter boats and water
taxis depart from Rowes Wharf, where this elegant 230-room hotel
sits. Check out the premier collection of Boston Harbor maps. Rates
range from $350 to $450. Call (800) 752-7077. Where to eat
</P>
<P>
   - Legal Seafoods. This chain of seafood restaurants boasts that
its clam chowder has been served at the last five presidential
inaugurations. Locations are all over Boston, including one at Long
Wharf, across from the New England Aquarium. Visit
www.legalseafoods.com
</P>
<P>
   - No-Name, 151/2 Fish Pier. Fresh seafood on a working pier has
made the No-Name popular with tourists. Call (617) 338-7539.
</P>
<P>
   - Artu, 6 Prince St. This small North End Italian restaurant is
just around the corner from the Paul Revere House. Call (617)
742-4336.
</P>
<P>
   - Henrietta's Table, in the Charles Hotel, Cambridge. This
trendy restaurant near Harvard serves fresh New England comfort
foods like Yankee pot roast and chicken pot pie. Call (617)
661-5005.
</P>
<P>
   - Plaza III _ The Kansas City Steakhouse. Sound familiar? The
Country Club Plaza institution has a location at Fanueil Hall. Call
(617) 720-5570. Attractions
</P>
<P>
   - Boston Tea Party Ship &AMP; Museum, Congress Street Bridge.
American patriots dumped tea from three ships from nearby Griffin's
Wharf in December 1773 to protest a tax on tea. One of those ships,
the Brig Beaver, is re-created here. Hours are 9 a.m.-6 p.m.
through Labor Day. Admission is $8 for adults, $7 for students 13
and older, $4 for children 4-12. Call (617) 338-1773.
</P>
<P>
   - New England Aquarium, Central Wharf. Centerpiece is the Giant
Ocean Tank Caribbean Coral Reef Exhibit, which rises four stories
and contains 200,000 gallons of water. Through Labor Day, hours are
9 a.m.-6 p.m. Monday, Tuesday and Friday, 9 a.m.-8 p.m. Wednesday
and Thursday, 9 a.m.-7 p.m. Saturday and Sunday. Admission is $12
for adults, $10 for senior adults, $6 for children 3-11, free for
children younger than free. Call (617) 973-5200 or visit
www.neaq.org.
</P>
<P>
   - Children's Museum. 300 Congress St. Take the kids to Arthur's
World, Boats Afloat and Grandparents' Attic. Open 10 a.m.-5 p.m.
Saturday-Thursday, 10 a.m.-9 p.m. Friday. Admission is $7 for
adults; $6 for senior adults and children 2-15; $2 for 1-year-olds.
Call (617) 426-6500.
</P>
<P>
   - Freedom Trail. From Boston Common to Bunker Hill and the USS
Constitution, this three-mile walking trail encompasses 16 historic
sites, including the State House, Fanueil Hall, Boston Massacre
site and the Old North Church. Follow the red paint on the sidewalk
or get a map from the Visitors Information Center on Tremont Street
in Boston Common.
</P>
<P>
   - USS Constitution. ``Old Ironsides'' is in the Charlestown Navy
Yard. Navy sailors provide free guided tours from 9:30 a.m. to 3:50
p.m. daily. Self-guided tours are available until sunset. Call
(617) 242-7511 or visit www.ncts.navy.mil//homepages//constitution.
</P>
<P>
   - Old North Church, 193 Salem St. The Old North Church is still
an active Episcopal congregation but is open for tours to see the
place where two lanterns gave direction to Paul Revere in 1775.
Donations are accepted. Call (617) 523-6676 or visit
www.oldnorth.com
</P>
<P>
   - Paul Revere House, 19 North Square. The house, built in 1680,
was old when Revere bought it in 1770. Open 9 a.m. to 5:15 p.m.
through Oct. 31. Admission is $2.50 for adults; $2 for students and
seniors; $1 for children 5-17. Call (617) 523-2338 or visit
www.paulreverehouse.org
</P>
<P>
   - Deer Island Treatment Plant. Free tours of the Massachusetts
Water Resources Authority plant on Deer Island are available by
appointment. Call (617) 539-4139 or visit www.mwra.com
</P>
<P>
   - Big Dig Visitor Center, on Milk Street across from the New
England Aquarium. Understand why the traffic near Boston Harbor is
so bad and what's being done about it. Free admission. Hours: 10
a.m. to 4:30 daily. Call (617) 973-5271. For other information
about the Big Dig visit www.bigdig.com For more information
</P>
<P>
   Call the Greater Boston Convention &AMP; Visitors Bureau at
1-888-SEE-BOSTON or visit the Web site www.bostonusa.com
When the harbor isn't enough ...
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the developing harborfront, Boston is a virtual must-do
list. A few choices:
</P>
<P>
   1. Find pleasure in the Common. Boston Common, covering 50 acres
in the city's heart, is reported to be the country's oldest public
park. It's still a great place to find a park bench, rest your feet
and people-watch. Or ...
</P>
<P>
   2. Make your way to the ducklings. Bronze sculptures of Mrs.
Mallard and her eight ducklings _ made famous in Robert McCloskey's
children's book Make Way for Ducklings, waddle through Boston
Common near Beacon and Charles streets.
</P>
<P>
   3. Or ride a duck. Boston Duck Tours offers narrated excursions
on renovated World War II amphibious landing vehicles. You'll get a
view of Boston 1) by land and 2) by sea. Call (617) 723-DUCK.
</P>
<P>
   4. Pay your respects at the Holocaust Memorial. Six five-story
green glass columns are filled on all sides with identification
numbers representing the Jews who were killed during the Holocaust.
The memorial is at Union Park across from City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   5. Have lunch at Fanueil Hall. In the 18th century, Fanueil Hall
(between Congress Street and Merchants Row) was a food market, as
well as a meeting hall. It serves much the same purpose today, with
dozens of food stalls and shops. Hint: To find the meeting hall
where the revolutionary patriots met, look for the center doors and
head upstairs.
</P>
<P>
   6. Look for Norm's bar stool. The Bull &AMP; Finch, 84 Beacon St.,
is the place where everybody knows your name, the inspiration for
the TV series ``Cheers.'' Truth is, there's a lot more ``Cheers''
here than there is ``Bull &AMP; Finch.'' Call (617) 227-9605.
</P>
<P>
   7. Find time for Fenway. The Red Sox's days are numbered in
historic old Fenway Park, where Babe Ruth, Ted Williams and Carl
Yastrzemski played (not to mention Pedro Martinez and Nomar
Garciaparra), but there's still time to see the Green Monster. The
Sox hope to move into a new Fenway by 2003. Call (617) 482-4SOX or
visit www.redsox.com
</P>
<P>
   8. Visit the Oval Office. Besides exhibits on the president and
an Oval Office replica, the John F. Kennedy Library and Museum (at
Columbia Point in the Dorchester neighborhood) features displays on
first lady Jacqueline Kennedy and Bobby Kennedy, who served his
brother as attorney general. Call (617) 929-4500 or visit
www.cs.umb.edu//jfklibrary/main.html
</P>
<P>
   9. Take in a show. Boston has a lively theater district, with
several Broadway-style venues and stars. Check out the booth at
Fanueil Hall for half-price tickets the day of the show. Or call
(617) 482-BTIX.
</P>
<P>
   10. Say ``I went to Harvard'' (if only for the afternoon).
Cambridge, the home of Harvard University, is just across the
Charles River. You can soak up plenty of atmosphere, if not
education, here.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
