<HEADER>
A4248 &Cx1f; kan-z
r l BC-TRAVEL-YMCA-KANSAS-KA     08-30 1609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-YMCA-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN COLORADO, YMCA ACREAGES ARE NEW PLACES FOR FAMILY REUNIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KAREN UHLENHUTH  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star   ESTES PARK, Colo. _ Somewhere,
somehow, a rocking-chair rumor got started about this place.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``There are no rocking chairs on our porch,'' Dave Thomas told
me over the phone with a finality that left no room for hope.
``That's a figment of someone's imagination.''
</P>
<P>
   Benches and Adirondack chairs they do have at the YMCA of the
Rockies meeting center here. And an awesome view to go with them.
And a cafeteria that seats 600. And an auditorium with chairs for
800. And 530 lodge rooms. And 205 cabins set back in the fringes.
</P>
<P>
   Although most of the facilities were built decades ago to
accommodate conferences of church members and young people, school
and recreational groups, in more recent years this has become a
magnet for grannies and grandpas, aunts and uncles, siblings,
grandchildren and cousins.
</P>
<P>
   The YMCA's Estes Park Center, and its sister center, Snow
Mountain Ranch near Winter Park, Colo., now find themselves in the
family-reunion business. And a booming business it has proven to
be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say they certainly are right up there at the top in
terms of number of reunions they hold,'' said Edith Wagner, editor
of Reunions magazine, based in Milwaukee. ``The YMCA does recruit
reunions and really does an excellent job.''
</P>
<P>
   In an average year, the two Colorado Y centers, which more or
less flank Rocky Mountain National Park on the east and southwest
sides, play host to about 650 family reunions, according to Thomas,
the marketing director for both of them. They've become such
popular sites for big family get-togethers that for extremely
popular times of the year, such as the Fourth of July, ``you'd
better say you want it in the year 2020,'' Wagner jokingly said.
</P>
<P>
   The Y's have much to offer to far-flung extended families.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're less expensive than a lot of other places,'' Wagner
said. ``They offer a lot of options. You can eat there or not eat
there. They have dorms, they have places like motels, they have
lodges, they have cabins and they're adjacent to camping.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their location is spectacular. There's so much happening
around them. The land they cover is huge, too. This is not a tiny
little place like a hotel. It's humongous.''
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, she said, ``They have anything you would want to do
right on site.'' The options include horseback riding, swimming,
golf and the miniature version, arts and crafts, hiking and biking.
</P>
<P>
   ``It lends itself to families that want to do a couple of
different things,'' Wagner said, and to parents who'd like a wee
bit of time away from their children. The Y's offer day camp for
children and adolescents from 3 through 17, setting their parents
free to pursue their own agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Pam Henderek, communications assistant for the centers, said
that the facilities' relative isolation gives many parents ``a
sense of safety. They don't feel that they have to take their kids
everywhere. They let their kids walk to the program office and the
pool.''
</P>
<P>
   Although there is a Christian presence at the centers _ both
have a chapel and a chaplain and strive to provide service that is
infused with Christian values _ Henderek said there is no
proselytizing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't push it. You don't have to be a Christian to come
here. We have Jewish groups, Muslim groups.''
</P>
<P>
   Sherry Swinton heard about the Y from her son, who was a pastor
for a time in a church in nearby Littleton, Colo. Over the years,
one or another of her husband's cousins occasionally proposed a
reunion, and Swinton figured that a place where the guests wouldn't
have to cook, and with a mountain backdrop, would be just the
ticket.
</P>
<P>
   The location is ``an extra inducement to get people to come,''
said her husband, Jerrold Swinton, a Methodist minister in their
hometown of Waterloo, Iowa. ``The second and third generations need
an extra inducement. To get people to leave California ... they're
not sure there is civilization beyond. Tcome to the
Rockies.''
</P>
<P>
   And come they did, from as far away as North Carolina, Texas
and, yes, California. It was a relatively short trip for Bruce
Giddings and his wife, Melissa, who live in Logan, Utah. They
appreciated the freedom and the multitude of options provided by
the Estes Park Center and by Bruce's relatives, who persuaded about
60 members of the Giddings clan to attend.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so many things to do here,'' Melissa said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice in that it's not structured all day long,'' Bruce
said. He and his wife felt free to spend the days on their own,
especially hiking next door at Rocky Mountain National Park, and
returning for the nightly reunion get-together from 7 to 9 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The Giddingses were an unmistakable presence at the Estes Park
Center in late July, with their color-coded T-shirts that said,
``Giddings Family Reunion _ Estes Park, Colo. _ July 1999.''
</P>
<P>
   Descendants of Jerrold's mother and her four siblings were
present. Each of the five branches had its own T-shirt color.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure I'd recognize them without their shirts on,''
said Bruce, who recalls meeting just a few of his relations when he
was a boy three decades ago. ``It's pretty much strangers.''
</P>
<P>
   The entourage had a block of rooms in a hotel-type building, as
well as the use of a common area where they had a get-together each
evening amid tables with displays of family
me.MDBO/.MDSD/.MDNM/mentos.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors find a variety of uses for their meeting space,
Henderek said. Some families set up a family tree. Some work on
quilts.
</P>
<P>
   Having been to a reunion of the other side of his family in
which things were a bit less orderly and there wasn't enough food
to go around, Bruce had praise for the way in which this one
unfolded.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a good place. We are all in the same place. It's
fairly easy. I'm impressed.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Y's Estes Park Center opened for business in 1909, and
the Snow Mountain Ranch about opened 60 years later, they were
geared toward conventions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably 20 years ago, we began to see a lot of family
reunions,'' said Thomas, the marketing director. ``They said they
wanted the same services conferences wanted _ lodging, meals,
meeting space, recreation. Since we had that in place, we began to
see a lot of family reunions coming to both centers. We began to
book them more or less as fill-in business.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reunions have grown like crazy. I don't want to say
they've crowded out conferences, but they have filled in more
vacancies than we ever thought they might.''
</P>
<P>
   The two centers have some distinct differences. Snow Mountain,
which can accommodate about 2,000 people, is situated on 5,100
acres about 12 miles from the town of Winter Park. Estes Park
Center can house about 4,000 people and is situated on 860 acres
just a short walk from the town of Estes Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people like going into town, they'll have more access at
Estes Park,'' Henderek said. ``We've had family groups go to both
places. Some love Snow Mountain Ranch, some like Estes Park. It's
an emotional thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Snow Mountain has an extensive network of trails for hiking,
biking and cross-country skiing.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can be biking and not see a car at all,'' Henderek said.
The Estes Park Center has much more ``hustle and bustle,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Snow Mountain resort is on the west side of the
Continental Divide, within easy reach of major downhill ski
resorts. The Estes Park Center is on the east side of the divide,
much farther from Alpine skiing opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Both centers, however, are structured in a way that encourages
family togetherness. Take the room furnishings, for example: You
could probably count on two hands the number of televisions at both
centers combined. It's partly a response to poor reception and
partly aimed at fostering family togetherness.
</P>
<P>
   ``The YMCA philosophy is to encourage family interaction, so the
rooms have no TV or radio,'' said Holly Dugan, assistant conference
director at Snow Mountain Ranch. ``Some people are surprised by
that.''
</P>
<P>
   A few televisions and videocassette recorders are available for
rent by those experiencing withdrawal symptoms, however.
</P>
<P>
   And the sleeping arrangements are cozy, to say the least. Rooms
with bunk beds sleeping six or even eight are not at all uncommon.
That keeps the price down, Dugan said. At the same time, ``it
really tests them to see if they can get along.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Estes Park's most popular accommodations is a 9-year-old,
16-bedroom manse known as the Pattie Hyde Barclay Reunion Lodge. It
has its own hostess on the grounds, sleeps 72 people and has four
long dining tables to accommodate the maximum crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Family groups staying anywhere on the grounds may make use of
picnic shelters, fire pits and large barbecue grills. And the Y
staffs are willing to organize all manner of family activities for
those who don't wish to bother with the details.
</P>
<P>
   If a family wants to have a campfire, for example, a staff
member ``will get the fire going, bring the marshmallows and bring
songs,'' Henderek said. They'll organize relay games or educational
sessions on outdoor survival or Native American heritage.
</P>
<P>
   But there's no pressure on guests to take part. They may take in
all of it or none of it. They can spend their entire visit just
watching _ the mountains, the slam dunks on the volleyball court
and the adolescents promenading along the little avenue that serves
as a main street.
</P>
<P>
   But they won't be watching from a rocking chair.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-99 1119EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
