<DOCNO> NYT19990830.0150 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 11:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4250 &Cx1f; kan-z
r e BC-CLASSICAL-REVIEW-KANS     08-30 1509
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLASSICAL-REVIEW-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLASSICAL WAYS TO SPEND THE LAZY, HAZY DAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT CANTRELL  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star   Summertime, when in most cities the
concert schedule slows to a crawl, is a good time for settling into
an easy chair, enjoying the air conditioning and catching up on
recordings. Here's a rundown of recent CDs of note, including
several outstanding reissues.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Orchestral
</P>
<P>
   - Beethoven: Symphony No. 9. Ruth Ziesak, soprano; Birgit
Remmert, alto; Steve Davislim, tenor; Detlef Roth, bass; Swiss
Chamber Choir, Zurich Tonhalle Orchestra, conducted by David Zinman
(Arte Nova, distributed by BMG).
</P>
<P>
   If I could have only one recorded cycle of Beethoven symphonies,
it would be John Eliot Gardiner's ear-opening period-instruments
survey (on DG Archiv). But those who can't give up the plushness of
the modern orchestra now have an excellent alternative from David
Zinman and his Swiss charges. In the Ninth Symphony Zinman tracks
Beethoven's oft-ignored metronome markings pretty closely _ except
in the middle of the scherzo and the finale's tenor solo, where
scholars largely agree that the composer's nephew Karl wrote down
the wrong note values.
</P>
<P>
   The results fairly crackle with excitement, and even the
``slow'' movement really moves. The soloists, although hardly
big-name, are as fine as you'll find anywhere, and the chorus is
superb. Sonics could be a little more transparent, but at Arte
Nova's superb budget price who could complain?
</P>
<P>
   - Gershwin: Rhapsody in Blue; Concerto in F; An American in
Paris; Variations on ``I Got Rhythm.'' Earl Wild, piano; Boston
Pops Orchestra, conducted by Arthur Fiedler (RCA Victor Red Seal).
</P>
<P>
   Not even record companies are immune to the current rage for
'50s design _ including the cover art that RCA is recycling on
current CD repackagings of its early stereo recordings. The pretty
little woman on this Earl Wild//Boston Pops Gershwin release has
plenty of reason to smile: These are ebullient and suave
performances not to be outdone anywhere. Newly remastered, the
40-year-old recordings _ big, bright and spacious _ sound better
than plenty of brand-new ones.
</P>
<P>
   - Mahler: Symphony No. 4. Amanda Roocroft, soprano; City of
Birmingham Symphony Orchestra, conducted by Sir Simon Rattle (EMI
Classics).
</P>
<P>
   For years I wondered what all the fuss was about Simon _ now Sir
Simon _ Rattle; his recorded performances kept sounding turgid and
overindulgent. But his recent Mahler Ninth Symphony, with the
Vienna Philharmonic (also on EMI), suggests a new depth and
subtlety, and here he lays quite a sensitive hand on the vernal
Fourth. One might have wished a soprano soloist more girlish than
Amanda Roocroft, but the Birmingham orchestra plays with a finesse
I've not heard before. (Too bad the strings and sleigh bells don't
coordinate their ritardando at the beginning.) And, working in
Birmingham's acoustically resplendent Symphony Hall, the EMI
engineers offer state-of-the-art transparency and atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   - Mahler: Symphony No. 5. New Philharmonia Orchestra, conducted
by Sir John Barbirolli (EMI Classics).
</P>
<P>
   Recorded in 1969, only a year before Barbirolli's death, this is
a justifiably legendary performance. One may quibble about the
slowish second-movement tempo, but Barbirolli persuasively uses
force rather than speed to realize Mahler's ``with greatest
vehemence'' direction. By contrast, surprisingly, his Adagietto is
one of the fastest on record _ and one of the closest to timings of
Mahler's own performances.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout, this is intensely personal music-making of
life-and-death commitment. Sonics are superb, too _ a tribute to a
golden age of EMI engineering but also to the best present-day
remastering technology.
</P>
<P>
   - Ravel: Piano Concerto in G major; Concerto for the Left Hand;
Gaspard de la nuit. Samson Francois, piano; Paris Conservatoire
Orchestra, conducted by Andre Cluytens (EMI Classics).
</P>
<P>
   Wasted by high living, the French pianist Samson Francois was
only 46 when he was felled by a heart attack in 1970. Even in his
heyday he could be maddeningly uneven as a performer. But listen to
these Ravel performances _ the concertos from 1959, ``Gaspard de la
nuit'' from 1967 _ and you'll know why Samson's countrymen were
willing to forgive his ``off'' days.
</P>
<P>
   Not even Martha Argerich so grippingly captures the demonic side
of these scores, and Cluytens and the Paris Conservatoire Orchestra
occasionally struggle to keep up. Yet Francois brings a
breathtaking vulnerability to the G major Concerto's slow movement.
Apart from a bit of brassiness in the concertos, the recordings
sound fine.
</P>
<P>
   - Stravinsky: Orpheus; Danses concertantes. Orpheus Chamber
Orchestra (Deutsche Grammophon).
</P>
<P>
   Stravinsky was at pains to emphasize the objectivity of his
music, particularly in his neoclassical period. But to hear these
incisive yet suave performances of two of the composer's
masterpieces in the idiom is to realize that Stravinsky couldn't
turn off the charm even when he pretended to. This is music of
worldly elegance _ and humanity, too _ and the conductorless
Orpheus Chamber Orchestra has its measure. And DG's sonics are
almost startlingly lifelike.
</P>
<P>
   Chamber music
</P>
<P>
   - Prokofiev: String Quartets Nos. 1 and 2. Nadarejshvili: String
Quartet No. 1. St. Petersburg String Quartet (Delos).
</P>
<P>
   The most electrifying performances at the recent Strings of the
Future string quartet festival in Ottawa, Canada, came from this
Russian foursome. Their intensity and razor-edged acuity fairly
leap from the loudspeakers on this new CD, too: There can't be
finer performances anywhere of Prokofiev's irresistible quartets.
The 1985 Quartet No. 1 by the Georgian composer Zurab Nadarejsvili
is an important addition to the repertory, mingling out-of-body
hypnosis a la Arvo Paert with stylized folk dances (complete with
percussive thumpings and slappings). It, too, is compellingly
played, and Delos supplies typically vivid reproduction.
</P>
<P>
   - Reger: Violin Sonatas Nos. 1 and 5. Ulf Wallin, violin; Roland
Poentinen, piano (CPO, distributed by Naxos).
</P>
<P>
   Organists sometimes trot out Max Reger's fist-busting hymn
fantasias, but otherwise the German composer _ of the remarkable
generation including Scriabin, Ravel and Vaughan Williams _ has
been largely relegated to footnote status. Reger composed some
superb orchestral tone poems, though, and these violin sonatas are
worthy successors to Brahms'.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, their nobility and their subtle rhythmic and harmonic
elusiveness audibly pick up where Brahms left off; the
throbbing-piano opening of the Fifth Sonata, in F sharp minor, is a
striking echo of the older composer's D minor Sonata. These skilled
and ardent performances, superbly recorded, should win Reger new
friends.
</P>
<P>
   Keyboard
</P>
<P>
   - Bach: Goldberg Variations. Christine Schornsheim, harpsichord
(Capriccio, two discs).
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the ``Goldbergs'' were conceived for harpsichord, but,
alas, most modern harpsichord recordings treat the work with the
earnestness you'd expect from your dental technician. Here, though,
the German harpsichordist Christine Schornsheim captures the
dancing rhythms and sheer elegance that otherwise you'll find only
on Andras Schiff's piano recording _ plus all the repeats. Brava!
</P>
<P>
   - Great Pianists of the 20th Century: Ignaz Friedman. Music by
Beethoven, Chopin, Mendelssohn, others (Philips, two discs).
</P>
<P>
   This is one of the gems of Philips' 100-volume survey of
20th-century pianists. Trained in his native Poland, and in Vienna
under the formidable Theodor Leschetizky, Friedman was one of the
last of the larger-than-life interpretive personalities that
fortunately flourished into the early decades of recorded sound.
(He lived from 1882 to 1948.)
</P>
<P>
   Sheer impetuousness gets the better of a couple of the Chopin
etudes, and even the ``Berceuse'' (a lullaby, after all) is too
hurried. But in general these are compellingly personable, often
freewheeling interpretations to be placed alongside those of Cortot
and Benno Moiseiwitsch. And having danced mazurkas as a lad,
Friedman has a wonderfully idiomatic _ and quite daring _ way with
teasing the rhythms of Chopin's essays. Not even 60- and
70-year-old recordings can detract from music-making like this.
</P>
<P>
   - Byron Janis: True Romantic. Music by Chopin and Liszt. Byron
Janis, piano (EMI Classics).
</P>
<P>
   Just when one's prepared to declare the art of Chopin-playing
all but dead _ with the exception of Ivan Moravec _ here comes the
American pianist Byron Janis with exquisite performances of a
potpourri of both Chopin and Liszt. Janis' recent return to the
recording studio, after a period of health problems, is one of the
happiest developments on the piano scene in a long time. And if the
previous issue (``Byron Janis Plays Chopin,'' also EMI) favored
less challenging pieces, this one suggests that the once-renowned
Janis' virtuosity isn't just a memory. And we have veteran engineer
Max Wilcox to thank for utterly natural sound.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-99 1121EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
