<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 11:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4298 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-BREWER-PROFILE-HNS &LR;      08-30 1515
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BREWER-PROFILE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUIET SUSPECT IN BRYAN FOR SECOND DRAGGING DEATH TRIAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PATTY REINERT 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRYAN, Texas _ High school held no interest for Lawrence Russell
Brewer, so he didn't bother showing up for his senior year.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the quiet, rather unremarkable son of fundamentalist
Christians gained fame in the small East Texas town of Klondike by
becoming a thief. Half-heartedly targeting even his own family, he
lifted a few car parts here, some stereo speakers there.
</P>
<P>
   But when he landed in prison for burglary at age 19, and later
returned for cocaine possession and parole violations, he seemed to
embrace inmate life. Tattooing his arms with racist symbols, he
joined a fringe gang affiliated with the Ku Klux Klan and
proclaimed himself a ``peckerwood,'' a white prisoner willing to
fight to avoid being robbed or raped.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Brewer's friends insist that whole thing was only prison
posturing _ doing what he had to do to survive in a violent
environment. The real Russell Brewer, they say, is a loving man who
married a Hispanic woman and became a father, who later entertained
his girlfriend's children by making festive meals, and who showed
up for a hearing last spring wearing a smile and flashing a message
hastily scrawled on a manila envelope, wishing a Happy Mother's Day
to moms everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   But as jury selection begins in Brewer's capital murder trial in
Bryan this week, prosecutors plan to prove that on June 7 last
year, Russell Brewer accompanied two other white men to a clearing
in the woods outside Jasper. There, they say, he smoked a cigarette
and drank a Bud Light before stripping a black man, chaining him to
a pickup and dragging him three miles to his death.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, neighbors on their way to church discovered
the decapitated body of James Byrd Jr., 49, in the middle of Huff
Creek Road, just outside the gates to a black cemetery. His head,
right shoulder and arm lay in a ditch a mile away.
</P>
<P>
   The hideous crime shocked the town of 8,000 _ and the nation _
into a new dialogue on race relations.
</P>
<P>
   The Ku Klux Klan marched on Jasper and black militant leaders
carried shotguns through the streets, offering to arm the
community's black residents. Local leaders responded with prayer
services and town meetings to address their own prejudices, and
Byrd's relatives urged their neighbors to remain calm.
</P>
<P>
   Last February, a Jasper jury of 11 whites and one black
convicted Brewer's prison buddy and fellow white supremacist John
William ``Bill'' King, 24, and sentenced him to death. Another
defendant, 24-year-old Shawn Berry of Jasper, sits in the Jasper
County Jail awaiting trial in late October.
</P>
<P>
   This week, though, it's Brewer's turn. If convicted, the
32-year-old will face either life in prison or death by injection.
</P>
<P>
   Although King was tried in his hometown, Brewer's lawyers sought
to move his trial out of Jasper, saying local jurors would
improperly try to redeem their town's good name by securing a
conviction without fully considering the evidence.
</P>
<P>
   State District Judge Monte Lawlis at first ruled against a
change, but later relented, when prosecutors asked that the trial
be moved because they feared handing the suspect a reason for
appeal. The trial will be held at the Brazos County Courthouse in
Bryan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd prefer to be right here at home sleeping in my own bed and
working out of my own office, talking to Jasper jurors,'' Jasper
County District Attorney Guy James Gray said recently, ``but I
think it was the smart thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, authorities in Bryan prepared for the onslaught of
media and spectators, installing metal detectors and security
cameras at the courthouse, processing credentials for 150
journalists from more than 30 news organizations and converting a
former barbecue restaurant into a makeshift press room
</P>
<P>
   ``We're bracing ourselves, because it just so happens that the
trial falls when all the Aggies come back to school,'' said Joe
Brown, public information officer for the city that is next door to
College Station, home of Texas A&AMP;M University. ``There's always a
lot of chaos whenever the Aggies are in town, and the hotels are
scarce because of home football games.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with the added tension, though, Brown says he's proud of
Brazos County for stepping forward to help Jasper officials when
more than two dozen other counties shunned the racially charged
trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't something we asked for,'' he said, ``but sometimes
you have to do what's right instead of what's easiest. We're ready
to get this on the ground and get it over with.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see it as a responsibility to our fellow Texans,'' he
added. ``This is something that we owe them because they would do
it for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Jury selection, which begins Tuesday, is expected to last about
two weeks, with lawyers questioning 12 prospective jurors per day
and testimony tentatively scheduled to start Sept. 15.
</P>
<P>
   Gray said he doesn't anticipate any problem seating a jury in
Brazos County, even though the murder made headlines around the
world and the local Bryan Eagle carried daily stories during the
trial of Bill King.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Jasper, about 50 percent of the jurors were qualified, and
I'm hopeful that in Bryan we'll get a higher percentage,'' Gray
said. ``People there know generally that there was a dragging case
out of Jasper, but they don't know a lot of the details.''
</P>
<P>
   Gray declined to say much about his trial strategy, and Brewer's
court-appointed attorney, Doug Barlow of Beaumont, did not return
phone calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   But during King's trial last winter, Jasper County jurors heard
testimony so gruesome it drove the victim's family and the
defendant's father from the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it was King's own writings that convicted him, as
prosecutors produced racist letters he'd penned from prison to
girls in Jasper and letters to the media that placed him in the
pickup the night of the murder.
</P>
<P>
   Also entered into evidence were a recruiting letter,
``constitution'' and bylaws for King's own personal hate group, a
chapter of the Confederate Knights of America, which he intended to
call Texas Rebel Soldiers. He wanted to launch the group in Jasper
on July 4, 1998, and even outlined plans to kidnap a black person,
take him to the woods and kill him.
</P>
<P>
   He also wrote a ``kite,'' or jailhouse note, which he passed to
Brewer, who was being held in a separate cell.
</P>
<P>
   The note, delivered by an inmate trusty who first turned it over
to jailers for photocopying, discussed bloodstained clothing at
King's apartment and explained that he and Brewer could escape the
death sentence if prosecutors failed to prove the kidnapping
charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seriously though, bro, reguardless (sic) of the outcome of
this, we have made history and shall die proudly remembered if need
be,'' King wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``It killed us,'' King's court-appointed attorney, C. Haden
``Sonny'' Cribbs Jr., later said of the jailhouse writings and the
kite _ the only piece of evidence jurors asked to see before
announcing their guilty verdict.
</P>
<P>
   Gray said jurors in Brewer's trial will see four or five kites
that Brewer passed to King. The prosecutor declined to reveal their
contents, except to say that they refer to Brewer's thoughts and
feelings after the murder, but apparently offer no hint of his
alleged role in planning Byrd's murder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brewer wrote some, but he was not as prolific a writer as
King,'' Gray said. ``This trial will have a little more prison gang
life flavor than the first case because we need to use other
evidence to establish his motive and what he was thinking before
the murder.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, prosecutors have subpoenaed more than 30 witnesses,
including several prisoners expected to testify about Brewer's gang
activities and racist beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors previously have theorized that King and Brewer, who
met while both were inmates at the Beto I prison unit in Tennessee
Colony, may have planned Byrd's murder as a ``blood-in'' ceremony
that would guarantee them membership in a free world hate group. An
alternative theory suggests that the murder was an initiation rite
for the Texas Rebel Soldiers' first recruit: King's high school
friend and fellow defendant, Shawn Berry.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever Brewer's alleged motive or role in Byrd's death,
prosecutors will likely have little trouble placing him at the
crime scene. Physical evidence and testimony during King's trial
put Brewer in Berry's pickup the night that three white men were
seen picking up an intoxicated Byrd, who was walking down Martin
Luther King Boulevard on his way home from a party.
</P>
<P>
   A DNA expert from the FBI also testified that Brewer's genetic
blueprint showed up on a cigarette butt and a beer bottle found in
the woods where Byrd was chained to the pickup.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer's tennis shoe _ recovered from King's apartment, where
the men were staying the weekend of the killing _ was stained with
Byrd's blood.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
