<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 11:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4303 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-BOOK-STORM-REVIEW-HNS     08-30 1464
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-STORM-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BIG ONE: STORY OF 1900 GALVESTON STORM ALSO TALE OF ERRING
METEOROLOGIST 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (``Isaac's Storm''; by Erik Larson; Crown, $25.) 
 
By BOB TUTT 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the dawning of the 20th century neared, Isaac Cline, chief of
the U.S. Weather Bureau station at Galveston, confidently forecast
no dangerous hurricane would ever ravage that thriving Texas port
city.
</P>
<P>
   Wicked hurricanes in 1875 and 1886 had dealt ultimately fatal
blows to the once up-and-coming town of Indianola on Matagorda Bay
120 miles farther down the Texas coast, but Cline contended natural
features would protect Galveston.
</P>
<P>
   If any regretted that a proposed sea wall to protect Galveston
hadn't materialized, he may well have put their minds at ease. And
civic leaders could go on dreaming that their city might someday
rank with Baltimore, New Orleans and San Francisco and far surpass
the rival town of Houston 50 miles inland.
</P>
<P>
   But as Erik Larson recounts in ``Isaac's Storm,'' the monster
hurricane that struck without warning in 1900 and devastated
Galveston also shredded Cline's analysis. So there is an element of
irony in the book's title.
</P>
<P>
   In an article Cline wrote for the Galveston News in 1891, he
theorized that ``the shallow slope of the seabed off Galveston
would wear down incoming seas before they struck the city.''
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, he contended that low-lying mainland areas north
of Galveston Bay would serve as basins to capture whatever flood
waters a storm did manage to drive ashore.
</P>
<P>
   Larson notes how the national office of the Weather Bureau
quickly distanced itself from Cline's prognosis in its October 1900
Monthly Weather Review. One of its top meteorologists wrote that,
in fact, Galveston's natural setting rendered it ``in the presence
of severe storms, peculiarly subject to inundation.'' That's a
classic understatement.
</P>
<P>
   And in the wake of this nation's deadliest natural disaster,
claiming more than 8,000 lives, Galveston proceeded not only to
construct a sea wall but also to elevate the whole city.
</P>
<P>
   Larson isn't the first writer to vividly dramatize the storm's
mounting fury and movingly bring to life many of the resulting
human dramas.
</P>
<P>
   For example, John Edward Weems' ``A Weekend in September,''
first published in 1957 and reprinted in 1980, also splendidly
accomplished that. What distinguishes Larson's work is his delving
into Cline's character as well as his exposing the hubris and
shenanigans of the Weather Bureau's top brass.
</P>
<P>
   Cline, 38 at the time of the storm, clearly was highly
intelligent, possessing doctorates in both meteorology and
medicine. He prided himself on being a conscientious scientist
despite a possible lapse into civic boosterism when he proclaimed
Galveston immune to serious hurricane damage.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, he was a loving husband and father, a Sunday
school teacher, a strait-laced man who paid his debts in cash, an
avid hunter. And like all meteorologists, Larson observes, he was a
lover of electrical storms. Cline once confided, with a touch of
humor, that he was drawn to the study of weather because he wanted
``some field where I could tell big stories and tell the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Upon first meeting Isaac,'' Larson writes, ``men found him to
be modest and self-effacing, but those who came to know him well
saw a harshness and confidence that verged on hubris.''
</P>
<P>
   Larson divines evidence of ``a persistent, low-grade rivalry''
between Cline and his brother Joseph Cline, who was nine years
younger and also a meteorologist on his staff. It seems the
brothers frequently differed in their interpretations of weather
phenomena; after the hurricane they became totally estranged.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, meteorology then was far from the science it is now.
More accurate understanding of the workings of weather lay many
years in the future, as did the technology to track hurricanes such
as the recent Bret literally hour by hour.
</P>
<P>
   Larson adds a dimension to the Galveston storm's story by
describing how toward the end of the 19th century a dispute over
weather predictions sprouted between American and Cuban weather
forecasters.
</P>
<P>
   So it came as no surprise that American meteorologists based in
Cuba and in the States would scoff when Cuban weathermen in August
1900 predicted that a weather system heading north across their
newly independent island nation gave indications of growing into a
hurricane and that it was likely to take a westward turn.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans were sure it would be no more than a tropical
storm. They forecast it would take a turn to the east, cross over
Florida, then enter the Atlantic without significant consequences.
They stuck to that prediction as the storm did just what the Cubans
forecast. Some ships encountered this burgeoning piece of weather,
but in those pre-radio days there was no way they could send a
warning.
</P>
<P>
   The storm grew into a powerful hurricane. With a gigantic
low-pressure zone in North America drawing it like a magnet, it
traveled unobstructed over open waters for 800 miles. It slammed
into Galveston head-on Saturday, Sept. 8, 1900. It appears to have
packed winds that at their worst may have ranged from 150 to 200
mph.
</P>
<P>
   It was as if the storm ``had set a course for Galveston soon
after leaving Cuba,'' Larson writes, and ``Galveston became
Atlantis.''
</P>
<P>
   On the morning of the day the storm struck, Cline wrote,
mounting ``storm swells'' signaled him ``as though it was a written
message that great danger was approaching.''
</P>
<P>
   He claimed he drove his horse-drawn cart up and down the
beachfront warning Galveston residents and visitors to seek shelter
on the mainland. He estimated he saved ``some 6,000 lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Larson seeks to set the record straight on this. He says that in
reviewing hundreds of reminiscences of the storm in archives of
Galveston's Rosenberg Library, he found no mention of Cline's
giving such a warning. Additionally, he says, means of
transportation to safety for so many people weren't available.
</P>
<P>
   Later that terrible day about 45 people joined Cline; his wife,
Cora; their three young daughters; and Cline's brother in taking
refuge in the Clines' home. Only 18 of those assembled were thought
to have survived the house's destruction and the storm's later
perils. Cora Cline, pregnant and ill in bed, was among those lost.
</P>
<P>
   Larson explains how, despite personal grief, Cline strove to
write a dispassionate, scientific report on the hurricane for his
agency's national headquarters. But for the first time in his
career, he wrote in the first person. He advised Willis Moore, the
bureau's director, to omit personal references he might think
inappropriate. Moore released Cline's report as written, including
a description of Cline's wife's death.
</P>
<P>
   Larson notes how the Houston Post newspaper castigated the
Weather Bureau for providing no warning of the storm's approach.
``With the weather bureau saying that Saturday would be `fair,
fresh, possibly brisk, northerly winds on the coast' of East
Texas,'' the paper asked rhetorically, ``who would have looked for
the most destructive hurricane of modern times on the coast on that
date?''
</P>
<P>
   Undaunted by this criticism, Moore sent out a release falsely
stating his agency had warned Galveston the storm was coming.
Larson found that some papers, not doubting the official's word,
responded by praising the weather service for a job well done.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isaac's Storm'' flows admirably except for some historical
detours early in the book. These occur first when Larson, in
considerable detail, fills readers in on how power struggles dogged
Christopher Columbus during New World explorations. Larson should
have limited his narrative to weather events that shaped things for
the great explorer but couldn't resist including such details as
how at one point a rival had Columbus locked in chains.
</P>
<P>
   Then Larson launches into a survey of pioneering weather-related
scientific study. It ranges over Galileo's experiment that
determined air had weight; research by Evangelista Torricelli and
Robert Boyle that led to the barometer's development; William
Dampier's descriptions of ``lurid atmospheric colors'' seen before
storms; and Daniel Defoe's chronicles of the destructive storm that
battered the British Isles in 1703.
</P>
<P>
   This was probably intended to inform readers on the then still
limited meteorological knowledge available to Isaac Cline, but it
comes across as a pedantic detour.
</P>
<P>
   From there on Larson plunges unstintingly into the story of a
monumental tragedy, bringing Cline to life and reminding us of the
complex factors underlying our fates, from bureaucratic bungling to
pure chance.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
