u e BC-FILM-SPELLING-PROFILE     08-30 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-SPELLING-PROFILE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPELLING RELISHES SHOWING A DIFFERENT SIDE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOEY GUERRA 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Oh my God _ I didn't know you could act!''
</P>
<P>
   According to Tori Spelling, that's the usual reaction from
people who see her touchingly funny, scene-stealing performance in
the movie ``Trick.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Great, thanks. I've been working since I was 5,`` said
Spelling recently. She was on her way home after a day of shooting
in Los Angeles for the 10th season of ``Beverly Hills, 90210.``
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I've been doing good acting on (90210) for 10 years,
but they dismiss that because it's my father's (TV guru Aaron
Spelling) show,'' she said. ``People's perception is really weird.
No one wants to see you get ahead, but all of a sudden you do one
thing that's completely different and has nothing to do with your
dad, and all of a sudden they're like, `Oh wow, now she's good.'
I've had to deal with it my whole life.''
</P>
<P>
   Katherine, Spelling's character in ``Trick,'' shows up at
precisely the wrong times throughout the film. It's a charming
romantic fluff about two guys, Gabriel and Mark, whose plans for a
one-night stand in New York City are constantly thwarted by
annoying interruptions. One moment Katherine is printing out 150
resumes in best friend Gabriel's (Christian Campbell, Neve's
brother) apartment, the next she's yakking it up at a late-night
diner where Gabriel finally thinks he can be alone with go-go
dancer Mark (John Paul Pitoc).
</P>
<P>
   It's in these scenes that Spelling deftly balances the
caricature aspects of aspiring actress Katherine with her
deep-rooted insecurities, sometimes without even saying a word.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm most proud of this part, I really am. I made that
character my own,'' Spelling said. ``That's the personality I chose
to give her. I also wanted to make sure that I made her vulnerable
so that people wouldn't be just plain annoyed by the character. I
don't know. With my big eyes and everything, I always look
vulnerable.''
</P>
<P>
   Those characteristics have also helped her craft a sympathetic
portrait of rich girl Donna Martin for the past decade on
``90210.'' Spelling has become an integral part of the show's
success, despite harsh criticism in the beginning because her
father was the show's creator.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been dealing with it for so long that I kind of just got
hardened to it,'' Spelling said. ``At first it hurt, and it was
hard to deal with. Then I kind of got the attitude like, `I'm gonna
just try really hard and do really great work, and then they won't
be able to say it anymore.' Now I'm over it. I don't care what
people say.''
</P>
<P>
   Spelling saw ``Trick`` as another opportunity to show people
what she can do. Besides being charmed by the romantic storyline,
the actress was attracted to the role of Katherine because of its
comedic possibilities, skills she doesn't get to showcase on
``90210`` or in TV movies like ``Co-ed Call Girl`` and ``A Friend
to Die For.'' Spelling auditioned for director Jim Fall, who was
already interested in her during initial talks, and won the part.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to choose characters that are completely different from
what people would think of me as doing or what I've done in the
past to challenge myself,'' Spelling said. ``We all have that
Broadway star inside of us that's bursting to get out, so I related
to that part. I've always wanted to be that character _ that
vibrant, outgoing character that would do anything at any time. It
was fun ... to be crazy and loud.''
</P>
<P>
   Singing and dancing were required of Spelling who, as Katherine,
accompanies Gabriel to a musical writing workshop early in the
film. It was Katherine's time to shine, but for Spelling, it was a
new (and somewhat exhausting) experience. She took two weeks of
singing lessons to prepare for her debut vocal performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always thought I'd been tone deaf, so I was freaking out
(when I got the part). When I got to New York, they're like, `Oh
and by the way, you're gonna have to tap now.' I learned this whole
choreographed routine in a week. I was kinda nervous,'' Spelling
admitted. ``The room of people was sitting there watching me. We
were in this little classroom building that had no air
conditioning, and I had to do it, like, 20 times. I was sweating.
Ugh. My makeup was pouring off.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with 1997's ``The House of Yes,'' Spelling has
concentrated her big-screen career on supporting roles in edgy,
independent films. (Her parody of herself in ``Scream 2`` doesn't
really count.) While it's made for a surprisingly interesting
addition to her resume, Spelling admits that it wasn't necessarily
intentional.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably the fact that I didn't get a big Hollywood
movie,'' she said with a laugh. ``But I haven't minded it because I
think more of the interesting roles and scripts are independents
anyway. Big-budget features usually have to follow a certain
formula because they're banking on it. For women, it's really hard
to find those interesting roles that are really different, and I
didn't wanna be, like, the token girlfriend.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the latest developments on ``Beverly Hills, 90210,''
Spelling was vague, only offering that this year, like always, will
bring lots of ``love transitions.'' She did admit, though, that
this will likely be the last hurrah for Kelly, David, Donna and the
rest of the gang, which will give Spelling more time for films and
a possible sitcom, where she can showcase her affinity for physical
comedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't even know if the (90210) pilot would get picked up.
It was, at the time, such a new venue _ the teen drama. There
really weren't any others like it. Every year we thought, `Who
knows? It might be the last year,' but it's been going on and on
and on. I'm pretty sure this is the final year.''
</P>
<P>
   Rest assured, however, that this isn't the end for Spelling. If
she keeps up her current pace, she'll be tapping her way into
interesting and varied roles for a while longer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
