<HEADLINE>
ROCKER'S NAME ON LUBBOCK FESTIVAL? THAT'LL BE THE DAY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JIM HENDERSON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lubbock, Texas, will celebrate its most famous son next weekend,
and Buddy Holly will be there in spirit, if not in name.
</P>
<P>
   A music festival that has borne the late singer's name for the
past three years, and sporadically for several previous years, will
still be held, but this year it will be called the Crossroads of
Texas Music Festival.
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago, Holly's widow, Maria Elena Holly of Dallas,
turned down the city's offer of $50,000 and 15 percent of the
profits for the right to use his name.
</P>
<P>
   City officials said she wanted more money, but Holly blamed them
for the collapse of negotiations. She did not return phone calls
this week, but in June she told The Associated Press, ``I am tired
of being used as a scapegoat. I am tired of city officials who
don't know how to put a festival together saying bad things about
me.''
</P>
<P>
   She reportedly threatened to sue the city if the festival were
held even under a different name, claiming it would benefit from
proximity to Holly's birthday, Sept. 7.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Holly has given her approval to the Buddy Holly
Center, whose opening next weekend will coincide with the music
festival.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's been very supportive,'' said Connie Gibbons, director of
the Holly Center, a 12,000-square-foot train depot turned cultural
arts center that will house a permanent exhibit of Holly
memorabilia. ``She has given permission to name a building after
him, and she has given us licensing agreements and loaned some
artifacts for the exhibit.''
</P>
<P>
   Holly's band, the Crickets, which includes two of the original
members, will perform with the Lubbock Symphony as part of the
three-day opening of the center.
</P>
<P>
   Holly's blend of country, rock 'n' roll and rhythm and blues
made him a sensation in the 1950s, and songs such as ``Peggy Sue``
and ``That'll Be The Day`` are still considered classics of that
era.
</P>
<P>
   In 1959, he was killed in a plane crash that also took the lives
of rock icons Richie Valens and J.P. ``The Big Bopper'' Richardson.
</P>
<P>
   Since his death, his family has fought to maintain control over
royalties and licensing of his name and likeness. Legal battles
have been waged over a guitar company's marketing of Holly's
silhouette on its instruments and a record company's marketing of
red suede shoes like the ones he wore.
</P>
<P>
   The family prevailed in both disputes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-99 1201EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
