<DOCNO> NYT19990830.0166 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 12:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4309 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l BC-BARLOW-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-30 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARLOW-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SAFER WAY TO USE A CELLULAR PHONE AND DRIVE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JIM BARLOW 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Cellular phone use is growing 40 to 50 percent a year.
By next year, it's estimated there will be 80 million cell phone
users in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   At times, it seems that every one of those people are sharing
the streets and highways with me.
</P>
<P>
   They yak away, driving 20 to 30 miles below the speed limit.
They wander into other lanes as they become engrossed in their
conversations. They are a menace.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, I know that cell phones are great timesavers. They allow
people to keep in touch on the road. In case of an emergency, they
can be lifesavers. I'm glad that my spouse carries a cell phone for
that reason. At times, I've even been guilty of calling her in her
car, although I do try to keep the conversation as brief as
possible.
</P>
<P>
   But they are dangerous. Here's news to all you people using your
cell phones in your car. You're snockered. You are driving just
about as well as someone who has quaffed the legal limit of
alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   That's the conclusion of a Toronto study published in the
prestigious New England Journal of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
MORE ACCIDENT-PRONE WITH PHONES? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The study looked at people who had car accidents and also had
car phones. Then it looked at billing records of those car phones
to see if the persons were talking on the phone at the time of the
collision.
</P>
<P>
   The study had several holes. The authors noted that people who
were talking a lot on car phones might also have been under
emotional stress at the time. So that stress, rather than car phone
use, might have contributed to the accident. However, it also noted
that they had to receive permission from people in the accident to
examine their car phone records. Those worried about legal
liability might have refused access. So, the relationship between
car phone use and accidents might be higher than the study found.
The study also excluded drivers injured in the accident.
</P>
<P>
   There also are plenty of other distractions drivers suffer.
Those can include everything from the children screaming in the
back seat to someone riding with you who insists on holding a
conversation at the worst possible time.
</P>
<P>
   Distraction is, after all, distraction.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the study concluded that those talking on car phones are
four times more likely to have an accident than those not using
them. That's the same rate of people who are driving while mildly
intoxicated, but beyond the legal limit.
</P>
<P>
   So, what about different styles of car phones? Is it safer to
have a hands-free model, rather than holding up the phone with your
hand or raising a shoulder and tilting your head to the side to
hold the phone against your ear?
</P>
<P>
   Hands-free, says the conventional wisdom, is safer. The Toronto
study found no difference in the accident rate. It's the
distraction of carrying on a conversation rather than the way you
do it that causes the mischief.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
DWR or DWC? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   People with hands-free cell phones do make it more difficult to
spot people guilty of DWR _ or driving while raving. Those are the
ones holding animated conversations while alone in the car. These
people should be avoided at all costs.
</P>
<P>
   Although, come to think of it, in view of the Toronto study,
there's no difference between DWR and DWC _ driving while celling.
</P>
<P>
   Three countries, Brazil, Israel and Australia, have banned the
use of telephones while driving. Don't expect similar legislation
in the United States. There are just too many cell phone users and
they tend to be people who not only vote but give money to
politicians.
</P>
<P>
   As yet, the car insurers also aren't willing to address the
problem _ saying there's not enough evidence that having a car
phone means you must pay a higher rate for insurance because of the
increased danger.
</P>
<P>
   There's standard advice on car phone use from safety experts _
which few people follow.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't use it while driving. Park.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you call while driving, program frequently called numbers
so you have to hit one or two buttons instead of 10.
</P>
<P>
   _ In heavy traffic, let a voice messaging service pick up the
call.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't engage in emotional, frustrating or stressful calls
while driving.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you use a portable phone, secure it so you won't be
grabbing at it during sudden stops.
</P>
<P>
   _ When talking on the phone, end the call when driving
conditions deteriorate so you can put all your attention on the
road.
</P>
<P>
   Cell phone users should develop a standard phrase like,
``Whoops, gotta go. Bad traffic.''
</P>
<P>
   And then use it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
To voice comments, send e-mail to jim.barlow(at) chron.com &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
