<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TREASURES-TRASH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PULLING TREASURE FROM THE TRASH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PATRICIA C. JOHNSON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The proverbial van Gogh in the attic and Rembrandt in the cellar
have become more than proverbs as the millennium draws to a close.
More than 200 news stories about lost art rediscovered have been
printed in the past 24 months, snaring attention from Dublin to
Houston, Singapore to New York.
</P>
<P>
   The key words are almost always the same: lost, masterpiece,
attic, anonymous.
</P>
<P>
   These aren't stories about works of art looted from
pre-Columbian archaeological sites or stolen by the Nazis during
World War II. Nor are they about art theft from museums.
</P>
<P>
   They are about discovering that the unidentified thing stashed
irreverently in a corner somewhere is not a piece of junk but a
treasure that makes headlines when its anonymous owner sells it for
a fortune.
</P>
<P>
   Like any other object, artworks get misplaced or mislabeled.
Some are damaged or forgotten. Taste and context change over time,
as does scholarship, all of which can affect the desirability and
market value of an artwork.
</P>
<P>
   Consider these classic examples of treasures recovered:
</P>
<P>
   A painting by the 16th-century Italian master Caravaggio was
found in a Dublin monastery during a remodeling project. In the
mid-1800s, the painting had been mistakenly attributed to Gerrit
von Hothorst, a Dutch follower of the Italian master; at auction in
1921, it failed to reach the minimum bid of $50, and it soon
disappeared from view. For decades it hung in the dining room of
the Society of Jesus, until a restorer for the National Gallery of
Dublin was recently assigned to clean the dark old painting. It was
``The Taking of Christ,'' valued in the tens of millions of
dollars.
</P>
<P>
   In June, the Museum of Fine Arts, Houston, announced the
acquisition of a painting by the 19th-century American naturalist
and artist Martin Johnson Heade, a leading exponent of the Luminist
movement. The painting of two magnolias on gold cloth was valued at
an estimated $1.25 million. An unidentified man had bought it for a
few bucks at a rummage sale and taken it to a dealer in New York,
who then contacted the MFA. Just a month before, another Heade
painting of magnolias, bought for $29 in the late 1980s, had sold
at auction for $882,500.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, a passer-by retrieved a badly damaged painting from a
Manhattan trash bin. It turned out to be a portrait of Andrew
Foster, an influential businessman of the 19th century whose
descendants included Henry Francis du Pont. Its condition was
described as ``deplorable,'' with punctures and flaking paint, but
it was the work of Samuel Lovett Waldo and William Jewett, whose
renowned New York studio specialized in portraiture of the rich and
famous. After restoration, the painting went to the Museum of the
City of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Such headlines _ reinforced by the enormously popular PBS series
``Antiques Roadshow'' _ have people scouring houses, barns and
garages looking for hidden treasure. They grab hold of our
imagination, like the dream of winning the lottery _ but with a
more active, challenging role for the dreamer.
</P>
<P>
   How do you know whether your Aunt Martha's vase is purely
ornamental or a Tiffany worth $100,000? Or whether that smudgy old
portrait could be the work of a 17th-century Dutch master?
</P>
<P>
   Take your find to an expert, say those who know, but do some
legwork first.
</P>
<P>
   ``Find out what it is first,'' said David Lackey of Houston's
David Lackey Antiques. People often don't know the difference
between a reproduction and a painting, for example, or between
glass and porcelain, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Then look for more specific information, Lackey added. Is the
work signed? Is it dated? If it's framed, look at the back for
labels that may tell you where it was bought, framed, maybe even
exhibited.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing can be older than the style (of featured clothing or
architecture, for example), but it can be newer,'' Lackey said. ``A
lot of it is just plain logic. It can't possibly have been painted
in 1885 if there is a Model T in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Other clues include materials such as oil-based paint, which was
not readily available until after 1870, said Houston art dealer
John ``Sandy'' Parkerson.
</P>
<P>
   In porcelain, a stamp on the bottom identifying the country of
origin means it dates from after 1890. In 1891, Lackey explained,
the United States required that all products entering this country
be so identified.
</P>
<P>
   The more you narrow the field, the easier and more fruitful your
research will be. Then you may want an expert to help.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Cavanaugh, Houston representative for the Christie's
international auction house, says her office gets an average of 25
calls a week, of which 10 sound promising and four may actually pan
out.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, ``Antiques Roadshow'' has raised the number of inquiries
and ``the level of curiosity,'' Cavanaugh said, although at the
high end, collectors have always been there.
</P>
<P>
   When people call, she said, she asks for basic information _ a
photograph of the object, details such as a signature or hallmark,
dimensions, condition and so on.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are all sorts of criteria we look for,'' Cavanaugh said.
``There's a form on our Web site you can fill in and send to us in
Houston or New York (www.christies.com/sell/index.html).''
</P>
<P>
   If the object seems to warrant it, a visit by an expert can be
arranged. Frequently, of course, the hoped-for treasure is not
treasure at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``People get tricked,'' Cavanaugh said. ``There are a lot of
photo reproductions and synthetic stones, so we deliver bad news,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People also bring you everything they bought at a garage sale
which they hope is worth more than what they paid for it,''
Parkerson added.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases his response is something like: ``It's very nice,
but it doesn't have a collectible value. It has a decorative
value.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Parkerson still tells the story of a phone call about 20
years ago, when he worked for Sotheby's in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   A couple had inherited a scene of Yellowstone and didn't know
whether it was a print or an original, Parkerson said. It turned
out to be an original _ by American master landscape artist Thomas
Moran. It was a view of a geyser dated 1872, done as part of the
Hayden Survey of a year earlier (named for its leader, Ferdinand V.
Hayden).
</P>
<P>
   ``You're always a bit skeptical,'' Parkerson said, ``but this
turned out to be a watercolor with perfect provenance (history). It
had been sent to this couple's ancestor, a U.S. senator from
Vermont, as a lobbying effort to make Yellowstone a national
park.''
</P>
<P>
   Parkerson recalled that the work sold at auction for $24,000. It
was a fortune to the sellers, who had to be notified by mail
because they had no telephone. Last year, the piece resurfaced and
sold for more than $650,000.
</P>
<P>
   Once in a while, fame and monetary value play no role in happy
endings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds like a plot in a movie: Buy an old house, enter its
attic and stumble across treasure,'' Irene Ng wrote in the Straits
Times of Singapore in March. Greg and Joo Mee Seow had bought a
house in the capital last October. Several months later, while
checking on the condition of the roof, they discovered that the
house had an attic. There they found a cache of some 30 paintings
by Chen Wen Hsi, one of Singapore's pioneer artists of the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   The Seows gave the entire collection to the artist's son.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the millennium, with our global press,
international sales rooms and worldwide Internet access, things as
valuable and well-known as the Caravaggio or as historically
interesting as Foster's portrait can no longer simply disappear.
Can they?
</P>
<P>
   Think again.
</P>
<P>
   Vincent van Gogh's ``Portrait of Dr. Gachet,'' at $82.5 million
the most expensive painting ever sold at auction, has done just
that.
</P>
<P>
   It was bought by Japanese businessman Ryoei Saito in 1990 and
stored in a vault; it has not been seen in public since. When Saito
died in 1996, the painting's whereabouts increased in mystery.
</P>
<P>
   Was it destroyed? (Saito said at one time that he wanted it
cremated with him.) Is it stored in a Tokyo warehouse? Was it sold
to an unidentified private collector in America, as a German
television network reported last month?
</P>
<P>
   If it turns up someday, will people praise and covet it as they
did in 1990? Because there's no such thing as absolute quality, and
market value is subject to changing tastes, how will future
generations perceive the notorious portrait of the faintly amused
physician, painted by an artist on the edge of a mental breakdown?
</P>
<P>
   'Tis indeed the proverbial van Gogh in the attic.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
