<SLUG> BC-BIKE-TRAILS-HOUSTON-ART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOSS OF TRAILS PUTS BUMP IN THE PATH OF HOUSTON CYCLING
ENTHUSIASTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Photo available on NYT database) 
 
By ALLAN TURNER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Deep in the urban heart of Houston _ a place known for
its relentless flatness _ lies a near-wilderness startling in its
verticality. Hills erupt from the trail bed at 70-degree angles;
paths trace the rims of ravines that plunge 30 feet to the bayou
below.
</P>
<P>
   Thrill-seekers who probe its shadowed subtropical recesses give
it names like Cambodia, Laos and Ho Chi Minh _ labels that bespeak
impenetrable jungles fraught with danger.
</P>
<P>
   Picnickers, golfers, bird-watchers and others of the sedate set,
though, know it as Memorial Park, an unthreatening 1,500-acre haven
for weary city-dwellers.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the park and its proper use are at the center of a shrill
debate between thousands of youthful off-road mountain bikers and
the park's traditional defenders, the Memorial Park Advisory Board.
</P>
<P>
   Board members, whose recommendations led the city this summer to
close about six of 12 miles of mountain bike trails, claim the
low-slung bicycles with their studded tires accelerate devastating
erosion along Buffalo Bayou. Bikers, they say, additionally have
vandalized the park by ripping down ``trail closed'' signs hours
after they were posted.
</P>
<P>
   Bikers counter that board members are affluent snobs whose
efforts to close the Memorial Park trails are based on class bias.
``They never did want us back in their park,'' said one.
</P>
<P>
   Caught in the middle, parks director Oliver B. Spellman Jr. has
called a series of meetings to obtain additional comment on the
closings. Ultimately, he hopes, better mountain bike trails can be
established inside and outside Memorial Park.
</P>
<P>
   Although all decisions in the matter ultimately are his, the
opinion of the park advisory board traditionally has carried great
weight. Other park-support groups have called upon the city to
stand by its original decision.
</P>
<P>
   Among mountain bikers _ as many as 2,000 Houston off-road
cyclists use the park _ the charms of Memorial are legendary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in Aspen, Colo.,'' said local bicyclist Phillip Mount,
30, ``and a guy was saying, `You've got a killer trail system down
in Houston.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a gem,'' added biker Dave Calvo, 36, who has ridden
the trails since 1994. ``I'd venture to say that most metropolitan
areas just don't have anything like it.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston business owner and biker Dave Parker, 35, said, ``The
trails are one of the few things that keep me from moving to
another part of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Lured by the trails' ``technicals'' _ challenging twists, hills
and tree roots _ a number of Houston riders who have gone on to
national and international celebrity have relied on Memorial for
training. In coming weeks, an Italian road bike team will arrive to
begin off-road training in the park.
</P>
<P>
   Without access to Memorial, bikers say, they must drive at least
100 miles to find challenging trails.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've taken out some of the best trails,'' Calvo said of the
closures. ``I don't know if it was by design or not, but the city
has taken the fun out of ridership.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the trails now closed is a nerve-sapping segment dubbed
``The Widow Maker.''
</P>
<P>
   Off-road bikers first began using the park's back trails about a
decade ago, and their presence in an area previously used largely
by hikers and equestrians generated almost instant concern.
</P>
<P>
   At least one rider has met his death on the back-park trails,
but most official concern is directed to injury to the environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``They cut their own trails in many cases, and the results have
not been good for the park,'' said Glenda Barrett, a member of the
Memorial advisory board and executive director of Park People, a
nonprofit group supporting Houston parks. ``There has been a great
deal of ecological damage.''
</P>
<P>
   Barrett is among those calling on the city to resist biker
efforts to get trails reopened.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city of Houston Parks and Recreation Department is
besieged by these mountain bikers,'' she wrote Mayor Lee Brown.
``One group of citizens must not be permitted to abuse a public
park, destroying its fragile ecosystem for other citizens and for
generations to come.''
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-'90s, the advisory board _ an oversight body
established by philanthropist Ima Hogg after her family sold the
city the property in the mid-1920s _ began seeking ways to limit
the damage.
</P>
<P>
   Although riding bicycles on park trails is illegal by city
ordinance, board chairwoman Claire Caudill said her group began
negotiating with the Houston Area Mountain Bicycle Riding
Association, or HAMBRA, then the only such group in the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time, we were very happy to get a compromise,'' said
Larry Pruitt, a HAMBRA board member who was active in the
discussions. ``There was a good deal of bouncing back and forth,
and it finally came up with what we have today. We got about 60
percent of the trails and agreed to close about 40 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   The agreement also provided for user fees of up to $50 a year.
</P>
<P>
   The deal was signed in December 1996, but almost two years
elapsed before the parks department approached City Council for
$60,000 to improve or close trails.
</P>
<P>
   When city crews began erecting barricades and blocking trails
with brush earlier this summer, many riders were shocked. That
surprise gave birth to a new, strident biker group called the
Memorial Park Mountain Biking Association.
</P>
<P>
   While group leadership has been reluctant to make public
comments on the controversy, individual members have expressed
dismay with the older HAMBRA group's negotiated agreement. ``No one
has ever sanctioned HAMBRA as the negotiating committee,'' one
biker complained.
</P>
<P>
   It was the new group's agitation that led parks director
Spellman to reopen the issue for discussion.
</P>
<P>
   Christina Case, spokeswoman for the new mountain biking group,
charged that the city ``closed three-fourths of the biking/hiking
trails to mountain bikes and runners by installing barricades and
cutting live trees down to block the trails.''
</P>
<P>
   Other biking association members said they had seen live trees
bent across the trails and tied to block passage. ``It's ironic,''
said one, ``that they trashed the trails in order to close them.''
</P>
<P>
   Some bikers have criticized the city for failing to undertake a
scientific examination of the erosion problem, and they have
suggested that erosion is purely a natural result of the bayou's
periodic flooding.
</P>
<P>
   ``A majority of the guys, they won't admit it,'' said biker
Calvo, ``but they're really tree huggers. If there's a reasonable
environmental study that says, `Sure enough, bikers are trashing
trails and causing damage,' I think 75 (percent) to 95 percent
would say, `Fine, we'll stay off the trails and find another place
to ride.'''
</P>
<P>
   Calvo said, however, that most of the discussion about the cause
of the erosion seems to be imprecise.
</P>
<P>
   ``They see parts of the area being eroded away,'' he said, ``and
they see mountain bikers. They put one and one together whether
they're right or wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what has everybody up in arms,'' said fellow biker
Parker. ``They have closed down the trails using the reasons that
it's damaging the ecosystem. Yet they have no studies and no
evidence. I would say, in general, there is a reason. But no one
can figure out why. Everyone has an opinion, though.''
</P>
<P>
   Advisory board chairwoman Caudill admitted that no formal
scientific study has been conducted. But she said, ``You can pretty
much see what the situation is by looking.''
</P>
<P>
   A tour of some of the closed trails reveals areas where ravines
have eroded to a depth of about 15 feet. A number of areas are
scarred by abandoned, eroded trails that have been replaced by new
trails a short distance away.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of this was as flat as the rest of Houston at one time,''
said Don Gray, a retired geologist and advisory board member.
``These are just ravines.''
</P>
<P>
   Horse hooves or even human hikers could damage the trails and
set the stage for erosion. But, Caudill said, ``we don't have 2,000
hikers coming through here.''
</P>
<P>
   Caudill disputed Case's claim that the trails now are impassable
to runners, but noted that closing the damaged trails for all uses
might be advisable. ``Some of them just would benefit from being
rested for a while,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Bikers argued that the closure of trails may lead to unsafe
conditions on those that remain open.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very unfortunate situation,'' said Mount. ``You've cut
the existing trails by more than half, and you'll still have the
same amount of traffic. You'll still have runners and hikers using
those trails. There's a real probability that someone will get
hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
