<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DORM-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDENTS NOT SWEATING LIFE IN GENERAL AT TEXAS A&AMP;M'S COED DORM 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PATTY REINERT 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ Whoever said ladies don't sweat was
flat out lying.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask the new residents of Hart Hall.
</P>
<P>
   One of only two Texas A&AMP;M University dormitories with no air
conditioning, Hart has traditionally been an all-male bastion of
stoics who cope with the heat by stripping to their underwear,
throwing open their doors and cranking up the window fans.
</P>
<P>
   It's an Aggie pride thing.
</P>
<P>
   Shared misery is their bond.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and it's the cheapest housing on campus.
</P>
<P>
   This year though, Hart Hall is going coed, giving 24 women the
equal opportunity to swelter and save.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was expecting it to be worse than it really is,'' said Becky
Howard, a senior in history who is a member of the hall staff.
``People have told me, `It's so small and the guys will be mean to
you,' but it's not like that. Most of the guys have been
positive.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, she's already lived in the nicer, newer,
air-conditioned halls.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it was kind of boring, quiet,'' she said. ``Here there is
a lot more bonding. The doors are open because you want the
ventilation, and the heat drives everybody out of their rooms so
it's easier to meet people.''
</P>
<P>
   The hall's director, Mark Chaszer, a graduate student from
Spring, Texas, said that when women seeking a low-cost housing
option proposed making Hart coed two years ago, some of the hall's
276 male residents voiced ``serious displeasure.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And of course, some sexist attitudes popped up,'' he said.
``But last year, everything came together. Some of the guys who
were opposed to it graduated or moved and since then, all I've
heard is, `When are the women coming? When are the women coming?'''
</P>
<P>
   Vic Romero, a university staffer who supervises seven residence
halls, said the 68-year-old Hart building has one of the highest
return rates on campus.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason is economic. Hart and Walton Hall, the
campus' only other dorm without air conditioning, cost $612 per
semester. That compares with fees up to $2,500 a semester for newer
halls with bigger rooms, private baths and better carpet.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the freshmen are moving in, well, it's usually the
mothers who have a problem with them being in a non-air-conditioned
building and the building being so old,'' Chaszer said. ``But by
the end of the day, their kids have already met two or three people
who will be their friends, and most college students are successful
if they can make a connection with someone within three weeks of
being on campus.''
</P>
<P>
   The real test of the women's integration, though, will be the
Aggie bonfire, said Ryan Locker, a political science major who
serves on the hall staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the women have been very active in their former
halls,'' he said, so it will be interesting to see how fully they
are included in the hall's annual participation in building the
bonfire. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; And both men and women are anxious to see how the newly coed
hall will vote on the issue of visiting hours. If 90 percent of the
residents vote in favor, visitation could be expanded from the
current 9 a.m. to 2 a.m. to 24 hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   A few other changes are likely in the works as well, as the
overwhelmingly male hall attempts to accommodate two dozen women.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a rather testosterone-filled dorm, with a lot of guys
going around in their boxers,'' Locker said. ``They still do that,
though I was hoping they wouldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
