<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRESS, BUGS CAUSE BRANCHES TO DROP 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY HUBER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Branches are breaking off the pecan trees in my neighborhood.
The limbs do not seem to have any insect damage and seem healthy.
Is it because of the earlier summer rains that are causing the
limbs to be too heavy to support the heavy pecan load? Is there
anything that can be done to prevent further damage to the trees?
</P>
<P>
   A: Some years pecans produce too many nuts for the trees to
support the entire load. This, coupled with the fact that the trees
can become weak and brittle when stressed, increases the likelihood
of breaking branches.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's drought and the recent long, hot and dry period have
weakened many trees. Keep pecans well watered. Water slowly and
deeply so that the soil is moist 8 to 12 inches down. A good layer
of organic mulch will help modify soil temperatures and moisture.
</P>
<P>
   It's sometimes beneficial to reduce a tree's load by knocking
some of the nuts to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Also, pecan branches are sensitive to lack of sunlight. When
branches shade others, those limbs that receive insufficient light
die, and the trees self-prune. This usually is not worth the worry.
</P>
<P>
   This time of year, we also get questions about what causes
smaller limbs and twigs to fall. The culprit is usually twig
girdler beetles. These pests cause pecans, oaks, mimosas and other
trees to drop branches. Twig girdlers lay their eggs in the twigs
of these trees, then chew around the twigs, and the girdled
branches die and drop. The eggs in these fallen pieces hatch, and
the larvae mature.
</P>
<P>
   The best thing to do in this situation is to gather the fallen
pieces of wood. I find myself removing such wood from beneath our
red oak each year.
</P>
<P>
   All trees are suffering from the extremes of recent years. Last
year's drought weakened many, making it easier for pest invasions.
We have lost many large pines that became vulnerable to pine bark
beetles. We did get rain earlier this summer, but it's been
terribly dry in the past six weeks. When so stressed, trees can
drop what they can't support. Our red and post oaks are dropping
leaves like crazy, even though I work hard to provide adequate
moisture. About all I can do at this point is hope for a break.
</P>
<P>
   Q: For five years I've been battling two vines in my beds. Could
you tell me what they are and how I can eliminate them without
destroying existing flowers and shrubs? The first twines around
azaleas, oleander _ everything. It seems to ``choke'' some of my
plants. Is this wild morning glory? The second vine is thorny with
a variegated leaf.
</P>
<P>
   A: The thorny vine with the variegated, heart-shaped leaves is
one of the species of Smilax, commonly called greenbriar. It is
difficult to eradicate since this member of the lily family
reproduces from an underground tuber. If you can't get a hold on
the tuber, keep cutting the vine back to the ground. Eventually,
the roots will die since there will be no top growth to replenish
and support the underground system.
</P>
<P>
   Greenbriar (``Smilax spp.'') also goes by the common names bull
briar and cat briar. The vines have green woody stems that are
armed with sharp spines that easily tear your clothes and you.
</P>
<P>
   The other vine with the simple, three-lobed leaves appears to be
one of the morning glories. Thanks to a mild winter, those got a
running start this spring. From time to time, I set aside a weekend
morning and go after the vines. This heavy-duty removal lasts for
several weeks, but I do have to repeat the process.
</P>
<P>
   You can CAREFULLY apply a systemic herbicide for some possible
relief of these vines. But be sure this chemical does not come in
contact with valued plants. I'm afraid some things just grow well
when others are dying in the heat and drought.
</P>
<P>
   Q: There is a biblical story about the passionflower, that each
part is symbolic.
</P>
<P>
   A: The passionflower vine (``Passiflora spp.'') is one of our
most exotic blooms. It is steeped in Christian symbolism. The five
blood-colored anthers at the center of the bloom suggest the five
wounds of Christ, and the fringed corona represents the crown of
thorns. The stamens resemble a cross, the stigmas are symbolic of
the nails that impaled Christ to the cross and the petals represent
the apostles at the crucifixion.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mail garden questions to Kathy Huber, garden editor, Houston
Chronicle, P.O. Box 4260, Houston TX 77210. The bulk of mail
prevents an individual reply to each unpublished letter.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
