<HEADLINE>
SPENDING ON SMOKING-PREVENTION EFFORTS LAGGING IN TEXAS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ It was almost refreshing last week when the
federal health experts at the Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention renewed debate over the tobacco settlements negotiated
by Texas and other states.
</P>
<P>
   It was refreshing in the sense that they didn't have a single
word to say about the fees awarded the lawyers who won the
settlements, a worn-out dispute that should have gone away a long
time ago.
</P>
<P>
   The CDC people have their priorities straight. Their No. 1
concern is not whether a few rich lawyers get richer but whether
Texas and other states make the best possible use of their tobacco
dollars to fight smoking, the single most preventable cause of
death and disease in the United States today and, supposedly, the
main reason the states sued cigarette companies in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Not so refreshing was that the CDC, in a new report, found
smoking-prevention efforts in Texas and most other states woefully
lacking, despite their settlement windfalls.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sad fact remains that most states have not earmarked
significant settlement funds for tobacco control,'' Dr. Jeffrey P.
Koplan, the CDC director, told the National Conference on Tobacco
and Health, which met in Kissimmee, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Texas was one of the first states to sue the tobacco industry
over cigarette marketing practices and public health-care costs
related to smoking. And it was one of the first states to settle,
negotiating an agreement under which cigarette makers are to pay
Texas $17.3 billion over the next 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, the Legislature budgeted Texas' first $1.8 billion
in tobacco payments. And, under an agreement that chief budget
writers had with former Attorney General Dan Morales, who won the
settlement, they earmarked all of the $1.8 billion for health care.
</P>
<P>
   The money was either placed in endowments or appropriated
outright for the next two-year budget period.
</P>
<P>
   The largest single outright expenditure was about $180 million
for a health insurance program for low-income children. Hundreds of
millions of dollars were set aside in numerous endowments for
medical schools, and a $200 million endowment was created for an
anti-smoking education program to be development by the Texas
Department of Health.
</P>
<P>
   Most health-care providers and advocates supported the
Legislature's approach. But the American Cancer Society of Texas,
the American Lung Association's Texas division and the Campaign for
Tobacco Free Kids protested that not enough was being spent on
anti-smoking programs.
</P>
<P>
   That's because the $200 million health department endowment will
generate only about $10 million a year that can actually be spent.
</P>
<P>
   Although that is a significant increase over the $1 million to
$2 million a year the health department had been spending to
discourage people from smoking, the dissenting groups said it was
woefully inadequate for developing effective anti-smoking programs
for a state as large as Texas.
</P>
<P>
   And, in its new report, the CDC agrees. The CDC said Texas
should be spending (not endowing) at least $103 million a year and,
optimally, more than twice that much. Part of the money, the CDC
said, should be spent on programs to help adults quit smoking. But
much of it would be earmarked for programs in the schools and local
communities _ including television commercials _ to convince
teen-agers not to start smoking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people begin using tobacco in early adolescence,
typically by age 16; almost all first use occurs before high school
graduation,'' the CDC said.
</P>
<P>
   Koplan said that comprehensive tobacco control programs already
tried in California and Massachusetts have been successful.
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco control efforts, however, are still untested in Texas
because they have been virtually nonexistent here. That's one
reason legislators took a conservative spending approach. They said
they wanted to be sure the health department can come up with
programs that work.
</P>
<P>
   But with only $10 million a year, the health department won't be
able to develop a statewide program. So health officials will
probably concentrate their efforts on only one region of the state
and try to demonstrate some effective results there, said Dr. Phil
Huang, chief of the agency's bureau of disease, injury and tobacco
prevention.
</P>
<P>
   Let us hope they do.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature will be spending billions of dollars in tobacco
money for years to come and can re-evaluate its commitment to
smoking prevention. Spending money to treat cancer and other
smoking-related health problems is important. But it would be more
cost-effective _ and humane _ to prevent many of those illnesses in
the first place.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Robison can receive e-mail at clay.robison(at)chron.com &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
