<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DESIGNER-DRUGS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHARMACISTS FILL A NICHE BY HAND MIXING PRESCRIPTIONS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LISA DAVIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A toddler needs cardiac medication that only comes in
adult-strength.
</P>
<P>
   An elderly woman can't swallow pills, but she needs pain
medication.
</P>
<P>
   A cat refuses to take needed medication in any form.
</P>
<P>
   To treat such problems, more and more physicians _ including
veterinarians _ are turning to specialized pharmacists who
customize medicine the old-fashioned way: with mortar and pestle.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a growing area of pharmacy practice,'' said David
Sparks, the president and chief executive officer of the
Houston-based Professional Compounding Centers of America, or PCCA.
``The needs have always been there, but a lot of physicians were
not always aware of the capabilities of pharmacists to meet their
needs.''
</P>
<P>
   Compounding, or making drugs by hand, fills a niche not met by
commercially manufactured drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be that all pharmacy was compounding, and then we
got in to the manufactured pill,'' said Lynn Simpson, an assistant
clinical professor at the University of Houston College of
Pharmacy. ``Now the pendulum is swinging back to things that can be
compounded and made better for the patient.''
</P>
<P>
   John Cianca, a physiatrist who specializes in musculoskeletal
problems, said he started prescribing pain medicine dispensed in a
topical cream instead of the standard oral pill form when he
learned about compounding two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most pain medications have some sort of systemic effects like
drowsiness. Others are more problematic, like ulcers and high
toxicity levels in the liver,'' Cianca said. ``The topical
applications are good for superficial pain. They provide localized
pain medication without having to go through your whole digestive
system.''
</P>
<P>
   When pills and liquids come in a more desirable form and are set
to a custom dosage, patients are more likely to take their
medicine, said Ken Hughes, a Houston pharmacist. These designer
drugs, therefore, have a higher success rate than commercially
prepared prescriptions, Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
   Some prescriptions can be time-consuming for a pharmacist to
compound, making them more expensive than a commercially prepared
alternative. But that's not always the case, Hughes said. While
most compounded prescriptions cost $30 to $50, some may be cheaper
than name-brand drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors and pharmacists alike said most patients have no problem
getting reimbursed by their insurance carrier for compounded
prescriptions.
</P>
<P>
   Pharmacists can create medications in almost any form through
compounding. Lozenges, creams, suppositories, capsules and
lollipops are just some of the possible forms. They also can change
the medicine to a child's favorite flavor or put the medicine in a
fish compound to entice a cat to take it.
</P>
<P>
   PCCA, which provides compounding pharmacists with bulk
pharmaceuticals, equipment, devices, flavoring, training and
consultation services, has seen demand increase 20 percent a year
since its founding in 1981, Sparks said.
</P>
<P>
   The pharmacists that PCCA serves, like most pharmacists who
compound, work in small independently owned shops that specialize
in compounding.
</P>
<P>
   One such pharmacy, The Remedy Shoppe, opened two years ago near
the Texas Medical Center in Houston. Business has grown so rapidly,
the pharmacy is moving to a larger location, said pharmacist Jeanne
Horner.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of specialty patients and specialty clinics to
go to in Houston, and to go along with it, you need a specialty
pharmacist,'' Horner said.
</P>
<P>
   Those who benefit most from the compounded prescriptions are
hospice and terminal cancer patients, Sparks said.
</P>
<P>
   In the last stages of disease, many patients are no longer able
to take pain medication orally, and it may even be difficult to
give them medicine intravenously, therefore creams that can be
absorbed through the skin, suppositories or fast-dissolving wafers
are immensely helpful, Sparks said.
</P>
<P>
   Pharmacists learn basic information about compounding in their
first two years of pharmacy school, and they may do a six-week
clinical rotation with a pharmacy that specializes in compounding,
Simpson said. Pharmacists need to have basic compounding skills
because they will use them on occasion whether they work at a chain
or independent pharmacy.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, all drugstores are required by state law to have
the basic equipment _ mortar and pestle, balance, measuring devices
and spatulas _ to do compounding. Pharmacies that don't focus on
compounding, however, usually don't have the equipment needed to do
compounding more efficiently, Sparks said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know any pharmacists who don't do any (compounding),''
Sparks said. ``But the chains are geared toward doing high
volume.''
</P>
<P>
   While a pharmacist at a chain drugstore might mix up a cream for
a dermatologist, they spend more time counseling patients than they
do preparing prescriptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doing drug therapy doesn't just mean dispensing medications,''
Simpson said. ``A pharmacist is accessible, so patients go there
because their physician doesn't always have time to tell them
everything about their pills.''
</P>
<P>
   Debbie Platts, a district pharmacy supervisor for Walgreens in
Houston, said her pharmacists may refer people to specialty
pharmacists rather than fill the prescription themselves. She also
said Walgreens is not planning to increase its compounding
services.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see a whole lot of compounding going on, and I'm not
aware of demands in our case going up,'' Platts said. ``But that
might be in our case because doctors don't refer them to us because
they know other pharmacists who specialize in it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
