<HEADLINE>
TOOL SYSTEM HELPS TEXAS AMPUTEE TACKLE DAILY TASKS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Photo available on NYT database) 
(Attn: Mass.) 
 
By STEVE OLAFSON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRAZORIA, Texas _ Necessity really is the mother of invention
for Ron Farquharson.
</P>
<P>
   For some, necessity is being able to pull a wrench or hoe a
garden or cast a rod and reel.
</P>
<P>
   For Farquharson, it was slicing an onion.
</P>
<P>
   With a prosthetic right arm, it wasn't impossible, but it wasn't
easy, either. The knife invariably would slip out of the hook in
his prosthesis.
</P>
<P>
   There's got to be a better way, he figured. So he and a
co-worker invented a system in which amputees are able to lock a
variety of tools into their prosthetic arms to perform everyday
tasks that most of us take for granted.
</P>
<P>
   Farquharson (pronounced FARK-uh-sun) has turned the solution to
his onion-slicing dilemma into a business that helps others.
</P>
<P>
   ``It works,'' he said recently, moments after pulling a 5-pound
catfish out of a pond behind his rural home in Brazoria County near
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The fishing rod he used to land the catfish is among the tools
that can be locked into a terminal device that fits onto his
artificial arm.
</P>
<P>
   Farquharson still could use a rod and reel before the invention
of his tool system. It was just more difficult for the natural
right-hander to hold the rod with his left arm and crank the reel
with the hook on his prosthetic arm.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to a fishing rod, dozens of other tools have been
modified to fit into the terminal system. Hand and carpentry tools,
such as wrenches, files, vise grips and saws; kitchen utensils,
such as cheese slicers, melon ballers, knives and forks; and garden
tools, such as hoes and trowels.
</P>
<P>
   Next, they're thinking about adapting golf clubs for the
terminal device.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no other system like it in the world,'' said
Farquharson, 52.
</P>
<P>
   His company, Assistive Devices of Texas, obtained a patent on
the terminal device in 1995. Made of lightweight aircraft aluminum,
it can be turned to a 45-degree angle or be rotated 360 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Adapting tools to fit the terminal device is a matter of cutting
off the ends of whatever the customer wants.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a lot of wrench handles lying around,'' said Johnnie
Rouse, 45, who owns Reactive Metals in Angleton, Texas, and handles
that end of the business.
</P>
<P>
   Sales have been modest, with just more than 60 of the terminal
devices sold, but Farquharson and his partner, Glenn Betts, 48, go
to trade shows around the country and maintain an Internet site
(www.txad.com) to promote their product.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been beating the bushes showing people this thing
exists,'' Farquharson said.
</P>
<P>
   His first partner, Dan Still, who helped him create the
invention, dropped out of the business venture and sold his
interest to Betts.
</P>
<P>
   Farquharson and Betts realize that their product has a small
market because statistics show that 6,000 to 10,000 people lose an
arm each year and only about half of them get prostheses.
</P>
<P>
   Farquharson admitted that he had been ready to give up two or
three times, but success stories from people like Bryan Lague
convince him of the need for his product.
</P>
<P>
   Lague, 19, of Hampden, Mass., lost his right hand in a fireworks
accident when he was 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was playing with something that was supposed to sparkle, but
it blew up,'' he said in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   At the culinary school where he is a student, he would use the
stump of his right hand to guide food and his left hand to wield
knives and other kitchen utensils.
</P>
<P>
   His therapist at a Shriners Hospital told him about Assistive
Devices of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Today, if he needs a spatula, a knife or a peeler, it just takes
him a few seconds to snap one onto his prosthesis and go to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're great,'' he said. ``It's a great invention.''
</P>
<P>
   Farquharson calls the terminal device an ``enabler.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1971 while working at Dow Chemical Co., a 7,500-pound
hydraulic press malfunctioned and crushed his right hand. His arm
was amputated below the elbow.
</P>
<P>
   What Farquharson calls the ``frustration factor'' led him to
give up most mechanical tasks.
</P>
<P>
   His invention, he said, ``takes a lot of the frustration out. It
doesn't take it all away, but it takes a lot away.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
