<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOMATO FIGHTS AND OTHER FUN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: A tilde is needed over n in Bunol) 
 
By HARRY SHATTUCK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He seemed perfectly sane when he stopped by the office some time
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Polite. Soft-spoken. Articulate. Feet planted firmly on the
floor.
</P>
<P>
   So why does Doug Lansky find himself fending off hippopotamuses
from a canoe on the lower Zambezi River bordering Zimbabwe and
Zambia?
</P>
<P>
   Lassoing reindeer above the Arctic Circle in Sweden?
</P>
<P>
   Playing underwater hockey in Australia?
</P>
<P>
   Riding an ostrich in South Africa?
</P>
<P>
   Attending acupuncture school in Beijing?
</P>
<P>
   Participating in the world's largest tomato fight in Spain?
</P>
<P>
   ``The regular tourist trail just doesn't cut it for me,'' Lansky
explains. ``I crave a more challenging lifestyle.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
UNUSUAL HONEYMOON &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I renewed acquaintances with Lansky by e-mail a few days ago as
he was beginning a five-month around-the-world honeymoon with his
Swedish wife, Signe, a frequent traveling companion familiar to
readers of Lansky's syndicated ``Vagabond'' column
(www.houstonchronicle.com).
</P>
<P>
   Normally, I'd never dream of bothering a guy during such a
significant occasion. But normally, folks don't honeymoon in
Uganda, Rwanda and Kenya. For starters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tomorrow, I'm hoping to go deep-sea fishing off the Kenyan
coast where Hemingway pulled in a few fish,'' Lansky answered my
correspondence. ``Next week, I'm scheduled to climb Kilimanjaro.''
</P>
<P>
   And when he comes down from the mountain, he'll rest?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I plan to attend sumo wrestling school in Japan next
month,'' Lansky assured me.
</P>
<P>
   Lansky likes to say that his adventuresome spirit was born ``on
the Third-World island of Manhattan.'' He was raised in Minnesota
and graduated from Colorado College, and in the introduction to his
hilarious new book, ``Up the Amazon Without a Paddle'' (Meadowbrook
Press, $10), he recalls the impact of commencement day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just waiting for them to call my name so I could go up
and collect my diploma, fold it into a paper hat and start flipping
burgers at McDonald's,'' he writes. ``While the speaker was
rambling on about networking, I was daydreaming about sailing down
the Nile, crossing the desert on a camel, ski instructing in the
Alps, crewing on a yacht in the Caribbean, scuba diving in the Red
Sea, splashing around in the Ganges, questioning a guru in Tibet,
swimming with sea lions in the Galapagos, climbing mountains in
Patagonia. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's a lot of daydreaming. It was a long speech.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
OFFBEAT ADVENTURES &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Most of us daydream. But over the past eight years, even before
reaching his 30th birthday, Lansky has lived out many of his
fantasies _ hugely assisted by Signe, whom he describes as ``an
editor, a photographer and all-around great person.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I'm not just saying this because she is a doctor and
financially supports me.''
</P>
<P>
   His new book details 60 offbeat adventures, each covered in
about four pages and many updated from previous Vagabond columns.
</P>
<P>
   My favorite is Lansky's description of Tomatina, or ``getting
sauced in Bunol, Spain. When it comes to parties, it's hard to top
the creativity of the Spanish,'' he writes. ``Give them a few
bulls, they run them down the street and call it a fiesta. Give
them 250,000 pounds of ripe tomatoes and ... well, you can imagine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I, for one, will never again look at tomatoes the same way _
those innocuous little red slices that garnish your dinner salad
are actually ballistic weapons. At noon, cannon fire signaled the
entrance of the first truckload of tomatoes and the beginning of
the one-hour battle. By the time the sixth truck came through, the
plaza looked like the sight of a Ragu factory explosion.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few of the 30,000 participants wore swim goggles and gas
masks. I even saw one guy who had fastened a pasta strainer to his
face.''
</P>
<P>
   Underwater hockey _ also known as ``Octopush'' _ provided a
different kind of splash. ``The English invented it in 1954,''
Lansky explains, ``perhaps as a way for underwater basket weavers
to stay in shape during the off-season.''
</P>
<P>
   Maneuvering the puck _ or ``squid,'' as Lansky's Aussie
teammates in Brisbane called it _ along the bottom of the pool was
challenging enough. But, then, a teammate brought up the subject of
fights. (This was, after all, still hockey.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I wondered if the offending players have to go to the penalty
box,'' Lansky writes. ``I couldn't see one. I just hoped it wasn't
underwater.''
</P>
<P>
   I asked Lansky if half-way through any of his adventures he'd
ever had the urge to shout, ``Get me out of here!''
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized I was over my head when I was up the Amazon living
with the Jaguar Indians and woke up with a machete pressed up
against my forehead,'' he responded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another time was when I bought a horse in Ecuador and started
riding north to Colombia without a guide, map, compass, tent or
sleeping bag. For some reason, the importance of those things
didn't occur to me until I was sitting on the horse.''
</P>
<P>
   Undeterred, he still daydreams. His current ``wish list'' for
future adventures? ``Of course, the moon is at the top,'' he says.
``And maybe ski jumping school ...''
</P>
<P>
   Area bookstores stock or can order ``Up the Amazon Without a
Paddle.'' Or call 800-338-2232, or access www.meadowbrookpress.com
on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
