<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-BOOKS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TERM LIMITS' AUTHOR FINDS HIS GROOVE IN NEWEST WORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DOUG BLACKBURN  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Transfer of Power,'' by Vince Flynn. Read by Daniel Oreskes.
Abridged, approximately 4.5 hours. Simon &AMP; Schuster Audio. $24.
</P>
<P>
   There is good news to report: Vince Flynn is getting better. He
struck pay dirt last year with his first political thriller, ``Term
Limits,'' a not particularly believable or well-told tale that was
nonetheless a big success. (It has been on many paperback
best-seller lists this summer.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Transfer of Power'' is a significant improvement. Sure, it
contains some roll-your-eyes plot developments and capitalizes on
well-worn stereotypes. Arab terrorists have taken over the White
House. The president's trapped in an underground bunker and it's up
to the CIA's top counterterrorism operative to save the day.
</P>
<P>
   But Flynn is clearly working harder this time out. He does well
in developing minor characters who are more than one-dimensional.
The protagonist, Mitch Rapp, is enough of a lone wolf that, as you
root for him, you also try and figure out who might be cast in his
part in the sure-to-come movie. Bruce Willis would be a good bet.
Stage and screen veteran Daniel Oreskes gives a fine reading.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Back to the Moon,'' by Homer H. Hickam Jr. Read by Boyd
Gaines. Abridged, approximately 5 hours. Simon &AMP; Schuster Audio.
$24.
</P>
<P>
   There is a schizophrenic quality to Homer Hickam's fiction
debut. The retired NASA engineer, whose memoir ``Rocket Boys''
received high critical praise, clearly knows the space business and
is able to translate this in ways that don't leave the average
reader gasping to keep up.
</P>
<P>
   But Hickam would benefit from some basic lessons in creating
characters and dialogue; too much of ``Back to the Moon'' fails to
achieve liftoff.
</P>
<P>
   In this space adventure, a zealous space scientist successfully
hijacks a shuttle and pilots it to the moon, where the secrets of
his deceased wife await him. On board, by accident, is a beautiful
daredevil-journalist named Penny High Eagle (yes, the Eagle will
have landed before Hickam is finished). They are forced to battle
unexpected mechanical and logistical challenges, all the while
fighting with one another in a most predictable fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Hickam probably has a good novel in him waiting to be hatched,
but at this point the scientist and the storyteller aren't working
on the same level.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``McNally's Dilemma,'' by Lawrence Sanders. Read by Boyd Gaines.
Abridged, approximately 3 hours. Simon &AMP; Schuster Audio. $18.
</P>
<P>
   The latest in Lawrence Sanders' McNally series jumped
immediately to the best-seller lists this summer, where it stayed
far longer than it deserved.
</P>
<P>
   Palm Beach private investigator Archy McNally, who works for his
father's law firm, unravels a tangle of blackmail and deceit that
is lacking one crucial element: tension.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders' prose has a '40s flipness, with pseudo-wiseguy cracks
that ring hollow. Neither McNally nor any of the men and women he
encounters is especially likable, and collectively they fail to
captivate us.
</P>
<P>
   ``McNally's Dilemma'' can be found in most bookstores' mystery
section, but the only thing that puzzles me is Sanders' popularity.
His fans' loyalty outweighs Sanders' talents, I'm afraid, though
Simon &AMP; Schuster workhorse Boyd Gaines is not to be faulted for
failing to make this sizzle. Steak is required for sizzle, and
``McNally's Dilemma'' is missing the meat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-99 1241EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
