<SLUG> BC-CONVEX-MIRRORS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONVEX MIRRORS HAVE PRACTICAL USES IN DECORATING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRANCES INGRAHAM HEINS  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TROY, N.Y. _ Convex mirrors became the fashion in the late 18th
and early 19th century. Traditionally, they are round and ensconced
in a gilt frame ornamented with hand-carved eagles or dolphins and
goldleaf trim, such as small spheres and carved foliage.
</P>
<P>
   The mirrors, also called ``bull's-eye,'' were popular in the
neoclassical era, the Federal period and with Hepplewhite
furnishings, which have graceful curves. One type, the girandole
looking glass, often features a branched candleholder.
</P>
<P>
   Convex mirrors come in many sizes and also can be rectangular or
square. The outward curve of the mirror makes images appear smaller
than they really are.
</P>
<P>
   Pairs of mirrors would flank a fireplace or hang at each end of
a dining room. Few survive in pairs today, as they were often
broken, or divided when an estate was sold.
</P>
<P>
   Their function was not for grooming, but to reflect light and to
provide an interesting view of a room.
</P>
<P>
   The earliest convex mirrors were most likely manufactured in
England. Lots of reproductions were made in this country during the
late 19th century during the Colonial Revival period and into the
1930s. Although the carving is not as crisp in these replicas, they
can still be hard to tell from the real thing.
</P>
<P>
   They are quite valuable and remain most desirable for interior
design.
</P>
<P>
   One of the finest local examples of a convex mirror is in the
Hart-Cluett Mansion in Troy. Researchers believe that this mirror,
created circa 1816, was part of a pair that originally graced the
front parlor.
</P>
<P>
   Because of their weight, early convex mirrors were attached to
the wall in a more permanent way, rather than today's method of
using picture wire.
</P>
<P>
   New gilt-framed convex mirrors come in many sizes, and a
reproduction can cost approximately $500 and up. Depending on the
maker, age and condition, an antique convex mirror can cost $2,500
or up into the thousands.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to being decorative, unframed convex mirrors also
have a commercial purpose. Convex mirrors made of glass or acrylic
are used for security in retail stores to discourage pilfering and
to give peripheral views.
</P>
<P>
   You can even get a small convex mirror from Spinner.com that
affixes to your workplace computer monitor, so you can keep an eye
on the activity behind your back.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-99 1242EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990830.0182 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 12:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4355 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-30 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SIERRA GEM GLISTENS WITH SECRETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM STIENSTRA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ California's best places in the great outdoors
are a mystery. But I've learned that these secrets can be
discovered and unlocked.
</P>
<P>
   Hell Hole Reservoir, set deep on the west flank of the Sierra
Nevada, is much like this. I first saw it by accident, heading back
from Tahoe in my little airplane, and with no turbulence, I decided
to enjoy the smooth air by cruising over the Sierra. The original
idea was to get an eagle-eye view of the Granite Chief Wilderness
and Desolation Wilderness, and trace the route of the Pacific Crest
Trail.
</P>
<P>
   But, in the process I became transfixed instead by this long,
narrow lake set in a granite gorge. The lake was obviously remote,
yet accessible by car, with a paved road all the way in.
</P>
<P>
   Soon I made the trip in my pick-up truck and found that Hell
Hole Reservoir is not only a classic Sierra lake, but offers a
series of features not found anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   On the way there, you pass French Meadows Reservoir, a huge,
beautiful place with excellent camping, boating and fishing. The
lake covers nearly 2,000 acres, circled by conifers, with five
campgrounds, including a great boat-in site, and also provides good
trout fishing. For many, this is perfection, and there is no reason
to go any farther.
</P>
<P>
   But if you want something unique, you do keep going, and
eventually arrive at the primitive, dirt boat ramp near the dam at
Hell Hole, set at 4,580 feet, deep in the Sierra Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   The first thing you will notice is that the water is azure blue,
not green, and that at lake's edge is a craggy, granite shoreline.
These two features give rise to several special opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   The reason the water is blue is because of its excellent
clarity, a product of the pristine, low-nutrient flows of the
Rubicon River, which feeds the lake, emerging from the Sierra crest
and running through the untouched Granite Chief Wilderness.
</P>
<P>
   According to a taste test of hydrologists, it is the
best-tasting water from any of the 19 national forests in
California. Because of these pristine qualities, the lake is not
stocked by the little rainbow trout the state Department of Fish
and Game is well known for, but instead provides a fishery for
mackinaw trout and brown trout, often elusive but quite large, as
well as the more abundant but smaller kokanee salmon.
</P>
<P>
   There are many other special qualities here. Because of the
rocky shoreline, for instance, no lakeside camps can be reached by
car, which also throws people off. A standard drive-to camp is set
about a mile from the lake; it is clean, sheltered and popular. But
there is another option.
</P>
<P>
   There is a small camp that can be reached by boat, or by hiking
3.5 miles, located at head of the lake along the southern shore.
</P>
<P>
   And here's another secret: On the north side of the lake there
is a 4-wheel-drive jeep road, fairly rough, but which will allow
you to drive to water's edge near the lake's headwaters. This is an
ideal spot, both sheltered and remote, to put in a canoe, then make
the easy paddle across to the boat-in campsite.
</P>
<P>
   To reach this camp by foot, you hike over the dam, then turn
left, where you will find the trail rises and falls in 60-foot
climbs and descents, over and over, routed well above the lake's
shore. An outstanding swimming area is hidden along this trail,
part of a huge granite formation; it can be reached only by foot or
by boat.
</P>
<P>
   Note: This trail camp also provides a jump-off spot into the
neighboring Granite Chief Wilderness to the east for a backpacking
trip, with the wilderness border just another mile up the trail.
The trail is routed along the Rubicon River, and then rises amid a
huge, glacially sculpted face of the high Sierra, where dozens of
lakes are hidden in rock bowls.
</P>
<P>
   The name ``Hell Hole'' comes from its setting in a 400-foot deep
granite gorge. The gorge was dammed and filled with water from the
Rubicon.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, I've seen this lake in many conditions, and it
is always pretty, even in low water, when the lake is bordered by
the high walls of the granite gorge. When near full, as this
summer, it is a more classic mountain setting, with pines and
cedars on the ridges on each side.
</P>
<P>
   There are 383 lakes you can drive to in California, including
hundreds secreted away in little canyons and pockets much as this.
But none of them are quite like Hell Hole: deep, crystal clear
waters, hidden campsites, great nearby hiking, swimming and
exploring, excellent boating, unique fishing and a 4-wheel-drive
road.
</P>
<P>
   Like so many of my favorite spots, I discovered it by accident.
All because I looked down one day from my little airplane.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For information: Phone the Eldorado National Forest Information
Center at 530-644-6048. For a map, ask for Eldorado National Forest
and send $4.30 to Maps, Office of Information, U.S. Forest Service,
1323 Club Drive, Vallejo, CA 94592.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
