<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 12:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4365 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-30 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A COLUMNIST SPEAKS THE TRUTH, AT LAST 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Yet another newspaper columnist was fired
recently for allegedly making up people and quotes. Now I've
decided to come clean.
</P>
<P>
   After all, this column is nearly 12 years running; that's a
tanker truck full of material that my employer could investigate
and find bogus. Rather than join Patricia Smith and Mike Barnicle,
formerly of the Boston Globe _ and now Julie Amparano, formerly of
the Arizona Republic _ I'll just save my bosses the trouble of
outing me as a fraud.
</P>
<P>
   First and most egregious, I confess that I've made up San
Francisco Mayor Willie Brown.
</P>
<P>
   I got the idea from my colleague Rob Morse, who has turned
writing about the mythical mayor into his life's yoga. But, as Rob
confessed in June 1998 when Smith was fired for fabricating people
and quotes, Rob fabricated Willie.
</P>
<P>
   What Rob didn't say was that the impeccably dressed man who
appears at various city functions is an actor _ a very good actor _
but has no connection to genuine government. If he did, wouldn't
the streets be in better shape and the public transportation system
run on time?
</P>
<P>
   In a related vein, I'm sorry to say that, more than a decade
ago, I made up the homeless. I've been lying about them ever since.
</P>
<P>
   The homeless aren't really poor, disenfranchised, messed up
folks. They, too, are actors. But, unlike ``Mayor Brown,'' their
roles are in an ongoing morality play that was scripted about 2,000
years ago by a guy who believed you could judge people and
civilizations by the way they treat ``the least'' among them.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of religion, regular readers know that I often write
about the Catholic Church. All those anonymous priests I quoted?
Especially the ones who are critical of the church? I made them up.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, Catholic priests are just like White House aides,
CIA operatives and chief financial officers for privately held
corporations _ a reporter never has trouble getting them to speak
on the record and for full attribution.
</P>
<P>
   Another common topic in my columns is life in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   I've made up most of that, too.
</P>
<P>
   I earn $60,000 a year. How could I afford to live here, let
alone buy a house, which I said I did last year? The truth is, I
live in Prunedale and rely heavily on guide books, the Weather
Channel and a collection of Herb Caen newspaper columns.
</P>
<P>
   Because I don't really live here, I don't honestly know anything
about the San Francisco Opera. Every word I've ever written about
it, including all those columns about spending weeks each season
working as an extra actor (or supernumerary) _ they're all lies.
</P>
<P>
   I'm amazed no one's ever called me on it. How could anybody
believe a grown woman would put in that kind of time _ not to
mention wear clown noses, bald pates and elf shoes _ just to pull
down $6 per show and $3 per rehearsal? And why hasn't anybody
caught on to the mendacity behind another of my pet subjects:
feminism?
</P>
<P>
   There was never any real women's liberation movement. Gloria
Steinem just got a few of us together back in the late '60s and
said, ``Hey, let's pretend that women are sick of getting paid less
than men, being hit on by their bosses, achieving only token
representation in medicine, law, science, government, sports and
finance, and being valued primarily for the size of their
breasts.''
</P>
<P>
   All you have to do to see that we made it up is take a look at
the Howard Stern show, 98 percent of contemporary advertising and
the U.S. Senate, where the score is 91-9, boys vs. girls.
</P>
<P>
   The last big fabrication I must admit to is the most personal. I
made up my parents.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, I've written dozens of columns about them, my
alleged sister, brother-in-law and nieces. They don't exist. Not as
my family, I mean.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there are some nice people living in Indiana who consented
long ago to let me pass them off as ``my folks.'' But we aren't
related.
</P>
<P>
   It's shameful, I know, but I'd just gotten this column in a big
city newspaper and felt I needed a homespun, stabilizing family to
give me warmth and credibility. I thought they could be my version
of Ma and Pa Kent, the Smallville couple who adopted baby Superman
after his space capsule from Krypton crashed on Earth.
</P>
<P>
   The truth? I'm the illegitimate daughter of an ultra-wealthy San
Francisco oil tycoon.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her electronic mail address
is salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
