<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of Tuesday,
Aug. 31. If you have any questions, please call the Star's
Universal Desk at (816) 234-4784.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WANT: KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Convicted killer Alan Echols evaded the
law for eight years before his capture last week, but a Jackson
County man wanted for murder has avoided the law for almost two
decades. Yellowing police reports tell of the tale of Richard G.
Bocklage, his 10-foot Burmese python and a bizarre letter that
foreshadows a murder. Jackson County probably has fewer than a
dozen outstanding warrants for murder, investigators say. But
Bocklage's case is the oldest one that prosecutors could take to a
jury. Bocklage is accused of killing his former girlfriend who was
doctor at the time. Joe Lambe. 25. Photos.
</P>
<P>
   with SHARON31: Jackson County's oldest active murder warrant is
probably also the most notorious _ a pretty brunette called ``La
Pistolera.'' Sharon Kinne was charged with killing three people
before her 25th birthday, but the Independence woman once called
herself ``just an ordinary girl.'' She's been on the run for nearly
40 years. Joe Lambe 10. Photos, list of others wanted for murder.
Stories will move in the ``a'' category.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KCSKUL: KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A host of changes will welcome
students Tuesday as they enter Kansas City School District schools:
different grade configurations, surveillance cameras, a new
transportation policy and tough new attendance and truancy
policies. Photo of school preparations at Gladstone Elementary.
Phil O'Connor. 20. Stories will move in the ``a'' category.  &QL;
</P>
