documents available to the public today. By Grace Hobson.
(Tentative.) Stories will move in the ``a'' category.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SAL-BUSINESS _ Executive compensation survey to show how
higher-ups are faring. By Diane Stafford, WITH GRAPHIC. Stories
will move in the ``f'' category.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   POZ-SPORTS-COLUMN: KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ From Celebrity Skins Game,
featuring Tom Watson, George Brett and Marcus Allen, to kick off
Senior PGA Tour at Tiffany Greens Golf Club. Column by Joe
Posnanski. Stories will move in the ``s'' category.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHIEFS-SPORTS: Kansas City, Mo. _ Feature. TBA. Stories will
move in the ``s'' category.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ROYALS-SPORTS: Kansas City, Mo. _ Game coverage of KC Royals at
Boston. Stories will move in the ``s'' category.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WALKMAN-20YEARS: Technologically, it was trivial. Culturally, it
was a milestone. Twenty years ago this summer, the Sony Walkman was
introduced in America. From that moment in 1979 the world changed.
Look around. They're ubiquitous. Eric Adler. Art. 890 words.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BOSTON:BOSTON _ It wasn't so long ago that Boston Harbor
was a laughingstock. In the 1988 presidential campaign George Bush
embarrassed rival Michael Dukakis, Massachusetts' governor at the
time, when he called Boston Harbor the dirtiest in America.
</P>
<P>
   Now gleaming new hotels welcome well-heeled guests to the
waterfront. The Temptations, Willie Nelson and Donna Summer brought
yuppie suburbanites to a summer pavilion in the Seaport District. A
federal courthouse opened on Fan Pier last year, and plans call for
a $695 million convention center. Construction is everywhere. Allen
Holder. Has art, separate sidebar. 1,700 words.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BOSSIDE: Travel arrangements, accommodations,
restaurants, tourist attractions. Allen Holder. 1,400 words.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-YMCA: Benches and Adirondack chairs they do have at the
YMCA of the Rockies meeting center here. And an awesome view to go
with them. And a cafeteria that seats 600. And an auditorium with
chairs for 800. And 530 lodge rooms. And 205 cabins set back in the
fringes.
</P>
<P>
   Although most of the facilities were built decades ago to
accommodate conferences of church members and young people, school
and recreational groups, in more recent years this has become a
magnet for grannies and grandpas, aunts and uncles, siblings,
grandchildren and cousins.
</P>
<P>
   The YMCA's Estes Park Center, and its sister center, Snow
Mountain Ranch near Winter Park, Colo., now find themselves in the
family-reunion business. And a booming business it has proven to
be. Karen Uhlenhuth. Has art. 1,500 words.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CLASSICAL-REVIEW: Summertime, when in most cities the concert
schedule slows to a crawl, is a good time for settling into an easy
chair, enjoying the air conditioning and catching up on recordings.
Here's a rundown of recent CDs of note, including several
outstanding reissues. Scott Cantrell. 1,300 words.
</P>
