<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUITTERS NEVER WIN _ OR GO HOME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: Recently, I have been having problems shutting
down my computer. It will get to the part where it says ``Please
wait while your computer shuts down,'' and then it doesn't. I know
I need to get it worked on, but would like to have some idea of
what they need to do rather than just paying for anything the tech
tells me.
</P>
<P>
   _ Quittin' Time
</P>
<P>
   DEAR QUIT: This is such a common problem, I don't even know
where to start. Or stop, I guess. And the first thing we have to
stop is this ridiculous notion you have to pay somebody to fix your
computer problems.
</P>
<P>
   A Windows machine is no Macintosh. You actually have to learn
what makes it tick, and you get smarter in the process. So here's
lesson No. 1: The reason it takes Windows so long to shut down is
that it's trying to terminate all the stuff that's going on behind
the scenes, making it safe for you to kill the power. That stuff
can include programs that are running, memory caches that are being
dumped or even Microsoft Stealth Inquisitor 2000 transferring your
bank balance and all your private personal records to World
Domination Headquarters in Redmond, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   Something is refusing to shut itself down, so Windows can't. Do
a Control-Alt-Delete, and you'll see everything that's going on
displayed in a new window on your screen. You can selectively
terminate programs there, then try shutting down to see if things
work better. Virus checkers are prime candidates for gumming things
up, but almost anything else has the potential to do it, too.
</P>
<P>
   I've also seen a clogged CD-ROM memory cache get caught in the
flywheel. Unless you're some data-crunching Poindexter, right-click
on My Computer, then select Properties. Click the Performance tab,
and go for the File System button. You get another set of tabs to
deal with. Hit the CD-ROM tab and cut your cache size to the
minimum. Never thought you'd turn into such a tech-head did you?
But look how much more you know about your computer now.
</P>
<P>
   If things are still jammed, Microsoft has an online
troubleshooter to help you identify the problem. I guess they got
tired of answering calls from irate consumers, Go to
support.microsoft.com/support/tshoot/w98startup.asp and have at it.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I forgot about using the Add/Remove utility in
Windows 98 to eliminate programs. I merely deleted the folders to
get rid of them. They are still listed in the Add/Remove programs
list, though.
</P>
<P>
   _ Gone But Not Forgotten
</P>
<P>
   DEAR GONE: Normally, I'd tell you to go look on Microsoft's Web
site for TweakUI, a wonderful little free utility that works harder
than my rehab counselor. One of the things it does is clear bogus
entries from that list.
</P>
<P>
   But it's as if Microsoft is embarrassed by TweakUI, which
contains tools that are so helpful only a moron would have left
them out of the release version of Windows. If it's still on the
download site at all, then it's hidden better than crazy old Uncle
Elbert during a Bombay family reunion. Tweak UI used to be buried
on the Win98 CD, too, but I can't find it on the Second Edition
disc.
</P>
<P>
   Don't mess with Microsoft. Go to www.shareware.com and do a
search for TweakUI98.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I would appreciate it if you would let me know
if you get this E-mail.
</P>
<P>
   _ Without a Clue
</P>
<P>
   DEAR CLUE: Nope. Never got it. Better try again.
</P>
<P>
   (Dr. Bombay will let you know if he doesn't get your e-mail,
too. Just look for no letter from him in your mailbox to confirm
nonreceipt. The address is drbombay(at)star-telegram.com or, if you
still use snail-mail, Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort
Worth, TX 76101. Fax: 390-7257. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-99 1307EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
