<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 13:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4376 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN     08-30 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS HELL A STATE OF MIND, OR A PLACE? (AND WE DON'T MEAN TEXAS IN
AUGUST)
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When you live in Texas, where temperatures often reach higher
than 100 degrees, the idea of a fiery hell isn't all that bizarre.
</P>
<P>
   I grew up with outdoor summertime revivals in Texas, where the
visiting evangelist was expected to terrorize us with sermons about
the possibility of being cast into a pit filled with fire and
brimstone.
</P>
<P>
   Now, few pastors talk about hell. Even its existence is being
disputed. How could a loving God make us suffer eternally in a
blazing furnace?
</P>
<P>
   People who don't like to think about hell as a fiery fate likely
took some solace recently when Pope John Paul II gave a message
from the Vatican saying that hell is a spiritual state, not a
physical place. It is ``the state of those who freely and
definitively separate themselves from God,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   I was a little surprised by the pope's message. Some of the art
treasures of the Vatican depict a very literal, torturous place
called hell.
</P>
<P>
   When I visited the Vatican last year with some other religion
reporters, we had a private tour of the Sistine Chapel and
Michelangelo's famous masterpieces.
</P>
<P>
   We had time to linger in that great room and craned our necks
looking at the paintings on that magnificent ceiling. Among them
were depictions of the biblical creation story.
</P>
<P>
   On the front wall of the chapel were the most graphic visions of
hell I had ever seen. Wide-eyed figures were being pulled down into
hell. They were besieged by demons biting them on the heels.
</P>
<P>
   As they went downward, others with beatific smiles were
ascending into heaven.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those old-time Texas evangelists, I'm sure, would have
loved to have had copies of Michelangelo's scenes of hell to go
with their sermons.
</P>
<P>
   As might be expected, many evangelicals do not agree with Pope
John Paul's view that hell is a spiritual state and not a literal
place.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pope's denial of the traditional Christian understanding
of hell is one more step in a progressive rejection of the very
real and very horrible picture of hell revealed in the Bible,''
wrote Albert Mohler in a column for Religion News Service.
</P>
<P>
   He quoted polls consistently indicating that most Americans
believe in heaven. A high percentage believe they will also end up
in heaven. Few believe in hell. Almost none think they will be
going to hell.
</P>
<P>
   Blame it on American optimism.
</P>
<P>
   Mohler, the conservative president of Southern Baptist
Theological Seminary in Louisville, Ky., is right when he says that
most people today simply joke about hell. We speak about
``air-conditioning'' the place.
</P>
<P>
   But it is a serious theological subject.
</P>
<P>
   Those who see hell as fiery place of suffering argue that Jesus
talked about a burning hell many times in the New Testament.
</P>
<P>
   Mohler, for example, refers to Mark 9:44-47, where Jesus was
giving a message that I hope wasn't intended to be taken literally.
</P>
<P>
   As he exhorts humans to turn from sin, Jesus states: ``If thy
foot offend thee, cut it off; it is better to enter halt in life,
than having two feet to be cast into hell, into the fire that never
shall be quenched.''
</P>
<P>
   The pope's view of hell differs only slightly from the
definition of hell in the Catholic Dictionary, which says hell is
``the place and state of eternal punishment for the fallen angels
and human beings who died deliberately estranged from the love of
God. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``The punishment of hell is eternal as declared by Christ in his
prediction of the last day. ... The existence of hell is consistent
with divine justice since God respects human freedom and those who
are lost actually condemn themselves by resistance to the grace of
God.''
</P>
<P>
   So what is hell?
</P>
<P>
   I'm following the lead of a friend who said she doesn't know
whether hell is an actual place or a spiritual state of suffering.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't intend to ever find out, either,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Jones is religion editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7707, or e-mail:
jimjones(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
