<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990830.0188 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 13:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4380 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-DYING-HNS &LR;      08-30 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DYING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOO BUSY TO WORRY ABOUT DEATH 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DALE O'REILLEY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEDFORD, N.J. _ We Americans take dying much too seriously.
Death is serious, but dying is just a step on the way, a place
where you can choose, by the way you think, to be very much alive.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, once other people know you're dying, they think
they have to say things like, ``I'm so sorry,'' when what you
really wish they would do is tell you a good joke.
</P>
<P>
   But most people are either concerned about being appropriate or
so afraid of the idea of death that they avoid the subject by
avoiding you.
</P>
<P>
   So there you are, dying, with all this time on your hands. Time
to kill (joke). And no one is quite sure what to do about, or with,
you.
</P>
<P>
   I was told eight years ago that I had ALS (amyothrophic lateral
sclerosis, also known as Lou Gehrig's disease) and that it is
incurable, untreatable and always fatal. I knew I had to find a new
way of thinking about life and death, or I would go crazy before I
ever actually died.
</P>
<P>
   My first idea was a flop. I asked for a referral to a
psychotherapist. I'm not sure if the problem was her inexperience
or my expectations. What I asked is that she teach me how to change
my thoughts so I wouldn't dwell on the negative.
</P>
<P>
   When I was depressed, I wanted to be able to get over it and be
calm, if not happy. Unfortunately, it's not that easy. Elizabeth
Kubler-Ross, in her classic book, ``On Death and Dying,'' told us
the five stages of loss or grieving were: anger, denial,
bargaining, depression and acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   I had to move through those stages, or something like them,
before jumping right to acceptance. Along the way, I had to get rid
of a lot more than negative thoughts. I had to change my whole way
of thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Time. One of the first things I gave up after going on a
ventilator six years ago was my watch. The exact time was
irrelevant. Before ALS it was always ``time'' for something ... to
get up, go to work or a meeting.
</P>
<P>
   I'm a journalist; there were always deadlines. Now I think about
time in more general terms ... the season, or when my husband will
be home. I don't make plans too far in advance.
</P>
<P>
   However, I do have infinite time on any given day for doing and
thinking about just what I feel like.
</P>
<P>
   Image. I used to think about my looks. I wanted to look
professional yet feminine. That meant makeup, styled hair, business
suits and pantyhose without runs. Now, out of necessity, my hair is
cut short and glasses replaced contact lens. I gave away all my
clothes and live in T-shirts with shorts or sweat pants. Makeup
went because I have a horror of ending up with blue eye shadow,
pink circles of blush and crooked lipstick. In fact, I stopped
looking in mirrors, an easy way to stop wasting thoughts on your
looks.
</P>
<P>
   Jean-Dominique Bauby, in his wonderful memoir, ``The Diving Bell
and the Butterfly,'' wrote that if he had to drool (he had suffered
a crippling stroke), ``let it be on cashmere.'' I drool constantly
because I can't swallow. I had to give up silk dresses, belts and
high heels, but every cool evening, I'm wrapped in a luxurious
cashmere shawl, given to me by my husband.
</P>
<P>
   Work. My last boss was insane. He snuck into the office after
everyone had gone home to read our mail and leave scribbled notes
on scraps of paper. He bugged our phones and saved whole rooms full
of old magazines.
</P>
<P>
   I don't have to work for or with psychos any more. Now I write
when and if I feel like it. When I wake in the morning, I think
about who and what I want to write, for as long as I want to.
</P>
<P>
   I've met many people who, once disabled, don't know what to do
with themselves. I've met others who have started whole new
careers, and one who happily announced he'd always wanted to be ``a
couch potato.'' Now he is. It's all how you think about it.
</P>
<P>
   Faith. I was raised as a Congregationalist, like my Puritan
ancestors. Somewhere around college I lost my belief in religion
and stopped thinking about God.
</P>
<P>
   When I was diagnosed with ALS, I envied people of faith. They
are able to believe there is a reason for their affliction and that
when they die, they will go to a better place. I think about
religion a lot. I've tried reciting remembered Bible verses,
reading books on spiritism, praying with friends. A good friend
brought a healer/medium all the way from Brazil to help me. Was his
failure my lack of faith or his inability? Faith isn't something
you can think into existence.
</P>
<P>
   Family and friends. When I became seriously disabled by my ALS,
I'm not sure what amazed me more: the people who disappeared from
my life, or the ones who found me and became part of my life.
</P>
<P>
   My husband frequently reminds me to be thankful for the people
who are here for us and stop obsessing about the ones who are not.
We've had to open our home, 24 hours a day, to nurses.
</P>
<P>
   They, and their families, are now our family. My life is in
their hands, and yet this wouldn't work unless we were friends.
I've had to redefine friendship. I e-mail dozens of people I'll
never meet, many with, or touched by, ALS. We support, advise and
encourage each other. We send jokes and laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the people who have just appeared ... the lady
who helped me find switches, the man who built me a special table
for my computer, the reporter who wrote a series on me, the
neighbors who help me shop and wrap Christmas presents ... and
stayed. All are people who never knew me before ALS.
</P>
<P>
   One old friend asked me what I do when I get bored. ``Bored?'' I
e-mailed back. ``I don't have time to get bored. I have people to
write, books to read, music to listen to, so much to think about.''
</P>
<P>
   The critic Randall Jarrell described Walt Whitman as someone who
wrote of ``the tears of things, and the joy of things, and the
truth beneath either tears or joy.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, that's something worth infinite time and thought.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dale O'Reilley is a contributing columnist to the San Francisco
Examiner.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
