<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOUISIANACAUCUS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOUISIANA GOP DETERMINED TO HOLD FIRST '00 ELECTION CAUCUS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JAY ROOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BATON ROUGE, La. _ For GOP presidential candidates who have
grown tired of pork chops and county fairs, the Louisiana
Republican Party is offering up a spicy alternative to Iowa's
``first in the nation'' caucus.
</P>
<P>
   For a mere $5,000 entry fee, candidates can get a break from the
heartland hoopla by going deep into the heart of Cajun country _
where GOP officials are vowing to host the first caucus of the 2000
election even if it means they have to hold it at Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   The party's drive for a slice of the national spotlight is
contributing to a more compact and early presidential primary race,
likely to be decided by early March, months before the summer
nominating convention.
</P>
<P>
   With its reputation for favoring social conservatives, the
Louisiana caucus is not expected to draw mainstream candidates such
as Gov. George W. Bush and former Red Cross director Elizabeth
Dole, though they haven't officially ruled anything out.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the caucus system is not open, and if the rules are fuzzy,
and if it's hard to find places where people can vote, I think I'm
going to shy away,'' Bush said. ``If it's an open caucus where
people can participate, I'll participate. Right now, it's hard to
tell what the rules are. There's no date, there's no rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, other hopefuls on the far right are organizing early
and hoping the contest will give them a ``bump'' going into the
Iowa caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   Or, suggest the experts, maybe it will bump somebody from the
race and narrow the field.
</P>
<P>
   That's what happened to Sen. Phil Gramm of Texas in 1996.
Conservative talk show host Pat Buchanan took on Gramm with an
under-the-radar, grass-roots campaign and walked away with a
majority of the 21 delegates up for grabs.
</P>
<P>
   ``My view is you're going to have a conservative elimination
contest down here,'' said Jeff Crouere, a former executive director
of the state Republican Party and now co-host of ``Politically
Speaking,'' a New Orleans talk radio show.
</P>
<P>
   Although Buchanan still has a loyal following in Louisiana,
conservative activist Gary Bauer and wealthy magazine publisher
Steve Forbes appear to be the most competitive so far.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes has snapped up Buchanan's 1996 Louisiana campaign chief,
a former director of the state GOP and the former head of the state
Christian Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   And Bauer, the only candidate with an official campaign
headquarters in the state, has tapped a network of church leaders
and activists and is relying on support from some of the 30,000
Louisiana followers of ``Focus on the Family,'' a conservative
radio program with which Bauer has been associated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody beats Bauer in terms of the amount of time spent in the
state,'' Crouere said. ``Forbes has the money, like Gramm did. But
Bauer has the grass-roots support. It may be sort of money vs. the
grass roots.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes spokesman Greg Mueller dismissed the comparison between
Gramm and Forbes, saying the Texas senator fell prey to his own
high expectations. When he didn't live up to them, he abruptly
ended his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes will be competitive in Louisiana while still respecting
the traditional role that Iowa plays, Mueller said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tradition holds for us,'' he said. ``It's the top three
candidates that come out of the Iowa caucuses. One of them will win
the nomination and potentially the presidency. ... Louisiana is an
opportunity for the more niche candidates.''
</P>
<P>
   For some candidates in the top tier, participating in Louisiana
could be an unnecessary risk. Former Sen. Bob Dole ignored the
state in 1996 and still won the GOP nomination, though not the
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   This year, his wife is running, but she has not made a decision
about whether to participate in the Louisiana caucus, a spokesman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Sen. John McCain does not consider Louisiana to be ``one
of his priority states right now,'' said Bryan Wagner, a McCain
ally and longtime Republican leader in the state. A McCain
spokesman in Washington said the senator has been to Louisiana at
least three times this year but has made no decision about whether
he'll participate in the caucus.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Bush appears to be leaning against participating.
</P>
<P>
   His advisers are more blunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fixed. I can't recommend that he play,'' said Donald
Ensenat, a longtime friend and former roommate of Bush (and former
ambassador to Brunei) who is helping the governor raise money in
Louisiana. ``I'd sure like him to play, because if it was a fair
election, (Bush) would win.''
</P>
<P>
   Ensenat cited a meeting that party officials called about a
month ago to discuss the caucus. He said the Bush campaign got no
notice of the gathering.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's hogwash,'' said state Rep. Tony Perkins, who is running
Bauer's Louisiana campaign. Perkins, who attended the meeting, said
Bush is not entering the Louisiana caucus because Republican Party
Chairman Mike Francis did not commit to him at a February meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Scott McClellan acknowledged that Bush talked
with Francis about the caucus during a winter visit with Louisiana
Gov. Mike Foster, but he said he was not aware of ``any discussions
of support.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, the impending absence of several major
contenders in Louisiana has been cause for joy in Iowa, where
Democratic and Republican party officials guard the
first-in-the-nation label like a family heirloom.
</P>
<P>
   As long as the national news media and top candidates aren't
acting like the Louisiana caucus is a big deal, neither is Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure their event is technically a caucus,'' said Kayne
Robinson, chairman of the Iowa state GOP. ``It probably does not
cause us to change our date, in any event.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Iowa's caucus date has been set for Feb. 7, officials
there expect to move it to Jan. 31 to ensure that the state stages
its event one week before the New Hampshire primary, now set for
Feb. 8.
</P>
<P>
   That has prompted Louisiana Republicans to fixate on Jan. 22 as
the date for their caucus, meaning that it would be held a week
before Iowa. But in the event that Iowa moves its caucus to an
earlier date, Louisiana has vowed to follow suit, even if that
means backing into 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why shouldn't we be the first?'' said Connie Chittom, deputy
chairwoman of the Louisiana Republican Party. ``I don't think Iowa
should be afraid of us. We're just another state having a caucus.
It's not going to take anything away from them, except they want to
be first. So do we.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
