<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 13:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4399 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i BC-CAYMAN-FALL-$ADV21-CO     08-30 1838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAYMAN-FALL-$ADV21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    VISITING THE CAYMAN ISLANDS IN THE FAMILY WAY
 &HT;    1300&AMP;ADDS
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (t) Travel categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sat., Aug. 21 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By RICK CHRISTIE 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GEORGE TOWN, Cayman Islands _ We needed this family vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Four months of shuffling correspondents throughout the Eastern
Hemisphere to report on the bombing of Yugoslavia and its aftermath
had me cursing at the mere mention of the name ``Milosevic.''
Worse, my family was leaving me notes in lieu of conversation.
</P>
<P>
   To re-connect we came here, to the Cayman Islands.
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, this gorgeous three-island chain may be one of
the best kept secrets for family vacations in the Caribbean
off-season _ generally the summer and early fall.
</P>
<P>
   Flights, car rentals and rooms can be found at reasonable
prices. Restaurants run the gamut: from expensive to affordable,
from authentic island cuisine to Pizza Hut. The primary
entertainment (read that, the beach) is free.
</P>
<P>
   And there are a few things you can't put a price on: No theme
park crowds. No panhandlers. A low crime rate.
</P>
<P>
   For about what it costs to jet a family of five down for a week
of Disney or Universal Studios, we treated ourselves to turquoise
blue water, sugar white beach sand, and marine life in spectacular
colors both below and above water.
</P>
<P>
   Although we visited this summer, the fall has an added bonus:
Pirates Week, when Caymanians abandon their British reserve with
parades, costume parties and treasure hunts. The October festival
is one of only two main events all year; the other being the
Carnival-style Batabano holiday in April.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, we have three young daughters. My wife, Klemie, took
them down a week ahead of me to visit family on the main island,
Grand Cayman. The ``oohs,'' ``aahs'' and ``whoas'' that began
flowing from the girls even as they gazed out the plane window
before landing _ 2-year-old Elisabeth included _ was worth the
exhausting, frustrating, taxing trip down. (I'm still paying for
that one.)
</P>
<P>
   By the time I arrived the following week, visiting the beach had
become a daily routine for Klemie and the girls. They'd even staked
out a semi-private, partially shaded piece of it called ``Our
Spot.''
</P>
<P>
   Even hundreds of yards from shore, the water is crystal clear
and rarely deeper than 10 feet, allowing the kids to do a little
shallow-water snorkeling. If it wasn't for the large coral rocks
and little fish swimming around your feet, you'd think you were in
a big warm swimming pool.
</P>
<P>
   There was a downside: Tearing the girls away from the beach also
became a daily routine. This was primarily a problem with
Elisabeth, who could not fathom why she couldn't live in the water
and thus, had to be carried away kicking and screaming most days.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and did I mention the sand? There is sand _ lots and lots of
sand. It's everywhere. It's on you, your clothes, in your car and
if you're not careful, your food.
</P>
<P>
   Three little girls provide a further challenge with sand. It
gets in their hair. Well, actually they tend to pour it in one
another's hair. I was never able to figure out the genesis of this
ritual. But given that I have sworn a vow of restraint against
meddling in our little girls' ebony locks, my beautiful wife was
forced to take up this challenge alone.
</P>
<P>
   I did mention that my wife is beautiful, right?
</P>
<P>
   Thank goodness there's a lot more to Grand Cayman, the main
island, than the beach. It remains environmentally pristine,
despite the continued incursion of big-name hotels, restaurants and
shops. But overall, the island had changed noticeably from the last
time Klemie and I visited 11 years ago. . . alone. . . with no kids
. . . oh, sorry I drifted there for a moment.
</P>
<P>
   On this trip, we rented a car and spent the majority of our time
exploring: everything from sights on and off the beaten path to
character-filled shops to local restaurants. (We had five rolls of
film to prove it.)
</P>
<P>
   Every morning, we ate at our hotel, the Sleep Inn. The hotel
cost included a daily complimentary breakfast buffet. Not bad for
US$140 a night.
</P>
<P>
   Elisabeth's second birthday gave us a reason to celebrate one
evening by trying out one of Grand Cayman's nicest restaurants, The
Wharf. The setting is gorgeous, allowing you to eat in an
air-conditioned veranda dining room or on a seaside patio. We chose
the latter.
</P>
<P>
   But while the ladies preferred the safety of foods they've
tasted before, I had turtle steak _ a beef-like delicacy in the
Cayman Islands.
</P>
<P>
   The night's entertainment involved hand-feeding tuna to some
massive, hungry tarpon off The Wharf's small dock. Rachel, our
adventurous 10-year-old, decided to give it a shot. But 5-year-old
Taylor thought better of it after a closer view revealed that she
was smaller than the fish. Elisabeth? Well, she was too busy
tearing into her birthday chocolate mousse to care.
</P>
<P>
   We tried another authentic restaurant called Ocean View at White
Hall Bay, located on the waterfront, downtown _ and down the price
scale. It's less formal, but the food was just as good, and with
big portions. The charming old hostess who greeted us was also the
cook and waitress. I don't think we got better service or food
anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   But we certainly got worse. As our exploring took us from Grand
Cayman's West Bay to the East End area, we found hole-in-wall dives
that reminded us that just because it's authentic, doesn't mean
it's good.
</P>
<P>
   That goes for island shops, as well. There are plenty of places
where you can buy T-shirts, jewelry, shells and cigars _ duty free.
And ``50% Off'' signs are everywhere, a result of the off-season.
Most of the major shops are in or near downtown. But there are
others to be found exploring the island; including shops that
people have set up out of there homes.
</P>
<P>
   Wherever you decide to shop, don't be in a big hurry. We saved
most of our shopping for the last couple of days and that was
plenty of time. And don't forget, the Cayman Islands are pretty
relaxed and reserved. Most shops close at 5 p.m. on Saturday and
stay closed on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The rate of exchange for cash is US$1 equals CI$.80. Don't sweat
trying to figure it in your head. Everyone from the fisherman
selling the day's catch on the dock to the Tiffany's jeweler can
figure it for you _ and you can be pretty sure they won't try to
stiff you. I took the easy route and exchanged much of my cache of
U.S. dollars for C.I. dollars when I first arrived.
</P>
<P>
   It was a good thing, too. You don't want to be bogged down
counting coins when you're listening to interesting characters like
Carey Hurlstone, the owner of Dr. Carey's Black Coral Clinic, spin
one of his island tales. A burly guy with a booming voice, ``Mr.
Carey'' _ he likes to be called that _ prefers to walk around
shirtless, showing off the myriad tattoos covering his weathered
skin. He also was one of the many native Caymanians we ran into who
was either somehow related to my wife or knew one of her many
relatives here.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Carey polishes and crafts black coral into jewelry, one of
the islands' best-known traditions. He mesmerized my daughters with
stories of acquiring the precious commodity from the sea. And he
showed off other unusual items in his shop. (He owns giant shark's
teeth and the largest collection of marbles I've ever seen.)
</P>
<P>
   There were, of course, places we visited that were more on the
tourist path. Among them are two great nature and history stops.
One is Queen Elizabeth II Botanic Park, which sports all of
Cayman's flora and fauna in living color. The other is Pedro St.
James _ known locally as Pedro's Castle _ which touts itself as the
``birthplace of democracy in the Cayman Islands.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of nature, we got up close and personal with huge green
sea turtles at the world's only turtle farm. The girls loved this
because they saw how turtles go from eggs to hatchlings and grow to
weigh a quarter-ton or more. There's even a tank where they picked
up and held smaller turtles.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Another world-famous tourist spot is Hell, a tiny community here
so-named for its rugged surreal pointed rock formation near town.
It has learned to trade on its name, and no one is better at
exploiting it than Ivan Farrington, the owner of the Devil's
Hangout Gift Shop who dresses as none other than the devil himself.
Farrington was actually very nice. He gave the girls a bunch of
postcards from his shop. He gave Klemie a peck on the cheek. And he
gave me . . . well, hell.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, Mr. Farrington ,you've got an interesting place here,'' I
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to turn it into paradise but business went to hell,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Uh, OK. So what kind of town is it,'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a hell of a town,'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``Uh-huh. How warm do you think it is today,'' I asked, looking
to change the subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hot as hell,'' he answered.
</P>
<P>
   ``All right, I think that's enough. We're heading out now , Mr.
Farrington,'' I said, exasperated. ``Take care.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Go to Hell!'' he said, smiling and waving.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Finally, I found time to go fishing. Ever since I'd arrived I'd
been trying to get together with a guy named ``Red'' Smith, who
worked at our hotel. He was also distantly related to my wife, and
offered to take me out on his little 12-footer to teach me ``line''
fishing _ the popular way natives fish here sans rod and reel.
</P>
<P>
   We hooked up the day before the family was set to leave. Klemie
and the girls set off for the beach one last time. Smith and I set
off from a little cove in the North Sound with his Yamaha outboard
motor pushing us about two miles out over beautiful green water
that was clear enough to see the coral-covered bottom.
</P>
<P>
   I got the hang of line fishing quickly enough to haul in more
than a dozen small grunts and grouper in a little more than an
hour. The problem came when we tried to leave. The motor wouldn't
start. I guess I should have known this could be a problem when I
first saw that it was held together by duct tape.
</P>
<P>
   As I turned toward what I thought was land (and noticed how far
away it was), I gleaned that the water was getting choppy. It
occurred to me that we could be getting back rather late.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, what do we do,'' I asked, straining to remain calm as
screaming came to mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah man. You wanted adventure, eh,'' he said with a big
smile. ``Grab that oar, man. We'll be there before you know it.''
</P>
<P>
   We were lucky the current was with us. It took a good hour and a
half, but we made it back just after nightfall. We passed the time
talking about everything under the setting sun: fishing, politics,
marriage, children.
</P>
<P>
   But not once did I ever hear the words ``Kosovo'' or ``the
Balkans.'' That's what I call a family vacation.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-99 1327EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990830.0191 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 13:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4400 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i BC-CAYMAN-SUMMER-$ADV21-     08-30 1870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAYMAN-SUMMER-$ADV21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    VISITING THE CAYMAN ISLANDS, IN THE FAMILY WAY
 &HT;    1200&AMP;ADDS
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (t) Travel categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sat., Aug. 21 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By RICK CHRISTIE 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GEORGE TOWN, Cayman Islands _ We needed this family vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Four months of shuffling correspondents throughout the Eastern
Hemisphere to report on the bombing of Yugoslavia and its aftermath
had me in hives at the mere mention of the name ``Milosevic.''
Worse, my family was leaving me notes in lieu of conversation.
</P>
<P>
   To re-connect we came here, to the Cayman Islands.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a summer vacation? What about Disney or Universal
Studios,'' a friend asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not if I want to avoid hearing the words 'Kosovo' or
'Balkans,''' I answered.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what about the kids,'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``What? Turquoise blue water, sugar white beach sand, and marine
life in spectacular colors both below and above water,'' I replied.
``This will be big fun.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But what about the cost,'' he queried, sounding a bit more
perplexed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the off-season,'' I said. ``Flights, car rentals and
rooms are more reasonable. Restaurants run the gamut: from
expensive to affordable, from authentic island cuisine to Pizza
Hut. The primary entertainment (read that, the beach) is free.
</P>
<P>
   ``And there are a few things you can't put a price on: No theme
park crowds. No panhandlers. A low crime rate.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, as my wife Klemie noted to me later, the ``oohs,''
``aahs'' and ``whoas'' that began flowing from our three daughters
as they gazed longingly out the plane window on the trip over _
2-year-old Elisabeth included _ were worth the exhausting,
frustrating, taxing trip down. (I'm still paying for that one.)
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Optional trim starts here.)
</P>
<P>
   It was a situation made more trying by Delta Airlines' flight
problems, and the fact that my wife _ she grew up here _ decided to
fly down a week earlier with the girls to spend time with her
parents. Let's just say that it was so bad that my four favorite
ladies had to switch to two other airlines to get to Grand Cayman,
while their luggage eventually showed up on Delta about 12 hours
after their trip began.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Optional trim ends here.)
</P>
<P>
   By the time I arrived the following week, visiting the beach had
become a daily routine for Klemie and the girls. They'd even staked
out a semi-private, partially shaded piece of it called ``Our
Spot.''
</P>
<P>
   Even hundreds of yards from shore, the water is crystal clear
and rarely deeper than 10 feet, allowing the kids to do a little
shallow-water snorkeling. If it wasn't for the large coral rocks
and little fish swimming around your feet, you'd think you were in
a big warm swimming pool.
</P>
<P>
   There was a downside: Tearing the girls away from the beach also
became a daily routine. This was primarily a problem with
Elisabeth, who could not fathom why she couldn't live in the water
and thus, had to be carried away kicking and screaming most days.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and did I mention the sand? There is sand _ lots and lots of
sand. It's everywhere. It's on you, your clothes, in your car and
if you're not careful, your food.
</P>
<P>
   Three little girls provide a further challenge with sand. It
gets in their hair. Well, actually they tend to pour it in one
another's hair. I was never able to figure out the genesis of this
ritual. But given that I have sworn a vow of restraint against
meddling in our little girls' ebony locks, my beautiful wife was
forced to take up this challenge alone.
</P>
<P>
   I did mention that my wife is beautiful, right?
</P>
<P>
   Thank goodness there's a lot more to Grand Cayman, the main
island, than the beach. It remains environmentally pristine,
despite the continued incursion of big-name hotels, restaurants and
shops. But overall, the island had changed noticeably from the last
time Klemie and I visited 11 years ago. . . alone. . . with no kids
. . . oh, sorry I drifted there for a moment.
</P>
<P>
   On this trip, we rented a car and spent the majority of our time
exploring: everything from sights on and off the beaten path to
character-filled shops to local restaurants. (We had five rolls of
film to prove it.)
</P>
<P>
   Every morning, we ate at our hotel, the Sleep Inn. The hotel
cost included a daily complimentary breakfast buffet. Not bad for
US$140 a night.
</P>
<P>
   Elisabeth's second birthday gave us a reason to celebrate one
evening by trying out one of Grand Cayman's nicest restaurants, The
Wharf. The setting is gorgeous, allowing you to eat in an
air-conditioned veranda dining room or on a seaside patio. We chose
the latter.
</P>
<P>
   But while the ladies preferred the safety of foods they've
tasted before, I had turtle steak _ a beef-like delicacy in the
Cayman Islands.
</P>
<P>
   The night's entertainment involved hand-feeding tuna to some
massive, hungry tarpon off The Wharf's small dock. Rachel, our
adventurous 10-year-old, decided to give it a shot. But 5-year-old
Taylor thought better of it after a closer view revealed that she
was smaller than the fish. Elisabeth? Well, she was too busy
tearing into her birthday chocolate mousse to care.
</P>
<P>
   We tried another authentic restaurant called Ocean View at White
Hall Bay, located on the waterfront, downtown _ and down the price
scale. It's less formal, but the food was just as good, and with
big portions. The charming old hostess who greeted us was also the
cook and waitress. I don't think we got better service or food
anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   But we certainly got worse. As our exploring took us from Grand
Cayman's West Bay to the East End area, we found hole-in-wall dives
that reminded us that just because it's authentic, doesn't mean
it's good.
</P>
<P>
   That goes for island shops, as well. There are plenty of places
where you can buy T-shirts, jewelry, shells and cigars _ duty free.
And ``50% Off'' signs are everywhere, a result of the off-season.
Most of the major shops are in or near downtown. But there are
others to be found exploring the island; including shops that
people have set up out of there homes.
</P>
<P>
   Wherever you decide to shop, don't be in a big hurry. We saved
most of our shopping for the last couple of days and that was
plenty of time. And don't forget, the Cayman Islands are pretty
relaxed and reserved. Most shops close at 5 p.m. on Saturday and
stay closed on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The rate of exchange for cash is US$1 equals CI$.80. Don't sweat
trying to figure it in your head. Everyone from the fisherman
selling the day's catch on the dock to the Tiffany's jeweler can
figure it for you _ and you can be pretty sure they won't try to
stiff you. I took the easy route and exchanged much of my cache of
U.S. dollars for C.I. dollars when I first arrived.
</P>
<P>
   It was a good thing, too. You don't want to be bogged down
counting coins when you're listening to interesting characters like
Carey Hurlstone, the owner of Dr. Carey's Black Coral Clinic, spin
one of his island tales. A burly guy with a booming voice, ``Mr.
Carey'' _ he likes to be called that _ prefers to walk around
shirtless, showing off the myriad tattoos covering his weathered
skin. He also was one of the many native Caymanians we ran into who
was either somehow related to my wife or knew one of her many
relatives here.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Carey polishes and crafts black coral into jewelry, one of
the islands' best-known traditions. He mesmerized my daughters with
stories of acquiring the precious commodity from the sea. And he
showed off other unusual items in his shop. (He owns giant shark's
teeth and the largest collection of marbles I've ever seen.)
</P>
<P>
   There were, of course, places we visited that were more on the
tourist path. Among them are two great nature and history stops.
One is Queen Elizabeth II Botanic Park, which sports all of
Cayman's flora and fauna in living color. The other is Pedro St.
James _ known locally as Pedro's Castle _ which touts itself as the
``birthplace of democracy in the Cayman Islands.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of nature, we got up close and personal with huge green
sea turtles at the world's only turtle farm. The girls loved this
because they saw how turtles go from eggs to hatchlings and grow to
weigh a quarter-ton or more. There's even a tank where they picked
up and held smaller turtles.
</P>
<P>
   Another world-famous tourist spot is Hell, a tiny community here
so-named for its rugged surreal pointed rock formation near town.
It has learned to trade on its name, and no one is better at
exploiting it than Ivan Farrington, the owner of the Devil's
Hangout Gift Shop who dresses as none other than the devil himself.
Farrington was actually very nice. He gave the girls a bunch of
postcards from his shop. He gave Klemie a peck on the cheek. And he
gave me . . . well, hell.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, Mr. Farrington ,you've got an interesting place here,'' I
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to turn it into paradise but business went to hell,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Uh, OK. So what kind of town is it,'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a hell of a town,'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``Uh-huh. How warm do you think it is today,'' I asked, looking
to change the subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hot as hell,'' he answered.
</P>
<P>
   ``All right, I think that's enough. We're heading out now , Mr.
Farrington,'' I said, exasperated. ``Take care.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Go to Hell!'' he said, smiling and waving.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Finally, I found time to go fishing. Ever since I'd arrived I'd
been trying to get together with a guy named ``Red'' Smith, who
worked at our hotel. He was also distantly related to my wife, and
offered to take me out on his little 12-footer to teach me ``line''
fishing _ the popular way natives fish here sans rod and reel.
</P>
<P>
   We hooked up the day before the family was set to leave. Klemie
and the girls set off for the beach one last time. Smith and I set
off from a little cove in the North Sound with his Yamaha outboard
motor pushing us about two miles out over beautiful green water
that was clear enough to see the coral-covered bottom.
</P>
<P>
   I got the hang of line fishing quickly enough to haul in more
than a dozen small grunts and grouper in a little more than an
hour. The problem came when we tried to leave. The motor wouldn't
start. I guess I should have known this could be a problem when I
first saw that it was held together by duct tape.
</P>
<P>
   As I turned toward what I thought was land (and noticed how far
away it was), I gleaned that the water was getting choppy. It
occurred to me that we could be getting back rather late.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, what do we do,'' I asked, straining to remain calm as
screaming came to mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah man. You wanted adventure, eh,'' he said with a big
smile. ``Grab that oar, man. We'll be there before you know it.''
</P>
<P>
   We were lucky the current was with us. It took a good hour and a
half, but we made it back just after nightfall. We passed the time
talking about everything under the setting sun: fishing, politics,
marriage, children.
</P>
<P>
   But not once did I ever hear the words ``Kosovo'' or ``the
Balkans.'' That's what I call a family vacation.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
