<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4406 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-CAYMAN-TRAVEL-$ADV21-     08-30 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAYMAN-TRAVEL-$ADV21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DIVERS, HONEYMOONERS, FAMILIES: Relaxing Cayman Islands Style
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (t) Travel categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sat., Aug. 21 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By RICK CHRISTIE 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GEORGE TOWN, Cayman Islands _ Divers. Honeymooners. Families.
</P>
<P>
   Encircled in powdery white beaches that seem to float calmly in
clear turquoise blue waters, the three islands that make up this
Caribbean chain _ Grand Cayman, Little Cayman and Cayman Brac _
have been expanding in the type of tourist they attract. For many
of the same reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want a little hustle and bustle with your rest and
relaxation, Grand Cayman won't let you down,'' according to
``Fodor's 99 Caribbean'' guidebook. ``If it's pure R&AMP;R you seek,
you'll find pockets of sweet seclusion, especially on Cayman Brac
and Little Cayman.''
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Columbus, on his fourth Caribbean voyage, sighted
the islands in 1503 and noted the large turtle population in the
surrounding waters. He named the islands Las Tortugas _ ``The
Turtles'' in Spanish _ but over the next 100 years the name was
changed to ``Caymanas'' or Caymans, derived from the Carib Indian
word for crocodile.
</P>
<P>
   This tiny group of islands has always seemed to hold a special
place in the heart of some wayward group _ from the adventurers who
made them a regular stop to load up on turtle meat, to the pirates
rumored to favor the coves of the sparsely populated islands, to
the divers who have made the Caymans one of the world's top diving
destinations.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the Cayman Islands _ they are actually the tips of
underwater mountains _ are clearly best-known as a divers'
paradise. They are surrounded by shallow reefs and then sheer walls
that drop off thousands of feet to the ocean floor, making diving
here both unique and exciting.
</P>
<P>
   There are literally hundreds of places to dive and scores of
professionals to dive with. To be sure, there are resorts catering
to divers. But any hotel on the islands worth its salt offers scuba
diving and snorkeling excursions to its patrons.
</P>
<P>
   A favorite, well-known site is Little Cayman's Bloody Bay Wall,
rated the third-best dive site in the world by the late Jacques
Cousteau. Its drop-off begins at 18 feet, then plunges sharply to
1,200 feet. The array of coral, sponges and fish of various shapes,
sizes and colors in the coastal water is nothing short of
spectacular.
</P>
<P>
   As stories of gliding through these waters spread, however, the
attractiveness of the Caymans grows with young honeymooners and
older couples. From jewelry and cigar shopping to fine dining to a
simple evening stroll on a quiet beach, the islands _ particularly,
Grand Cayman _ offer the perfect romantic background.
</P>
<P>
   The Cayman Islands Tourism Ministry has seized upon, and sought
to enhance this image with its ``Relax, Cayman Islands Style,''
advertising campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Couples can be seen all over doing just that _ relaxing. Some do
it by swimming with the stingrays at Stingray City. Some dine under
the stars on the seaside patio at The Wharf restaurant here in
George Town. And some escape to the serene isolation of Cayman Brac
where they can hike a nature trail through a 180-acre parrot
reserve.
</P>
<P>
   It is activities like the latter, however, that are opening the
Caymans to yet another group _ families _ in the Caribbean
off-season (generally the summer and early fall).
</P>
<P>
   With airline flights, car rentals and hotel rooms offered at
reasonable prices, many families are finding the Caymans a relaxing
alternative to the harried theme park vacation. What's more, to go
along with the pricier restaurants, there are plenty of familiar
and affordable fast-food eateries.
</P>
<P>
   The primary entertainment (read that, the beach) is free.
</P>
<P>
   There's plenty more where that comes from. One of the best known
is Queen Elizabeth II Botanic Park, which sports all of Cayman's
flora and fauna in living color. Another is Pedro St. James _ known
locally as Pedro's Castle _ which touts itself as the ``birthplace
of democracy in the Cayman Islands.'' Both are great nature and
history stops. And the Cayman Turtle Farm allows kids to get up
close and personal with giant green sea turtles.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most important for families, however, is the safe
environment of the Caymans. Panhandling is illegal and the crime
rate is very low. And in the off-season, crowds are largely
nonexistent.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
