<HEADER>
A4407 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-TV-REVIEW-PARKERS-HNS     08-30 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-REVIEW-PARKERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MOESHA' SPINOFF DOESN'T MAKE THE GRADE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TIM GOODMAN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Give UPN credit for launching one of the few television shows
this season that has an African-American cast. Then subtract points
for airing yet another sitcom that is as predictable and rim-shot
rote as they come.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Parkers'' is a spinoff from one of UPN's longest-running
hits, ``Moesha.'' But any resemblance _ especially to quality _
ends there.
</P>
<P>
   Where ``Moesha'' has been about family, coming of age and the
various dramatic and comic moments that spring forth, ``The
Parkers'' is first and foremost an over-the-top sitcom. That it
tries to temper the cartoonish behavior with a life lesson or a
sweet hug just makes it all the more formulaic and dislikable.
</P>
<P>
   Countess Vaughn, who made a name for herself as the
wise-cracking friend on ``Moesha,'' continues her Kim Parker
character as she enters Santa Monica College. The hook, borrowed
from a ``Moesha'' plot line, is that her mother, Nikki (played by
stand-up comic Mo'Nique), who went back to high school after 18
years and finally earned her degree, is now so into higher learning
that she's coming along to college.
</P>
<P>
   That's it, really. ``The Parkers'' is about a mom who wants to
do the same thing as her daughter and ends up _ punch line after
punch line _ crowding her space. Then, when mom has gone too far _
by being too popular or too loud or attracted to the same men _
there's always a heartfelt mother-daughter make-up speech, and then
the two sassy sisters get back to business.
</P>
<P>
   One of the apparently humorous devices is to have mother and
daughter dress outrageously, to match their personalities. Both
also possess screeching voices that reach a fever pitch about every
five lines of the show _ but at least it temporarily knocks out the
laugh track.
</P>
<P>
   The jokes in ``The Parkers'' were baked from the same
cookie-cutter sitcom recipe that inhabits other sitcoms, as well.
It's the obvious setup-and-punch-line bit that's older than Milton
Berle's dad. At one point, Nikki says, ``College is just as I
imagined.'' Another character says, ``Hard?'' To which Nikki, in
that tired, you-go-girl smirk that dominates so many black sitcoms,
says, ``No, but the bodies on those young boys was.''
</P>
<P>
   In another scene, Kim says she's going to sign up for a
black-studies class. Says mom: ``Black studies? Isn't that like
taking Me 101?'' When the writers tire of that kind of hilarity,
they fall back on the exasperated daughter dealing with overbearing
mom, and the resulting refrain _ heard endlessly _ is: ``But why,
momma?'' And in that not-quite-endearing way that Vaughn has about
her.
</P>
<P>
   None of the charm and freshness of ``Moesha'' translates to
``The Parkers.'' The producers _ the same ones who built ``Moesha''
_ have opted for the effortless, old-school ways of unenlightened
comedy. Perhaps they had no real direction from the start, because
even though Vaughn was a scene-stealer in ``Moesha'' and long
rumored to get her own show, the initial title to this show was
``Mo'Nique,'' which probably didn't sit well with Vaughn. The two
barely looked at each other on a recent publicity tour, and Vaughn
ends up saying the straight lines most of the time.
</P>
<P>
   Not that it matters. ``The Parkers,'' as it stands now, is
nothing to be territorial about. Unless either of them thinks being
called the ``ghetto fabulous Doublemint twins'' is cause for
excitement.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Tim Goodman is the television critic for the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is goodman(at)examiner.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
