<HEADLINE>
BOOKS RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Places Left Unfinished at the Time of Creation'' by John
Phillip Santos (Viking, $24.95). A lyrical memoir of a life on both
sides of the Texas-Mexico border. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Flowers in the Dustbin: The Rise of Rock and Roll, 1947-1977''
by James Miller (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $26). A guided tour of the glory
days of the music that parents were never meant to like. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Wrack'' by James Bradley (Holt, $25). In this novel of
southern Australia, an archeologist looks for an ancient lost ship,
but finds a not-so-ancient body. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Painting Religion in Public: John Singer Sargent's `Triumph of
Religion' at the Boston Public Library'' by Sally M. Promey
(Princeton University Press, $45). A fascinating study of Sargent's
unfinished murals and of changing attitudes toward the display of
religious belief.
</P>
</TEXT>
