<DOCNO> NYT19990830.0199 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 13:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4412 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-LAST-LIFE-BOS &LR;      08-30 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-LAST-LIFE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HAUNTING NOVEL _ AND A FLIGHT FROM THE PAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GAIL CALDWELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
THE LAST LIFE 
By Claire Messud. Harcourt Brace. 352 pp. $24. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We tend to wear the past lightly in America, flaunting it when
it suits us and discarding it at the first sign of weight or
trouble. This gauzy memory is part of the American contract, or at
least its nebulous promise: The chains of history, having brought
so many to these shores, can always be cast off in the name of
becoming someone else. A lot of this is delusional poppycock, of
course _ as a society, we are both mired in class and family
origins and mesmerized by them _ but the dream is part of what
grants the American character its peculiar (some would say unreal)
optimism.
</P>
<P>
   One need only eavesdrop on a cafe conversation among European
students in Harvard Square to get a glimpse of an older world view,
where your life is bound inextricably by blood of family and
politics alike. Claire Messud's somber and luminescent novel
sustains this idea, using the hint and lure of America as a
contrasting color in its margins. Unfolding through the memories of
a young French-Algerian woman, Sagesse LaBasse, who has fled her
homeland for the equivocal anonymity of New York, ``The Last Life''
is the story of a family beholden to the past and nearly drowning
in its waves.
</P>
<P>
   This is Messud's second novel; her first, ``When the World Was
Steady,'' was a finalist for the PEN/Faulkner Award. Born in 1966,
she possesses a voice blessed with ruminative depth _ with the
knowledge that no action lives outside of memory, that the imprints
in sand are often more revealing than the step that left them
there. Such a sensibility is usually earned by years alone, and its
defining presence in ``The Last Life'' is what grants the novel its
heft as well as its haunting afterglow.
</P>
<P>
   Sagesse is in her 20s as she begins her story, ensconced in her
bookish lair near Columbia University, looking back on a few
critical years in the LaBasse family when the girl was 15. The clan
was ruled by the seamless tyranny of her grandfather, Jacques, a
self-starting patriarch who managed to build a hotel on the French
shores of the Mediterranean after fleeing Algeria's civil wars.
Nearly three decades later, Sagesse is a teenager hanging out at
the Hotel Bellevue's pool _ a girl who cares mostly about her
year-round bikini line and the boys who admire it. Her father,
Alexandre, is trapped in the shadows of Jacques; heir apparent to
his father's emotional tempests, he is also no match for his
strengths, and so languishes at the hotel waiting for the chance to
run it. His wife, Carol, is a mostly unhappy, displaced American _
a woman, now middle-aged, who fell for the romance of France and
Alex before she was old enough to see beyond their high-gloss
illusions. Her marriage into the LaBasses was cemented by the
births of Sagesse and then a son: Etienne, wonder-child and
tragedy, who, trapped too long in the birth canal, lives his life
in a wheelchair, profoundly mentally retarded.
</P>
<P>
   With his implicit contracts of duty and mystery, Etienne is in
some ways the emotional center of the family _ all its failings
writ large, all its possibilities for connection manifest in his
touch. Sagesse knows this, and her love for her brother is one of
the cornerstones of the novel. But the LaBasses possess other dark
legacies, less subtle than Etienne but ultimately more dangerous.
Jacques's deterioration is revealed before it is explained:
Infuriated by the gaggle of hotel teenagers who invade his swimming
pool each night, he finally fires a gun into their midst _ wounding
one, terrifying them all, and setting in motion the ruination of
the empire he tried to erect.
</P>
<P>
   LaBasse pere is arrested and eventually tried for his wild
assault, which also serves as a narrative apex from which to
explore the rest of the family's collective saga over the decades _
Jacques's emigration from his beautiful Algeria, on the verge of
upheaval; the journey of Alex as a teenaged boy, fleeing Algiers as
it fell; and bearing the corpse of his beloved grandmother. These
are extraordinary stories in and of themselves, and if they
sometimes feel disjointed within the larger span of the novel, they
also tend to float above it like shooting stars of history.
Sickened by her grandfather's actions, ostracized by her peers,
Sagesse takes brief refuge with her American relatives in New
England _ long enough to taste the sweet amnesia on this side of
the Atlantic, though too transient to escape the grievous sorrows
that await her at home.
</P>
<P>
   And in the future: ``The Last Life'' is a novel that draws its
structural core from time itself: from yesterday and tomorrow and
the stillness of the present, and the innumerable effects of each
upon the other. While this grants the novel some admirable
reflection, it can also overwhelm the here-and-now that any plot
requires with muddy speculation and self-conscious prose. Messud
may be Proustian in her temporal intentions, but some of her
sentences, too, are as long as Algeria's civil wars, and not always
conferred with the magic that made Proust's worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the voice that conveys this sad story _ one of deceits and
regrets, nighttime escapes and transcendent flights _ is remarkably
assured and self-aware. The horrifying indignities to which Etienne
is prone are captured in one breathtakingly awful comment from a
smiling relative: ``How tall _ or long _ or whatever, is he? You do
keep track, I imagine?'' At the other end of the spectrum is
Messud's stunningly apt description of a philosophical landscape
glimpsed by St. Augustine, then Camus, as ``the teetering flail of
the void gaped where God's safe shore had loomed.'' Messud has been
ambitious enough to go after that territory where memory and
history cohabit: where a falling city reflects its populace's
personal anguish, where a girl can see her grandfather on his way
to prison and feel only ``agonizing recognition.'' This complexity
is what lends ``The Last Life'' its fineness of vision and makes
its insights as interior as they are far-flung.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
