<HEADLINE>
CLINTON MAY   BE PONDERING HIS LEGACY TO THE NATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Bill Clinton is in a race against time.
</P>
<P>
   As the sand runs out on his administration, Clinton is
determined to be an activist in his remaining 17 months in office,
particularly because of the year he lost to the Monica S. Lewinsky
scandal and impeachment, friends and observers said.
</P>
<P>
   A confluence of interests has emerged to energize him: His
wife's expected run for the US Senate from New York, his vice
president's race to succeed him, and his own legacy as president,
observers said. His ability to withstand the impeachment and Senate
trial and still lead the United States and NATO to victory in
Kosovo has lifted Clinton's confidence and noticeably lightened his
mood.
</P>
<P>
   The president's closest friends said that while Clinton has
become more reflective and has started to think about his
post-White House future, he remains principally occupied with a
strong finish to his term.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not playing the Boston Celtics slow-down the 24-second
clock, freeze game,'' said Thomas F. McLarty, Clinton's former
chief of staff and longtime friend from Arkansas. ``He's still
aggressively trying to get points on the board.''
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, the business of governing is on hold. The past
two weeks have been consumed by house hunting in New York and a
languid vacation in Martha's Vineyard. This weekend, the Clintons
are in New York for fund-raising in the Hamptons, then will get in
a few more days of vacation in the state's Finger Lakes region.
</P>
<P>
   But the president intends to pick up the pace when he returns to
Washington in September. Because of the lack of progress on his
agenda in the year of Monica and because of his own relative youth,
Clinton has adopted a strategy different from most two-term
presidents winding up their seventh year, said Stephen Hess, a
presidential scholar at the Brookings Institution.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's still thinking as a sixth-year president,'' Hess said.
``He's very anxious to make amends, to catch up in a way that will
correct a legacy that is apt to start, `William J. Clinton, who was
impeached by the House of Representatives but not convicted.'. .
.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Clinton believes he will be vindicated by historians
who will judge that the zeal of Republicans to remove him from
office for lying about an affair with Lewinsky was worse than his
own misdeeds. He and his friends also think he will be remembered
for such things as the drops in crime and welfare rolls, and his
stewardship of a booming economy.
</P>
<P>
   But most of those events took shape in Clinton's first term. And
a 1996 poll of historians ranking the quality of presidents put
Clinton in the ``low average'' category, far below the men he
idolizes, such as Franklin D. Roosevelt, Woodrow Wilson, and John
F. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton desperately wants to improve his standing, starting with
this year's fight with Congress over using projected budget
surpluses to expand the life of Medicare and Social Security, while
offering targeted tax relief. But the obstacles include not only
GOP opposition, but the preference of some Democrats to keep the
issue alive for next year's election.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, said Hess, who has worked for four presidents
beginning with Dwight D. Eisenhower, as a president's term winds
up, ``your relations with Congress, particularly if it's an
opposition Congress, is mostly posturing.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodney Slater, Clinton's transportation secretary and a friend
from his Arkansas years, said that is why the next 17 months ``are
so important, and that's why he is redoubling his efforts and
really trying to take full advantage for the American people of the
opportunity that he's been blessed with.''
</P>
<P>
   Historian Doris Kearns Goodwin said Clinton's full-court press
is not without precedent. President Lyndon B. Johnson, succeeded in
getting landmark civil rights legislation through Congress as he
was about to leave office.
</P>
<P>
   Though many of Clinton's key staff members have left or are
looking to leave, and while the rewards and punishments a president
can employ might be less effective now as both parties in Congress
cast their eye toward the elections, Clinton can ``counter that
with extra passion and focus,'' Goodwin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What may be possible may be a long shot, but it's worth the
effort,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has begun taking other steps that could influence what
the history books say. For example, he has resumed regular news
conferences, and in recent months he has been having dinner with
small groups of reporters who regularly cover the White House.
</P>
<P>
   He took an antipoverty tour that took him to Appalachia, a South
Dakota Indian reservation, and South Central Los Angeles, among
other impoverished areas, where he called on businesses to invest
in untapped markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a year and a half left on my term and, yet, I'm
thinking more about the long term than I did even when I got
here.'' Clinton said earlier this month at a Democratic fund-raiser
at the Washington home of Senator John F. Kerry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are now in a position to think about the long term and
about how we can do more than just make the country work . . . how
we can secure a framework for opportunity for America, for a
greater social justice, for a greater good at home and around the
world than ever before,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   McLarty, who has had several conversations with Clinton about
his plans, said: ``I think he's obviously beginning to think about
what he's going to do after the presidency. But he is so
superstitious, and he's frankly so committed to the job, that he's
only beginning to formulate that in a general way.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that Clinton planned to write his memoirs and work on
his library and his golf game, at least for his first two
post-White House years.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Jesse Jackson said he envisioned Clinton using his
popularity abroad to promote human rights and international
relations. ``And then he could spend the rest of his time driving
Miss Hillary,'' quipped Jackson, referring to the first lady's
interest in becoming a US senator.
</P>
<P>
   Other friends said they would not be surprised if Clinton turned
to lecturing and teaching at home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Skip Rutherford, president of the William J. Clinton
Presidential Foundation, which raises money for the library to be
built in Little Rock, said Clinton plans to use the library to
focus on race relations in America and on international issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he leaves the presidency, he will be 54 years old. He
will be the youngest ex-president since Teddy Roosevelt,''
Rutherford said. ``He's been to the mountaintop twice in his
career.''
</P>
<P>
   From that perspective, Rutherford said, if Clinton accomplishes
nothing else at the White House, ``there has got to be a great
sense of personal fulfillment, not withstanding the obstacles, the
setbacks, the shortcomings of any president.'' And that, he said,
accounts for the president's livelier mood.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
