<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-GUIDE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVIES RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE BOSTON GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   !! 1/2 ``Better Than Chocolate'' This nugget is a low-budget
little charmer. Set in Vancouver's lesbian community, it is a
coming-of-age story about a law school droput turned artist trying
to explain why she's a lesbian to her straight mother. (Unrated)
(Jim Sullivan) &QL; 
 &QL; 
!!! ``In Too Deep'' This story about an undercover cop trying to
bring down a drug lord sidesteps the usual cliches of the usually
dumbed-down genre by sidestepping stereotype and allowing
psychological complexity. Omar Epps is dynamic and affecting as the
cop who finds himself conflicted as well as stressed, and LL Cool J
proves he's as much an actor as a rapper by not only keeping the
vicious drug lord in the human race, but giving him a couple of
seductively charming traits. (R) &QL; 
 &QL; 
!!! 1/2 ``The Muse'' Albert Brooks at his best in a wickedly funny
satire of Hollywood craziness and its need to believe in magic.
Brooks plays a just-fired screenwriter who, needing a quick career
fix, hires a high-maintenance muse, played by Sharon Stone with
high style and a flair for insouciant comedy. Brooks's writer
scores with amusingly cranky asides and responses to being royally
dissed. Cameos by Martin Scorsese and James Cameron add to the fun.
(PG-13) &QL; 
 &QL; 
!! ``The 13th Warrior'' Sword-happy 10th century multiculturalism
adds up to a lot of epic nothingness as Moslem diplomat Antonio
Banderas joins a gang of Norsemen fighting off flesh-eating
savages. Between his brain and their brawn, they get the job done,
but apart from a lot of enthusiastic and gory whacking, the film
has little to recommend it except atmosphere and imposing Vancouver
Island locations standing in for the gloomy Scandinavian forest.
(R) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
