<SLUG> BC-HOOKER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REMEMBER TO FIGURE EFFECTS OF INFLATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am 43 and my husband is 63. Our combined income is well
over $200,000 yearly. We have the following assets: $275,000 in
Fidelity Blue Chip Growth fund, $155,000 in a Fidelity money market
IRA account, $65,000 in a Putnam Growth Fund IRA, $30,000 in a T.
Rowe Price Money Market account, $10,000 in a CD, and $20,000 in a
bank savings account. Our yearly goal is to purchase $43,000 worth
of shares in Fidelity Blue Chip, contribute $4,000 to the money
market IRA accounts, and to add $3,000 to the taxable money market
fund. My husband will receive a $12,000 annual pension and
approximately $14,000 from Social Security. If we retire in six
years, what kind of income stream might we expect?
</P>
<P>
   C.H., Orange, Calif. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. In the end the answer is largely up to you. Using an estimate
of 8 percent average annual portfolio growth, you would accumulate
a total of $1,252,947 over the next six years if you continue the
savings program you outline.
</P>
<P>
   If that entire amount were then invested in a fixed-income
portfolio that produced an average yield of 6.5 percent, its yield
would combine with the pension and Social Security to give you a
$107,441 annual income stream.
</P>
<P>
   But even though your husband will be 69 at that time, you will
be only 49, and you should anticipate many years of retirement. For
that reason, you also should be worrying about the effects of many
years of inflation on your savings.
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, it would be more prudent to leave a good
chunk of the portfolio in growth instruments such as the Fidelity
Blue Chip Growth and the Putnam Growth funds.
</P>
<P>
   I'd put about $850,000 in fixed-income holdings designed to
produce your income stream, leaving the balance of $402,947
invested for capital appreciation.
</P>
<P>
   If you did that, using the same assumptions, you would have an
annual income of $55,250 from your fixed-income portfolio, and a
total of $81,250 when the pension and Social Security are counted
in.
</P>
<P>
   You could, of course, establish any level for the growth segment
of the portfolio after retirement, but as I said, given your
relative youth, it should probably be fairly sizable.
</P>
<P>
   Another way to approach this problem _ a more dangerous one, in
my opinion _ is to look at the beginning balance, calculate a
maximum expected lifespan, and then calculate how much money you
might be able to withdraw monthly so that the balance would be
depleted at the end of the period.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if you estimated a 40-year withdrawal period and
presumed average portfolio earnings of 7.5 percent, you could
withdraw $8,015 a month, or $96,180 a year. With the pension and
Social Security added in, the income stream would be $122,180 a
year.
</P>
<P>
   Why did I say this method is dangerous? Well, one factor is
inflation. It's certain that what $122,180 a year buys in the year
2005 will be a great deal more than what the same amount will buy
in the last year, 2045.
</P>
<P>
   The second factor is that, when you establish a set period of
time and deplete your funds over that period, you put yourself in
the morbid position of betting that you will die before the period
is up. In the example I chose, you would have to dread the prospect
of your 89th birthday, because that's about the time your financial
well would run dry, even if you happened to be in splendid health.
</P>
<P>
   In the You-Didn't-Ask-But Department, I think you should
diversify the stock side of your portfolio. Both of your funds are
in the same sector _ large-cap domestic growth stocks. Since the
lion's share of this money is in a taxable account, I wouldn't sell
as a means of diversifying, but I would use your substantial
ongoing contributions to the savings plan to diversify _ buying a
value-oriented large-cap fund, a mid-cap fund, a small-cap fund, an
international fund, and a health care fund.
</P>
<P>
   A more broadly allocated stock portfolio would enhance your
chances of attaining the growth level I projected at the outset.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. The company I work for has increased the number of options
into which I can invest my 401(k) money from 10 to 23 funds. My
problem is that with so many funds, I'm unsure where to invest. I
want to diversify without being redundant. I now have $45,000 in
the account, with $2,000 to $6,000 in each of these funds: Fidelity
Equity Income II, Fidelity Equity Portfolio Growth, Fidelity Growth
Opportunities, Fidelity Magellan, Invesco Small Company Growth,
Janus, Janus Worldwide, Twentieth Century Ultra, Vanguard Growth
and Income, and Vanguard Wellington. The new options are these:
Cigna Lifetime funds (five separate offerings), Charter Guaranteed
Income fund, Charter Corporate Bond fund, Charter High-Yield Bond
fund, Charter Large Company Stock Index, Charter Large Company
Stock Growth, Charter Large Company Stock Value, Lazard
International Equity, and Warburg International Equity. I am 29 and
newly married. My current salary is $62,000 and I invest 10 percent
in the 401(k) with 3 percent matched by my company as well as
yearly profit sharing, which this year will amount to 2 percent. I
consider myself an aggressive investor and anticipate retirement in
25 to 30 years. Or when I can afford it. Where should I focus my
401(k)?
</P>
<P>
   G.B., Lehighton, Pa. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Just as important as which of the new selection of funds you
might chose is which of the current holdings you should get rid of.
Building a properly balanced portfolio isn't like baseball _ you
don't have to touch every base.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the new offerings and a few of the funds you hold are
designed for people much older than you, those who are nearing
retirement and want to reduce their risk exposure as the time when
they will need the money gets closer.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason I would begin by jettisoning Vanguard
Wellington. It's an excellent balanced fund, but you are about 20
years away from the time you might want to look there.
</P>
<P>
   Next, I'd cut Janus Worldwide loose as well, not because it's
not a solid fund, but because you'd be better served by getting
your international exposure in an all-international fund, rather
than a world fund such as Janus Worldwide, which holds more than a
third of its assets in large-cap US stocks. I suggest you select
Lazard International Equity from the new list to represent your
international exposure.
</P>
<P>
   Third, I would select among Fidelity Equity Income II, Vanguard
Growth and Income, and the new fund you identify as Charter Large
Company Stock Value. (The latter isn't a publicly offered fund,
although it may share management and largely duplicate the results
of one; many 401(k) offerings devise new names for their menu
options, which sometimes mean they are funds that are particular to
the manager of the 401(k), and sometimes are simply variant
identifications of public funds.) My guess is that Vanguard Growth
and Income will end up showing the best long-term results in the
large-cap value arena.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, you'll want to compare the results of Invesco Small
Company Growth with the Charter Small Company Value Stock offering
and decide which is the better prospect. If the results show that
the value-oriented fund has been only slightly better than the
Invesco offering in recent years, I'd stick with Invesco, since the
results are probably more a function of the current small-cap
malaise than the virtues of the fund.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, I'd assess the various large-cap growth offerings,
limiting the selection to no more than three, consisting perhaps of
one in the large-cap growth sector and a couple in the sector
representing a blend of growth and value issues. If the Charter
Large Company Stock Index is a Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 fund, I'd put
25 percent of the entire portfolio there.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, I'd design the portfolio so that 60 percent of the
money and ongoing contributions are in large-cap domestic stock
funds, and 20 percent each in small-cap and international funds.
</P>
<P>
   If in the future a mid-cap and a health care sector fund become
available, I would cut the large-cap position to 50 percent and put
12 1/2 percent each in mid-cap, small-cap, international, and
health care offerings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I'm 63 and in the process of selling my winter home. What
should I do with the money?
</P>
<P>
   P.G., Gloucester, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. To give you advice, I need to know something of your overall
situation, needs, and desires. Write again with more detail and
I'll try to help.
</P>
<P>
   I don't answer this in the paper to frustrate you, but because I
get many letters which are unanswerable because of inadequate
information.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send letters, including your name, address and telephone number,
to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
