<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ESSAY-CENTURY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
END-OF-CENTURY ISSUES HAVE A FAMILIAR RING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALAN LUPO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the century ends, there is much concern about the state of
the nation. Citizens fear violent crime and seem overwhelmed at the
abundance of guns and drugs. Scholars and journalists worry about
public apathy. We argue over whether America should deal with
China, how many more immigrants we can absorb, and if we can
protect our environment.
</P>
<P>
   It is 1999, and it was also 1899, and though it would be too
simplistic to suggest that nothing has changed, it is either ironic
or reassuring to note that human nature does not radically alter
itself in a mere century.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the economy is fueled not only by high technology,
information systems, international investment, and the lucrative
entertainment industry. Its engine runs also on organized crime,
the ethnic and racial diversity of which would satisfy the most
aggressive of affirmative action proponents.
</P>
<P>
   In 1899, Butch Cassidy, the Sundance Kid, and their Wild Bunch
gang robbed a Union Pacific train of $60,000 near Wilcox Station,
Wyo.
</P>
<P>
   That same year, Ignazio Saietta, a Sicilian mafioso, arrived in
New York and organized an extortion outfit called The Black Hand.
He and his pals would terrorize their Italian immigrant neighbors
for more than two decades.
</P>
<P>
   By then, Monk Eastman, born Edward Osterman, a Jew, had a gang
of about 1,200 members in New York City's Lower East Side. They
were very entrepreneurial. If you wanted a person's ear chewed off,
they would charge you $15. It cost $100 or more to eliminate the
whole person.
</P>
<P>
   Eastman, a brutish man, was also a sophisticated criminal. He
understood the connections between the underworld and the political
world and pledged his loyalty to Tammany Hall, long a target of
``reformers,'' who blamed clubhouse politics for the ills of the
city.
</P>
<P>
   Today, ``reformers'' bemoan the high cost of political campaigns
and the influence of money and special interests on candidates.
</P>
<P>
   A century ago, ``reformers'' agonized over the influence of
corporate wealth and the existence of political machines in both
major parties.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, Irish political bosses were doing well by doing good.
In Philadelphia, a Republican machine was so strong that a reform
organization did not even bother to oppose the machine's
candidates. Why even that ``reformer,'' Teddy Roosevelt, was
alleged to have made deals with the Republican machine in New York
state.
</P>
<P>
   Some idealists got off their duffs and did something. They
started settlement houses for the poor or campaigned for clean
housing and clean elections.
</P>
<P>
   But The Nation magazine warned that America's ``indisposition to
have principles, to stand fast and adhere to them, to meet the
enemy at the gate, and sink or swim, live or die, for what you
believe will be right rather than pleasant, is the curse of the
nation and the great obstacle to reform.''
</P>
<P>
   Author Frederick Lewis Allen would later call it ``a time of
complacency. Since the end of the depression of the mid-'90s, the
voices of protest at the disparities of fortune in the United
States had weakened. Populism was dead; the free-silver agitation
had petered out; the once angry farmers of the Plains States were
making out so well that in 1899 a traveler commented that `every
barn in Kansas and Nebraska has had a new coat of paint.' ''
</P>
<P>
   To the irritation of those who worried about an expansionist
America, Republican Senator Albert Beveridge would soon embark on
one of those famous ``fact-finding'' tours to the Far East. He
would return to tell his colleagues, ``And just beyond the
Philippines, are China's illimitable markets. We will not retreat
from either.''
</P>
<P>
   While anti-imperialists warned their fellow citizens against
expansionism, Secretary of State John Hay was worried that Japan
and the European colonial powers would divide China up so quickly
and efficiently that American business would be left behind.
</P>
<P>
   Fast-forward to 1999, as the Clinton administration, business
leaders, and certain economists and scholars argue for continuing
dialogue and trade with a communist China, and a combination of
human rights activists and consesrvatives counter with condemnation
of such rapprochment.
</P>
<P>
   As both sides have at it, Chinese gangsters round up countrymen
who will pay a price to be illegally brought to America, crowd them
into ships, and unload them to disappear into the indentured
servitude of the underbelly of the new economy.
</P>
<P>
   Even as they engage in this, the poorest of Mexican families
entrust their lives to Mexican criminals to spirit them into the
underbelly of the United States, ironically the land their nation
once claimed as its own, to work at low wages. They're the lucky
ones. Some die in transit.
</P>
<P>
   Add to the ``illegals'' the thousands of legal immigrants from
all over Latin America, Southeast Asia, India, Pakistan, northern
Africa, Nigeria, the Middle East, Russia, and, again, as a century
ago, voices are raised in protest that America can take only so
many, that the nation's bloodlines will somehow be diluted by these
new arrivals. Among those protesting are the grandsons and
granddaughters of the eastern and southern Europeans whose arrival
a century ago convinced ``native'' Americans that the nation was
doomed. It seems to have flourished.
</P>
<P>
   Not all has flourished, however. By 1899, the real ``native''
Americans, the Indians, were no longer a threat to white expansion
within the continent. They had become, at best, objects of
curiosity; at worst, a defeated, demoralized people who had warned,
in their own way, that too much growth, too much ravaging of the
land, would defy the spirits of nature. But, of course, they were
savages. Who listened?
</P>
<P>
   Now, a century later, the new, or, one might say accurately,
renewed, buzzword in political, environmental, and journalistic
circles is ``sprawl.''
</P>
<P>
   Even in sprawl, there may be what some might consider an element
of justice, however. Foxwoods, in Connecticut, is noted now for
more than its abundant greenery. It is host to a lucrative gambling
casino. The Indians run it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
