<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEDIGREE CROP; CALMING RAGE; A GUT FEELING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is the summer of the heirloom tomato. The phrase crops up
on restaurant menus, in newspapers, and in magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Cute tomatoes for food snobs? Not at all, says Carolyn Male,
author of ``100 Heirloom Tomatoes for the American Garden.'' Some
reviewers of her book have mistakenly thought the word ``heirloom''
implies some sort of snobbery. It's a term used in agriculture and
livestock breeding to indicate plants and animals that pre-date
hybridization.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past 10 years, Male has grown and evaluated more than
1,200 heirloom varieties and offered seeds through the Seed Savers
Exchange. She says the best of the heirlooms far exceed hybrids
when it comes to taste. In her book, just published by Workman,
Male writes short histories and descriptions of 100 of her
favorites. The accompanying color photographs, by Frank Ionanotti,
are positively voluptuous.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Male retired from teaching biochemistry to
medical students and moved to Salem, N.Y., ``just over the
mountain'' from Manchester, Vt. Her property used to be owned by
Andy and Martha Stewart, before the divorce. Male, who describes
herself as ``anti-domestic,'' says a friend gave her a plaque to
hang in her new home: ``Martha Stewart Doesn't Live Here _ and It's
a Good Thing.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Traffic calming. Another phrase that seems to be popping up all
over the place. It's an engineering term that originated in Europe
to describe a system of narrowing roads, extending curbs, and
installing speed bumps, rumble strips, and other obstructions to
force drivers to slow down.
</P>
<P>
   When I first saw a sign reading ``Practice Traffic Calming'' on
Route 2, at a spot where four lanes suddenly turn into two, I
assumed it had something to do with road rage. It does, in a way.
Such signs warn motorists to be careful, to slow down and be civil
to other drivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lack of traffic calming can lead to road rage,'' said Jay
Scirame, deputy highway commissioner of Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   In some places, traffic calming has, unfortunately, led to road
rage. In Denver, for example, some drivers were furious at being
forced to put on the brakes when the city experimented with traffic
calming.
</P>
<P>
   Cambridge was one of the first local communities to try traffic
calming in certain neighborhoods, including Central Square, where
sidewalks and curbs were widened and pedestrian crossings
installed. You still take your life in your hands every time you
cross Mass. Ave., but traffic calming seems to have made the trip
less of an extreme sport than it used to be.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a friend told me she had an appointment to see an
intuitive healer. The other day I met a woman who told me she
practices intuitive feng shui. Now here's a book, sent along by a
publicist, ``Practical Intuition,'' by Laura Day (Broadway Books).
It doesn't take intuition to see that intuition is huge this
season.
</P>
<P>
   The shelves of the self-help sections have a dozen or more
intuition-related titles, among them, ``Cracking the Intuition
Code,'' by Gail Ferguson; ``Ignite Your Intuition,'' by Craig
Karges; and my favorite title on the subject, ``You Already Know
What to Do,'' by Sharon Franquemont. So why do I need this book?
Day's ``Practical Intuition'' and her ``Practical Intuition for
Success'' are the bestsellers on the subject, in part because Demi
Moore is an outspoken Day disciple. She provides a glowing
introduction for the first book, in which she credits Day with
helping her choose the right roles. My intuition tells me it's time
Demi went back for a tuneup.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
