<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-REDRIVER-GIMMICKS-ART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIVIDED CITY, EIFFEL TOWER REPLICA AMONG RED RIVER DRAWS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Photos available on NYT database) 
 
By SYD KEARNEY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You gotta have a gimmick.
</P>
<P>
   That was the advice given to a young Gypsy Rose Lee by Electra
and the other strippers in the popular musical ``Gypsy.''
</P>
<P>
   And those words ring true for tourist-hungry towns as well as
entertainers.
</P>
<P>
   On a tour of the Red River Valley, several Texas cities touted
attractions too appealing to pass up:
</P>
<P>
   _ In Texarkana, the state line separating Texas and Arkansas
runs directly through the center of downtown. The city's split
personality requires two of nearly everything: two mayors, two city
governments, two police departments, two fire departments. ...
Well, you get the idea.
</P>
<P>
   The twin cities do share two entities: the State Line Post
Office and the Bi-State Justice Center.
</P>
<P>
   The State Line Post Office straddles State Line Avenue, meaning
that offices on the west side of the building are in Texas and
offices on the right side are in Arkansas. In front of the building
is a specially constructed island designed solely for visitors who
want to stand in two states at once for that Kodak moment.
</P>
<P>
   A more unusual situation is found at the Bi-State Justice
Center, also on State Line Avenue. Inside the building are judicial
and law offices serving two states, two cities and two counties.
</P>
<P>
   It took special legislation in both states for the concept to
work, making it possible for a Texas judge to preside over a
courtroom that is physically in Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   _ Taking its cue from that European city on the Seine, the Texas
town of Paris boasts its own Eiffel Tower. Constructed by union
workers with donated materials, the tower debuted five years ago
and enjoys a spot overlooking the city's civic center.
</P>
<P>
   At about 65 feet in height, the Red River valley version isn't
as imposing as France's famous 900-foot structure. But the Paris,
Texas, landmark has a special feature: Last year, the town topped
its Eiffel Tower with a huge red cowboy hat.
</P>
<P>
   To which we say, ``oui, oui.''
</P>
<P>
   _ No one is ever going to confuse Muenster with Fredericksburg.
With 100 shops and 300 bed and breakfasts, Fredericksburg in the
Hill Country isn't likely to lose the title of most touristy
Teutonic-tinged Texas city.
</P>
<P>
   That's OK. Muenster's German heritage is not in question. The
town was founded in 1889 by two brothers, Carl and Emil Flusche.
Today, it counts about 1,500 citizens, and 90 percent are
descendants of the first German Catholic settlers.
</P>
<P>
   Each April, the city celebrates its roots with Germanfest, a
three-day event that features a bike rally, fun run, arm wrestling
contest, sausage cook-off, live music, dancing, arts and crafts and
other family entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   During the rest of the year, visitors can get a taste of
Germany. Fischer's Market, a large grocery store/butcher shop, has
been operating since 1927. Cases of smoked sausages and cheese
entice shoppers and picnickers. Or make Bayer's Kolonialwaren your
stop for apple strudel or sweets.
</P>
<P>
   The city also has two dining rooms: The Center Restaurant and
Rohmer's. We prefer the latter, which has served German and other
homestyle fare in unpretentious quarters for more than 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   _ Just two days after we rumbled through Nocona, this little
town got some disturbing news. About 160 workers at the local boot
factory would be losing their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The city of Nocona, named for an Indian chief, was losing the
factory that put it on the map. The downturn in the Western fashion
industry is forcing Justin Industries to close two Texas factories
_ the Nocona plant and one in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Although the closure means Nocona loses its largest employer,
the boot company that was founded here still will have a presence.
The Nocona Boot Factory Outlet, located adjacent to the factory, is
as good a reason as any to slow down on U.S. 82.
</P>
<P>
   Whether you are looking for that first pair of cowboy boots or a
baseball glove your teammates will envy, the factory store's staff
is helpful, friendly and knows good leather when they see it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
