<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-REDRIVER-ART-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOING WITH THE FLOW IN THE RED RIVER VALLEY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Photos available on NYT database) 
 
By SYD KEARNEY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Forget Wal-Mart, strip shopping centers and malls.
</P>
<P>
   In the small communities of the Red River Valley, which hugs the
Texas-Oklahoma border, the place to be is downtown, where historic
commercial districts lure tourists and residents with an agreeable
mix of shopping, history and nostalgia.
</P>
<P>
   In county seats such as Bonham and Gainesville, central town
squares are dominated by courthouses. These were among the first
structures built in Texas' fledgling counties. Around them,
commerce thrived: Cotton was bought and sold, household necessities
were acquired in shops that fronted the square, and any leftover
cash was entrusted to the corner bank.
</P>
<P>
   In other towns, Main Street was just that. Whether the route of
a stagecoach line or the site of a train depot, Main Street
attracted traffic, and traffic attracted business.
</P>
<P>
   Skinny and unruly, U.S. 82 lolls across the copper-colored earth
of the Red River Valley, linking cities from Henrietta to Paris. On
stretches where battered sedans and shiny pickups disregard the
generous speed limit, drivers here follow the custom of pulling off
to the shoulder to let the faster fellow pass.
</P>
<P>
   That's just the way a visitor should tour Texas' small towns:
slowing down at the first glimpse of a water tower, pulling over
for a historic marker or pausing for the daily special at a local
lunch spot. These tasty bits of history and color can't be gleaned
from the interstate or gathered from the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   They must be taken in small-town bites.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
PARIS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The prettiest square in the Red River Valley may belong to
Paris, where an ornate fountain is the centerpiece of the historic
business district. The Culbertson Fountain was constructed in 1927
after a 1916 fire had destroyed most of a town center dating to the
mid-1840s.
</P>
<P>
   Today the square is home to five antiques dealers, dueling
optical companies, four boutiques, a tux shop, a sporting-goods
store, an art gallery, a bank, the Paris Community Theater and a
blue-eyed, bobtail stray that accompanied us on our stroll.
</P>
<P>
   The Lamar County Courthouse is on Lamar Street, a few blocks
from the square, and is worth a stop. The imposing
marble-and-granite structure was built in 1917 in the Classical
Revival style.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
BONHAM &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An ``I Believe in Bonham'' sticker decorates the front door of
Bewley's 5 &AMP; 10, one of dozens of businesses on Bonham's town
square. The old-timey five-and-dime sells everything from washtubs
to fake floral arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   Its neighbors on the square include a chiropractor, four law
offices, two medical-supply stores, a jewelry shop, a bank, a
travel agency and Pizza Plaza. Although several empty storefronts
detract from the scene, the square is a treat, with signs recalling
past glories and stories.
</P>
<P>
   At the center is the rather drab Fannin County Courthouse. The
original courthouse, built in 1888, was more elaborate and
better-suited to being the focal point of town. But a fire
destroyed its decorative roof and steeple in 1929. A modernization
in 1965 incorporated parts of the 1888 structure. Check out
photographs of the original courthouse and its pretty grounds at
the Fannin County Museum of History, a few blocks away in the
restored 1900 Texas and Pacific Railway Depot.
</P>
<P>
   One of the oldest towns in Red River Valley, Bonham was founded
in 1837. The city was named for James Butler Bonham, who carried
news of the siege of the Alamo to James Fannin, then returned to
San Antonio to die with the defenders of the now-famous mission.
</P>
<P>
   A statue of Bonham decorates the courthouse grounds, which have
been nearly completely paved for parking. Also on the grounds is a
Confederate memorial.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SHERMAN &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sherman's town square is more inviting, welcoming visitors with
benches and large shade trees. The lawns of the Grayson County
Courthouse are peppered with monuments, markers and other mementos.
</P>
<P>
   A Confederate memorial was erected in 1896. Other markers honor
the Ninth Texas Calvary and recall the history of Grayson County.
One marker recounts a 1905 visit by Theodore Roosevelt, who was on
his way to a Rough Rider reunion in San Antonio; more than 35,000
people turned out to see him.
</P>
<P>
   Two time capsules are buried in the courthouse lawn. One was
placed there on July 4, 1976, to mark America's 200th birthday; the
other was buried in 1986 to mark the county's sesquicentennial.
</P>
<P>
   The concrete-and-limestone courthouse was built in 1936 in the
style of Stripped Classicism. A thriving business district,
dominated by law offices and a large furniture store, envelopes the
structure.
</P>
<P>
   In the summer, free weekly concerts are given on the square.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
GAINESVILLE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The bustle of Gainesville's town square may be due to its
proximity to I-35. While thoroughfares have bypassed the historic
business districts of many Texas small towns, here the freeway runs
close enough for drivers to see the Beaux Arts dome of the Cooke
County Courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
