<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4430 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-PROVIDENCE-BOS &LR;      08-30 1671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-PROVIDENCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE INSIDE STORY ON `OUTSIDE PROVIDENCE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Michael Corrente picked up a novel by an unknown
author named Peter Farrelly in 1988 at a yard sale in Easthampton,
N.Y., where Corrente was living. The novel was called ``Outside
Providence.'' It cost him a dollar. ``I figured, a buck, how bad
could it be?'' Corrente says, in an office at a Manhattan hotel.
</P>
<P>
   It resonated, big time. ``I fell in love with it,'' he says. The
novel, dealing with teenagers growing up in working-class
Pawtucket, R.I. during 1974, brought back feelings Corrente, now
40, had back then, when he grew up in a similar environment in that
Rhode Island city.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven years later, ``Outside Providence,'' out Wednesday, is a
movie directed by Corrente, and co-produced by two Duxbury, Mass.
brothers named Farrelly _ that same Peter and his younger sibling
Bobby, now rather famous for making ``There's Something About
Mary'' and ``Dumb and Dumber.'' They co-wrote the script with
Corrente.
</P>
<P>
   ``This story is more my life than it is Peter's,'' says
Corrente, ``which is another reason people wanted me to do the
movie. I really have to tell you that most people between New York
and LA know that guy, they know that house, that lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a great foundation, which was Peter's novel,'' adds
Corrente. The Farrellys, he says, grew up somewhat privileged, sons
of a doctor in an upper-middle-class family. ``We were less
fortunate.'' The book was ``a great blueprint. It's not like we
were creating any of this stuff. We got to add and fill in stuff
from our own personal lives. Movies work when they work.''
</P>
<P>
   Of his own upbringing, Corrente says his father was illiterate,
but a film buff. Michael, one of six children, used to see foreign
movies with his dad, and he'd have to read him the subtitles. That,
Corrente says, was his version of going to film school. First film
that floored him: ``The Bicycle Thief.''
</P>
<P>
   As ``Outside Providence'' begins, you meet Dunph, an affable,
but semi-dim, pot-smoking teenager played by Shawn Hatosy. Dunph
has a paper route that is a collaborative effort with his younger
brother Jackie, who is in a wheelchair. Dunph drives with his
brother's chair roped to his truck, and Jackie hurls the papers at
his customers' houses. Trailing on a leash is their smelly,
three-legged, one-eyed mutt named Clops, whom their embittered
widowed father (Alec Baldwin) won't even let in the house. His
father has nicknamed Dunph, whose name is Timothy Dunphy, Dildo,
and relishes calling him that in public.
</P>
<P>
   Dunph hangs out with three low-wattage, no-ambition pals,
nicknamed Tommy the Wire, Decenz, and Drugs. It is not a life of
much promise.
</P>
<P>
   It is one, however, that changes for the better because of
Dunph's stupidity. While stoned, he crashes the family car and, as
things could happen in those days, a friendly judge ``punishes''
him by enrolling him in a tony Connecticut prep school. There, his
dumbness _ he thinks Arizona is an ocean state _ slowly dissipates
and a certain studiousness and self-awareness take over. Plus, he
falls in love with a preppy girl named Jane Weston, played by Amy
Smart. A window to another world is opened. And then, maybe,
closed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Outside Providence,'' which began shooting early last year and
was made entirely in Rhode Island, is not a movie of simple yuks or
of lesson-learned poignancy. Yet in the Farrellys' world of sex,
silliness, and slapstick this might qualify as an almost subtle
picture. It is a movie of ambiguity, with situations that teeter
between funny and pathetic, grim and riotous.
</P>
<P>
   This, of course, might be seem something of an anomaly in a teen
film market predicated on the idea of high concept. (You should
ignore the implication of the ad's limerick, which runs ``There
Once Was a Boy From Pawtucket . . .''; there's no ``hair gel'' kind
of vibe here. ) The makers of ``Outside Providence'' are taking the
risk that viewers can handle the juxtaposition of tone.
</P>
<P>
   `` `The Graduate' was funny and it was serious,'' says Corrente.
``There are a lot of good movies that had elements of both in it.
`Good Will Hunting' was very funny at times and very serious at
times. . . . This is about some blue-collar people in a tough
neighborhood with the inability to express how they feel.
Ultimately, they figure a way out.'' Well, some do.
</P>
<P>
   The serious bent is due, it would appear, to the efforts of
Corrente, who is known for gritty films such as ``American
Buffalo'' and ``Federal Hill,'' art-film-circuit pictures. He says,
with a laugh, that the $7.5 million budget of ``Outside
Providence'' is a big picture _ ``It's actually going to end up in
more than 50 theaters.''
</P>
<P>
   He says the money was spent on the production, the look. ``It
wasn't on the talent. It was a period piece and all the cars, all
the clothes, you have to be careful where you put the camera.'' The
money, incidentally, was raised by soliciting Rhode Island business
people, who put up the cash against the film's future earnings.
Corrente says virtually every studio passed on it, this, of course,
being before the Farrellys got hot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard every excuse,'' says Corrente. `` `It's too funny';
`It's not funny enough.' . . . I would love to be in a position to
go back now after `There's Something About Mary' grossed what it
grossed.''
</P>
<P>
   Corrente's young stars _ Hatosy and Smart are both 23 _ are
aware of the boom in teen-oriented movies. ``Kids go and see these
kind of movies,'' says Hatosy, who is from the Baltimore area.
``Any movie, really.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It appeals to a lot of different age groups,'' adds Smart, who
hails from Laurel Canyon, Calif. ``Teenagers, people that lived
through the '70s. I don't think (the teen movie boom) will last
forever, but this is definitely a time when they are doing well.''
</P>
<P>
   Corrente added one disturbing scene, based on his own
experiences, a flashback scenario about Dunph's mother shooting out
Christmas lights with a popgun. ``That scared Peter, he didn't like
it. But for me, it's the only pleasant moment (Dunph) remembers
with his mom and dad and brother, even if it's a little twisted.
It's enough to let you know things are a little crazy here.''
</P>
<P>
   Corrente and company get the details right, from the scruffy
garb worn by the actors to the rock music played to the locals'
beer: Narragansett and Old Milwaukee. The soundtrack _ with hits
from Wings, the Eagles, Lynyrd Skynyrd, and others _ is impressive,
not just for its representation of the era, but for the fact that
heavyweights like Paul McCartney signed on.
</P>
<P>
   McCartney, says Corrente, liked the movie and sold them the song
for, well, a song. ``He said, `I know you don't have a lot of
money, but here is a number we can live with,' '' recalls Corrente,
who figures his picture received ``favored nation's status'' from
Big Mac. The other rockers agreed to low figures, saying, ``Well,
as long as no one is making more money than we are . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Hatosy says he was initially stymied by the Rhode Island accent
and needed a dialect coach. Corrrente told him just to hang out
with him and the Farrellys and in a month ``you won't be able to
stop talking like this.''
</P>
<P>
   As to the characters' look, Corrente says he told the costumers,
``I don't want to get caught looking at a costume. Give me a pair
of ratty jeans and a T-shirt and an Army jacket _ not a new one.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Negative role models &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dunph's dad and his male buddies, one of whom is played by
George Wendt (Norm from ``Cheers''), play poker and drink beer
around the Dunphy kitchen table for most of the movie. Clearly,
their dead-end routines and casual bickering are what could lie
ahead for Dunph and his pals.
</P>
<P>
   Corrente is unflinching about the kids' use of marijuana. It is
part of the fabric of their lives, for better or worse. The movie
doesn't tell an audience drugs rule; neither does it say they
necessarily kill.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the characters does pay a pretty price for what
happens,'' Corrente says, ``but if you were alive in 1974 and went
to a concert, there were at least 15,000 joints floating around.
The way I make movies is I want the ability to tell a story the way
that I remember it and not sit back and say, `Is the studio going
to let me?' That's what was going on; I didn't overdo it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatosy's character is one of those who preside over a makeshift
memorial to a late friend. They toss an Allman Brothers Band album
on the fire, a pack of rolling papers, a bottle of booze. ``I guess
that's when he finally makes that change,'' says Hatosy of Dunph.
``He realizes these characters are such knuckleheads and that `I
don't have to end up playing cards with these guys 20 years from
now, like my old man does.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``Outside Providence'' easily earned its R rating because of
frequent cursing _ not quite ``Scarface'' but not ``The Brady
Bunch'' either _ and portrayals of drug use. Does Corrente worry
that might shut out the core audience?
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact of the matter is, the best way to get teenagers into
a movie is to tell them they can't go.''
</P>
<P>
   But ``Outside Providence'' does not go anywhere near the
explicitness of, say, ``American Pie'' when it comes to sexuality.
Given the R, why didn't he go further when it came to that aspect?
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not a big sexual-content guy. For me, it's either sell me
triple-X-rated pornography or shut the door with your foot on the
way into the bedroom. Anything in between is embarrassing and
awkward. I don't want to see kids going at it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this picture will do well,'' Corrente says, ``because
I think it delivers on a lot of levels that a lot of teen pictures
are not delivering. A lot of pictures are made because somebody
thinks teen movies are making money, so they put 115 pages of stuff
together that gives you a reason to put teenagers in a movie, but
they forget to put a heart and soul in the story.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-99 1348EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990830.0211 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4431 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t BC-TRAVEL-REDRIVER-ART-2     08-30 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-REDRIVER-ART-2NDTAKE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
UNDATED: Cooke County Courthouse.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The courthouse, a concrete-and-stone structure built for
$150,000 in 1911, is the fourth on this site. The first courthouse,
a log cabin, was built in 1850, two years after the county was
created. Cooke County takes its name from Capt. William Cooke, a
hero of the Battle of San Jacinto.
</P>
<P>
   On the grounds are monuments to World War II and Confederate
veterans. The clocks that adorn the copper dome of the courthouse
were added in 1920 as a World War I memorial.
</P>
<P>
   The streets facing the courthouse are pedestrian-friendly.
Shoppers have a choice of several antiques malls, a couple of gift
shops, a jeweler, a gallery, a JCPenney catalog store and more. But
it wasn't always bustling.
</P>
<P>
   Like many small-town commercial districts, Gainesville's
downtown struggled for survival. When Joe Albro opened his Carousel
Antiques Mall in 1991, more than 65 percent of the storefronts on
the square were empty. Today, Albro says, ``You can't rent a
building downtown.''
</P>
<P>
   Albro's antiques mall is housed in a former hardware store;
across the street, past the courthouse, is his wife's Shady Oak
Gallery.
</P>
<P>
   Albro, who owned an insurance company for 28 years, says the
nearby interstate has aided downtown's revival; about 95 percent of
shoppers are from out of town.
</P>
<P>
   One place that draws both locals and visitors downtown is the
Fried Pie Co., a laid-back diner that serves home-style meals
topped off with pies filled with apricots, apple or chocolate.
</P>
<P>
   Just a block off the square is the Morton County Museum, a small
historical museum with changing exhibits and a fine collection of
stained glass. Ask for a brochure detailing a self-guided tour that
points out some of the 30 Victorian homes nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Not too far from the square is the Santa Fe Passenger Depot, a
small 1901 Mission Revival railroad station that is being
renovated. Rail service, discontinued two decades ago, was recently
restored with Amtrak service that runs between Oklahoma City and
Fort Worth. The train pauses at several small Oklahoma towns, and
the Gainesville stop _ the only stop in Texas besides Fort Worth _
is popular with shoppers drawn to Gainesville's many antiques shops
and its large outlet mall.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
DENISON &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Denison has no main square, but it certainly has a thriving
downtown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alive and well'' is how Gary Sewell, owner of the Blue Moon
Antiques Mall, describes Denison's historic commercial district.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two Wal-Marts within seven miles of downtown, and
we're still lucrative,'' Sewell says.
</P>
<P>
   This border city was established in September 1872 to
accommodate the Missouri, Kansas and Texas Railroad, commonly
called the MK&AMP;T or the Katy. Within 100 days of its founding,
Denison boasted 3,000 citizens. According to historians, every
third building under construction was a saloon.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the city's first buildings still survive and are among
the more than 130 structures in the city's historic commercial
district. One of the earliest predates the town's founding. The
J.K. Miller House, built in 1866, served as a stop for the
Butterfield Stagecoach.
</P>
<P>
   The most prominent building in the historic district is the Katy
Depot. The Beaux Arts depot cost $250,000 to build in 1909, but
that was appropriate for a station that at one time disembarked
more than 50 passenger trains per day.
</P>
<P>
   Stretching like a ribbon from the Katy Depot, Main Street is
home to a diverse collection of businesses that include a winery, a
bow (as in arrows) shop and galleries with cute names such as the
Little Louvre.
</P>
<P>
   Sewell's Blue Moon Antiques Mall also is on Main Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have enough art galleries, antique malls and
bed-and-breakfasts to keep visitors busy for two days,'' Sewell
says, adding that many weekenders from Dallas and Fort Worth know
Denison as well as the locals.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Main Street is the 1920 Rialto Theater, one of several
downtown movie houses that entertained Denison residents and
visitors during the town's boom days. The 900-seat Rialto's claim
to fame was a visit by Montgomery Clift, who came to town for the
1948 world premiere of his film ``Red River,'' co-starring John
Wayne.
</P>
<P>
   Denison's only theater, the Rialto is enjoying a renaissance.
Main Street Country Showcase presents Branson-style entertainment
to standing-room-only crowds each Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, downtown is the place to be.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
