<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 13:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4436 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-PERFECT-STORM-HNS &LR;      08-30 1365
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERFECT-STORM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRET HELPS THE GULF COAST GET IN SHIPSHAPE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JAMES PINKERTON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CORPUS CHRISTI, Texas _ At his baitshop beneath the John F.
Kennedy Causeway, Wilbert Gohlke and his wife scrubbed out bait
tanks they hope will soon be brimming with shrimp.
</P>
<P>
   Gohlke, 70 and a veteran of four decades of wresting a living
from the bays behind Clem's Marina, has a hunch Hurricane Bret did
the Texas coast a favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fishing and shrimping is good after a storm. I think all the
water that comes in from the Gulf of Mexico, it's good. It cleans
out all the dead water,'' said Gohlke.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the state's top marine scientists predict Bret's massive
infusion of freshwater will bring long-term, beneficial effects to
South Texas bay systems normally closed off from freshwater and
saltwater inflows. The flushing of the bays will mean more than
just better sport fishing. Experts say a whole marine ecosystem of
interdependent species, ranging from invisible plankton to ungainly
brown pelicans, will be helped.
</P>
<P>
   And the pesky brown tide, which has plagued Texas bays for
nearly a decade, may have been flushed away.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the most dramatic effect of the storm can be seen on
beaches along the Gulf of Mexico. Bret's storm surge carved open 12
new channels through the barrier islands along the Gulf from Port
Isabel to Corpus Christi, allowing huge quantities of fresh sea
water to flood the bays.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you have a big storm event like this one _ and this
storm Bret went right through the center of the Laguna Madre,
dumped a lot of water, raised the tides to very high levels _ it
has a big effect on the flushing of the Laguna Madre,'' said Ken
Dunton, an associate professor at the University of Texas Marine
Science Institute at Port Aransas.
</P>
<P>
   Dunton, an expert in sea grass and coastal marshes, expects new
and expanded growth of three of the five species of sea grass,
which serve as a nursery for shrimp, crabs and fish. Those grasses
_ shoal grass, manatee grass and wigeon grass _ are also an
important food source for millions of ducks that winter in Texas
bays.
</P>
<P>
   ``The long-term benefits of increased freshwater inflows through
a major event such as a hurricane to Texas estuaries far outweigh
the short-term, negative effects. Long-term, you'll see increased
habitat utilization by commercially important species of finfish
and shellfish,'' including shrimp, blue crabs, trout, redfish and
black drum, Dunton said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the immediate short-term concerns is the heavy runoff
from farm lands, which means increased nitrates that promote algae
blooms such as brown tide. Other concerns are that larval marine
life could have been flushed out of protective bays into the Gulf;
sea grass could be covered in silt in areas near the new channels.
</P>
<P>
   When Bret moved ashore late Sunday, huge quantities of rainwater
were dumped directly into a number of South Texas bays with
relatively high salt levels, rapidly lowering their salinity. As
the storm moved inland, additional freshwater poured into the bays
after draining into creeks, sloughs and rivers that form the
watershed for the lower Laguna Madre, Baffin Bay, the Nueces
estuary _ which includes Corpus Christi Bay, Nueces Bay and Redfish
Bay _ and the Aransas estuary.
</P>
<P>
   ``What that means is when you flush the system like that, you're
carrying away a lot of material in the Laguna Madre that has been
sitting there decaying for a long time, dead sea grasses and
vegetation that has been rotting, and you're revitalizing the
system,'' said Dunton, who has been studying the bay system for the
last 13 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're exposing substrates, or (bottom) areas that have not
been exposed for a while, providing perhaps new opportunity for sea
grass growth or growth expansion, through the removal of this dead
and decaying material.''
</P>
<P>
   Late last week, state wildlife biologists and officials from the
Texas General Land Office were preparing to take aerial photographs
of Gulf beaches where Bret cut a dozen new channels above and below
the Port Mansfield cut, which divides North and South Padre Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hurricane has literally wiped out part of the island,''
Jock Whitworth, superintendent of Padre Island National Seashore,
told the Corpus Christi Caller-Times. ``It's a huge natural
phenomenon. That's what barrier islands do for us is dissipate part
of that energy. It's kind of exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   The granite jetty at the Mansfield cut, once accessible by
vehicle from South Padre Island, is now blocked by four wide
channels to the south, said Deputy Land Commissioner Andrew
Neblett. The largest of the new channels is 50 to 60 yards wide and
3 feet deep.
</P>
<P>
   Most experts expect the channels to be temporary, eventually
silting up and disappearing, some as soon as several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   But the storm's benefits will take longer to realize,
``something we'll see over the next year or two. You'll see it in
the amount of aquatic life, the vegetation, and the (marine)
creatures you'll see over a period of time,'' Neblett predicts.
</P>
<P>
   UT's Dunton, the sea grass expert, and colleague Paul Montagna
note that it normally can take a year or longer to flush out the
Laguna Madre and Baffin Bay, which have few connections to the Gulf
and limited freshwater flowing into them due to the arid South
Texas climate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The complete area of Baffin Bay and Laguna Madre, we think it
takes a year to flush naturally. So clearly this big event has a
beneficial effect, flushing it on the order of a couple of days or
a week,'' said Montagna, a research scientist at UT Marine Science
Institute.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers believe brown tide has been flushed from a
number of small ``refuge'' bays where plankton has lingered for a
decade. Montagna and other marine scientists began extensive
sampling on Friday in those bays to see if the brown tide remains.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big issue to us is the brown tide, which started in 1990
and has persisted,'' Montagna said. ``We had been predicting it
would take a big event like this to flush the system, and we're
hoping that's what happened. We're hoping we won't see brown tide
for many, many more years.''
</P>
<P>
   Montagna also notes that new channels to the Gulf benefit a
number of marine species, including shrimp, which spawn in the
ocean, but whose offspring migrate into the protective bays to
mature.
</P>
<P>
   ``So again, there is a direct oceanic connection which I'm sure
hasn't occurred since Hurricane Allen (in 1980),'' the scientist
said. `` It's good, because almost all the organisms, and many of
the fish and shrimp and crabs in the bay, have an
estuarian-dependent life cycle. They spend their adult lives in the
ocean and their juvenile lives in the bays, so it's really
important they have good ways to get to the ocean.''
</P>
<P>
   Fishing guides and outfitters say they already have seen
increased activity in the bays just days after the storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get all the new water and oxygen, it really turns the
fish on, and there is more bait for them to eat,'' said Roger Viar,
manager of the Marker 37 Marina on Corpus Christi Bay. ``I don't
know, they get real frisky.''
</P>
<P>
   Viar reported parties taking limits of trout and redfish in
Baffin Bay late last week, which he attributes to a recharge of the
bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``It brings a lot of freshwater with the rain and it drops the
water temperature down, and it's probably down to the low 70s now.
That does a lot of good because it brings your crabs out of hiding
_ your crustaceans and shrimp _ they bury themselves when it gets
hot. It brings in new oxygen for the water, and it helps the grass
... and gets rid of the old stagnant stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   In Port Isabel, fishing guide Gilbert Vela said the influx of
fresh sea water through new channels in the island has
traditionally improved the fishing in the landlocked bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always a plus, bringing freshwater or getting a cut to
the ocean,'' he said. ``I caught 18 reds (redfish) today out of one
school. We boxed eight, and the rest were oversized and we released
them. So the fish are there.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
