<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSS FANS ROCK 'N' ROLY-POLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EILEEN MCNAMARA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thunder thighs are clogging up ``Thunder Road'' and ``Hungry
Hearts'' are chowing their way through the concession stands.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Springsteen and the E Street Band are the stars of a
sellout, six-city reunion tour this summer, but the real show is in
the stands.
</P>
<P>
   The Boss sold out his first two shows in Boston in 30 minutes,
all five in less than three hours. In five nights last week, he
drew nearly 100,000 fevered fans to the Fleet Center. Clearly, in
the decade since he last toured the United States with the band,
Springsteen's appeal has not diminished.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, neither has the size of his audience.
</P>
<P>
   Remember when the only food you were likely to encounter at a
rock 'n' roll concert was an herbally enhanced brownie? Entering
the FleetCenter last week, your first impluse was to wonder whether
you had wandered into a wrestling match by mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Who were all those graying Baby Boomers with nacho chips and
deep-dish pizzas on their laps? A glimpse in a pane of glass at the
refreshment counter proved a quick reality check. They were us, of
course _ members of the generation that long ago parted with its
hairline and its waistline, but will never surrender its youth.
</P>
<P>
   We are not aging gracefully, boys and girls.
</P>
<P>
   It is harder to say what was more disorienting Friday night,
pulling into a rock concert in the family minivan (behind a Volvo
and a Mercedes-Benz), watching rock fans check in with their baby
sitters by cell phone from their balcony seats, or seeing hundreds
of flickering Bic lighters reflected in hundreds of pairs of
bifocals in the darkened arena.
</P>
<P>
   At least there is no gender disparity at a Springsteen concert;
there's an equal opportunity to embarrass yourself in public. Last
week was enough to make one ponder whether there shouldn't be a
city ordinance regulating the age of women who wear spandex and men
who don tie-dyed T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   Previous generations of men might have dreamed of being fighter
pilots or international spies. This one, it is clear, still
fantasizes about rock stardom. To watch men of a certain age
pumping their arms, playing air guitars, and spinning imaginary
microphones over their heads, like so many Roger Daltrey wannabes,
was to wonder whether some boys ever grow up.
</P>
<P>
   Until you checked out the women.
</P>
<P>
   Mothers who left adolescent daughters at home dreaming about a
date with one of the Backstreet Boys were screaming themselves
hoarse at every shot on the overhead screen of Springsteen's
sweat-drenched chest. We haven't swooned like that in Boston since
Mark Lindsay of Paul Revere and the Raiders threw his tricorn hat
into the orchestra seats at Symphony Hall during a rousing chorus
of ``Kicks'' in the summer of 1967.
</P>
<P>
   About the only people in the crowd who did not look like they
needed to be told to act their age were Springsteen and his wife
and band mate, Patti Scialfa. He of the taut muscles, tight jeans,
and boundless energy. She of the sunken cheekbones, leather pants,
and ``I've-got-Bruce-and-you-don't'' smirk.
</P>
<P>
   They don't have to lie about their age; they defy it.
</P>
<P>
   He is 49 years old; she is not much younger and the mother of
three young children. Yet they played relentless rock 'n' roll for
three hours each night without a pause or a discernible diminution
of energy. (Poor Peter Wolf of the J. Geils Band. With the
mummified mien of a Mick Jagger, he could only suffer by comparison
with the Boss during his guest appearance on Friday night.)
</P>
<P>
   In what Jim Sullivan, the Globe's rock critic, describes as the
``Church of Bruce,'' it is easy to feel like an agnostic at a Billy
Graham revival meeting unless you know from the first chord every
song about to be sung and every word once it begins. Among the
faithful, many of whom attended all five concerts last week, it is
not enough to appreciate Springsteen's music; you have to become an
acolyte.
</P>
<P>
   Getting the lyrics down is one form of homage; putting the fork
down might be another. The Boss, bless his heart, loves us anyway.
(``You're not a beauty but, hey, you're all right.'') But if our
arteries are going to hold out long enough for us to catch the next
reunion tour, we are going to have to hit the gym or the track.
It's the gospel, according to Bruce: ``Tramps like us, baby we were
born to run.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Eileen McNamara's e-mail address is mcnamara(at sign)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
