<DOCNO> NYT19990830.0219 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4445 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-SCI-ALCOHOLISM-BOS &LR;      08-30 1608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-ALCOHOLISM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDICATIONS MAY REDUCE ALCOHOL CRAVINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A pill to cure alcoholism?
</P>
<P>
   We're not there yet, and a pill may never be enough by itself.
But leaders in alcoholism research report significant recent
progress in the use of drugs to diminish alcoholics' craving for
the substance, increase their abstinence rates, and convert problem
drinkers into moderate imbibers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're entering a major new epoch in alcoholism
treatment,'' said Dr. Enoch Gordis, director of the National
Institute on Alcohol Abuse and Alcoholism (NIAAA), who will
summarize recent research Sept. 2 at an international meeting in
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the neuroscience cooking along as it is, and the prospect
that we'll find genes related to alcoholism, we'll have far more
targeted drug therapies for alcoholism in the next five to 10
years,'' Gordis predicts.
</P>
<P>
   The social impact could be enormous. An estimated 14 million
Americans are alcohol abusers _ about 10 percent of adult men and
three percent of women _ and the problem costs society more than
$100 billion a year. Yet only about 700,000 people are in
alcoholism treatment at any given time, federal officials say.
</P>
<P>
   The pioneer ``anti-craving'' drug of Gordis's new epoch,
naltrexone or ReVia, is already on the market, though not yet
widely used. This month the Archives of General Psychiatry
published an encouraging study on a second such agent, nalmefene.
And last week in Paris, researchers discussed (behind closed doors)
the first results of a large US trial of acamprosate, a third
anti-alcoholism drug already in widespread use in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us are sworn to secrecy, but basically the European
results have been very positive, and I would imagine the US results
will be positive too,'' said Dr. Robert Swift of Brown University's
Center for Alcohol and Addiction Studies, one of the US study sites
for acamprosate.
</P>
<P>
   Encouraged by the accumulating drug studies, the NIAAA this fall
will launch a major program in Boston and nine other cities called
Project Combine to test whether combinations of drugs, along with
established ``talk therapies,'' can significantly improve long-term
success rates in treating alcoholism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under the best conditions currently, you might get total
alcohol abstinence after 12 to 15 months of treatment for a
minority of roughly a third of patients,'' Gordis said. ``Treatment
is of modest help to a smaller group, and it will fail in about
half. We can't cure alcoholism yet, but then we can't cure most
chronic diseases _ and that's what alcoholism is.''
</P>
<P>
   The new approaches reflect a dawning of scientists'
understanding about the complex brain chemistry of alcohol
addiction, first among experimental animals trained or bred to seek
alcohol and more recently among human subjects.
</P>
<P>
   Alcohol is a brain stimulant, accounting for its pleasurable,
sociable, and de-inhibiting effects. But it's also a sedative,
dulling normal cognitive and motor processes and also damping
anxiety and tension. Thus, it's not surprising that alcohol acts on
several important neurotransmitters and their respective receptors
on brain cells, with both acute and long-term effects.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, many of alcohol's stimulant effects are due to the
chemical's action on dopamine neurons, which are instrumental in
the brain's pleasure-seeking or ``reward'' systems.
</P>
<P>
   Alcohol also inhibits receptors for glutamate, the brain's major
excitatory neurotransmitter, responsible for arousal and attention.
The brain reacts to long-term alcohol ingestion by increasing nerve
cell arousal to counter alcohol's depressant effect. When an
alcohol-addicted individual stops drinking, this chronically
over-excited state becomes unbearable, producing the notorious
symptoms of withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   That's not all alcohol does to the brain. It also enhances the
function of neural receptors for GABA, the brain's primary
inhibitory neurotransmitter. And it lowers levels of serotonin, a
neurotransmitter that modulates mood and may mediate aggressive or
violent behavior.
</P>
<P>
   The very complexity of these brain effects offers multiple
opportunities for targeting drugs to counter alcohol's action.
Naltrexone and nalmefene counteract the brain's natural opiates to
dull the craving for alcohol. Acamprosate works on the glutamate
system in ways not entirely understood, somehow normalizing the
hyper-excited state that chronic alcohol abuse causes.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers hope that combining two or more different-acting
drugs will damp the drive to seek alcohol while preventing the
distress of withdrawal symptoms. But, as studies with naltrexone
have shown, it will only work if patients faithfully take the
drugs, which is where counseling and supportive talk therapy come
in.
</P>
<P>
   Another current strain of research focuses on which patients are
more susceptible to alcohol dependence, and which are more likely
to respond to drug therapy. After eight years of effort,
researchers have identified dozens of ``candidate genes'' that put
patients at risk for alcoholism, and four human chromosomes where
those genes are likely to lurk. The next step is to tease out the
genes and determine what proteins they code for. Voila _ more
potential targets for drug therapy.
</P>
<P>
   But merely devising ingenious new treatment approaches for
alcoholism will not be enough. Putting treatment advances into
widespread use is another matter, as the disappointing experience
with naltrexone shows. Naltrexone won federal approval four and a
half years ago _ the first anti-alcoholism drug since the 1948
approval of Antabuse (disulfiram).
</P>
<P>
   Antabuse was supposed to cure alcoholism by making users
violently ill if they drank alcohol while taking the medication.
But the well-known drug is not widely used today, since a large
1986 study showed no difference in abstinence rates among patients
who took it.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, a number of studies in North American and Europe
have shown that naltrexone combined with supportive ``talk
therapy'' produced long-term abstinence rates two to three times
higher than patients who took placebo pills along with
psychotherapy. The new drug, which interferes with the
neurochemistry of the brain's pleasure-seeking circuits, is the
first anti-alcoholism medication to act on the brain's chemistry of
craving and reward. But the alcoholism treatment community has not
embraced the drug approach with enthusiasm, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Naltrexone hasn't made the inroads one would expect,'' said
Klaus Miczek of Tufts University School of Medicine, a co-chairman
of this week's joint meeting of the US and European Behavioral
Pharmacology Societies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last time I heard, naltrexone was only selling in the
range of $20 million to $30 million a year, which is minuscule,''
added Dr. Raymond F. Anton of the Medical University of South
Carolina in Charlestown. ``Part of the reason is the lack of
knowledge among treatment providers and the general public about
the effects of alcohol on the brain and how medications can affect
that.''
</P>
<P>
   The ignorance may be due to the lackluster marketing of
naltrexone by its manufacturer, DuPont-Merck, which won approval
only two years before the drug's patent expired, greatly lessening
its profitability. Many alcoholism treatment providers and dominant
groups such as Alcoholics Anonymous have a strong bias against
using drugs to treat addictions and favor social supports,
counseling, self-help, willpower, and spiritual approaches.
</P>
<P>
   Because of this longstanding orientation _ and the lack of
effective pharmacologic agents _ alcoholism treatment has been
``dominated by non-medical approaches,'' Anton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of evidence that physicians don't do a good job
in identifying people who could benefit from treatment,'' the South
Carolina researcher added. ``And there is some concern among
non-medical counselors that an overemphasis on medications will
diminish attention to counseling and behavioral therapies.'' Gordis
speaks of ``a legacy of ideology about alcoholism which has impeded
acceptance of pharmaceutical therapy.''
</P>
<P>
   This may change with the availability, possibly within the next
year, of more anti-alcoholism drugs. Drug companies are finally in
hot pursuit of such agents, and the European company Merck-Lipha
developing acamprosate is aggressively seeking US Food and Drug
Administration approval for that drug.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought naltrexone would change the world, but it didn't,''
said an observer. ``But the advent of a couple more drugs is sure
to make an impression on the treatment community.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Gordis said, it should be possible to harmonize the
opinions of those who emphasize willpower and social supports with
the neuroscience and genetic research that are revealing the
biological basis of alcoholism. In other words, drugs to treat
alcoholism do not relieve alcoholic patients of responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``A person who has been drinking heavily for some time is
largely overcome with the biological pressure of craving for
alcohol and the physiological demand to drink,'' Gordis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there are two situations in which the individual still has
a major responsibility to do something,'' he continued. ``First, if
a person is a member of a family in which there have been drinking
problems, he should be very alert to early signs of a problem.
Second, there's the established alcoholic who has become sober,
been presented with the impact of alcohol, and has the chance to do
something about it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
