<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4448 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-FOOD-AND-WINE-LIFEBEA     08-30 1244
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-AND-WINE-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MARRIAGE OF FOOD AND WINE
</HEADLINE>
  Includes color photos of Chef Evely and a plate of food 
 By MIRIAM SILVER 
 c.1999 NYT Regional Newspapers 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ''Gray meat and brown vegetables'' was the standard home-cooked
fare for Mary Evely when she was growing up in Michigan. Today,
Evely is an expert on another culinary pairing: food and wine.
</P>
<P>
   Not only is she chef at Simi Winery in Healdsburg, Calif., where
combining foods and wines is a studied pursuit, but she is also the
author of a cookbook called ''The Vintner's Table,'' aimed at
giving others guidelines on how to balance the tastes and textures
of various foods and wines.
</P>
<P>
   The book was the first place winner in the ''first book''
category of the 1998 Julia Child Cookbook Awards, sponsored by the
International Association of Culinary Professionals. That the award
was named for Julia Child was particularly meaningful to Evely.
</P>
<P>
   ''I couldn't accept the award for myself,'' Evely said, ''but on
behalf of Julia Child, because she taught me how to cook.'' Instead
of going to culinary school, Evely studied the teachings of three
food luminaries: Craig Claiborne, James Beard and, her favorite,
Julia Child.
</P>
<P>
   Her enthusiasm for food was cultivated in New York City, where
she was an art student at Cooper Union in the early '60s.
</P>
<P>
   Evely lost herself in the gustatory pleasures of the restaurants
and sidewalk cafes in Little Italy, Chinatown and the other ethnic
areas that crowd the city. Her friends in the arts became equally
as passionate about food.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a gathering of interests and energy. It was like
critical mass,'' Evely said. ''We all started getting interested in
food and cooking. We'd start having dinner parties and getting into
fun one-upmanship. That got me interested in wine.''
</P>
<P>
   But Evely's path to chefdom was not straight.
</P>
<P>
   She moved to Los Angeles in the late '60s, working as a graphic
artist and then opening a clothing store. She stayed interested in
food and wine, joining a chapter of Les Amis du Vin (The Friends of
Wine). She started making annual trips north, mostly to Sonoma
County, to try the wine and began selling California wine in her
store.
</P>
<P>
   After losing the lease for her store, she decided to move to
Sonoma County. In 1983, Simi Winery hired her to run visitors
services. Her talent for pairing wine and food came out of wine
tasting parties Evely was involved in with other people in the food
and wine business.
</P>
<P>
   She tells of the night when each person brought a bottle of 1977
cabernet sauvignon and some food to go with it.
</P>
<P>
   ''Someone brought smoked salmon. I loved it. I started tasting
the wine; it tasted terrible. The smoked salmon was destroying the
wine. It's a huge conflict,'' she said. ''It really makes a
difference. I wanted to know about this.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, Evely set up the first wine and food pairing events at
the winery, long before wine and food pairing meant much in the
area.
</P>
<P>
   While the winery had a small kitchen and dining room, there was
no equipment, so Evely hired a caterer. But the stuffed grape
leaves were stuffed with canned mushrooms and Evely thought: ''I
can do better than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Next time around, she brought in her own kitchen equipment and
set out to learn about which wine went well with which food.
</P>
<P>
   ''I sat down with the group and we tasted six different wines
with six different kinds of food. I taught myself by doing those
tastings. I started seeing patterns, certain categories of food I
could predict would work with certain kinds of wine.''
</P>
<P>
   Now called The Vintner's Table series, Evely's annual winery
events are centered around particular food producers or products,
paired with the appropriate wines. The dinners, which range in
price from $40 to $65, were among the first such events, which many
other Wine Country restaurants and wineries now present.
</P>
<P>
   In ''The Vintner's Table''cookbook, based on these ongoing food
and wine programs at the winery, Evely shares her experiences
through recipes that are divided by wine varietals.
</P>
<P>
   The sweetness in a particular dish, Evely advises, should always
be more subtle than the sweetness of the wine that is being served
with it. Otherwise, she says, ''the palate cannot perceive the
fruit in the wine and it appears thin, tart or bitter.''
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, most desserts, she said, do not do well with
most wines unless the wines are slightly sweeter than the food,
such as sweet sparkling wine, a sauterne, or a cognac. But, Evely
nevertheless includes some dessert recipes in her cookbook.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't have a cookbook without dessert, because I love
dessert,'' said Evely, who maniacally clips and tries almost every
new cookie recipe she finds.
</P>
<P>
   She hopes the cookbook will lead people who love food to care
about wine. It's a sneaky way, she said, to get more people to
drink good wine.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am trying to bring people into the fold,'' she said. ''Wine
is such a wonderful part of life. I can't separate it from food.''
</P>
<P>
   Typical of her commentaries in the book is this one, which
accompanies a recipe for Chicken Charmoula: ''The strong green
herbs, the heat from the cayenne pepper, and the acid of the lemon
juice would fight with any wine other than sauvignon blanc. Ask
your local wine merchant to help you avoid the softer
''wanna-be-Chardonnay'' styles of this varietal, however, which
would not work nearly as well with this dish.''
</P>
<P>
   She says sauvignon blanc is her favorite wine because it is the
most ''food-friendly.''
</P>
<P>
   CHICKEN CHARMOULA
</P>
<P>
   Serves six
</P>
<P>
   1 clove garlic
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped flat-leaf Italian parsley
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped cilantro
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon sweet paprika
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   6 boneless, skinless chicken breast halves
</P>
<P>
   1 cup nonfat yogurt
</P>
<P>
   Cilantro sprigs for garnish
</P>
<P>
   For the seasoning mixture, mince the garlic in a food processor
fitted with a steel blade to make about 1 teaspoon minced garlic.
Add the parsley, cilantro, cumin, paprika, salt and cayenne pepper
and process until minced. Add the lemon juice and olive oil and
process until smooth.
</P>
<P>
   Rinse the chicken and pat dry. Spread half the seasoning mixture
over the chicken and cover. Chill the chicken and remaining
seasoning mixture for 2 to 12 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the broiler or prepare a fire in the grill. Grill or
broil the chicken for 3 minutes on each side or until it springs
back to the touch and is cooked through. Place on serving plates.
</P>
<P>
   Mix the reserved seasoning mixture with the yogurt. Serve the
chicken with a dollop of the yogurt sauce and grilled vegetables;
garnish with the cilantro.
</P>
<P>
   Note: This dish is equally good hot or at room temperature. It
also makes great sandwiches.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Miriam Silver writes for The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa,
Calif.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this ``separate buy'' article, call
New York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
(732) 390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
