r l BC-SCHOOL-CRISES-LIFEBEA     08-30 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-CRISES-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KIDS CAN LEARN FROM SCHOOL CRISES
</HEADLINE>
  By LAURA TAXEL 
 c.1999 magazine 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although the event lies almost 40 years in my past, the memory
of getting on the wrong bus and going to the wrong place on my
first day of first grade is still vivid. When I arrived at school,
nobody had any record of me. No one knew where I should go. I
watched all the other children go with their teachers, and I was
left behind, confused and frightened.
</P>
<P>
   The principal took me under her wing and after a lengthy
question and answer session and a few phone calls, she located my
mother, who, I was assured, was on her way to get me. Meanwhile the
principal figured out where I actually belonged.
</P>
<P>
   I have often remembered that day and the realization that I
survived is an important part of the memory. A bad thing happened
to me, but I came out okay.
</P>
<P>
   This was something I knew even then, a lesson learned and
understood on the spot with no explanation necessary. I noticed
that day that strangers _ adults I'd never met before _ were nice
to me. People wanted to help. Being unhappy was something I could
endure. In fact, getting myself lost wasn't as awful as I had
always imagined it would be. In fact, it was interesting.
</P>
<P>
   I think perhaps that it was on that day that I began to become a
person who would move through the world with a basic trust that
things always work out, that this is a generally kind universe, and
that I would be safe in it. I believe that's a working definition
of confidence. It is something that has helped me countless times
in my own life, and it's something I very much want my children to
feel.
</P>
<P>
   So it was with this in mind that I agreed, when my nine-year-old
twin boys requested permission to walk to school alone on the first
day of a new school year. They had never before braved the occasion
without a parent in hand.
</P>
<P>
   They left the house, emboldened with a sense of adventure and
new notebooks, a little hesitant to be on their own, but, for
reasons never explained to me, determined to do it. I thought about
them during the day, hoping that they were all right. If they'd
somehow gotten lost, I told myself, then surely I would, like my
mother before me, have heard about it.
</P>
<P>
   We had decided I would meet them at school at 3:00. They knew
they'd be so excited they wouldn't be able to wait till they got
home to tell me all about their day. Standing in the sunshine,
networking with all the other parents meeting children, I
discovered that many were quite surprised I had not been there that
morning.
</P>
<P>
   There was, I thought, some veiled criticism, in remarks like ``I
couldn't believe you weren't here with your boys on the first day
of school'', or ``I don't think my nine year old is mature enough
to handle being alone on the first day.'' Another told us that she
and her son had come to school the day before the first day for a
dry run. The building was open as staff prepared, so they could
find his classroom, meet his teacher, and be sure the next day held
no surprises.
</P>
<P>
   Some mothers were quick to tell me that things hadn't gone well
that morning. The school had tried a new approach to bringing
teachers and children together in groups outside the building and
the result had been rather chaotic. Some youngsters had not been
able to locate their teachers, others couldn't find their
classrooms once inside.
</P>
<P>
   The parents were visibly upset with the fact that it had not
been a perfectly smooth operation. I had some guilt pangs that my
boys had gone off into this melee on their own.
</P>
<P>
   Over milk and cookies later that afternoon, we talked about it.
One of the boys remarked that it had been sort of crazy and he
wasn't sure at first where he was supposed to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``Were you sorry you'd gone to school alone,'' I asked``Were you frightened, did you get upset?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course not,'' he said, giving me a comforting grin that
made me feel as though I was the one who needed reassurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We handled it just fine,'' added his brother. ``I asked
someone for help,'' said Simon with visible pride, ``and Nathan
figured it out by himself.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Did it make you feel nervous when you didn't know where to
go?'' I probed, determined to know about any moments of suffering
they may have endured.
</P>
<P>
   ``A little,'' said Nathan, ``but it wasn't a bad kind of
nervous.'' And then, having had enough of both cookies and
conversation, they ran out to play.
</P>
<P>
   They were clearly neither traumatized nor put off by the fact
that things had not been smoothly orchestrated. And although many
parents obviously thought that the process should have been handled
differently, arranged so that it would be easy and problem free, I
could see that the first day had gone perfectly for my children.
</P>
<P>
   It was an opportunity, without much danger, for them to learn
many things about themselves and their ability to come out the
other end of a rocky encounter. I suddenly saw a certain
mythological character to the experience; they'd faced a dragon,
albeit a small 4th grade sized one, and like their mother before
them, survived the encounter, and even vanquished the foe.
</P>
<P>
   I'm glad I was not there to shepherd them through their
difficulties. I'm happy they suffered a brief, but oh-so-bearable
moment of distress, and then found a way to take care of
themselves. It means that they are now one step closer to being
ready for life, their own life, which they will inevitably have to
live without me watching over them and fixing everything. This day,
imperfect as it was, had allowed them a chance to add confidence to
their repertoire of responses to the world. If they're anything
like me, they will remember the event in the years to come with a
certain deep and abiding pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Laura Taxel is an Ohio-based free-lance writer.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this ``separate buy'' article, call
New York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
(732) 390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
