<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARMY-ADS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMY CONSIDERS NEW SLOGAN TO REVERSE RECRUITING SLUMP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SIG CHRISTENSON  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Army Secretary Louis Caldera says he will take a
hard look at the future of the service's familiar jingle, ``Be all
that you can be.''
</P>
<P>
   Caldera isn't sure how to modify or replace the slogan, listed
by Advertising Age magazine as one of the century's leading
commercial tunes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is a question of whether it's a little bit
dated,'' Caldera said of the slogan, which was introduced in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   The Army is reassessing its advertising strategy as the service
tries to reverse its worst recruiting year since 1979, falling
short by about 7,000 enlistees. And things will get tougher next
year as the service seeks to sign up 80,000 active-duty recruits,
5,500 above this year's goal.
</P>
<P>
   A $92 million publicity campaign is planned, but the Army would
like to boost its ad budget to as much as $130 million. Just what
the new ad campaign will look like when it debuts in December isn't
yet known. But there are hints the time-honored ``Be all that you
can be,'' which replaced three previous Army themes used over the
years, is already on the way out.
</P>
<P>
   The song was scrapped in a series of 15- and 30-second spots
that first aired last October. The slogan instead appeared in
writing at the end of the commercials, which continue to air. Focus
groups thought the jingle was too old, and preferred to see it
rather than hear it, said Col. Kevin Kelley of the Fort Knox,
Ky.-based Army Recruiting Command.
</P>
<P>
   Caldera said the Army had not discarded the slogan because it is
so readily recognized. It is ranked by Advertising Age, a trade
weekly, 18th among the century's 100 top ad campaigns, pulling
ahead of Burger King's ``Have it your way,'' Campbell Soup's
``Mmm-mm good,'' and Budweiser's ``This Bud's for you.''
</P>
<P>
   The Army theme song topped the General Motors Corp.'s ``See the
USA in your Chevrolet,'' Coca Cola's ``It's the Real Thing,'' and
Oscar Meyer's ``I wish I was an Oscar Meyer Wiener.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really become part of the lexicon of America,'' Kelley
said.
</P>
<P>
   The new campaign will shift its focus from high school
graduates, and concentrate more on community college and vocational
students, as well as Hispanics, blacks and women, he said. The ad
drive will target cities considered the most fertile grounds for
cultivating recruits, among them El Paso, Texas; Fresno, Calif.;
Houston; Jacksonville, Fla.; Phoenix; San Antonio; Seattle; and
Waco, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Cities likely to see fewer ad spots are Chicago, New York and
Los Angeles, said Kelley, who heads the Army's ad campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Air Force, which has kicked off an 18-month, $54
million advertising blitz in hopes of boosting sagging enlistment,
the Army sees advertising as a key in its campaign to win the
hearts and minds of young people.
</P>
<P>
   Changes include adding more rural recruiting stations, moving
some offices from strip shopping centers to busy malls, and giving
recruiters cell phones and computers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Caldera, the nation's first Hispanic Army secretary, said his
service would put more money into Spanish-language advertising.
About $8 million will be spent for those spots.
</P>
<P>
   The Army also will reach out to Hispanics this fall as it
unveils a pilot project in California, Texas and the Northeast that
pays high school dropouts to earn their equivalency diplomas.
Caldera has said his service's recruiting woes would disappear if
it got its ``fair share'' of Hispanics who make up 11.4 percent of
the population but 7 percent of the service.
</P>
<P>
   To reach them and others, he said, the Army must air ads that
appeal to a wide spectrum of people. ``Right now we have one
message being broadcast primarily at sports-watching audiences,''
Caldera said. Though ``Be all that you can be'' hasn't been
discarded because it's so well known, he said, it stresses the
tangible personal benefits of the service, rather than
self-sacrifice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about you personally, as opposed to serve your country,''
Caldera SAID. ``So we do need to look at it, we do need to look at
whether it needs to be updated.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, ``We wouldn't want to discard it without thinking
very hard about it given how much we've invested in that slogan.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
