<HEADLINE>
HORIZONTAL DRILLING ALLOWS OPERATORS TO CUT TIME, SAVE MONEY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NELSON ANTOSH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Oil-field service companies say that by using the
latest technology they could drill a well at One Shell Plaza in
downtown Houston, swing horizontally, and after several miles of
boring, hit a target half the size of a business desk.
</P>
<P>
   The technology behind that boast comes in many forms.
</P>
<P>
   Boring inch by inch through rock and compressed sediment, the
drill bit is guided by computers. If it seems to be heading off
course, the driller sends a series of pulses _ almost like a Morse
code _ down through the drilling mud that flows within the drill
pipe.
</P>
<P>
   The pulses coming back up through the mud tell the operator
precisely in what direction the tool is headed.
</P>
<P>
   And, to get a better feel for what is happening in an invisible
spot far away, an attached tool package measures naturally
occurring gamma radiation, which tells whether the bit is cutting
through shale, or moving through a strata containing oil, natural
gas or saltwater.
</P>
<P>
   At a recent conference, Baker Hughes Chairman Max Lukens said
that his company's latest steerable drilling system could start
downtown, head west beneath Interstate 10, then cross under the
Houstonian conference center where he was talking, and come up in
the Galleria ice rink.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the major oil-field service company was making that
claim for his company's AutoTrak tool because hitting a diminutive
target can be the difference between a major discovery and a dry
hole.
</P>
<P>
   And, being able to hit within a couple of feet is almost a given
now for a directional driller, says Dave Bergt of Schlumberger,
whose Anadrill subsidiary also manufactures steering tools.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, if the drill bit ends up two feet above the
oil-bearing deposit, ``you've just thrown away a couple million
dollars,'' says Bergt, describing the cost of drilling a dry hole.
</P>
<P>
   The ability to drill horizontally for miles is particularly
important offshore because one such rig can do the work of several
that had to be used previously.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to deepwater drilling, ``you will see a ton of
advancement in these technologies,'' says Marshall Adkins, an
energy service analyst in Houston for Raymond James &AMP; Associates,
an institutional research company.
</P>
<P>
   Most technologies to date have been evolutionary, according to
Adkins. The revolutionary ones will be in fiber optics, deepwater
drilling, underbalanced drilling and seismic data collection, he
predicts. ``We are on the edge.''
</P>
<P>
   One idea involves running fiber-optic cable into the hole to
monitor the well. Another has seismic companies suspending their
listening devices in established wells, using the crunching of a
drill bit as a source of vibrations.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the improvement is from horizontal drilling, which
requires more accurate targeting of the bit than a vertical hole.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the obvious advantage of being able to hit one or
more &UR;  &LR; slim-profile &UR;  &LR; vertical pockets, says Raymond James &AMP;
Associates, horizontal wells produce oil and gas five to 10 times
faster than vertical wells. This rapid drain is considered
important, although horizontal wells cost one-and-one-half to three
times as much to drill.
</P>
<P>
   Schlumberger's tools have been used in drilling record-setting
horizontal wells, one at the tip of South America and another on
the southern coast of England, drilled laterally nearly seven
miles.
</P>
<P>
   The current record was set last month with a 35,196-foot hole _
or ``stepout'' _ on the Wytch Farm Field in England, says Linda
Silinsky of Schlumberger Oilfield Services in Sugar Land.
</P>
<P>
   Using drilling rigs sitting on dry land, the tools drilled
horizontally under the sea to reach oil.
</P>
<P>
   Traditional drilling methods would have required either the use
of an expensive offshore rig or the construction of an artificial
island for $260 million, Bergt says.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line, according to Raymond James &AMP; Associates, is
that technologies of the past 10 years have allowed operators to
continually cut the time it takes to drill a well. This saves
money.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of finding oil and gas has plunged, but that is more a
function of oil companies selecting only the cheapest prospects to
drill, in line with recent oil prices, the study says.
</P>
<P>
   Technology such as three-dimensional seismic data collection has
helped the industry by boosting the success rate of wells, which
means fewer dry holes.
</P>
<P>
   And, drillers are using technology to go deeper and deeper.
Average U.S. well depth will exceed 6,500 feet in 2003, Raymond
James &AMP; Associates estimates.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to tapping into previously inaccessible reservoirs,
there will be less damage to underground formations, which allows
more oil and gas to be recovered.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these concepts seem impossible to people who are not in
the oil business, however.
</P>
<P>
   Adkins and his research associates say laymen need to let go of
the idea that the steel in drill pipe is rigid. The truth is that
steel is very flexible.
</P>
<P>
   A string of drill pipe about 3 1/2 inches in diameter and
several miles long ``is about as flexible as a thin tree branch,''
the report says.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, directional drilling is best visualized as a bit
``swimming'' through the earth as it pulls a flexible leash of
drill pipe behind it. The notion of a stiff pipe pushing the bit
straight down is outdated.
</P>
<P>
   The AutoTrak tool, introduced by Baker Hughes' Inteq subsidiary
in 1997, is so steerable it can make 90 degree turns (although very
gradually), and weave to hit four or five oil deposits with the
same bit, said Product Manager Jonny Haugen from Inteq's office in
north Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike earlier tools that utilize a slight bend near the front
for steering, the AutoTrak is straight. Four pads backed by
hydraulic cylinders push on the sides of the hole to change the
direction.
</P>
<P>
   With the more-conventional bent type, the tool doesn't rotate.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to change direction, just shift the position of the
tool a little and it will follow the direction of the bend. If you
want to go straight, spin the tool and it wallows out the hole.
When making a turn with this kind of tool, only the drill bit on
the front rotates.
</P>
<P>
   On conventional directional tools the bit is turned by a mud
motor, an innovative downhole device powered by drilling mud
flowing past vanes in a turbine.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
