<HEADLINE>
WHY DOES LIGHTNING ZIG-ZAG? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ROPEIK  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Why does lightning zig-zag? If it didn't, would it affect the
bolt's speed?
</P>
<P>
   M.B., Leominster, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Let's start before the first zig. When turbulence in the air
sends particles crashing into one another, electrons get ripped
loose and those particles usually end up with either a positive or
negative charge. In a thunderstorm, the particles are usually tiny
slivers of ice, water droplets, or pieces of hail.
</P>
<P>
   In thunderstorms, the heavier particles of hail end up with a
negative charge. They fall to a lower altitude within the storm
clouds, while the updraft winds carry the lighter ice slivers and
frozen water droplets, with a positive charge, higher up. That
creates something like the top and bottom of a battery.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Uman, professor of electrical and computer engineering at
the University of Florida at Gainesville and a world-renowned
lightning expert, explains that the air breaks down and becomes a
conductor.
</P>
<P>
   Like a piece of wire, the conducting air lets the opposite
charges attract, creating a spark. That's the first zig in the
lightning. Zag is created when zig zaps an adjacent chunk of air
that already has the right electrical charge. Remember, the air
where this is happening is churning wildly. So it's almost
impossible to expect all of the particles in the next
electrically-charged chunk of air _ zag _ to be perfectly lined up
with zig when it hits. That's why lightning zig-zags.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My friends say thunder is louder in Buffalo than it is in
Boston. Can thunder be louder in some places than others?
</P>
<P>
   V.W., Boston
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes, but it's not the geographic location per se that
dictates loudness. Uman of the University of Floriday says that
loudness can vary with atmospheric conditions like humidity and
wind or the stability of the air through which the sound is
traveling, or surface topography, including buildings, that can
intensify or muffle sound waves.
</P>
<P>
   Thunder is exploding air. Since the peak temperature of
lightning in the return stroke, 50,000 degrees Fahrenheit, is five
times hotter than the surface of the sun, and it travels at 20,000
to 60,000 miles per second, it heats up air molecules faster than
they can expand. When they finally do expand _ CRACK! Or BOOM, or
RUMBLE _ depending on what direction the lightning is traveling.
</P>
<P>
   If it is up and down, perpendicular to you, all the shock waves
from the exploding air along the length of the lightning arrive at
your ear about the same time, and you get more of a crack sound.
But for every cloud-to-ground blast, five to 10 bolts of lighting
happen only up in the clouds. Intra-cloud lightning runs horizontal
to you. The first shock waves from the nearest end hit your ear
seconds before the vibrations from the far end. That produces the
more familiar rumble.
</P>
<P>
   Intra-cloud lightning can be tens of miles long, producing a
rumbling thunder that can last more than a minute.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Readers are invited to send science questions to How&AMP;Why. Write to
How&AMP;Why, Health/Science, Box 2378, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA
02107; or send via Internet to: howwhy(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
