<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-MYSTERY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POST MORTEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBIN W. WINKS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The weather and my reading mood have matched this long, hot
August: dry, desiccated, a bit severe. I twisted and turned in my
bed at night, unable to get cool even as the air conditioning
hissed and sighed away, and I tried here, there, and nearly
everywhere to find a book or two that gave me unqualified pleasure.
Did I read more critically because of the heat or despite the heat?
Whatever, discontent was the result.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Deaver's work is hailed as ``dazzling,'' ``brilliant,'' and
he is described as a brainy lawyer who quit law practice to write
full time. ``The Devil's Teardrop'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $25) is his
12th book, and that must be the problem _ too many, too fast _
though I have read only a third of his work, which may also be the
problem: Perhaps this book isn't typical of him. The plot is a
sizzler, as they say on dust jackets. On New Year's Eve, Dec. 31,
1999, in Washington, D.C., a killer mows down a group of people at
the Dupont Circle Metro station, and the mayor, already beleaguered
over an effort to introduce reforms to the city's decaying
educational system, receives a note demanding $20 million. If not
paid, the killer, soon dubbed the Digger, will strike again and
again, every four hours, killing expansively and randomly. Then the
apparent mastermind behind the robotic assassin is killed, run down
by a car, and the Digger, programmed to kill endlessly, simply goes
on. The FBI, special agent Margaret Lukas, and a retired forensic
document examiner must figure out where the Digger will strike next
and stop him.
</P>
<P>
   The premise is chilling, and the buildup holds plenty of
suspense, but the plot manipulation is as robotic as the Digger.
One-sentence paragraphs abound, illogical sequences squirm across
the page, and in the end the Digger proves both less and more
complex then we can imagine. Three times the FBI agents are trailed
by another car or person and never notice; the Digger is fired upon
repeatedly but always slips away into the darkness, the crowd, the
prose. The forensic expert behaves stupidly several times. Tiny
sentences jangle. ``Luke's cell phone rang. She answered. Listened.
Then she said, `Thanks.' She hung up, not pleased.'' This is
suspense? Writing?
</P>
<P>
   Grouchy, grouchy. Jeremiah Healy is one of my favorite writers,
and his John Francis Cuddy series, normally set in Boston, is
attractive and entertaining. In ``Spiral'' (Pocket Books, $23) he
moves Cuddy off to Florida, not for the first time, and disaster
results. The story begins with the death of Cuddy's lover in an
airplane accident. He goes to Florida to forget, and ostensibly to
help an old buddy. The buddy, known as ``the Skipper'' back in
Vietnam, is not at all interesting and everyone around him is
unpleasant. His grandmother had died during a pool party. Perhaps
someone is trying to get at the Skipper. Healy never makes us care
one way or the other in a book that is flaccid, much too long, and
quite without suspense. Take Cuddy back to Boston, please!
</P>
<P>
   And, please, will Howard Engel return to Benny Copperman and
Ontario? Engel is a prize-winning author of excellent mysteries,
but he wants to tell us about the literary life in Paris in the
1920s. ``Murder in Montparnasse'' (Overlook Press, $23.95) gives us
a serial killer, expatriate writers, and some fairly mindless
people. The writing is earnest, the dialogue rehearsed, and one
longs for Benny to return, with all the placid sense of Canada that
Engel has described so well in eight earlier books.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the secret is to read only authors of whom one has no
preconceived expectations. David Ball's ``Empires of Sand''
(Bantam, $23.95) is a first novel, and a splendid adventure tale, a
kind of Count of Monte Christo in imperial dress, beginning in
Paris in 1870 and racing off to the Sahara where two boys, once the
best of friends, become bitter enemies. There are nomadic Tuareg,
there is passionate love, rich writing, a vibrant sense of place,
and much research worn lightly. This is a big book, full of
incident, and precisely what I needed to pull me back from my
despairing thought that I couldn't find anything that really sang.
This is romance at its best.
</P>
<P>
   I also like ``Silent Snow'' (Viking, $24.95) by Steve Thayer,
perhaps because it took me away from August, but more because it
too tells a fine story, which in the end is what this kind of
fiction is all about. Rich Beanblossom, an investigative reporter
in the Twin Cities, must solve the mystery of the disappearance of
his young son from his nursery, and he can do so only by
contemplating the Lingbergh kidnapping. Thayer provides a blend of
history and fiction that is quite satisfying, and between them
Thayer and Bell restore one's faith in the craft of storytelling:
logical yet surprising, cleanly written yet intricately argued,
compelling of locale and enterprising of plot _ just what we need
to end this long hot summer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Robin W. Winks, a professor of history at Yale University, reviews
mystery fiction on the last Sunday of each month.)
</P>
</TEXT>
