<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 14:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4468 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-YUGOSLAVIA-MILOSEVIC-     08-30 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-MILOSEVIC-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US TRIES TO TURN YUGOSLAV OFFICIALS 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE _ US intelligence agents and State Department
officials, seeking turncoats in hopes of an ouster, have been
contacting associates of President Slobodan Milosevic in his ruling
coalition and in the top ranks of the army, according to officials
in Washington and Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   With the goal of finishing what NATO's 78 days of bombing left
undone _ unseating Milosevic and avoiding a repetition of the Gulf
War outcome of failing to oust a dictator _ US officials have been
``talking to as many people as we possibly can,'' a Clinton
administration official said.
</P>
<P>
   A government source in Belgrade confirmed the account: ``The
Americans have been contacting the top officers in the army, saying
to them, `The war crimes indictment list will be extended to 600
names, so you betray the big boss when I tell you, or you'll go to
the Hague.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But the source said that many in the government are reluctant to
put faith in the Americans because of past US deals with Milosevic,
including the 1995 Dayton peace accords, and because over the past
12 years Milosevic has shown an uncanny ability to hold fast to
power.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think this could be the Titanic, and they are being
offered a lifeboat. But they are afraid the Titanic might survive
and they will be stuck in the lifeboat,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome of the behind-the-scenes US efforts to overthrow
Milosevic, complemented by three public meetings with Serbian
opposition leaders this summer in the other Yugoslav republic of
Montenegro, is difficult to predict, according to intellectuals,
opposition leaders, and diplomats in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Still, a diplomat said, ``This is the beginning of the end of
Milosevic. He knows it. But around him is a strong structure of
economic interests, and that is the main problem. They will not
permit him to resign.''
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic and four associates have been indicted on war crimes
charges by the United Nation's International Criminal Tribunal in
the Hague. The diplomat said that since Milosevic cannot leave
Serbia without the near-certainty of arrest, ``He feels now as if
he is in a cage. There's no way out. This is a most dangerous
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Two months after NATO's last bomb fell on Yugoslavia, other
pressures continue to mount on the Serbian leader. Among them:
</P>
<P>
   --A bitterly divided opposition will try to regroup by starting
daily street protects beginning Sept. 21.
</P>
<P>
   --The country's bomb-damaged electric power system could
collapse when demand rises in winter, leaving many without heat and
potentially fueling domestic unrest.
</P>
<P>
   --Financial reserves are down to a reported $150 million.
Without new funds or substantial United Nations assistance, the
government must make painful choices, such as whether to put money
toward fixing power stations or paying pensioners.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, no one is predicting Milosevic's immiment departure.
</P>
<P>
   His fiercest opponents begrudgingly see him as clever and wily,
and he has two great advantages: He controls the armed forces, and
persistent infighting keeps the opposition divided. A poll released
last week by the independent magazine NIN reflected strong
dissatisfaction with the choice of leaders. Asked whether Milosevic
should resign, 57 percent said yes, 31 percent said no, and the
rest said they were undecided. But asked which opposition leader
could lead the country, 68 percent said none. Twenty percent
refused to respond. The poll's margin of error was not available.
</P>
<P>
   But even opposition leaders do not see much error in the poll.
</P>
<P>
   ``The basic fact is that the majority of people are fed up with
Mr. Milosevic. It's also true that they are not happy with the
opposition groups . . . in part because of the leadership's
vanities,'' said Goran Svilanovic, 35, of the Alliance for Changes,
a coalition of opponents.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, said Svilanovic, Milosevic's Socialist Party of Serbia
has seized the initiative by saying it might back early local
elections on Nov. 7. While Svilanovic wants the opposition to unite
and challenge Milosevic in a national election with one candidate
this fall, his coalition is leaning toward boycotting any early
elections with daily street protests, he said. A decision may be
announced early this week.
</P>
<P>
   It is a time of maddening uncertainty in Serbia. Many ordinary
Serbs make passing references to going crazy, and some close to
power have chosen to go elsewhere _ such as Montenegro _ until the
country's future becomes more clear.
</P>
<P>
   One influential leader, Bogoljub Karic, reportedly the
wealthiest man in Serbia, resigned as minister without portfolio to
distance himself from the Milosevic regime, the government insider
and a diplomat said. Karic is in Montenegro, refusing all interview
requests.
</P>
<P>
   The uncertainty over the country's fate is not entirely
surprising.
</P>
<P>
   In half a year, this nation of about 11 million people has
lurched from one extreme to the other, from war to peace, from the
Serbs' massive ``ethnic cleansing'' of ethnic Albanians from the
province of Kosovo to seeing returning Albanians drive out Serbs,
from censorship of government criticism to large antigovernment
rallies, from the overnight rise of opposition leaders to their
dizzying downfall.
</P>
<P>
   What next? An internal American-backed coup? A civil war? A
million protesters in the streets?
</P>
<P>
   If the outside world is having difficulty making sense of it and
forecasting the future here, so are Serbia's exhausted people. As
they try to sort it out, and as they watch the government and
opposition for signals, they are certain only that Milosevic has
never been weaker _ and that there is no clear path to a
post-Milosevic society.
</P>
<P>
   One afternoon last week, after a protest of pensioners in a
downtown square, Gordana Stoyanovic, 50, a former chemist, said she
has a recurring fantasy. It is a Serbian version of the Hollywood
movie character who shouts out his window, ``I'm mad as hell and
I'm not going to take it anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People can't organize and do something together, so I think
about demonstrating by myself in front of all the federal
government buildings,'' Stoyanovic said. ``But if I did it, they
would take me away to a lunatic's asylum.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
