<DOCNO> NYT19990830.0234 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 14:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4472 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-YUGOSLAVIA-MILOSEVIC-     08-30 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-MILOSEVIC-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 BELGRADE: ... lunatic's asylum.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   She laughed. ``All of us in this country,'' she said, grinning,
``are on the edge of mental illness.''
</P>
<P>
   Belgrade, population 2 million, sprawls out from the confluence
of the rivers Danube and Sava, and on these late summer days all
seems quiet, especially along downtown pedestrian walkways, as
residents sip espresso and mineral water. NATO bombs hit several
dozen targets in the city, and while a few structures such as the
Army and Communist Party headquarters are landmarks of destruction,
bomb damage does not define the looks of Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Yet signs of trouble are elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Lines of cars stretch for a half-mile around gas stations
because of shortages. Pensioners regularly hold protests _ 31 at
last count _ because the government is more than four months behind
in paying them. Police are due two months' back pay. Fresh milk is
almost never in the supermarkets, and farmers take out newspaper
ads saying it won't be available until the government pays a fair
price. Many people sit for hours in cafes, in no rush to go
anywhere. Unemployment, at 26 percent before the war, now is over
50 percent, according to independent economists.
</P>
<P>
   And it's only going to get worse.
</P>
<P>
   Winter worries people. Everyone is bracing for a severe shortage
of electricity.
</P>
<P>
   The country lost one-third of its electric capacity in the war,
said Momcilo Cebalovic, spokesman for the government-run Electric
Power Industry of Serbia. NATO's new graphite bombs, each
containing three miles of string-like fiber, fell on electric
transformers and power stations, drapping the wires and coils like
bales of cotton candy. On contact, the fiber short-circuited power
facilities, causing widespread damage to Serbia's electrical
system.
</P>
<P>
   This happened four times. Repairs haven't caught up.
</P>
<P>
   The estimate to fix the entire system is about $200 million, $50
million more than Serbia's federal reserves. There's some hope that
a visiting United Nations team will recommend that humanitarian aid
be used for repairing the electrical system. Officials also hope
that Russia will agree to a new natural gas contract, even though
Yugoslavia owes more than $300 million from the last contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wonder about the winter,'' Cebalovic said. ``But we know
that we won't be able to provide electricity for heating for
civilians.''
</P>
<P>
   The government is asking people to switch to wood and coal for
heat, but a group of wood-sellers on the outskirts of Belgrade said
there have been few takers so far. They acknowledged raising the
price for a cord of wood to $60 from $50. And they said with little
apology that the price probably will soar to $120 in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be no electricity,'' said Rade Milosauljevic, 48,
as he leaned against his wood-laden truck. ``Everyone is worried,
and everyone is asking what will happen to this country.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Only Milosevic is surviving here,'' said a woodcutter who
identified himself only as Dragan, 38, a father of three. ``We will
probably screw Milosevic eventually. He is screwing us. He'll go
like Ceaucescu _ only even worse.''
</P>
<P>
   (In a 1989 uprising, Romania's dictator, Nicolae Ceaucescu, and
his wife were savagely murdered.)
</P>
<P>
   Considering the divided state of Serbia's opposition,
intellectuals believe a better shot at removing Milosevic rests
with the American effort to get his associates to turn on him.
</P>
<P>
   No one would disclose results of the talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that Milosevic and his wife are hanging on by their
fingernails for a while longer,'' said a second US official, adding
that classified intelligence reports have said for the last two
months that Milosevic was in deep trouble internally and that there
is increased domestic turmoil between Milosevic and his powerful
wife, Mirjana Markovic, head of the Yugoslav Left Party. The
official said Markovic, a pillar of support for Milosevic during
NATO's bombardment of Yugoslavia, ``has been going into tirades
against him.''
</P>
<P>
   The official declined to give specifics, saying only,
``Milosevic has always looked to her as a sounding board, and that
isn't happening so much now.''
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, meanwhile, several developments suggest that Milosevic
may be worried about US contacts with those around him.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Milosevic reshuffled his Cabinet, replacing seven
ministers. One of them was Milosevic's predecessor, Zoran Lilic,
who was demoted from deputy prime minister to economic adviser.
</P>
<P>
   And earlier this month, the Globe reported that Serbian
President Milan Milutinovic suddenly was assigned a new security
detail, out of suspicion he may be ready to turn against Milosevic.
Milutinovic was also indicted on war crimes charges by the Hague
Tribunal.
</P>
<P>
   Jovan Mandic, a former electric department supervisor for the
city of Belgrade, said there is a high chance many parts of the
country's electrical system could simply shut down. The peak winter
electricity load will be 50 percent higher than available supply,
and when demand outstrips supply the system will collapse, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``For years, we have been using spare parts to fix problems. Now
there are no spare parts,'' Mandic said on a recent night in the
Belgrade suburb of Zemun, as a harvest moon rose over the Danube.
``All the systems will be destroyed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
