   &UR; FOR TUESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Tuesday, Aug. 31:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-TIMOR (Dili, East Timor) _ Developments in the
independence referendum: A big turnout and, after weeks of mayhem,
very little violence; one U.N. worker was killed. Results of the
voting are expected in a week. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-TIMOR-SCENE (Odemau Atus, East Timor) _ The scene as
pro-independence rebels vote at a chapel up in the hills.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-JERUSALEM (Jerusalem) _ Jordan is ready to yield its
control over Muslim holy sites in Jerusalem to the Palestinian
Authority, the Jordanian prime minister, Abdul-Raouf al-Rawabdeh,
says.
</P>
<P>
   And
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Jerusalem) _ Developments in peace talks. By
Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   VENEZUELA-POLITICS (Caracas) _ As the political crisis
continues, the constitutional assembly is expected to take away
more of the Congress' powers. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE-DENNIS (Wilmington, N.C.) _ The heart of Hurricane
Dennis continued to track parallel to the North Carolina coast on
Monday, while its edge brought pelting rain, wind gusts up to 80
mph and some beachfront flooding. Forecasters expected the storm to
turn northeast away from land, but the possibility of a full-force
landfall in North Carolina remained. Even if Dennis' eye remains
offshore, they said, the storm's strong wind could cause problems
for coastal residents. By Emily Yellin.
</P>
<P>
   NURSE-MURDER-TRIAL (Chicago) _ Jury selection begins in the
trial of a nurse who is suspected of killing as many as 100 elderly
patients in a tiny hospital in Indiana. The nurse, 37-year-old
Orville Lynn Majors Jr., was charged with seven murders, all by
lethal injection, at Vermillion County Hospital. By Bill Dedman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   KEYES-PROFILE (Greenville, S.C.) _ Alan L. Keyes, the
arch-conservative radio talk show host, is the invisible man in the
Republican primary for president. He gets few cameras at his
events. Political analysts tend to forget him in their
prognostications. Polls show him receiving one percent of the vote,
or less. And when the Log Cabin Republicans, a homosexual group,
issued a news release last week attacking religious conservatives
for intolerance, Keyes didn't even merit a mention. But to his
small yet devoted cadre of followers, Keyes a former Reagan
administration diplomat with a Harvard Ph.D., has something his
fellow arch conservatives lack: mesmerizing oratorical skills
twinned with a messianic vision. By James Dao. (1600 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-LIVERMORE-RESIGN (Undated) _ The head of the the National
Ignition Facility at Lawrence Livermore resigns when it is
disclosed that he had never received the doctorate he claimed. The
division he headed is the cornerstone of U.S. nuclear fusion
research with a $1.6 billion budget. By Malcolm W. Browne. (800
words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-TREE-OF-LIFE (Undated) _ As part of an outpouring of
research that is revolutionizing notions about the genetic,
biochemical, structural and evolutionary relationships among living
things, fungi like mushrooms have now been revealed as being closer
to animals than to plants. The revelation is just one of many
emerging new ideas about family ties in the upper reaches of the
earth's 3.8-billion-year-old tree of life, in particular ties among
plants and between them and other higher forms of existence. By
William K. Stevens. (2000 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   For other science stories, see the separate
SCIENCE-TIMES-BUDGET.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   FED-STOCKS (Jackson Hole, Wyo.) _ The ever-rising U.S. stock
market _ and its growing importance in the economy _ was the big
topic at the recent forum here for central bankers and economists.
While there is much debate about whether the boom may turn out to
be a bubble, it is increasingly clear that the Federal Reserve
under Alan Greenspan is prepared to help minimize any damage from a
sharp downturn in stock prices. By Louis Uchitelle.
</P>
<P>
   SPLURGE-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ As stocks ascend to ever-more
dizzying heights, many investors who have put off major purchases
have now decided to sell some of their holdings and use the
proceeds to remodel the bathroom, buy a new washing machine, take
that expensive vacation or splurge in some way. Indeed, investors
are cashing out of mutual-fund shares at the highest rate in almost
a dozen years. Economists say that the giant profits reaped from
stock portfolios this decade have led individuals to spend far more
than they otherwise would, thus helping keep the economy _ and
corporate profits _ perking along. By Richard A. Oppel Jr.
</P>
<P>
   CARREFOUR-PROMODES (London) _ Carrefour says it will buy a
French rival, Promodes SA, for $16.7 billion in new shares,
creating the world's second-biggest retailer after Wal-Mart Stores.
The merger creates a company with 9,000 stores in three continents,
overtaking Metro of Germany as Europe's biggest retailer. The
merged company will be able to demand lower prices from suppliers
to better compete with Wal-Mart, which is expanding in Europe. By
Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T-RATES (Undated) _ AT&AMP;T is cutting rates for long-distance
phone calls to 7 cents a minute in response to a price war begun by
MCI Worldcom and Sprint. By Saul Hansell.
</P>
<P>
   SUN-WEB-SOFTWARE (Undated) _ Sun Microsystems Inc. is planning
an ambitious campaign to move everyday software applications like
word processing and spreadsheets away from the personal computer
desktop and onto the World Wide Web, a strategy that amounts to a
direct assault on Microsoft's biggest business. At the center of
the plan is Star Division, a German producer of office productivity
software, which Sun has acquired. By Steve Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At 1:35 p.m., stocks were lower. The Dow
Jones industrial average was down 68 points, the S&AMP;P 500 down 11
points and the Nasdaq composite index was down 27 points. The
30-year bond was yielding 6.03 percent. In Europe stocks were
modestly lower, with Frankfurt down 0.51 percent. London is closed
for a bank holiday. The Japan's Nikkei closed up 1.82 percent,
while Hong Kong's stock index rose 2.28 percent. By Kenneth N.
Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   CREDIT (New York) _ Credit market developments. By Robert
Hurtado.
</P>
