<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STUDENT-INVENTOR-ART-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDENT'S ``LIGHTNING MACHINE'' INVENTION MAKING SPARKS IN THE
MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SARAH SKIDMORE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ When you get the Rives family together the sparks fly.
Literally.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Rives, an 18-year-old Lakeside School senior, is the
proud inventor of the ``Lightning Machine,'' an educational toy
being sold through his parent's scientific toy company, Scientific
Explorer.
</P>
<P>
   The toy is making sparks on the market too, with more than
30,000 sold since April. It's now in close to 2,000 stores,
including the Discovery Channel and Museum Company stores,
according to Alexander's father, William.
</P>
<P>
   It made the list of ``Best Children's Vacation Products for
1999'' which is produced by Dr. Steven Auerbach, an expert in child
development.
</P>
<P>
   The Lightning Machine itself is a hand-held lightning maker,
which has a suggested retail price of $19.98. Children construct
the toy out of plastic tubing, copper wire and copper strips. The
end product is an advanced form of the 18th-century Leyden jar,
which is the world's first device to store electricity.
</P>
<P>
   To make lightning, the toy is run across a television screen to
collect the electrons and then the two copper covered spheres at
the top are touched together to create a lightning bolt.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander's father previously considered creating a
lightning-related toy but nothing was ever constructed. However,
Alexander did not brainstorm long.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just didn't have much homework one week and we were studying
Leyden jars and capacitors in school and it just sort of
happened,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He started with a prototype created out of foil, a film canister
and a nail. He said the concept and construction was easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alexander has been a great source of ideas in production
development since we started this business. I am very pleased,''
William said. ``But this is the first time he has really followed
it through the entire developmental process.''
</P>
<P>
   Although science is one of Alexander's better subjects, he said
he does not feel it is his favorite subject. He wouldn't divulge
his cumulative grade-point average but admitted it was close to a
4.0. He created the idea himself and went to his physics teacher
just once, not for assistance but to show off his handiwork.
</P>
<P>
   After spending this summer as a volunteer for Earthwatch in
Iceland studying the relationship between glaciers and the island's
volcanoes, Alexander is making plans to create a new volcano toy
for Scientific Explorer.
</P>
<P>
   When he isn't helping with his parent's business, he operates an
Internet business of his own.
</P>
<P>
   His Web site, Bryce's Tips, offers tips on computer generated
graphics (www.halcyon.com/alrives/brycetips/). He is also a member
of the crew team at Seattle's private Lakeside School and is a
recreational photographer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-99 1430EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
