<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 14:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4490 &Cx1f; tth-z
u l BC-SINGERS-SIDEWALK-ART-     08-30 1010
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SINGERS-SIDEWALK-ART-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUARTET HAS MADE SEATTLE'S PIKE PLACE MARKET ITS SIDEWALK STAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIKA HAYASAKI  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ On a sunny weekday afternoon, tourists swarm Seattle's
famed Pike Place Market while Clifford Miller, Wil Smith, Levi
Barnes and James Butler seize a spot on the Pike Place sidewalk.
</P>
<P>
   After clearing their throats and cracking a few jokes, it's time
to do their thang.
</P>
<P>
   They bust out with a few hit tunes: ``Under the Boardwalk,''
``This Little Light of Mine'' and ``I Got Sunshine.'' Within
minutes they're surrounded by a whooping, clapping, toe-tapping
crowd of nearly 50 people.
</P>
<P>
   When the vibrant quartet, known as A Moment in Time, debuted at
the Market three years ago, they electrified the street performance
scene.
</P>
<P>
   The rhythm-and-blues singers have roused crowds with their
animated performances every afternoon since, usually performing
between noon and 3 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time we performed we only had three songs. We still
blocked off the street and traffic couldn't get through,'' Smith
said. ``The Market said if we didn't keep people from blocking the
street, we'd have to leave and they would take away our permits.''
</P>
<P>
   The group was started three years ago by Barnes, 54, a friendly
jokester from Tennessee who had been singing alone on street
corners in Pioneer Square for two years.
</P>
<P>
   He ran into Smith, 42, who had just moved to Seattle from
Tennessee and was wandering around First Avenue and Yesler Way.
They decided to form a group and later discovered Miller, 45, a
short man with a powerful voice who was singing alone in front of
the downtown Nordstrom store.
</P>
<P>
   ``One day we were in the elevator at St. Charles Hotel, where
Levi was living, and (Barnes and Miller) started singing. I added a
note and we said, `Wow, we've got something here,' '' said Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Six months ago, the three came across Butler, 56, a Louisiana
native, playing the guitar at the Market. After hearing his soulful
voice, they quickly recruited him. His Dixieland musical and vocal
talent added just the right twang to the group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I come here, I check them out. I've probably come
to see them nine or 10 times,'' said Pauline Harrison, who lives in
Arizona and owns a second home in Issaquah, a Seattle suburb. ``I
think they're great. I love their voices.''
</P>
<P>
   The foursome have a rare magnetic energy.
</P>
<P>
   On that busy weekday, few people paid attention to the man on
the corner with dancing toy monkeys. A man in a wheelchair who sang
the blues had an audience of three. And an a cappella trio earned a
mere couple of bucks in change.
</P>
<P>
   But A Moment in Time had a tall pile of bills in its plastic
yellow bucket. And the group never fails to attract a crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen them before, but I love them,'' said Lasara
Jarvis, an 18-year-old who moved to Seattle from Northern
California a couple of weeks ago, as she danced to their music.
``So far, this is the best part of Seattle. They are down-home and
I love to see someone who is willing to perform their soul out.''
</P>
<P>
   Although they take in more cash than most street performers,
they don't make enough money to pay the bills or cut a CD, which
they estimate will cost about $1,900. Miller works as a carpenter
to support himself, while Butler and Barnes say they are on
disability. The group occasionally performs at weddings and
parties.
</P>
<P>
   They say they don't sing for money or fame, but because they
love to perform.
</P>
<P>
   ``This gives me a chance to express myself. And if you're good,
you make some money,'' said Butler, wearing a faded linen shirt
with a pack of smokes in the pocket. ``You work your own hours down
here _ no more than two to three hours a day. And I love music, I
don't know what I would do without it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I love making people happy, I can't live without entertaining,
and I can't live without singing. I sing everywhere I go,'' said
Miller, a St. Louis native.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes, who previously worked as a tree planter in Forks, Wash.,
and used to be a drifter, boasted he's been drug free for 18
months. He used to sing on the street corners of New York, but
didn't make much money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was doing it for fun, drinking wine and beer on the
corner,'' he said. ``I drifted around for a while and then six
years ago, in Tennessee, I watched them throw fish on the TV (at
Pike Place Market) and I said, `I'm going to Seattle. And I've been
here ever since.' ''
</P>
<P>
   He serenaded twin toddlers who shyly hid behind their father,
and flirtatiously joked with a young lady asking her, ``Are you
Miss America?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to do this forever. It's something I enjoy,
seeing the smiles and making people happy,'' Barnes said.
</P>
<P>
   All four say they have music in their blood. Barnes came from a
musical family with 13 siblings. Butler performed in various blues
bands in the 1960s. Smith enjoys writing music in his spare time.
And Miller was raised in the church, where his father was a
preacher and his mother sang in the choir.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been singing all my life. My daddy was a preacher and
I've been singing since I was 3 years old. I sang in choirs,''
Miller said. ``I used to preach on the street. I was singing all
gospel when I started.''
</P>
<P>
   Passersby, who saunter between shops chatting with each other,
are drawn to the group by their impassioned musical flavor and
dynamic charisma. They glimpse, listen, come closer, stop and
pretty soon they're clapping their hands and dropping money in the
bucket.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a great rhythm and great voices,'' said Kathy
Thoman, a tourist from Cincinnati. ``And they have fun _ that's the
best part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of A Moment in Time say a CD is in the works, but it
will be a few months before they can take care of technicalities,
such as raising money and obtaining permission to record songs with
copyrights.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope for something bigger and better, to get recognized and
recorded. That's every musician's dream,'' Butler said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
