<HEADER>
A4496 &Cx1f; tth-z
u f BC-FISHING-HARD-TIMES-AR     08-30 1520
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FISHING-HARD-TIMES-ART-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO SOCKEYE SEASON WILL BE DEVASTATING TO MANY FISHERMEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ARTHUR C. GORLICK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLAINE, Wash. _ Nick Karuza and his wife Diedra sat on the aft
deck of their 50-foot purse seiner Alice Anne moored at Blaine
Marina last week and checked the old boat's nets for damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``My grandfather came from the Croatian island of Vis in the
early 1900s, and he fished for salmon in Puget Sound,'' Nick Karuza
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father fished in Puget Sound for 50 years, and I was 14
when I started fishing for sockeye salmon in Puget Sound, and I'm
53 now.''
</P>
<P>
   But this year, for the first time that anyone can remember,
there will be no Puget Sound fishing season for sockeye.
</P>
<P>
   Karuza, the Alice Anne and its crew will remain idle.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 70 other purse seiners and 150 gill-netters who paid
$630 for licenses will remain at their docks, too.
</P>
<P>
   It may be the last gasp for commercial fishing in Puget Sound,
one of the last of the state's traditional industries struggling to
survive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We forecast a run of more than 8 million sockeye for this
season, and it now appears the run is going to be a little over 3
million sockeye and virtually all of those fish are needed for
escapement,'' said Dennis Austin, of the state's Department of Fish
and Wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   ``Therefore, there is not going to be any Canadian or U.S.
commercial fishery this year. The economic impact will be
devastating,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists blame the small sockeye return on 1997 weather
conditions at sea that killed young fish.
</P>
<P>
   Austin, who leads a U.S.-Canada panel overseeing sockeye and
pink salmon from Canada's Fraser River, source of the Puget Sound
sockeye, estimates the value of the lost harvest at ``somewhere up
to $10 million.''
</P>
<P>
   But Karuza and others who depend on the sockeye season, which
typically begins in August, say effects are far greater than that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We estimate it will be more like $24 million or $31 million
for some, but that's just the dollar value,'' Karuza said.
</P>
<P>
   He is convinced he will lose the Alice Anne, his Bellingham home
and the way of life his family has lived for almost 100 years. Last
year, Karuza caught fewer than 1,000 fish, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In good times, owners of purse seiners could make $100,000 a
year fishing in Boundary Bay off Point Roberts, a thumb of U.S.
territory jutting south of the Canadian border.
</P>
<P>
   Purse seiner skippers would put a small skiff into the water
behind the larger fishing boat. The small boat would loop a net in
an arc behind the main vessel, forming a net ``purse,'' trapping
fish inside. The larger boat would haul aboard the net and its
catch of fish.
</P>
<P>
   Karuza is not alone in facing hard times.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Anderson placed an advertisement in a local newspaper
offering to give away for free his 58-foot purse seiner Sunshine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an albatross around my neck, and it will spiral me down
to ruin,'' said Anderson, who lives in a camper and showers with a
garden hose.
</P>
<P>
   He is ``on the beach,'' working for $8 an hour training horses
and giving riding lessons.
</P>
<P>
   The Port of Bellingham, which operates the Blaine and Squalicum
marinas, wants $17,000 from Anderson to pay $1,500 in overdue
moorage fees, $8,000 to reimburse the Coast Guard for pumping out
petroleum products from the boat to prevent environmental damage
and other costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't pay it,'' Anderson said. ``If I could pay that, I'd
pay to have the hull fixed so I could use it for fishing.''
</P>
<P>
   Four commercial boats are chained to the dock in Squalicum
Marina, big red impound stickers on cabin windows, for being
delinquent in moorage payments, said Reed Gillig, harbormaster
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chaining up a boat for us is a last resort,'' Gillig said.
``You take away a means of making money to pay the fees and take
away a means for the owner to make a living.''
</P>
<P>
   More boat slips are expected to go to pleasure craft.
</P>
<P>
   The port will continue to have income from the rentals, but
Gillig agrees that it won't be from fishermen. Many fishing boat
owners are finding other work ashore these days.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question that from the time I started at the Port
of Bellingham 14 years ago, the fishing fleet has diminished with
the decline of salmon returns,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson's boat has not been chained to the dock for unpaid
moorage fees but is considered ``not seaworthy and environmentally
dangerous,'' Gillig said.
</P>
<P>
   Karuza estimated that as many as 300 Puget Sound families whose
livelihood is tied to salmon fishing face economic hardship and,
perhaps, bankruptcy by the lack of a sockeye season this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are deckhands and people who sell supplies on the docks
and the fish processors,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Dodd at the Blaine Marina Fishermen's Wharf sells fuel and
other supplies to fishing boat skippers. He buys fish from the
boats for companies such as Seattle-based Trident Seafoods Corp.,
receiving a commission for each fish.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll get by, but there will be a big loss in income,'' Dodd
said.
</P>
<P>
   As the fishing industry declined, he cut expenses by leasing one
of his two docks to a company buying crab. He diversified by
turning part of his operation into a store selling hardware,
furniture, appliances, televisions and audio equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Norm Walsh, manager of Westman Marine Inc., a Blaine Marina boat
yard, said many of the older wooden hull boats are in disrepair.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't make any money so we're handling less and less
fishing boat repairs in recent years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His yard will survive by serving pleasure boats and larger
vessels.
</P>
<P>
   State legislators with ties to the Puget Sound commercial salmon
industry say they are working to ease the hardship.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad has been fishing since he was 16, and he'll be 73 in
September,'' said State Rep. Kelli Linville, D-Bellingham, whose
district includes the Whatcom County fishing boat harbors.
</P>
<P>
   Her father, Martin Kuljis, operates Sea-K Fish, a processing
facility on Blaine's Boundary Bay pier.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not out of the salmon business, but he has diversified
because he can't depend on the salmon,'' Linville said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He also processes bottom fish, crab and other seafood.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Legislature, she and Rep. Doug Ericksen, R-Bellingham,
have led efforts to obtain financial assistance for people hit by
the decline in the salmon industry.
</P>
<P>
   Linville said she also has been forging a coalition of loggers,
Eastern Washington farmers and other groups crippled by financial
hard times to oppose Initiative 696, which would ban the use of
commercial fishing nets in state waters.
</P>
<P>
   Voters rejected a similar proposal in 1995, but sport anglers
are back for a second try, saying overharvesting by commercial
fishing interests has contributed to the decline of wild salmon
runs.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters say nets kill all species indiscriminately.
</P>
<P>
   But Aaron Briones and Barney Kieper, deckhands aboard the Alice
Anne, said they separate fish hauled aboard, keeping legal species
and returning others to the water.
</P>
<P>
   Voters will decide Nov. 2 on the measure to ban commercial nets.
</P>
<P>
   Linville said she also has been working to obtain financial
assistance for fishing families, but other state officials said
help won't come quickly.
</P>
<P>
   A program to buy back fishing licenses was part of the
U.S.-Canada Salmon Treaty that went into effect earlier this year,
said Curt Smitch, the governor's special assistant and head of the
Governor's Salmon Recovery Office.
</P>
<P>
   ``The status of that is that we have some money in the state
budget for salmon buyback _ about $2 million over three years _ but
it is a bit vague as to whether the Legislature intended for that
to be statewide and go for all fishing efforts or just for the
Puget Sound fishers,'' Smitch said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is approximately $15 million in the federal budget that
would begin Oct. 1 this year, but that is all up in the air,'' he
said, noting the House and Senate have conflicting versions of the
bill that will have to be worked out in conference committee.
</P>
<P>
   Karuza, who has a degree in history and education from Western
Washington University in Bellingham, temporarily works maintaining
machinery used in the environmental cleanup after an explosion of a
Bellingham fuel pipeline.
</P>
<P>
   He and others in the Puget Sound fishing industry say they need
more help immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the $630 license, Puget Sound commercial anglers have an
average moorage and web locker bill for their nets of about $3,600
a year, insurance of $1,500 or more, annual gearing their boats for
repairs and maintenance at $1,200, plus home expenses and taxes,
Karuza said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figure my total expenses come to $31,230 a year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality of the issue is most commercial fishers are
already overextended in credit because of past economic disasters.
We're in the same situation as the farmers when there was a buyback
program to help them and the same as the loggers when they got a
buyback.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel we deserve it, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
