<SLUG> BC-ART-MARATHON-ART-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPRESSIONS AT NIGHT: SEATTLE MUSEUM'S LATE-NIGHT SHOW WILDLY
POPULAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By REGINA HACKETT  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Midnight at the Seattle Art Museum, and the place was
hopping. The line snaked out the door, up University Street and
back along Second Avenue on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in its history, the museum held an art
marathon to celebrate its immensely popular exhibit,
``Impressionism: Paintings Collected by European Museums,'' keeping
the doors open from 9 a.m. Saturday to midnight Sunday night, when
the show closed.
</P>
<P>
   Looking crisp and clear-eyed, Anna Loper, 89, said she went
Saturday at midnight with her daughter to participate in the
``spirit of a party'' and because the 19th-century French art
movement known as Impressionism is her favorite form of painting.
``It's not as restrained as what came earlier and not as crazy as
what came later,'' she said. The exhibit inspired her to think
about taking up painting herself. ``I've got a couple of years
left,'' she said, smiling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Impressionism'' drew more visitors to the downtown museum than
any other show in its history, attracting about 316,000 from the
exhibit's opening June 12 to its flamboyant end.
</P>
<P>
   During the 39-hour finale, the show drew roughly 18,000 people,
meaning anyone going late Saturday night to avoid a line was
disappointed. The typical wait was 2{ to 3{ hours, evaporating to
immediate access and no line at all at 4 a.m. and building back up
by 10 a.m. Sunday to a line along University and halfway down
Second Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a yellow T-shirt appropriately inscribed ``Life is
Short, Stay Awake for It,'' Gary Roshak said his long stretch in
line Saturday night didn't bother him. ``How many times can you be
inside an art museum at 2 a.m.?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   The same reason drew Sarah Jubinski, 15, on hand with her
friends Aston Edmonds, 15, and Jesse Palek-Zahn, 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was in third grade, my favorite book was `From the
Mixed-Up Files of Mrs. Basil E. Frankweller,' by E.L. Konigsburg,''
said Jubinski, brightly. ``It's about a girl who runs away from
home and hides in the Met. Ever since, I've wanted to be in an art
museum late at night.''
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds said she went because she likes to be up late and there
aren't that many places to go for ``clean fun at 2 in the
morning.'' Palek-Zahn, a bagger in a grocery store soon to be an
ex-bagger as he leaves to start college in the fall, said he went
to escort the girls and keep them distracted from the wait in line
with tales of strange shoppers, like the woman earlier that day who
had demanded he list the ingredients in honey.
</P>
<P>
   Museum guard and creative writer Yoona Lee said her shift was 9
p.m. Saturday night to 9 a.m. Sunday. About 2 a.m. Sunday, she was
looking a little dazed, but had her journal out to take notes in
case she wanted to write something later.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great crowd,'' she said, looking around.
``Everybody's polite, better than crowds we've seen during regular
hours for this show.'' Consulting her notes, she observed that she
was trying to ``coagulate my thoughts,'' which were slipping away
from her. ``Through the sheer lateness of the hour, the walls are
starting to undulate,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Carrying his 3{-year-old daughter Jenai in a backpack, Marshall
Kirkpatrick called the late-night museum show a
``once-in-a-lifetime opportunity. I wanted my daughter to be able
to say, `I was there.'''
</P>
<P>
   She beamed down over his shoulder, one arm wrapped around his
neck in what looked like a police choke hold. Looking at her
somewhat warily from his perch in his dad's backpack, Jacob Moran,
also 3{, sported a bruised face acquired earlier in the day when
Jenai hit him with a garden hose. He said he liked the Monets,
adding that there was a Monet in his house ``in Daddy's room.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a real one,'' amended his father, Jason Moran. Jacob
frowned, puzzling that over.
</P>
<P>
   Jessica Drenkel, 21, could have explained the difference between
a reproduction and an original to him. That's the reason she stood
in line, to see the real thing, that and the fact she and her
friends ``function best at night and travel in packs,'' she said,
gesturing to the motley band beside her. ``You can see these
paintings in books, but I like to see the texture of the brush
stroke up close,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   By 3 a.m., Bethany Graves, 23, was getting a reviving massage
from her friend Jill Seager, 22. Coming to the show was Seager's
idea. ``I had a day planner full of Monets,'' she said. ``It got me
interested.''
</P>
<P>
   By 2:30 a.m., Anthony Plank, 17, looked as if he had been ready
to head home hours ago. ``I respect these paintings, but not this
late at night,'' he said. His girlfriend, Denise Junell, 17, said
she had seen a lot of Impressionism in Chicago, and ``there are
only so many a normal person wants to see,'' she said. ``Paintings
of blue sky and green trees, how many do you need?'' Because they
were there with her mom and her aunt, they had no choice but to
wait.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like surrealism better,'' she said, sagging a little into
Plank.
</P>
<P>
   Past 1 a.m. all over the exhibit, children were starting to
slump. Some stretched out on benches and some were fast asleep in
their parents' arms.
</P>
<P>
   Josh Moore, who had been painting his house all day with his
wife, leaned against the wall and started to slide, eyes closed.
When his wife reached him and gently shook his arm, he opened his
eyes, straightened up and smiled. ``My sister-in-law talked us into
coming,'' he said. ``I'm tired, but this show was worth being tired
for.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
