<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRIGHT-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE REAL QUESTION? MEDICINE, NOT DRUGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM WRIGHT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The nation's political reporters are on the wrong track. People
don't care if Gov. George W. Bush did foolish things in his youth.
They do care desperately, however, what he and other presidential
candidates would do about health care.
</P>
<P>
   While a scandal-starved press corps prattles on about whether
Bush ever took illicit drugs, a serious nationwide problem has been
rapidly reaching crisis proportions. The record number of
Americans, now estimated at 44 million, without any health
insurance at all _ that, in this summer's trivialized political
dialogue, is the smoldering time bomb.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters paid little attention in May when former U.S. Surgeon
General C. Everett Koop and John C. Baldwin, dean of Dartmouth
Medical School, warned that the health-care situation has become so
grave that it simply cannot be solved by tinkering around the edges
with peripheral reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Both the political media and the nation's lawmakers should have
been awakened to the gravity of the situation by the stirring words
of Dr. Paul Ellwood, the acknowledged founder of the HMO movement.
His ideas spawned the managed-care industry in this country. But
Ellwood warned a Harvard University conference last month that
``uneven health care in the United States is a national disgrace
... unacceptable ... can't be allowed to continue.'' Astonishingly
few pundits noticed.
</P>
<P>
   This man, whose model at Jackson Hole, Wyo., was responsible for
the rampant spread of HMOs, is bitter now that the nation's health
insurance net has deliberately discarded so many of the very people
who need coverage the most. According to Koop, a record 16 percent
of all Americans have fallen through the cracks without any help to
fall back upon.
</P>
<P>
   Ellwood despairs of any major improvement surfacing from within
the profit-driven health system. He says the need has become so
critical that it requires broad government intervention. ``Market
forces will never work to improve quality, nor will voluntary
efforts,'' he declares, predicting foreseeable double-digit
increases in health premiums.
</P>
<P>
   Health is intensely personal. It affects everyone. Hardly
anything can shatter a family's tranquility or threaten its
economic lifeline more catastrophically than a major illness. Yet
whole segments of our society _ self-employed, domestic, workers in
countless service trades, newly created unemployeds outsourced by
the big corporations as a means of reducing payroll _ an entire
culture living on the edges of the new global economy has been
abandoned by health insurers.
</P>
<P>
   Scarcely a family anywhere has escaped some cataclysmic illness.
Lucky are we who contracted for coverage years ago and have been
able to hold onto it. I should know.
</P>
<P>
   For 60 years I was never hospitalized. Now, twice in the past
decade I've undergone major surgery for cancer and subsequent
treatment. I'm fortunate to have had good insurance coverage. But
suppose I were a commissioned salesman, or a small businessman, or
a self-employed carpenter or plumber, or someone dropped from
coverage by corporate downsizing. I could have been rendered
penniless.
</P>
<P>
   Even those with coverage in the health-care system often suffer
short-lived security. They live on the precipice of unannounced
change, driven by the profit motive, over which they have no
control.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, two Metroplex hospitals canceled their contracts with
managed-care companies. As many as 2,900 patients could be required
to find new doctors or new hospitals, or both.
</P>
<P>
   This sort of thing is going on across the country, as
money-motivated health-care providers vie with hospitals and
predatory nationwide groups buy up community hospitals or drive
them out of business. Often insurance premiums increase while the
number of physicians available to the patient shrivels.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, one of my daughters received a diagnosis of
multiple sclerosis. Twice she has been forced by her insurance
providers to change doctors. Today her company recognizes only one
of this specialty in the entire Metroplex. Kay has heard very good
things about a doctor in Dallas, but the arbitrary rules of the
company make his services inaccessible to her.
</P>
<P>
   The public momentum for change is beginning to reverberate in
Congress. Support is growing for a Patients' Bill of Rights.
Several Republican lawmakers with personal backgrounds in medical
practice have broken ranks with their party to support a Democratic
plan to strengthen protection for all Americans covered by private
health insurance. It would give patients broader rights to choose
their physicians and guarantee that doctors, not insurance company
personnel, determine what care is ``medically necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   One Oklahoma Republican, an obstetrician professionally,
recently told the House about a pregnant patient who'd been exposed
to chickenpox. As her doctor, he had prescribed an injection of
anti-serum. Her insurance company refused to pay, although it
covered obstetric care, saying the injection was not medically
necessary. The serum cost $700, and the mother needed it to protect
her unborn infant.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Rep. Charles Norwood, a dentist, rounded up 238
colleagues (19 more than a majority) to join him in sponsoring a
stronger bill than the GOP House leadership wanted. Still, this
measure got nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Gregg Ganske, a plastic surgeon, found 285 co-sponsors for
a measure to stop HMOs from imposing autocratic rules on their
doctors to prevent them from even telling patients about effective
treatment options that might cost a few dollars more than the HMO
wants to pay. That bill, too, has gone nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   But an undeniable momentum is building, fueled by public unrest.
Something must give. The need to fix an unresponsive system is
urgent. How to do so affordably is what people want to know.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Wright of Fort Worth is a former speaker of the U.S. House
of Representatives. You can write him at P.O. Box 1413, Fort Worth,
TX 76101, or at j.wright(at)tcu.edu. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
