 ART ADV.: Photos with SCI-STRESS and SCI-HYDROCEPHALUS, and a photo
and graphic with COLLEGE-ADULTS are being transmitted to NYT Photo
Service subscribers.  
 For Immediate Release  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following FEATURE stories for
use by NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta  &LR; at the
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of graphics
or photos please call 212 556-4204 or -1927.
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-MILOSEVIC (Belgrade) _ Operatives from Washington are
passing messages to Slobodan Milosevic's closest associates and
fishing for turncoats. Yet, as he struggles to hold on to power,
Milosevic has one major advantage: Who will succeed him? By John
Donnelly. 1500 (2 takes)
</P>
<P>
   DIANA-FORGET (London) _ Two years after Britain was swamped by
emotion over the death of Princess Diana, she seems to have been
forgotten by many. There are no official commemorations scheduled
Tuesday, the second anniversary of her death. By Kevin Cullen. 1400
words.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-HOMES (Izmit, Turkey) _ Almost two weeks after the
earthquake, which killed more than 13,000 people and left at least
200,000 homeless, officials are struggling to come up with a plan
to provide housing for survivors. By Aliza Marcus. 1030 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON (w) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-LEGACY (Washington) _ As Bill Clinton begins his
vacation, with retirement in 17 months, he's determined to use the
balance of his presidency to make up for the year he lost to the
Lewinsky scandal. By Ann Scales. 1218 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MACDONALD-INNOCENCE (Heridan, Ore.) _ His was one of the most
celebrated murder trials of this half-century, the subject of a
best-selling book and a TV movie that painted him as a cold-blooded
killer. Now Jeffrey MacDonald, the former Green Beret and surgeon,
is awaiting new DNA tests that he says will support his insistence
that he didn't kill his wife and two daughters in 1970. By Mitchell
Zuckoff (2 takes)
</P>
<P>
   COLLEGE-ADULTS (Undated) _ Only 25 percent of the students in
higher education are 18-22. About 50 percent are adult learners,
and that is the fastest-growing segment of higher education. By
Kate Zernike. 1360 words. PHOTO; GRAPHIC: 44 picas x 4 inches,
``Changing student body.''
</P>
