   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SKY-MYSTERY (Undated) _ Astronomers think they have solved
the mystery of the mysterious object that has confounded them ever
since its discovery three years ago. It's not any kind of star or
galaxy. Nor is it some entirely new celestial phenomenon. As a few
astronomers had suspected, the object is almost certainly an
extremely rare type of quasar. By John Noble Wilford. (1000 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MULTICELL-AMOEBAS When times are good and there are plenty
of bacteria to eat, Dictyostelium discoideum _ a species of soil
amoebas _ are loners. These microscopic one-celled animals are
content to crawl through their environment, absorbing whatever food
they come across. But when famine or other catastrophes strike,
something remarkable happens: using their protruding false legs for
propulsion, the amoebas seek each other out and stick together to
create a multicelled creature that can sense light and heat and can
travel faster and farther than any of its component cells traveling
alone. By Malcolm W. Browne. (1350 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ARCTIC-REDTAPE (Undated) _ Of all the adversaries of the
Arctic explorers of the 19th century, the most dangerous foe was
government bureaucracy, according to researcher who found many more
perils as part of government missions. By Michael Pollak. (450
words)
</P>
