<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RATTO-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SEEDY SIDE OF BASEBALL 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RAY RATTO  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The story was floated deftly, so that it would
sort of stick to the back of your brain rather than hit you flush
in the face. Plus, there were no fingerprints to lead the reader
anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   The story was that there have been some backchannel discussions
among baseball executives about buying out a few of the straggling
teams, presumably to save their cities the shame of having to
tolerate underfunded baseball any longer.
</P>
<P>
   The four cities mentioned were Kansas City, Minnesota, Montreal
and Oakland. The Royals saw an attempt by a local businessman to
buy the team for $75 million summarily rejected by the owners, the
Twins were rebuffed in their attempt to move to Charlotte, the
Expos are in position to become the first team in nearly two
decades to average fewer than 10,000 per game, and the A's because,
well, they're the A's.
</P>
<P>
   And the one doing the mentioning was an anonymous management
figure who admitted while the chances ``weren't 50-50, they were
better than 20-80.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, right. In fact, the chances of this are zero, but it does
give you fresh insight into the modern-day owners' thinking.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, ``Partners? What partners?''
</P>
<P>
   Before you get too worried about your favorite team, it should
be mentioned here that nobody in baseball is prepared to pick up
the tab for any of these alleged buyouts, which would total in the
neighborhood of $600 million if only four teams were folded. That
would be roughly $23 million from each of the surviving 26, and
frankly, we don't see a lot of will for that.
</P>
<P>
   But we know why the owners are at least whispering about it.
</P>
<P>
   This last expansion not only gobbled up the last promising city
for baseball (Phoenix) but stuck it with another city that could
take the game or leave it (Tampa-St. Petersburg). In other words,
there are no good places left to go, and too many teams that can't
muster up a good extortion pitch to their cities or politicians.
</P>
<P>
   So of course, confronted by this little conundrum, some
management deep thinkers suggest Plan B _ thinning out the herd.
</P>
<P>
   This wouldn't be much of a story if the A's weren't part of this
alleged discussion. It could hint at one more hurdle for the
Piccinini-Dolich group to clear in its attempt to convince the
owners to approve their $122 million offer to buy the Elephants.
</P>
<P>
   But since the A's are not only making money but actually
contending for a postseason berth, the timing of the story has a
particular poignancy and aroma to it. Aside from the economic and
logistical nightmare (asking Peter Magowan for $23 million to help
the A's get lost is in itself a Lucy skit waiting to happen), the
whole concept has that curiously half-baked taste to it that only
owners with too much time on their hands can produce.
</P>
<P>
   After all, what are the criteria? Not winning? Fine. Lose the
Dodgers, Rockies, Cubs, Orioles and Angels. Not making money? If
you believe the owners, everyone has to fold; if not, why don't you
throw the Marlins, Devil Rays, Tigers, Brewers and Pirates down the
gurgler? Not fashionable enough? The Astros, Rangers, Phillies and
White Sox.
</P>
<P>
   See how easy it is to put someone else on the endangered list
once you get started? Why, if it weren't for the owners' apparent
affection for commissioner Bud Selig, the Brewers would meet every
criterion for extinction, new stadium or no.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, even if you get back to 26 teams, you'll still be
looking at four teams that aren't cutting it with everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, what is so special about the Angels or White Sox or
Mariners or Padres? Tradition? Hah! May we refer you to four
divisions, the designated hitter, interleague play, six divisions
and Milwaukee back in the National League?
</P>
<P>
   And what's to say the Giants won't be in trouble in five years,
or the Tigers, or Pirates? They'll all have new stadiums next year,
but what happens in five years' time if they're not playing well?
They won't be drawing well, either, and then they'll become teams
on the extinction bubble too. And if you can do it once ...
</P>
<P>
   In other words, if four teams won't do it, why not eight? Why
not 14? Why not go back to two eight-team leagues and bring back
the Washington Senators, in case you need a little federal
legislation exempting baseball from the laws on inheritance taxes?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, anything is possible in this grand industry, including
euthanasia. And never mind the fact that the problems inherent in
shooting the slackers are currently insurmountable. It's the fact
that someone thought enough of the idea to float the concept in the
media that should make you think, and shake your head in disgust.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
