<HEADER>
A4591 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     08-30 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS THIS ABOUT DRUG USE OR HYPOCRISY?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the popular rationalizations for demanding that George W.
Bush answer these continuing questions about possible past drug use
is that he supports harsh treatment of drug offenders by the
criminal justice system.
</P>
<P>
   The theory seems to be that it is hypocritical for an elected
official to believe in punishing people for something that he may
have done at one time or another _ and that the public has a right
to know if the front-runner for the Republican presidential
nomination is a hypocrite.
</P>
<P>
   I have no objection to the practice of unmasking hypocrites. I
can say without reservation that unmasking hypocrites is a noble
pursuit.
</P>
<P>
   But that is not what's going on here. For one thing, there's
nothing hypocritical about a former drug user supporting tough drug
laws.
</P>
<P>
   For another, there's no indication that the media are concerned
about hypocrisy. There's as much hypocrisy in the media as there is
in any other field of endeavor.
</P>
<P>
   No, this hypocrisy business is simply an excuse invented by the
media to justify their continuing preoccupation with a nonstory
about George W. Bush and his alleged drug use.
</P>
<P>
   The media _ and Bush's political opponents _ may very well
suspect that the public has little interest in a candidate's
long-ago personal failings. But they can safely assume that the
American people have no use for a hypocrite.
</P>
<P>
   So if they can just convince everyone that the story is about
hypocrisy rather than drug use, they can keep it going a lot
longer.
</P>
<P>
   But if it is hypocritical for public officials to support tough
laws against conduct that they may have engaged in somewhere along
the way, then every member of Congress, every member of every state
legislature, every criminal court judge and every law enforcement
officer who has ever voted for or enforced the laws against drunken
driving should stand up in public and answer the question: Have you
ever driven under the influence of alcohol?
</P>
<P>
   Ridiculous, you say? Sure it is _ but no more ridiculous than
the suggestion that a politician who may have used illegal drugs
many years ago is now a hypocrite because he supports drug laws.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has confessed to abusing booze when he was younger. Is it
hypocritical for him to support enforcement of laws against drunken
driving and underage drinking? Of course not. And no one has even
suggested such a thing.
</P>
<P>
   But there's an aspect of this flap over Bush and drugs that's
even more distressing than the phony charge of hypocrisy: the
suggestion that certain categories of personal conduct have become
legitimate or even mandatory areas of inquiry for presidential
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Do most voters really want to know if some candidate for the
nation's highest office may have once upon a time smoked marijuana
or snorted cocaine or cheated on a spouse? A case can be made that
such behavior is relevant if it is current or recent _ but 25 years
ago? Now that's ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   And who gets to decide which areas of conduct are fair game for
inquiry? If we're asking about drug use and adultery, shouldn't we
also ask about domestic violence, alcohol abuse, exotic sexual
proclivities, underhanded business dealings, pathological lying,
reckless driving, speeding, road rage and stealing paper clips at
the office?
</P>
<P>
   Couldn't the list go on forever?
</P>
<P>
   With so many personal questions to ask, will there ever be time
to ask candidates where they stand on balanced budgets, military
preparedness, foreign policy, taxes, federal debt?
</P>
<P>
   By the time we get through examining and analyzing the personal
shortcomings of all the folks who want to be president, will there
be a moment or two left over to wonder about their actual
qualifications to serve as chief executive of the world's lone
remaining superpower?
</P>
<P>
   The new morality police in the media and politics apparently
believe that voters don't care about real issues. They believe that
all we care about is making sure that we have a president who has
never made a mistake and who will keep his hands off the interns.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
