<HEADLINE>
CHALLENGING WOMEN TO WALK FOR HEALTHIER HEARTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Mass., Conn.) (nk) 
 By ALISHA BERGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Women do not need to jog, much less run marathons, to reduce
their chances of heart disease. A survey of more than 72,000 women
ages 40 to 65, published last week in The New England Journal of
Medicine, showed that women who either walked briskly (20-minute
miles or faster) for a minimum of three hours a week, or who
exercised vigorously at least 90 minutes a week, had a 30 percent
to 40 percent reduction in their risk of heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   But getting people to exercise can be as challenging as getting
them out to vote. ``As many as 60 percent of adult women are
sedentary,'' said Dr. Elaine Stone, a health scientist
administrator at the National Heart, Lung and Blood Institute.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that women are less active than men, and this begins
as early as middle school,'' Stone said. ``About a third to a
fourth of adults participate in no physical activity at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Kyme, a vice president at the New York Health and Racquet
Club in Manhattan, says making the decision to be active is the
first step. ``It sounds crazy,'' he said, ``but the first thing is
making that decision. Any exercise routine becomes easy to
procrastinate. You have to say, `It's time I started doing
something _  &UR; now. &LR; ' Then you should consult your doctor. Once you
have the go-ahead, you need a plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Kyme suggested finding a workout partner because people tend to
show up more often when they have an appointment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Working out can be anything,'' he said. ``Any form of stress
on your heart in a good way will be good for you. Keep it fun, and
you'll go back. That's what matters in the long run.''
</P>
<P>
   The new report is part of the long-running Nurses' Health Study
at Brigham and Women's Hospital in Boston, which is following tens
of thousands of healthy women through the years to determine risks
of certain diseases.
</P>
<P>
   It showed that the more exercise people did, the greater the
reduction of their risk of heart disease; walking briskly for five
hours a week cut the risk of heart attacks 50 percent, for example.
</P>
<P>
   But any exercise is better than no exercise: 1 to 2.9 hours of
brisk walking a week brought a 30 percent reduction in heart
attacks and deaths from other coronary problems, the study said.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is it ever too late to start. Women who started exercising
later in life showed significantly reduced risk as well. ``At any
age,'' said Stone of the Heart, Lung and Blood Institute, ``it's
important to be active.''
</P>
<P>
   Terri Cingari, a 61-year-old retiree from Easton, Conn., says
she has been getting up early most mornings for the past 15 years.
She puts on her walking shoes, turns on her Walkman and sets out
for a three-mile walk to the banter of a local morning show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Walking makes me feel great,'' she said. ``I'd tell everybody
to walk. You don't have to buy anything special. You just get up,
get dressed and go. I really enjoy it, even though some mornings
you don't want to do it at all. And then, once you're going, before
you know it, you find yourself in step.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
