<SLUG> BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE HAUNTING OF OUR LANGUAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Sept. 5)  
(Eds: Items in bold should be set in italics.) 
(lb) 
(Jeffrey McQuain is the author of ``Never Enough Words: How
Americans Invented Expressions as Ingenious, Ornery and Colorful as
Themselves'' (Random House). William Safire is on vacation.) 
 By JEFFREY McQUAIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Most individuals arrested by the government,'' a Sudanese
dissident told ABC News, ``are routinely taken to unmarked
buildings we call  &UR; ghost houses &LR; . In these places all forms of
torture are practiced, and sometimes the detainees are killed.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only houses, however, are being haunted nowadays.  &UR; Ghost &LR; 
expressions have been rising rapidly throughout our language.
</P>
<P>
   The solid word  &UR; ghostware &LR; , for instance, first appeared in
computer lingo a few years ago. In 1996, Time magazine's Techwatch
included `` &UR; ghostware &LR; : technology that is alive and well today
with no one (or almost no one) sensing its presence.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's spookspeak also contains hyphenated compounds. Martha
Grimes, in her haunting 1996 novel ``Hotel Paradise,'' described
how a dying flashlight points ``its dim  &UR; ghost-circle &LR;  at the
wall.''
</P>
<P>
   Most  &UR; ghost &LR;  terms, though, are two-word phrases. The
lexicographer Cynthia Barnhart cites  &UR; ghost nets &LR; , a 1980s term
used by environmentalists for abandoned drift nets that entrap
marine life, and  &UR; ghost children &LR; . Writing for The Atlantic Monthly
in 1994, Xiao-huang Yin examined China's population problems: ``To
get around strict child quotas, villagers often fail to register
the births of their daughters. ... In a village near Baoying, in
northern Jiansu, I found seven such  &UR; ghost children &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   The first element of these scare words is nothing new.  &UR; Ghost &LR; 
itself came into Old English as  &UR; gast &LR; , ``soul, spirit.'' Among its
varied meanings are a doubled image on a TV screen and an absent
student counted as being present.
</P>
<P>
   Other English compounds may include words worth looking at for
their intimations of immortality. The lively  &UR; deadline &LR; , for
example, began as a literal term during the Civil War for the
boundary of a prison camp; any prisoner crossing that designated
line would be shot. Similarly, in the early 20th century,
 &UR; graveyard shift &LR;  (now often shortened to ``I'm working
 &UR; graveyard &LR; '') provided a fatal phrase for late-night employment.
But  &UR; ghost &LR;  terms have proved far more pervasive.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody said ``boo'' when the English philologist W.W. Skeat
coined  &UR; ghost word &LR;  in 1886. Skeat's term indicated any false
dictionary entry, usually the result of a misprint or misreading,
known in Latin as  &UR; vox nihili &LR; . A current dictionary maker detected
a  &UR; ghost word &LR;  in ``firmwave,'' a misspelling of the computer
``firmware.''
</P>
<P>
   Next came  &UR; ghost town &LR;  and  &UR; ghostwriter &LR;  early in this century,
but the lexical explosion began just a generation ago. Since the
1960s,  &UR; ghost feather &LR;  has been among a dusting of synonyms for
``dust bunny,'' a bit of fluff under furniture.
</P>
<P>
   Then  &UR; ghost time &LR;  appeared during the Vietnam War as military
slang for being off duty, and  &UR; ghost town &LR;  was revived to denote a
resort area after its busy season (leading the humorist Richard
Lederer, in his spirited new ``Word Circus,'' to serve up its
spoonerism:  &UR; toast gown &LR; ).
</P>
<P>
   The dead-on  &UR; ghost rider &LR;  has also been recently revived. This
expression, first popularized in the 1949 Western song `` &UR; (Ghost)
Riders &LR;  in the Sky'' by Stan Jones, came back in the early 1990s
for insurance fraud; when a bus or train wreck suddenly produces
more victims than the number of actual riders, the added claims are
said to come from  &UR; ghost riders &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Other transportation terms that have come out of nowhere include
 &UR; ghost train &LR; , identifying a train that runs at night to carry
convicts or to keep tracks from being shut down by snow.  &UR; Ghost
train &LR;  is also what London bus drivers call each night's final run,
while  &UR; ghost station &LR;  designates an unstaffed or unused train
depot.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Ghost plane &LR; , perhaps based on the Flying Dutchman myth of a
 &UR; ghost ship &LR; , began in the early 1990s for flights without fliers.
During an American Airlines strike in 1993, Michael Riley reported
in Time that ``angry passengers watched helplessly as  &UR; ghost
planes &LR;  _ no flight attendants, no passengers, just baggage _
pulled away from the jammed gates at Dallas-Fort Worth
International Airport.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert L. Chapman, the slang expert who revised Roget's
Thesaurus, notes the development of ``several dozen  &UR; ghost &LR; 
phrases. They have the same general semantic core: either something
that was once alive and is now dead (like  &UR; ghost town &LR; ) or
something that is mysterious or evanescent.''
</P>
<P>
   Explaining the popularity of these terms, Chapman adds: ``I
strongly suspect that the prevalence of  &UR; stealth &LR;  has stimulated
the productivity of  &UR; ghost &LR; . Perhaps  &UR; stealth &LR;  became too trendy,
so we consult our mental thesaurus for a way to avoid it.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon  &UR; ghost &LR;  may be the word to avoid. In the last decade, Wall
Street has scared up  &UR; ghost stock &LR;  for stock that cannot be
delivered, because it was sold short without being acquired for
delivery. A doctor can perform  &UR; ghost surgery &LR;  on another
physician's patient without that patient's knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   In The New Dickson Baseball Dictionary, Paul Dickson reveals
that sandlot baseball games may include a  &UR; ghost runner &LR; , an
imaginary player to enlarge a team's roster. More recent is the
street slang  &UR; get ghost &LR; , a verb phrase meaning ``to leave quickly
or disappear.''
</P>
<P>
   Anne H. Soukhanov, the author of ``Word Watch,'' also calls up
 &UR; ghost band &LR; . That musical noun phrase, she explains, conjures a
``group, especially one specializing in swing, that still bears the
name of its deceased leader and continues to perform with a new
leader and chiefly new members, in the manner of the Nelson Riddle
Orchestra.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, any unexpected reversal or change of direction is
called a  &UR; ghost turn &LR; . The ubiquitous signal of  &UR; thumbs up &LR; , for
instance, underwent a reversal of meaning a century ago. Until
then, the gesture was an ancient symbol for death or disapproval; a
Roman emperor would turn  &UR; thumbs up &LR;  (not  &UR; thumbs down &LR; ) to
indicate death, and a reverse or  &UR; ghost turn &LR;  produced its modern
sense of encouragement.
</P>
<P>
   Other supernatural sayings may soon materialize. In fact, these
 &UR; ghost &LR;  terms could be just the first part of the  &UR; phantom &LR;  menace.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
