   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   EVOLUTION-KANSAS (Pratt, Kan.) _ Despite controversy and
confusion swirling around her like dust devils in the wheat fields,
Lu Bitter, a science teacher at Pratt High School, is clear about
one thing: She will continue teaching the theory of evolution, as
she has for 27 years, until she is ordered to stop. She will do
this despite a recent decision by the Kansas State Board of
Education to remove any mention of evolution from the state's
science curriculum. By TONY FREEMANTLE.
</P>
<P>
   SPANISH-ONLY (El Cenizo, Texas) _ Mayor Rafael Rodriguez and
other city leaders say they never expected they would ignite a
national firestorm over an ordinance requiring that official town
business be conducted in Spanish. The mayor says the town
government has been the target of death threats because of the
ordinance. By DANE SCHILLER.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-SUIT (Austin Texas) _ Texas Attorney General John Cornyn
urges a judge to dismiss a subpoena seeking testimony from Gov.
George W. Bush in a whistleblower lawsuit filed by the fired head
of the state Funeral Service Commission. ``This is not a search for
the truth. This is about harassment. This is about politics,''
Cornyn tells state District Judge John Dietz. By JOHN GONZALEZ.
</P>
<P>
   ACLU-BUSH (Austin, Texas) _ The American Civil Liberties Union
says it will name Gov. George W. Bush and the Texas Department of
Public Safety as defendants in a lawsuit alleging that the state
police violated the free-speech rights of environmentalists
protesting outside the governor's mansion. By KATHY WALT.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-VIOLENCE (Washington) _ A leading juvenile-crime-fighting
organization says metal detectors and other popular anti-violence
measures alone won't protect school children. What will work _
according to the group, Fight Crime: Invest in Kids _ are programs
for mentoring and for expanding after-school activities. By MARK
HELM.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DIXIE-REVIEW (Undated) _ The Dixie Chicks are easily the
freshest act to emerge in country music in the last two years. The
group's bluegrass-inflected sound _ born and bred on the Texas club
circuit in the early `90s _ proved immediately accessible to
contemporary country audiences. By RICK MITCHELL.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBN-ASTROS (Houston) _ Pitcher Shane Reynolds goes for his 15th
win of the season as the Houston Astros host the New York Mets
tonight at the Astrodome. (Gametime is 7:05 p.m. CST.) By JOSEPH
DUARTE.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ The federal court ruling in Ohio
questioning the constitutionality of a Cleveland school voucher
program sent an overdue zinger through the political world. Many of
today's voucher champions don't care what happens to public
education. They crusaded years ago to kill the Department of
Education, which would have downgraded the importance of learning
by taking it out of the Cabinet. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
