<HEADLINE>
BEHAVIOR: WHEN TELEVISION SHAPES A SEX LIFE  
 SAFETY: CARRYING BAGGAGE, THE RIGHT WAY  
 PERFORMANCE: DOUBLE IRONWOMEN ACHIEVE THEIR GOALS 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Mich., Va., Mass.) (nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eagerly wondering what will happen to Ross and Rachel and
Chandler and Monica after the cliffhanger Las Vegas episode of
``Friends''?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you should not be too eager: Young women who get deeply
involved in the sexual content of television programs are more
likely than others to view sex as recreation, researchers say.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers, from the University of Michigan, surveyed 314
college students of both sexes, aged 18 to 20.
</P>
<P>
   ``This study found that females who are more active viewers
identify with the characters and attribute greater realism to the
portrayals are more likely to see sex as a goal and a game, unlike
a relationship,'' said Dr. L. Monique Ward, an author of the study,
who is an assistant psychology professor at the university. The
study appears in the current issue of The Journal of Sex Research.
</P>
<P>
   Where previous research focused on the role of heavy regular
consumption of television on viewers' attitudes, this study also
explored the role of viewer involvement. Ultimately, the
researchers found that how much viewers were involved, rather than
how much they watched, was a more consistent predictor of sexual
attitudes.
</P>
<P>
   ``TV may be a contributor to adolescent attitudes and
expectations about sex, especially for women,'' Ward said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It creates a heightened sexual atmosphere,'' she added, ``and
creates an impression that that's how things are in the real
world.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By ALISA TANG
</P>
<P>
   SAFETY: Carrying Baggage, the Right Way
</P>
<P>
   In the world of baggage, backpacks are better for joints and
muscles than briefcases and shoulder bags. But if worn improperly,
the backpack has its own perils.
</P>
<P>
   As students are gearing up for school, the American Physical
Therapy Association, a national professional organization, is
warning children and their parents to use care when they strap on
their packs.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're seeing is increased incidence of headaches,
shoulder pain, upper back pain and lower back pain,'' said Patrice
M. Winter, a physical therapist in private practice in Fairfax,
Va., and a member of the American Physical Therapy Association.
``In my opinion, it's a combination of more time at the computers
and having backpacks.''
</P>
<P>
   Many teen-agers have taken to slinging packs over just one
shoulder, said Ms. Winter, but that could lead to back pain,
strained shoulders and neck, or even scoliosis. Girls entering
puberty should be particularly aware of this danger, she said,
because they already face a greater risk of curvatures of the
spine.
</P>
<P>
   Students should also pay attention to the contents of their
bags, she said, because toting too many heavy textbooks can cause
children to alter their posture, affecting the natural curve of the
lumbar vertebrae, or the thoracic region in the upper back. She
advised students to carry loads no more than 15 percent to 20
percent of their body weight.
</P>
<P>
   ``When bags are overloaded or carried on one shoulder, the fine
balance of their structures are put in stress, and you can have
mechanical breakdown,'' Ms. Winter said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A bag should have wide shoulder pads that are well-padded,''
she added. ``But the most important thing is to have a backpack
that is the right size for the child.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By NINA SIEGAL
</P>
<P>
   PERFORMANCE: Double Ironwomen Achieve Their Goals
</P>
<P>
   They never claimed to be great athletes. But in Colonial Beach,
Va., this weekend, two New Yorkers, Patricia Buttenheim and Ann
Snoeyenbos, overcame heat, humidity and schools of stinging
jellyfish to become two of the first American women ever to finish
a ``double ironman'' triathlon: a 4.8-mile swim, a 224-mile bicycle
ride and a 52.4-mile run.
</P>
<P>
   It took Ms. Buttenheim, a 38-year-old registered nurse from
Brooklyn, 31 hours, 38 minutes. ``The hardest part,'' she said,
``was a tossup between the huge jellyfish stinging me on every
exposed part of my body during the swim and the pain in the feet at
the end of my run.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Snoeyenbos, a 35-year-old reference librarian from
Manhattan, missed the official cutoff time of 36 hours, but
soldiered on to finish in 37 hours, 22 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The two friends said they undertook the event to prove that
ordinary people can perform extraordinary feats. They began
training for the competition six months ago, arising at 4 a.m.
every weekday to cycle 40-plus miles around Central Park, then do
an hour and a half of yoga and strength training.
</P>
<P>
   The winner of the double ironman, Paul Bedard of Westport,
Mass., finished in 25 hours, 7 minutes. The women's top finisher,
Sylvia Wieneke of Switzerland, placed fourth overall, in 26 hours,
54 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   _ By LIZ NEPORENT
</P>
</TEXT>
