<HEADLINE>
JUSTICE TAKES A WALK IN ROBISON CASE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By J.R. LABBE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For 17 years the families of Larry Keith Robison's five murder
victims have waited for justice. Tiny measures of it came after two
jury trials found him guilty of killing Bruce Gardner. Numerous
appeals that upheld those convictions helped. But the families
thought they were finally going to get closure on Aug. 17 when a
lethal mix of chemicals was to be pumped into the veins of the
42-year-old murderer.
</P>
<P>
   A surprise ruling by the Texas Court of Criminal Appeals on a
petition filed the day before execution means that they may have to
wait many more years.
</P>
<P>
   Four hours before the scheduled execution, the appeals court
decided to stay Robison's date with death until doctors can examine
him to see if he's competent enough to be executed.
</P>
<P>
   That decision literally knocked the strength from members of the
Gardner family, who collapsed in a prison waiting room when word
came that their brother's killer had dodged his fate.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been so emotionally traumatic for the victims'
relatives,'' said Melissa Estes, an Oregon attorney who traveled to
Huntsville to be with her cousins, Bruce's brothers. ``If it hadn't
been for the compassion and support of Dan Guerra and the Victims
Services division of the Texas Department of Criminal Justice, we
would not have made it through.''
</P>
<P>
   Lois Robison, Larry's mother, got her prayer answered, at least
temporarily. She had some highly organized outside assistance in
making that happen.
</P>
<P>
   Amnesty International, the Roman Catholic Church and other
special-interest groups see Larry Robison as an opportunity to make
a political statement about capital punishment at the expense of
carrying out justice for the families of Bruce Gardner, Rickey Lee
Bryant, Gloria Ann Reed, her son, Scott, and her mother, Earline
Barker. Mrs. Robison no doubt welcomes this attempt to go against
the majority of Texans who, in poll after poll, have said they
support the death penalty as a means of exacting punishment for
premeditated, heinous crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Two separate juries and a number of appeals courts found Robison
sane when he committed the crimes, sane when he was convicted and
sane when he was sentenced. But now Robison is allegedly not
competent enough to understand the nature of his punishment and why
it is being imposed, the criteria necessary for execution to take
place, according to Robison's lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   William S. Harris, self-described as ``the lawyer who has
represented Larry Robison for the last four years through writs of
habeas corpus in both state and federal courts,'' told a Fort Worth
Star-Telegram reporter on Aug. 21 that he only recently found out
that ``Larry was making statements that suggested he didn't think
he could be killed.''
</P>
<P>
   How convenient for Larry. Why, even Harris admits that less than
two months ago his client was acutely aware of his situation _
enough to try to find a way around his jury-imposed death sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I don't think you know is (that) Mr. Robison, through his
attorneys, offered to plead guilty to the four remaining murders
and accept consecutive life sentences if the state would commute
his sentence to life. This offer was made more than a month and a
half ago,'' Harris wrote in an Aug. 18 e-mail to me.
</P>
<P>
   Problem 1 with this statement: Robison's legal eagles are trying
to undo what 24 jurors decided _ exchange a death sentence for life
in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Problem 2: In early July, Robison was competent enough to know
that he was going to die if he and his lawyers didn't come up with
Plan B. For Robison, Plan B is to believe he can't be killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``People go in and out of states of competency mentally in the
criminal justice system all the time,'' Harris wrote. ``In my
experience, it is not uncommon for some of them to go back and
forth from a state of incompetence to one of competence several
times.''
</P>
<P>
   One wonders if this will become a prevalent characteristic among
Death Row inmates with aggressive legal strategists in future
high-profile cases should Robison prove successful. It could rank
right up there with vicious killers suddenly finding Jesus when the
jail gate slams shut. Just as there are no atheists in a foxhole,
there are very few nonbelievers in a prison cell. There could be
fewer competent ones in the future.
</P>
<P>
   The question has never been, nor is it today, whether Robison
slaughtered five people on Aug. 10, 1982. It's whether he can
convince psychologists and a reviewing judge that he's incompetent.
Even if he's found competent, his attorneys will no doubt pursue a
series of appeals that could delay final resolution for years,
according to Tarrant County Assistant District Attorney Greg Pipes.
</P>
<P>
   It's no wonder that the families of the victims feel they've
been betrayed by the legal system.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been dragged through this horrible ordeal for 17
years,'' said Estes.
</P>
<P>
   What, exactly, is just about that?
</P>
<P>
   (Jill ``J.R.'' Labbe is senior editorial writer and columnist
for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. She can be reached via e-mail at
jrlabbe(at)star-telegram.com or by phone at (817) 390-7599. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
