<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Breeds Unto Their Own
</P>
<P>
   Scientists have always assumed that familiarity breeds. That is,
if two populations of a species live near each other, they will
eventually mingle and produce offspring.
</P>
<P>
   But researchers from Montpellier, France, studying blue tits on
Corsica, found that for two populations of the birds the island was
hardly a melting pot. The birds, which are highly mobile, lived
just 15 miles apart, one group in a forest of deciduous oaks, the
other among evergreen oaks. Tracking the two populations over six
years, the researchers found little evidence of interbreeding.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers, whose paper on the subject appears in the
current issue of Science, discovered that the birds' main food
source, leaf-eating caterpillars, became available a month earlier
in the spring in the deciduous forest than in the evergreen one
(corresponding to the earlier availability of leaves in one forest
versus the other).
</P>
<P>
   The birds breed when food is at its most abundant; therefore,
the two populations have adapted to their distinct food situations,
breeding one month apart. Blue tits from one population have little
interest in the other population at breeding time, helping to keep
them separate. The researchers suggest their work could have
implications for conservation policies that are meant to protect
diversity among species.
</P>
<P>
   Changing a Food Chain
</P>
<P>
   In their short lives, commercially raised chickens eat a lot of
phosphorous, a nutrient that helps their muscles and bones grow.
They also produce a lot of manure.
</P>
<P>
   Putting two and two together, that means manure contains a lot
of phosphorous. Chicken manure is often used as fertilizer, and
phosphorous-containing runoff from fields can pollute streams and
ponds and the water supply.
</P>
<P>
   This is a problem in areas with large commercial chicken
operations. Now scientists at the University of Delaware, working
with the United States Department of Agriculture and researchers
from companies with a stake in the chicken industry, have found a
way to reduce the amount of phosphorous in manure.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists have developed a corn hybrid that contains more
phosphorous that can be digested by the chickens. Regular corn
contains a lot of the element, but much of it is bound to phytic
acid and cannot be absorbed by the birds. The hybrid contains less
of the acid, and thus more of the phosphorous in the corn is
available. The researchers also fed the chickens an enzyme that
helps break down the phytic acid and make even more of the
phosphorous digestible.
</P>
<P>
   Grandfather of the Apes
</P>
<P>
   In the field of ape evolution, it's a jungle out there. The ape
family tree has been pared down in recent times, but millions of
years ago it was a mess, with lots of species around. It was hard
to separate the oreopithecus from the otavipithecus, not to mention
all the other pithecuses.
</P>
<P>
   A new fossil find from Kenya, announced in Science, has helped
sort out one twist of primate evolution. The fossil, a 12 million-
to 15-million-year-old partial skeleton about the size of a modern
baboon, represents a new genus, which the scientists who studied
the fossil named Equatorius.
</P>
<P>
   The find may be most important for what it says about another
fossil ape. By comparing the Equatorius skeleton with the two
species of another genus, Kenyapithecus, the researchers determined
that the more primitive of the two Kenyapithecus species belongs
among Equatorius.
</P>
<P>
   That may not seem like much of a distinction, but making it
frees up paleontologists to look at the remaining Kenyapithecus
species, named wickeri, in a different light. Considering wickeri
on its own, the researchers could see that some of its advanced
features connected it to more modern apes. For one thing, its
dental pattern is close to that of a fossil ape from Turkey,
evidence that wickeri is linked to a great explosion of apes out of
Africa 14 million years ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
