r i BC-HAVANA-NUN-2000(2TAKE     08-30 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAVANA-NUN-2000(2TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOTHER ROSARIO HAS RENEWED HOPE FOR MONASTERY AS CUBA CHANGES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nearly three years had passed since the 1959 revolution that
brought Fidel Castro to power.
</P>
<P>
   But the chaos lingering in Haydee Fernandez's native Cuba in
March 1962 was too much to bear. Church land had been seized,
private and secular schools had been closed and open worship
outlawed. The peso, once the equivalent of the American dollar, was
virtually worthless.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything was in turmoil,'' said Fernandez during a recent
visit to her parents' home in Burleson in North Texas. ``And not to
have freedom of speech and religion was the worst thing that could
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   That March, 55 days after requesting a visa, Fernandez boarded a
plane to Florida on the pretense that she wanted to continue her
education. The only things that she was allowed to bring were three
dresses and a pair of shoes _ the ones on her feet. The new clothes
that she had hoped to wear in America were left behind.
</P>
<P>
   For a 17-year-old who admittedly was in love with the material
world, that was as devastating for Fernandez as communism's
invasion of her homeland.
</P>
<P>
   Today, at age 58, the thought is almost too embarrassing for her
to repeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very worldly,'' Fernandez said as a smile hid the shame
in her brown eyes. ``I loved my clothing.''
</P>
<P>
   But Fernandez has changed. She is now known as Mother Superior
Maria Rosario, the driving force behind efforts to complete
additions to the Monastery Santa Catalina de Siena in Havana, a
project that began more than a decade ago. She has forfeited all
her worldly possessions _ including her name _ for a life of
introspection, solitude and prayer in a country in which religion
had been outlawed since Castro rose to power.
</P>
<P>
   But Cuba is changing, too, with religious prohibition slowly
being lifted. Winning government approval to make additions to the
monastery and other religious facilities is, perhaps, the single
best example of change in what was an atheist state from the time
of the Castro-led revolution until 1992.
</P>
<P>
   With only two years left in her stay in Cuba and no money,
however, Mother Rosario knows that she faces a formidable task. She
wants to build a 2-story addition to the centuries-old monastery
that would include four additional bedrooms, an infirmary,
wheelchair ramp and library. The estimated cost: $120,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's a lot, but I have faith it can be done,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ANSWERING A CALL
</P>
<P>
   Born in Cuba in 1941, Mother Rosario spent half her life in
North Texas with her stepmother, father and two brothers.
</P>
<P>
   She came to the United States first, alone, and lived with other
relatives until her immediate family arrived. Cuba was in turmoil
after the Castro-led revolution, with the Bay of Pigs invasion
having failed to topple him early in 1961. Mother Rosario's
departure from Cuba came only months before the Cuban missile
crisis almost plunged the world into nuclear war.
</P>
<P>
   She quickly adapted to life in the United States and was working
for Pier 1 in the late 1970s, but her strong religious convictions
led her to follow another path.
</P>
<P>
   She was on assignment as a temporary manager of a Pier 1 store
in Amarillo in the Texas panhandle when by chance she met a
Dominican priest. When she told him about her feelings, he
recommended that she visit the Monastery of the Infant Jesus four
hours away in Lufkin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt this calling many times, but I was too busy for that,''
she said. ``I always said, `No, no, Lord.' ''
</P>
<P>
   It was while on another assignment in Houston that Mother
Rosario decided to make the trip to Lufkin. She immediately felt at
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt I was not alone,'' she said. ``I felt the Lord was with
me, and he had brought me to the place I was to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Mother Rosario made four more visits to the monastery. Each
time, the nuns would share their stories and she would share with
them something from her own life.
</P>
<P>
   On Easter Sunday in 1980, she took a leave of absence from her
job with Pier 1, to enter the monastery to begin the process of
becoming a Dominican nun.
</P>
<P>
   It took nearly six years, but eventually, she took the vows of
obedience, which encompass chastity and poverty.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a very exciting day for me,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `THE CHURCH IS ALIVE'
</P>
<P>
   Mother Rosario is sitting in her parents' kitchen in Burleson,
dressed in a white habit and black veil. On her right ring finger
is a single gold band, signifying her marriage to Christ.
</P>
<P>
   She has come home for a short visit to see her father, who is
getting on in years, her stepmother and brothers, Jose and Robert.
</P>
<P>
   Mother Rosario talks openly about daily life in the monastery
but measures her words carefully about life in Cuba, fearing that
what she says might get back to the Cuban government.
</P>
<P>
   The life that she describes seems almost unbearable. Any hope
for progress that followed the much-publicized visit by Pope John
Paul II a year ago is slowly fading.
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
<P>
   Mother Rosario says little has changed either in Cuban society
or in Castro's regime. The Communist Party's rule remains strong,
and life for most people is a daily struggle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard because life is completely different,'' she said.
``You work, but the pay is very low. Food is rationed. You can't
buy clothing, toothpaste. You have to have dollars. The money in
the nation has no value.''
</P>
<P>
   But like most Cubans, she also believes that things have gotten
better in the past six years, even more so since the pope's visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The church is very much alive,'' she says. ``Mass is full.
People get their children baptized. They have Bible study and
catechism.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, she says that this is only a beginning. Mother Rosario
says that when a child reaches 7, the government no longer makes an
allotment of milk for the family. Almost everyone steals to get
things that they can sell for U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst part, though, is to live in a place where you don't
have freedom of speech,'' she said. ``Now people are more willing
to say things, but they still see if anyone is listening.
Everything is done with fear and trepidation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hope is there for the first time,'' she added, ``but they
move a little forward and then back.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SACRIFICE AND REWARDS
</P>
<P>
   Mother Rosario's stepmother hands her a Pepsi from the
refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   The soft drink, she says, is a luxury in Cuba. It symbolizes the
kind of sacrifice that she makes day to day to do what she believes
is the Lord's work.
</P>
<P>
   At first, she says, she was drawn back to Cuba because she
wanted to visit her sister, Eva, who has remained there alone, and
nephew, Waldre.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also wanted to see my mother's grave one more time (her
mother died when Mother Rosario was 10), and the people I left
behind,'' she said. ``But the longer I was there, the more I felt I
wanted to be there to help, to be with my people, to pray with
them, to help the sisters.''
</P>
<P>
   In September 1998, after a year of waiting for permission from
monastery officials in Lufkin, Mother Rosario returned to Cuba for
a three-year posting.
</P>
<P>
   What she didn't expect was to be voted Mother Superior.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a big surprise, believe me,'' she said. ``I didn't
know what I was getting into when I said yes, but the Lord has
given me the grace to take a day at a time and do my best.''
</P>
<P>
   Under her leadership, the nuns at Monastery Santa Catalina de
Siena rise at 5 a.m. and pray for people who leave requests either
in a box on the monastery grounds or on the telephone answering
machine. Seldom, she says, are those prayers specific.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that the world is in need of prayer, and we don't have
to know the specific need,'' Mother Rosario said. ``God knows what
each of us needs.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to praying, the nuns perform physical tasks such as
gardening, sewing habits, making fruit juice and cleaning.
</P>
<P>
   They rarely leave the monastery, and when they do, it's to visit
the doctor or dentist, or to buy groceries. None of them has a
stereo or television in her room, but each nun has a desk clock.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday nights, sometimes during supper, they indulge
themselves and listen to classical music on a small tape recorder.
It's a spartan existence, one still fraught with uncertainty and an
element of danger, but they persevere. Communism and religion are
co-existing in Cuba, and that alone is an accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sacrifice but I don't do it as a morbid thing,'' Mother
Rosario said. ``I really feel the Lord wants me there. I'm trying
to do my best for my people and my country.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   To make a donation to Mother Rosario's renovation effort,
contributions may be made to Monastery Santa Catalina, c/o Norwest
Bank, 100 Main St., Fort Worth, TX 76102.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
