<HEADLINE>
IF THIS IS DIVERSITY, CAN STEREOTYPES BE FAR BEHIND?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Parkers'' is a breed of sitcom that has been nearly
nonexistent during the past few television seasons but will
undoubtedly make a comeback over the next two. Uproar concerning
the absence of minority faces on prime-time dramas and comedies
will see to that as networks scramble to present a future world
more representative than the one that, for the time being, looks
like the proverbial polar bear in a snowstorm.
</P>
<P>
   The question is whether the future of black sitcoms will look
and sound like ``The Parkers.'' UPN was slow in sending a review
tape of Monday's episode, which is enough of a red flag to warrant
concern. But let's be optimistic. Having seen the premiere episode
of this comedy and the introductory, test-the-waters episode of
last season's ``Moesha,'' I have a pretty good idea of what we have
to look forward to. It's isn't pretty.
</P>
<P>
   Following ``Moesha'' and sitting in the middle of UPN's
segregated Monday of black-oriented programming (hey, why not stay
around for Jaleel White in ``Grown Ups'' and Eddie Griffin in
``Malcolm &AMP; Eddie'' for your black cultchah!), ``The Parkers''
arrives on the shoulders of two amusing women who might be better
digested as bit players to straight-man performers but are much too
much when presented as a tag team.
</P>
<P>
   Countess Vaughn, who played the comedic spark plug on
``Moesha,'' brings her fast-talking, slang-throwing character to
``The Parkers'' as half of a mother-daughter team that has invaded
the local junior college. The running gag here is the educational
setting itself, that the 36-year-old Mom (who just got her high
school diploma, by the way) is hanging out with these young folks
and driving her daughter up a wall. Monday's episode dealt with Mom
and daughter joining the same sorority.
</P>
<P>
   Mom is played by Mo'Nique, a stand-up comic who is a lot like
Thea Vidale, the latest oversized, loud-mouthed, take-no-mess black
female stand-up comic whom the networks deemed a mainstream crowd
pleaser. The creators of ``Thea'' were sensible enough to keep a
lid on Vidale's bulldozing persona, but something tells me that in
the name of ratings, the same restraint might not be exercised
here.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Parkers'' is co-executive produced by Ralph Farquhar, who
co-created ``Moesha'' with integrity and was the mastermind behind
the superb but short-lived ``South Central'' as well as the bland,
but amusing, ``The Sinbad Show.'' I have to say that surprise is my
initial reaction to Farquhar's decision to even put ``The Parkers''
out there, but maybe he'll surprise me.
</P>
<P>
   I always thought that Vaughn's neck-wiggling, bug-eyed Kim was a
change of comic pace on ``Moesha,'' sort of a nod to the fact that,
well, despite the potential stereotype of the sassy black woman,
the Kims of the world do exist. That her character was part of a
balanced set of images made her tolerable and therefore comical.
</P>
<P>
   The question is whether we can take Kim and now a larger version
of her as leads who will more than likely fill nearly every frame,
and whether there will be an effort to balance what could very well
be the target of the image police.
</P>
<P>
   Missing from the current no-people-of-color debate in this
year's crop of series is what happens when networks dash out and
buy products for the sake of having minority faces. TV's track
record is dismal when airing black-oriented series anyway, so the
thought of networks jumping into the game just to silence the NAACP
is scary.
</P>
<P>
   Then we'll be right back where we were a few seasons ago,
wondering why every black character is a criminal or buffoon and
every Hispanic is the wacky gardener.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Contact him at (817) 390-7862 or
kperkins(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
