<HEADLINE>
SCHOOLS REACH OUT FOR HOMELESS CHILDREN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By YVETTE CRAIG 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ At 6:30 a.m., tiny voices begin to resonate
inside the Presbyterian Night Shelter. Thirty-nine children have
slept there overnight, and more than a dozen are getting ready for
school.
</P>
<P>
   There is no smell of brewing coffee or sizzling bacon. Instead,
the odor of sweat, stale cigarettes and dirty mop water lingers in
the facility hidden on a side street east of downtown Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   For reasons as varied as their appearance, more and more
children and teen-agers are being reared in homeless shelters once
occupied mostly by men on Skid Row. Educators in Fort Worth and
nationwide are reaching into the shelters and pulling these
children into classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1998-99 school year, the Fort Worth school district
counted 1,470 homeless children among its students. The numbers
this year are higher.
</P>
<P>
   ``The average age of a homeless person is now 9,'' said June
Davis, the district's guidance program coordinator. ``I am amazed
at how resilient these children are. They tend to make the best out
of the situation they are in.''
</P>
<P>
   The number of children housed at the night shelter recently
swelled to 54, forcing the staff to rearrange the cots on the
concrete floor in the cavernous sleeping rooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't make any sense of this,'' said John Suggs, head of
the area's largest walk-in shelter, which serves more than 500
people. ``The only thing we can think of is that people are trying
to stabilize their lives now so that their children can go to
school.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite a booming economy, children end up on the streets, often
with a parent, because of a shortage of affordable rental housing,
a parent's addiction to drugs or alcohol or an attempt to escape an
abusive family member.
</P>
<P>
   Cut off from familiar surroundings, friends or relatives,
homeless children can become alienated. They can't have sleepovers
with classmates. They rarely join scouting groups or after-school
sports teams, and they have no comfortable place to do homework.
</P>
<P>
   They live in uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   But just as a desperate environment can breed apathy and
cynicism, it can also produce remarkable grit.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PREPARING FOR SCHOOL
</P>
<P>
   Pam Nesmith wipes the sleep from her eyes and flips on a light
switch inside a mint-green room, not much bigger than a walk-in
closet, on the second floor of the Presbyterian Night Shelter.
</P>
<P>
   Stretched out on a narrow mattress, their feet draped over each
other's legs, are Jeffrey and Ashley, Nesmith's 9-year-old twins.
Nesmith came to Texas from Massachusetts, and the three have been
in and out of shelters since the twins were born.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time to get up and get ready for school,'' Nesmith says,
nudging them.
</P>
<P>
   Ashley sweeps her strawberry-blond hair from her cheek, sits up
and greets her mother with an angelic smile. Her brother needs more
coaxing.
</P>
<P>
   For Nesmith, the chore of rousing her children and getting them
off to school is the same as for any parent at home.
</P>
<P>
   But there, the similarities end.
</P>
<P>
   The twins just started third grade at Van Zandt-Guinn Elementary
School. Through the school district's homeless program, the two
have received blue-and-white uniforms to wear, a package of
underwear and socks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get dressed now so you can go and brush your teeth,'' says
Nesmith, whose private room is a perk of being on the shelter's
staff.
</P>
<P>
   The children are unfazed by the sounds of a resident vomiting in
the hallway below.
</P>
<P>
   Ashley heads to the bathroom. Wearing too-small sneakers, she
walks past the coughing and scratching vagrants just waking up on
the men's side of the shelter.
</P>
<P>
   There's no bubble bath _ just weary mothers gently brushing
tangled hair.
</P>
<P>
   The school bus will come soon. Waiting along Cypress Street,
both children ignore the people sleeping on the sidewalks. And when
the school bus stops, the twins run to it and plop down next to
other children just picked up from the Union Gospel Mission down
the street.
</P>
<P>
   Nesmith worries about the teasing her children may endure.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know how kids can be cruel,'' she says, waving at the bus
in her tattered cotton nightgown. ``They tease them and call them
shelter kids. It isn't fair.''
</P>
<P>
   When the children leave, Nesmith's smile does, too.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE VAN ZANDT-GUINN
</P>
<P>
   Monday morning. The 300 students file into the hallways as if
their shoes were made of lead; the weekend seems to have drained
their energy.
</P>
<P>
   A breakfast of toast, cereal and chocolate milk in the school
cafeteria raises their energy a notch.
</P>
<P>
   In uniforms, there is no way to distinguish homeless students
from others. Educators want it that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want these students singled out,'' Davis says.
</P>
<P>
   The school bell rings and the students, prekindergarten through
fifth grade, walk single file to their homerooms.
</P>
<P>
   Ashley and Jeffrey are in adjacent rooms. Jeffrey, at least for
now, is tired of his sister's company. She's been pouting all
morning, since she fell down the stairs at the shelter.
</P>
<P>
   MORE &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Ashley reports the mishap to her teacher, Mayme Macon, who
promptly sends her to the school nurse.
</P>
<P>
   Gregorita Smith examines a painful spot on Ashley's back and
notices that insect bites cover her back. She also has bites on her
ankle and arms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen a lot of things,'' Smith says later. ``The children
come in here with ringworm, ant bites, lice and a number of other
things. One kid came in complaining about his leg hurting, and I
found a scorpion on him, which scared me to death.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said she often serves as the primary medical caregiver for
the homeless students.
</P>
<P>
   Ashley returns to class, and the learning begins.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey, an introvert with bright eyes, appears most comfortable
completing his schoolwork in the computer lab.
</P>
<P>
   ``Line the horses up in order,'' the computer screen reads.
</P>
<P>
   Click. Click. Click. The task is done.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey smiles.
</P>
<P>
   Macon has been teaching at Van Zandt-Guinn for more than 20
years and says that meeting the educational needs of homeless
children is a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never know how long they will be with us,'' says Macon, a
certified reading recovery teacher. ``One student came to my
classroom, and he had already lived in seven different states.''
</P>
<P>
   Some homeless students are in school one day and gone the next.
Others show up in the middle of the year. Some students are shy and
don't want to participate in class. Others are bright and fit right
in.
</P>
<P>
   Davis says parenting classes stress the importance of keeping
children in school.
</P>
<P>
   According to a report the Department of Education issued to
Congress last week, homeless children are almost three times more
likely than other students to miss three or more weeks of school
during a three-month period. As a result, the report said, many are
slower to develop language and motor skills and to acquire personal
and social skills.
</P>
<P>
   In Fort Worth, the district provides tutors to assess homeless
students' individual needs.
</P>
<P>
   Macon visited the shelters to see firsthand the conditions in
which homeless students live.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an eye-opening experience,'' she says. ``You know about
the homeless adults, but you don't know about the children until
you see it for yourself. It ripped my heart right out.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, Macon says, homeless children need a stable home.
But while they are homeless, she says, they need to be in school to
acquire the skills to escape poverty.
</P>
<P>
   Van Zandt-Guinn has more than 60 homeless students enrolled this
session, the most of any school in the Fort Worth district.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth's homeless program, called Give 'Em A Chance,
receives $135,000 in federal funds, most of which provides school
supplies, clothing and field trip money, as well as emergency
medical, dental and eye care, Davis says. The district kicks in an
additional $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   Youngsters from the Salvation Army attend Meadowbrook
Elementary. Children from Second Chance, an agency that provides
transitional housing for homeless women with children, attend
Sagamore Hill Elementary.
</P>
<P>
   Van Zandt-Guinn is part of the district's Elementary Schools
Initiative, a program started in 1995-96 to help low-achieving,
low-income schools improve.
</P>
<P>
   It worked.
</P>
<P>
   Once rated as one of the state's low-performing schools, Van
Zandt-Guinn can now boast that more than 80 percent of its students
passed the Texas Assessment of Academic Skills test, earning it a
rating of ``recognized'' from the state for two years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL IS OUT
</P>
<P>
   The view from the bus on the ride back to the shelter is hardly
scenic. The bus passes blighted streets dotted with abandoned
homes, littered streets and vagrants gulping alcohol from bottles.
</P>
<P>
   Dinner _ the usual fare of rice and beans _ is being served when
Ashley and Jeffrey return to the shelter about 3:30 p.m. The twins
frown at the meal and instead race up to their room to watch
cartoons on a small TV with poor reception.
</P>
<P>
   Nesmith wakes from a nap and asks the two about their day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The teachers have told me that the both of them have improved
quite a bit,'' Nesmith tells a visitor, kissing Jeffrey on his
forehead. ``They both work so hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Later that evening, as overnight visitors fill the shelter, the
children are visited by church volunteers who participate in play
groups and help with homework.
</P>
<P>
   Rachel Griesemer, 22, is the shelter's case manager. This is her
first job since graduating from Texas Christian University in May.
</P>
<P>
   When she's not tracking down immunization records, birth
certificates and school report cards, Griesemer says, she lends an
ear to the children who want to vent about their day.
</P>
<P>
   She describes them as having hard-earned street smarts.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know the ins and outs of the streets,'' Griesemer says.
``The people here don't scare them, and they are not surprised by
their environment. It's a lifestyle they have learned to deal
with.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
