<HEADLINE>
FOCUSING ON PREVENTION IN FIGHT AGAINST AIDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Ga., Calif., Md., Texas, La., Fla., Colo.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
(nk) 
 By LAWRENCE K. ALTMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Death rates from AIDS in the United States slowed again in 1998.
But the rates are no longer falling as rapidly as they did from
1995 to 1997, after the introduction of combination drug therapy,
health officials said Monday at a meeting in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   And the rate of infection with HIV, the AIDS virus, is no longer
declining and has stabilized, the officials said. About 40,000
Americans have been infected annually in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, AIDS deaths dropped 42 percent from 1996 to 1997 but
only 20 percent from 1997 to 1998, reported the Centers for Disease
Control and Prevention in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Although these rates are much lower than they were at their peak
in the 1980s, the slowing rate of decline shows that more
aggressive prevention efforts are needed, officials said. At the
same time, a new method of testing blood has been providing
hitherto unavailable information about trends in new infections and
fresh ways to detect hot spots of infections _ steps that are
expected to help focus prevention efforts on groups in which the
virus is being transmitted most rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   The incidence of new infections with HIV was ``dangerously
high'' in some areas among young gay men and heterosexual women,
particularly blacks and members of other minorities, participants
at a conference in Atlanta said.
</P>
<P>
   The new studies also showed that the highest rates of HIV
infection were found among men and women who had been infected with
other sexually transmitted diseases.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this era of better therapies, it is clear that people are
becoming complacent about prevention,'' said Dr. Helene Gayle, who
directs the AIDS program for the CDC in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Experts have offered several explanations why the decline in the
death rates has slowed. One is that a saturation effect has set in:
Most people who know they are infected are already receiving the
newer combinations of drug treatments and are responding favorably,
which has helped reduce the death rate.
</P>
<P>
   But at the same time, many people are unable to take the large
number of pills prescribed each day according to a rigid schedule
that is often built around meals, or the HIV strains infecting them
are resistant to the drug combinations.
</P>
<P>
   In New York City, AIDS deaths dropped by 25 percent in 1998
after falling a total of 63 percent in the two previous years. But
the number of deaths did not drop at all from the first half of
1998 to the second half, said Dr. Mary Ann Chiasson, an assistant
commissioner of disease intervention research at the New York City
Department of Health. And the death rate during the first six
months of 1999 was expected to be about the same as the first six
months of 1998, which would suggest that the rate has leveled off.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, AIDS deaths in New York City dropped sharply from 1995
to 1998, but different groups declined at different rates. White
men had the greatest decline, 83 percent; black women declined 75
percent. But two new studies, from the New York City Department of
Health and the Michigan Department of Community Health, hint that
bisexual practices among black men may lead to a higher rate of
infection among black women, as men are infected by other men and
then transmit the virus to women.
</P>
<P>
   In the New York City study of more than 7,000 men in gay bars
and other meeting places, 20 percent of the black men reported
having had sex with both men and women, compared with 12 percent of
Hispanics and 4 percent of white men.
</P>
<P>
   There was one bright spot: HIV infections in New York have been
decreasing among people who inject drugs, according to a study by
the New York Department of Health AIDS Institute. The decline was
attributed in part to prevention programs.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The emphasis on prevention was the impetus behind a four-day
meeting in Atlanta, which began Sunday. Although sessions on
prevention are part of the large international meetings held every
other year and the scores of smaller meetings held each month, AIDS
workers felt that prevention was not getting enough emphasis. So
the CDC and 17 other organizations are sponsoring a national
meeting to focus on scientific efforts to monitor and prevent
infection.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting comes at a time when more people are living with
AIDS and HIV.
</P>
<P>
   The CDC, a federal agency with an annual budget of $2.6 billion,
also is under pressure to justify spending $657 million on AIDS
programs. Nearly seven-eighths of the AIDS budget, $565 million,
was spent on HIV prevention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if we get better treatments, we are naive in thinking we
will wipe out AIDS by treatment alone,'' Gayle said. ``Prevention
perhaps is more important than ever, and we need to elevate its
importance.''
</P>
<P>
   Prevention efforts have been hampered by the lack of a national
reporting system for HIV. Since the disease was discovered in 1981,
health officials have tracked the virus by using reported cases of
AIDS. But because drug therapy is delaying or preventing HIV from
progressing to AIDS, new tracking techniques are needed, and health
officials are beginning to use a combination of two blood tests to
estimate the number of new infections.
</P>
<P>
   One is the standard blood test that detects the antibodies that
are formed to fight infections. HIV antibodies develop an average
of six to eight weeks after the virus has entered the body, but
there is no way to tell from a single test when a person became
infected. Because it takes many weeks for the antibody production
to peak, researchers have developed a second test, a less-sensitive
version of the standard one.
</P>
<P>
   When the two tests are done together, scientists can identify
new HIV infections. ``If the first test is positive and the second
is negative, the probability is that the individual got infected in
the last six months,'' said Dr. Robert S. Janssen, an expert on the
tests at the CDC. ``And if both tests are positive, infection most
probably occurred more than six months earlier.''
</P>
<P>
   Using these tests, researchers from the CDC led by Dr. Hillard
Weinstock found an annual infection rate of 6 percent among gay men
treated in clinics specializing in sexually transmitted diseases in
Baltimore, Denver, Houston, Los Angeles, Miami and New Orleans. The
rate was 15 times the 0.4 percent figure for heterosexuals treated
in the same clinics.
</P>
<P>
   And a study by Dr. Sandra Schwarcz of 34,866 men and women
treated in sexually transmitted disease clinics in San Francisco
found an annual infection rate of 1.6 percent. The rate was highest
among gay men who used drugs (8.2 percent); for other gay men, it
was 6.6 percent. People with gonorrhea had an HIV infection rate
five times that of those without gonorrhea (6 percent compared with
1.2 percent). Inflammation from gonorrhea and other sexually
transmitted diseases is believed to enhance the transmission of
HIV.
</P>
<P>
   The rates, which were higher than expected, underscored the need
for improved detection and treatment, Gayle said.
</P>
<P>
   In a study in six cities, researchers led by Dr. Linda Valleroy
found ``alarming'' rates of HIV infection in 3,492 gay men, aged 15
to 22 years. Valleroy found that an average of 7 percent of the
participants were HIV-infected and that new infections occurred at
a rate of 3 percent each year.
</P>
<P>
   Young blacks had the highest rates of infection (14 percent)
compared with mixed race (13 percent) and Hispanics (7 percent).
HIV incidence rose with age, rising from 2 percent among
adolescents to 4 percent among young men in their 20s.
</P>
<P>
   Blacks represent 13 percent of the U.S. population. But blacks
accounted for 49 percent of AIDS deaths and 48 percent of AIDS
cases in 1998, and are experiencing less dramatic declines in AIDS
deaths than whites, according the CDC.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
