<HEADLINE>
TIGER ASKS FOR SUBDUED ROAR AT RYDER CUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SUSAN FORNOFF  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Golf is an old game, but its fans may be younger
than ever. And one 23-year-old is sounding almost fatherly in
expressing concern about where this may lead.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods was talking specifically about next month's Ryder
Cup in Brookline, Mass., in light of the boisterousness of the fans
during the final hours of his battle with Sergio Garcia at the PGA
Championship two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope our fans won't be as loud as they can be and as
boisterous,'' Woods said recently. ``I don't want them to go
overboard where they are rooting against the other team. Cheer for
both sides. Maybe bipartisan in how loud the roars are. I
understand that. But make sure that you be fair and understand that
golf is a gentleman's sport.''
</P>
<P>
   That's an interesting concept coming from Woods, who many think
oversteps the gentlemanly boundaries with his on-course
fist-pumping. But he was the enemy in his match with Costantino
Rocca in Spain two years ago, and establishes some boundaries of
his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope they don't get out of hand where they are either booing
or yelling for someone to hit a bad shot,'' Woods said.
</P>
<P>
   If he hears any of that next month, at least it should be on his
side. In the meantime, he's heading for San Francisco to present a
junior golf clinic and exhibition at Harding Park on Sept. 6.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
