<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-PATIENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ESSAY: PATIENT SUFFERS FROM CONNOTATIONITIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 By ABIGAIL ZUGER, M.D.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Another aspect of health care is coming up for some needed
reform. The chief executive of the King's Fund, an influential
British health charity and research organization, says it is high
time to abolish the word ``patient.''
</P>
<P>
   Derived from the Latin ``patior,'' or ``I suffer,'' ``the word
indicates immediately the unequal nature'' of the relationship
between the patient and the doctor,'' the executive, Rabbi Julia
Neuberger, wrote in the June 26 issue of The British Medical
Journal.
</P>
<P>
   Patients are timid, passive, horizontal creatures, while doctors
are powerful, decisive and vertical. This distinction ``may have
sat happily with ancient ideas of respect for doctors,'' Rabbi
Neuberger went on, ``but it fits poorly with modern views of users'
taking an active part in their own health care, and indeed taking
responsibility for some of their own recovery.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Patient'' also implies that the person on the receiving end of
health care is ill. But in fact, Rabbi Neuberger noted, as disease
prevention plays an ever more prominent role, patients are likely
to be at least as healthy as anyone else in the examining room.
</P>
<P>
   But if ``patient'' has to go, what word should replace it?
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Neuberger considered but rejected ``client,'' which she
thought made health care delivery sound like a purely financial
transaction. (Actually, ``client'' derives from the Latin word for
an underling who leans on a patron in a fawning, subservient kind
of way, and has possibly even more unfortunate implications than
``patient.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumer'' also struck her as wrong, conjuring an image of the
``constant ingestion of pills and potions.'' She finally settled
for ``user,'' a word that ``despite its lack of elegance,'' conveys
action rather than passive acceptance, confidence rather than
bewilderment, power rather than dependency. ``It could even suggest
an equalization of status between health professional and service
user that is nearer the climate in which modern health services
should be provided,'' she declared.
</P>
<P>
   But who exactly are these ``health professionals''? Our patients
_ that is to say, our users _ used to know us as doctors, dentists,
nurses, pharmacists, therapists. Perhaps we are now called health
professionals to distinguish us from health amateurs: mothers,
grandmothers, patron saints and swamis who have managed to squirm
into our fields without forking over the requisite tuition.
</P>
<P>
   We answer to ``health care providers,'' an optimistic term
evoking a pleasant utopian vision of banquet tables overflowing
with cornucopias of free health, which we periodically restock from
the heavy trays on our shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   One cannot help but feel that some further change in
nomenclature is in order for all of us, so that our usual roles in
modern health care delivery might be reflected more precisely.
</P>
<P>
   One option would be to return to a more technical language, as
is already the custom in operating rooms, emergency rooms and other
rapid-action medical settings. People seeking care there tend to be
called by the pertinent part of their anatomy: the hernia in Room
5, the appendix in the O.R., the rash who just ducked out for a
smoke. But elsewhere in medicine, this approach would transform far
too many people into pains, drips and headaches to be widely
acceptable. It would be equally hard on us providers: I, for
instance, would turn into the prescription pad in Room 2 _ a
depressing if not entirely inaccurate description.
</P>
<P>
   A second approach might be simply to ignore the technicalities
of the relationship. Patients and providers would become friends,
colleagues, associates or longtime companions; we would all be
persons, humans and comrades in health.
</P>
<P>
   But as long as disability and insurance forms, those most
politically incorrect of documents, circulate among us, this reform
would never fly. ``Please have your friend or associate complete
this section'' would reduce us to chaos in a month.
</P>
<P>
   A better plan might be to take a long step back and look at the
realities of our mutual enterprise these days. A classic 1977
collection of essays analyzing the American health care scene was
titled ``Doing Better and Feeling Worse''; to anyone scanning
today's headlines, the phrase still rings true. Health is the still
the pot of gold at the end of an ever more glorious, nebulous and
unsatisfactory health-care rainbow.
</P>
<P>
   Patients pick the name of yet another strange doctor out of a
new care plan's catalog. Doctors scan lists of patients they never
met, and rules they never bargained for. Wonderful new operations
are possible. Magic pills with unpronounceable names flood the
market. Cash registers clink. The invisible ranks of the uninsured
mount.
</P>
<P>
   A new children's hospital slated to open in the Bronx in 2001
plans to distract sick children with a theme of space exploration.
On admission, children will be told they are ``explorers on a
journey to healing'' and will get a passport, a compass and a
periscope to help them navigate. The truth is that every one of us
could use a kit like this for ourselves, for that is what we really
are these days: whatever name we answer to, we are explorers,
fellow adventurers, worried pilgrims all.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
