<HEADLINE>
CHARGES VOLLEYED IN ARIZONA FIRING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating for San Antonio; moved 8/25)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A battle is brewing in Phoenix where Arizona Republic columnist
Julie Amparano, fired last week for allegedly fabricating sources,
is denying the charges and threatening to sue the paper.
</P>
<P>
   According to executive editor Pam Johnson, on Aug. 18 a
senior-level editor informed her of some newsroom fears that
Amparano might be inventing characters in her new ``Conversations''
column. An internal examination of the sources in 11 of her columns
turned up 20 names that could not be traced.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the investigation, Julie offered contradictory
statements about her work that raised futher doubts,'' said a
statement issued by Johnson. ``She also described her reporting
methods, which fell far short of accepted journalistic practices.''
She was fired on Aug. 20.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all had a lot of fondness for (Amparano),'' Johnson said in
an interview. But ``nobody is bigger than our public trust.''
</P>
<P>
   Amparano, 39, is a regional director for the National
Association of Hispanic Journalists and a five-year Republic
veteran. Her attorney Stephen Montoya offered a ``flat out denial''
of wrongdoing, saying ``the practices that Julie employed in
writing her feature column are employed throughout the paper.''
Montoya adds that he and Amparano are searching for the sources in
question and ``weighing our options. The possibility of a
defamation action .
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, however, the Amparano furor does not seem to have
stirred up much passion outside the newsroom. As of Aug. 25,
Republic reader advocate Richard de Uriarte said he'd received only
about 20 public comments on the firing. ``In comparison to the loss
of a bridge column, it's nothing,'' he says.
</P>
</TEXT>
