<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOULD TAXPAYERS SUBSIDIZE PRIVATE SCHOOLS? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In this democracy of ours, some places are
experimentally turning against the free, nondiscriminatory public
schools to prop up private religious schools with taxpayers' money
for individual tuition costs.
</P>
<P>
   If carried out nationally, this shift of educational emphasis
could drain the secular public schools and authorize a widespread
separate religion-based training system for young children at their
most impressionable age.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, a federal judge in Ohio said last week that this
notion is constitutional nonsense.
</P>
<P>
   He ultimately allowed Cleveland school officials to go ahead
with plans for a citywide school voucher program that would give
some 3,400 low-income students public money for education in
private schools, most of them religious-based. But in setting a
Dec. 13 trial date for the case, he did not back off his contention
that the program has ``the primary effect of advancing religion.''
</P>
<P>
   His criticism sent an overdue zinger through the political
world.
</P>
<P>
   If he finally rules against the voucher program and is upheld by
higher courts, the decision will be a much-needed legal correction
in a partisan controversy that has pitted Republicans against
Democrats for the past decade. The issue has become a central test
of the direction of education in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP, favored by fundamentalists and the organized Catholic
establishment, wants to encourage religious schools by forcing
taxpayers to subsidize pupils who attend them. Except for
presidential candidate Bill Bradley, the Democrats _ long backed by
the National Education Association, the biggest teachers' union _
want to strengthen public schools with generous aid from the
taxpayers for better teaching tools.
</P>
<P>
   Politically, it does not seem possible to do both
simultaneously. Even if the financial resources were there, the
ideological gap is too enormous to overcome.
</P>
<P>
   Both public and private schools are in financial trouble. They'd
like federal help. Who wouldn't?
</P>
<P>
   But one direction represents the American way, and the other a
return to the overbearing religious influence our forefathers and
mothers fled Europe to escape.
</P>
<P>
   The best argument for parochial schools is a practical rather
than theological one. They have a better reputation for discipline
and learning than the public schools. Why not help poor ghetto kids
get the kind of good education at private institutions that rich
kids get? Sob stories about poor minority children in Cleveland
denied a decent education have flooded the media.
</P>
<P>
   But private schools can refuse pupils they don't want and are
not required to educate every dummy on their doorstep, as public
schools are. Nor are they held up as rigorously to media scrutiny
as public schools, which are accountable to elected local school
boards. By their very nature private schools can hide their
decisions and need not obey public antidiscrimination or disability
regulations.
</P>
<P>
   This is not, however, really about which school best teaches
reading and writing and arithmetic. It is about the extent to which
public money should be used to expose children to a specific
religious doctrine.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans contend that religious schools do not impose their
beliefs on their pupils. This is disingenuous. Even if the message
is not expounded in a classroom textbook, a religious context is in
the atmosphere, the dialogue, the prayerful attitude, the
references, the social pressure. In a learning environment, it does
not take much to make it overwhelming. And we who may not share
those religious views are supposed to pay to spread the word!
</P>
<P>
   The federal judge in Ohio was the second to attack a voucher
plan on the grounds that it violated the constitutional separation
of church and state. The first was a federal court ruling in Maine
earlier this year that three families did not have the right to
spend public money for their children's tuition at a private
Catholic school.
</P>
<P>
   Florida has just begun a statewide school voucher program pushed
by Gov. Jeb Bush, brother of the would-be next president. This
program is also under a legal challenge. The issue is clearly on
its way to the Supreme Court, which is the final authority on
constitutional conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has never displayed much collective respect for the
Constitution, despite rhetorical flourishes about its importance.
Our legislators currently harbor a host of constitutional
amendments that range from the frivolous to the dangerous. So it is
not surprising that the GOP-controlled Congress would demand a
voucher system despite ample warning that it crosses the
traditional line protecting the country from the promotion of any
one specific religion.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have used their voucher vision as an alternative to
financially supporting sensible policies that promote national
testing standards, better salaries for teachers, security systems
to protect students, and anti-smoking and drug campaigns. The
voucher plan gives them an excuse to cut education spending.
</P>
<P>
   If successful, vouchers would reduce public school enrollment,
which affects how much state aid school systems get. Voucher-aided
private schools might also lure away the better pupils, leaving
public schools with the kids with educational and discipline
problems.
</P>
<P>
   But to understand what the voucher champions are really up to,
consider this: Many of them also crusaded for two decades to kill
the Department of Education, downgrading the importance of learning
by taking it out of the Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached by e-mail at
means(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
