<SLUG> BC-SPANISH-ONLY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS TOWN STICKS TO ITS GUNS ON SPANISH-ONLY LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DANE SCHILLER  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL CENIZO, Texas _ Mayor Rafael Rodriguez and other leaders of
this dusty community founded by immigrants say they never expected
they would ignite a national firestorm over an ordinance requiring
that official town business be conducted in Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   Despite reported death threats and violence, Rodriguez said
there were no plans to retreat from the ordinance, or another town
law that calls for firing city employees who help the U.S. Border
Patrol apprehend illegal immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say they will kill us and burn City Hall,'' the mayor
said Saturday. Alluding to divine powers, he said he was not
worried because ``our security is from above.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, who came to the United State illegally but is now an
American citizen, said conducting business in Spanish is necessary
to give more residents an opportunity to understand and participate
in their local government. The mayor himself speaks very little
English.
</P>
<P>
   With 1,500 residents, El Cenizo is home to poverty and unpaved
streets. It began as a housing development, hugging the banks of
the Rio Grande some 10 miles south of Laredo.
</P>
<P>
   The two ordinances, approved by Rodriguez and the city's two
commissioners earlier this month, have made international headlines
and provided talk show fodder across the country.
</P>
<P>
   The Baltimore-based syndicated show ``Geronimo and O'Meara''
featured El Cenizo on one of its programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If your people cannot understand my language, they should get
on their burros and go back to Mexico,'' said a caller to the show,
according to a transcript published by the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   The ordinances stipulate that city business, including council
meetings, will be conducted in Spanish and that English translation
will be provided with 48 hours' notice.
</P>
<P>
   In compliance with state and federal laws, written ordinances
will be adopted in English and translated into Spanish, according
to documents filed at City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the town has been declared a ``safe haven'' for
undocumented immigrants and employees face dismissal if they assist
Border Patrol agents.
</P>
<P>
   El Cenizo City Commissioner Flora Barton said there had been as
many as 100 calls about the ordinances, many have laced with hatred
and, sometimes, racism.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been happening every day,'' said Barton, who said she
received a call from a listener on the ``Geronimo and O'Meara''
program.
</P>
<P>
   In another call, a man threatened her life, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He kept saying ugly things,'' Barton said during an interview
at City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go back to Mexico; if you do not, you will not be here long,''
Barton recalled being told.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the barrage, a new phone has been installed to
identify the numbers of incoming calls and city officials have been
in touch with law enforcement agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Hispanic groups in New Mexico are demanding that an Albuquerque,
N.M., radio station ban the ``Geronimo and O'Meara'' radio program.
</P>
<P>
   The town leaders never thought they would generate such
attention with ordinances they say look out for the rights of its
residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did not do it for publicity or to have people against us,''
Barton said. ``We did it for the residents of El Cenizo; we need to
help each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many U.S.-Mexico border communities, most residents speak
Spanish and many are either immigrants, married to immigrants or
the children of immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people know English, but they prefer Spanish,'' said
Soledad Vasquez, 34, the owner of a convenience store. ``It does
not matter where you go (along the border), people speak Spanish.
Our parents are from Mexico.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Vasquez said the community is slowly evolving from its
immigrant roots. ``My nieces speak English. They do not even speak
Spanish.''
</P>
<P>
   Israel M. Reyna, the lead attorney for Texas Rural Legal Aid in
Laredo, has said city leaders are doing what they can in a place
where many people have limited English skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a developing democracy opening government's doors to the
people,'' Reyna said shortly after the ordinances were passed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
