<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, Aug. 31, 1999, sent to computer graphics clients of The
New York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane Dennis will continue to produce heavy rain showers and
gusty winds from southeastern Virginia to northeast North Carolina
on Tuesday. Dennis will slow its forward progress during the day,
becoming nearly stationary offshore of the Outer Banks. The storm
will most likely remain in this vicinity for several days, leading
to very high surf and the potential for large amounts of beach
erosion.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, a strong Canadian high-pressure system will push
eastward across New England. After an unseasonably cool morning,
interior sections of the Northeast will warm to near normal
afternoon readings, while gusty winds out of the northeast keep
shoreline locations slightly below normal. Farther south, a
disturbance at 18,000 feet over the western Gulf of Mexico will
trigger scattered showers and thunderstorms over parts of coastal
east Texas and southern Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   A potent low-pressure system pushing through the Canadian
Prairie will drag a strong cold front across the northern Rockies
and northern Plains. Ahead of this front, scattered showers and
thunderstorms will erupt from Kansas through the Dakotas. Some of
the storms in the Dakotas will be severe with large hail and
damaging winds possible.
</P>
<P>
   Farther west, moisture laden Pacific air behind the front will
ascend the mountains, leading to numerous showers on the western
slopes of the Cascades and the Bitterroots. Elsewhere, isolated
afternoon thunderstorms will develop from Arizona to Utah as a jet
stream disturbance passes overhead.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Inadvertent Heat
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane Dennis inadvertently brought a heat wave to eastern
Florida this past weekend. From Melbourne to Miami, highs on Sunday
rose into the middle and upper 90s. Miami Beach was the hottest
site with a reading of 98 degrees, within a degree or two of their
all-time record. The counter-clockwise wind circulation around the
offshore storm combined with subsiding air at the periphery of the
hurricane to produce a dry, hot, persistent wind from the west.
Ample sunshine assisted in raising temperatures to their highest
levels of the season. Onshore breezes will return Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
