<HEADER>
A4743 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-DENNIS-CHASER31-COX     08-30 0439
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DENNIS-CHASER31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Middle school teacher tracks Dennis
 &HT;    By David Blount
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCKY MOUNT, N.C. _ While nervous eyes watched weather forecasts
and hoped Hurricane Dennis would steer far away from North
Carolina, at least one area man welcomed the storm's appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Holdsworth, 53, has been a weather buff since sitting
through Hurricane Hazel in 1954. A teacher at Southern Nash Middle
School, Holdsworth in 1995 decided to pursue his life's dream and
graduated from Mississippi State University with a degree in
meteorology.
</P>
<P>
   Holdsworth operates his own by-contract weather forecasting
business in Rocky Mount named Down East Weather Associates and is
hoping to catch a glimpse of Dennis along the Outer Banks.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can find out where to go, we will definitely check it
out,'' Holdsworth said. ``It isn't moving very fast and everything
is still up in the air. From a human standpoint, you don't want to
see anything happen. From a scientific standpoint, you want to be
able to study the storm a little.''
</P>
<P>
   Holdsworth said he hoped to ride out the hurricane while
monitoring the storm's strength on his computer and weather
equipment. He also hopes to videotape the effects of the storm and
produce a hurricane feature.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went to Bertha (in 1996),'' he said. ``That was my first
hurricane since 1964 in Florida. I was bound and determined to
witness a hurricane so we went and rode it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Holdsworth said he was disappointed by the effects of Bertha.
Ideally, he said, every meteorologist wants to see a Category 5
storm with no damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's impossible, of course,'' he said. ``Bertha was pretty
weak and Fran was a little stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   After Dennis continued its slow track to the north Saturday,
Holdsworth began to wonder if he would be able to make the trip to
see the storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to sit tight for now,'' he said. ``I have a
meeting at school on Tuesday that I have to attend so I might not
make it down.''
</P>
<P>
   While some may wonder why Holdsworth would scramble toward the
coast to see a storm that thousands of others would flee, he claims
the data collected in a hurricane is valuable for future forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more information we can collect, the better,'' he said.
``We are interested in the measurements of air pressure, wind speed
and rainfall to help us to predict how these storms move and react
to other weather patterns. Right now we use computer generated
models, but they don't work very well with tropical systems.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
