<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Tuesday, Aug. 31, Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Henry Warnken (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Jerusalem) _ Israeli and Palestinian leaders
expressed guarded optimism Monday that they could cinch a deal to
revive the frozen Wye River peace agreement by the time Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright arrives in the Middle East on Thursday.
But as senior negotiators threw themselves into a final round of
meetings, the two sides apparently remained deadlocked on several
key issues. These included the terms for the release of Palestinian
prisoners by Israel and a target date for concluding the framework
of a permanent peace accord. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T-RATES (Undated) _ AT&AMP;T is cutting rates for long-distance
phone calls to 7 cents a minute in response to a price war begun by
MCI Worldcom and Sprint. By Saul Hansell.
</P>
<P>
   FAITH-POLITICS (Undated) _ Presidential candidates have always
made a point of having themselves photographed as they step out of
church on Sunday, carrying a Bible perhaps, and shaking the
minister's hand. But in the early campaign for the 2000 elections,
the rite of political piety has moved far beyond the sacramental
photo opportunity. This time around, the candidates are engaging in
``God talk'' that is more explicit, more intimate and more
pervasive than at any time in recent decades, historians and
political analysts say. By Laurie Goodstein.
</P>
<P>
   TEACHER-SHORTAGE (undated) _ As the nation's children swarm back
to school, principals from Baltimore to Palm Beach, Fla., and from
the Texas panhandle to inner-city Los Angeles, say they are
grappling with perhaps the most acute teacher shortage in recent
memory, with student enrollments continuing to swell and a rising
tide of educators flowing out of their classrooms to retirement.
The problem is not a depleted national supply of teachers, but
rather geography and qualification. By Jacques Steinberg.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-TIMOR (Dili, East Timor) _ Proud, optimistic,
determined to have the last word, almost all the registered voters
here in East Timor cast their ballots Monday in a referendum on the
territory's future that one U.N. official said approached a
best-case scenario. For the first time since the U.N.-sponsored
process began nearly four months ago, it was a day largely free of
violence and intimidation by military-backed militias determined to
block what seems to be a growing momentum for independence from
Indonesia. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   NY-CLUBS (New York) _ Long a mecca for anything-goes nightlife,
New York and its big-box dance clubs have become heavily regulated
places where drugs, underage drinking and unseemly behavior are
zealously discouraged. By Andrew Jacobs.
</P>
<P>
   NY-GIULIANI-JUROR (New York) _ Mayor Giuliani is picked as a
juror in a civil case in Manhattan. By Robert D. McFadden.
</P>
