<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4770 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-MULTICELL-NYT &LR;      08-30 1344
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-MULTICELL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW PERIL TURNS LONER AMOEBA INTO A SOCIAL CREATURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 By MALCOLM W. BROWNE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When times are good and there are plenty of bacteria to eat,
Dictyostelium discoideum _ a species of soil amoebas _ are loners.
These microscopic one-celled animals are content to crawl through
their environment, absorbing whatever food they come across.
</P>
<P>
   But when famine or other catastrophes strike, something
remarkable happens: exchanging chemical signals with their freely
moving neighbors and using their protruding pseudopoda (false legs)
for propulsion, the amoebas seek each other out and stick together
to create a multicelled creature that can sense both light and heat
and can travel faster and farther than any of its component cells
traveling alone.
</P>
<P>
   The aggregated cells within the animal then differentiate into
two distinct types _ stalks and armored spores _ and the starving
Dictyostelium is ready to sow its dormant spores into the winds,
seeking a more hospitable environment.
</P>
<P>
   All this has been known for many years. But a team of biologists
and physicists at the University of California at San Diego has
invented a revealing new technique for observing Dictyostelium and
has devised a mathematical model to account for its behavior.
</P>
<P>
   The ability of an organism to switch between unicellular and
multicellular forms is not unique to Dictyostelium; myxobacteria,
yeasts and sponges can do something similar. But to some biologists
and physicists, Dictyostelium has a special attraction. For one
thing, it is relatively easy to study. And, says Dr. William F.
Loomis of the University of California team, the multicellular mode
of Dictyostelium offers insights into the structures of all
multicelled animals, including people.
</P>
<P>
   Loomis, a professor of biology, worked with a team of physicists
headed by Dr. Herbert Levine, also of San Diego, to study
Dictyostelium's sophisticated strategies for dealing with stress
and hunger. Preliminary results of their experiments were published
recently in the journal Physical Review Letters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the organism,'' Loomis said in an interview. ``You get
familiar with it and end up with a burning curiosity to understand
it. It's simple enough that a person can understand all of its life
cycle, and in 1970 I thought we could achieve that understanding in
10 or 15 years. But by 1990 I knew better, and I still have much to
learn.''
</P>
<P>
   Many scientists have been intrigued by transitions in the same
species between one-celled and multicelled forms. How is it, for
example, that one-celled creatures living independently of one
another can join together to form a new, multicelled entity that
exhibits self-awareness, like that of the supposedly higher life
forms?
</P>
<P>
   Might the metamorphosis from the one-celled state of
Dictyostelium to its multicelled state have something in common
with the highly structured flocking of birds, schooling of fish,
the collective movement of ants and even the movements of human
pedestrian and vehicular traffic?
</P>
<P>
   To seek answers the San Diego team realized that studying the
life cycles of amoebas in their ordinary three-dimensional
environment involves many difficulties. To simplify observation,
Loomis and his colleagues devised a containment system that forced
amoebas into a flat two-dimensional environment. Their technique is
to smear a very thin layer of single-celled Dictyostelium amoebas
on a microscope slide and seal the organisms, bereft of nutrients,
away from the outer world under an impenetrable film of a substance
called agarose.
</P>
<P>
   The result, Loomis said, was the creation of a kind of window
into the life cycle of Dictyostelium, like the windows used to view
subterranean ant colonies.
</P>
<P>
   After a short time the Dictyostelium cells, deprived of food in
Dr. Loomis' experiment, began to assemble into their multicellular
incarnation, in preparation for differentiating into stalk cells
and spore cells, the latter engineered by nature to withstand an
indefinite famine.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stalk cells are little towers rising above the ground
providing perches for the spores up in the air, where they can be
dispersed,'' Loomis said. ``The differentiation of Dictyostelium
cells into two distinct types designed for different functions is
like turning part of some material into golf tees and another part
into golf balls. Having a tee to hold up the golf ball makes it
easier to hit the ball down the fairway.''
</P>
<P>
   But when Loomis replayed this scene in two dimensions instead of
the familiar three, there were some surprises. The independent
single cells soon aggregated into a thin, pancake-shaped
multicellular organism. Then, as the pancake formed, came another
surprise: it began rotating under its own power, and continued
turning for some 10 hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``The remarkable thing about this behavior is that these
organisms are not penned in by any kind of external fence like
horses running around in a coral, and yet they rotate,'' Loomis
said. Moreover, the multicellular pancakes often form doughnutlike
holes in their centers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The holes are of great interest because similar holes form in
turning flocks of birds and schools of fish that get themselves
into loops, and a common factor may be at work,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Simple rules can explain some of this behavior. When a fish is
approached too closely by another fish in the same school, Loomis
said, it moves slightly away, and this simple response by many fish
can trigger the onset of circular motion for the whole school. An
empty hole in the middle of the rotating school forms because the
amount of bending a fish backbone can undergo as it swims in a
circle is limited, preventing further tightening of the circle.
</P>
<P>
   Analogous mechanisms may explain a variety of collective
movements in different organisms, the scientists suggested, and
their paper proposed a mathematical model that could account for
such behavior.
</P>
<P>
   It is essentially this: All individual cells of Dictyostelium
(and analogous organisms) constantly change shape, using their
pseudopodal protuberances to propel and reorient themselves. In
their multicellular configuration, the organisms secrete adhesive
proteins that tend to draw them together.
</P>
<P>
   If one cell begins to move past another, the two cells will
reorient themselves and try to draw closer together, checking the
separation. This trend throughout the entire aggregate eventually
becomes coherent as cells line up with one another, and collective
rotation results. This behavior probably helps the organism sort
out its stalk and spore cells as they form and prepare for their
different roles, Loomis theorizes.
</P>
<P>
   But because single cells at the outer edge of a turning
Dictyostelium pancake cannot move fast enough to keep up with the
rotation of cells closer to the axis of the pancake, they lag
behind, and the result is a pancake whose shape under the
microscope looks remarkably like a spiral galaxy.
</P>
<P>
   The team tested their model with a computer simulation, in which
deformable cells were bunched together, each cell pressing against
its neighbors, changing shape in response to forces applied to it,
and moving randomly. After 100 to 1,000 computer equivalents of
flipping a coin the movements and orientations of the individual
cells became coherent and the simulated pancake began to rotate.
</P>
<P>
   Although it is tempting to suppose that a common factor
influences the formation of galaxies and amoebic conglomerates,
Loomis says that their size scales rule it out. ``You can't really
compare phenomena that happen on a scale of microns with those
unfolding over thousands of light years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Dictyostelium has established itself as a powerful tool for
biologists.
</P>
<P>
   ``It allows us to study the processes common to all multicelled
organisms,'' Loomis said. ``Dictyostelium offers understanding in
terms of highly disciplined physical analysis. It's kept me
interested for 30 years and still intrigues me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-99 1754EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990830.0289 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4772 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-DIXIECHICKS31-COX     08-30 1561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIXIECHICKS31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    High-flyin' chicks
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Dixie Chicks have plenty of reasons to cluck.
</P>
<P>
   As their highly anticipated new album, ``Fly,'' reaches stores
today, the perky country music trio is hotter than a sparkler _
media darlings du jour. They are everywhere, from the pages of
Seventeen magazine to giggling sound bites on ``Entertainment
Tonight.'' Designer Todd Oldham begs them to wear his clothes.
Julia Roberts romps through her latest movie to their music.
Dressed in ripped leather costumes, their blond hair streaked in
black, the group was this year's camera grabber at the Grammy
Awards, where they won for best country album and duo/group. The
women are nominated for four Country Music Association trophies,
which will be handed out Sept. 22, including the coveted
entertainer of the year, which they just might win. Move over,
Garth Brooks.
</P>
<P>
   Not since Dolly Parton's ascension in Hollywood in the early
1980s has a country music act created such a buzz outside Nashville
circles. But the Chicks haven't done it by catering to pop. Their
music is solidly country _ a breezy, fun style rooted in the
traditional bluegrass backgrounds of sisters Emily Robison (banjo,
dobro) and Martie Seidel (fiddle, mandolin) and the powerhouse
vocals of lead singer Natalie Maines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they are having a profound impact on country music,
and an important, positive impact,'' says country singer Dwight
Yoakam. ``They are continuing the illustration of the case in point
that females can and will continue to help shape country music into
the next decade.''
</P>
<P>
   A mere 19 months ago, few outside Texas had ever heard of the
group with the big smiles and cutesy name. They were a quirky
novelty act that dressed like Dale Evans and mostly played
conventions in and around Austin. After nearly a decade of
rejection, they were ``discovered'' by Monument Records' producer
Blake Chancey, who says he had to close his eyes when he listened
to them to get past their somewhat cartoonish looks. Even after a
major record deal, the trio was turned down for an appearance on an
Atlanta TV show in 1998 for having a name that was ``politically
incorrect'' (i.e., the word ``Dixie'').
</P>
<P>
   With the release of the album ``Wide Open Spaces'' in January
1998, however, fans of all ages responded to their music. It
spawned five hit singles, and went on to sell 7 million copies,
making the Dixie Chicks overnight superstars.
</P>
<P>
   The phenomenon was glaringly apparent at the group's July 25
show in Atlanta, where they opened for Tim McGraw, a date booked
long before anyone had gauged their mass appeal. At a backstage
party hosted by country radio stations Kicks 101.5 and Y-106.7, the
trio was smothered by the normally blase VIP crowd like a blond
float at a Mardi Gras parade. As cameras flashed and bodies pressed
against them, the Chicks wore dazed smiles and dutifully signed
autographs until handlers whisked them back to their lipstick red
bus.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting on the meet-and-greet, lead singer Natalie Maines
called the coach her ``safe haven.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I love meeting fans, but I started feeling very panicky. When
there are a lot of hands on me like that, I start freaking out
'cause I don't know these people. Everything has happened so fast.
One day you could walk through a mall, the next day you couldn't.
You have to know when you step outside, you're a Dixie Chick.''
</P>
<P>
   Producer Chancey says he had no clue just how popular the trio
was going to be until he celebrated his 4-year-old nieces' birthday
in Florida. ``It was a theme party, and everyone showed up dressed
as their favorite Dixie Chick,'' he says. ``The record hadn't been
out all that long. That's when I realized, `Omigod, this is going
to be huge.'''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the formula behind the Chicks' appeal is a combination
of solid musicianship and successful imaging.
</P>
<P>
   The acoustic instruments that make up most of the group's sound
are more than props. Robison and Seidel are superb pickers who have
a knack for knowing how to turn traditionalism into something fresh
and new. ``When is the last time you heard a banjo on a country
record?'' Chancey asks. On lead vocals, Maines has a set of pipes
like a whistle on a Mississippi steamboat, packed with twang and
sass.
</P>
<P>
   RCA recording artist Sara Evans says, ``I knew I really loved
them when I heard them sing `Stand By Your Man' at the Academy of
Country Music Awards last year. Natalie has a wonderful voice, and
she just hit that note right on. That's a hard song to sing, and
they sounded perfect. I looked at my husband and said, `These girls
are great!'''
</P>
<P>
   On top of the tight sound, the Chicks' exude an image of
countrified girl power _ best girlfriends who can be harmlessly fun
hell-raisers. They have tiny chicken tracks tattooed on their feet,
one for each No. 1 record. Onstage, they banter about Maines'
recent divorce, and are self-deprecating about their looks. Maines
quips, ``Emily's goal in life was to be on `Hee Haw,' but I told
her `Sorry. They don't take double A's on that show.''' The new CD
even comes with a tune called ``Sin Wagon,'' in which the Chicks'
say they want to ``do a little mattress dancin'.''
</P>
<P>
   Maines certainly exudes a devilishness straight out of ``Thelma
&AMP; Louise,'' as if she'd take a dare on a moment's notice. She says
what she thinks, quite often making her label executives grimace.
Onstage, she dances and sings with such energy you worry she's
going to pop out of her tiny body in a puff of spontaneous
combustion. Her style has apparently always been a bit of a
joyride.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since I was 3 I was like this. There was this time I was
sitting at a piano banging on it, and my dad came in and told me to
stop,'' Maines recalls. ``I wouldn't, so he said, `If you play one
more key, you are going to the bathroom and get spanked.' I looked
directly in his eye, lifted one finger and pressed one key. He
couldn't believe I had the nerve. He didn't spank me, and, in a
way, I think that's when he knew I could go out there in the world
and stand on my own.''
</P>
<P>
   Both the Chicks and their producer say they didn't feel under
the gun while recording ``Fly,'' or pressured to repeat the success
of their ``Wide Open Spaces.'' ``I think we felt more confident, if
anything,'' Maines says. ``Our voices blended better, our producers
were more comfortable. We didn't want to remake `Wide Open Spaces,'
but we didn't want to go pop. I think we took some risks
creatively.''
</P>
<P>
   And what if the Chicks lay an egg?
</P>
<P>
   ``If it bites me in the butt tomorrow, so what,'' Maines laughs.
``They can take my money, but they can't take my happiness.''
</P>
<P>
   CHICK IT OUT
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  History: The band was formed in Dallas in 1989 by sisters
Emily Robison, 27, and Martie Seidel, 29, along with two friends.
They played western swing, mostly on street corners, and wore campy
cowgirl outfits with fringe. In 1995 Nashville producer Blake
Chancey told them to ditch the costumes and signed them to a record
deal. Six months before going into the studio, Robison and Seidel
decided to change lead singers, and asked Maines, 24, to join the
group. The result was the album ``Wide Open Spaces,'' which sold 7
million copies.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The sound: Robison and Seidel's parents were private-school
teachers in Dallas who insisted their daughters take music lessons.
Robison became proficient on dobro and banjo, Seidel on fiddle.
Maines attended the Berklee School of Music in Boston, but was
heavily influenced by her father, Texas steel guitarist Lloyd
Maines.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The name: Dixie Chicks is derived from the tune ``Dixie
Chicken'' by Little Feat.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The hits: ``I Can Love You Better Than That,'' ``There's Your
Trouble,'' ``Wide Open Spaces,'' ``You Were Mine,'' ``Tonight the
Heartache's on Me,'' ``Ready to Run.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The new album: ``Fly,'' in stores today.
</P>
<P>
   TRES CHICK
</P>
<P>
   There's been nearly as much buzz about the Dixie Chicks' look in
the past year as their music, and Melanie Shelley intends to keep
it that way. She's the Nashville hairstylist who oversees the
band's image as part of a consulting team known as the Glam Squad.
</P>
<P>
   From her funky headquarters near downtown Nashville, a vintage
1950s' beauty parlor called Trim Classic Barber &AMP; Legendary Beauty,
she meets regularly with the Chicks to come up with the quirky
hairstyles and costumes that define their style.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would describe the look as 100 percent fun,'' she says.
``The Chicks aren't afraid of color, of pushing the boundaries of
what's tasteful and what's not. They can't stand not to change, and
that allows me to be super creative.''
</P>
<P>
   Shelley is the one who put those black streaks in the band's
hair for their splashy Grammy appearance. (``A lounge hostess
look,'' she calls it). Costume concepts, from hair barrettes to
platform shoes, are typically sketched out on a board, presented to
the band, then sent to designers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not everyone approves, but everyone notices,'' Shelley says.
``Nobody looks at TLC and says, `I think they are going too far or
changing too often.' They are a girl group who really loves their
bodies and fashion. To me, the Dixie Chicks are a country's TLC.''
</P>
<P>
   _Miriam Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
