<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSTAND31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A Catalyst for young entrepreneurs
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Catalyst ($4.50), the newest magazine in the Atlanta market,
debuts this week with slick graphics and short articles aimed at
entrepreneurs and high-tech professionals under 40.
</P>
<P>
   Catalyst is intended to be primarily a business publication with
complementary articles on food, fashion and recreation, says Laura
Nix of the Leader Publishing Group. ``It's all about how technology
and the Internet not only affect business, but how it affects our
lifestyle.''
</P>
<P>
   The cover story for the bimonthly magazine features thumbnail
sketches of entrepreneurs Andrea Arena, founder of 2 Places at 1
Time; Jeff Levy, co-founder of Relevant Knowledge; Alan Daniels,
chairman of Realestate.com; Alexis Abramson, founder of Mature
Mart; and Tom Noonan, president of Internet Security Systems.
</P>
<P>
   The most interesting article is Terri Thornton's look at the
battle between chain bookstores, independents and Amazon.com. The
secret to survival, says Outwrite Bookstore owner Phillip Rafshoon,
is finding a niche and offering better service. ``We give more than
a bookstore experience,'' he says. ``We offer passion for what we
do.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Home tour: To prove that the city is more than a hodgepodge of
subdivisions, Atlanta ($3.50) devotes 20 pages to 50 of the most
beautiful homes in the metro area. Writer Kevin Benefield visits
Tara-like mansions such as Roswell's Barrington Hall and Cobb
County's Tranquillas, Neel Reid and Philip Shutze creations in
Druid Hills, Ansley Park and Buckhead, and charming bungalows in
the Virginia-Highland neighborhood. Elsewhere in the magazine,
Rebecca Poynor Burns tells us eight things we must know about David
Hasselhoff of ``Baywatch.'' Why Hasselhoff? Editor Lee Walburn
explains that the actor grew up in Atlanta before discovering a TV
gold mine in a show where women wear skimpy red bathing suits and
run up and down the beach in slow motion.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Risky business: Time ($3.50) investigates why more Americans
than ever are taking chances with their lives and investments. Some
get their kicks parachuting off 650-foot concrete dams while others
resort to day trading. Experts say the dangerous trend is a result
of Americans seeking the widest range of human experiences. ``If
you don't assume a certain amount of risk,'' says paraglider pilot
Wade Ellet, 51, ``you're missing a certain amount of life.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Testing the tests: Nerve-wracking exams have become a normal
part of life for most students, as SAT scores determine who gets
into the best colleges and who gets left behind. Tests have been
around for decades, but Newsweek ($3.50) finds there is even more
emphasis today on high scores. Some students complain that real
learning is being neglected because teachers are more interested in
boosting test scores. And even some educators are questioning the
value of some standardized tests.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Lynch's return: It would seem that the man who gave us the
bizarre and fascinating TV series ``Twin Peaks'' would have free
rein with any of the networks. Not so, says Tad Friend in the Sept.
6 issue of The New Yorker ($3). When David Lynch proposed a series
called ``Mulholland Drive'' to ABC, the network eagerly invested $7
million in a two-hour plot. Now there are problems with content.
ABC, for instance, was concerned about the number of
cigarette-smoking characters in the show and decreed that
``characters who smoke should manifest a hacking cough.'' Says a
frustrated Lynch: ``I feel it's possibly true that there are aliens
on earth, and they work in television.''
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
