<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990830.0294 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4778 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-TV-GOODYKOONTZ_AZR &LR;      08-30 1819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-GOODYKOONTZ_AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETWORKS SKIRT MINORITY STARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) - The irony was overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   After listening to television bigwig after television bigwig try
to explain how the Big Four networks managed to produce a slate of
26 new fall shows without a single minority character in a lead
role, I went back to my hotel room and clicked on the TV.
</P>
<P>
   On came an old favorite: ``The Jeffersons.'' Everyone on the
screen was Black (neighbors Tom Willis and Harry Bentley weren't in
the scene). And seemingly everyone loved the show.
</P>
<P>
   What happened?
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of threats of lawsuits and boycotts by the NAACP and
Latino groups upset at the lack of racial diversity on network TV,
that question consumed everyone at a gathering of television
critics in California earlier this summer _ critics, network
executives and actors and writers alike.
</P>
<P>
   Asking network executives a controversial question is often like
asking a 5-year-old how the cookie jar got broken _ the answers are
creative, the excuses more so. Thus, the responses ranged from
lukewarm justifications (we went with actors we knew, so we didn't
have time to cast minorities in the pilots) to back-pedaling
promises (we've added three new minority characters) to out-and-out
apologies (we'll try to do better).
</P>
<P>
   This being television, money also played a big role. Many shows
added minority characters after pilots were shot and then screened
for advertisers, when advertising rates were set _ and after the
complaints.
</P>
<P>
   But the questions and answers were really just academic
exercises. The truth of the matter remains that if you're looking
for a Black, Latino, Asian or Native American lead character on a
new NBC, CBS, ABC or Fox show this fall, you can keep on looking.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller networks, such as Black Entertainment Television and
Telemundo, pick up the slack to some degree. But NAACP President
Kweisi Mfume dropped a bombshell this summer that made it clear
that, to paraphrase the great movie ``Network,'' minorities were
mad as hell and they weren't going to take it anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Whether a boycott happens remains to be seen. But the threat
hung heavy in the California air. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Casting unintentional
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
``I don't believe they're intentionally doing this (excluding
minority talent),'' said Ralph Farquhar, creator and executive
producer of ``The Parkers,'' a new show on UPN that features a
mostly Black cast (Farquhar is Black). ``But people have to pay
attention, you know? The makeup of America . . . has changed
radically over the past 20 or 30 years, and yet TV doesn't
necessarily reflect the diversity and the composition of the
American population.''
</P>
<P>
   To Steven Bochco, the color really at issue is green.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a network point of view, I don't think racism is an
issue,'' said Bochco, who created ``L.A. Law'' and ``NYPD Blue,''
and co-created ``City of Angels,'' a CBS midseason drama set in an
urban hospital with a largely Black cast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think economics is an issue. When things that you try don't
succeed, there's a reluctance to try them again. When they do
succeed, you try them over and over again.
</P>
<P>
   ``That said, if I'm a Black artist in this community, I don't
give a (expletive) what the reason is. The reality is, I don't have
a job.''
</P>
<P>
   Les Moonves, president of CBS Television, disagreed with the
money theory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think any network executive _ I know we certainly
don't _ sits there and says, `Gee, if we make this show all White,
we're going to get more (advertising) dollars from Madison Avenue,'
'' he said. ``I don't think anybody thinks that way, and if they
do, they shouldn't be in these jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   But someone's thinking something, and it resulted in a
lily-White new fall schedule. Robert Johnson, chairman of Black
Entertainment Television, thinks he knows how it happened. &QL; 
 &QL; 
The risk factor
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
``I think the problem is the networks don't like to take risks,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an economic environment where the networks face a
multichannel environment. . . . You're, you know, one click away
from 60, 70, pretty soon 100 channels. So, if I'm a network
executive _ who's probably White _ I'm sitting back saying, `My job
depends on delivering that half-hour show that's going to get the
ratings for that slot. . . . So, what am I going to do?
</P>
<P>
   `` `I'm going to launch a show that I think, one, advertisers
will like . . . because it will deliver a White audience that the
advertisers value more. I'm not going to go and try to do something
risky and creative with Black people and White people. I'm
certainly going to stay away from Black-and-White sex, so that
takes out any romance stories involved with Black men and White
women.
</P>
<P>
   `` `I'll probably take out any show that shows a Black man as a
dynamic businessman sort of lording over White people, because
that's going to offend the angry White male.'
</P>
<P>
   ``And you go on and on down the line, and pretty soon the guy
says, `OK, let's do ``Seinfeld.'' New York. No Black people.' And
it turns out to be a great hit, and there ain't no Black people.''
</P>
<P>
   Diversity on television has long been a roller-coaster ride,
with minority characters sometimes played by Anglo actors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to tell you, growing up, seeing David Carradine as a
Chinese guy (ticked) you off,'' said Scott Sassa, president of NBC
West Coast, referring to ``Kung Fu.'' (Sassa is Asian.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Minority successes
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Yet shows with true minority leads have succeeded: ``Good Times,''
``The Jeffersons'' and all of Bill Cosby's shows had Black leads.
You can go back as far as ``I Love Lucy'' and find not only Ricky
Ricardo but an inter-ethnic marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know all of a sudden why that memory lapse is there,''
said Diane Houston, executive story editor for ``City of Angels''
and an Oscar-nominated director. ``They were either good shows or
they weren't good shows. (Those shows) happened to be very good, or
they wouldn't have lasted, and we wouldn't be remembering them. . .
.
</P>
<P>
   ``The same cannot be said for the hastily put together Black
sitcoms that are on now. You don't have classic characters. The
thing that made ``The Jeffersons'' and ``Good Times'' and ``Cosby''
stand out is that the shows are centered around classic, universal
characters who happen to be Black, and bring with them that aspect
of culture.''
</P>
<P>
   She's right, of course. No one _ especially not minority actors
_ wants to see token minority characters added just to satisfy a
numbers game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The minute that you start denying someone a role because of
their color _ or giving them one _ you're playing into the entire
controversy,'' said Jonathan Prince, executive producer of ``Grown
Ups,'' another new show on UPN with a Black lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the wrong way to deal with it. Don't cast affirmative
action and don't cast non-affirmative action. Cast for merit.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if you're a minority actor, those words may ring
hollow. Sure, you may get a role. But what kind?
</P>
<P>
   Khalil Kain, a Black actor, landed a role as the owner of a
software company in a Black Entertainment Network movie scheduled
for this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the type of role that's offered to me regularly,
or ever offered to me before in my career,'' Kain said.
</P>
<P>
   So, what kind of role is he usually offered?
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say half of my body of work is thugs, hoodlums,
criminals,'' Kain said. ``I've played them well, but that's what I
played.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Frivolous threat
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Not every minority in the business agrees with the threat of
boycotts and the like.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think the NAACP, when it comes to priorities, has other
things they need to do,'' said Arsenio Hall, an actor and former
late-night talk-show host. ``There's a guy right now who's
unemployed in Michigan. I bet he can't understand why the NAACP is
dealing with entertainment first.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gang violence, Black-on-Black crime is ridiculous. . . . There
are so many things going on that I think are at the top of the
list. After you deal with that stuff, let's get Urkel the right
time slot. Entertainers will battle this out here, but there's a
bigger picture of Black people who need the help of the NAACP.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps. One could also argue that television is merely
entertainment. Yet meaningful entertainment reflects the people who
enjoy it. This fall's schedule doesn't come close to doing that.
And a knee-jerk quick fix _ poorly done shows that simply fill
quotas _ would do as much harm as good.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is diversity and there is meaningful diversity,'' NBC's
Sassa said. ``You not only want to see someone that looks like you
on TV, you want to see someone that is a role model, someone that
you want to be with, someone that you want to be like, someone that
you want to aspire to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, those kinds of characters do exist on network
television this fall _ just not in lead roles. Some of the most
interesting supporting characters in new series are played by
minority actors.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Haysbert, who is Black, landed the plum role of a
government doctor in ``Now and Again,'' a promising new drama on
CBS created by Glenn Gordon Caron, who also created
``Moonlighting.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been dreaming about playing a role like this my entire
career,'' Haysbert said. ``And . . . hopefully, this will open some
doors for other actors . . . that don't walk around with their
pants halfway down their butts . . . swearing and using the ``N''
word every time they have a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   The supporting role of a rookie cop in ``The Badland,'' a Fox
police drama, was written for a Hispanic woman, said Roselyn
Sanchez, so it excited her. But she worried that her Hispanic
accent might cost her the role.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I just went there and I said, `I'm going to be ``very''
Latina, and I'm going to try to do my best,' '' she said. ``And
they went for me. And I'm very grateful, you know. . . . I'm just
proud that they took the chance and went with a Puerto Rican accent
for real.''
</P>
<P>
   With luck _ actually, with a concerted effort _ maybe those
kinds of characters will be featured as leads in series next fall,
not just as supporting parts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to tell you, I'm enlightened by what is going on,''
said Kevin Williamson, creator of ABC's ``Wasteland'' (and writer
of ``Scream''). ``I think we should do more. It certainly raised my
awareness and I would love to see pilots . . . as diverse as they
come.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, I'm one diverse person myself, you know (Williamson is
gay), and I'd love to see it happen across the board. And I've
certainly been made aware of it and I'm certainly going to do my
best to do my part.''
</P>
<P>
   Strong words. We'll find out next fall whether he _ and the rest
of network television _ can back them up. &QL; 
Reach Bill Goodykoontz at (602) 444-8974, or at
bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
