<HEADER>
A4779 &Cx1f; tad-z
u t BC-CAYMAN-BOX-$ADV04-COX     08-30 0655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAYMAN-BOX-$ADV04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CAYMAN ISLANDS: IF YOU GO . . . WITH KIDS
 &HT;    With CAYMAN-TRAVEL-$ADV04; CAYMAN-SUMMER-$ADV04;
CAYMAN-FALL-$ADV04.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (t) Travel categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sat., Sept. 4 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By RICK CHRISTIE 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VITAL STATISTICS
</P>
<P>
   Capital: George Town (Grand Cayman)
</P>
<P>
   Geography: Grand Cayman is the largest island, at 76 square
miles. The other islands are Little Cayman and Cayman Brac.
</P>
<P>
   Population: 37,000, mainly of mixed European and African
descent.
</P>
<P>
   Currency: Cayman Island dollar (Exchange rate: US$1  &QC;  CI$.80).
</P>
<P>
   Official language: English
</P>
<P>
   Political status: British Dependent Territory
</P>
<P>
   Religion: Christianity
</P>
<P>
   GETTING THERE
</P>
<P>
   The first place to go for information should be the Internet:
www.caymanislands.ky or www.caymans.com. The Cayman Islands
Department of Tourism also has offices in Miami, Houston, New York,
Chicago, Los Angeles and Toronto, Canada.
</P>
<P>
   As for guidebooks, Fodor's or Frommer's provide pretty good
overall information. Another guide, ``Caribbean With Kids'' (Open
Road Publishing) is also good. But beware: It puts the Cayman
dollar exchange rate at ``US$1 equals CI$1.20.'' (According to
banking officials, the rate remains fairly constant at US$1  &QC; 
CI$.80.)
</P>
<P>
   Once you're in the Caymans, be sure to pick up both ``Horizons''
and ``Key to Cayman'' magazines. Both are complimentary
publications that contain information on just about everything
there is to do there.
</P>
<P>
   The Caymans, south of Cuba in the Caribbean Sea, are less than
two hours flight time from Houston and just over an hour from
Miami.
</P>
<P>
   GETTING AROUND
</P>
<P>
   The best way to get around and see most of Grand Cayman is to
rent a car. The cheapest rates are offered by the locally owned car
rental companies.
</P>
<P>
   For smaller families and those with older kids, you can also
rent 4x4 Jeeps, and motorized and non-motorized bikes.
</P>
<P>
   GETTING GOING
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the place that the kids will want to spend most of
their time is the beach. It's a good thing too, since it's free.
The other water activities are basically snorkeling or diving, and
they can cost. There are plenty of people offering rental equipment
for both services.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some other spots and activities on Grand Cayman:
</P>
<P>
   --Submarine rides (Atlantis Submarines; Nautilus, The Undersea
Tour)
</P>
<P>
   --Stingray City (Take a ferry boat over to one of the best-known
dive sites in the world and swim with the stingrays. There are
actually two: a deeper one for divers; a sandbar for waders and
snorkelers.)
</P>
<P>
   --Queen Elizabeth II Botanic Park (A 65-acre showcase of
Cayman's flora and fauna in living color.)
</P>
<P>
   --Mastic Trail (A restored 200-year-old footpath that great for
hiking.)
</P>
<P>
   --Cayman Turtle Farm (A chance to get up close and personal with
green sea turtles.)
</P>
<P>
   --Pedro St. James Castle (Known as the ``birthplace of democracy
in the Cayman Islands,'' it is the oldest structure in the
islands.)
</P>
<P>
   --Cayman Islands National Museum (A great cultural arts stop for
kids who love this sort of thing.)
</P>
<P>
   --Hell (A tiny community so-named for its rugged surreal pointed
rock formation near town. It's kitschy. It's kooky. It's catchy.)
</P>
<P>
   --Shipwrecks (There are numerous spectacular wrecks lying off
the coast on every side of Grand Cayman.)
</P>
<P>
   GETTING GRUB
</P>
<P>
   Not a problem. For kids, the more than 120 restaurants run the
gamut: from expensive to affordable, from authentic island cuisine
to fast food. Don't worry if you're having trouble getting the kids
to eat that turtle steak or conch stew. There's no McDonald's, but
other old reliables like Burger King, Wendy's and Pizza Hut are
just around the corner. There are even coffee shops for when you
need that extra shot of caffeine.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
