<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4806 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-TV-FORD-BOS &LR;      08-30 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FORD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORD HEADS TO ABC, WITH AN EYE ON `GMA' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In an era when many big news stories are interwoven with legal
issues, attorney-turned-TV-journalist Jack Ford has managed to be
in the right place at the right time with the right expertise.
</P>
<P>
   It paid off big-time Monday as Ford was named a coanchor on
ABC's prime-time newsmagazine, ``20/20.'' To take that post, Ford
will give up his job as NBC's chief legal correspondent, and will
also bid farewell to the anchor desk on the weekend ``Today'' show.
</P>
<P>
   But Ford's early-to-rise days are not behind him: He has also
been named a regular substitute on ``Good Morning America,''
meaning that he is a strong candidate to succeed Charles Gibson if,
as expected, Gibson steps down next year from ``GMA.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Monday, the 49-year-old Ford confessed he finds
it ``astonishing'' to have landed the ``20/20'' post. ``All of a
sudden, ABC comes over and says `We've got this job for you,''' he
said. ``And you realize this is one of the handful of the best jobs
in journalism.''
</P>
<P>
   By now, he should be used to the sound of opportunity knocking.
In September 1994, after a three-year stint as an anchor at Court
TV, Ford was named legal correspondent for NBC. Here's what
happened next, in his own words: ``You walk in the door and the
first thing you have is the O.J. Simpson trial. Then there's the
second Simpson trial, the Oklahoma City bombing trial, and the
presidential impeachment trial for only the second time in our
constitutional history.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford, a onetime prosecutor and trial attorney, is perhaps the
most prominent of a group of lawyers _ others include Rikki Klieman
of Court TV and Greta van Sustern of CNN _ who have parlayed their
legal expertise into a TV career. From the Simpson trial to the
Louise Woodward case to President Clinton's impeachment, the
networks have increasingly placed a premium on reporters and
commentators who understand the intricacies of the law.
</P>
<P>
   That was reflected in the demands placed on Ford at NBC. In
addition to his weekend ``Today'' duties, he cropped up all over
the weekday NBC schedule, offering legal analysis on the ``Today''
show, on ``Dateline,'' on ``NBC Nightly News.'' He also was a
substitute anchor for Tom Brokaw on the ``Nightly News'' and for
Tim Russert on ``Meet the Press,'' but he acknowledged Monday that
he knew it was crowded at the top.
</P>
<P>
   Alluding to the starry news lineup assembled by NBC News
president Andrew Lack, Ford said: ``I had become something of a
victim of his success. He's got great, talented people in all the
positions there.'' A former football player at Yale, Ford resorted
to a sports analogy to explain the attraction of the ABC job:
``It's nice being the backup on somebody else's team, but this is a
chance to start.''
</P>
<P>
   Regarding the ``Good Morning America'' job, Ford stressed that
he has been offered no guarantees. ``Would I be flattered if
someone considers me the heir apparent? Of course I would,'' he
said. ``But I'm not coming over here with any promises made. We'll
just see how it evolves.''
</P>
<P>
   Though it has not been finalized, Ford is likely to coanchor the
Monday edition of ``20/20'' with Connie Chung. Gibson is currently
the coanchor on Monday nights, but he has reportedly expressed a
desire to lessen his workload after recently undergoing an
angioplasty.
</P>
<P>
   In other ABC news, foghorn-voiced reporter Sam Donaldson has
decided to relinquish the White House beat with which he has become
so vividly identified. Donaldson is expected to leave the beat,
which he returned to in a blaze of publicity in 1998, in the next
couple of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The 65-year-old Donaldson, who recently underwent vocal cord
surgery, is still deliberating whether he will leave his coanchor
slot on Wednesday night's ``20/20,'' according to ABC News
spokeswoman Eileen Murphy. ``That decision is Sam's, and he has not
come to that decision yet,'' she said. Donaldson will remain as
coanchor of ``This Week,'' the Sunday interview show.
</P>
<P>
   As for Ford, his last appearance on weekend ``Today,'' which he
has coanchored since May 1995, will be Saturday. Sarah James and
John Seigenthaler will fill his slot for the immediate future, but
no permanent coanchor has been named yet to sit opposite Soledad
O'Brien, according to NBC spokeswoman Allison Gollust.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
