<SLUG> BC-BABUSHKA-TV-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BYE-BYE BABUSHKA': RUSSIA'S BURDENSOME HISTORY, ETCHED INTO FACES
AND SOULS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since the collapse of communism and the breakup of the Soviet
Union, journalists have been producing reports on the new face of
Russia. Rebecca Feig, the American director of the affecting
documentary ``Bye-Bye Babushka,'' provides instead a few old faces,
grandmothers who lived for decades under the Communist system and
now are left to their memories.
</P>
<P>
   Marina Igorevna, 91, was a peasant on a communal farm in a
village near Siberia for her entire life. Larisa Josefovna and
Tamara Vassiyelevna are professors who dissented from Soviet
policies. Tonya Gregoriyevna joined the Communist Party in 1940 and
remains a dedicated Leninist.
</P>
<P>
   In a comment on what she found, Ms. Feig waxes rhapsodic about
the babushkas, or grandmothers, who ``gave off a life force that
was elusive to me.'' She discerned in their weathered faces ``a
lifetime of strength, struggle and survival. They seemed to have so
little and yet so much.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for her documentary, the portraits go deeper than
such damp reactions. Viewers may wonder how much these women ever
had, as they hear of Baba Marina's endless labors, binding grain
sheaves and cooking kasha; encounter Baba Tonya's rote faith in a
bankrupt ideology; and learn of the government's suppression of
people like Larisa and Tamara.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why wouldn't I be a Communist?'' asks the still-sturdy and
plain-talking Baba Marina, as she goes about making bread the
old-fashioned way and displays her ``warm and good'' little bedroom
to her visitor. It's hard to know whether to be touched or saddened
by her gratitude for a warm room after laboring for so long in the
Russian frost and by her lack of apparent anger at the forces that
ruled her life. Party members had books, she reports; ``I had
nothing.'' She identifies herself, without apparent irony, as
``just an honored collective worker.''
</P>
<P>
   Baba Tonya, the loyal party member, now 78, tells proudly of her
labors on behalf of the Motherland. She once headed collectives,
and now sells Communist newspapers on the street. Here, to clips
from Sergei Eisenstein's ``Revolution,'' she recites a long quote
from Lenin on the October Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Baba Larisa and Baba Tamara tell of their protests and
punishments. ``There was no socialism in our country,'' says
Tamara, the professor of Marxism. Larisa's husband died in prison,
where he was sent for protesting the 1968 invasion of
Czechoslovakia. She is unsparing about the past: ``Well, that about
sums up my life.'' Along with such testimony, we see propaganda
movies featuring bright Young Communists swearing allegiance to the
state.
</P>
<P>
   At Baba Marina's birthday party, in one of the happier moments
of this not very happy work, comrades from her collective join in
comic songs for her: ``Oh, mama don't marry me to him.'' Like her
friends, she recalls the deaths of husbands and children.
</P>
<P>
   ``So it turns out,'' she says, with what may be resignation or a
dry bitterness not long before her death, ``I have had a good life.
That's it.''
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `BYE-BYE BABUSHKA'
</P>
<P>
   PBS (Channel 13 in New York), Tuesday at 10 p.m. ET
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca Feig, director; Mitchell Rosenbaum, cinematographer;
Ekaterina Skorik, co-producer; Daisy Wright, editor. A Persistence
of Vision Films presentation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
