<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-VIOLENCE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUP CALLS SCHOOL ANTI-VIOLENCE MEASURES INEFFECTIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Metal detectors and other popular anti-violence
measures alone won't protect school children from harm, a leading
juvenile-crime-fighting organization said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   What will work _ according to the group, Fight Crime: Invest in
Kids _ are programs for mentoring and for expanding after-school
activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are looking for the `quick fix' to school violence, and
it just doesn't exist,'' said James Alan Fox, an expert on crime at
Northeastern University in Boston and a member of Fight Crime, a
national advocacy organization of more than 500 police chiefs,
academics and victims of crime.
</P>
<P>
   Fox said some anti-violence measures instituted around the
country in the wake of the Columbine High School shootings in
Littleton, Colo., simply won't work by themselves and, in some
cases, may cause more problems than they solve. In the April
Columbine massacre, two students killed a dozen classmates, a
teacher and themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Fox said metal detectors, while stopping youngsters from
bringing large guns into a school, can't prevent a student from
killing his victims in the schoolyard, as in the Jonesboro, Ark.,
shooting in March 1998, in which four children and a teacher were
killed.
</P>
<P>
   He also warned against banning certain articles of clothing,
such as the long, black trench coats worn by the Columbine killers,
saying this strategy could make alienated students feel persecuted.
He added that requiring students to wear school uniforms has not
stopped teen-agers from finding ways to stand out through such
things as hair styles and tattoos.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids can always find ways to get around rules, and,
unfortunately, they can always find ways to kill each other,'' Fox
said. ``What we need to do is stop them from wanting to hurt each
other.''
</P>
<P>
   He said one of the most effective antidotes to teen violence is
the mentoring approach, where an adult becomes a role model for a
child or children, teaching them _ before they might turn hostile _
how to deal effectively with other youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   Fox said that children who have gone through early development
programs like Head Start are five times less likely to become
chronic lawbreakers when they become teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt that the sooner you reach a potentially
violent child, the better your chances are of helping him or her
choose another path,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For older children, Fox said, the best way to stop violence is
to expand after-school activities that keep students off the
streets between 2 p.m. and 7 p.m., when teen-agers commit most
their crimes. He suggested that schools bring back extra-curricular
activities, such as intramural sports, chorus and drama club, that
have been cut in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Fox also said that communities should consider building smaller
high schools, limiting them to around 500 students. He said
youngsters in smaller schools tend to participate in more
activities and to feel a stronger bond to their school than
children in larger schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Students in these huge institutions no longer feel connected
to their schools, their communities and their fellow students, and
this disconnection can be potentially dangerous,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sanford Newman, president of the three-year-old Fight Crime:
Invest in Kids group, released a survey Monday showing that three
fourths of parents were willing either to pay more in taxes or pass
up tax cuts to provide more after-school activities and early
child-development programs like Head Start.
</P>
<P>
   He said the survey, conducted by Opinion Research Corporation
International, a polling firm based in Washington, D.C., of 1016
randomly selected parents found that two thirds of them ranked
these programs, along with Social Security and Medicare, as
priorities that they considered more important than tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   In the poll, conducted from Aug. 12-15, those surveyed said they
were more concerned about violence in the classroom than the
quality of the nation's schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``People figure that it doesn't matter how good or bad your
school is if the students are afraid getting shot,'' Newman said.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-99 1816EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
