<DOCNO> NYT19990830.0310 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4829 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-BROADBAND-0901-COX     08-30 1694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROADBAND-0901-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    THE EMERGING BATTLE OVER FAT PIPES TO CYBERSPACE
 &HT;    With BROADBAND-DATA and BROADBAND-PLAYERS
 &HT;    For release Wednesday, Sept. 1
 &HT;    Moving in (f) financial and (w) Washington categories
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON As the new millennium approaches, the long-awaited
advent of high-speed access to the Internet promises to change the
way millions of Americans go online. As early users know, these
fast broadband services already allow data, music and video images
to zip over either cable systems or juiced-up phone lines, doing
away with the finger-tapping tedium of the World Wide Wait.
</P>
<P>
   In the next few years, nearly every U.S. telecommunications
company and Internet service provider intends to support such ``fat
pipe'' traffic, which previously has been available mainly to large
enterprises. In the not-so-distant future, a slew of
``last-mile-to-the-home'' network operators plan to offer direct
access to consumers via their local telephone, cable-TV, satellite
and wireless cellular networks.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, several firms are also at work on power line
technology that they claim would allow the existing electrical grid
to be used to send data, voice or video signals at speeds that
would leave the current cable modem or telephone-based systems back
in the dust. If those plans succeed, users could gain blazing
access to the Internet at any electrical socket.
</P>
<P>
   William Kennard, chairman of the Federal Communications
Commission, estimates that about 40 percent of U.S. households have
home computers and about half of them are hooked up to the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Says Kennard: ``Almost every one of those computers has more
computing power than can be accommodated over narrowband pipes. So
we have to have a real sense of urgency about this because if we
can get broadband deployed more quickly and more ubiquitously, it's
going to open up a whole new horizon for Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   Forrester Research Inc., which analyzes high-tech trends for
Wall Street clients, estimates that by year's end 1.25 million U.S.
households will have an express connection to cyberspace. Within
four years, Forrester predicts that one in four online homes will
employ broadband access, providing an always-on capability at
speeds at least 100 times faster than today's dial-up modems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Broadband will generate addictive content, combining the
interactivity of the Web with the immersiveness of television,''
says Forrester's Mark Hardie.
</P>
<P>
   Another private consulting unit, Washington-based Strategis
Group, predicts that total broadband-services revenues will grow
globally from $67 billion in 1998 to $161 billion by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   As broadband technology spreads, Congress, the courts and
government regulatory bodies will weigh whether Internet service
providers such as America Online Inc. should be allowed to use the
cable companies' proprietary lines to offer their own high-speed
services.
</P>
<P>
   The prime focus: AT&AMP;T Corp., the long-distance telephone
Goliath, which has put some $120 billion on the table to buy two of
the nation's largest cable systems, Tele-Communications Inc. (TCI)
and MediaOne Group.(cq) AOL and its allies are pressing regulators
to force AT&AMP;T to give its rivals access to its high-speed cable
pipes as a condition for approving its planned purchase of
MediaOne.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the FCC has spurned their pleas, although some local
governments have voted to impose ``open access'' requirements.
</P>
<P>
   The traditional access providers say AT&AMP;T is creating a
broadband monopoly by refusing to share access to its cable
networks. But AT&AMP;T supporters contend the company's proprietary
strategy holds the only realistic hope of creating genuine
competition to the powerful Bells, in both the high-speed Internet
and telephone markets.
</P>
<P>
   In mid-August, AT&AMP;T began removing TCI signs throughout the
country and replacing them with its own logo. If the FCC similarly
approves the MediaOne deal _ it is expected to act early next year
_ the combined colossus will have access to nearly two-thirds of
U.S. cable-TV households.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T spokesman James McGann said the prime purpose behind the
mergers is to enable the company to compete with the regional phone
companies on local telephone and Internet service. ``If AOL wanted
to build a broadband network, with its huge (stock) market value,
they could easily do it,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the regional Bells have geared up to market their own
consumer broadband services via high-tech telephone lines. Their
online speeds are competitive. Their approach also does away with
the need for an extra modem line. But the Bells' digital subscriber
line, or DSL, technology still requires a separate cable hookup.
</P>
<P>
   Technical experts note that the cable companies have designed
their broadband services in such a way as to make direct links with
AOL or other service providers virtually impossible. While new
equipment could solve this problem, it would also make the
million-plus cable modems already leased or sold to customers
useless.
</P>
<P>
   A new report by the Yankee Group, a consulting firm, concludes
that ``the delivery of high-speed Internet access falls into a
legal and regulatory vacuum.''
</P>
<P>
   In a recent private study for its clients, the firm said the
issue boils down to whether high-speed data over a cable system is
a ``cable service'' or whether it is a ``telecommunications
service'' that is being offered via cable. (Perhaps, the study
allowed, it is ``a third, as yet undefined, service for which new
rules and regulations will have to be developed.'')
</P>
<P>
   Based upon current law, if it is a cable service, then local
municipalities do not have the right to regulate it. This is
generally the view of the cable industry. But if it is a
telecommunications service, then local municipalities do have the
right to regulate it. This is generally the view of AOL and some
local municipalities.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking the high ground in the emerging broadband battle, both
sides have enlisted batteries of high-priced lawyers and lobbyists.
Among those engaged in the fight are at least two former U.S.
senators, three former members of the House, and Michael McCurry,
the former White House spokesman. On Capitol Hill their efforts
have so far tended to cancel each other out, dimming prospects for
any major action soon on the legislative front.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no consensus on how best to move ahead,'' says Sen.
John McCain, R-Ariz. McCain, chairman of the Senate Commerce
Committee, who favors a drastic overhaul of the FCC's role _ one
that would no longer require the Bell regional phone companies,
such as BellSouth, to share their upgraded networks with their
competitors for dial-tone service.
</P>
<P>
   ``If ever you wanted to see a battle to the death in which there
is almost no prospect of a winner emerging unscathed, take a good
look at the fight over cable 'open access,''' says Bill Frezza,
general partner at Adams Capital Management, a high-tech investment
firm.
</P>
<P>
   Frezza adds: ``The stakes are huge. AT&AMP;T's multibillion-dollar
cable strategy is predicated on its ability to bundle access and
services in order to earn the return on investment required to
upgrade the nation's cable TV systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``AOL's future hinges on its ability to maintain its dominance
as broadband services go mainstream. Federal regulators loathe
losing control to local authorities, who are happy to balkanize the
Internet. And consumers crave choice as they patiently wait for
cable modem service to reach their communities.''
</P>
<P>
   (According to AOL president Bob Pittman, the company plans to
add broadband content through a separate tier to be called ``AOL
Plus.'' In addition, AOL is testing a ``bandwidth sniffer'' that
automatically determines what bandwidth the customer has and
delivers the appropriate content.)
</P>
<P>
   Frezza notes that the Bells' local copper telephone line
infrastructure requires little capital improvement to make it
usable by third parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not so with cable,'' he says. ``Countless billions in upgrades
are required to bring most cable systems up to the level where
broadband two-way traffic can be supported. The business case for
making these upgrades is remarkably flimsy. Much of the hoped-for
return hinges on capturing not just the access portion of the
business but content services as well. Take away this upside and
any pretense of a business case collapses.''
</P>
<P>
   But AT&AMP;T critics say regulators must insure that the company's
immense power in the communications marketplace cannot be used to
shape how independent rivals challenge its cable arm or to suppress
competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regulators and consumers are at a crossroads,'' says Vinton
Cerf, a senior vice president at MCI WorldCom and pioneer developer
of the Internet. ``One path,'' Cerf maintains, ``leads to an open,
competitive Internet. The other leads to an Internet whose users
are locked in to closed, proprietary networks by a handful of
operators.''
</P>
<P>
   He concludes: ``Only by ensuring that all players have equal
access to the 'last mile' connecting users to the network will
regulators be able to guarantee that the Internet continues to
benefit from explosive investment, innovation and price
competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Writing recently in the Wall Street Journal, FCC chairman
Kennard observed: ``We cannot regulate against problems that have
yet to materialize in a market that has yet to develop. Moreover,
we cannot have 30,000 local cable communities trying to make their
own predictions and placing their own regulatory bets on the
future.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of its drive to foster a national broadband policy, the
FCC recently filed a friend-of-the-court brief in a case pending
before the U.S. Ninth Circuit of Appeals in San Francisco. It
argues that the commission should have sole authority over
broadband providers.
</P>
<P>
   In choosing thus far not to intervene in the budding broadband
market, Kennard says ``we are following advice as old as Western
civilization itself: First, do no harm _ a high-tech Hippocratic
Oath.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
