<HEADER>
A4833 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-BROADBAND-DATA-0901-C     08-30 0340
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROADBAND-DATA-0901-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DATA ON BROADBAND USE
 &HT;    With BROADBAND.
 &HT;    For release Wednesday, Sept. 1
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   RESIDENTIAL BROADBAND SET TO EXPLODE
</P>
<P>
   Millions of U.S. home subscribers to high-speed Internet
services
</P>
<P>
   1998.....0.45 million
</P>
<P>
   1999.....1.25
</P>
<P>
   2000.....2.70
</P>
<P>
   2001.....4.50
</P>
<P>
   2002.....7.00
</P>
<P>
   Source: The Yankee Group
</P>
<P>
   Note: 1998 figures are actual; 1999-2002 are projected.
</P>
<P>
   FROM DIGITAL PATH TO BROADBAND SPEEDWAY
</P>
<P>
   How the speed of online access for home personal computers (PCs)
as new technology has become generally available. Often, the
technology was available earlier to commercial users.
</P>
<P>
   Access is generally measured in ``bits,'' a unit of information
equal to one binary decision, such as ``yes'' or ``no.'' Typically,
each alphanumeric character such as the letter ``a'' requires 8
bits (a ``byte'') to be created and read.
</P>
<P>
   1962: 300 bits per second (bps) analog modems.
</P>
<P>
   1977: 1,200 bps analog modems.
</P>
<P>
   1982: 2,400 bps analog modems.
</P>
<P>
   1984: 9,600 bps analog modems.
</P>
<P>
   1990: 14.4 Kbps (kilobits, or 1,000 bits, per second) analog
modems.
</P>
<P>
   1992: 28.8 Kbps analog modems.
</P>
<P>
   1994: 33.6 Kbps analog modems.
</P>
<P>
   1998: 56 Kbps analog modems with a common standard, ending
interoperabilty problems among incompatible units.
</P>
<P>
   1999: 3.1 Mbps (megabits, or 1 million bits, per second) cable
TV modems.
</P>
<P>
   1999: 7.1 Mbps asymmetric digital subscriber lines (ADSL).
</P>
<P>
   In the near future: 2.4 Gbps (gigabits, or 1 billion bits, per
second) fiber-optic modems capable of using the ``Internet2,'' the
next-generation infrastructure involving more than 70 universities
and research labs.
</P>
<P>
   Sources: ``Modern Dictionary of Electronics'' (Radio Shack); Kim
Maxwell ``Residential Broadband,'' ADSL Forum; Dataquest; Intel
Corp.; National Coordination Office for Computing, Information, and
Communication.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
