<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4843 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-FUSS-DAGUERREOTYPES-5     08-30 0557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUSS-DAGUERREOTYPES-520(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOING BACK TO THE DAGUERREOTYPE, AND THEN AHEAD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., N.M., Britain, India)  (jw) 
 By MARGARETT LOKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Adam Fuss has made a career out of bucking
photographic trends.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1980s, when cutting-edge artists were busily
appropriating sundry signposts of popular culture in ironic and
postmodern ways, Fuss took the modernist route. He made insistently
experimental and abstract photograms, creating some of
photography's most arresting images by placing various objects on
photographic paper and exposing them to light. The images included
molten sunflowers, hypnotic concentric circles with a white-hot
core, brutalist sculptural forms, Abstract Expressionist tangles
and fantastical silhouettes of water babies.
</P>
<P>
   Fuss continues to experiment and to produce abstract images of
undeniable beauty, even as artists like Cindy Sherman eschew that
esthetic. ``My Ghost,'' a show of his work that opens at Cheim &AMP;
Read in the Chelsea neighborhood of Manhattan on Sept. 9, includes
Fuss' ever more blurry photograms and a number of his extraordinary
reinterpretations of that quintessential 19th-century photographic
medium, the daguerreotype.
</P>
<P>
   Just as his photograms bear scant resemblance to those made by
earlier artists like Man Ray, Fuss' daguerreotypes are a radical
departure from the earlier, precisely representational studies of
people and places. His spare daguerreotypes bear images like a
grieving woman's silhouette, an incandescent butterfly, a ghostly
self-portrait and a shadowy christening dress.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent hot and humid day in his Chelsea studio, which was
cooled only by the breezes wafting in from open windows along one
wall, Fuss recalled the genesis of his daguerreotype project.
</P>
<P>
   He saw daguerreotypes more than a decade ago, he said, and
thought they were ``a magical medium.'' His interest was sharpened
after he attended a 1989 lecture and demonstration at the New-York
Historical Society by Robert Shlaer, a daguerreotypist who lives in
New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall Fuss took a workshop given by Kenneth Nelson, a
daguerreotypist, at the George Eastman House in Rochester. With
subsequent advice from Jerry Spagnoli, a Manhattan daguerreotypist,
Fuss rigged up the necessary equipment in his studio.
</P>
<P>
   Following a process invented by Louis J.M. Daguerre in the early
1830s, a daguerreotypist begins by polishing a silvered copper
plate to a mirror finish. He then photosensitizes the plate with
iodine vapors before inserting it in a camera to make an exposure.
If he chooses, which is what Fuss prefers, he can dispense with a
camera and place an object directly on the plate and expose the
pair to light.
</P>
<P>
   The exposed plate is developed with mercury or, as Fuss does it
in his studio, through a technique discovered by the French
physicist Edmund Becquerel in 1840, with a red light for about 10
to 20 hours. (For the mercury development process, Fuss goes to
Rochester.)
</P>
<P>
   Fuss says his studio equipment is all homemade because he can
not buy what is needed to make a daguerreotype. He recalled
Nelson's saying, ``There are less people making daguerreotypes than
there are who have climbed Mount Everest.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In The Journal of the West in January 1989, W.R. Young III
wrote: ``The daguerreotype is ... unique in photography. Success
with the process requires a familiarity with chemistry, physics and
laboratory safety procedure, as well as physical dexterity, keen
powers of observation, careful note keeping, library research
skills, tenacity and a scientific bent.'' (The chemicals involved
in producing a typical daguerreotype _ mercury, bromine, iodine _
are highly toxic.)
</P>
<P>
   Since his youth, Fuss has been a close observer of his
surroundings and nature's oddities and alchemic powers. When he was
a boy living in West Sussex, England, he was intrigued by the
combustible marsh gas in a nearby pond. Not content to collect the
gas in a bottle and set it on fire, he put a match to dead leaves
he piled on the surface of the pond, where gas from the bottom of
the pond had bubbled up.
</P>
<P>
   As a boy, he was mesmerized as well by the mysterious black
mirror that was the surface of the pond. It is hardly surprising,
then, that at this point in his career he should be teasing
expressionistic images out of another kind of mirror surface.
</P>
<P>
   ``My approach to daguerreotypes is purely as a contemporary
photographer,'' Fuss said. Continuing his photograms by other
means, he has, for instance, placed a butterfly on a 5-by-7-inch
photosensitized plate, the finished combination photogram and
daguerreotype yielding an image of glowing translucence.
</P>
<P>
   Fuss' initial group of daguerreotypes, which were made late last
year, was first shown in Calcutta. That exhibition had already been
planned, he said, but there was another reason he wanted his new
work to appear there.
</P>
<P>
   Within a year of the announcement of the daguerreotype's
invention, in 1839, ``there were people making daguerreotypes in
Calcutta,'' Fuss said. ``It got there very quickly,'' he added.
``And I think of this moment in history as being the beginning of a
renaissance in the daguerreotype, and I like the idea of it
returning to Calcutta very early in that renaissance.''
</P>
<P>
   Grant Romer, director of conservation and museum studies at the
George Eastman House and a daguerreotypist, also sees a resurgence
in interest in this medium. ``There are more people experimenting
with daguerreotypes than at any period since the commercial demise
of the process in the early 1860s,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   To make life-size photogram daguerreotypes of his larger
objects, like a christening dress, Fuss has been experimenting with
20-by-24-inch daguerreotype plates. He is one of the few modern
daguerreotypists to work with plates this size.
</P>
<P>
   The christening dress and a rabbit motif are carry-overs from
two earlier photogram series. ``My Ghost,'' featuring a christening
dress, first appeared a few years ago; ``Love,'' a startling series
of dead rabbits with intertwined intestines, was created in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   With the rabbit and the dress now pared down to minimalist
silhouettes or hazy outlines, and with daguerreotypes giving an
illusion of being three-dimensional, Fuss' photogram daguerreotypes
are more ethereal and haunting. Among his daguerreotypes is one of
a mask with upright ears. The mask is a delicate celadon and the
background slate gray. Fuss explained that this was a rabbit's face
peeled off the skull.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dress image is like the body of a child without life,'' he
said. ``The rabbit is the idea of a life without a body.''
</P>
<P>
   As enigmatically beautiful as they are, Fuss' images are
inextricably tied to darkly exhilarating questions of life and
death, change and loss. Given this sense of the evanescent in his
work, the elusive nature of the daguerreotype image seems
particularly apt. Reflecting a light surface, the image appears as
a negative. Reflecting a dark material, the image appears as a
positive. But brightly illuminated, the daguerreotype springs
instantly and magically to life.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
