<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4845 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-COX-BROADBAND-PLAYERS     08-30 0496
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-BROADBAND-PLAYERS-0901 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MAJOR PLAYERS IN THE BROADBAND BATTLE
 &HT;    With BROADBAND.
 &HT;    For release Wednesday, Sept. 1
 &HT;    Moving in (f) financial and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's the lineup of the major players and their current
positions in the emerging battle over broadband services:
</P>
<P>
   Player: AOL
</P>
<P>
   Stance: AT&AMP;T is forging a broadband monopoly by refusing to
share entry to its dominant cable networks. Regulators should
require AT&AMP;T and other cable networks to offer ``open access'' to
America Online and other Internet service and content providers. If
the company refuses, the FCC should block its pending merger with
cable's Media One Group.
</P>
<P>
   Player: AT&AMP;T
</P>
<P>
   Stance: Asserts the right to retain control over broadband lines
after having paid close to $120 billion for privately owned
networks. Maintains its entry into the broadband cable market
offers the only realistic hope of creating genuine competition with
the powerful regional Bells in both high-speed Internet and local
telephone markets.
</P>
<P>
   Player: Regional Bells
</P>
<P>
   Stance: Congress and the FCC need to recognize that these issues
cut much more deeply than the quarrel between AT&AMP;T vs. AOL over
broadband Internet access. Argue that they need to be freed from
their tight regulatory harness if they are to compete effectively
against both AT&AMP;T and the cable operators for broadband and
long-distance customers.
</P>
<P>
   Player: FCC
</P>
<P>
   Stance: Generally favors a nonregulatory, market-determining
approach while privately prodding cable operators to embrace the
Internet's tradition of openness so that more Americans can gain
access to high-speed Internet services. Warns of chaos if local
regulators pile in with their own rules for new broadband pipes.
</P>
<P>
   Player: Cities
</P>
<P>
   Stance: In Portland, Ore., officials tell AT&AMP;T that it must open
its network to outside Internet service providers as a condition of
merging with the local cable company. When AT&AMP;T sues, a federal
judge supports Portland's views. That legal ruling has set off a
flurry of copycat actions among other local governments.
</P>
<P>
   Player: Courts
</P>
<P>
   Stance: In San Francisco, the 28-judge U.S. Ninth Circuit Court
of Appeals has agreed to hear arguments over whether localities
have the right to force open cable networks. This key issue, which
has never been litigated, is likely to be eventually decided by the
U.S. Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Player: Congress
</P>
<P>
   Stance: House and Senate lawmakers seek to offer relief to both
sides in offering at least nine bills that address the competing
needs of cable and telephone giants. Even as their lobbyists enter
the fray, most congressional leaders show scant interest in
stirring anew the battle that led to passage of the 1996
Telecommunications Act, which permitted the current spate of
mergers and buy-outs.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
