<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990830.0322 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4880 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-HAZING-0831-COX     08-30 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAZING-0831-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FOUR-FIFTHS OF COLLEGE ATHLETES RECALL HAZING INCIDENTS
 &HT;    Eds: With HAZING-DATA
 &HT;    620&AMP;add
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (s) sports categories
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON - Four out of every five NCAA college athletes have
undergone humiliating or dangerous hazing by their teammates,
according to a study released here Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Some rookies were cursed at, paddled, branded or kidnapped.
Others were pressured to enter drink-til-you-puke contests or
perform other illegal acts, said the report by Albert University in
western New York state.
</P>
<P>
   Still, only one out of every eight student athletes would
describe what they underwent as ``hazing.'' And 60 percent of the
2,009 athletes who filled out an anonymous questionnaire said that
even if they were hazed, they wouldn't report it to their coach,
school or police.
</P>
<P>
   Hazing is seldom reported, agreed the 1,498 college officials
who also answered anonymously.
</P>
<P>
   Half of the coaches and athletic directors and more than 70
percent of the student affairs deans agreed that hazing isn't
reported to them. One major reason: Only 25 percent of students
believe that if their college or university knew of a hazing
incident, it would take strong disciplinary action.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have on the other side, coaches saying, 'We have rules and
they're good rules, but I can't enforce a rule with hearsay,' ``
said Nadine Hoover, the principal investigator for the study.
``Given the combination of the secrecy around the behavior, and the
desensitization and even denial that it's really happening, getting
somebody to report it is very unlikely.''
</P>
<P>
   She stressed that hazing should not be confused with positive
``team-building'' initiation rites _ such as making rookies
carrying the balls to the field or court, or ordering them to join
their teammates at skit nights, team roasts or team parties.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers defined hazing as ``any activity expected of
someone joining a group that humiliates, degrades, abuses or
endangers, regardless of the person's willingness to participate.''
</P>
<P>
   A startling 68 percent of male athletes and 63 percent of female
athletes who responded to the national survey reported undergoing
what the researchers described as ``questionable'' activities that
were designed to humiliate or embarrass them. Those included being
yelled, cursed or sworn at, being forced to wear silly clothing, as
well as tattooing, body-piercing, head-shaving or branding.
</P>
<P>
   Just over half of both male and female athletes said that as
newcomers trying to fit in they had participated in drinking
contests or other alcohol-related hazing, which is illegal for
those under age 21 in every state. In fact, 42 percent had started
earlier, consuming alcohol with future teammates while on
recruiting trips to a campus during their high school years.
</P>
<P>
   And 27 percent of the men and 16 percent of the women on NCAA
teams said they had been involved in activities that the
researchers described as ``unacceptable, dangerous and potentially
illegal.'' They extended from being pushed to commit crimes _
making prank phone calls or harassing others, destroying or
stealing property _ to being paddled, whipped, beaten, kicked,
kidnapped or tied up and abandoned. Even if the victim is willing,
such violent hazing is illegal in most of the 41 states with
anti-hazing laws.
</P>
<P>
   Swimmers, divers and soccer or lacrosse players were most likely
to be hazed. At the other extreme, basketball and tennis players,
fencers and track athletes were least likely to be hazed.
</P>
<P>
   Hazing levels for most sports fell between those extremes, and
few big differences were found among schools in Divisions I, II or
III. The researchers said that low response rates prevented
accurate measurement of hazing levels for football, cross-country
and squash.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``As a university president, I find the results of our study on
hazing to join athletic teams horrifying,'' said Edward G. Coll of
Albert University. He arranged for the study after some freshmen at
his school had to be hospitalized after veteran football players
tied them up and forced them to drink. He received technical help
from the NCAA and funding from an insurance company.
</P>
<P>
   Coll called upon other college presidents to join him in
establishing a ``zero-tolerance policy,'' in order to break the
chain of hazing in which rookies are harassed by older teammates
who were hazed in previous years.
</P>
<P>
   While fraternities and sororities can sometimes use their
private status to frustrate enforcement of collegiate anti-hazing
policies, ``athletic hazing is different,'' Coll said. ``These are
our teams, supported by our money, supervised by our coaches ....
on our playing fields in our gyms and locker rooms.''
</P>
<P>
   The study reveals that hazing ``is pervasive and appalling,''
said Ron Stratton, a former track star and Portland State coach who
is vice president for educational services at the NCAA.
</P>
<P>
   ``We recruit student athletes to come to our member
institutions,'' Stratton said. ``To the degree we put their lives
in danger physically or emotionally, our athletic administrators
will have to take responsibility for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Calling upon college presidents to deal with the problem,
Stratton added, ``This is an institutional problem, not an NCAA
problem, at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   A majority of coaches, athletic directors and student affairs
deans, as well as at least one-third of the students, agreed on the
same set of specific strategies that could diminish hazing.
</P>
<P>
   Offered 11 choices, their top selections were:
</P>
<P>
   - Strong disciplinary and corrective measures for known cases.
</P>
<P>
   - Setting clear standards for hazing-free recruitment.
</P>
<P>
   - Creating alternative bonding and recognition events for teams.
</P>
<P>
   - Involving law enforcement in monitoring, investigating and
prosecuting hazing incidents.
</P>
<P>
   The questionnaire was answered by 20 percent of the 10,000
students and 26.5 percent of the coaches and college officials to
whom it was mailed.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
