<DOCNO> NYT19990830.0323 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4881 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a k BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$     08-30 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$ADV01-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMNISTS' ADVICE NOT ALWAYS WORTH TAKING
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Wednesday, Sept. 1)  
(mk) 
 By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As if alcohol, tobacco and presidential elections were not bad
enough, it now appears that medical columnists can be hazardous to
your health.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Canadian Medical Association, information
published by medical columnists in newspapers is sometimes so wrong
that it can kill elderly patients.
</P>
<P>
   After surveying dozens of medical columns in Canadian
English-language newspapers in 1995, a team of doctors judged 50
percent of the advice to be ``inappropriate'' and 28 percent
``dangerous and potentially life-threatening,'' according to a
Reuters news story.
</P>
<P>
   The doctors said some errors might have been introduced during
the editing process and suggested that only those with medical
knowledge should alter newspaper columnists' stories.
</P>
<P>
   Although I am not a medical columnist per se, this story made me
wonder how much inappropriate and/or life-threatening advice I have
passed along to readers over the years, and more importantly how I
can pin the blame on my editors in case I am ever sued.
</P>
<P>
   Just yesterday, for example, I advised readers to send me
$90,000 in exchange for one (1) authentic Florida palmetto bug
captured in my garage. I did not, thankfully, suggest that the
palmetto bug had any medicinal properties, but that is not to say I
wouldn't have had I had more space.
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago it was suggested in a column bearing my name
that Vice President Al Gore take his vacation in Bradenton, Fla.,
rather than on Longboat Key, and that he should consider spending
the night, 15 minutes at a time, in some of the many fine motels
lining 14th Street.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, this was medical advice of the most dangerous and
irresponsible kind and I am still waiting for the sniveling editor
who committed this outrage to identify himself or herself and
apologize to Gore, his family, and the owners and customers of the
many fine motels lining 14th Street.
</P>
<P>
   In another column, I urged readers to vote only for those
candidates who support federally subsidized lawn care. Tax cuts are
all well and good, I argued, but nothing beats having a fat
Washington bureaucrat come by once or twice a week to mow your
grass and pull your weeds, free of charge.
</P>
<P>
   Looking back, it is clear that I failed to take into account any
possible pre-existing medical conditions of fat Washington
bureaucrats such as high blood pressure or heart disease, nor did I
give any thought to the fact that anyone, fat Washington bureaucrat
or otherwise, is likely to keel over dead from sunstroke after 15
minutes of pulling weeds in the Florida heat, assuming the fire
ants don't do him in first.
</P>
<P>
   Next on the train of dubious advice was a column I wrote
suggesting that families that eat garlic bread with their spaghetti
dinners are less likely to fight among themselves than families who
don't eat garlic bread. Unfortunately, some readers interpreted the
words ``less likely'' to mean ``not likely at all'' and blamed me
when their next spaghetti-and-garlic-bread family dinner
degenerated into the kind of scene one normally associates with
English soccer riots and stock market ``adjustments.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, and most dangerously irresponsible of all, was the
column with my name on it that stated that one can reduce stress
and achieve feelings of well-being by plunging ones nose into the
armpit of an overheated elderly woman.
</P>
<P>
   The column went on to say a bunch of other equally rude and
ridiculous things, every one of which sprang full-blown from the
fevered imagination of some craven, unidentified copy editor who
clearly does not share my respect and admiration for this area's
many fine senior-citizens, especially those who happen to be
subscribers with access to telephones and/or writing paper.
</P>
<P>
   All of which just goes to show that you can't be too careful
about what you say.
</P>
<P>
   Or, in my case, what I didn't say.
</P>
<P>
   (The Sarasota, Fla., Herald-Tribune is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-99 1849EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990830.0324 </DOCNO>
