<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4883 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-RUSSIA-ANTARCTIC-     08-30 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-RUSSIA-ANTARCTIC-660&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIANS, FINANCIALLY PRESSED, SCALE BACK RESEARCH AT SOUTH POLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Science Times) 
(mk) 
 By MALCOLM W. BROWNE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As Russia's impoverished scientific institutions face ever more
severe cuts in financing, Moscow's main station on the Antarctic
continent has been forced to close. If the participation of Russian
institutions in Antarctic research is to continue, scientists say,
they will require increasing international support.
</P>
<P>
   Among the latest victims of Moscow's austerity measures is
Molodezhnaya Station, the headquarters station of Russia's network
of bases on the white continent. Molodezhnaya (pronounced
Mah-luh-DYOZH-na-ya), which had a peak summer population of
scientists and technicians of more than 200, was ordered two years
ago to begin closing down and by now no one is left there except a
half dozen caretakers who are moth-balling the station for
indefinite closure.
</P>
<P>
   Staffs at other Russian Antarctic stations have been severely
reduced and Russian support operations throughout the continent
have been cut to the bone.
</P>
<P>
   Molodezhnaya, founded in 1963, lies on East Antarctica's Prince
Olav Coast, south of the Indian Ocean. Besides coordinating
activities at other Russian bases, Molodezhnaya was a center for
glaciology, geology and life sciences.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Vladimir Papitashvili, a specialist in Arctic and Antarctic
geophysics, has conducted research for Soviet and Russian
institutions in polar regions since the 1970s. He said in an
interview that Molodezhnaya was not being closed forever. ``It will
be preserved for future use, although that won't come during my
lifetime,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Molodezhnaya has relatively comfortable quarters for its staff
and visiting scientists, and it has both a port and a good
packed-snow airstrip, which the Russian polar agency had considered
as a possible hub for a future Antarctic air transport network. But
the other 17 nations conducting research in Antarctica and their 43
year-round stations have shown little interest in the proposed
Antarctic air service, and the Russian revenue-earning scheme seems
unlikely to bear fruit.
</P>
<P>
   Papitashvili, a Georgian, now conducts polar research for the
University of Michigan and for the Danish Meteorological Institute
in Copenhagen. With the coming of the Southern Hemisphere spring in
September he plans to return to Vostok Station _ a Russian base on
the South Polar Plateau that is now partly assisted by non-Russian
air transport, equipment and scientists, including Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from being the world's low-temperature record holder
(minus 128.6 degrees Fahrenheit, recorded on July 21, 1983), Vostok
Station and the two-mile thickness of ice on which it rests overlie
an enormous lake, whose water has been sealed off from the outer
world for perhaps as much as 1 million years.
</P>
<P>
   Any life forms found in Lake Vostok would be of extraordinary
interest, but an international team of drillers at Vostok Station
has stopped short of the liquid water, until a way is found to
sample the water without contaminating it with organisms from the
world above.
</P>
<P>
   Because of financial problems, the Russian staff of scientists
at Vostok has been halved. The station is exceptionally difficult
and expensive to maintain because it is beyond the range of
suitable Russian aircraft. Nearly all its supplies must be brought
overland from Russia's coastal Mirnyy Station, which is supplied by
ship when the ea ice breaks up.
</P>
<P>
   The harrowing supply run from Mirnyy to Vostok, 870 miles, is
made by a tractor-hauled sledge train. The train takes one month to
reach its destination.
</P>
<P>
   Papitashvili said that during most of the 42 years since Vostok
Station was founded, two trips were made each year by the supply
train, but recently the schedule was reduced to just one round trip
to save money. Because the train must bring 300 tons of fuel to the
base each year, correspondingly less room is left for other
supplies, although in summer, American C-130 transport planes,
equipped with skis, have begun bringing light equipment to Vostok
from McMurdo Station.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Russian government is considering closing Mirnyy Station and
transferring its function as the supply port for Vostok to another
Russian coastal station, Progress, that was established 12 years
ago. Progress, on the shore of Prydz Bay south of Africa, was
recently designated as the new Russian headquarters station,
replacing Molodezhnaya.
</P>
<P>
   Russia is not the only nation facing problems maintaining its
Antarctic stations, scattered across a continent the size of the
United States and Mexico combined.
</P>
<P>
   Great Britain has also had to cut back. In 1956, the British
Antarctic Survey established Faraday Station near the northern tip
of the Antarctic Peninsula, some 700 miles south of Tierra del
Fuego. The location was ideal for the study of marine wildlife, but
in the early 1990s Britain decided to divest itself of Faraday.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of abandoning or moth-balling the base, London turned it
over to Ukraine in 1996, which has renamed the station Academician
Vernadskiy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good deal for both nations,'' said Erick Chiang,
operations chief for the United States' National Science Foundation
in Antarctica. ``Ukraine got its own ready-made base in Antarctica,
and Britain unloaded the maintenance cost.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we'll see more of that kind of deal in the coming
years,'' Chiang said. ``Antarctica really needs to be more fully
internationalized.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-99 1850EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
