<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Sept. 5) 
(jt) 
 By JOSEPH SIANO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Transport in Spain
</P>
<P>
   Q. My husband and I will be in Spain early next year and will be
traveling from Madrid to Torremolinos, then on to Valencia and
finally to Barcelona. We do not plan to rent a car or fly from one
city to the next. What is the better way to go: by bus or train? _
Rhoda Peterson, Briarcliff Manor, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   A. Here is some basic information on intercity travel in Spain
by bus and rail to help you decide which mode of transportation is
better for you based on time and cost. Fare and schedule
information applies to this month; prices and timetables for the
period that you plan to travel have not been set yet.
</P>
<P>
   By bus, the trip from Madrid to Torremolinos can be made on
Daibus, (34-91) 468-5141, with eight buses daily. The first leaves
at 8:30 a.m., the last at 11 p.m. The trip takes about six and a
quarter hours and the fare is $16.70 (at 159 pesetas to $1).
</P>
<P>
   From Torremolinos to Valencia, Vacoma, (34-96) 348-7980,
currently has daily departures at 12:20, 6:35 and 11:25 p.m. The
trip takes 10 to 11 hours; cost: $38.75.
</P>
<P>
   From Valencia to Barcelona, Ubesa, (34-96) 340-0855, now has
nine departures Monday to Saturday and seven on Sunday. The trip
takes about four and a quarter hours. The fare is $18.20.
</P>
<P>
   By Renfe, the state railway, you can get from Madrid to Malaga
(next to Torremolinos) in about four and a quarter hours on an
express train (Talgo 200) for $62.80 in first class (preferente)
and $43.30 in tourist class. An Intercity train costs less _ $40.20
in first class, $30.80 in tourist _ but takes about seven hours.
</P>
<P>
   Service from Malaga to Valencia is much less frequent (usually
two trains a day) and there is no express service. An Intercity
train takes nine and a half hours, with a tourist fare of $36.40.
An overnight train takes about the same time and costs $43.30 with
a sleeping bunk and $34.50 in tourist class.
</P>
<P>
   From Valencia to Barcelona, there is a much greater selection of
service and frequency (more than a dozen trains a day). A Euromed
train, for example, makes the trip in just under three hours at
speeds nearing 140 miles an hour; the first-class fare is $45.20
and tourist fare is $30.80. The Arco, which takes about 3 hours 40
minutes, is $35.20 in first class and $27 in tourist. The Intercity
service, about 3 hours 20 minutes, is $29 in first class, $22.60 in
tourist.
</P>
<P>
   For information on Spanish railways, call (34-91) 328-9020 in
Madrid or www.renfe.es/hir/ingles.html. You can reserve tickets in
the United States from Iberojet Travel, (800) 222-8383 or
www.iberojet.net, or Rail Europe, (800) 438-7245 or
www.raileurope.com, for an extra charge.
</P>
<P>
   The Tourist Office of Spain is at 666 Fifth Ave., 35th Floor,
New York, N.Y. 10103; (888) 657-7246 or www.okspain.org.
</P>
<P>
   Hotels in Santiago
</P>
<P>
   Q. We are going to be in Santiago, Chile, later this year. Can
you give us the names of some moderately priced hotels? _ Abe
Margolies, New York, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   A. You can try one of the following hotels:
</P>
<P>
   The Hotel Montebianco, 2911 Isidora Goyenechea, (56-2) 2330427,
fax (56-2) 2330420, is a new hotel in the Las Condes district, a
middle-class neighborhood. The rate of $80 includes breakfast and
rooms have patios, TV, telephone and private bath.
</P>
<P>
   The Hotel Neruda, 164 Avenida Pedro de Valdivia, (56-2) 2310010,
fax (56-2) 2311007, is in Providencia, adjacent to Las Condes. It
costs $120 a night with breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   The Hotel Los Espanoles, 2539 Los Espanoles, (56-2) 2321824, fax
(56-2) 2331048, costs $80 a night with breakfast. This 50-room
hotel is in Providencia and has 24-hour room service and free
e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   The Hotel Director, 3600 Vitacura, (56-2) 2460101, fax (56-2)
2287503, is a modern 96-room hotel near downtown. It has many
amenities (gym, pool, sauna); $145 without breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   A Day on a Steam Train
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am looking for a day trip on a steam or electric locomotive
for my 9-year-old son. It has to be close to my home and near
public transportation because I do not drive. _ Yvonne Cook,
Brooklyn, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   A. The most convenient journey for you and your son appears to
be one that involves two trains _ a steam locomotive and a more
modern conveyance, an Amtrak train _ and a boat ride, too, if you
wish.
</P>
<P>
   The Valley Railroad in Essex, Conn., operates the Essex Steam
Train. The restored locomotives follow a 12-mile route along the
Connecticut River Valley. The 50-minute train ride connects with an
optional riverboat cruise back down the river; the boat and train
trips together take about two and a half hours.
</P>
<P>
   The line was established in 1871, linking Saybrook on Long
Island Sound with communities along the river valley all the way up
to Hartford. But the valley was so sparsely populated that the line
never made much money and eventually stopped running. It was
revived as a tourist attraction in 1971, with restored cars.
</P>
<P>
   To reach Essex from New York, you can take Amtrak to Old
Saybrook, Conn., and take a cab for the 15-minute ride to the steam
train.
</P>
<P>
   When you arrive in Old Saybrook, you can call the East Shore Cab
Co., (860) 388-2819; the cab fare to Essex will be $6 to $7. On the
way back to Old Saybrook, you can call Essex Cab, (860) 767-7433,
which would charge about $12.
</P>
<P>
   After this weekend, the steam train switches to its fall
schedule, in effect through Oct. 31, with trips Wednesday through
Sunday (and Columbus Day) at 10:30 a.m., noon, 1:30 p.m. and 3 p.m.
(no boat ride available with the last train departure). On Oct. 29
and 30, there are special Ghost Trains at 6 and 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The combination train-boat fare is $16.50, ages 3 to 11 $8.50.
For the train ride only, it is $10.50, children $5.50; prices
include tax, but there's a surcharge to ride in the parlor car ($3)
and open car ($2).
</P>
<P>
   And on Nov. 6, 7, 11, 13 and 14, Thomas the Tank Engine will be
there for rides and photographs; adults $11, 12 and under $9.
</P>
<P>
   To contact the Essex Steam Train, call (860) 767-0103 or
www.valleyrr.com on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   To give you an idea of the frequency of service on Amtrak, on
Sept. 22 (a Sunday), there is a train out of Penn Station at 6:58
a.m. that reaches Old Saybrook at 9:38 a.m. The unreserved adult
coach fare is $31 one way. There are return trains at 4:16 and 6:28
p.m. One or two children ages 2 to 15 can travel at half the adult
fare when traveling with an adult.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Amtrak at (800) 872-7245 or www.amtrak.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
