<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 19:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4889 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-800(2TA     08-30 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEGOTIATORS PUSH TO REVIVE MIDEAST PEACE ACCORD BY THURSDAY
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Israeli and Palestinian leaders expressed cautious
optimism Monday that they could forge a comprehensive deal to
revive their frozen peace agreement by the time Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright arrives in the Middle East on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But as senior negotiators threw themselves into a final round of
meetings, the two sides apparently remained deadlocked on several
key issues. These included the terms for the release of Palestinian
prisoners by Israel and a target date for concluding the framework
of a permanent peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed possible, then, that Albright would be thrust back
into the role of mediator on her arrival. In the Middle East, it is
a familiar role for the Americans, who brokered the frozen
agreement in Wye, Md., last fall.
</P>
<P>
   Ehud Barak, the new Israeli prime minister, had hoped that the
first negotiations under his leadership could be concluded without
brokers. He has an ambitious agenda for forging a broad regional
consensus on peace, under a tight deadline _ 15 months is his goal
_ that demands efficiency in negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   By the weekend, though, the Israelis and Palestinians had
reached an inefficient impasse, and President Hosni Mubarak of
Egypt stepped in to help. His diplomatic troubleshooter, Dr. Osama
el-Baz, shuttled between Barak and Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian
leader, reportedly urging Arafat to focus on long-range, rather
than short-term solutions to the Israeli-Palestinian conflict.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Mubarak will meet with Arafat in Egypt to discuss
the remaining differences with the Israelis on a detailed plan to
carry out _ and go beyond _ the Wye agreement.
</P>
<P>
   All parties have seized on Albright's visit as a self-imposed
deadline for reaching a deal. Mubarak optimistically hopes to play
host to a signing ceremony for a new memorandum of understanding
between the Israelis and the Palestinians on Thursday, when he
receives Albright in Alexandria on her first stop in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Barak adopted a tough-guy posture toward the Palestinians on
Sunday, threatening to break off talks, but on Monday he seemed far
more accommodating and hopeful of a deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm assuming that in two or three days we'll reach an
agreement,'' Barak said. ``And I believe that together we will have
reached a solution that is better than Wye as it is written.''
</P>
<P>
   Emerging late Monday from a negotiating session at the King
David hotel, Saeb Erekat, the senior Palestinian negotiator, told
Palestinian reporters that not much progress had been made.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still exerting our maximum effort but these issues do
not require further negotiation,'' Erekat said. ``They require
political decisions from President Arafat and Mr. Barak.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Erekat, expressing confidence that a deal
could be struck by Thursday, had suggested that the Israeli leader
might have ``cold feet'' about reaching an agreement because he was
``new.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak had issued a curious threat to the Palestinians on Sunday.
He had said that if no agreement were reached to modify the Wye
memorandum, Israel would carry it out as is, ``by the book'' _
which is what the Palestinians have long been demanding.
</P>
<P>
   Erekat said that Barak's ultimatum created a ``win-win''
situation for the Palestinians. Either way, the frozen agreement
would be thawed out.
</P>
<P>
   What Barak reportedly meant, however, was that the Israelis
would be literal-minded and less flexible, abiding by the letter of
the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Since the agreement does not specify what kinds of prisoners
would be released, for instance, the Israelis would release whom
they chose _ criminals rather than political prisoners, say _
instead of negotiating a release formula with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Since he took office in early July, Barak has been trying to
persuade Arafat to modify the Wye agreement and to link carrying it
out with the next step: the thorny negotiations for a final peace.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians have been very resistant and suspicious of
Barak's motives.
</P>
<P>
   After a meeting between Barak and Arafat at the end of July, two
senior negotiators, one from each side, were assigned to work
through the resistance.
</P>
<P>
   The two men, Erekat and Gilad Sher for the Israelis, have forged
a close, trusting relationship, clearly working well together as
they gingerly attacked difference between them as problems but not
obstacles.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli negotiator has called their talks ``intellectually
stimulating.'' Erekat has joked about Sher, ``He is my new love.''
</P>
<P>
   It has represented a sea change of difference in atmospherics
from the tense, hostile Israeli-Palestinian negotiations conducted
under Barak's predecessor, Benjamin Netanyahu _ almost always with
the Americans as baby sitters.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   But some issues remain as thorny and difficult to resolve as
ever.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of the prisoner release, in particular, is keenly
sensitive for Arafat. There were several small demonstrations in
the West Bank and Gaza Monday, mothers holding outsized, framed
photographs of their jailed sons. And if Arafat is perceived by his
people to be compromising his demand for the release of 650
political prisoners _ the Israelis call them security prisoners _
there could be significant unrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of empathy for the delicacy of the situation,''
an Israeli negotiator said Monday. ``We understand the human aspect
of the problem. But it's a sensitive issue in Israeli society,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   The Israelis want to include criminals in the prisoner release,
and they do not want to release any members of Islamic
fundamentalist groups. The Palestinians demand that only political
prisoners be released _ those who were arrested before the Oslo
agreement, the first step toward peace, was signed in 1995 _ and
that they be released without regard to the severity of their crime
or to their affiliation.
</P>
<P>
   If an agreement is reached this week, the first prisoners would
be released by the end of the second week of September, an Israeli
official said, and the second group in early October.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Israelis and Palestinians reportedly came to an
agreement on the overall timetable for staged Israeli withdrawals
from the West Bank, which would begin immediately and continue
through the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   But Barak wants to link the final withdrawal under the Wye
agreement with progress in the permanent status negotiations,
which, among other things, will determine the fate of the Jewish
settlements in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   He has said that he wants to talk about the division of land in
the West Bank more comprehensively, partly so as to create
contiguous Palestinian areas, and not to chop up everything in
advance.
</P>
<P>
   The Israelis think that enough progress can be made in the
permanent status talks to reach a framework agreement by January or
February of next year. A permanent status agreement could be
reached by the end of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   They want to include those dates as deadlines.
</P>
<P>
   But the Palestinians, who prefer to see no dates inscribed in
the new document, think the final date is too far off.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
