<HEADLINE>
HEAD OF THE CLASS: RICHARD RILEY CHAMPIONS EDUCATION WITH LOW-KEY
PASSION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Tenn., Ala., S.C., Pa.) (dw) 
 By SEAN LOUGHLIN   
 N.Y. Times Regional Newspaper Group   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON - In a way, Richard Riley has yet to graduate from
school.
</P>
<P>
   At 66, Riley is still consumed by tests and teachers, reading
and mathematics, classrooms and college.
</P>
<P>
   But as secretary for the U.S. Department of Education, Riley's
homework these days is a little more daunting - preparing students
for the next millennium.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have many challenges, as many challenges as there are
children out there,'' Riley said in his distinctive reedy drawl.
</P>
<P>
   Quiet and unassuming, Riley steadfastly preaches the value of
education, urging Congress to commit more money to America's
schools, exhorting parents to take a greater interest in the
academic lives of their children, pressing business leaders to
support education reform in their communities, and calling on
states to enact tougher licensing standards for teachers.
</P>
<P>
   This year, a record 53.2 million elementary and secondary school
students will pack into America's classrooms. College enrollment
has also risen to a new record of 14.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Education has been Dick Riley's highest priority since we were
governors together,'' President Clinton said in a statement. ``As a
Southern governor and now as education secretary, he has always
understood how central education is to the futures of our children
and our society.''
</P>
<P>
   A former governor of South Carolina, Riley has served as
education secretary since 1993. The longest serving education
secretary since the post was created in 1979, Riley is also,
according to many observers across the political spectrum, the
best.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Riley is probably my favorite,'' said Rep. William
Goodling, a longtime Pennsylvania Republican and chairman of the
House Education and Workforce Committee.
</P>
<P>
   As the new school year kicks off, Riley will travel for three
days throughout the South on a yellow school bus, highlighting
local programs that work and touting the administration's education
goals _ which include having all students read by third grade,
ending social promotion, stepping up new school construction, and
making it easier for all students to attend college. His bus tour
starts this Tuesday with stops in Chattanooga, Tenn., Birmingham
and Gadsden, Ala., and includes a stop the following day in
Greenville, S.C., his hometown.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bus trip is another way of saying what's happening out
there in the states is what important to us, rather than staying
here and talking about rules and regulations,'' Riley said.
</P>
<P>
   Although many Republicans fight the Clinton administration over
some education initiatives _ the White House, for example, strongly
opposes education vouchers favored by conservative lawmakers _
Riley's integrity and commitment have never been questioned.
</P>
<P>
   Riley is something of an anomaly in Washington: Unfailingly
gracious, he appears devoid of a political ego, shunning the social
whirl and limelight. He seems not to have one single enemy in a
city that thrives on partisan clashes.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to compare Riley with William Bennett, who served under
President Reagan and remains perhaps the most well known education
secretary, Goodling paused for a second. ``Mr. Riley has never
given anybody the impression that he has all the answers and he
knows it all,'' Goodling said. ``He never gives anybody the
impression that there's a quick fix or there's an easy answer and I
think that's to his benefit.''
</P>
<P>
   David Griffith, a lobbyist with the National Association of
State Boards of Education, said Riley's greatest accomplishment may
simply be that conservatives talk a lot less about abolishing the
department.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to remember but in 1994, there was concern about
whether the Department of Education would actually exist anymore,''
Griffith said. ``It is much to his credit that that talk is
certainly on the fringes now.''
</P>
<P>
   Nina Rees, an education analyst at the Heritage Foundation, a
conservative think tank, said simply that the American people are
``not ready'' to dismantle the department, which the foundation had
advocated.
</P>
<P>
   Riley, by the way, is doing ``a fine job,'' she said, as he
preaches flexibility and freedom for states and school districts, a
key concern of conservatives. Still, Rees took issue with a Clinton
proposal to hire 100,000 new teachers, describing it as a federal
mandate.
</P>
<P>
   But, she said, ``I've been impressed with some of the
initiatives,'' including Riley's call for more accountability on
the part of teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Much in Washington is made of Riley's perseverance and
determination, a character trait that some trace to Riley's long
battle with a painful and disabling back disease. With the
condition, known as rheumatoid spondylitis, bone spurs slowly grow
out of the backbone. Riley has been left with a stooped appearance
and he is unable to move his neck. But when the disease developed
in 1955, Riley refused to take painkillers, fearing they would
cloud his mind.
</P>
<P>
   Riley is especially highly regarded in South Carolina, where he
enacted a major education reform package in 1984 that toughened
standards for students, teachers and school administrators.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Harpootlian, chairman of the South Carolina Democratic
Party and a friend, called Riley ``one of the big plusses about the
state.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has always demonstrated the belief ... that in America, a
quality education is a great equalizer, that you can solve most of
society's ills with a great education.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
