<HEADER>
A4893 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-CARS-WILLIAMS-COLUMN-     08-30 1280
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARS-WILLIAMS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MITSUBISHI ROLLS OUT NEW ECLIPSE SPORTS-HATCHBACK FOR 2000
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by CARS-GLANCE) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mitsubishi, an industrial giant in Japan but a bit player in the
U.S. car market, rolls out an all-new version of its Eclipse
sports-hatchback for 2000, hoping that this remake of the company's
best-selling little car might help boost its overall sagging sales.
</P>
<P>
   Since entering the U.S. market with its own branded products in
the mid-80s, Mitsubishi has struggled here. For years it had sold
cars under the Chrysler Corp. umbrella, badged as Dodge or Plymouth
models. Like Chrysler had been for years in the United States,
Mitsubishi was second-class among automakers in Japan. Hooking up
with Chrysler didn't help the company build its image here or
abroad.
</P>
<P>
   But seeing its larger Japanese counterparts Toyota, Nissan and
Honda enjoy great success in the United States made Mitsubishi
yearn for a piece of the American pie. The company decided to try
to establish itself as a brand separate from Chrysler. Now,
Mitsubishi no longer provides its vehicles to DaimlerChrysler.
</P>
<P>
   One of its first products for the U.S. market, the miserable
little Precis subcompact (a clone of the comparably miserable
Hyundai Excel), did nothing to build Mitsubishi's brand image among
U.S. consumers.
</P>
<P>
   But the 1989 rollout of the first Eclipse began a decade-long
success story for this sporty hatchback/convertible model and
brought some prestige to the brand. During most of that period,
Mitsubishi sold 50,000 or more Eclipses annually in the United
States. That's certainly not high volume by most U.S. standards _
Ford, Honda and Toyota midsize sedans are sold here at annual rates
often far exceeding 300,000 cars. But for a small company, it has
been a fairly impressive number.
</P>
<P>
   The first Eclipse was something of a departure from what other
automakers offered U.S. consumers, bringing up to 190 horsepower to
a market segment where 140 horsepower was considered high-powered.
</P>
<P>
   A remake for 1995 made the Eclipse even better, with more power,
a roomier interior and more sporty performance.
</P>
<P>
   But Eclipse aficionados _ in fact, anyone who likes a good
sporty coupelike car _ will appreciate the completely redesigned
2000 model. Since the more expensive Mitsuibishi 3000GT sports car
has now been discontinued, the new Eclipse has been taken slightly
upscale to help replace the 3000GT.
</P>
<P>
   This vehicle is new from the ground up. Its longer and wider
than its predecessor, there is more interior space (including extra
room for the two back-seat passengers), and there is more power in
the base engine, which, thankfully, is built by Mitsubishi rather
than borrowed from Chrysler as the previous 2.0-liter base engine
was.
</P>
<P>
   Rated at 155 horsepower (manual transmission) or 145 horsepower
(automatic transmission), the new 2.4-liter four-cylinder gives the
base RS ($17,697 manual/$18,497 automatic) and midlevel GS ($19,047
manual/$20,047 automatic) decent if not dazzling performance.
</P>
<P>
   For dazzling performance, you'll have to spend a few more bucks
for the top-of-the-line GT model, which lists for $20,187 with
five-speed manual transmission and $21,187 with four-speed
Sportronic automatic, which allows the driver to manually shift the
transmission without having to use a clutch.
</P>
<P>
   The GT comes with Mitsubishi's 3.0-liter V-6 engine, rated at
205 horsepower and 205 foot-pounds of torque. Although its
horsepower is lower than that of the 210-horsepower, turbocharged
2.4-liter four-cylinder in the higher-priced Eclipse models of last
year, this is a much smoother engine because of its extra two
cylinders and the absence of a turbocharger.
</P>
<P>
   Making this engine normally aspirated _ that means without a
turbocharger or supercharger _ immediately adds a measure of
reliability and longevity that a turbocharged engine lacks. And
many American consumers now are demanding V-6 engines and refusing
to buy four-cylinder cars, no matter what their horsepower is.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for performance buffs, however, all three models
of the new Eclipse come only with front-wheel drive. Last year's
all-wheel-drive configuration has been discontinued.
</P>
<P>
   Gone, too, is the truly fun convertible model. I believe we can
expect to see the new body style offered in convertible form within
the next year or two, but don't hold your breath waiting for
all-wheel drive to return. Mitsubishi didn't sell many of those, so
the company has no plans to offer all-wheel drive in the new model.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even with front-wheel drive, torque steer is not a
problem with the new Eclipse, which was a pleasant surprise to me
as I put the V-6 model through its paces on some interesting, curvy
roads. (Torque steer is the tendency of a front-drive car to turn
toward the wheel that is getting the power during hard
acceleration, and it can be rather scary if it comes unexpectedly
during a turn.)
</P>
<P>
   If you like muscular, sporty car exteriors, you'll probably love
the new Eclipse's styling. It looks like a much more expensive
sports car than a high-teens, low-$20,000s sporty hatchback. In
fact, even though this is a hatchback, which allows for easy
loading of skis, surfboards and other sports equipment favored by
the typical Eclipse buyer, the smooth, clean lines of the car make
it appear to be a sports coupe.
</P>
<P>
   The redesigned interior gives the driver and front passenger
separate cockpit-style seating pods, helping to add significantly
to the Eclipse's sporty image.
</P>
<P>
   Standard features abound even on the base RS model. They include
air-conditioning, power windows and door locks, AM/FM/compact-disc
in-dash stereo with four speakers, 15-inch alloy wheels, manual
remote-control outside mirrors, interior air-filtration system, an
engine-immobilizing anti-theft system, and a tilt steering wheel.
Options include a dealer-installed rear spoiler.
</P>
<P>
   The midlevel GS model adds 16-inch alloy wheels, power glass sun
roof, rear stabilizer bar, dual power remote outside mirrors, fog
lamps, cruise control, remote keyless entry, AM/FM/CD stereo with
six speakers, leather-wrapped steering wheel and adjustable lumbar
support. The Sportronic automatic transmission and a six-disc
in-dash compact disc changer are among the available options.
</P>
<P>
   With the uplevel GT comes the V-6 engine, 17-inch alloy wheels,
twin-piston front brake calipers, rear disc brakes, side airbags
and upgraded seat fabric. The sun roof that comes on the GS is
optional on the GT ($850). Other options include leather front
seats, antilock brakes, side air bags for driver and front
passenger, Sportronic automatic, traction control (automatic
transmission only), rear wiper, and a premium audio system with
four-disc in-dash compact disc changer (all together in a premium
package for $2,040).
</P>
<P>
   Roadhandling is best in the uplevel model, but even the base
model handles well thanks to the vehicle's much-improved structural
rigidity and suspension system.
</P>
<P>
   Fuel economy ratings are rather decent, ranging from 20 miles
per gallon in the city and 27 mpg on the highway for the V-6
automatic to 23 city/31 highway for the four-cylinder with manual
transmission.
</P>
<P>
   The fuel tank holds 16.4 gallons of gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   (G. Chambers Williams III is transportation writer and
automotive columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Contact him
at 3201 Airport Freeway, Suite 108, Bedford, TX 76022; telephone
(817) 685-3810; e-mail chambers(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
