<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-BRIEFS-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Sept. 5) 
(jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Bit of Tudor Fantasy Comes to Prague
</P>
<P>
   Londoners may think their Globe Theater is unique, but visitors
to Prague can see a faithful reproduction of the Elizabethan
playhouse, supposedly less than an inch different in size from the
original. The Prague theater will be one of the attractions of the
Prague 2000 _ European City of Culture festival next year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Except for steel stairways, the entire theater is made of wood,
with no ceiling, and walls that are open to the surrounding
greenery. Globe '99, as the project is called, opened on July 21
with a performance of ``Romeo and Juliet'' by a Brno student group
called Theater Studio of Pure Joy. For the next few years
performances will take place only in summer; the management hopes
eventually to turn it into an all-year affair. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Karel Klima, the project's manager, observed the reconstruction
of the Globe in London two years ago and started planning his own
Globe in Prague. After almost two years of preparation, the actual
construction took less than three months. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Plays on the list for September include ``As You Like It,'' in
English, performed by Misery Loves Company, a Prague ensemble, and,
in Czech, ``Othello'' and a musical version of ``Midsummer Night's
Dream,'' both performed by the Brno Municipal Ensemble, as well as
``Aucassin et Nicolette,'' a 13th-century tale of romantic love.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Globe is on the sprawling Exhibition Ground (Vystaviste),
which also includes a sports stadium, two other theaters and a
19th-century fountain. Tickets (about $6 each) can be purchased at
the Vystaviste kiosk or through Ticket Express, Vystaviste Praha,
17005 Prague 7, Holesovice; (420-2) 1067. Information: (420-2)
2010-3204.
</P>
<P>
   Pursuing Fall Colors on New England Rails
</P>
<P>
   Travelers who aren't deterred by reports on how the drought may
diminish New England's fall colors have at least two scenic train
trips to choose from next month. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Scenic Rail Excursions, operated by the Green Mountain Railroad,
offers rail tours of the scenic southern Vermont countryside in
restored coaches pulled by a diesel locomotive. The Ludlow Limited
departs from Bellows Falls, stops in Ludlow for half an hour, then
continues up to the summit in Mount Holly, the highest place on the
railroad tracks. Departure dates are Oct. 2, 3, 9, 10 and 11. The
round-trip fare between Bellows Falls and Ludlow is $25, $16 for
ages 3 through 12; Bellows Falls to the summit is $30, $20 for
children. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Reservations and information: Green Mountain Railroad, Post
Office Box 498, Bellows Falls, Vt. 05101, (800) 707-3530.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Mystic Valley Railway Society is sponsoring an autumn
excursion in Massachusetts. The Berkshire Limited is a 300-mile
round-trip journey on a chartered Amtrak train between Boston and
Pittsfield, Mass., leaving Boston on Oct. 23 at 9 a.m. and
returning at 6 p.m. The train will cross the Connecticut River and
pass through the hill country of Charleton, through the communities
of Jacob's Ladder, by and over Whistler's Arches and through the
rugged Westfield River Gorge just west of Springfield. The fare of
$65 includes a lunch served at your seat.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Information: Mystic Valley Railway Society, Post Office Box
365486, Hyde Park, Mass. 02136; (617) 361-4445.
</P>
<P>
   On-Line Directory Maps Trails for Hikers
</P>
<P>
   Hikers have a new Web site. Launched in August,
www.trailmaps.com provides information and maps for more than 4,000
hiking trails in five Western states: California, Colorado,
Montana, Oregon and Washington. The site is expected to have
information for trails in the rest of the country by the end of the
year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A search function that includes choices of elevation, season and
distance finds trails that range from difficult hikes that require
back-country permits to easy, scenic hikes for the whole family. A
particular hike is featured each week, with difficulty rating,
trail map and legend. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The directory of national parks also provides information about
permits, fees, lodging, concessions and special programs, as well
as a boot-fitting guide, with hints for the most common fit
problems. Under the heading In the Marketplace, more than 7,000
gear products are available, including books, maps and CD-ROMs
related to various trails. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Related sites include www.mountainzone.com, which covers hiking,
climbing, mountain biking, skiing and snowboarding, and
www.skiresorts.com, providing news and information about winter
resorts.
</P>
<P>
   Design Your Own Hotel Room in London
</P>
<P>
   Ever check into a hotel and wish your room were blue instead of
yellow? A new hotel in London will offer guests the opportunity to
play interior decorator and change the color and mood of their
rooms with the spin of a lighting dial. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Guest rooms at St. Martins Lane, the latest hotel to bring
together the talents of the designer Philippe Starck and the
hotelier Ian Schrager, could be described as cool white envelopes.
With a flip of a bedside dial that contains the full spectrum of
colors, guests can change the color _ and brightness _ of the
reading lights over the beds, which are strong enough to alter the
shade of the room. Since rooms have floor-to-ceiling windows, color
preferences of the guests can be seen from the outside, and the
hotel's glass exterior will continuously, if subtly, change hue. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 204-room hotel in Covent Garden, which is scheduled to open
on Tuesday, is one of two hotels Schrager plans for London. Room
rates at the St. Martins Lane, in a former office building, start
at $200. It will offer a 24-hour gym, 24-hour brasserie, video art
installations in the elevators, a supervised children's play area
and a branch of Asia de Cuba, the restaurant in Schrager's Morgans
hotel in New York.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
