<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOAH-WYLE-IN-ER-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM `ER' TO KOSOVO: NOAH WYLE'S SUMMER OF '99
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes black-and-white photos and color slides of Noah Wyle in
``ER.'' 
 &HT;    By CHRISTOPHER LOUDON  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Most network stars spend the summer months either padding their
resumes with movie roles or retreating to an exotic hideaway.
 &HT;    Not Noah Wyle.
 &HT;    ``I had a really unbelievable summer,'' says ``ER's'' resident
charmer, who spent the first two weeks of his hiatus in war-ravaged
Kosovo.
 &HT;    ``I was invited by an organization called Doctors of the World
to go to southern Serbia, visit refugee camps and observe the work
these doctors were doing.
 &HT;    ``I spent the bulk of my time in a camp called Senicose, which
had about 12,000 people in it, and only six doctors caring for
them. It was unbelievable. I've never seen such acts of heroism in
aid of such acts of senseless brutality.
 &HT;    ``I came back shaken to the core,'' says Wyle, who returned home
to extend some altruism of his own.
 &HT;    Back in 1991, three years before he earned international fame as
``ER's'' dashing Dr. John Carter, he helped establish Los Angeles'
non-profit Blank Theater Company, a showcase for neophyte
playwrights aged 18 or under. The company recently staged its
eighth annual Young Playwright's Festival.
 &HT;    ``We choose ten plays and fly kids out here. We cast their plays
with professional actors, most of whom are recognizable faces from
film and television,'' Wyle says.
 &HT;    ``Then we bring in professional directors,'' he adds, noting
that among this year's visiting directors were Gary Marshall
(``Pretty Woman,'' 1990) and his sister Penny Marshall (``Big,''
1988.)
 &HT;    Wyle seems delighted at the prospect of helping to shape the
next Tennessee Williams or Wendy Wasserstein, and says the festival
has already given about 80 young playwrights their first taste of
professional experience.
 &HT;    ``That's pretty gratifying,'' says Wyle, who was himself
provided a leg up by his stepfather, who became his artistic mentor
and helped shape his creative ambitions.
 &HT;    Wyle was born and raised in Hollywood, and he was just six years
old when his parents were divorced. When his mother re-married,
Wyle became stepson to a film producer and restorer who raised him
on a diet of Hollywood classics. , The two watched James Stewart's
Hitchcock films repeatedly, and Wyle also fell in love with the
films of Spencer Tracy, Errol Flynn and Charlie Chaplin.
 &HT;    ``Those are the people I was taught to look up to,'' Wyle says,
adding that these early lessons would eventually serve him well.
 &HT;    After struggling to gain a foothold in films, taking small but
meaty parts in films such as ``A Few Good Men'' (1992) and ``Swing
Kids'' (1993), he was offered a role that James Stewart himself
would have felt comfortable with.
 &HT;    The part was in a risky and ambitious new series set inside a
Chicago emergency ward, and Wyle took on the role of med student
John Carter.
 &HT;    When ``ER'' hit the airwaves, it had been more than 20 years
since ``Marcus Welby, M.D.'' cracked the Neilsen top 10. Medical
dramas were long gone from prime time, and television doctors
appeared, for the most part, in aspirin commercials.
 &HT;    ``I signed a four-year contract, fully expecting ER to last for
about seven weeks,'' laughs Wyle.
 &HT;    From the outset, it was Carter's naivete that appealed most to
him.
 &HT;    ``(The character) was starting out at such a low level of
proficiency. He was either going to wash out or become an excellent
physician, or maybe a bit of both. I think we've charted those
waters pretty carefully over the last five years.''
 &HT;    Those five years made Wyle a wealthy man.
 &HT;    While he prefers not to discuss his income, one can assume that
contract re-negotiations, which will keep him in the show through a
seventh season, have netted him about the same as co-star Eriq
LaSalle: $27 million.
 &HT;    Wyle, adopting his traditional wet-behind-the-ears mode, says
that it's more important to him that his return to the show will
provide an opportunity for personal growth both for himself and for
his character.
 &HT;    ``When I started on the show I was extremely intimidated by the
actors I was working with, and tried not to call attention to
myself. I think that's exactly how John Carter approached his work.
Like John, I've spent the past five years searching out good role
models, looking for guidance, and asking lots of questions,'' Wyle
says.
 &HT;    ``I never thought I'd reach professor emeritus status, but now,
going into year six, I feel like I'm a member of the old guard,''
he adds.
 &HT;    ``And that's how Carter's feeling now that he's a second-year
resident and is sort of calling the shots around the ER ... I guess
it's true that we've matured at the exact same rate.''
 &HT;    Wyle is also anticipating an exciting year beyond ``ER.''
 &HT;    When he re-signed with the show two years ago, his contract came
hand-in-hand with a Warner Brothers development deal. So the actor
is reviewing film scripts, two of which are being ``groomed for
development,'' and he is considering a television series written by
a friend.
 &HT;    ``We've got our fingers crossed,'' he says.
 &HT;    On the homefront, Wyle's prospects seem equally bright _ he
proposed to his girlfriend on Valentine's Day and purchased a
rambling ranch previously owned by actress Bo Derek (``Bolero,''
1984).
 &HT;    With his financial, professional and personal futures all in
apparent order, Wyle says he has few worries.
 &HT;    He used to fret about a television ailment known as ``Ted
Danson's Syndrome,'' wherein an actor is forever linked to a
particular character on a long-running show, and finds it hard to
make a mark in any subsequent endeavor.
 &HT;    ``But last year I looked around and said: `Why would I want to
parlay this into something else so quickly?' This is a
once-in-a-lifetime opportunity,'' Wyle says.
 &HT;    ``This type of show comes around once in a career, and I really
want to play my hand out the way it's been dealt to me until it's
done.''
 &HT;    Wyle still struggles, however, with the need to reconcile his
shyness and the urge to embrace the rewards of celebrity.
 &HT;    ``It's a conflict I grapple with on a daily basis: my desire to
have solace and time to recharge my batteries and the fear that I'm
becoming a recluse and cutting myself off from the exact stimuli I
should be involved in. I have a tendency to want to go home and
spend time with my friend and my dogs and read my books.
 &HT;    ``But at the same time, when you're on a show like this, the
invitations pour in to meet such exciting people and become
involved in such exciting projects ...
 &HT;    ``For me, the trick is striking a balance between what your
instincts are telling you to do and what your head thinks you
should do,'' Wyle says.
 &HT;    ``It's hard. It really is.''
 &HT;    As Jimmy Stewart once said, ``It's a wonderful life.''
 &HT;     c.1999 Christopher Loudon  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.)
