<HEADER>
A4917 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e BC-THE-MAN-SHOW-STARBEAT     08-30 1370
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THE-MAN-SHOW-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
56 MILLION VIEWERS CAN'T BE WRONG: COMEDY CENTRAL HITS PAYDIRT
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes black-and-white photos and color slides of the cast of
``The Man Show.'' 
  By CHARLES STRUM  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   One day long ago, before fire or the wheel, ancient man slipped
on the prehistoric equivalent of a banana peel and fell on his
fanny.
</P>
<P>
   And another ancient man laughed.
</P>
<P>
   Thus did the funny bone evolve, tickled by ridicule, nourished
by hostility and cradled by a measure of relief that it was the
other guy who took the fall.
</P>
<P>
   What's changed since then?
</P>
<P>
   Not much, except that the cable channel Comedy Central has
discovered the secret of eternal yucks: keep an endless supply of
banana peels on hand and be confident that humanity will be ever
eager to watch the next poor schnook take that fateful misstep.
</P>
<P>
   Pratfalls, fraternity pranks, wise guys, goofballs, misfits: the
human condition seen through cracked eyeglasses.
</P>
<P>
   If it makes you cringe with modesty or self-recognition, Comedy
Central will find a way to examine it.
</P>
<P>
   Behold the animated foul-mouthed urchins of ``South Park'' or
the perverse high school corridors of ``Strangers With Candy.''
</P>
<P>
   Stepping well beyond the boundaries crossed long ago by
``Saturday Night Live,'' the late-night roster on Comedy Central
ventures deep into the dark side of vaudeville, mining the
absurdity of everything from flatulence to incest.
</P>
<P>
   For these brave men and women on comedy's frontier, only
squeamishness is a dirty word. The network has freshened its
lineup, with new original programming as well as new episodes of
popular standbys like ``The Daily Show With Jon Stewart,''
``Upright Citizens Brigade'' and ``Dr. Katz, Professional
Therapist.''
</P>
<P>
   Two new series, ``The Man Show'' and ``Comedy Central's Vs.,''
capitalize on smirking, winking and nudging.
</P>
<P>
   Few double-entendres go unexplored.
</P>
<P>
   ``Comedy Central Pre-sents,'' a showcase for stand-up comedians,
had its series premiere this summer, and a fourth newcomer, ``Frank
Leaves for the Orient,'' about a dissatisfied guy in his 30's who
runs off to Japan to become an English teacher, began airing in
August.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Vs.'' (pronounced versus), the host, Gregg Proops (of ABC's
``Whose Line Is It Anyway?''), is a lascivious Wink Martindale.
</P>
<P>
   In this simple game show two culturally mismatched teams compete
for cash by answering questions in the manner of ``Win Ben Stein's
Money,'' one of the channel's most successful shows.
</P>
<P>
   Categories might include ``I just diet in your arms last night''
or ``Come on Shania, ride my twain.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus you have three-member teams like soccer moms vs. the
dominatrixes. (Or, as Mr. Proops says in one of his naughty asides,
``It's seat belts and Kool Whip versus choke chains and
bullwhips.'')
</P>
<P>
   Also Harvard graduates vs. community college students, bikers
vs. prison guards, and used car salesmen vs. Consumer Reports
writers.
</P>
<P>
   But it is ``The Man Show'' that has become Comedy Central's new
summer centerpiece, featuring Ben Stein's co-host, Jimmy Kimmel.
</P>
<P>
   How to describe it?
</P>
<P>
   Comedy Central's own public relations department calls it ``an
unapologetic look at the things men like, do and think.''
</P>
<P>
   And what might these things be?
</P>
<P>
   They are, not necessarily in order of preference, eating,
drinking and watching nubile young women in skimpy outfits jump on
trampolines.
</P>
<P>
   A kind of lodge meeting for men who feel Oprah and feminism have
too much influence in American culture, ``The Man Show,'' a happy
hour with edge, is the invention of Kimmel and Adam Carolla, its
unabashed-chauvinist hosts.
</P>
<P>
   The show has ambush interviews, sketch comedy and a signature
bit featuring a piano-playing singer of bawdy songs named Billy
Foster, known as the Fox, whose remarkably wide gullet allows him
to chug a mug of beer in one gulp.
</P>
<P>
   As Kimmel put it in an interview, ``Basically he drinks beer for
a living.''
</P>
<P>
   This would seem to play to one of Comedy Central's strengths, a
market in which 63 percent of the audience is between 18 and 49,
almost 60 percent of it male.
</P>
<P>
   The eight-year-old network, which has 56 million subscribers,
has just reported its 15th consecutive quarter of full-day ratings
growth. Its prime-time ratings rose 40 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   The man behind the curtain at Comedy Central is Larry Divney, a
56-year-old broadcast-advertising executive who was named president
and chief executive in February.
</P>
<P>
   A true son of the 1950s who grew up with the last gasp of
network radio, Divney is ``not much of a sitcom fan, but I love
comedy,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like most men I've got the remote in my hand.''
</P>
<P>
   As comedy heroes, he cites Ernie Kovacs, George Carlin (``If I
could be anybody, I'd want to be George Carlin'') and David
Letterman.
</P>
<P>
   Chosen in part because he is an insider in a network with a
singular mission _ he has worked at Comedy Central since its
creation in 1991 _ Divney says he would be more of a ``business
president'' than the maximum leader at the creative core.
</P>
<P>
   In succeeding Doug Herzog, who left last year to become the head
of programming for the Fox network, Divney says, ``The best tribute
we could give Doug is to take it to another level.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to be thought of as whoopee cushion humor,''
Divney says, endorsing a preference for the ``more satirical look''
embodied by ``The Daily Show,'' the network's half-hour sendup of
news programs in general and sanctimonious news programs in
particular.
</P>
<P>
   Or by the often surreal sketch comedy of the ``Upright Citizens
Brigade,'' whose members have ``no government ties but unlimited
resources'' to create chaos.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm someone who likes to laugh at life,'' he says. ``I don't
find Littleton funny. I don't find vandalism funny and property
damage funny. I find people funny. Humor helps get us through a
lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Can you go too far?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, but we don't mean to be mean-spirited,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``The line moves. The environment changes.''
</P>
<P>
   That environment may be changing with the barroom humor of ``The
Man Show.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to do stuff that makes us laugh and appeal to a lot of
guys,'' Kimmel said from Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   At 31, he is a full generation younger than Divney, but the two
seem to share sensibilities, a kind of Mad magazine state of mind.
</P>
<P>
   Kimmel, who grew up in Las Vegas and attended college there and
in Phoenix, left school for radio in Seattle, where he began to
develop characters like Jimmy the Sports Guy, ``me doing sports in
a very aggressive way.''
</P>
<P>
   With the deadpan Ben Stein, Kimmel has honed the smart-aleck
persona that runs like a theme through many of Comedy Central's
top-rated shows.
</P>
<P>
   Yet somehow the banana peel in its many forms is at the heart of
Kimmel's sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest influence on his comedy, he says wistfully, was his
boyhood pal Cleto.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd stay up all night sending pizza to people's houses.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Charles Strum is a New York-based writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.)
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``The Man Show,'' consult Comedy
Central's official Website at www.comedycentral.com. And don't
forget to visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-99 1925EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
