<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 19:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4918 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-AIDSBLACKS31-COX     08-30 0481
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDSBLACKS31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Black AIDS rate 10 times white
 &HT;    By Lillian Lee Kim
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ African-Americans are nearly 10 times more likely than
whites to develop AIDS _ and to die from the disease.
</P>
<P>
   New national statistics released Monday by the Centers for
Disease Control and Prevention confirm that blacks continue to lead
the AIDS epidemic with alarmingly high rates of new infections,
AIDS cases and deaths.
</P>
<P>
   The situation is especially dire in Georgia. Of the 8,776
Georgians living with AIDS, 5,686, or 65 percent, are black,
according to the CDC. Nationally, African-Americans represent 40
percent of the 271,327 people with AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   The CDC presented its figures at the National HIV Prevention
Conference in Atlanta, which it co-sponsored.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a tremendous crisis impacting the African-American
community,'' said Cornelius Baker, executive director of the
National Association of People With AIDS. Baker called the AIDS
epidemic ``one of the worst catastrophes since slavery'' to affect
blacks.
</P>
<P>
   Two studies presented at the conference indicate that a major
factor is bisexuality among black men. These studies challenge the
popular perception that many black women acquire HIV, the virus
that causes AIDS, through injecting illegal drugs. Instead,
researchers say, many black women are being infected through
heterosexual sex with black men who also have sex with men.
</P>
<P>
   One study, conducted at gay venues in New York City, found that
20 percent of black men said they had sex with men and women. In
comparison, 12 percent of Hispanics and 4 percent of white men
reported bisexual behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Another study, involving 1,001 HIV-positive black men in
Michigan, found that 36 percent of those who had sex with men also
had sex with women.
</P>
<P>
   ``The heavy stigma against homosexuality in the African-American
community leads to bisexuality,'' Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   Of young gay men, blacks have the highest prevalence of HIV,
according to another study.
</P>
<P>
   As many researchers and policy-makers have pointed out, poor
access to health care among blacks also is a problem. Because many
HIV-positive blacks can't get the costly drugs that can control the
virus, they're more likely than whites to develop AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   And many African-Americans still harbor deep distrust of the
U.S. health care system, due to the infamous Tuskegee study, in
which black men with syphilis were left untreated for more than 40
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The legacy of Tuskegee looms large when it comes to HIV and
other sexually transmitted diseases,'' said Dr. Helene Gayle, who
heads the CDC's HIV prevention center.
</P>
<P>
   Of the CDC's $600 million-plus HIV prevention budget, $137
million is earmarked for programs specifically aimed at
African-Americans, Gayle said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
