<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4929 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e KEVIN-BACON-IN-STIR-OF-E     08-30 1273
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
LIFE AFTER `FOOTLOOSE': KEVIN BACON GOES SUPERNATURAL
</HEADLINE>
 KEVIN-BACON-IN-STIR-OF-ECHOES-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Kevin Bacon in the upcoming film ``Stir
of Echoes.'')
 By IAN SPELLING  
 &HT;    Kevin Bacon is waiting for a sign.
 &HT;    A knock on the ceiling.
 &HT;    A rush of cold air.
 &HT;    A door that blows open, suddenly...
 &HT;    ``I've never had any kind of psychic experience,'' says the
``Footloose'' star. ``I've never seen a ghost, never had anything
paranormal happen to me, but I'm totally open to it. If there are
spirits out there that want to contact me and say, `Hi,' ... I'm
for it... I'll sign autographs.''
 &HT;    Bacon shot to fame in 1984 in the musical ``Footloose'' (1984),
but today he's promoting a scary new supernatural thriller called
``Stir of Echoes.''
 &HT;    The actor hasn't entirely made up his mind about the whole grand
subject of the afterlife, but he says he'll stay tuned.
 &HT;    ``I'm not a firm disbeliever. I just haven't had anything happen
and I need to be convinced,'' he adds.
 &HT;    Tom Witzky, Bacon's character in his new movie, needs
convincing, too. And during the course of the movie, he becomes
entirely convinced.
 &HT;    A working-class hero who lives with his wife Maggie (Kathryn
Erbe) and young son Jake (Zachary David Cope) in a modest Chicago
house, Tom agrees to let his sister-in-law Lisa (Illeana Douglas)
hypnotize him.
 &HT;    Soon after, he experiences horrific visions of an unspeakable
crime, visions that nearly push him over the edge.
 &HT;    Given the success of ``The Blair Witch Project,'' ``The
Haunting'' and ``The Sixth Sense,'' the timing seems perfect for
``Stir of Echoes,'' which is based on Richard Matheson's 1958 novel
of the same name and which will be released September 10.
 &HT;    Bacon puts down down his leather-bound Filofax, doffs his black
sunglasses and lies back on the couch at his publicist's Manhattan
office to talk about ghosts, rock 'n' roll and marriage.
 &HT;    ``What I was drawn to in `Stir of Echoes' was that if you took
out the ghost and the murder mystery aspects, I'd still be
interested in this character, a guy at a crossroads,'' says Bacon,
 &HT;    ``On one side he sees his youth, his rock and roll, his chance
to live out his dream all dissipating, and on the other side he
loves his wife and kid, and feels he's a good father. That was
interesting, right there,'' he adds.
 &HT;    In one particularly disturbing scene, Bacon feverishly digs up
the family's backyard in a manic scene which echoes Jack
Nicholson's lunatic performance in ``The Shining.''
 &HT;    Bacon smiles at the comparison.
 &HT;    ``This may be my downfall, but I always like to err on the side
of being a little too big, of pushing things a little too far,'' he
says. ``I think, often times, film actors were just told to `dial
it down, dial it down.''
 &HT;    ``I'll look at a performance and think, `Wake the f--- up! Do a
little acting. Do something.'
 &HT;    ``I want to see some semblance of a performance if I'm paying my
money to see something. I tend to appreciate actors who go over the
top.''
 &HT;    Bacon rubs his goatee and runs his fingers through his hair.
 &HT;    ``I was very lucky on `Stir of Echoes.' From the very first
meeting (writer-director) Dave Koepp said, `I want to push it. I
want to test the limits.'''
 &HT;    Truth be told, ``Stir of Echoes'' is a typical Bacon film in
that it's another atypical choice in a career of atypical choices.
 &HT;    Now 41 years old, Bacon's resume includes ``Animal House''
(1978), ``Friday the 13th'' (1980), ``Diner'' (1982), ``Footloose''
(1984), ``JFK'' (1991), ``Apollo 13'' (1995) and ``Wild Things''
(1998), as well as a batch of independent films, assorted stage
appearances, a thriving music career and a 1996 stint as a
director.
 &HT;    ``As far as the films go, I've always just gone back and found
these little independents that have something I want to do as an
actor,'' he says.
 &HT;    Later this year Bacon can be seen in the family film ``My Dog
Skip,'' and he is currently filming a big-budget popcorn flick,
``The Hollow Man,'' with Elizabeth Shue and Josh Brolin.
 &HT;    ```Hollow Man' is probably a good film for me to do, but I also
need to do `Digging to China' (1998) and `Telling Lies in America''
(1998) and `My Dog Skip.'''
 &HT;    Beyond mixing studio and independent features, Bacon tackles
villains and saints, action and comedy, drama and thrillers.
 &HT;    Does anything scare him?
 &HT;    ``There's nothing I'd be afraid to do,'' he says. ``Some things
might scare me, actually, but I wouldn't not do something because
it scares me.''
 &HT;    Bacon keeps busy when he is not making films. Off the set, he
has spent the last few years performing and recording with his
older brother Michael in a band called The Bacon Brothers, which
will release a new album and go on tour early next year.
 &HT;    As for his marriage, Bacon and actress Kyra Sedgwick have been
together for nearly a decade and are the parents of two children.
The family divides its time between homes in Manhattan and
Connecticut.
 &HT;    ``The last thing Kyra and I want to do is hold ourselves up as
poster children for a happy, healthy marriage,'' Bacon says. ``Life
for us is as difficult as it is for anybody.
 &HT;    ``We're a two-career family and I don't care what the two
careers are, that makes it a struggle. Kyra and I just lucked out.
We found each other.''
 &HT;    As the conversation reaches an end, Bacon can practically smell
the ``Footloose'' and ``Six Degrees of Kevin Bacon'' questions in
the air.
 &HT;    After all, ``Footloose'' remains Bacon's biggest hit and ``Six
Degrees'' -- a game that posits the theory that everyone in
Hollywood is removed from Bacon by no more than six people -- is
not only a water cooler favorite in Tinseltown but now a board
game.
 &HT;    Bacon, however, is caught a little off-guard by the question _
if he could jettison either ``Footloose'' or ``Six Degrees'' from
his life, which would he drop?
 &HT;    ``I'm grateful I had a `Footloose' in my life,'' he says. ``It
had a tremendous impact on my career, but the movie came out more
than 15 years ago. I have worked since then.
 &HT;    ```Six Degrees' is more of an odd piece of pop culture. I had
nothing to do with it. It just goes along. It doesn't bother me and
I don't work it.''
 &HT;    And the answer to the question?
 &HT;    ``If one of them had to go away?'' he says, smiling. ``I'd let
the game go. The work is work, and I've got to live with what I put
out there.''
 c.1999 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
