<SLUG> BC-HEATHER-LOCKLEAR-IN-SPIN-CITY-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEATHER LOCKLEAR VS. THE TELETUBBY
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes black-and-white photos and color slides of Heather
Locklear in ``Spin City.'' 
  By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Heather Locklear is one of the most famous blondes in La La
Land, but she can't compete with Laa-Laa, a Teletubby.
 &HT;    Ava, her 18-month-old daughter, doesn't care if her mother is
watching one of three final episodes of ``Melrose Place.''
 &HT;    She wants to watch her Teletubby tape. And she wants it now.
 &HT;    Locklear's husband, rock star Richie Sambora, defers to both
females.
 &HT;    It's Monday night at their Malibu home, and mother and child are
at odds.
 &HT;    But this ain't no ``Melrose Place'' _ and there's no mud
wrestling here.
 &HT;    ``Honey, mommy wants to watch grown-up TV,'' says Locklear, who
as Amanda Woodward on ``Melrose Place'' could handle any crisis.
 &HT;    She's brought down the mob, survived a helicopter crash, a fatal
disease and a few bad color jobs.
 &HT;    But dealing with a two-year-old _ now there's a challenge.
 &HT;    ``Laa-Laa, Laa-Laa, Laa-Laa,'' cries Ava.
 &HT;    Whereas Amanda Woodward might have spent seven years in
television's alternate universe, slinking around her apartment with
a bottle of wine in one hand and a guy's tie in the other, Locklear
herself lives in a simple world of diapers and dinosaurs.
 &HT;    ``Now the man in my life is Barney,'' she says, referring to the
prehistoric lizard preferred by infants everywhere.
 &HT;    ``I can't believe the mother in me who tells the baby, `We have
to switch this off because you're not learning anything.'''
 &HT;    Locklear has learned that there are second, third and fourth
acts on television.
 &HT;    Barely had she taken a breath after ``Melrose'' ended last May
when she accepted a role opposite Michael J. Fox on the political
comedy series ``Spin City.''
 &HT;    Fox is a longtime fan of Locklear's, and when the show's
producers were casting about for the part of the campaign manager,
his vote went to Locklear. (The two will team up as co-presenters
for the 51st Annual Emmy Awards, on September 12.)
 &HT;    Locklear says that when she was offered the ``Spin City'' part,
she was taken aback.
 &HT;    ``It was a little terrifying because we do the show in front of
a live audience,'' she says, adding that she has not always lived
by the showbiz dictum ``Never let them see you sweat.''
 &HT;    ``I have sweated. There has been a little dry mouth,'' she
admits.
 &HT;    Locklear has been a network staple since 1981, with starring
roles in dramas including ``TJ Hooker,'' ``Dynasty'' and ``Melrose
Place.''
 &HT;    But catch her on a rare night at her LA home and one thing is
clear: she is not a vixen. She just played one on TV.
 &HT;    Sounding like a typical harried mom, she apologizes profusely
for being just three minutes late, and concedes that before she
accepted the role in ``Spin City,'' she felt few qualms about the
end of ``Melrose Place.''
 &HT;    ``I knew in my heart that it was time to move on. We had a good
run. I can't complain.''
 &HT;    Her Amanda character goes down in television history as one of
the baddest of the bad girls. And the skirts she wore on the show
will be remembered for their brevity.
 &HT;    ``You know who really started that trend? The actresses on
`Knots Landing.' They wore suits where you seriously hoped that
there wasn't a strong breeze that day. I guess I don't care who
started it. I got to wear some fabulous outfits,`` Locklear says.
 &HT;    Born in Los Angeles in 1961, she was a quiet, shy girl who
harbored secret ambitions to act. As a UCLA student, she perfected
the California surfer girl look and was cast in a series of
national commercials.
 &HT;    Then, in 1982, she played a police officer on the crime series
``TJ Hooker,'' a show she says she enjoyed working on save for the
tight polyester uniform which she was forced to wear and in which
she sweated away several pounds.
 &HT;    After the show ended in 1987, Locklear signed up for
``Dynasty,'' the long-running series in which she played man-eater
Sammy Jo Carrington.
 &HT;    On one ``very, very strange'' episode, she says, her part called
for her to mud-wrestle a rival, played by actress Emma Samms.
 &HT;    ``We fought in specially sterilized mud, which supposedly could
breathe and had air bubbles in it. That's so we wouldn't drown when
shoving each other's faces in it,'' she sighs.
 &HT;    When Locklear joined the cast of ``Melrose Place'' as a special
guest star in 1993, ratings jumped 50 percent and producer Aaron
Spelling signed her to a long-term contract.
 &HT;    ``I had been working for 20 years, but `Melrose' just catapulted
me to a different level of fame. Young guys would come up to me and
say, `In Heather We Trust' or they would bow down at my feet and
say, `We're not worthy,''' Locklear marvels.
 &HT;    ``Inside I was, like, `Wow, I can't believe this is happening.'
I also kept my head on my shoulders realizing that along with the
ups come the downs,'' she adds.
 &HT;    One of the downs, Locklear says, included a dismal marriage to
rocker Tommy Lee, Motley Crue's tattooed drummer.
 &HT;    When the two divorced, Locklear decided to live the single life
for a while.
 &HT;    Then along came Sambora, who plays guitar for the band Bon Jovi.
 &HT;    ``It's funny: I met Richie four years earlier and I knew he was
the right guy, but I was married. One little glitch,'' Locklear
says, laughing.
 &HT;    After her divorce, a friend set her up with the musician.
 &HT;    ``I clearly remember our first date. He kept trying to get me to
be alone with him. We were in New York and he kept saying, `Come to
my room.' I was like, `I'll meet you in the bar. I'll meet you with
friends.' He said, 'No, why don't you just come up to my room. I'm
not going to do anything.'''
 &HT;    She agreed.
 &HT;    ``He had a huge bunch of roses waiting and he was a total
gentleman,'' Locklear says.
 &HT;    A few months later, she proposed.
 &HT;    ``I think I proposed ... And he proposed with the ring.''
 &HT;    Five years later, the two are enjoying the role of new parents
as well as the everyday chores that are part and parcel of their
lives.
 &HT;    ``Tonight the big event is going to the supermarket for turkey
burgers,'' Locklear says, adding that there will be no mob scene in
the produce aisle.
 &HT;    ``People in my neighborhood see me all the time, and they could
care less,'' she adds.
 &HT;    ``I'm just a mom with no makeup and her hair up in a ponytail.
I'm just like everyone else.''
 &HT;    Another day in La La Land.
 &HT;     c.1999 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Cindy Pearlman is a Chicago-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
