<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ACLU-BUSH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACLU, ENVIRONMENTAL GROUPS SUE BUSH OVER PROTEST 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY WALT 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The American Civil Liberties Union and two
environmental groups sued Gov. George W. Bush and the Texas
Department of Public Safety on Monday, alleging that
environmentalists' free-speech rights were violated when they were
arrested earlier this year for demonstrating in front of the
Governor's Mansion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Constitution does not stop at the public sidewalk next to
the governor's mansion,'' said Rick Abraham, executive director of
the environmental group Texans United, and one of those arrested.
</P>
<P>
   He said the humiliation of being thrown in jail, strip-searched
and forced to sleep on the floor in a crowded jail ``is not
something people should have to go through just because they want
to exercise their constitutional right to disagree with what a
governor, a politician, a presidential hopeful wants to shove down
our throats.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the sidewalk around the mansion for years has been a site
of public protests, DPS troopers earlier this year arrested the
environmentalists on charges of obstructing a sidewalk after they
refused to move to a designated protest site across the street.
</P>
<P>
   The charges later were dismissed by Travis County Attorney Ken
Oden. Oden, however, said the four environmentalists who were
arrested could have been charged with a lesser city violation _
failure to obey a lawful order. DPS, however, did not refile the
charges against the protesters.
</P>
<P>
   The ACLU and environmentalists contend that the policy was
implemented once Bush decided to run for president as a means of
silencing critics who contend Bush's environmental record is weak.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision on how to handle protests at the Governor's
Mansion are made by the Department of Public Safety,'' said Bush
spokesman Ray Sullivan. ``DPS wants to protect the safety of
pedestrians and protesters around the Governor's Mansion. They've
been concerned that, when protesters block the sidewalks or rights
of way, that may encourage people to walk in the street or
otherwise avoid the protest, putting them in harm's way.''
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan also said the governor's staff is ``curious whether the
ACLU will include President Clinton in the lawsuit, since the White
House also has a designated protest area (outside the White House)
and more stringent rules than the DPS.''
</P>
<P>
   DPS spokesperson Tela Mange said the agency has not seen a copy
of the lawsuit but it has a policy of not commenting on pending
lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   She acknowledged, however, that DPS has no written rules on
protesting on the sidewalk around the Governor's Mansion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are asking the court to secure the most basic of
fundamental rights _ that of political expression in a public
forum,'' said David Kahne, an ACLU attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Because the governor's office and DPS have given conflicting
signals on the policy on protesting outside the mansion and because
``the police can make up, enforce and change rules against
expressing opinions,'' the police can arrest individuals on the
basis of the message they are carrying, Kahne added.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit seeks no monetary award; it was filed in Travis
County. The plaintiffs include the ACLU, Texans United and
Downwinders at Risk.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
