<P>
   Here are the business news stories the Los Angeles Daily News
plans to move for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs
of August 31 and thereafter. The stories will carry the ``f''
financial news category code unless otherwise noted. For questions
about stories, contact Jeremy Bagott at the Daily News, (818)
713-3702.
</P>
<P>
   ARCO-MERGER (Los Angeles) _ Arco shareholders overwhelmingly
approved a proposed merger with British petroleum giant BP Amoco
Monday, but several key questions remain about the merger's effect
on Arco's Los Angeles headquarters and the company's 3,000
employees in the region. By Jason Takenouchi.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in the ``f'' financial and ``n'' California news
file.)
</P>
<P>
   ESPN-STORE (Los Angeles) _ The Walt Disney Co. pulled the plug
Monday on its trio of ESPN Stores, the entertainment giant's
two-year-old venture into sports retailing. Disney, which
originally planned to open hundreds of ESPN stores as a way of
taking advantage of the powerful cable network's brand name, will
``redirect'' its efforts toward its two-outlet ESPN Zone
restaurants and the ESPN Internet operations. The move makes sense
due to the difficult of attracting free-spending males between ages
18 and 34 _ the key ESPN viewer _ browsing at shopping centers,
according to sports consultant David M. Carter. By Dave McNary.
(Will move in the ``f'' financial and ``s'' sports news file.)
</P>
