<SLUG> BC-BUSH-SUIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE RULES BUSH NEED NOT SUBMIT TO DEPOSITION IN WHISTLEBLOWER
CASE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Lawyers for a fired state regulator cannot force
Gov. George W. Bush to submit to a deposition, despite conflicting
accounts about Bush's role in the official's dismissal, a district
judge ruled Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General John Cornyn, who convinced District Judge John
K. Dietz to quash Bush's deposition subpoena, portrayed the ruling
as a victory for common sense. Cornyn said Bush simply doesn't know
much about the events that led up to the termination of Texas
Funeral Service Commission Director Eliza May, and those who know
more haven't been questioned yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has no personal knowledge of the facts in this case,''
Cornyn said of Bush. ``This was their opportunity to come forward
and present (contradictory) evidence and they didn't do it,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   May, who filed the civil lawsuit against her former employer in
March under the Texas Whistle Blowers Act, claims Bush collaborated
with commission members to illegally oust her in February, but she
didn't include the Republican governor as a defendant.
</P>
<P>
   May contends that after several high-level meetings and
communications _ some involving Bush's top staff _ various
officials carried out an unlawful ``conspiracy'' to appease
co-defendant Service Corporation International Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston-based funeral company's top executives are longtime
political supporters of the governor and his father, former
President Bush, and corporate officials have acknowledged they
applied political pressure in response to regulators' tactics. But
they adamantly contend that's their First Amendment right.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're glad we finally got some relief from the ... innuendo
and rumor and speculation,'' Cornyn said, portraying the failed
attempt to force Bush's testimony as a publicity stunt designed to
capitalize on Bush's notoriety as a GOP presidential candidate. In
recent weeks, several national news organizations have joined Texas
media in covering May's charges against Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it were a search for the truth, Ms. May's lawyers would
have taken depositions from the 50 or so other witnesses _ even the
people she was complaining about in the meetings _ before she tried
to take the governor's deposition,'' Cornyn said.
</P>
<P>
   May's attorneys didn't rule out an appeal of Dietz's ruling,
which came after five hours of testimony and arguments. But they
said they would soon begin taking depositions of key aides to Bush
to begin developing their case.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not about getting Gov. Bush. This is a whistle blower
lawsuit. It involves a state employee's report of illegal activity,
and as a result of that, she was fired,'' said attorney Derek
Howard.
</P>
<P>
   He said questions persist regarding how much Bush knew about the
1998 regulatory spat between the commission and SCI. Bush submitted
a sworn affidavit saying he knew no ``relevant'' facts about the
dispute or May's dismissal, but May's attorney's labeled it
``false'' and ``inadequate'' because he didn't deny all knowledge
of relevant events.
</P>
<P>
   ``The judge said we can get the evidence we need from lower
level people, and we intend to do that,'' said May attorney Charles
Herring Jr.
</P>
<P>
   In a bid to discredit the plaintiff's underlying accusation _
that SCI improperly influenced the commission and perhaps others to
oust May _ Cornyn turned over newly sworn statements from the
commission members, past and present, who voted to fire her. All
said they were dissatisfied with her job performance and denied
acting in response to political pressure from Bush, his staff, SCI
or others.
</P>
<P>
   But May, a former Democratic Party official, took the stand
briefly to insist she was railroaded out of the job she was given
in August 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question about it. I felt pressure'' to drop her
investigation of SCI, she said, adding she never heard directly
from Bush.
</P>
<P>
   May said Bush appointees on the commission and Bush's top staff
exerted the pressure, ostensibly to curtail a still-unresolved
investigation which alleged that two SCI-owned funeral homes
employed embalmers who didn't have the correct licenses.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
