<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-DENNIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DENNIS SKIRTS COAST OF N.C. ON ITS WAY OUT TO SEA 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Will be updated.) 
 (nk) 
 By EMILY YELLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, N.C. _ Hurricane Dennis continued north and east
just off the coast of North Carolina on Monday afternoon,
apparently sparing the state the kind of damage it suffered in
three other hurricanes since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in the southern coastal part of the state began
re-opening barrier islands that had been evacuated Sunday night.
Northern coastal communities remained hunkered down late Monday
afternoon against the rain and wind from the storm, but seemed to
have avoided a direct hit.
</P>
<P>
   So far, all along the southeastern coast of the United States,
the eye of Hurricane Dennis has come close but not made landfall.
Forecasters predicted it would continue farther east and out to sea
Monday evening, with its eye continuing to avoid the coast.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Jarrell, director of the National Hurricane Center in
Miami, predicted the hurricane would ``come to a screeching halt
out there'' Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, heaven only knows what it's going to do,'' Jarrell said.
``But we think it'll probably sit there for one, two or three days,
and then almost anything is possible after that.''
</P>
<P>
   Although no deaths were directly attributed to the storm as it
blew along the coast here Sunday night and Monday morning, a
head-on collision which killed two people Monday morning in Onslow
County north of Wilmington was blamed on 60 mph winds and heavy
rain associated with the storm. The storm did not appear to have
caused any major structural damage in the southern part of North
Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clontz, of the New Hanover County Emergency Management
Agency in Wilmington, said, ``We're thinking we're very lucky we
only got a glancing blow, compared to the three storms we've had in
the past few years. The rest of the state seems to be fairing very
well just like we are.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems the whole country made out. It's like Dennis said,
`How close can I get to land and not cause any damage?''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The storm cut electrical power to 60,000 people in the state,
according to the North Carolina Division of Emergency Management.
The disruptions stretched as far inland as the Raleigh area, where
about 10,000 customers were without power at one point. ``As far as
damage in the state,'' said Bill Furney of the North Carolina
Division of Emergency Management, ``we have a few roads out, and
bridges closed.''
</P>
<P>
   A state of emergency and a state of disaster, declared Sunday by
Gov. James B. Hunt, remained in effect Monday. More than 100 state
law enforcement officers and 374 National Guard officers assisted
in evacuation and stood by to help residents after the storm
passed.
</P>
<P>
   On Hatteras Island, where the brunt of the storm began to hit
around noon Monday, two gas pumps were blown over at Danny Couch's
service station. ``They were both embedded in concrete,'' Couch
said about 1 p.m. as the storm raged outside.
</P>
<P>
   Couch, 40, decided to sit out the storm. Even though the island
was under an evacuation order, residents were allowed to stay if
they remained on their own property.
</P>
<P>
   Valerie Tucker, 39, from Michigan, also stayed on the island
with 24 family members who were making their annual visit to the
Outer Banks Motel on the beachfront. The motel owner let the family
stay at her house farther from the beach. ``We were here for
Hurricane Emily in 1993,'' said Ms. Tucker, ``but we evacuated for
that. This one didn't seem like it would be as bad. We haven't been
out yet, but I don't think there will be too much damage. We're
still hoping to get a good week out of our vacation.''
</P>
<P>
   The coast of North Carolina has been battered by three
hurricanes in recent years, Fran and Bertha in 1996 and Bonnie last
year.
</P>
<P>
   And as Dennis moved away from the coast Monday afternoon,
officials cautioned that the storm is still a threat to the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``These things are so unpredictable,'' said Furney. ``It could
stay off the coast for a day or two and gather strength and come
back in. We hope that doesn't happen. What we need is a good front
to come in from the coast and push Dennis back out to sea.''
</P>
</TEXT>
