u p BC-BAXTER-ALABAMA31-COX     08-30 0601
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAXTER-ALABAMA31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Alabama lottery soon may rival Georgia's
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If any gathering was likely to be a hotbed of
sentiment against the proposed Alabama lottery, to be voted on Oct.
12 in a special election, it would have been the Republican
presidential straw poll last weekend in Birmingham.
</P>
<P>
   It was the lottery issue, after all, that helped Democrat Don
Siegelman oust incumbent Republican Fob James in last year's
governor's race, and Alan Keyes' victory in the straw poll was
proof that religious conservatives were solidly in attendance at
the event.
</P>
<P>
   There was, in fact, a good sprinkling of anti-lottery stickers
among the Republican regalia on display in Birmingham. But a poll
published the next day showed that opposition to the lottery is
weak even among Republicans and regular churchgoers.
</P>
<P>
   The poll, conducted by the University of South Alabama polling
group for newspapers in Birmingham, Huntsville and Mobile, also
indicated that most voters in the state have already made up their
minds: 61 percent for the lottery, 34 percent opposed and 5 percent
undecided.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans narrowly opposed the lottery, 50 percent to 47
percent. It was closer among those who said they attended church at
least once a week: 48 percent opposed the lottery, but 46 favored
it.
</P>
<P>
   As was the case when Georgia voters approved a lottery amendment
in 1992, African-Americans in Alabama showed much greater support _
78 percent _ than whites, who favored it by 57 percent. The
Birmingham mayoral election held on the same day is likely to boost
black turnout. Of 12 announced candidates so far, 10 are
African-American.
</P>
<P>
   What this means is that barring a sea change of opinion across
the Chattahoochee, there will soon be competition for the Georgia
Lottery, which draws an estimated $85 million to $90 million a year
from Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   The Alabama measure is a virtual carbon copy of Georgia's in
many respects, with funds to be earmarked for college scholarships,
pre-kindergarten programs and education technology. There are
differences in the two states' educational systems, however.
Alabama has a hybrid system of two-year academic and vocational
colleges, which will make it harder to sort out who qualifies for
scholarships when students from those schools apply to four-year
schools.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Dent, who was press secretary to former Georgia Gov. Zell
Miller and now works for the Alabama Lottery Foundation, predicted
the political impact will be similar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Republicans will be on the defensive, and Democrats will get
all the credit. It's not an accident that the current attorney
general (Thurbert Baker) and lieutenant governor (Mark Taylor) in
Georgia were the House and Senate floor leaders who passed the
lottery legislation,'' Dent said.
</P>
<P>
   He said Miller advised Siegelman not to wait, as he did, for a
big-turnout election, but to put the lottery question to the voters
while it still had momentum. Selling the idea to Alabama voters has
been easier partly because of the success of the Georgia program.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Zell campaigned for the Hope Scholarship program, people
thought it was too good to be true. All we had to compare was the
Florida Lottery, and Florida was screwed up,'' Dent said.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Lottery officials have expressed confidence that their
marketing prowess will enable Georgia to continue with no
significant impact from the new competition. Soon, it appears, that
confidence will be tested.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
