<HEADER>
A4957 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-HAWAII-KAUAI-$     08-30 1159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-HAWAII-KAUAI-$ADV05-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE END OF THE RAINBOW 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Sept. 5) 
(jt) 
 By TODD S. PURDUM    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It may have been the homemade pupu platter, with coconut shrimp
_ fried crisp and fresh _ and barbecued spareribs oozing sticky,
magenta--colored sauce. It may have been the nightly mai tai's or
the morning French toast with coconut syrup and fresh mangoes, or
the fragrant plumeria blossoms just outside the door. But somewhere
around the fourth day of a weeklong sojourn in a rented beach house
on Hanalei Bay in Kauai, I understood what those legions of
disapproving colonial missionaries meant when they warned against
going native.
</P>
<P>
   The enduring appeal of Hawaii for visitors from the 49 other
states lies in just this effortless ability to make the mystical
seem routine, and vice versa. The exoticism of the island state is
palpable and omnipresent, in its flowers and fruit, its
pan-Polynesian diet, its soft moonlight and sudden double rainbows
after a storm. That can be true even on those stretches of Waikiki
pavement that are as commercialized and crowded as the Chicago
Loop.
</P>
<P>
   But for a taste of old Hawaii, the romantic retreat of song and
story, it would be hard to beat Kauai, the 551-square-mile outpost
of flooded taro fields, lush mountains, thick jungles, craggy
cliffs and pristine beaches that Hawaiians themselves call the
garden isle. My wife, Dee Dee, and I discovered some of its many
pleasures in May when our friends Ruth and Sean and their
3-year-old son, Quincy, invited us to join them in a 72-year-old
green-shingled cottage overlooking the bay where ``South Pacific''
was filmed.
</P>
<P>
   Ruthie was raised in an old San Francisco family, and began
coming to Hawaii when the transport of choice was still the elegant
Matson Liner, the Lurline, and the trip took five days by sea. Our
guide in all things, she chose Hanalei, a sleepy little
hippie-surfer town on the island's misty, rainy north shore, for
our vacation, and after an Internet search came up with just the
place right on the beach: Hale Ola (House of Health), built in 1927
to lure a doctor to the island. At $3,000 for the week, the
two-story, four-bedroom house with wraparound balconies was a great
space. And since other friends, Madeline and Steve, joined the
party, it proved a great value, too, about $140 a couple a night.
</P>
<P>
   The house was well equipped and charmingly furnished, with
memorabilia of the original owners, plus framed photographs, 78-rpm
records, vintage Hawaiian sheet music and comfy tropical wicker
furniture covered in vintage tropical prints. Local lore holds that
it was strafed by Japanese Zeros flying back home from the raid on
Pearl Harbor. It was filled with the sort of casual bric-a-brac and
personal touches that made us feel like guests, not tenants. The
kitchen lacked nothing, and the wide porches made a perfect perch
for breakfast or a lazy afternoon read. There were neighbors close
by, but high hedges provided privacy.
</P>
<P>
   Kauai is a short jet hop from Honolulu. The island is just west
of Oahu and the westernmost main island in the chain except for
Niihau, the tiny, privately owned ``forbidden island'' that is the
sole province of the Robinson ranching family and some 200 workers
who live there in a kind of feudal kingdom. Before we knew it, we
were bustling through the pleasant open-air concourse of the
airport at Lihue and heading off on the 45-minute ride to Hanalei
in the silver Mustang convertible we'd rented on a lark.
</P>
<P>
   Ruthie had instructed us in no uncertain terms to stop at Ono
Charburger, a famous roadside stand near the beach town of Anahola
that serves local Kauai beef on big buns with sliced pineapple,
swiss cheese and teriyaki sauce, but we were so intent on not
missing the spot that we stopped by mistake at the first restaurant
we saw with ono (which simply means good) in the name: The Ono
Family Restaurant in Kapaa, also known as Auntie Ono's Kitchen. It
may not have been the assigned destination, but the burger was
top-notch, as was the fluffy fresh coconut cream pie. Thus
fortified, we pressed on around the coast road to Hanalei, which
means ``lei-shaped bay,'' and arrived in late afternoon in a kind
of eerie mist. That did not stop us from taking a swim in the balmy
water, or riding the good-sized waves on our stomachs on the boogie
boards found at the house.
</P>
<P>
   We also made an outing to the well-stocked, fairly expensive
grocery in the nearby modern resort town of Princeville, five miles
back up the hill. There is no real hotel in Hanalei proper, only
bed-and-breakfasts and rental houses, but the Princeville Hotel
sits like a white scar on the bluff where Mitzi Gaynor and Rossano
Brazzi once sang ``Some Enchanted Evening'' and is more than enough
hostel for the whole area. Princeville has a world-class golf
course and a collection of sterile-looking condominiums and is the
sort of place you'll like if you like that sort of thing. We were
happy to be within easy reach of its commercial establishments and
yet in our own quaint world.
</P>
<P>
   That night, we established what became a pattern of home-cooked
meals, often inspired by the folksy advice of the spiral-bound
``Maui Association for Family and Community Education 50th
Anniversary Recipe Book,'' which Ruthie bought in a local store,
and which featured a concoction that we never managed to make
called ``Sex in Pan,'' consisting of walnuts, cream cheese, Cool
Whip and vanilla and chocolate pudding.
</P>
<P>
   The week's achievements did include Ruthie's leg of lamb grilled
in peanut sauce; Madeline's pot stickers stuffed with ground pork
and shredded cabbage; pies made with coconut, mango and banana; and
a fresh pork butt marinated in liquid smoke, soy sauce and the
sodium-laden mix of sea salt and spices known as Hawaiian salt,
then slowly oven roasted in ti leaves.
</P>
<P>
   From that first night on with CD's of Hawaiian music playing in
the soft night air, we felt truly at home in our big second-floor
bedroom with its screen door and ocean-view veranda and shared bath
down the hall.
</P>
<P>
   Overcast skies are not uncommon on the north shore of Kauai, an
almost perfectly round island with the 5,148-foot Mount Waialeale,
which may be the wettest spot on earth, with average annual
rainfall of about 40 feet, rising smack in the middle. But cloudy
weather made it easy to just hang around the house and read
guidebooks and Somerset Maugham short stories. We also explored the
quiet village of Hanalei, really nothing more than a short strip of
modest restaurants, sporting goods stores and a boutique or two,
and brought home some fresh opah (or moonfish) steaks from the
Hanalei Dolphin fish market, which we grilled with soy sauce, fresh
ginger and butter. When the clouds lifted and we stood in the ocean
facing the shore, green hills and waterfalls worthy of Gauguin
suddenly revealed themselves.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
