<HEADLINE>
THE CANDIDATE AS DIVA AND ICON
</HEADLINE>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Columnist  &UR; Michelangelo Signorile  &LR; writes in the latest Advocate
that  &UR; Hillary Rodham Clinton &LR; , first lady and almost-candidate for
the Senate, has become an icon to gays and lesbians _ note to gays
and lesbians who are not movie fans: Signorile is teasing _ because
it's so easy to see her rise in terms of classic movie roles:
</P>
<P>
   - The first lady's physical transformation is reminiscent of
 &UR; Bette Davis  &LR; in ``Now, Voyager,'' turning herself from ``the dowdy
intellectual ... into (a) dazzling and cosmopolitan woman.''
</P>
<P>
   - The sense of drama in her life, writes Signorile, is ``as if
she were &UR; Julia Roberts &LR;  during her thriller period,'' making such
films as ``Filegate,'' ``Whitewater'' and ``It Takes a Village.''
</P>
<P>
   - The Lewinsky scandal is Clinton's ``All About Eve,'' says the
journalist, with  &UR; Monica Lewinsky &LR;  as ``the conniving young
upstart.''
</P>
<P>
   - The first lady's taking charge afterward, becoming ``a woman
who wasn't going to take it anymore and who was ready to do
something for herself,'' brings to mind  &UR; Joan Crawford &LR;  in
``Mildred Pierce.''
</P>
<P>
   - Her latest role, writes Signorile, is ``the graceful and pious
 &UR; Audrey Hepburn  &LR; in `The Nun's Story,' '' a woman who describes why
she forgave her husband in Talk magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the role-playing, the first lady ``doesn't have a record
to speak of'' on gay rights issues, writes Signorile, ``nor has she
said a great deal on the subject.''
</P>
<P>
   Issues should be more important than image, he realizes, but
maybe the Senate needs ``an industrious Joan Crawford for the new
millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I imagine gay men like her sense of style _ though I want to
go to sleep for six years just for having said that,'' says
playwright  &UR; Tony Kushner &LR; . ``I think she is basically a corporate
lawyer with towering ambitions and the morals of _ well, a
corporate lawyer. She's obviously brilliant and powerful. I'm for
her because the alternative is unthinkable.''
</P>
<P>
   P.S.  &UR; Glenn Close &LR; ,  &UR; Bette Midler &LR; ,  &UR; Al Franken &LR; ,  &UR; Blair Brown &LR; 
and &UR; Elaine May  &LR; are expected to attend  &UR; Marlo Thomas &LR; ' fund-raiser
for Clinton in New York on September 8, says the New York Daily
News.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - In response to news about the Yale Club's free-and-easy
summertime apparel, Harvard Club member  &UR; David Elliott &LR;  writes that
dress-downs _ ``gentlemen without coats and ties'' _ are permitted
at the Harvard Club on the weekends. During the week, he writes,
``the Club's popularity permits it to maintain high standards in
dress, unlike, it seems, the Yale Club, which appears to be
struggling for clientele.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Bob Geary  &LR; reports that a cricket has taken up residence in a
San Francisco pied a terre, one of the Central Station cells.
</P>
<P>
   - The menswear journal DNR describes the new Venetian
Resort-Hotel-Casino in Las Vegas: ``Throughout the property,
graceful arched bridges, flowing canals, vibrant piazzas and stone
walkways capture the spirit of Venice and its different
architectural periods. ... Later this year, (the hotel's) C2K
Carnevale 2000 will feature ... the first `Bay Watch' restaurant
and bar with seating for 270.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOMAGE TO LEONARDO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Lawrence Ferlinghetti &LR;  is one of 70 artists who have
contributed 10 works each about  &UR; Leonardo da Vinci &LR; , to be
exhibited in Milan in the year 2000, &LR;  in celebration of the 500th
anniversary of the prototype Renaissance man. (Da Vinci was
actually born in 1452 and died in 1519; the date is rough.)
</P>
<P>
   Ferlinghetti told the artists' periodical studioNOTES that he
was browsing in City Lights Italia, a bookstore in Florence
unrelated in anything but name to City Lights in San Francisco,
when an art collector approached him and asked him to participate
in the da Vinci project.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HEADLINE POETRY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Reading last week's Chronicle headline ``Retired Men With New
Careers/ Happier Than Idle Peers/ In Study,'' the poetry-loving
 &UR; Robbie  &LR; and  &UR; Herb Behrens &LR;  observed, ``It sings, it's true and
rather pretty.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, it's a 17-syllable haiku (modern haiku, Personals is
informed, don't have to follow the 5-7-5 syllable pattern).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something therapeutic about nudity.''
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Kevin Bacon  &LR; on being naked in movies, in InStyle.
</P>
</TEXT>
