<HEADER>
A4959 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-HAWAII-KAUAI-2     08-30 1154
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-HAWAII-KAUAI-2NDTAKE-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (For release Sun., Sept. 5.)  
 UNDATED: revealed themselves.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dee Dee and I took off in search of clearer skies on the south
shore one day, stopping to rent snorkels, masks and fins on the
way, and visiting the historic Kilauea Lighthouse and its
surrounding bird sanctuary on a wind-swept point at the island's
northeast corner. We managed to stop at Ono Charburger, and its
giant Local Girl specialty was as promised. By the time we reached
Poipu and Koloa, the south shore towns where most of the island's
major resorts are, it was finally sunny and we fell fast asleep in
a double hammock on the charming grounds of the Hyatt Regency
Resort and Spa, where interlocking saltwater lagoons make up for a
roiling beach whose surf is often too dangerous for swimming. This
area was hit hard by Hurricane Iniki in 1992 but has now been
largely rebuilt.
</P>
<P>
   When we awoke, there was just enough time for a quick snorkel at
Poipu Beach Park, a wonderful public beach with showers and
changing rooms. We stopped by the giant, lushly landscaped Marriott
in nearby Lihue for a drink before meeting Ruthie, Sean and Quincy
at Hamura's Saimin, a no-frills Japanese noodle parlor where
steaming bowls of the trademark soup arrived bearing slivers of
Hawaii's beloved staple meat product: Spam. The pinkish strips of
ham-like protein take some getting used to, but the broth was
unbeatable, as was the foamy piece of fresh passion-fruit chiffon
pie.
</P>
<P>
   One gloriously sunny day, we headed down the tiny two-lane road
that leads west from Hanalei, narrowing occasionally to one-lane
bridges, to one of the island's best snorkeling beaches, known as
Tunnels. Its underwater lava formations make a perfect habitat for
thousands of brilliantly colored fish. This beach, which like all
north shore beaches can have dangerously high surf in winter, has
the pronounced advantage of offering a gorgeous view of Makana
mountain, a cone-shaped coastal outcropping more commonly known as
Bali H'ai peak, which is what it was used for in the film version
of ``South Pacific.'' We happily paddled through bathwater-warm
shallows, surrounded by Day-Glo colored fish.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday we visited the weekly evening luau at Tahiti Nui, a
local dive with the simple, unaffected charm of an Elks Club but an
authentic floor show featuring an appealing cast and dances, songs
and stories from around the Pacific, including the requisite hula
skirts and coconut-shell brassieres. We skipped the food, which was
steam-table ordinary, because Madeline and Steve were arriving from
Los Angeles and we wanted to impress them with our homemade pupu
platter of Polynesian appetizers.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, the whole gang of us rented kayaks from Kayak
Kauai in town and made the gentle paddle inland up the winding
Hanalei River, past fields and forests for an hour or so until
rocks made the stream impassable; we turned back for a shave-ice,
the Hawaiian version of the sno-cone, flavored with tropical
syrups, from a trusty roadside stand.
</P>
<P>
   All week, as our idyll unfolded, I had been dreading precisely
one thing: Dee Dee and Ruthie's fearless plan to hike the beautiful
but treacherous Kalalau Trail, which slithers along the wild Na
Pali Coast, one of the most spectacular stretches of scenery in all
the world and the place where parts of ``Jurassic Park'' were
filmed.
</P>
<P>
   The trail begins at Kee Beach, where the Kuhio Highway, Route
56, ends at the island's northwest edge. Parts of the path are only
a foot or so wide, with 1,000-foot sheer drops to the rocky
coastline below. Where it does descend to beautiful and isolated
beaches, the surf is often so dangerous, the guidebooks warn, that
unsuspecting hikers have been known to stand in apparently benign
calf-high waves only to be knocked over by a sudden roller, dragged
out to sea and drowned.
</P>
<P>
   This intelligence left me not so quietly quaking _ loudly
whining, in fact _ all week, and I was relieved when lack of time
left us hiking just the first dramatic four-mile round-trip leg, to
Hanakapiai Beach and back. It is a steep and moderately challenging
series of switchbacks, and though we began at 7:30 a.m. in a cool
forest, the rising sun made the return trip along exposed swatches
blisteringly hot.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the sweeping views down to the banded blues of the ocean,
studded with a school of leaping dolphins, and ahead to the
undulating outcroppings of rock and foliage, were among the most
uplifting I've ever seen, and I was glad to have made the trek. I
was equally glad not to have had to face finding the courage to go
farther. We washed off the heat and grime with more snorkeling.
</P>
<P>
   One of our last purchases at the Princeville grocery was a
vintage Don Ho CD, and back in California in these summer sunsets I
sometimes put it on just to play the old Hawaiian standard that
begins, ``When you see Hanalei by moonlight, you'll be in heaven by
the sea.''
</P>
<P>
   If you go native
</P>
<P>
   Where to Stay
</P>
<P>
   The oldest rental agent on Kauai's North Shore is Hanalei North
Shore Properties, Post Office Box 607, Hanalei, Kauai, Hawaii
96714; (800) 488-3336, fax (808) 826-1188. It lists 130
accommodations ranging from $600-a-week two-bedroom condominiums to
a seven-bedroom house belonging to the entertainer Charo that costs
$6,000 a week, plus scores of properties represented by other
agents. Beachfront houses book up a year or two in advance, and are
especially scarce over holidays and summer vacation. On the Web:
planet-hawaii &QL; 
.com/visit-kauai.
</P>
<P>
   What to Do
</P>
<P>
   Kayak Kauai Outbound on Kuhio Highway in Hanalei rents river and
ocean kayaks and organizes guided trips (starting at $55 for three
hours) for those who don't want to paddle alone. All-day rentals
are $24 for a one-seat boat, $48 for a double; (808) 826-9844.
</P>
<P>
   Hanalei Surf Co., in an old Hanalei school building that is now
a shopping arcade, offers all kinds of equipment for sale or rent,
plus reliable advice about surf and weather conditions. A mask,
snorkel and fins rent for $5 a day or $20 a week. A
prescription-lens mask is available for the nearsighted; (808)
826-9000.
</P>
<P>
   Where to Eat
</P>
<P>
   Tahiti Nui on Kuhio Highway in the heart of Hanalei offers
unremarkable food, predictable tropical drinks and luaus on
Wednesday night. The fixed-price luau menu is expensive at $40, but
the show only is a deal at $15; (808) 826-6277.
</P>
<P>
   Ono Charburger on Route 56 in Anahola, next to Whalers General
Store, is a simple roadside stand with superb burgers. Service can
be slow, but the burgers _ $4 and up, with crispy, spicy fries
extra _ are worth the wait; (808) 822-9181.
</P>
<P>
   Hamura's Saimin, 2956 Kress St., Lihue, is a no-frills lunch
counter serving steaming bowls of Japanese noodle soup, grilled
chicken and barbecued beef. Soups start at about $5 for giant
portions. Cash and traveler's checks only; (808) 245-3271.
</P>
</TEXT>
