<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following for
clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of Tuesday, Aug.
31, and thereafter. If you have any questions, please call Bob
Schenet on the Post-Intelligencer's National/Foreign Desk at (206)
448-8037.
</P>
<P>
   BATTLESHIP-MUSEUM (Seattle) _ The decommissioned battleship USS
New Jersey will begin a final voyage into history in two weeks when
it departs at the end of a tow line for Philadelphia and future
service as a naval museum.
</P>
<P>
   By Ed Offley. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   ART-MARATHON-ART (SEATTLE) _ Midnight at the Seattle Art Museum,
and the place was hopping. The line snaked out the door, up
University Street and back along Second Avenue on Saturday night.
For the first time in its history, the museum held an art marathon
to celebrate its immensely popular exhibit, ``Impressionism:
Paintings Collected by European Museums,'' keeping the doors open
from 9 a.m. Saturday to midnight Sunday night, when the show
closed. Art.
</P>
<P>
   By Regina Hackett. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   STUDENT-INVENTOR-ART (SEATTLE) _ When you get the Rives family
together the sparks fly. Literally. Alexander Rives, an 18-year-old
Lakeside School senior, is the proud inventor of the ``Lightning
Machine,'' an educational toy being sold through his parent's
scientific toy company, Scientific Explorer. Art.
</P>
<P>
   By Sarah Skidmore. (Story has moved in the ``l'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   SINGERS-SIDEWALK-ART (SEATTLE) _ On a sunny weekday afternoon,
tourists swarm Seattle's famed Pike Place Market while Clifford
Miller, Wil Smith, Levi Barnes and James Butler seize a spot on the
Pike Place sidewalk. After clearing their throats and cracking a
few jokes, they bust out with a few hit tunes: ``Under the
Boardwalk,'' ``This Little Light of Mine'' and ``I Got Sunshine.''
Within minutes they're surrounded by a whooping, clapping,
toe-tapping crowd of nearly 50 people. Art.
</P>
<P>
   By Erika Hayasaki. (Story has moved in the ``l'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FISHING-HARD-TIMES-ART- (BLAINE, Wash.) _ Nick Karuza and his
wife Diedra sat on the aft deck of their 50-foot purse seiner F/V
Alice Anne moored in Blaine Marina last week and checked the old
boat's nets for damage. ``My grandfather came from the Croatian
Island of Vis in the early 1900s and he fished for salmon in Puget
Sound,'' Nick Karuza said. But this year, for the first time that
anyone can remember, there will be no Puget Sound fishing season
for sockeye. It may be the last gasp for commercial fishing in
Puget Sound, one of the last of the state's traditional industries
struggling to survive.
</P>
<P>
   By Arthur C. Gorlick. (Story has moved in the ``f'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   TEN-VECSEY-COLUMN (New York) _ Column from the U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   By Laura Vecsey. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-MARINERS (Chicago) _ White Sox host Seattle Mariners in a
doubleheader.
</P>
<P>
   By Tyler Kepner. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
