<SLUG> BC-TIMOR-VOTE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUGE TURNOUT FOR EAST TIMOR VOTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DILI, East Timor _ Hundreds of thousands of people defied months
of violence and intimidation Monday to cast ballots in an historic
vote widely expected to bring independence to the disputed island
territory of East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   After centuries of Portuguese colonial control and 24 years of
Indonesian rule, the determination to decide their own future was
so strong that some East Timorese slept at polling stations and
others lined up before dawn to insure they would not be denied a
chance to vote. One man was shuttled to a polling station in Dili
by ambulance, an intravenous drip attached to his arm. Several
frail elderly voters hobbled to the front of long waiting lines,
smiling triumphantly as they emerged.
</P>
<P>
   More than 90 percent of 430,000 registered voters turned up to
choose between autonomy under Indonesian sovereignty or full
independence _ a remarkable showing considering the upsurge in
violence between pro- and anti-independence factions that had
claimed at least a dozen lives in the last several days.
</P>
<P>
   The heavy turnout was widely interpreted to presage a decisive
vote for independence, but the results will not be announced until
next week. The outcome must also be approved by Indonesia's
national assembly, which convenes this autumn.
</P>
<P>
   Jamsheed Marker, UN special envoy to East Timor, said Monday
night that ``it would be very difficult, if not impossible, to
reverse whatever the result.''
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, voting in the UN-sponsored referendum was
peaceful and orderly, with an air of solemnity at many polling
stations, a sense of festivity at others, and a cloud of fear
pervading only a few.
</P>
<P>
   The vote was marred, however, by attacks on three local United
Nations workers, one of whom died from stab wounds Monday night.
Pro-Indonesia militias have accused the UN of favoring
independence.
</P>
<P>
   There were reports of intimidation, road blocks and threats by
pro-Indonesia militias that temporarily shut down seven of the 800
polling stations. There were no recorded attacks on voters,
however, and the balloting went off far more peacefully than most
observers had expected.
</P>
<P>
   The UN mission ``and Indonesian police did a very good job of
keeping the balloting process today free from intimidation and
violence,'' said Charles Costello, head of an observer mission from
the Carter Center in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in a scrap of shade cast by a single tree outside his
polling station, Antonio DeJesus Nunes, 45, said quietly, ``Today
is very, very important for me and all of East Timor. Today is what
I've been waiting for for 24 years.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Indonesia always told us what to do.'' said Nunes, a former
member of the pro-independence guerrilla group Falintil who was
waiting for the lines to thin. ``If independence wins, East Timor
has a new home. Good or bad, at least we will control our own
home.''
</P>
<P>
   But Saskia Kouwenberg of the International Federation for East
Timor Observers Project, warned ``there is no reason to sit back
and think this is all over.''
</P>
<P>
   Many have predicted a fresh civil war, regardless of the vote
result.
</P>
<P>
   doomsday scenarios were far from the mind of Inacia DeJesus, 35,
who couldn't contain a shy grin when asked how she felt about
voting. Shading herself from the blazing sun with a rainbow-colored
umbrella, DeJesus declared, ``I'm happy. This election will
determine the future of East Timor and my future, too. I have
always known how I would vote if I had the chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked which side she favored, DeJesus glanced at the crowd
around her and demurred, ``It's a secret.''
</P>
<P>
   Many voters waited patiently in the almost 90-degree heat for
hours, shielding their faces with copies of an election-day edition
of Suara Timor Timur (``The Voice of East Timor''), the territory's
daily newspaper, which had a copy of the ballot printed on the
back. The ballots were printed in English, Portuguese, Indonesian,
and Tetun, the local dialect. For illiterate voters, a picture of
the Indonesian flag accompanied the choice for autonomy, and the
pro-indepedence flag marked the vote for separation.
</P>
<P>
   Though there were countless red-and-white Indonesian flags
flying, it was hard to find anyone in the capital who would admit
to voting for autonomy. In several neighborhoods, posters of the
revered jailed guerrilla leader Xanana Gusmao, who Indonesia has
promised to release shortly, plastered the walls. Grafitti declared
``We are masters _ Anti-autonomy!''
</P>
<P>
   In the western corner of the territory, a stronghold of
pro-Indonesia sentiment and paramilitary groups, many anxious
voters hesitated to talk to reporters, and some said they had been
told to vote for autonomy or be killed.
</P>
<P>
   One problem the UN was unable to solve was how to let people
vote who had fled their homes because of threats _ and thereby
abandoned their assigned polling stations. Tens of thousands of
people have been displaced by violence in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   To prevent fraud, everyone had to vote at an assigned post,
explained Tony Lapsley, a district electoral officer who had to
announce the bad news to scores of displaced villagers sheltering
outside his polling place.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in Indonesian, Lapsley told the group how sorry he was
that they ``wouldn't be able to take part in this very historic
day,'' but that didn't make the disappointment any easier to take.
No one argued, but a few looked as if they might cry, and several
men stalked off, cursing.
</P>
<P>
   One man sputtered in frustration that he had been threatened in
Liquica, where more than two dozen people seeking shelter in a
Catholic church were massacred by pro-autonomy militias four months
ago. He fled with only the clothes on his back.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hid in the jungle and only two days ago we came here and
asked to be able to vote, and now we can't. It's not fair!'' he
cried out. ``Now Timorese must get independence _ 100 percent!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
