<SLUG> BC-BATTLESHIP-MUSEUM-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USS NEW JERSEY PREPARES FOR FINAL VOYAGE INTO HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ED OFFLEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The city of Bremerton's half-century history as a
homeport for battleships will come to an end in two weeks when the
retired USS New Jersey heads out to sea on its last mission.
</P>
<P>
   The battleship, which amassed 16 battle stars in combat in World
War II, Korea and Vietnam, and served from Central America to
Lebanon in the 1980s, will become a naval-maritime museum in its
namesake state.
</P>
<P>
   The ship was stricken from the naval register Jan. 4, ending a
56-year career that included four periods of active service and 21
years in mothballs at Puget Sound Naval Shipyard near Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The Sea Victory, a seagoing tug operated by Crowley Marine
Services of Seattle, will tow the 58,000-ton warship nearly 6,000
miles from Bremerton via the Panama Canal to a temporary pier at
the former Philadelphia Naval Shipyard, said Todd Busch, a
contracts manager for the towing firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the longest tow we've ever done, but it is a
lengthy tow, no question about that,'' Busch said. The trip is
expected to take about seven weeks with an estimated arrival date
on Nov. 7.
</P>
<P>
   Navy veterans who served on the New Jersey during World War II
and later conflicts have scheduled a reunion in the Seattle area
the weekend of Sept. 9-12, said battleship vet Ralph Wasmer.
``We'll go down there on the 12th to bid her farewell,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Sea Victory was scheduled to arrive in Seattle early Tuesday
to begin preparing for the New Jersey tow, following an even longer
mission, Busch said. The 149-foot-long tug and its crew of eight is
returning after towing the decommissioned aircraft carrier USS
Oriskany more than 15,000 miles from San Francisco Bay to Beaumont,
Texas, requiring a circumnavigation of South America and transit of
the Straits of Magellan, Busch said.
</P>
<P>
   Under a plan worked out between the Navy and New Jersey state
officials, the battleship will be temporarily stored in
Philadelphia while the state finishes a competition process to
select the organization and permanent moorage site on the Delaware
River.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state of New Jersey wanted to move the battleship closer
to the state,'' Pat Dolan, a Navy spokeswoman, and the Navy agreed
to temporarily transfer the ship to the state.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey tow will come just 16 months after its sister
ship, the USS Missouri, left Bremerton for the final time to become
a memorial at Pearl Harbor, Hawaii. Like its more famed sister
ship, the New Jersey fell victim to gains in naval weapons
technology and shrinking Pentagon budgets that made it financially
prohibitive for the Navy to continue operating them.
</P>
<P>
   Each battleship required a 1,500-man crew which boosted annual
operating costs to more than $80 million per ship, including $45
million in payrolls, despite the fact that newer Aegis missile
cruisers packed more firepower with a crew one-fourth the size. It
cost the Navy $20 million to mothball each of the battleships and
required more than $100,000 per year in upkeep for each ship,
officials said. The Navy also estimated it would cost at least $95
million to reactivate one of the ships.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
