<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAZING-SURVEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURVEY SHOWS INTENSE HAZING AMONG COLLEGE ATHLETES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EUN LEE KOH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A new survey has found that 80 percent of all
college athletes go through hazing as part of a team initiation
process, with as many as one in five being forced to engage in
potentially criminal activities.
</P>
<P>
   The survey released Monday shows that athlete hazing involves
excessive heckling to beating and kidnapping new team members,
debunking the notion that hazing on college campuses occurs
primarily within fraternities and sororities.
</P>
<P>
   Half of the hazings involved alcohol and about 20 percent of the
students admitted committing an illegal act such as forcing
teammates to destroy or steal property or engage in lewd sexual
acts, according to the survey of 2,027 college athletes from 224
NCAA schools.
</P>
<P>
   The survey included athletes from the University of
Massachusetts at Boston, the University of Massachusetts at
Dartmouth, Brandeis University, Bowdoin College, Tufts University,
Middlebury College, Brown University, and the University of New
Hampshire. Not represented, however, were two of New England's
sports powerhouses, the University of Connecticut and Boston
College.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let these survey results serve as a wake-up call to this
nation and its colleges and universities,'' said Edward G. Coll,
president of Alfred University in New York, the school that
conducted the study in conjunction with the NCAA earlier this year.
``Our results show evidence that hazing to join an athletic team is
a huge problem on our campuses.''
</P>
<P>
   Hazing, an activity that degrades or abuses a new member of a
group, is illegal in 41 states, including Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Most colleges and universities make their athletes pledge in
writing that they will not engage in hazing and will report it if
such activities occur, but the survey found that most athletes are
reluctant to report hazing, even if it happens to them.
</P>
<P>
   About 60 percent of the students questioned said they would not
report hazing, and only 12 percent of the respondents admitted to
being hazed, even though an overwhelming majority, 80 percent, said
they had engaged in activities that could be considered hazing
under most state laws.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Mullen, the athletic director at University of
Massachusetts at Dartmouth, said even though UMass has a strict
policy against hazing, the school has difficulties enforcing it
because students do not report violations.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the school investigated two hazing cases and both
turned up inconclusive because students who may have witnessed the
activities did not come forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've tried to make it anonymous for them, but still there's
this notion that hazing is acceptable, that it builds brotherhood
or camaraderie,'' Mullen said. ``Some coaches turn their heads and
say it's OK, even though we threaten them with their jobs if they
tolerate such behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Stratten, the vice president of educational services for
the National Collegiate Athletics Association, said, ``It's really
appalling what's going on. Schools really need to open their eyes
on this issue.''
</P>
<P>
   While hazing is already forbidden under NCAA guidelines,
Stratten said it is up to individual schools to seek out and punish
those who violate the rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though this is a national issue, enforcement needs to
take place on a local level,'' Stratten said. ``We can't keep an
eye out on the hundreds of thousands of athletes out there, so the
schools need to do their part.''
</P>
<P>
   But according to the survey, only 25 percent of athletes
reported that their schools took disciplinary measures against
students involved in hazing. Other students reported their coaches
and athletic directors ``turning a blind eye.''
</P>
<P>
   The survey found that both men and women engaged in some form of
hazing, but women were less likely to be involved in violent
activities, according to the survey. While 27 percent of male
athletes said they had subjected teammates to violence such as
binding and gagging or whipping, 16 percent of female athletes
reported doing the same.
</P>
<P>
   But women were more likely than men to be involved in
alcohol-related activities, such as forced consumption or drinking
contests, than any other form of hazing.
</P>
<P>
   Football players, swimmers, divers, lacrosse players, and water
polo players most frequently reported hazing than any other sport
in the survey. Students involved in tennis, fencing, and track
reported the least amount of hazing.
</P>
<P>
   Coll, who commissioned the study after several football players
at Alfred were hospitalized last year from hazing, said the results
were particularly disturbing because unlike most fraternities or
sororities, which are independently owned and under limited control
by universities, athletic teams are guided completely by college
rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are teams supported by our money, supervised by our
coaches, and whose activities are conducted on our playing fields,
and in our gyms and locker rooms,'' Coll said. ``If members of
athletic teams are hazing the rookies, then it is our problem, and
our liability as well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
