<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-DECLINE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DROP IN RATE OF AIDS CASES SLOWING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOLORES KONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   While the number of AIDS deaths continues to drop nationally,
the rapid rate of decline that had been attributed to new drugs is
starting to slow dramatically, public health officials reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of the 42 percent drop in the number of AIDS deaths
nationally between 1996 and 1997, the rate of decline was only 20
percent between 1997 and 1998, according to figures presented at a
meeting in Atlanta. In 1998, 17,047 people with AIDS died, down
from 21,222 AIDS deaths in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts AIDS deaths statistics for 1998 are not yet
available, but those on the front lines of battling the disease
here say they are already hearing stories about people infected
with the AIDS virus failing to do as well on the drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people are hitting the wall again,'' Larry Kessler,
director of the AIDS Action Committee of Massachusetts, said in a
telephone interview. While the new drugs have helped many,
``they're not a cure, and they're not a vaccine,'' Kessler said.
</P>
<P>
   Kessler and other health officials have known all along that
sooner or later the virus would figure out a way to outsmart these
latest AIDS drugs, which are known as protease inhibitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The virus has a mind of its own,'' said Kessler, who added
that he was discouraged. ``I can't say we're surprised,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Also at the National HIV Prevention Conference in Atlanta
Monday, public health officials estimated that about 40,000
Americans became newly infected with the AIDS virus in 1998, a
figure that has remained stable from year to year.
</P>
<P>
   But certain populations, such as young gay men and blacks,
continue to have a much higher rate of infection with HIV, the
virus that causes AIDS, than the general population, according to
studies presented Monday.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, one seven-city survey of nearly 3,500 15- to
22-year-old gay men found that an average of 7 percent were
infected with HIV. Young gay black men had the highest rate of
infection, 14 percent. The survey included Los Angeles, Miami, New
York, and San Francisco, but no Massachusetts city.
</P>
<P>
   While figures for AIDS deaths in 1998 are not yet available for
Massachusetts, the state's latest AIDS surveillance data show that
more than 8,800 people diagnosed with AIDS in Massachusetts have
died since the epidemic began in the early 1980s. As of Aug. 1,
5,869 people with AIDS are still alive, according to the figures.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997 Massachusetts AIDS deaths fell 60 percent, following a
35-percent decline the year before. The state has tended to do
better than the national average at battling the epidemic because
of its extensive public health programs.
</P>
<P>
   But if studies presented at the meeting Monday by public health
officials from New York and Seattle are any indication,
Massachusetts might also expect to see a dramatic slowdown in the
rate of decline in AIDS deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Both of those cities had at one point experienced a more than 60
percent drop in AIDS deaths, as Massachusetts had, but officials
said Monday that the decline slowed to only 25 percent in New York
in 1998 and to 27 percent in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The state's 1998 AIDS death statistics will not be available
until November, Jean Flatley McGuire, director of the state's
HIV/AIDS bureau, said by telephone from Atlanta, where she is
attending the national AIDS meeting.
</P>
<P>
   She added that there could be any number of factors entering
into the national slowdown in AIDS deaths. ``I don't think there's
any one story behind this,'' McGuire said.
</P>
<P>
   People who might have died in earlier years without the drugs
may have had their death postponed until 1998, McGuire said. Or
some of those who died in 1998 may have been among the HIV-infected
patients that researchers have known all along will get few
benefits from the drugs, she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
