<SLUG> BC-HOTMAIL-HACKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HACKER USES MICROSOFT WEB SITE TO READ E-MAIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A hacker gained access to millions of electronic mail messages
Monday by exploiting a bug in the software used by Microsoft Corp.
to run its popular Hotmail Web site. Worse yet, he revealed how he
did it, forcing Microsoft to shut down the service and scramble to
make repairs.
</P>
<P>
   Hotmail provides free e-mail accounts to more than 40 million
people worldwide. Monday the Swedish newspaper Expressen reported
that an unidentified hacker had set up a Web site that would give
visitors access to the mailbox of any Hotmail subscriber simply by
typing in the subscriber's user name. No password was necessary.
Since the user name of every Hotmail subscriber is included in his
or her e-mail address, it would be easy to find the user names of
total strangers and read their e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   A Microsoft spokeswoman said the company shut down the Hotmail
site Monday morning, as soon as technicians confirmed the existence
of the problem. The bug was closed and service was restored within
a couple of hours.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, word spread of another Web site that let
people gain unauthorized access to Hotmail. Microsoft says this
happened because one of its mail servers had not yet been updated
with software to repair the bug. As of Monday evening, Hotmail was
in operation and Microsoft insisted the problem had been repaired.
</P>
</TEXT>
