<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATT-RATES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATT SHOOTS FOR LONG-DISTANCE DOMINANCE WITH 7-CENT RATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T rolled out a 7-cent-per-minute domestic long-distance
calling plan Monday, aiming to stave off profit-dampening
defections by residential customers to flat-rate calling plans
announced earlier this summer by chief rivals MCI WorldCom and
Sprint.
</P>
<P>
   But the average consumer trying to figure out which of the Big
Three phone companies will give them the best deal would be well
served to have solid math skills _ and maybe even an accountant.
</P>
<P>
   The key question consumers need to answer is when they rack up
most of their long-distance minutes: During the daytime, when
AT&AMP;T's rate beats rivals handily, or on nights and weekends, when
MCI and Sprint would undercut AT&AMP;T's per-minute rate by 42 percent.
All three deals require a minimum monthly payment of about $5 or $6
a month.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T's strategy seems to be that consumers will appreciate a
true single rate for long distance without having to check the
clock before calling. ``It's amazing how complicated this industry
can make saying, `Hello,' '' AT&AMP;T chairman Michael Armstrong told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   People who sign up for AT&AMP;T's plan will get 7-cents-a-minute
long-distance calling all week long if they pay a fixed monthly
charge of $5.95, cut to $4.95 if people also use AT&AMP;T for
intra-state long distance calling (such as Boston to Framingham or
Cape Cod).
</P>
<P>
   MCI and Sprint offer rates as low as 5 cents a minute, with $5
or $6 monthly charge, but only on nights and weekends in MCI's case
or, in Sprint's, from 7 p.m. to midnight every day. At other times
their rates range from 10 to 25 cents per minute.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, AT&AMP;T had offered a 15 cent per minute deal with no
monthly fee, or 10 cents per minute and 5 cents on Sundays for a
$4.95 fee.
</P>
<P>
   Telecommunications analysts Jeffrey Kagan said of the new 7-cent
plan, ``While this is not the lowest price, it is the simplest . .
. It should be successful at keeping their customers from jumping
ship.''
</P>
<P>
   While AT&AMP;T consumer services president Gene Lockhart said the
new rate would serve as a ``core product'' through 2000, Kagan
predicted, ``We will see all the competitors tweaking their plans
in coming months.''
</P>
<P>
   Some industry observers questioned whether the race to the
bottom in long-distance calling charges means it no longer makes
sense for Bell Atlantic to be fighting hard to get into the
long-distance market in Massachusetts, New York and other states.
</P>
<P>
   Bell spokesman John Johnson said the company continues to
``think the long-distance market is still lucrative, perhaps more
so than the local business. And we think it's it's critical to be
able to bundle long-distance along with local services and Internet
and others. Customers practically demand it.''
</P>
<P>
   MCI's senior vice president of consumer marketing, John
Donoghue, saidof the 7-cent plan, ``It's certainly a better deal
than what AT&AMP;T customers are getting now, but it's not as good a
deal as they can get through MCI.''
</P>
<P>
   Donoghue said MCI finds its customers use 85 percent of their
calling minutes during the off-peak hours when it offers a 5-cent
rate. Someone making 100 minutes of monthly long-distance calls in
that pattern would pay MCI $1.20 to $2 a month less than the $11.95
AT&AMP;T would charge someone who also used AT&AMP;T for intra-state toll
calls.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint's Eileen Gaffen said her company has found residential
customers do their heaviest long-distance calling at night from 7
p.m. to 9 p.m., so it aimed its cheapest rate to nighttimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not all price these days,'' Gaffen added, noting that the
J.D. Powers survey has ranked Sprint tops for customer service five
years running. ``People should look at the way they are treated by
their phone company.''
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T officials said the recent spate of cut-price calling plans
is eroding long-distance revenues more than they expected. But they
told analysts Monday they would meet Wall Street expectations of 5
to 7 percent company-wide earnings growth this year because of
unexpectedly strong growth in wireless calling and other business
sectors such as Internet access. Still, AT&AMP;T shares, the heaviest
traded shares on the New York Stock Exchange Monday, dropped $1.50
to $46.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, AT&AMP;T also unveiled a new wireless calling plan
called the Family Plan under which up to five family members can
make unlimited wireless calls to each other and to a home phone,
with a designated georgraphic area, for $30 to $50 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Rivals questioned whether this is really a good deal, however,
with Bell Atlantic Mobile touting its own $10-a-month plan allowing
unlimited calls to any other Bell Mobile customer, subject to some
restrictions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-99 2010EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
