<SLUG> BC-ALPHA-CHIP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT DUMPS ALPHA, BUT CHIP'S FUTURE SECURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What happened to Alpha Processor Inc. last week would be the
kiss of death for many computer firms. But nobody's hanging any
crepe at Alpha, even though they've just learned that the world's
biggest software company is abandoning them.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft announced last week that future versions of its
Windows NT operating system would not be tailored to run on Alpha's
high-powered processor chips. A long-promised version of NT that
would take full advantage of the Alpha's unique design will never
see the light of day.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, computers using Alpha processors have been shut out
from the vast market for workstations and servers running Windows
NT. It's bad news for Alpha Processor, the leading distributor and
marketer of Alpha chips. But Jeff Borkowski, Alpha Processor's vice
president of marketing, doesn't see it as a portent of doom.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt it's a disappointment,'' said Borkowski,
``but the reality is there won't be a material effect on our
revenue line or our bottom line this year.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Borkowski says his company hopes to make Alpha-based
systems a favorite choice among heavy-duty users who may not want
to trust their computing tasks to Microsoft's NT software.
</P>
<P>
   Alpha Processor, of Concord, Mass., is owned by Korean
electronics firm Samsung Electronics Co. and Houston-based Compaq
Computer Corp. The Alpha was developed by Digital Equipment Corp.,
which was acquired by Compaq last year. Alpha Processor hasn't
released its earnings, but says that this year's revenues should
reach $100 million. About three-quarters of that comes from sales
of Alpha chips and motherboards to Compaq.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Alpha first appeared in 1992, versions of the chip
have consistently outperformed the industry-leading Pentium chips
made by rival Intel Corp. Alpha chips are now made by Samsung in
Korea and by Intel, under contract to Compaq.
</P>
<P>
   The Alpha's design made it incompatible with Intel processors.
The Alpha can't run Microsoft Windows software without an
additional program called an emulator, which makes the Alpha work
like a Pentium chip. But using an emulator slows the Alpha down,
thus eliminating the speed advantage that made the chip attractive
in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Alpha-based computers never became commonly used on
corporate desktops. Instead, most Alphas are found in corporate
back offices, running tough and intensive computing tasks. Most of
the Alphas run OpenVMS, an operating system designed for larger
computers, or True64 Unix, an Alpha-modified version of the
powerful Unix operating system. There's also an Alpha version of
the free Linux operating system.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft and Compaq had vowed to produce a version of Windows
NT that would solve this problem, but now that plan has been
scrapped. The Alpha will forever support only non-Microsoft
products.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market has basically been pretty clear that the market for
us is the Linux space,'' Borkowski said. Alpha Processor is betting
that the combination of Alpha speed with Linux reliability and low
cost will be a hit with small- and medium-size firms.
</P>
<P>
   Borkowski figures that about 300,000 Linux servers will be sold
worldwide next year. He says that if Alpha Processor can get a
quarter of that _ 75,000 servers _ they'll do fine.
</P>
<P>
   Alpha also has a steady following among scientists and
engineers. Microway Inc. of Kingston, Mass. will sell as many as
3,000 Alpha-based computers this year, many to these hardcore
users.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doubling in size every six to 12 months,'' said Microway
president Stephen Fried, ``and that's been going on ever since we
got into the Alpha business'' in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The abandonment of Windows NT for Alpha probably ensures that
the processor will always be a niche product, with little appeal to
many computer users. But Compaq, which actually owns the Alpha
technology, is continuing to upgrade and enhance the chip.
</P>
<P>
   A 750-megahertz version is due this fall, and a one-gigahertz
version should come out by next summer. Meanwhile, Samsung's Alpha
plant will start using some new chipmaking techniques to improve
performance and lower the Alpha's power consumption. In July,
Compaq announced it would spend $100 million to promote the use of
Alpha processors running True64 Unix. All of these signs suggest
that Alpha Processor may have a future after all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
