<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-FAITH-POLITICS-ART-880(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`POLITICAL PIETY' INCREASES IN PRESIDENTIAL POLITICS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING to add photo note)  
 (ATTN: Ohio, Wis., Ind.)  (ART ADV:  Photo  is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By LAURIE GOODSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Presidential candidates have always made a point of having
themselves photographed as they step out of church on Sunday,
carrying a Bible perhaps, and shaking the minister's hand.
</P>
<P>
   But in the early campaign for the 2000 elections, the rite of
political piety has moved far beyond the sacramental photo
opportunity. The candidates are engaging in ``God talk'' that is
more explicit, more intimate and more pervasive than at any time in
recent decades, historians and political analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   In a Houston church, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas describes his
decision to ``recommit my life to Jesus Christ.'' At a convention
of black Baptists, Vice President Al Gore declares himself ``a
child of the Kingdom and a person of strong faith.'' And at a
prayer breakfast in Philadelphia, Elizabeth Dole recounts a talk
she had with God. This is now common language on the campaign
trail.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this presidential contest there is much more discussion of
personal faith than there has been in the past,'' said John Green,
who studies how politics intersect religion as director of the Ray
Bliss Institute of Applied Politics at the University of Akron, in
Ohio. ``I suppose if you went far back enough in American history
you'd probably find a year like this one. But if you just think of
the last 20 years, more candidates are talking more openly about
their personal faith now.''
</P>
<P>
   The phenomenon is not confined to politics. This is an era in
which public figures of all kinds are ``coming out'' about their
private spirituality. Madonna gives interviews about studying
Kabbala, or Jewish mysticism. The singer Lauryn Hill brings a Bible
on stage to accept a Grammy award and reads a Psalm aloud. The
actors Richard Gere and Harrison Ford meditate at a Tibetan
Buddhist ritual led by the Dalai Lama.
</P>
<P>
   Politics, however, has its own rhythms, and there are particular
reasons why the candidates are now waving the flag of faith. The
most urgent reason, political analysts agree, is that in a nation
weary of White House scandal, the candidates must find ways to
signal that they can be trusted behind the Oval Office doors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's driven by the post-Monica hangover, almost like a drunk
reaching for the black coffee,'' said a Bush adviser.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Reeves, a historian at the University of
Wisconsin-Parkside, in Kenosha, and the author of ``A Question of
Character: A Life of John F. Kennedy'' (The Free Press, 1991), said
that the candidates ``are trying to distance themselves from the
squalor of the Clintons.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The language itself isn't new at all,'' Reeves said. ``James
Garfield and Rutherford B. Hayes made the point that they were
church members and spoke very staunchly about their faith, their
church affiliations and the union of God and country. They did it
because the politics of the Gilded Age were so squalid and so
corrupt. Candidates, then and now, are trying to say that they
stand above the mess that people perceive.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Bush, a Republican, and Gore, a Democrat, are promoting
charities run by churches and religious organizations as an
antidote to government welfare. But this is not the first time that
presidential candidates have linked piety and public policy, Reeves
said. Abolition of slavery, prohibition and even Theodore
Roosevelt's environmentalism were all proclaimed as ``godly''
policies, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But right now, the presidential contenders are responding to
polls showing that Americans are focused on immorality as the basis
of many social ills. Asked whether they were more concerned about
the nation's moral problems or economic problems, 58 percent of
Americans said moral problems, while 38 percent said economic
problems, according to a poll of 1,022 adults in a CNN/Gallup
survey conducted in February.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has something to do with the presidential scandals, and
the school shootings like the one in Littleton,'' Green said.
``There is a sense of disquiet in the land, and I think these
candidates have picked this up in their polling, in talking to
people. And when people are faced with existential issues, they
tend to turn back to religion, and that's not just conservatives,
it's everybody. Religion is a source of moral grounding.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican candidates especially know they must find ways to
appeal to the crucial evangelical voting bloc. For candidates like
Gary Bauer, Steve Forbes, Pat Buchanan and Alan Keyes, this is no
challenge; they stand with religious conservatives firmly against
abortion and homosexuality and for organized school prayer.
</P>
<P>
   But for a candidate like Bush, who is playing to the center on
those issues, his frequent religious testimony is ``almost like a
surrogate for the more hard-edged moral agenda of the party,'' said
the Bush adviser, who put the candidate's position this way:
</P>
<P>
   ``What he is doing is like saying to the social conservative
wing, `I can't say everything you want me to say, or propose
everything you want me to propose, but I want you to know that in
my heart or in my soul, I'm where you are personally. And what I
can accomplish, I will accomplish, and you can trust that.' In the
end, I think that formula will work, that he will be able to get
his fair market share of religious activists in the primaries.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Michael Cromartie, a senior fellow at the Ethics and Public
Policy Center in Washington, said, ``A little bit of religiosity
can cover a multitude of sins, and it can cover a multitude of
political sins.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see it with Elizabeth Dole,'' Cromartie said. ``A lot
of religious conservative folk are really unimpressed with her
ability to waffle on just about everything, but when they hear her
talking religious language, they think, `She may not be clear on
abortion, and on a multitude of other issues I care about, but she
loves Jesus.'''
</P>
<P>
   But not all the ``God talk'' can be chalked up to mere
posturing. Many of this crop of candidates are churchgoers who say
they read the Bible regularly and look to God and Scriptures for
guidance. Mrs. Dole, long before she or her husband were
presidential candidates, gave speeches ``witnessing'' her turn
toward God. After his Army service in Vietnam, Gore attended
divinity school briefly. And Bush says his faith in God is what
helped him give up alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   When Gore summoned religion writers to the White House in May
for an interview, he was asked whether he was trying to reclaim
religion from the conservatives. ``No,'' he said, ``I'm just trying
to be who I am.''
</P>
<P>
   But one unspoken rule is that the only candidates who benefit by
emphasizing their religious bona fides are Protestants. Former
presidential candidate Michael Dukakis, of Greek Orthodox heritage
and married to a Jew, avoided religious talk. President Kennedy,
the first and only Roman Catholic president, had to deflect slurs
about handing over the country to Vatican control. Buchanan and
Keyes, both Roman Catholics, use religious language that is
indistinct from that of evangelical Protestants.
</P>
<P>
   The evangelical talk of being ``born again,'' greeted as exotic
back in 1976 when used by Jimmy Carter, is now commonplace.
Clinton, a Southern Baptist, has displayed an ease with evangelical
language and Biblical reference that he put to use in his campaigns
and as president.
</P>
<P>
   It is paradoxical, says Nathan Hatch, professor of history and
provost at the University of Notre Dame, that religious talk is so
commonplace as the nation becomes increasingly diverse religiously
and ethnically. ``It's a far more diverse culture, so there's far
less one can assume'' about morality and religion, Hatch said.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, said Reeves, the historian, invoking ``American
civil religion, one nation under God, is almost a prerequisite''
for a presidential candidate today. ``The public eats it up,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wouldn't it be wonderful if you saw a candidate come along now
who said, `I'm an atheist,' just for a change of pace?'' Reeves
said.
</P>
<P>
   And what chance would that candidate have of winning? ``None,''
Reeves said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
