<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-ARCTIC-REDTAPE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ARCTIC TESTAMENT TO PRIVATE ENTERPRISE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By MICHAEL POLLAK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Scurvy, frostbite, exhaustion, starvation, faulty maps, terror
of the unknown _ but of all the adversaries of the Arctic explorers
of the 19th century, the most dangerous foe was government
bureaucracy, says Dr. Jonathan M. Karpoff, a professor of finance
at the University of Washington School of Business.
</P>
<P>
   Karpoff recently analyzed 35 government and 56 privately
financed Arctic expeditions from 1818 to 1909, originating from the
United States, Britain and elsewhere in Europe. The average death
rate was 9 percent on the public expeditions and 6 percent on the
private ones. Public explorations lost an average of 198 tons of
shipping; the private loss was 60 tons. Of expeditions lasting more
than one year, 47 percent of the public but only 13 percent of the
private ones were debilitated by scurvy, caused in part by lack of
vitamin C.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be sure, most leaders of government-funded expeditions
performed courageously,'' Karpoff wrote, adding that many privately
financed trips were disasters. The differences, Karpoff wrote, were
primarily related to differences in the ways public and private
expeditions were organized.
</P>
<P>
   According to historical accounts, the people initiating and
organizing public expeditions actually led them only 27 percent of
the time, compared with 78 percent for the private journeys.
Because of this, Karpoff wrote, ``the organizers of the public
expeditions faced few of the negative consequences of poor planning
or erroneous theories.''
</P>
<P>
   Private leaders were more enthusiastic about the Arctic and less
hampered by rank or tradition, he noted. They were more likely to
listen to fur trappers, Inuits and their own crews on equipment,
clothing and shelter. Private parties relied more on fresh meat, a
better source of vitamin C than salt meat, the staple of many
public expeditions.
</P>
<P>
   While extrapolating from the class-ridden 19th century to the
modern age is difficult, Karpoff said that such programs as the
Human Genome Project and space exploration might benefit from the
Arctic's lessons of leadership and motivation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-99 2015EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
