<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4996 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-SUN-STAR-OFFICE-NYT &LR;      08-30 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUN-STAR-OFFICE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIMING AT MICROSOFT OFFICE, SUN ACQUIRES STAR
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Germany)   (Eds., skedded earlier as SUN-WEB-SOFTWARE) 
(DW) 
 By STEVE LOHR    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sun Microsystems Inc. is planning an ambitious campaign to move
everyday software applications like word processing and
spreadsheets away from the personal computer desktop and onto the
World Wide Web _ a strategy that amounts to a direct assault on
Microsoft's biggest business.
</P>
<P>
   Sun is announcing Tuesday that it has acquired Star Division
GmbH, a German producer of office productivity software, which
moved its headquarters to California last year. Its Star Office is
a bundle of programs _ word processors, spreadsheets, schedulers,
personal data base and presentation software _ in the same
application categories as the Microsoft Corp.'s Office suite, the
industry leader.
</P>
<P>
   Star Office has received favorable reviews in the trade press,
and it has a devoted following among users of the Linux operating
system, the only market where Star's productivity suite is No. 1.
Still, the Star Office product has yet to move beyond niche status.
</P>
<P>
   But at a New York news conference Tuesday, Sun is to lay out its
plan to to try to catapult Star Office into the mainstream of
computer software. The company, according to Sun executives, will
allow anyone to download Star Office over the Internet free. More
significantly, Sun intends to transform the product from software
that resides on the hard disk of a PC or work station into a
Web-based application that a user with Internet access can tap into
from an emerging array of devices other than PCs, like hand-held
computers and cellular telephones with screens.
</P>
<P>
   In Silicon Valley, there is no greater focal point of
programming talent and venture investment than the new field of
Web-based applications. These are software applications that run
mainly on powerful central computers and can be reached over the
Internet by a user with a browser. Some early applications,
particularly Web-based e-mail, have been quite popular. Microsoft
itself owns one of the leading Web e-mail systems, Hotmail, and
earlier this year purchased Jump Inc., a maker of online personal
calendar software.
</P>
<P>
   Web-based applications are the software building blocks of what
some industry analysts see as a coming post-PC era. By that, they
do not mean the demise of the personal computer, but they see the
center of gravity in computing _ technology development and user
interest _ gradually shifting from the PC to the Internet and the
Web.
</P>
<P>
   Sun's plan for Star Office, analysts say, represents a bold
attempt to try to hasten the arrival of a post-PC era. But Sun is
not describing its move as a head-on confrontation with Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this was mainly about taking on Microsoft,'' said Edward J.
Zander, the president of Sun, ``we would have done this five years
ago and taken them on with a fat client,'' meaning desktop
software.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's really behind this,'' Zander added, ``is that the
networked model of computing is finally starting to take off.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet for Microsoft, the rise of Web software is similar to the
challenge that the rise of microprocessor-based computing was for
IBM back in the days when mainframes still ruled the computer
industry. No one expects users to abandon Microsoft's PC software
technology, just as IBM mainframes never disappeared. But the
emergence of a low-cost software alternative could well pose a
threat to Microsoft's stratospheric profit margins, and thus its
stock price, employee incentives and business model.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is another attempt by Sun to chip away at Microsoft's
dominance,'' said Richard Shaffer, principal of Technologic
Partners, a research firm. ``Anything that slows Microsoft is good
for Sun. That has been Sun's strategy for years.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the impact on Microsoft, Sun benefits from
anything that stimulates Internet computing. It is a leading
producer of the big server computers that power many major Web
sites, and it created the Internet programming language Java. While
Sun will make Star Office available free, it does plan to charge
for technical support and maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   If any company has a chance at making inroads against
Microsoft's Office it may well be Sun Microsystems, which has the
money and technology expertise to market Star Office aggressively.
Sun, as part of a three-way deal struck last year, has close ties
to a pair of Internet powers, America Online and its subsidiary,
Netscape Communications.
</P>
<P>
   Star says its software is ``completely interoperable'' with the
Microsoft Office file formats, like .doc for word processing and
.xls for spreadsheets. Star Office runs on several operating
systems including Microsoft's Windows, Sun's Solaris, IBM's OS/2
and Linux.
</P>
<P>
   Still, analysts agree that Sun faces a daunting challenge.
Microsoft's hold on the market for office-productivity software is,
if anything, even firmer than its grip on the market for
operating-system software with Windows. For millions of users
worldwide, Word, Excel and Powerpoint _ Microsoft's word
processing, spreadsheet and presentation programs _ constitute a
universal language of modern computer-mediated business. Getting
people to switch to anything else will be a formidable hurdle.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, analysts estimate, derives about half its revenue
from its Office product line, and it will fiercely defend that
franchise. Microsoft, they add, has a decade's worth of experience
with Office.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question that Web-hosted applications are an
interesting concept,'' said David Readerman, an analyst with Thomas
Weisel Partners, an investment firm in San Francisco, ``but this is
going to get down to the real features and functionality of the
software. Millions and millions of people use Microsoft Office and
they like it. What is possibly going to be so compelling that they
would want to switch?''
</P>
<P>
   The purchase price for Star, a private company with 200
employees, was not disclosed. But Sun has long been familiar with
Star since Andreas von Bechtolsheim, a founder of Sun and a
computer work station pioneer, made a personal investment in Star
in 1992. Marco Boeries, who founded Star in 1985, will become a
vice president of Sun and general manager of its software
applications unit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
