<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-MP331-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cox Interactive Media, MP3 to unveil Net radio service
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Everyone's been wondering what Atlanta-based Cox
Interactive Media would do with the large stake it recently bought
in MP3.com.
</P>
<P>
   Today, at the National Association of Broadcasters convention in
Orlando, Fla., the companies will announce the birth of
MP3radio.com.
</P>
<P>
   But what in the world is MP3 radio?
</P>
<P>
   Imagine all the Web's best applications rolled up into one and
you might have something that looks a lot like MP3radio.com.
</P>
<P>
   MP3radio.com will offer radio stations a variety of products to
turn their Web sites into major online destinations. In addition to
MP3 downloadable music files, listeners will also be able to buy
tickets and CDs, find out where their favorite artists are playing
and catch up on a variety of related news and entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   ``You probably have a favorite radio station and that station
probably has a Web site,'' says Gregg Lindahl, president and chief
operating officer of MP3radio.com. ``But even if you've been there
once, you probably haven't been back. Radio does realize they must
have the tools to compete on the Internet. The competition on the
Web isn't just radio; it's every Web site out there.''
</P>
<P>
   MP3radio.com, the first joint venture of Cox Interactive Media
and MP3.com, the Web's most popular source of music downloads, news
and information, is designed to capitalize on the strengths of both
companies.
</P>
<P>
   MP3radio.com is part of CIM's $45 million investment in MP3.com.
As part of the deal, MP3.com and CIM agreed to develop new music
sites that would incorporate Cox's portal expertise and MP3 digital
download technology.
</P>
<P>
   Cox Interactive Media is a subsidiary of Cox Enterprises, parent
company of The Atlanta Journal-Constitution. The first 60
affiliated radio stations are all owned by Cox Radio Inc., another
Cox Enterprises subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was expected that Cox and MP3.com would take advantage of
their relationship to expand the Cox radio reach on the Web,'' says
Forrester Research analyst Mark Hardie. ``By tying into MP3.com,
they are tying into the white hot center of the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   MP3radio.com will build a series of music portals for its
affiliated stations across the country corresponding to seven radio
formats including alternative, top 40, country, rock and urban.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll provide a network of programming that is relevant to the
music community,'' Lindahl says. ``For example, for a country music
station, we might also provide news about auto racing. Alternative
music stations will include information about local bands and
clubs.''
</P>
<P>
   MP3radio.com will offer affiliated radio stations more than
25,000 MP3 files that are currently available on the MP3.com site.
``The ability to download music from a radio Web site is a way for
radio stations to promote their sites,'' Lindahl says. ``It gives
users something to do.''
</P>
<P>
   But Forrester's Hardie says the real issue is how to make money
from their Web site traffic. ``There is a crying need for filtering
and editorial. MP3.com is a big flea market and someone has to come
in and create more filtered offerings for radio stations that just
don't have the time. That would be a valuable resource.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, MP3radio.com hopes to offer music downloads from
nationally known hit makers as well as local favorites, but for the
time being the company is still waiting for the music industry to
accept music downloads as an alternative promotion and revenue
stream.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have a music industry relations person who will work
with the artists and the labels to sort these issues out,'' Lindahl
says. As a longtime radio executive, he believes the relationship
between the radio industry and the music industry might help major
labels come around to the idea of MP3.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a very symbiotic relationship between radio and the
music industry,'' he says. ``This is just another extention of
reach and branding for radio. It gives stations the ability to bond
with their listeners. I believe artists and record companies will
want to continue to be part of that bonding process.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
