<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-CIVILITY31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Parents to get lessons in civility
 &HT;    By Paul Donsky
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ They get too rowdy during school sporting events and
sometimes yell or even curse at teachers.
</P>
<P>
   One Georgia school system has decided enough is enough and is
drafting a ``civility policy'' aimed not at students, but at their
parents and other adult visitors.
</P>
<P>
   The policy would ``set conduct for people when they enter the
building,'' Fayette County Superintendent John DeCotis said. It's
not that Fayette has had many problems with disruptive parents, he
said, though ``we have had administrators who have had to contact
police.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia law already allows administrators to remove disruptive
people from school property, and the proposed policy to be
discussed by the Fayette school board Thursday doesn't include any
new punishment. DeCotis said he's hoping that simply telling
parents they ought to behave should do the trick. Fayette
apparently would be the first school system in metro Atlanta to
have a behavior policy that includes parents and other adults.
</P>
<P>
   The policy states that ``district staff should treat parents and
other members of the public with respect and expect the same in
return. ... It is not intended to deprive any person of his or her
right to freedom of expression. In the interest of presenting
teachers, other employees, parents and other adults as positive
role models, the school system encourages positive communication
and discourages volatile, hostile, or aggressive actions.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim Callahan, spokesman for the Professional Association of
Georgia Educators, likes the idea. ``I think it's good that we
remind ourselves that this is a civil society, and (that) students
learn by example.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
