<DOCNO> NYT19990830.0398 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 20:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5016 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-HOLLYWOOD-TREND-LADN     08-30 1682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLYWOOD-TREND-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVIES ABOUT MOVIEMAKING ARE ALL THE RAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB STRAUSS  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ You can't get away from the movies these days.
</P>
<P>
   Not even at the movies.
</P>
<P>
   Movie-dependent entertainment publications, television shows,
Internet sites and even whole cable networks have proliferated over
the last decade or so. At the same time, general media outlets have
increased film coverage to the point that anyone in Iowa or Maine
can read the weekend grosses in their local newspaper, Roberto
Benigni is considered a great catch for the venerable news show
``60 Minutes,'' and both Time and Newsweek publish simultaneous
cover stories about ``The Blair Witch Project.''
</P>
<P>
   With movies being hyped at us like never before and from every
corner of the culture, it's no surprise that the people who are
most responsible for the phenomenon are addressing the subject at
an unprecedented rate, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hollywood, over the last number of years, has gotten more and
more filled with itself from seeing more and more programs about
itself,'' observes Albert Brooks, who's made and appeared in
several films about filmmakers (``Real Life,'' ``Modern Romance,''
``I'll Do Anything'') and plays a screenwriter in his latest
comedy, ``The Muse.'' ``You know, Hollywood is the most
self-promoting entity in the history of our planet. First came
`Entertainment Tonight,' then `Access Hollywood,' then the E!
Entertainment network started to get big viewers. The proliferation
of that sort of made Hollywood this pervasive subject that people
can't get out of their minds.''
</P>
<P>
   And the overload of information, not just gossip but a
substantial portion of inside-baseball data that only hard-core
Hollywood types understood just a few years ago, has increased
audiences' show-biz savvy.
</P>
<P>
   This has enabled the current crop of people making films about
films to move beyond the ain't-Hollywood-wacky? approach of earlier
generations and the aren't-movie-people-awful? expose that's
dominated the genre for most of the '90s. Now, they can reference
all kinds of film-world facts and notions with the confidence that
ever-larger audiences will get and appreciate them.
</P>
<P>
   For example, part of ``Notting Hill's'' big international
success was built on the reality blur between the emotionally
flighty, paparazzi-stalked movie star Julia Roberts played and
everyone's knowledge of the actress' real-life tabloid traumas.
``Blair Witch'' became the most profitable cost-to-revenues release
of all time by both convincing much of the market that it was a
true story and creating a brilliant metaphor for a much-reported
subject _ independent filmmakers' fears of disappearing off the
media map.
</P>
<P>
   Even this year's $100 million-grossing, Oscar-winning
``Shakespeare in Love'' is rich in jokes about how today's
Hollywood operates, a factor that surely made it accessible to many
people who would otherwise find its Elizabethan-era setting hard to
relate to.
</P>
<P>
   While both of recently released satires ``Bowfinger'' and ``The
Muse'' lean heavily on stereotypes such as cutthroat executives,
clueless creatives, paranoid superstars and starlets who sleep
their way to the top, they also both presume a deeper understanding
of the Hollywood social order among average filmgoers. And novelist
Bruce Wagner, who directed the just-out-on-video adaptation of his
scathing novel, ``I'm Losing You,'' reworked the screenplay into a
much more humanistic piece about a producer's family's joys and
struggles _ resulting in one of the first Hollywood exposes in
years (last fall's ``Gods and Monsters'' was another) about fully
rounded characters as opposed to dysfunctional icons.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Oz, who directed Steve Martin and Eddie Murphy in the
Martin-scripted ``Bowfinger,'' sees an emerging era of more
realistically detailed films about film people.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are in this business for many, many reasons,'' Oz says.
``Some are just making a living, others want the biggest (power
base) in Hollywood, some want to get girls, some want to do art, or
express themselves, or please a certain group of people. There are
tons of reasons why people do things out here, and they're usually
a mix of good and not-so-good.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, movies have always been a glamorous business, and
people have been interested in them _ and those who make them _ for
the better part of a century. And that has made them a worthy, if
only occasional, subject for movies themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The early efforts tended to reflect their creators' enthusiasm
about the new medium's potential, although satire and soap opera
became part of the mix relatively quickly. The great silent
slapstick genius Buster Keaton pretty much said all that was
necessary about the movies' capacity for illusion and escape in
``Sherlock, Jr.'' (1924), where he played a projectionist who
entered into the images on the screen (Woody Allen's 1985 ``Purple
Rose of Cairo'' reversed the concept).
</P>
<P>
   Filmgoers in 1932 saw the first version of the venerable,
tragedy-behind-the-tinsel ``A Star Is Born'' formula in ``What
Price Hollywood?'' Preston Sturges paid cockeyed tribute to the
healing power of movie comedy with ``Sullivan's Travels'' (1941);
Billy Wilder explored the dark side of the Hollywood delusion in
the noir classic ``Sunset Blvd.'' (1950); Gene Kelly both lampooned
and celebrated movie magic while ``Singin' in the Rain'' (1952),
and Vincente Minnelli's ``The Bad and the Beautiful'' (1952) and
``Two Weeks in Another Town'' (1962) compellingly looked at flawed
people's struggles to do good work and sustain their careers.
</P>
<P>
   The postwar era also saw the inevitable emergence of the
movie-star biography subgenre, with highly watchable pictures about
Al Jolson (plus a sequel), Lon Chaney and dueling Jean Harlow
melodramas among the most memorable.
</P>
<P>
   The new freedoms in subject matter and form that came about in
the 1960s led to the great European filmmakers Federico Fellini
(``8{''), Ingmar Bergman (``Persona''), Jean-Luc Godard
(`Contempt'') and Francois Truffaut's (``Day for Night'')
distinctively personal works about their art form. Even in the
'80s, when Hollywood turned decisively toward the money end of its
eternal art-or-commerce debate, movies like ``The Stunt Man'' and
``Who Framed Roger Rabbit'' still balanced complaints about the
production system with palpable excitement for creative cinema.
</P>
<P>
   But while films about films have always been self-critical to
more or lesser degrees, in the 1990s the genre went almost
completely sour _ even as more movie movies than ever were
produced. The keystone _ and best _ picture on the subject to
emerge this decade was ``The Player'' (1992), a lacerating allegory
of studio amorality that its director, Robert Altman, has since
said was much too gentle.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the folks who made ``Swimming With Sharks,'' ``Barton
Fink,'' ``... And God Spoke,'' ``The New Age,'' ``Living in
Oblivion'' and ``An Alan Smithee Film: Burn Hollywood Burn'' _ all
cynical studies of venality, egomania and degeneracy on sets and in
suites _ agreed with Altman. Even the '90s films that acknowledged
moviemaking had its joyous side were ironic comedies like ``Ed
Wood,'' ``Jimmy Hollywood,'' ``Get Shorty'' and the current Brooks
and Martin releases, where the celluloid dreamers were either
talentless, rudderless or otherwise ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   Much as the recent spate of movies about television (``Wag the
Dog,'' ``The Truman Show,'' ``Pleasantville,'' ``EDtv'') all riffed
on the same idea of ``real'' people lost in video pseudo-reality,
the films-about-films genre had ossified into a predictable,
mean-spirited formula.
</P>
<P>
   Oz, whose ``Bowfinger'' mixes its barbs with an equally funny
sweetness, blames that development on creative laziness.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's much easier to do something vicious,'' he says. ``Sweet
and incisive is much more difficult than vicious.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm Losing You's'' Wagner says the genre's recent sameness was
a result of the wrong careerists putting the cart before the horse.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of it was a kind of shabby chic,'' says Wagner, who
admits his novels are as scabrous as any filmed expose. ``The idea
that you were making some monstrous observation of this town
somehow had cachet for people. Robert Altman is an exception _ he's
a daring and adventurous artist. But these endless shows that are
winking acknowledgments to the business _ that we're all so witty
by examining ourselves, that's just a part of the overall
self-obsessed, narcissistic trend of the culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``If characters captivate you, and they happen to work in the
industry, that's enough,'' Wagner says. ``The idea that I'm going
to write a Hollywood genre piece first and then chase the idea with
characters, that's an absurdity to me.''
</P>
<P>
   As it may well be to the general public. For all their often
smart exposure of film-biz misbehavior _ an approach that
paralleled, interestingly enough, the focus on malfeasance, excess
and outrageousness that marked the rising tide of serious
entertainment journalism through the early and mid-'90s _ the nasty
movie movies weren't nearly as popular as the more forgiving and/or
imaginative entries we've seen in the last 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the overload of movie info, despite its emphasis on hype
and superficiality, has by sheer volume opened audiences' minds to
a wider range of films about the subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just have faith in people coming along,'' Oz says, apropos
to both new filmmakers and audiences with sharper receptors for
their original ideas. ``There's always a fresh, young approach that
comes along that, hopefully, will not be part of a genre but will
spearhead something new.''
</P>
<P>
   And hasn't that really been the most fascinating aspect of the
ever-changing, sometimes even improving medium of movies over the
last 100 years?
</P>
<P>
   ``Art ultimately widens a genre,'' Wagner concludes. ``If you do
make art, everyone benefits, just as when you do things for hollow
reasons, the world gets smaller.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
