<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5017 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-HOLLYWOOD-KRONKE-LADN     08-30 1679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLYWOOD-KRONKE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV SERIES PULL BACK MAGIC CURTAIN ON INDUSTRY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
(RUNS WITH HOLLYWOOD-TREND) 
By DAVID KRONKE 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Who needed to read Daily Variety, the
entertainment industry's trade newspaper, when there was ``The
Larry Sanders Show''? Garry Shandling's acclaimed HBO series about
the backstage bickering at a late-night talk show took a
ground-breaking view of the back-stabbing particulars of both the
``show'' and the ``business'' of show biz. Shandling routinely
recruited Hollywood players portraying themselves _ or satirical
variations thereof _ to blur the lines between mockery and TV's
surreal reality. It was perhaps the most insightful yet grisly
examination of an industry since Upton Sinclair took on meatpacking
in ``The Jungle.''
</P>
<P>
   Though few viewers may have watched poor Larry, the industry
certainly did, and it took notes. The series has proven to be
remarkably influential, with a number of TV series seeking to
replicate its deft blend of fact and fiction about the
entertainment industry and inviting celebrities to play, even mock,
themselves in fictional settings.
</P>
<P>
   ``People _ viewers, readers _ love to get behind the scenes,''
observes Ted Harbert, new president of NBC Studios and executive
producer of ``It's Like, You Know'' _ a sitcom which upped the ante
in the blurring-the-lines sweepstakes by hiring washed-up actress
Jennifer Grey to play washed-up actress Jennifer Grey and make fun
of her nose job, her stalled career and her sex life.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the reason talk shows work, that's why award shows and
game shows like `Hollywood Squares' work _ because you get to see
the stars being themselves,'' Harbert continues. ``So the idea of a
star playing himself in a fiction sitcom is, I don't want to go so
far as to say irresistible, but you're going to want to check out
what Jennifer Grey says about herself in the show. There isn't much
in the show that hasn't happened to one of us in the entertainment
industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, those entertainers are increasingly turning inward to
examine the phenomenon of the fascination they inspire. Such
television series as ABC's ``Sports Night,'' the WB's ``Movie
Stars,'' Showtime's ``Beggars and Choosers'' and Fox's upcoming
provocation, ``Action,'' are placed unabashedly in the world of
entertainment. NBC's ``Frasier'' is a radio star, and a lead
character in ABC's new ``Wasteland'' is a soap opera star.
</P>
<P>
   Some series use other media also populated by the powerful and
glamorous, like magazines in NBC's workplace sitcoms ``Just Shoot
Me'' and ``Suddenly Susan,'' and the world of book publishing in
NBC's impending ``Stark Raving Mad'' and ABC's upcoming ``Then Came
You,'' as entertainment-industry proxies.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, a number of new shows _ ``Get Real,'' ``Once and
Again,'' ``Malcolm in the Middle'' and ``The Mike O'Malley Show'' _
feature characters who address the camera, as if they're ersatz
celebrities starring in documentaries about their own lives. These
series try to use the prism of the medium itself to reflect a more
``real'' reality, using Hollywood technique to strip away,
allegedly, Hollywood gloss.
</P>
<P>
   It's a canny gambit, as audiences clearly are responding to
entertainments eschewing the usual high production values in favor
of something more immediate and ``real'' seeming. Witness the
success of the film ``The Blair Witch Project,'' or the live,
on-the-fly ABC game show ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire,'' or any
of the tabloid-style talk shows, or the endless freeway chases
local TV interrupts all these other programs to present.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think `Larry Sanders' did to some extent start this,'' says
Peter Lefcourt, executive producer of ``Beggars and Choosers,''
about the travails of the president of programming of a fictional
TV network who contends with temperamental ``artists,'' conniving
fellow executives and demented superiors.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a taboo. Doing TV about the TV industry, the fear
was demythologizing to some extent _ show people how the sausage is
made, and they're gonna say `This is not magic, this is not
special.' But the industry realized that there's a whole kind of
reservoir of great material that can be done, and how many cop
shows and lawyer shows and medical shows can you do?''
</P>
<P>
   James Widdoes, co-creator and executive producer of ``Movie
Stars,'' says that viewers were interested in all things before and
behind the camera well before ``Sanders'' entered TV's landscape.
</P>
<P>
   ```Entertainment Tonight' started it,'' Widdoes says. ``The
success of that show and everything that came after it _ the
magazines and all that stuff _ that began it all.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, since the dawn of the medium, TV series have focused
on the entertainment world.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the most legendary of all sitcoms, ``I Love Lucy,''
which often centered on Lucy's aching to get a taste of her
bandleader husband Ricky's stardom and their forays into Hollywood
lifestyles.
</P>
<P>
   The classic ``The Dick Van Dyke Show,'' about variety series
writer Rob Petrie, has been the benchmark for fond evocations of
the show-biz ethos. Even the most recent TV sitcom phenomenon,
``Seinfeld,'' featured Jerry Seinfeld as a stand-up comedian (and,
therefore, in possession of a lot of free time on his hands to get
into wacky predicaments) who tried for a while to break into TV on
NBC.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood certainly is a milieu with which those creating a show
are familiar, and it doesn't entail any tedious research into the
lives and workplaces of teachers, candlestick makers or sanitation
engineers.
</P>
<P>
   Following ``Larry Sanders'' lead, series such as ``Sports
Night,'' ``It's Like, You Know,'' ``Movie Stars,'' ``Action'' and
the late ``Lateline,'' all feature celebrities playing themselves
in cameo appearances. Such cameos are often self-deprecating, but,
given the subtext that the participant is in on a joke about him-
or herself that mainstream America will appreciate, they can also
be self-aggrandizing.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Mehlman, creator and executive producer of ``It's Like,
You Know,'' credits ``Larry Sanders'' for awakening Hollywood to
the upside of being a good sport by playing a bad sport in a
fictional setting.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are realizing the benefits of not taking themselves so
seriously,'' he says. ``Everybody takes themselves so seriously out
here. Every quote, every newspaper article's like, you know, the
end of the world. I said to Jennifer, `You're gonna get all this
stuff, with the nose and everything like that; it's all just words.
Have fun with it. It's not going to change who you are or
anything.' People are realizing it doesn't change their lives if
they have fun with themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Thompson, creator of ``Action,'' about a venal action-film
producer, suggests that for creators of these series, showing the
industry's bad behavior for all the world to see can be cathartic
for writers and performers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a town about bad behavior _ everything that goes on in
the show is about bad behavior that I've seen, heard of, or
probably participated in,'' Thompson says. ``And the verisimilitude
of that, the reality of that and the funniness of that is what
we're going after.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson adds that his series will concern ``how much of his
soul he has to sell in order to get his film made. Hopefully, we're
playing with all those moral themes _ in this carnivorous world,
how does one survive and keep something about yourself that's human
intact?''
</P>
<P>
   This trend of looking inward also comes at a time when some
creative minds are feeling there's little new to do with the sitcom
format, so a little postmodern, self-reflexive fun can shake it
from its doldrums.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been a long-standing taboo amongst TV executives _
under no circumstances will we do a show about this industry,''
says Widdoes. ``And we just thought the time is right to see if
some of this inside stuff really works.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've read a lot of Philip Roth, and I love the way he blurs
the line between reality and fiction, and that's what I want to
do,'' Mehlman adds. ``To be perfectly honest, I'm trying to avoid
getting bored with this form. I was on `Seinfeld' (as a writer and
executive producer) for seven years, and I'm in great danger of
getting bored doing standard shows.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether their stories will play to audiences unfamiliar
with how the entertainment industry operates, both Lefcourt and
Thompson, in separate interviews, said essentially the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson: ``If you watch `ER,' you don't have to know how to
bisect a colon to sit there and watch the show and enjoy what's
going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Lefcourt: ``That's a fight I have every now and then with
Showtime, they say, `Will people understand this inside-baseball
stuff?' and I say, `A guy walks into `ER' and a guy says `We've
gotta bifurcate the artery' _ that isn't common conversation
either, but it plays. &QL; 
``The television business is just faster than most businesses,''
Lefcourt continues. ``The money is crazy; the egos are crazy. But
essentially there is a business there. And anybody who works at a
big insurance company or advertising agency may in fact relate to
some of the paranoia of job security that we deal with here.''
</P>
<P>
   But is this obsession with the world of entertainment _
Hollywood's own, and, particularly, ours _ healthy? Is getting
immersed in the facts of the fantasy factories good for our
self-image, for maintaining a sense of perspective in our own
lives?
</P>
<P>
   Widdoes smiles sheepishly. ``That's a very profound question,''
he says. ``We make things out of whole cloth here, we make
entertainment. Are we curing cancer? No.''
</P>
<P>
   He pauses for a moment. ``No,'' he repeats for emphasis. ``I
wish I could do a really smart comedy about the fact that America's
children are getting dumber every year. I can't come up with the
concept. So I have to do shows that afford me he opportunity to
make sure that my kids get the best education (START ITAL)they(END
ITAL) can.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
