<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 20:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5019 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-BUSH-LAWSUIT31-COX     08-30 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-LAWSUIT31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush spared questioning in lawsuit
 &HT;    By Juan B. Elizondo Jr.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush will not have to answer
questions in a lawsuit against the Texas Funeral Service Commission
and Service Corporation International, the world's largest funeral
service company, a Travis County judge decided Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Bush repeatedly has said he knows nothing about a 1998 funeral
commission investigation of SCI nor a dispute that arose from it
that led to the lawsuit, which has drawn national attention because
of Bush's front-running presidential status.
</P>
<P>
   ``This ruling is an important one for Governor Bush and for
future governors because it essentially says that the governor
should not be used to generate publicity for lawsuits in which he
is not involved,'' said Bush spokesman Ray Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has been accused of showing favoritism to SCI founder and
chief executive Robert Waltrip, who is a longtime Bush family
supporter. Bush has called the lawsuit ``frivolous.''
</P>
<P>
   Former funeral commission director Eliza May, who sued the
agency and company after being fired in February, has argued that
SCI and Bush's office worked together to interfere with the
investigation and her job. May claims she was fired for complaining
about that interference. On Monday, her attorney called Bush a
co-conspirator in the effort, though he is not a defendant in the
case.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General John Cornyn, who argued on Bush's behalf,
called the accusation reckless innuendo that was not supported by
any evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe it's baseless,'' Cornyn said, adding that the claim
likely is related to Bush's bid for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's attorneys, citing statements from the eight funeral
service commissioners who voted to fire May, said the former
director was dismissed for a variety of legitimate reasons,
including a lack of confidence in her leadership. Each of the
commissioners said their decision was made independently of the
governor's office and SCI.
</P>
<P>
   In ruling that Bush doesn't have to give a deposition, District
Judge John Dietz said May's attorneys did not prove that the
governor has any knowledge of the investigation or her firing. He
also said that any information the governor might have can be
obtained from other sources.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of what has been alleged ... was witnessed by others,''
Dietz said.
</P>
<P>
   Dietz also rejected the idea that May's attorneys have a right
to question Bush because he filed what they call a false statement
in the case. They said Bush has knowledge of the investigation and
his office's interference partly because of a quote from SCI
attorney Johnnie B. Rogers in Newsweek magazine.
</P>
<P>
   The publication quoted Rogers as saying that during a 1998 visit
with aides at Bush's office, the governor stopped by and asked
Waltrip, ``Are those people still messing with you?''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers on Monday denied the quote, said he didn't remember what
he told the magazine, but then added that he was certain he didn't
say ``those people.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers said SCI wasn't seeking Bush's help to end the
investigation but was complaining about the hostile way the
investigation was being conducted.
</P>
<P>
   According to May's lawsuit, top Bush aides threatened to take
away the investigation if it was not quickly resolved. She also
said the aides tried to intimidate and harass her.
</P>
<P>
   May said the threats came at Bush's request. And her attorneys
argued that Bush has denied only that he has no personal knowledge
of the investigation, but has not addressed what, if any,
conversations he had with his staff about it.
</P>
<P>
   May's attorneys said they had not decided whether to appeal
Dietz's ruling, but will move forward with questioning other people
in the case, including former Bush aide Joe Albaugh, now the
manager for Bush's presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's office says no one from the office threatened or
intimidated May.
</P>
<P>
   May's investigation resulted in fines of $445,000 against SCI.
Among other things, the commission said SCI used unlicensed
embalmers to conduct services at unlicensed locations.
</P>
<P>
   SCI officials say the commission misinterpreted the law and
Cornyn has issued a legal opinion that SCI has used to support that
claim.
</P>
<P>
   Dietz didn't consider arguments over May's request to hold Bush
in contempt for filing his affidavit, which she says is false. Her
attorneys said they will pursue that motion, but Cornyn said
there's nothing to prove Bush did not tell the truth.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
