<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 20:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5021 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f BC-ARCO-MERGER-LADN     08-30 0599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARCO-MERGER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARCO SHAREHOLDERS OK SALE TO BP AMOCO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY JASON TAKENOUCHI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Arco shareholders voted overwhelmingly to approve
a $36 billion sale to British petroleum giant BP Amoco on Monday,
but several key questions remain about the merger's effect on
Arco's Los Angeles headquarters and the company's 3,000 employees
in the region.
</P>
<P>
   In a special vote at the Los Angeles Downtown Marriott hotel,
more than 97 percent of Arco shareholders in attendance approved
the transaction. In all, 75 percent of total shareholders approved
the sale of Atlantic Richfield Co.The merger still needs the
approval of U.S. and European Union regulators and the shareholders
of BP Amoco. Company officials expect it to close by year-end.
</P>
<P>
   After the vote, Mike Bowlin, Arco's chairman and chief executive
officer, offered few specifics on what the transaction means for
the company's employees, its charitable activities and its downtown
Los Angeles headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Bowlin said as many as 2,000 workers may be laid off companywide
_ an estimate that some analysts said was too few _ but he did not
say where those cuts would happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We recognize the anxiety and uncertaintly this causes,''
Bowlin said.
</P>
<P>
   In the Los Angeles area, a ``good portion'' of the approximately
700 workers in the company's corporate and related offices are
likely to face layoffs, said Arco spokeswoman Marylou Flynn.
</P>
<P>
   Bowlin also said London-based BP Amoco would maintain a presence
at the Arco Center, but it was unclear how large that presence
would be.
</P>
<P>
   And although he assured shareholders that BP Amoco has committed
to continue Arco's longtime support of charitable causes, Bowlin
said the details of future giving are up to Arco's new parent
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's got to be discussed and announced by BP Amoco,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Arco, the eighth-largest U.S. oil company, donated about $14
million to charity last year, according to the company. About 30
percent of that money went to the Los Angeles area.
</P>
<P>
   Arco's top employees will not have to wait for details of their
severence packages, though.
</P>
<P>
   According to the company's latest proxy statement to
shareholders, the merger will trigger lucrative pay-out packages
for many outgoing employees.
</P>
<P>
   Bowlin, a 31-year Arco employee, will receive over $27.5
million. Company President Michael Wiley and Chief Financial
Officer Marie Knowles will each receive over $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the company's top five officers will receive over $63
million, according to the proxy statement.
</P>
<P>
   As proposed, the merger would give Arco shareholders 0.82 shares
of BP Amoco American depository shares for each share of Arco. BP
would also assume about $7 billion in Arco debt.
</P>
<P>
   BP shareholders will vote on the deal Wednesday in London.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say the proposed merger will give BP Amoco a step up in
an oil industry that has been consolidating rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now you have a completely new ball game,'' said Fadel Gheit, a
senior analyst with Fahnestock and Co. in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Bowlin acknowledged the market's current merger imperative
Monday, telling shareholders that ``bigger is better in today's oil
and gas industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Shareholder and former Arco employee Robert Chambers said Arco
veterans, including its thousands of retirees, will miss the
venerable firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to have a lot of people that feel sad,'' Chambers
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But life changes,'' he added, ``and certainly the economy
changes.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
