<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5024 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-NEWT-CSPAN31-COX     08-30 0645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWT-CSPAN31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gingrich supports politicians' privacy
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Newt Gingrich says attacks on politicians' private
lives have no place in American politics.
</P>
<P>
   In a three-part interview about his career in Congress that
begins tonight on C-SPAN, Gingrich distinguishes between properly
criticizing President Clinton for lying to a federal grand jury and
inappropriately chastizing him for his personal behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the first place, nobody is a saint. I mean, if you believe
in God, by definition you believe nobody is a saint. So the most
religious of people should have the deepest understanding that
you're not going to elect saints, you're going to elect a sinner,
and hopefully, you elect a sinner who prays, a sinner who is
self-aware, a sinner who is responsible,'' Gingrich tells
interviewer Brian Lamb.
</P>
<P>
   The interview took place July 30, the day after Gingrich, 56,
filed for divorce from his wife, Marianne Gingrich, but before
reports surfaced that the former House speaker is involved in a
longstanding relationship with congressional aide Callista Bisek.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marianne is a wonderful person, and a very smart person, and
we've had a very long and complex relationship,'' Gingrich says.
</P>
<P>
   Of their break-up, he says, ``I think there is a cumulative
weight of the years that is debilitating.''
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich says he and Clinton talked about their ethical and
personal battles, discussions he called ``painful.''
</P>
<P>
   He says Clinton will be remembered for squandering his talent.
``People will look back at what a tragedy it was that he had so
much talent and did so little good,'' Gingrich says.
</P>
<P>
   Recounting his 20 years in Congress, Gingrich says he and Henry
Clay, a Kentuckian who served early in the 19th century, stand as
the most powerful speakers in U.S. history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was not a presider, I was the leader. And I think Henry
Clay's probably the only other speaker to have been a national
leader and speaker of the House simultaneously,'' Gingrich says.
</P>
<P>
   In his earlier years in Congress, he likens himself to the Rev.
Martin Luther King Jr. and other leaders of minority groups who had
to fight aggressively to be heard. He also describes himself as a
football coach who, after leading his team to the top, was too
battered to continue.
</P>
<P>
   But Gingrich says it was worth it to be the focal point of
Democratic criticism because his Republican majority balanced the
budget, cut taxes and reformed welfare. ``And if the price I had to
pay personally was to be demonized by the left ... sometimes you do
that,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   One area that was a frequent source of Democratic fury was
Gingrich's ethics. He agreed to a $300,000 fine in 1997 for
violating House ethics rules in connection with the financing of
the college course he taught in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   In the interview, Gingrich says repeatedly that he has since
been exonerated by the Internal Revenue Service. But tax law
specialists have said that two IRS rulings this year sent
conflicting messages about Gingrich's situation.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, the former speaker says he has no regrets about
leaving Congress this year. He stepped down after some Republicans
threatened to block his re-election as speaker following unexpected
GOP losses in the 1998 elections.
</P>
<P>
   He is now involved in several business ventures, including
speeches for up to $50,000 each, a new consulting company, and
positions on corporate boards and at think tanks.
</P>
<P>
   He periodically visits both Georgia Tech and the Centers for
Disease Control and Prevention to hear the views of experts in the
fields of high technology and public health.
</P>
<P>
   While Gingrich says he does not expect to seek office again, he
also does not rule it out.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
