<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990830.0404 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5026 &Cx1f; tad-z
s w BC-TECH-FAIRFAX-$ADV05-C     08-30 1401
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-FAIRFAX-$ADV05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FAIRFAX COUNTY RIDES HIGH-TECH BOOM TO RICHES _ AND SPRAWL
 &HT;    With TECH-FAIRFAX-DATA.
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories for
release Sunday, Sept. 5.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HERNDON, Va. _ The pastures and orchards that not long ago
produced a wealth of food here are sprouting a new bounty now:
high-tech jobs, stock options, luxury subdivisions and cars, cars,
cars.
</P>
<P>
   All over the rolling parcels of green in formerly rural Fairfax
County west of Washington, entrepreneurs are raising the heavily
wired, glass-encased office buildings that will contain the
industrial base for the Information Age.
</P>
<P>
   Working inside them are the Internet, telecom and software
executives and technicians who have helped boost Fairfax's median
household income to $87,569 _ the highest in the nation, according
to the market research firm Claritas Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Prosperity has its price. Like other high-tech hotbeds,
including Atlanta, Austin and Dallas, Fairfax County residents are
suffering from the aggravating side effects of rapid growth:
crowded schools, underdeveloped mass transit systems, skyrocketing
housing prices and the loss of trees.
</P>
<P>
   Residents complain bitterly about traffic snarls. But their
complaining is often done while sitting in BMWs, talking on sleek
cell phones. ``It's hard to complain too much,'' said Gerald
Gordon, president of the Fairfax County Economic Development
Authority, ``because what we suffer from is our affluence.''
</P>
<P>
   How this once-bucolic community figured out the future, and then
made a fortune from it, is a lesson in the value of post-urban
infrastructure. Instead of building roads, bridges and sewers to
attract new jobs, Fairfax County led in the laying of fat pipes for
computerized data.
</P>
<P>
   Because of Fairfax's advanced wiring, about two-thirds of all
Internet traffic in the world passes within a few miles of
Washington Dulles International Airport on the county's western
edge. By being able to move both data and air passengers quickly,
Fairfax is selling itself as a key port in the global economy.
Atlanta and Denver have similar strategies, but Fairfax also has
proximity to power, with the nation's capital just across the
Potomac River.
</P>
<P>
   Moving into the next century, the question facing Fairfax
residents is: Will this wiry infrastructure, bustling airport and
tight link to Washington keep the wealth growing? Or will
increasing quality-of-life problems and competition from other
cities cause high-tech businesses to pull out as fast as they built
up?
</P>
<P>
   In recent decades, Fairfax has seen nothing but growth. Before
World War II, Fairfax was a quiet Southern county with just 41,000
people thinly spread over rural acreage. But as the Pentagon
staffed up in the 1940s, Fairfax became a bedroom suburb of
Arlington, Va., and Washington. By 1950, its population was
106,000. Just a decade later, it was 272,000.
</P>
<P>
   For all the growth, Fairfax remained primarily residential and
rural, with lots of tall oaks but relatively few jobs. In the
mid-1970s, the county was still the state's leading producer of
milk.
</P>
<P>
   Though few realized it then, the seeds of Fairfax's 1990s
affluence were being planted in government computers. The Pentagon
was sponsoring the creation of Arpanet, the precursor of today's
Internet. Many of the engineers working for the government later
became founding fathers of the county's Internet giants, such as
UUNET Technologies Inc.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, other parts of the government were building
Washington Dulles, an airport whose value was not fully realized
until after the deregulation of airlines in the late 1970s and the
boom in travel in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't just air service that Dulles provided. Planners
also put a wide road through the middle of the county to connect
air travelers to Washington. Today, the Dulles Toll Road is the
main artery running through the heart of Fairfax County.
</P>
<P>
   With a pleasant climate, good air service, proximity to
Washington and a highly educated work force, Fairfax began to
market itself to entrepreneurs in the 1980s as a great place to
create jobs.
</P>
<P>
   And telecommunications companies started seeing Fairfax County
as a promised land, a place with lots of wires and computer
engineers, and all within miles of Capitol Hill. Having quick
access to Congress was important to telecom businesses lobbying for
fewer regulations. Satellite companies also settled into the area
because of their need to get government authorization for projects.
</P>
<P>
   Being near the federal government helps, too, when start-ups are
seeking contracts for work. The original Commerce Department
contract for registering Internet addresses gave rise to Network
Solutions Inc., now an e-commerce powerhouse in Fairfax.
</P>
<P>
   With Washington on one side, Dulles on the other, and lots of
brains and wires in the middle, Fairfax County boomed in the 1990s.
Contractors worked frantically to construct the office parks that
could contain the wildly growing work forces at companies such as
America Online, PSI Net Inc., Oracle Corp. and about 2,500 other
technology companies.
</P>
<P>
   In the past decade, roughly 130,000 people have moved into the
county and 20 million square feet of office space have been added.
The affluence level has rocketed up, with ``executive-style
living'' subdivisions covering former farmlands with swimming pools
and tennis courts. Pricey malls serve as town centers of sorts.
</P>
<P>
   While a few small towns are located within the county, such as
Herndon and Vienna, Fairfax is overwhelmingly defined by its lack
of urban-ness. It is a land of sprawling subdivisions, sprawling
office parks and sprawling malls.
</P>
<P>
   And cars.
</P>
<P>
   While Washington has an elaborate Metro rail system, the mass
transit system has barely penetrated Fairfax County. Seemingly
every day, local newspapers run another story about the political
battles over transportation in Northern Virginia. Everyone agrees
something must be done. The agreement stops there.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Economic Development Authority and Chamber of
Commerce continue to seek growth in the high-tech area and display
scant interest in diversifying the economy. Given the astonishing
growth in wealth that they have seen in the Internet and telecom
businesses, one could scarcely blame them for not trying to recruit
a tire factory or meat-packing plant.
</P>
<P>
   Still, seeing so many economic eggs in one high-tech basket is
some cause for concern. ``The pessimist in all of us might wonder
if it can last,'' said Tony Howard, a spokesman for county Chamber
of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   While he is abashed by the growth, Howard says the future is
bright because most of the numerous office buildings dotting the
county are generic boxes with parking decks. When one hotshot
company goes bankrupt, another company can take its space.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing unique about their buildings,'' Howard said of
the high-tech companies. ``The shell of a building is something we
would be able to make use of'' in marketing Fairfax to other
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its fantastic successes, Fairfax still has some
deficiencies as a high-tech mecca.
</P>
<P>
   For one, it has no first-tier technology research university
comparable to Atlanta's Georgia Tech or Austin's University of
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Second, venture-capital funding still lags well behind the
big-money magnets of Silicon Valley and New England.
</P>
<P>
   And now, Fairfax County has a new problem: too much success. One
of the reasons so many high-tech companies chose Fairfax was its
high quality of life. Company owners were able to lure young
workers by pointing out the area's relatively low cost of living,
low taxes, great schools and physical beauty.
</P>
<P>
   Now home prices are rising, schools are jammed and roads are
clogged. Shopping centers have replaced the barns and fields that
once added such charm to the area.
</P>
<P>
   Will these growing pains lead to a letdown for Fairfax in the
new century?
</P>
<P>
   ``Who can predict what will come next,'' Howard said. But for
now, people are still voting with their feet, running into Fairfax
at a blistering pace. ``These are really some of the best jobs in
the country,'' he said. ``And they will continue to attract the
most motivated citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-99 2059EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990830.0405 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 21:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5027 &Cx1f; tad-z
s f BC-TECH-FAIRFAX-$ADV05-C     08-30 1401
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-FAIRFAX-$ADV05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FAIRFAX COUNTY RIDES HIGH-TECH BOOM TO RICHES _ AND SPRAWL
 &HT;    With TECH-FAIRFAX-DATA.
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories for
release Sunday, Sept. 5.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
