<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5032 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-AT&AMP;T-RATES-ART-2TAKES     08-30 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT&AMP;T-RATES-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT&AMP;T LOWERS LONG-DISTANCE RATES, JOINS PRICE WAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By SAUL HANSELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T Corp. introduced lower long-distance rates Monday,
reluctantly joining a price war that is bringing bargains for
consumers but threatens to cut into phone companies' profits.
</P>
<P>
   The new plan, which has a $5.95 monthly fee, offers calls at 7
cents a minute any time. That represents a 30 percent cut in the
per-minute rate from AT&AMP;T's previous main offering, 10 cents a
minute with a $4.95 monthly fee. Customers must request the new
plan, otherwise they will remain with their older, more expensive
ones.
</P>
<P>
   The move by AT&AMP;T, the biggest long-distance company, comes after
its top two rivals, MCI Worldcom and Sprint, introduced plans in
recent weeks offering calls for 5 cents a minute on evenings and
weekends.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to be responsive to the pricing pressures,'' said
Eugene Lockhart, president of AT&AMP;T consumer services. ``We believe
this offer represents a real opportunity to gain'' market share.
AT&AMP;T's share of the $41 billion consumer long-distance market is 50
percent but declined slightly this year as it has ever since long
distance was deregulated in the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Driving much of the price war is that the cost of providing
long-distance calls continues to drop. The biggest cost are the
fees that long-distance carriers pay to local phone companies on
both ends of the call. These fees, which vary by state, average 3
to 4 cents a minute. But the Federal Communications Commission has
been moving to reduce them slowly and ordered a 4.5 percent
reduction that took effect in July.
</P>
<P>
   Even with lower costs, though, the declining prices could cut
into profits. ``On average, we are seeing our revenue on the newer
plans equal to or higher than the previous plans,'' said Len Lauer,
the president of Sprint's consumer long-distance unit. ``Our
margins may be a little squeezed for customers who make a lot of
calls at the 5-cent-a-minute rate.''
</P>
<P>
   The cost of moving voices from one end of the country to the
other is very small, so the biggest other costs are billing,
customer service and marketing. That is why AT&AMP;T and the other
companies are eager to find programs that will pack more services
in a single bill and keep customers from switching plans every time
a new deal hits the market place.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, AT&AMP;T's new aggressive price cuts represent at least
a temporary retreat from its plan to integrate long-distance
service, with highly visible rates, into more complicated bundles
of telecommunication services that include calling cards and
wireless phones. Eventually, AT&AMP;T hopes to offer packages that also
incorporate local telephone service and cable television, now that
it has bought Tele-Communications Inc., the nation's largest cable
company. To the extent that the new long-distance plan slows AT&AMP;T's
losses in long-distance market share, it will preserve more
customers to which it can sell other services.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, AT&AMP;T's first attempt at such a bundle, the AT&AMP;T
Personal Network, has attracted a disappointing 350,000 customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sprint and MCI have gone back to the tried and true method of
acquiring customers: heavy price competition,'' said Brian Adamik,
a senior vice president of the Yankee Group, a consulting firm in
Boston. ``AT&AMP;T had tried to move away from that, but it has been
forced to respond.''
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T said Monday that its new plan would accelerate the decline
in its consumer long-distance revenue. It now expects that revenue
to fall 4 percent to 5 percent this year, instead of the 2 percent
to 4 percent drop it had previously forecast. But it said its sales
are somewhat better than expected for wireless telephones, data and
other services, so that on balance its revenue and profits will
meet its previously announced goals. AT&AMP;T's stock nonetheless fell
$1.50 a share, or 3 percent, to $46. Sprint and MCI shares fell as
well.
</P>
<P>
   For consumers, the new plans offered by the top three
long-distance carriers ``are pretty comparable,'' said Rex
Mitchell, an analyst with Banc of America Securities. ``If you make
a lot of calls before 7 p.m., you're better off on the AT&AMP;T plan.
If you have the discretion to move most of your calls to the
evening and weekend, the best thing is the MCI plan.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   MCI's new plan charges 25 cents a minute during the day if
customers pay a $1.95 fee a month or 10 cents a minute with a fee
of $5.95 a month. Sprint's plan is also 10 cents a minute during
the day with a $5.95 monthly fee.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T is also offering several variations on its basic plan. It
will cut the monthly fee to $4.95 for customers who choose AT&AMP;T to
handle their local toll calls or who receive their bill over the
Internet rather than by mail. And it will waive the fee entirely
for customers who sign up for a new plan meant for households with
more than one cellular phone. Business customers negotiate their
own rates, but prices have been falling in that market, too.
</P>
<P>
   While consumers pay close attention to prices for state-to-state
long distance calls, they often overlook rates for international
calls, directory assistance and calling cards, each of which is
more profitable for the long-distance companies. Moreover, lower
prices are encouraging customers to make more calls.
</P>
<P>
   While MCI and Sprint have been gaining market share at AT&AMP;T's
expense, the fastest growing segment of the market has been the
hundreds of small companies that collectively split the 10 percent
of the market not controlled by the big three. These include a host
of aggressive upstarts, like Qwest Communications International and
``dial-around'' services that allow people to choose a different
long-distance carrier for each call by dialing a code beginning
with 10-10. These dial-around providers, which include AT&AMP;T and MCI
operating under different names, have been promoting complex
pricing schemes, such as a flat rate of 99 cents for calls of up to
20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers told us that with all the froth that is out there
now, they are not sure what they are getting anymore,'' Lockhart
said. ``We wanted to offer two real things: simplicity and value.''
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T first tried this strategy in 1996 with a 15-cent-a-minute
One Rate plan and later the One Rate Plus plan at 10 cents a minute
and a $4.95 a month fee. More recently, the company offered more
complex plans, such as one with a 5-cent rate on Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   The overall long-distance revenue of AT&AMP;T and the other
long-distance companies doesn't fall as quickly as the prices on
the heavily promoted plans because existing customers have to
request the new lower rates. Indeed, some 20 percent of AT&AMP;T
customers don't have any calling plan and still pay the old much
higher rates, which can be as high as 25 cents a minute.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T is not giving up on its effort at creating complex packages
of telecommunications services. Monday, it also introduced a
``Family Plan'' meant for families in which more than one member
has an AT&AMP;T wireless phone. The plan allows each of the wireless
phones to have unlimited calling to each other and to the family's
home telephone.
</P>
<P>
   The first family member must choose between a $49.99 plan that
includes 400 minutes of nonfamily calls and a $69.99 600 minute
plan. Up to four more family members can choose among those plans
and a $24.99, 60-minute plan. Additional minutes are 35 cents each.
Long distance is 15 cents a minute. And calls made outside of the
local area are 69 cents a minute. This plan is available in New
York and the other markets served by AT&AMP;T's wireless unit.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T says that this will be particularly popular with families
that want to keep track of their teen-age children.
</P>
<P>
   ``All our research shows that people want more ways to stay in
touch with their family members,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-99 2105EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
