<DOCNO> NYT19990830.0411 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5034 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-UGA-LINEBACKERS31     08-30 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UGA-LINEBACKERS31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Beefed-up Bulldogs: Linebackers eager to meet expectations
 &HT;    By Chip Towers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ On average, they are 6 feet, 1 1/2 inches tall.
They weigh 225 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   They are ``the kinds of guys Florida and Tennessee are winning
with,'' Georgia coach Jim Donnan said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of them will be NFL first-round draft picks, South Florida
coach Jim Leavitt said.
</P>
<P>
   They are the Bulldogs' linebackers _ perhaps one of the best
group of linebackers in the nation. They are eight strong, and they
are a big reason many people think Georgia this season will field
its best defense of the decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys like Boss Bailey and Will Witherspoon and Kendrell Bell,
with that type of size and speed, just don't come along often,''
Donnan said. ``Not all at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   The reverberations of Georgia's linebacking talent have been
felt as far away as Tampa, Fla., and Harrisonburg, Va. Redshirt
freshman Kawika Mitchell and senior Mike Luckie, two pretty good
players caught in a logjam at the position, transferred to Division
I-AA schools in those cities during the summer to get playing time.
Mitchell went to South Florida, Luckie to James Madison.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like this,'' Leavitt said. ``Georgia has some first-round
draft picks in that linebacking group.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean Kawika couldn't play in the NFL someday, but
he may be a third-round pick.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia didn't want the 6-foot-2, 235-pound Mitchell to leave.
He was listed as No. 2 strong-side linebacker for this fall. But he
was behind Bailey, a sophomore and one of those future
first-rounders to whom Leavitt referred.
</P>
<P>
   And there wasn't another linebacker position for Mitchell to
play. At the other two spots are All-America candidate Orantes
Grant, a senior, and Witherspoon, a sophomore and prospective
first-rounder. With junior-college transfer Bell and former
Washington County star Jessie Miller joining the ranks this summer,
Mitchell read the writing on the wall.
</P>
<P>
   The stockpile of blue-chip linebackers is part of Donnan's
recruiting philosophy aimed to re-establish Georgia as one of the
top programs in the SEC.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something we've put a premium on in recruiting _
getting the linebackers and the so-called defensive-end types,''
Donnan said. ``We've been fortunate to get a few good ones
lately.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's most profound statement about the linebacking corps
came in the spring when junior Adrian Hollingshed and senior Dustin
Luckie were moved from middle and strong-side linebacker,
respectively, to defensive end. Both started every game last
season, and Hollingshed was third on the team with 93 tackles.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs had two reasons for the move. They wanted to
improve their speed and athleticism at end, and Bailey and
Witherspoon had exhibited such skill and play-making ability in
practice that Georgia no longer could afford to use them part-time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Speed's the first thing you think of,'' linebackers coach Brad
Lambert said. ``We want to get the best 11 players on the field,
and we felt like this move helped increase our team speed. With the
depth we had, we had the luxury of moving some people around.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys bring athleticism to the table, and they should be
able to create big plays,'' Lambert said. ``That's the bottom
line.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia has since moved Hollingshed, who was unhappy at end,
back to middle linebacker, further enhancing its depth there. He
remains behind Witherspoon and is listed with Bell on the second
team. But Lambert stresses that all the linebackers will play.
</P>
<P>
   The linebackers take pride in their reputation. But they also
know that they have not accomplished anything yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``No doubt, it is the best (linebacker) corps we've had here, in
terms of talent and potential. On paper, we're dynamite,'' Grant
said. ``But we'd like to be considered one of the best units in the
conference at the end of the season. Right now it doesn't mean
anything. Anybody can say they have a great linebacker corps, but
if you don't do it on the field, you haven't done anything.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
