<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENEZUELA-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENEZUELAN CONGRESS STRIPPED OF ITS LAST REMAINING POWERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela _ A Constitutional Assembly loyal to
President Hugo Chavez stripped the opposition-controlled Congress
of its last remaining powers Monday, taking revenge against
legislators who had pledged to defy a decree last week that
declared a ``legislative emergency'' and gave the assembly
virtually unlimited powers.
</P>
<P>
   The assembly acted after congressional leaders had said, as they
exercised some of their few remaining powers over the weekend, that
they would refuse to authorize any government budget expenditures,
including money for the assembly. They also said they would
withhold the legal permission required for Chavez to leave the
country on two state visits this week.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Constitutional Assembly called the threats a
provocation and said they would retaliate unless Congress
retreated.
</P>
<P>
   Although the expansion of the ``legislative emergency'' decree
Monday does not formally dissolve the Senate and Chamber of
Deputies, its effect is the same. All of Congress' responsibilities
and powers have now been transferred to the Constitutional
Assembly, which was elected last month with the mandate to rewrite
the constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Legislators are explicitly prohibited from holding official
meetings of any sort.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez, 45, a former Army paratrooper who led a failed coup
attempt in 1992, took office in February, saying that he needed a
new constitution to carry out a peaceful social revolution and end
rampant corruption.
</P>
<P>
   But his critics see that stand as intended to establish a
leftist military dictatorship in this nation of 23 million, which
has in recent years been the principal source of imported oil for
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coup d'etat that has been proclaiming itself in slow
motion has taken its final step Monday,'' said Alberto Franceschi,
one of six opposition representatives in the 131-member assembly.
``The Constitutional Assembly has assumed all powers in the
country. That is a fact. Those who wanted to radicalize the process
have succeeded.''
</P>
<P>
   After convening this month for the first time, the assembly also
declared a ``judicial emergency,'' granting itself the power to
dismiss judges and overhaul the courts.
</P>
<P>
   ``How much more power do you want?'' Franceschi, a member of the
center-right Proyecto Venezuela Party, asked Chavez's supporters.
Sarcastically, he warned directors of condominium boards to be
alert to the possibility that the assembly might also try to take
over their functions.
</P>
<P>
   As the constitutional crisis deepens, leaders of other Latin
American countries have also begun to express concerns. In a visit
to neighboring Colombia over the weekend, President Eduardo Frei of
Chile said, ``In my judgment, if there are not three branches of
government functioning legitimately, the rule of law is broken, and
that for me is not a democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Chavez's supporters reject all accusations of a power grab as
ill founded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here there will be nothing but democracy,'' said Luis
Miquilena, president of the Constitutional Assembly and one of
Chavez's closest political advisers. ``The idea of a dictatorship
is light-years from our reality.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We aren't usurping their powers,'' Miquilena said Monday when
asked about broadening the decree against Congress. ``We are
assuming a duty that they have irresponsibly abandoned,'' because
``the nation will not forgive a power vacuum.''
</P>
<P>
   The assembly is widely expected to consider another move this
week against a branch of government, handing down a decree that
would declare a state of ``executive emergency'' and allow the
panel to dismiss the governors of the 23 states and hundreds of
mayors.
</P>
<P>
   A special committee appointed by the assembly would then screen
state and local officials, replacing those who fail the inquiry
with ``regional governing councils composed of three or five
members who enjoy high prestige and honor.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, some members of the assembly have suggested moving
to take control the largest labor union. On Sunday, in his weekly
radio program, Chavez suggested that he was contemplating similar
action against the police if they obeyed the instructions of local
officials who are members of the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can intervene in any police force in any municipality,
because we are not going to permit any tumult or uproar,'' he said.
``Order has arrived in Venezuela.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Constitutional Assembly prepared to vote Monday on the
decree, the speaker of the lower house of Congress, Henrique
Capriles, filed a petition with the Supreme Court, asking for a
ruling on the legality of the assembly's original ``legislative
emergency'' decree, adopted last Wednesday. He argued that ``in
Venezuela, no organ exists above the constitution,'' but conceded
that the court, now in recess, might decide against him.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Supreme Court ruled, 8-6, that the Constitutional
Assembly did indeed have the authority to seize the judicial system
under its ``judicial emergency.''
</P>
<P>
   That led Chief Justice Cecilia Sosa Gomez to resign, saying the
tribunal had ``simply committed suicide in order to avoid being
assassinated.''
</P>
<P>
   Capriles said his intent was for the court to be ``put to the
test to see if the rule of law still exists in Venezuela.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There can be no middle ground,'' he added. ``Either the rule
of law exists or it doesn't.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
