<SLUG> BC-EXP-DETROIT-TEACHERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON EVE OF NEW SCHOOL YEAR, DETROIT TEACHERS VOTE TO STRIKE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By ROBYN MEREDITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Against the recommendation of their union leaders,
teachers here voted to strike Monday, just one day before Detroit's
172,000 public school students were due to return to school.
</P>
<P>
   The strike will test not only a new school board appointed this
year by Detroit Mayor Dennis Archer and Michigan Gov. John Engler,
but also a 1994 law that makes the strike illegal and punishes
teachers with fines of a day's pay for every day spent on strike.
The last teachers strike in Detroit was in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The union, the Detroit Federation of Teachers, has been in
negotiations since February over the terms of a contract to replace
the one that expired Monday. The union's leadership recommended
that teachers accept a 10-day extension of the talks with the
Detroit Public Schools, but teachers rebelled, voting to strike by
an 80 percent margin.
</P>
<P>
   ``They voted not to return without a contract,'' said Janna K.
Garrison, executive vice president of the Detroit Federation of
Teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Parents were urged not to take their children to school Tuesday
until the school board can make sure there are enough teachers to
go around. The union, meanwhile, called for teachers to head for
the picket lines instead of their classrooms on Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``No teacher ever wants to go on strike,'' said John Elliott,
president of the Detroit Federation of Teachers. ``But when the
school system tries to undermine the teachers, it winds up hurting
students.''
</P>
<P>
   Half the students in Detroit's public schools do not graduate
from high school, and half of those who do graduate struggle to
meet state standards. Fourth-graders approach state averages on
standardized tests, but by the seventh-grade just a third can read
or do math at their grade level.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican-controlled Statehouse voted in March to transfer
control of Detroit's schools from an elected school board to the
mayor and governor, who appointed a new school board. The teachers
union supported the reform effort.
</P>
<P>
   The 11,500-member teachers union was seeking a pay raise and a
reduction in class sizes.
</P>
<P>
   The board had proposed raises of 95 percent of what teachers had
asked for, according to Ms. Garrison, and the school board had
agreed to study whether to reduce class sizes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
