<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXP-AT&AMP;T-RATES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT&AMP;T ENTERS PRICE WAR BY LOWERING LONG-DISTANCE RATES 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By SAUL HANSELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The AT&AMP;T Corp. introduced lower long-distance rates Monday,
reluctantly joining a price war that is bringing bargains for
consumers but threatens to cut into phone companies' profits.
</P>
<P>
   The new plan, which has a $5.95 monthly fee, offers calls at 7
cents a minute any time. That represents a 30 percent cut in the
per-minute rate from AT&AMP;T's previous main offering, 10 cents a
minute with a $4.95 monthly fee. Customers must request the new
plan, otherwise they will remain with their older, more expensive
ones.
</P>
<P>
   The move by AT&AMP;T, the biggest long-distance company, comes after
its top two rivals, MCI Worldcom and Sprint, introduced plans in
recent weeks offering calls for 5 cents a minute on evenings and
weekends.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to be responsive to the pricing pressures,'' said
Eugene Lockhart, president of AT&AMP;T consumer services. ``We believe
this offer represents a real opportunity to gain'' market share.
AT&AMP;T's share of the $41 billion consumer long-distance market is 50
percent but declined slightly this year as it has ever since long
distance was deregulated in the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Driving much of the price war is that the cost of providing
long-distance calls continues to drop. The biggest cost are the
fees that long-distance carriers pay to local phone companies on
both ends of the call. These fees, which vary by state, average 3
to 4 cents a minute. But the Federal Communications Commission has
been moving to reduce them slowly and ordered a 4.5 percent
reduction that took effect in July.
</P>
<P>
   Even with lower costs, though, the declining prices could cut
into profits. ``On average, we are seeing our revenue on the newer
plans equal to or higher than the previous plans,'' said Len Lauer,
the president of Sprint's consumer long-distance unit. ``Our
margins may be a little squeezed for customers who make a lot of
calls at the 5-cent-a-minute rate.''
</P>
<P>
   For consumers, the new plans offered by the top three
long-distance carriers ``are pretty comparable,'' said Rex G.
Mitchell, an analyst with Banc of America Securities.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you make a lot of calls before 7 p.m., you're better off on
the AT&AMP;T plan,'' he said. ``If you have the discretion to move most
of your calls to the evening and weekend, the best thing is the MCI
plan.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
