Blaine Marina last week, check the boat's nets for damage. Karuza
estimated that as many as 300 Puget Sound families whose livelihood
is tied to salmon fishing face economic hardship and, perhaps,
bankruptcy by the lack of a sockeye season this year. (Phil H.
Webber/Seattle Post-Intelligencer Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) SEATTLE -- Aug. 30, 1999 -- SINGERS-SIDEWALK-SPI, 08-30
-- James Butler sings and plays guitar during a performance by the
group ``A Moment in Time'' of which he is a member. ``This gives me
a chance to express myself,'' said Butler, 56, a Louisiana native.
``And if you're good, you make some money.'' (Meryl
Schenker/Seattle Post-Intelligencer Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) UNDATED -- Aug. 30, 1999 -- TUMBLING-ASTEROID-B&AMP;W, 08-30
-- Radar observations captured the slow tumble of a large,
bizarrely shaped asteroid known as 1999 JM8 as it streaked within
5.3 million miles of Earth in late July. The images, taken at the
Jet Propulsion Laboratory in Pasadena using NASA's Goldstone Radar
in California and the Arecibo Observatory's radar in Puerto Rico,
show the asteroid rotating at the the unusually slow rate of about
once a week. They were taken, clockwise from upper right, on July
28, Aug. 2, Aug. 1, and Aug. 5. (Jet Propulsion Laboratory/New York
Times Photo)
