<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5052 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-DENNIS31-COX     08-30 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DENNIS31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dennis veers off, for now
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COINJOCK, N.C. _ Hurricane Dennis is churning out to sea after
lashing coastal North Carolina with dangerous winds and rain blamed
for two deaths, but forecasters worried that the storm could come
roaring back toward land before week's end.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis is expected to stall at sea today for two or three days.
Monday, the storm tore at the North Carolina-Virginia Tidewater
region with 92 mph winds and dumped up to eight inches of rain in
southeastern North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Stretching into Virginia, the storm flooded streets in the
Norfolk area and knocked out electricity to more than 22,000 homes
and businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really do need to keep our guard up for the next 36
hours,'' said Richard Moore, secretary of North Carolina's
Department of Crime Control and Public Safety.
</P>
<P>
   Among those worried that Dennis was not gone for good was Ed
O'Neal, owner of Currituck Sports, a bait and tackle shop on a
sandy finger surrounded by Currituck and Albemarle sounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it goes off and sits for a while, that would be bad,''
O'Neal said.
</P>
<P>
   In North Carolina's extreme northeastern corner, hundreds of
hotels, restaurants and other businesses in Kitty Hawk, Kill Devil
Hills and Nags Head were hoping the lumbering storm would clear out
before Labor Day weekend, one of the biggest of the year on the
tourist-dependent Outer Banks.
</P>
<P>
   Late Monday, Dennis was 120 miles east of Cape Hatteras, moving
east-northeast at 17 mph and generating 90 mph winds. A hurricane
warning remained in effect for most of the North Carolina coast,
from Cape Lookout to the Virginia border, but winds were starting
to abate Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, one of our better models is showing that it
comes back into the coast, not far from where it is right now,
close to Norfolk or in that general vicinity,'' said Jerry Jarrell
of the National Hurricane Center in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, the storm's eye stayed 60 miles from shore, sparing
coastal North Carolina the widespread wind and flood damage
suffered from Hurricane Bonnie a year ago and Hurricanes Fran and
Bertha in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``It moved a lot of sand around, but it wasn't a big deal,''
said Houston Hendrik, who spent Sunday night in his Wrightsville
Beach home, despite mandatory evacuation orders for the barrier
island and most others in North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   As Dennis moved north Monday, Wilmington area officials lifted
evacuation orders and residents and vacationers returned to find
relatively little damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen a bunch of bad weather in this area, but we're real
happy with how things turned out this time,'' said Bob Sheppard, an
employee at Harbor Inn in Wrightsville Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis caused a bit of a mess on the Carteret County coast. On
Emerald Isle, down from the town hall's limb-strewn lawn, winds
toppled a green portable toilet on a construction site. A plastic
zebra was knocked over at the Jungleland Family Theme Park in
Atlantic Beach, near the Sheraton Hotel missing the letters ``h''
and ``n'' from its red plastic sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``There goes part of the roof,'' said Harry Russell, a Sheraton
guest who stood on a deck overlooking the pounding waves spewing
white spray high into the gray sky.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is almost like God's fury, I guess, so natural and yet so
unnatural to a person like me,'' said another guest at the hotel,
Jerry Gulledge.
</P>
<P>
   Two motorists were killed in a head-on collision in the coastal
Onslow County community of Richlands. Authorities said the crash
occurred about 7:30 a.m. as 60 mph winds and 2 inches of rain
blasted the area. Winds reached 102 mph at Buxton on Hatteras
Island and flooding temporarily closed N.C. 12, the only highway
along the barrier island. A stretch of the highway also was shut
down near Kitty Hawk. At times, blowing beach sand reduced
visibility to near zero along the highway on Hatteras Island. Sand
reportedly was drifted 3 feet deep near Buxton.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
