<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 21:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5053 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-$A     08-30 1218
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUMMER RENTALS EXTEND INTO FALL 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Sept. 5) 
(jt) 
 By BETSY WADE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not so long ago, Labor Day was the moment the cottage door
twanged shut. For rentals at the beach, the long season began on
Memorial Day, the short on July 4. But long or short, it was over
on Labor Day, just before school started.
</P>
<P>
   Like many travel patterns in America, this one is changing.
While no one has created the endless summer surfers dream of, nor
the ``second summer'' touted by the New Jersey Department of
Commerce, in the Northeast and even parts of the Midwest, September
and October have become beach time for many.
</P>
<P>
   On Cape Cod, in New Jersey and at shore resorts elsewhere along
the recreational vehicle flyway, officials all say yes, yes, there
is a post-Labor Day influx of retired people, especially those
taking a leisurely course to Florida. This flow of people who pause
along the way for more than a weekend is bolstered by a certain
number of younger vacation-house hunters who cannot go in summer.
But at Bethany Beach, Del., Mayor Joe McHugh sees something else:
families with preschool children. They come flooding in to swim,
rent cottages at a lower price and eat at restaurants that
increasingly keep their stoves alight into the fall, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lower prices at thriving Bethany Beach are a relative matter. In
the middle of summer, Michael Wilgus of Century 21 Wilgus real
estate company said, three-bedroom houses go for $1,800 to $1,950 a
week; in September, this might be $1,000 a week. Part of what is
driving prices, he said, is an increase in visitors from New
Jersey, New York, Connecticut and Massachusetts who are looking for
quiet places near the waves.
</P>
<P>
   Although 1999 has been a boom summer at the shore all through
the Northeast, with a heat wave, a lack of rain so serious it
became a drought, and a consequent freedom from mosquitoes, the
September-October ``season'' has been evolving for some time. On
Cape Cod, Everett Keyes of Real Estate Unlimited says things have
been moving that way for 25 years, but he has seen the most radical
change in the last 10. Others involved cite 10 or 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   On the Delaware shore, Wilgus said, 15 or 20 years ago in
Bethany Beach, ``My parents would walk me uptown on Monday evening
of Labor Day to see how quiet things were.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All we would meet were other local people walking around,'' he
said. ``Now a lot of people have caught on. The humidity is gone,
the crowds are gone, rentals are lower.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Wilgus and others note, families with school-age
children and all adults involved in education vanish by Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   What is more, as parks departments in Delaware, New Jersey, New
York, Connecticut and Massachusetts point out, parking lot
attendants and lifeguards must return to school, which means
beaches must reduce their hours or the space they patrol.
Connecticut's parks, including those with beaches on Long Island
Sound _ Sherwood Island, Hammonassett, Rocky Neck _ stay open all
year but provide lifeguards only in summer. Pamela Adams, director
of state parks, said: ``We try to keep our lifeguards until Labor
Day, but school years start earlier and earlier.''
</P>
<P>
   State beaches may be able to provide weekend services by hiring
local youths, but keeping hotels and restaurants operating into the
fall means corralling customers through the week, not just on the
weekend. Many hotels and motels maintain minimum-stay requirements
into the fall to keep the staff from moving on, as one hotelier put
it.
</P>
<P>
   Cape May, N.J., and Saugatuck-Douglas, Mich., which has beaches
on Lake Michigan, have extended the season by marketing efforts.
They imitated Atlantic City, which created the Miss America Pageant
in 1921 to keep the Boardwalk hotels going the week after Labor
Day.
</P>
<P>
   Felicia Fairchild of the Saugatuck Convention and Visitors
Bureau said her town of 954 people in western Michigan began its
organization in 1989 with the mission to expand the season. ``We
have had phenomenal success,'' she said. In the '80s, she recalled,
the season was Memorial Day to Labor Day, and the six B&AMP;B's of that
era closed then. Now the resort opens in May and the 40-odd B&AMP;B's
go all year, with 20,000 visitors in the peak of summer. Travelers
to Saugatuck, she said, are mostly empty-nesters from the higher
income brackets, with two working spouses. In fall, they visit
galleries, stay in inns with fireplaces and hot tubs and continue
to swim at Oval Beach among the dunes on Lake Michigan. ``We are a
throwback,'' Ms. Fairchild said, ``the kind of place where you can
lie in the grass and read and watch sailboats go by.''
</P>
<P>
   The Saugatuck mission was accomplished without advertising, Ms.
Fairchild said. The tiny town dispatched a display to the American
Society of Travel Agents convention in Taiwan in 1991, and its
presence among the booths set up by Portugal and other countries
attracted the attention of CNN. When the campaign began, 87 percent
of visitors came from Chicago, two and a half hours away. Now the
breakdown is 50 percent from Chicago, 50 percent from the Detroit
area and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Cape May set out to sell fall opportunities, and the
town's stylish restaurants and Victorian-style inns. Tags for beach
admission end after Labor Day, said Kathy Tomlin, office manager
for the county department of tourism. ``The water is at its highest
temperature,'' she said, ``and we are past the August chaos.'' She
said that events, including a lima bean festival, had used up all
the fall weekends, and that Victorian Week Oct. 8 to 17 now
surrounds Columbus Day. The Cape May Bird Observatory is a major
attraction in the migrating season.
</P>
<P>
   Dane Wells, proprietor of the Queen Victoria Inn and the smaller
Queen's Hotel in Cape May, said that his rates did not drop at all
until mid-September because early September was still ``prime beach
season.'' He applies a three-night minimum on fall weekends and a
two-day minimum midweek. He said his places had 70 to 80 percent
occupancy in the fall. Tom Carroll at the Mainstay Inn, also in
Cape May, said: ``We've watched the business go from 0 in September
30 years ago to excellent now.'' His summer rates do not drop until
after Victorian Week.
</P>
<P>
   On Cape Cod, Keyes, the real estate broker, said the strong
season is mid-June to mid-September, and rates for rentals drop
about a third after that. ``It's a lot heavier than it used to be
up to Columbus Day,'' he said. Ninety percent of the 100 to 150
cottages he handles are heated, he said, and he often rents in the
fall to people looking for houses to buy.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Hunter of Bedford, N.Y., says that she, her husband and
three small children rent a beach house on Long Beach Island, N.J.,
in the high season. But Ms. Hunter said the family likes the fall _
warm swimming, clothing sales, the absence of traffic signals _ so
they have been coming back, borrowing Ms. Hunter's parents' beach
house in September and October. But, she said, in the last two
years, her parents are getting demands for later rentals, and Ms.
Hunter, an agent at Valerie Wilson Travel in New York, is a realist
in these things. ``It's just getting harder to be a freeloader,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
