   (NYT18) UNDATED -- Aug. 30, 1999 -- TUMBLING-ASTEROID-B&AMP;W, 08-30
-- Radar observations captured the slow tumble of a large,
bizarrely shaped asteroid known as 1999 JM8 as it streaked within
5.3 million miles of Earth in late July. The images, taken at the
Jet Propulsion Laboratory in Pasadena using NASA's Goldstone Radar
in California and the Arecibo Observatory's radar in Puerto Rico,
show the asteroid rotating at the the unusually slow rate of about
once a week. They were taken, clockwise from upper right, on July
28, Aug. 2, Aug. 1, and Aug. 5. (Jet Propulsion Laboratory/New York
Times Photo)
