<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5055 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-HAWAII-MAUI-$A     08-30 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-HAWAII-MAUI-$ADV05-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POOLS AND PICASSO BY THE BEACH IN MAUI 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Sept. 5) 
(jt) 
 By HOWARD W. FRENCH    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Imagine for a moment a slow morning stroll to breakfast through
bright, colonnaded galleries, past massive bronzes by Leger,
Picasso lithographs and Warhol silkscreens. There is an
embarrassment of choice as you dine on a sumptuous buffet under
huge cast-iron chandeliers that seem to grow like vines downward
from painted ceilings that vault 40 feet skyward. You then pad
lazily toward the sea past the long, terraced reflecting pools.
Just above them, realistically sculptured dolphins are permanently
suspended in flight. Finally, beachside aboard your cushioned
chaise, you look out at the picture-book ocean where a school of
humpback whales playfully sounds not far offshore.
</P>
<P>
   The Grand Wailea Resort Hotel and Spa, one of the most luxurious
establishments on Maui, an island whose vocation seems to have
become luxury living, offers such dreamlike days. Although Maui
boasts seaside drives, mountain trails, free public recreational
parks and some of the best beaches in Hawaii, the sprawling Grand
Wailea, on the island's southwest coast, seems to take the credo of
all-inclusive resorts even more to heart than most, giving visitors
so many options it would scarcely occur to them to stray outside.
</P>
<P>
   At the Grand Wailea, this approach is called the ``detached
world.'' Start with the white, spiky chapel, which looks as if it
were straight from the ``Wizard of Oz'' _ except, that is, for the
brightly colored stained-glass windows depicting a royal Hawaiian
wedding. The swimming pool, a gargantuan affair, alone occupies
more space than many hotels. This uniquely designed waterworld
includes a 2,000-foot course of flowing water called the Wailea
Canyon, with a current that propels swimmers past manmade caves,
valleys, grottoes, restaurants, wet bars, Jacuzzi baths and,
obligingly, even a modest patch of simulated rapids.
</P>
<P>
   The pool also includes what is billed as the world's only water
elevator. For riders on this popular conveyance, however, the
experience is more like a thunderous, cold-water shower than an
elevator. Riders sit on a huge rubber tire that hoists passengers a
full five stories while the pumice-stone chamber that houses it is
filled with water cascading down from above, a bracing shower. What
keeps people coming back again and again for another ascent,
though, is the serpentine water slide, which is reached by the
elevator, and whose long and giddy ride rivals that of most water
parks.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming one's budget holds up, the Grand Wailea claims to be
all things to all people. With its variety of recreational
activities, six restaurants, rooms from presidential-type suites to
more prosaic singles and doubles, and many other choices, the hotel
largely succeeds, and certainly did for my family, which included
my wife, Agnes, and our sons William, 14, and Henry, 10, during a
three-day stay last spring.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel's swimming pool serves as a metaphor for the entire
enterprise. While children play on the slide (endlessly in Henry's
case), a small, deep pool is reserved for scuba lessons. And just
up the long terraced promenade to the hotel there is another large
formal pool reserved for adults. Alongside it are a number of
spacious Jacuzzi baths, as well as canopy-shaded tables where
professional masseurs ply their art.
</P>
<P>
   An even quieter form of relaxation is a walk between virtually
any two places in the hotel, affording a view of its 40 acres of
verdant, carefully manicured grounds that slope gently from the
foothills of Mount Haleakala to the beach. From the balcony of the
breakfast restaurant (where an elaborate buffet is served, with an
abundance of tropical fruits and traditional Japanese offerings),
while colorful tropical birds seek to raid tables of leftovers,
another mildly distracting choreography can be spied below:
white-uniformed grounds-keepers pruning regal palm trees aboard
telescoping lifts. And always, there is the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   The Grand Wailea sits along a beach that has often been
described as one of the finest in the world _ perhaps because of
its gentle turquoise waters and clean, fine white sand, and because
of a fantastic view of Molokini Island, Lanai Island and the West
Maui mountains. Whales and dolphins abound, as do sea turtles,
sharks and the countless tropical fish species that feed off the
abundant coral. The usual variety of water sports is available
here, from scuba, windsurfing and kayaking to sailboat outings on a
60-foot catamaran, the Alii Nui. Although there is no tennis or
golf at the resort, 11 tennis courts and three championship golf
courses are less than a mile away (cost is extra).
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   And then there is the spa, which Agnes and William frequented, a
soothing world of marble floors, waterfalls and a wide range of
treatments from around the world _ plus state-of-the-art equipment,
TV monitors, instructors and lots of fresh towels. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For children _ and for an extra fee _ the hotel has a recreation
center known as Camp Grande, with its own dining room and nursery.
Run much like a summer camp, it offers computers, video games, its
own movie theater and extensive professional supervision by a young
staff. For parents wishing a little extra privacy, the camp also
has an evening session.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of all the outdoor choices, for some guests the
greatest pleasures of the Grand Wailea will be found in the hotel's
spacious white-walled interior. The massive, whimsical Botero
sculptures _ like ``Woman Smoking a Cigarette'' or ``Sleepless
Night'' _ that grace many of the public areas are a particular
pleasure, and an unexpected touch for a hotel of any class. While
the art continually takes guests by surprise, a quieter
satisfaction comes from the unfussy luxury in the hotel's other
appointments.
</P>
<P>
   There are 780 rooms, including 51 suites, ranging from 640 to
5,500 square feet. The ordinary traveler _ one like me who
vacations on a budget _ will typically be lodged in the Molokini
wing, whose terraced rooms offer a full view of the mountains, but
just a glimpse of the Pacific Ocean. The furniture in each room,
however, shows an eye for understated elegance and craftsmanship,
whether it is the four--poster beds, the fine wicker cabinets, or
the solid, hardwood tables on the porches. Each room also has a
bath, separate shower and marble vanity.
</P>
<P>
   For Hawaii residents (as we were for nine months), the room is
discounted, in our case to $286 a night during our stay in late
March, down considerably from the standard rate of $380. It had a
queen-size bed and a double, plus a large, comfortable chaise
longue, which the boys took turns sleeping on, rather than sharing
the double bed.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Grand Wailea's six restaurants is the Kincha, an
austere Japanese dining establishment with private tatami rooms,
Japanese lanterns and calligraphy wall-hangings. What seems most
authentic is the cuisine, which must meet the demanding standards
of the hotel's large Japanese clientele. There is also an
Italian-Mediterranean restaurant known as Bistro Molokini, and a
Hawaiian seafood restaurant with the nearly impossible to pronounce
name of Humuhumunukunukuapua'a (more familiar is its thatched-roof
and stilts-in-the-water design, typical of Polynesia).
</P>
<P>
   If there was any disappointment at the Grand Wailea, it involved
service. Sometimes the hotel seemed unable to strike the right
balance between overweening attention _ as at some of its fine
restaurants _ and relative neglect _ sometimes the case in the
breakfast dining area, or at poolside, where snacks are served. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In fact, for this guest, the perfect cap to days long and rich
in choices were sunset cocktails on our room's terrace, dividing my
view between the foothills of the West Maui mountains and the deep
blue sea. The only music was live _ from a riot of birds fussing
and flirting as they tidied their nests for the evening.
</P>
<P>
   Surfing, sailing and lei making
</P>
<P>
   The Grand Wailea Resort Hotel and Spa is at 3850 Wailea Alanui,
Wailea, Maui, Hawaii 96753; (808) 875-1234 or (800) 888-6100; fax
(808) 879-4077. Rooms start at $380; suites, from $1,100. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Camp Grande, for children ages 5 to 12, operates a day camp
within the resort from 9 a.m. to 4 p.m. daily; $65 a day. The
morning session, which includes lunch, is $40, as is the afternoon
session. (A Night Camp, from 5 to 10 p.m., costs $50.) Three-day
packages are $180; five days, $295; seven days, $390; 10 days,
$500. There are also children's workshops in hula dancing, computer
graphics, pottery, tile painting, lei making, clay sculpture and
T-shirt dying; $30 to $45 depending on the activity. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The resort's spa offers a full range of treatments, from
hydrotherapy to shiatsu and Thai massage to Indian Siddha therapy,
masques and scrubs.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Windsurfer rentals: $20 an hour; 90-minute lesson, $69.
Surfboard rentals: one hour, $15; full day, $30; 90-minute lesson,
$59. Boogie board rentals: one hour, $5; one day, $15. Snorkel set
rental: one hour, $5; one day, $15. Kayak rental: one-seater, $15
for one hour; $25 for two hours; two-seater, $25 for one hour; $35
for two hours. Hobie Cat rides or lessons: $45 an hour. Free
lessons in fitness, yoga, water aerobics, aerobics.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
