<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5058 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-BRIBES-NYT &LR;      08-30 0504
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-BRIBES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN SAYS HE HAS PROOF   BRIBES WERE PAID TO KREMLIN  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Italy, Hungary, Switzerland)   By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ A Russian investigator said in a television interview
Monday night that published accounts of bribes paid to Kremlin
officials by a Swiss construction company were ``98 percent true''
and could be backed up by evidence in his files.
</P>
<P>
   The investigator, Georgi Chuglazov, a deputy in the prosecutor
general's office, made the comments after he was barred at the last
minute from joining a delegation from the office that is to leave
Tuesday for Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   Chuglazov confirmed that he had been removed Friday as head of
the investigation into Mabetex, a Swiss-based construction company
that has been at the center of a probe into kickbacks allegedly
received by top Kremlin officials.
</P>
<P>
   Chuglazov had hoped to wind up his investigation with a trip to
Switizerland. Instead, he said, he discovered not only that his
airplane tickets had been canceled but that his phones had been cut
off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized that no one here is interested in this case,'' he
said in an interview on NTV, Russia's largest independent station,
which has taken an increasingly strong stance against President
Boris Yeltsin in a politically charged media war.
</P>
<P>
   So far no charges have been filed against any Kremlin officials
in the investigation, which was begun last winter by a prosecutor
general, Yuri Skuratov. His subsequent dismissal was seen as
political retribution by Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   But the scandal flashed back to life last week when Corriere
della Sera, Italy's leading newspaper, reported detailed charges
against Yeltsin's inner circle and his family.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper, quoting unnamed sources close to the Swiss
investigation, said $1 million channeled by Mabetex through
accounts used by Pavel Borodin, head of the Kremlin's property
management office, had been labeled ``pocket money'' for members of
Yeltsin's family during an official trip to Hungary several years
ago. The paper also reported that Yeltsin's family had been given
access to credit cards that were paid by Mabetex's president,
Behgjet Pacolli.
</P>
<P>
   Pacolli has denied most of the charges, saying the $1 million
transfer had been to a subcontractor based in Budapest. Borodin has
also denied having a Swiss bank account of his own, although in an
interview last week he said Mabetex had paid for several business
trips that he and Kremlin colleagues had made to Switzerland and
Italy to inspect materials used by Mabetex for the reconstruction
of Yeltsin's residence and offices.
</P>
<P>
   In the interview Monday night, Chuglazov did not specify which
of the allegations made by the Italian newspaper may be backed up
by evidence in his files. But he insisted the evidence was
compelling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today the case has enough grounds to have some of the state
officials fired,'' he said. ``One doesn't have to have a court
sentence to be fired from a job.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-99 2137EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
