<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5059 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-FALL-FASHION-ART-NYT &LR;      08-30 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FALL-FASHION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT STORE WISHES TO BE A FASHION VICTIM? 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By ANNE-MARIE SCHIRO    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It shouldn't be surprising to anyone who has been
following fashion of late that women are more interested in
practical clothes than in designers' flights of fancy. In an
informal survey last week, women from 19 to 70 had similar
reactions to a lot of what they see pictured in fashion
publications, calling the clothes exaggerated and the styling
extreme and not realistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fashion these days should be straight and pure, with no
gimmicks,'' said Margot Rogoff, a consultant to the fashion and
beauty industries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to see realistic things, not celebrity stuff,'' said
Stacey Gubinski, a student in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would love to have direction,'' said Barbara Raynor, a copy
editor at a New York publishing house.
</P>
<P>
   Since the stores are currently stocked with new fall
merchandise, this is a good time to ask retailers about their
directions. Stores, after all, place their bets on what they think
customers will actually want to buy. They don't always guess
correctly, but are more down-to-earth than the fantasies of
stylists and fashion photographers. Herewith, a rundown of the
major trends a woman might think about if she wants to look au
courant but not like a fashion victim.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our customer is looking for something new, something
luxurious, something special,'' said Joan Kaner, a vice president
and the fashion director of Neiman Marcus. ``She's looking for high
fashion, not buying a basic.''
</P>
<P>
   The other day Ms. Kaner pulled from the racks a collection of
early best sellers for Neiman Marcus, which included cashmeres in
both knitwear and double-face woven fabrics, leathers and
shearlings. ``There's a lot of black and white,'' she said,
``especially tweeds and patterns, plus camels and browns. And
there's also color: orange, red and the whole family of greens.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the early hits are a vicuna-colored cashmere twin set and
a pony-printed hair-calf skirt by Michael Kors; a knitted jacket
and leather skirt from Chanel; a black and white cowl-neck tunic
sweater with tweed pants by John Galliano, and a black shearling
coat with rough edges and a decidedly bohemian air by Donna Karan.
</P>
<P>
   The bohemian, ethnic, hippie style _ call it what you will, it's
a throwback to the 1970s _ is a major trend that can make the
wearer look like a gypsy or can be toned down to a romantic,
feminine look with mere touches of decorative elements.
</P>
<P>
   James Aguiar, Bergdorf Goodman's fashion director for
ready-to-wear, sees bohemian as one side of the fashion coin and a
sleek urban look as the counterpart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each one can be at home in the city,'' he said. ``The urban
sophisticate dresses in a monotone _ black head to toe or white
head to toe, or camel. The bohemian mixes colors, prints and
textures. Boots are important for both looks. We also feel very
strongly about ponchos, capes and serapes, and luxurious
hand-knitted cashmeres.''
</P>
<P>
   His suggestion for a wearable urban bohemian look is a raw silk
skirt by Matthew Williamson bordered in velvet and beaded fringe,
topped by a simple two-tone pullover. The city sophisticate is
personified by a white Calvin Klein suit with a short jacket and a
knee-length skirt. For color, there is a reddish orange dress with
a matching poncho by Michael Kors.
</P>
<P>
   ``An individual style filters through all of these looks,''
Aguiar said. ``The most important thing is, there is no uniform.
And color is important, finally. People are responding to color.''
</P>
<P>
   At Barneys New York, Judy Collinson, an executive vice
president, sees the bohemian influence in details like embroidery,
beading and appliques. She mentioned a Marni skirt trimmed with
rows of flowers, shown with a red hair-calf jacket, and a red skirt
by Andrew Gn decorated with black embroidery and leather and shown
with a fur-trimmed sleeveless sweater.
</P>
<P>
   Other important trends that are already selling, she said, are
skirts from knee length to long; touches of fur; vests in leather,
shearling and knits; blanket wraps; velvet, and chunky sweaters.
She likes Burberry's plaid blanket skirt teamed with a shearling
vest, and a camel mohair skirt from the Barneys private-label
collection worn with a matching cashmere turtleneck that looks
hand-knitted.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of black on the runways, but also a lot of
color,'' she said. ``There's the warmth of camel tones and brown,
while blue and red are still powerful. And it's a strong boot
season, whether tall, short or in between.''
</P>
<P>
   At Henri Bendel, Ed Burstell, the store's vice president and
general merchandise manager, pointed out what he considers the
trends of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Animal prints are selling in cashmere, in fake fur, in coats
and accessories,'' he said, ``and they look terrific with orange,
one of the big colors. The other big color is olive in everything
from ponchos to coats. Athletic looks continue to be popular. And
chunky sweaters. I love this chunky turtleneck from Dirk
Bikkembergs in olive or blue. And the hippie, vintage look in
Catherine's wool poncho in diamond-patterned olive, plum and camel
worn with a long skirt. ''
</P>
<P>
   Sheri Wilson-Gray, Saks Fifth Avenue's executive vice president
for marketing, went through the store to see what she wanted for
fall and came up with the following shopping list: something
pashmina and something in hair calf, a poncho, boots and a status
bag. For color she favors red over orange because ``next year
you'll still want to wear red, but you may hate orange.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've just gotten used to the look of bare legs,'' she said,
``so I'm not sure about black hosiery. If you wear boots and
there's a gap between the boot and the hem of the skirt, what looks
better? A bare leg or black?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one thing when a magazine shows a picture,'' she added,
``and it's always interesting when people wear it and you think,
`Hmmmm.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
