sweeping poncho and matching dress by Michael Kors and boots by
Marc Jacobs at Bergdorf Goodman, left; a chunky wool turtleneck
sweater by Dirk Bikkembergs at Henri Bendel. (Marilynn K. Yee/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) NEW YORK -- Aug. 30, 1999 -- FALL-FASHION-1, 08-30 --
Cashmere sleeveless turtleneck, cardigan and printed hair-calf
skirt by Michael Kors at Neiman Marcus, left; cashmere tunic
sweater with a giant cowl and tweed cuffed trousers, all by John
Galliano, also at Neiman Marcus. (Marilynn K. Yee/New York Times
Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) NEW YORK -- Aug. 30, 1999 -- CLOSING-HURLEY'S, 08-30 --
Hurley's restaurant, at the corner of 49th Street and Sixth Avenue,
on Monday, top, and as Rockefeller Center was constructed around it
in the 1930's. For decades, Hurley's restaurant bucked the odds.
When Prohibition came, the Hurley brothers put a flower shop in
front to hide the speakeasy. When Rockefeller Center was built, the
family stubbornly refused to sell their property, forcing the
developers to build the huge complex around them. But now, it
appears, Hurley's days are coming to end. With more stylish tenants
moving in around them, the restaurant's owners have decided to
close. The restaurant will be replaced by Citarella's, the upscale
food store, according someone familiar with the deal who spoke on
condition of anonymity. (Chester Higgins Jr./New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) NEW YORK -- Aug. 30, 1999 -- NY-GIULIANI-JUROR, 08-30 --
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, a former federal prosecutor, was selected
to serve on jury duty Monday. The civil case involves a man named
Oliver Johnson who is suing his landlord because he scalded his
private parts while taking a shower. Giuliani is seen in a 1998
file photo. (Ruby Washington/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) NEW YORK -- Aug. 30, 1999 -- TEN-USOPEN-2, 08-30 --
Australian Open champion Yevgeny Kafelnikov during his first round
match at the U.S. Open, which began its two-week run in Flushing
Meadows on Monday. The third-seeded Russian defeated Alberto Martin
of Spain 6-1, 3-6, 6-3, 6-4, in two hours and 13 minutes. (James
Estrin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) BLAINE, Wash. -- Aug. 30, 1999 --
FISHING-HARD-TIMES-SPI, 08-30 -- Nick Karuza and his wife Diedra on
the aft deck of their 50-foot purse seiner Alice Anne moored at
Blaine Marina last week, check the boat's nets for damage. Karuza
estimated that as many as 300 Puget Sound families whose livelihood
is tied to salmon fishing face economic hardship and, perhaps,
bankruptcy by the lack of a sockeye season this year. (Phil H.
Webber/Seattle Post-Intelligencer Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) SEATTLE -- Aug. 30, 1999 -- SINGERS-SIDEWALK-SPI, 08-30
-- James Butler sings and plays guitar during a performance by the
group ``A Moment in Time'' of which he is a member. ``This gives me
a chance to express myself,'' said Butler, 56, a Louisiana native.
``And if you're good, you make some money.'' (Meryl
Schenker/Seattle Post-Intelligencer Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) UNDATED -- Aug. 30, 1999 -- TUMBLING-ASTEROID-B&AMP;W, 08-30
-- Radar observations captured the slow tumble of a large,
bizarrely shaped asteroid known as 1999 JM8 as it streaked within
5.3 million miles of Earth in late July. The images, taken at the
Jet Propulsion Laboratory in Pasadena using NASA's Goldstone Radar
in California and the Arecibo Observatory's radar in Puerto Rico,
show the asteroid rotating at the the unusually slow rate of about
once a week. They were taken, clockwise from upper right, on July
28, Aug. 2, Aug. 1, and Aug. 5. (Jet Propulsion Laboratory/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) PALMETTO, Fla. -- Aug. 30, 1999 -- TEACHER-SHORTAGE,
08-30 -- School supplies are handed out at Palmetto Elementary on
Monday. As the nation's children swarm back to school, principals
from Baltimore to Palm Beach, Fla., and from the Texas panhandle to
inner-city Los Angeles, say they are grappling with perhaps the
most acute teacher shortage in recent memory, with student
enrollments continuing to swell and a rising tide of educators
flowing out of their classrooms to retirement. (Bruce Bennett/Palm
Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) TEXARKANA, Texas -- Aug. 30, 1999 --
TRAVEL-REDRIVER-GIMMICKS-2, 08-30 -- HER HEART BELONGS IN TEXAS:
Taneka Washington, 7, straddles the state line separating Texas and
Arkansas which runs directly through the center of downtown
Texarkana. The city's split personality requires two of nearly
everything except the State Line Post Office and the Bi-State
Justice Center. (E. Joseph Deering/Houston Chronicle Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) PARIS, Texas -- Aug. 30, 1999 --
TRAVEL-REDRIVER-GIMMICKS-1-HNS, 08-30 -- Barbara Carpenter checks
out the new western hat on top of the Eiffel Tower at the Love
Civic Center in Paris. Constructed by union workers with donated
materials, the tower debuted five years ago and enjoys a spot
overlooking the city's civic center. (E. Joseph Deering/Houston
Chronicle Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- Aug. 30, 1999 -- TEN-USOPEN-1, 08-30 --
Those trying to purchase tickets for the U.S. Open on Monday are
forced to wait more than 2 hours. The Open, the last of the year's
Grand Slam tournaments, began its two-week run in Flushing Meadows
on a day windy enough to possibly play havoc with the tennis.
(James Estrin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- Aug. 30, 1999 -- NY-CLUBS, 08-30 -- Mitch
Dessaure, left, checks the identification of people trying to get
into the Sound Factory, a dance club on Manhattan's Upper West
Side. Long a mecca for anything-goes night life, New York and its
big-box dance clubs have become heavily regulated places. ( Linda
Rosier/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) HOUSTON -- Aug. 30, 1999 -- BIKE-TRAILS-HOUSTON-HNS,
08-30 -- Claire Caudill, chairwoman of the Memorial Park Advisory
Board, stands on one of the eroded mountain bike paths closed by
the Houston Parks Department. About half the trails in the
1,500-acre park have been closed because of erosion, raising
complaints from Houston-area cyclists. Now, the park and its proper
use are at the center of a debate between thousands of off-road
mountain bikers and the park's traditional defenders, the Memorial
Park Advisory Board. (Kevin Fuji/Houston Chronicle Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) BRAZORIA, Texas -- Aug. 30, 1999 --
AMPUTEE-INVENTOR-HNS, 08-30 -- Ron Farquharson shows off some of
the tools that he and a partner designed to be used with a
prosthetic arm and held by a terminal device. His company,
Assistive Devices of Texas, obtained a patent on the terminal
device in 1995. Made of lightweight aircraft aluminum, it can be
turned to a 45-degree angle or be rotated 360 degrees. Farquharson,
52, lost his right hand in 1971 when a 7,500-pound hydraulics press
malfunctioned and crushed his arm. (Steve Olafson/Houston Chronicle
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) SYRACUSE, N.Y. -- Aug. 30, 1999 -- NY-CLINTONS-CAMPAIGN,
08-30 -- President Clinton and his wife Hillary Rodham Clinton, who
is considering a run for the U.S. Senate seat from New York, during
a visit to Baker's Chicken Coop at the New York State Fair on
Monday. The Clintons arrived in upstate New York to begin five days
of holiday-making and some campaigning after finishing a weekend in
the Hamptons. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) UNDATED -- Aug. 30, 1999 -- SCI-EINSTEIN-PAPERS-B&AMP;W,
08-30 -- In 1918, Einstein considered breaking off his engagement
to his cousin Elsa and marrying her daughter Ilse, 20, shown in
this undated photo. 12 years of his life are chronicled in seven
volumes and thousands of pages of the Collected Papers of Albert
Einstein, a massive effort to publish all the 43,000 or so
documents he left behind at Princeton's Institute for Advanced
Study when he died in 1955. (Courtesy of Eva Kayser/New York Times
Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) OCEAN GROVE BEACH, N.J. -- Aug. 30, 1999 --
HURRICANE-DENNIS, 08-30 -- Despite restrictions on swimming,
surfers ride the waves on Monday. Beaches were closed to swimmers
Monday as heavy surf associated with Hurricane Dennis pounded the
shore. Winds of up to 25 mph kicked up 10-foot swells as the storm
moved northeast. (Dith Pran/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) WASHINGTON -- Aug. 30, 1999 -- KEYES-PROFILE, 08-30 --
Presidential candidate Alan Keyes waits to be interviews at Fox
studios last week. Keyes, the arch-conservative radio talk show
host, is the invisible man in the Republican primary for president.
But to his small yet devoted cadre of followers, Keyes, a former
Reagan administration diplomat with a Harvard Ph.D., has something
his fellow arch conservatives lack: mesmerizing oratorical skills
twinned with a messianic vision. (Shana Raab/New York Times Photo)
LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) LOWELL, Mass. -- Aug. 30, 1999 -- SCI-STRESS-BOS, 08-30
-- Robert Karasek, professor in the department of work environment
at the University of Massachusetts, Lowell. Adding to a growing
body of evidence that workplace stress is harmful, researchers have
linked job strain with higher rates of heart disease and other
physical ailments, and are exploring the psychological effects of
working long hours or being disenchanted with a job. (Janet
Knott/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEEDHAM, Mass. -- Aug. 30, 1999 -- SCI-HYDROCEPHALUS,
08-30 -- Lindsay Corkin, 13, suffers from hydrocephalus due to a
brain tumor. Hydrocephalus, sometimes called ``water on the
brain,'' is caused by a blockage in the brain's circulatory system
leading to excess fluid pressure. Corkin recently received a
programmable valve that changes the pressure of her brain without
surgery through an implanted device. (Bill Greene/Boston Globe
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) BOSTON -- Aug. 30, 1999 -- COLLEGE-ADULTS-BOS, 08-30 --
Jessica McDonald, 42, expects to receive her degree from
UMass-Boston this spring. Only 25 percent of the students in
colleges and universities are 18-22. About 50 percent are adult
learners, a fast growing segment of the student body. (John
Tlumacki/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) MEXICO CITY -- Aug. 30, 1999 -- MEXICO-CITY-SFCHRON-3,
08-30 -- Two youths are searched on suspicion of taking part in a
robbery after being stopped by ``Los Huracanes'' (''The
Hurrinanes''), a special anti-crime squad of the Mexico City police
force. A year and a half after sweeping into office as the most
powerful leftist elected politician in Latin America, Mayor
Cuauhtemoc Cardenas has failed to bring substantial reform to
Mexico City. Many observers say that no one, not even Cardenas, who
is recognized even by his enemies as stubbornly incorruptible and
pro-reform, could solve them. (Carlos Avila Gonzalez/San Francisco
Chronicle)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) MEXICO CITY -- Aug. 30, 1999 -- MEXICO-CITY-SFCHRON-2,
08-30 -- Raul Dolores Martinez, and his family eat lunch in their
makeshift home in the hills above Mexico City. The Mexican capital
has grown uncontrollably into the extensive ``green areas,'' or
designated parklands, climbing the mountains on the city's south
and west edges. Growth is propelled by the annual arrival of
180,000 people from the countryside and by corrupt officials who
ignore zoning regulations. (Carlos Avila Gonzalez/San Francisco
Chronicle)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) MEXICO CITY -- Aug. 30, 1999 -- MEXICO-CITY-SFCHRON-1,
08-30 -- Visitors atop the Latin American Tower look out over part
of the city's skyline. Mexico City, with a metropolitan area
population of 20 million, is the biggest metropolis in the
hemisphere and one of the largest in the world. It is so gargantuan
that it dominates Mexico politically and economically in the same
way as Washington, New York and Los Angeles would the United States
if they were one mega-city. (Carlos Avila Gonzalez/San Francisco
Chronicle)
</P>
