<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Monday, 08/30/99. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) WASHINGTON -- Aug. 30, 1999 -- SUB-MUSEUM-ORBITER, 08-30
-- Bernie Poppert, an employee at the Smithsonian's National Air
Space Museum, puts together the Breitling Orbiter 3 in the lobby of
the museum on Monday. The Breitling Orbiter 3, the first manned
balloon ever to make a non-stop trip around the earth, will be
permanently housed at the museum. The balloon was donated by the
pilots of the historic flight, Dr. Bertrand Piccard and Brian
Jones. The pilots completed their three-week trip when they landed
in Egypt on March 21, after flying 29,055 miles. No previous
attempts came even close. In the background at top is the Spirit of
St. Louis, which Charles Lindbergh flew across the Atlantic in
1927. (Justin Lane/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) ATLANTA -- Aug. 30, 1999 -- LIBRARY-DIRECTOR-COX, 08-30
-- Mary Kaye Hooker has been hired as director of the
Atlanta-Fulton Library System. Of her tumultuous experience
managing the public libraries in El Paso, Hooker says, ``That
library system demands so much of its director. You become well
qualified to take on any challenge. It's a wonderful training
ground.'' (Charlotte B. Teagle/Atlanta Journal-Constitution Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) NEW YORK -- Aug. 30, 1999 -- TEN-USOPEN-3, 08-30 -- A
record opening-day crowed turned out Monday, the first day of the
United States Open, where blustery winds tested the competitors in
Flushing Meadows. Despite the conditions, no top players were
upset. (James Estrin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) WASHINGTON -- Aug. 30, 1999 -- FAITH-POLITICS, 08-30 --
President Clinton and his wife speak with Rev. J. Phillip Wogaman
after services at the United Foundry Methodist Church in January
1998. Politicians have always made a point of having themselves
photographed as they step out of church on Sunday, carrying a Bible
and shaking the minister's hand. But in the early campaign for the
2000 elections, the rite of political piety has moved far beyond
the sac ramental photo opportunity. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) UNDATED -- Aug. 30, 1999 -- SCI-LIVERMORE-RESIGN-B&AMP;W,
08-30 -- E. Michael Campbell, associate director for lasers at
Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory, in an undated photo.
Campbell resigned last friday when it was disclosed that he had
never received the doctorate he claimed. Though he resigned his
position, he remains an employee of the laboratory currently on
leave, a laboratory spokesman said. Campbell is recognized as one
of the world's leading experts in ultra-high-energy lasers.
(Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) GARZE, China -- Aug. 30, 1999 -- CHINA-TIBETANS, 08-30
-- Tibetan women work a barley field at Garze, near Tibet. Controls
are less strict than in Tibet, but many ethnic Tibetans find
China's rule oppressive. (Seth Faison/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) UNDATED -- Aug. 30, 1999 -- SCI-MULTICELL-B&AMP;W, 08-30 --
Frames of a movie showing the vortex state of Dictyostelium
discoideum - a species of soil amoeba - upon forming a
pancake-shaped multicellular organism that rotates under its own
power. A team of scientists at the University of California at San
Diego has invented a revealing new technique for observing
Dictyostelium and has devised a mathematical model to account for
its behavior. (UCSD/New York Times Photo)
</P>
