<P>
   (NYT4) BOSTON -- Aug. 30, 1999 -- COLLEGE-ADULTS-BOS, 08-30 --
Jessica McDonald, 42, expects to receive her degree from
UMass-Boston this spring. Only 25 percent of the students in
colleges and universities are 18-22. About 50 percent are adult
learners, a fast growing segment of the student body. (John
Tlumacki/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) MEXICO CITY -- Aug. 30, 1999 -- MEXICO-CITY-SFCHRON-3,
08-30 -- Two youths are searched on suspicion of taking part in a
robbery after being stopped by ``Los Huracanes'' (''The
Hurrinanes''), a special anti-crime squad of the Mexico City police
force. A year and a half after sweeping into office as the most
powerful leftist elected politician in Latin America, Mayor
Cuauhtemoc Cardenas has failed to bring substantial reform to
Mexico City. Many observers say that no one, not even Cardenas, who
is recognized even by his enemies as stubbornly incorruptible and
pro-reform, could solve them. (Carlos Avila Gonzalez/San Francisco
Chronicle)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) MEXICO CITY -- Aug. 30, 1999 -- MEXICO-CITY-SFCHRON-2,
08-30 -- Raul Dolores Martinez, and his family eat lunch in their
makeshift home in the hills above Mexico City. The Mexican capital
has grown uncontrollably into the extensive ``green areas,'' or
designated parklands, climbing the mountains on the city's south
and west edges. Growth is propelled by the annual arrival of
180,000 people from the countryside and by corrupt officials who
ignore zoning regulations. (Carlos Avila Gonzalez/San Francisco
Chronicle)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) MEXICO CITY -- Aug. 30, 1999 -- MEXICO-CITY-SFCHRON-1,
08-30 -- Visitors atop the Latin American Tower look out over part
of the city's skyline. Mexico City, with a metropolitan area
population of 20 million, is the biggest metropolis in the
hemisphere and one of the largest in the world. It is so gargantuan
that it dominates Mexico politically and economically in the same
way as Washington, New York and Los Angeles would the United States
if they were one mega-city. (Carlos Avila Gonzalez/San Francisco
Chronicle)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
