<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5065 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CARREFOUR-PROMODES-AR     08-30 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARREFOUR-PROMODES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 FRENCH COMPANIES JOIN FORCES TO MAKE EUROPE'S LARGEST SUPERMARKET
CHAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Germany, France, Ark., The Netherlands, Spain, Brazil)  (ART ADV: A graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Pressed into the defensive by Wal-Mart Stores Inc.'s
aggressive march into Europe, two of the biggest supermarket
operators in France announced a $16.6 billion combination Monday
intended to build a stockade against Wal-Mart's ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   Carrefour SA said it would exchange six of its shares for every
share of Promodes SA in a deal that would create the world's
second-biggest retailer after Wal-Mart. It would supplant Metro AG
of Germany as Europe's largest retailer. The all-stock deal, which
must be approved by European Union regulators, will build a retail
chain with 9,000 stores in Europe, Asia and Latin America and
expected sales this year of $56 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Carrefour's offer values Promodes at 841.8 euros a share, or
15.9 billion euros, a 20 percent premium to its closing price of
700 euros on Friday. The announcement of the deal in Paris pushed
Carrefour's shares down by as much 4.8 percent before they
rebounded and closed up 0.10 euro, to 140.4 euros. Shares of
Promodes jumped by 129 euros, or 18.4 percent, to 829 euros. Retail
stocks rose across the Continent as investors anticipated a merger
wave among retailers, all unsettled by Wal-Mart's campaign. A
similar surge was forecast in London for Tuesday, which had a
holiday Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In June, Wal-Mart, which had sales of $138 billion last year,
agreed to pay $10.8 billion in cash for Asda Group PLC, Britain's
third-largest supermarket chain, adding to its acquisition of two
German retail chains _ Wertkauf and 74 Spar Handels AG outlets _ in
1997. The drive into Europe is propelled by acquisitions because
strict zoning regulations in France, Britain and elsewhere leave
little room for new stores. The maneuvers have forced European
retailers to consider joining forces so they can use size to
negotiate lower prices from suppliers, enhancing their ability to
meet the challenge from Wal-Mart, based in Bentonville, Ark.
</P>
<P>
   France _ one of Europe's big three retail markets along with
Britain and Germany _ had been seen by analysts as a big gap in
Wal-Mart's European armor, and it was not immediately clear how it
would respond to the French deal.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts differed on how the combination would affect Wal-Mart's
strategy. ``It only means that international retailers recognize
Wal Mart's aggressive push into Europe and are beginning to act,''
said Jeff Feiner, who follows Wal-Mart for Lehman Brothers. ``But
this will not deter Wal-Mart.''
</P>
<P>
   But Burt Flickinger, managing director of Reach Marketing, a
retail consulting firm in Westport, Conn., disagreed. ``This means
Carrefour will dominate the European Union, before Wal-Mart has a
chance to reload and get beyond its last merger.'' Although the
French retailer does $100 billion less in annual sales worldwide
than the American giant, Flickinger thinks that it has distinct
advantages in the global arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``To win the world war, Wal-Mart needs two things: fresh
consumables and fashion.'' Promodes, he reasons, was the jewel of
the supermarket chains available for purchase. Meanwhile,
``Carrefour has much more fashion authority, it is much more on
trend.'' Flickinger thinks that Wal-Mart will now have to push its
domestic expansion much faster to meet its internal goals for
increasing revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Salomon Smith Barney said in a report before the French deal
Monday that Wal-Mart ``is one of the main triggers for
consolidation in Europe.'' But, the report said, ``even with Asda
in its portfolio, Wal-Mart still has some way to go. It still lacks
access to France.'' In June, the family-owned French chain Auchan
said it had been approached by Wal-Mart.
</P>
<P>
   The chairmen of both Carrefour and Promodes left little doubt
that their move had been set off by the pressure for consolidation.
``Given the acceleration in alliances in the distribution business,
this merger comes at the right time and is without doubt the best
possible for the two partners,'' said Paul-Louis Halley, the head
of Promodes.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the deal, Carre-four will issue 115 million
new shares to Promodes stockholders. That means that, between them,
the founding families of the two companies, along with their
supporters, will have 33.5 percent of the stock and 35.8 percent of
the voting rights in the new company. Under French rules, a 33
percent share of voting rights constitutes a blocking minority,
theoretically immunizing the merged company against a hostile bid.
</P>
<P>
   But Daniel Bernard, the chairman of Carrefour, who will be
chairman and chief executive of the merged company, suggested that
Europe's vulnerability to Wal-Mart was not likely to go away. ``We
are still smaller than the biggest companies that are far from
renouncing their intentions to become ever more powerful,'' he said
at a news conference in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   The two companies said no layoffs were planned among the 240,000
employees, 110,000 of whom are in France.
</P>
<P>
   Even before Monday's announcement, Carrefour had been
aggressively seeking to strengthen its position globally and
domestically, overtaking Wal-Mart to become the biggest retailer in
Brazil while acquiring Comptoirs Modernes SA, which operates more
than 350 supermarkets in France. Carrefour's assets include more
than 1,500 large mass convenience stores known as hypermarkets and
supermarkets in 20 countries. Promodes had also been seeking to
expand, but failed in a hostile bid to take over Casino Guichard
Perrachon SA.
</P>
<P>
   The new company is expected to rely on the Continent for 85
percent of its sales.
</P>
<P>
   The deal puts pressure on other European retailers, notably
Koninlijke Ahold in the Netherlands and France's Casino, to embark
on consolidation moves. Ahold said Monday that it would refrain
from hostile takeovers but was considering deals in France,
Britain, Italy and Spain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
