NYT-08-30-99 2141EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990830.0433 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5066 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-MEXICO-CHIAPAS-ART-92     08-30 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-CHIAPAS-ART-920(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROAD DISPUTE REVIVES ZAPATISTA FIGHT IN MEXICO 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By JULIA PRESTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN CRISTOBAL DE LAS CASAS, Mexico _ A spat over a dirt road
through a soggy jungle has reignited the clash between the
government and Zapatista rebels in the Mexican state of Chiapas,
showing that five years of efforts by President Ernesto Zedillo to
bring peace to the Indian region have failed.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute began in mid-August when masked Zapatistas formed a
human barrier in a faraway rain forest hamlet to block the
government from opening a roadway into their main stronghold. Army
troops flew in to clear the way, activating tensions that led to
the first direct skirmishes between the two sides in more than a
year.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks later, Zapatistas and soldiers are still staring at
each other angrily across a coil of concertina wire in a humid
clearing.
</P>
<P>
   The confrontation with the Zapatistas, which President Zedillo
inherited when he took office in December 1994, has proved to be
one of the noisiest and most intractable issues of his
administration. The clamor for peace came not only from Mexicans
but also from devotees of the masked guerrillas, and their
pro-Indian cause, in the United States and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The president pledged time and again to engage the Zapatistas in
negotiations to settle the conflict and to expand the rights of
Mexico's indigenous peoples.
</P>
<P>
   But as Zedillo prepares for Sept. 1, when he will give his last
state of the union address before becoming a lame-duck leader in an
election year, protagonists on all sides have given up on a
resolution or even renewed talks before he steps down in November
of next year.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo's lack of results in Chiapas will be a political burden
for the man believed to be his choice for his party's presidential
nomination, Francisco Labastida Ochoa. When he was interior
minister, Labastida helped to devise, and then carried out, the
policies that instead of reducing animosities have kept the state
at a slow boil.
</P>
<P>
   Chiapas became national news in Mexico once again with the feud
that erupted in Amador Hernandez, a solitary hamlet in the Lacandon
rain forest, whose canopy hides the Zapatistas' most important
redoubts. The state government wanted to connect the hamlet and
muddy wilds around it to the outside world.
</P>
<P>
   But as charted, the road would also provide access to the jungle
from a military base the Mexican army uses for operations to harass
and hem in the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   While several nearby Indian communities support the road, in
Amador Hernandez a pro-Zapatista majority furiously opposes it.
Nevertheless, the state authorities sent surveyors to prepare the
final plans for construction.
</P>
<P>
   When Zapatista men, women and even children put up their
roadblock, the government dispatched two companies of military riot
police by helicopter, ostensibly to protect the surveyors.
</P>
<P>
   The Zapatistas called in their own reinforcements, several dozen
students who came to Chiapas at the invitation of Subcommander
Marcos, the Zapatista leader, from a strike at the National
Autonomous University of Mexico, in the capital.
</P>
<P>
   The standoff came to blows only once, on Aug. 15. The Zapatistas
began pummeling the soldiers with clubs, and the troops repelled
them with tear gas and truncheons, leaving a half-dozen people with
minor injuries.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 25, Zapatistas and soldiers stumbled into each other in
another village in the rain forest. Seven soldiers were wounded by
machetes or rocks, and two Zapatistas had bullet wounds. The next
day, the government suspended the road construction.
</P>
<P>
   On the face of it, the Zapatista rebellion should have been easy
for Zedillo to extinguish. The Zapatista National Liberation Army
never demonstrated any military prowess and met in combat with the
government for only about two weeks since staging an uprising in
January 1994.
</P>
<P>
   But the Zapatistas' demands for justice and equality for Indians
resonated with Mexicans, as did the seductive figure of Marcos, a
guerrilla strategist who also composes witty political epistles and
even children's books.
</P>
<P>
   The Zapatistas' resistance has been far more effective than a
straight show of military force could have been. Peace talks
produced a preliminary accord in February 1996, but the
negotiations collapsed in September of that year.
</P>
<P>
   Since early 1998, Zedillo has pursued a double-barreled
strategy. On one hand troops have borne down on the Zapatistas,
patrolling and setting up bases all around them but avoiding
head-on fights. Meanwhile, the government lavished resources on
Chiapas for health clinics, land reform, power lines and roads in a
bid to draw Indians away from the rebel movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the Zapatistas won't talk peace, my strategy has been to
press hard with our social programs to remove some of the causes of
the conflict,'' said Emilio Rabasa Gamboa, the federal government's
top official for Chiapas. ``The policy has been so successful that
the Zapatistas are trying to block it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the name of protecting Mexican sovereignty, the country's
immigration authorities have harassed and often expelled foreigners
who have come to Chiapas to help the Zapatistas, cutting the rebels
off from sorely needed overseas assistance.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy worked to undermine the rebels. About 100 people
have defected from Zapatista ranks this year _ the first year in
which there has been a steady flow of deserters.
</P>
<P>
   But the policies only antagonized Zapatista supporters and
exacerbated volatile rifts in Indian areas where they remain
strong, completely souring the environment for peace talks.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Zapatistas contributed to their own isolation. Marcos seems
less and less like a visionary and more like a cult leader. Holed
up in his hideout, he meets almost exclusively with admirers. While
the rest of Mexico is passionately embroiled in the presidential
campaign, the Zapatista leader rejected electoral politics and
disdained all political parties.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than keeping their focus on Indian rights, the rebels
took up other, oddly marginal causes.
</P>
<P>
   Most recently they held a jungle conference to drum up
opposition to an obscure legislative proposal that would grant
private concessions the authority to operate some of Mexico's
pre-Hispanic archeological sites.
</P>
<P>
   They tried to fend off the encroachment of government social
programs by barring their followers from any contact with them. Not
only have villagers who support the Zapatistas rejected new roads,
but they do not even allow their children to be vaccinated by
public health agents.
</P>
<P>
   Zapatista leaders had instead expected a shower of international
aid, but it has not materialized. Communities of their followers
struggle with severe want while watching others reap the benefits
of their rebellion.
</P>
<P>
   The events in Amador Hernandez brought out outlandish positions
on all sides, revealing the political morass that Chiapas has
become.
</P>
<P>
   At the outset Marcos announced that the army had ``gone to war''
in Amador Hernandez because the hamlet sat on top of ``the largest
petroleum reserves in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The Energy Ministry quickly responded that there is no petroleum
worth exploiting in the vicinity. Then the rebel leader came out
with another of his whimsical missives, a folk tale full of Maya
wisdom about the virtue of perseverance. In the midst of the
dangerous tension, it seemed less insightful than surreal.
</P>
<P>
   The Zapatista leader was soon eclipsed by the Chiapas governor,
Roberto Albores Guillen, an ally of Zedillo. Taking the jungle
standoff as a personal affront, he counterattacked by whipping up
the anti-Zapatista rage and state chauvinism of his supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The patience of the people of Chiapas is running out,''
Albores warned in a stemwinder speech in a pro-government village.
``We can't allow a band of delinquents to hold our state hostage
any longer.''
</P>
<P>
   A few days after the governor's speech, a mob of his Indian
supporters beat up a Mexican doctor and two foreigners on a rural
road, denouncing them as Zapatistas.
</P>
<P>
   But Albores' sharpest wrath was for Ofelia Medina, a former
television soap opera star who is one of the Zapatistas' best-known
Mexican supporters. Ms. Medina, in Indian garb and an elaborate
turban, slogged for nine hours through the underbrush to reach
Amador Hernandez and make a stand with the Zapatistas there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had it with little groups of radicals led by Ofelia
Medina who come to determine the destiny of Chiapas,'' Albores
said. The city council of San Cristobal de las Casas, the largest
city in the state's Indian region, declared Ms. Medina persona non
grata and ordered her to leave the state within 72 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Finally federal officials stepped in to restrain Albores. Rabasa
noted in public statements that all Mexicans, including Ms. Medina,
enjoy constitutional rights to travel within their country and
express their ideas.
</P>
<P>
   But Rabasa's action came too late to stop Albores from saying
what everyone in Chiapas now holds true: that Zedillo's peace plan
has failed and the Zapatistas seem certain to wait until after the
presidential election next year before considering a return to
talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I have to say to the federal government is this: Let the
people of Chiapas handle our own problems,'' Albores told the
president testily in his speech. ``We're ready to take the
responsibility into our own hands _ and that's not just brave
talk.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
