<HEADLINE>
BOND YIELDS RISE AS PRICES DROP  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Minn.)   By ROBERT HURTADO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bond yields rose sharply Monday amid investor fears
that the Federal Reserve would increase short-term rates again in
the coming months as evidence of a strong economy continues to
mount.
</P>
<P>
   By late in the day, in trading volume that was lighter than
normal, the price of the 30-year Treasury bond dropped 1 3/32 to
101, while its yield, which moves in the opposite direction, rose
to 6.05 percent, from 5.97 percent on Friday. It was the highest
level since Aug. 16, when the yield was 6.08 percent.
</P>
<P>
   With investors growing cautious, the market's tone has shifted
more toward selling rallies, traders said. Also weighing on the
market was concern about the supply of new debt issues, as
corporate treasurers scramble to sell securities before year-end.
The reluctance among investors to buy bonds as the year wears on
could lead to rising rates, as investors seek some reward for the
higher risk to which they feel they might be exposed if Year 2000
problems occur.
</P>
<P>
   ``The massive supply of corporate debt has added to the
liquidity squeeze,'' said Sung Won Sohn, senior vice president and
chief economic officer at Wells Fargo in Minneapolis. ``When
corporations issue debt, the underwriters selling that debt reduce
their exposure to losses by hedging those transactions.''
</P>
<P>
   Securities dealers of corporate transactions often sell or swap
Treasuries ahead of these debt offerings, adding to the available
supply of government securities and thus placing upward pressure on
rates. The securities dealers then buy back Treasuries when the
corporate paper is in the hands of investors.
</P>
<P>
   The corporate supply calendar, however, is sparse this week,
before an expected flood of issuance after the Labor Day weekend.
</P>
<P>
   While the Fed has signaled that it may be finished raising rates
for now, the door is not completely shut on further increases
should the economy not show signs of slowing. Monday's report on
new home sales in July took an unexpected rise to its
second-highest level on record, as sales rose one-tenth of 1
percent to an annualized rate of 980,000 units. Some analysts had
expected 910,000. The increase trailed only November 1998's annual
pace of 985,000.
</P>
<P>
   Sohn, citing labor shortages, the weakening dollar, economic
expansion abroad and a big rise in oil prices, said that the Fed
``is not finished with tightening.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The inflation picture is likely to deteriorate,'' Sohn said.
</P>
<P>
   Sherry Cooper, chief economist at Nesbitt Burns Securities,
thinks that bonds are vulnerable this week to the August National
Association of Purchasing Management report, due out on Wednesday,
which is expected to show a rebound after the outsized July
decline, as well as to the closely watched employment and payroll
report on Friday. Last week's report of a drop in initial jobless
claims suggests that this Friday's payroll figure is likely to be
strong, Ms. Cooper said, and the unemployment rate may well have
dipped a notch, to 4.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's weekly bill auction was in line with expectations, with
the three-month bill awarded at the high rate of 4.875 percent, up
from 4.85 percent a week earlier. The six-month maturity was
awarded at the high rate of 4.99 percent, up from 4.95 percent.
Noncompetitive bids were considered satisfactory for the
three-month bill, but a little soft for the six-month issue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
