<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRAPER DIDN'T WALK AWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The show goes on, and Scotty Draper went on with it.
For one day.
</P>
<P>
   One bleak Monday, when slate-gray clouds enshrouded Flushing
Meadow, and a wind like Pete Sampras's serve cut across the courts
and plazas, leading the customers to raise their collars and duck
into jackets and sweaters.
</P>
<P>
   No one felt bleaker than Draper out on Court 7, his thoughts,
like the day, ``very clouded.'' Still, he was part of the show
called the US Tennis Championships. Running for a 119th consecutive
year, it always goes on.
</P>
<P>
   Players have marched off to a variety of conflicts, including
the Spanish-American War and World Wars I and II. Hurricanes and
other inclemencies have taken bites out of the schedule. ``I waited
a week in the hotel for the '38 hurricane to blow out so I could
complete my Grand Slam,'' says Don Budge. Yet the tournament has
endured into old age. First at Newport, R.I. Then Forest Hills.
Now, a few miles down the road.
</P>
<P>
   It was opening day, and the original stadium, refurbished with
red brick facing and named for a neighborhood guy, Louis Armstrong,
gleamed like the trumpet he played with such style and feeling.
Gleaming as well on pedestals within the stadium's new museum are
US championship trophies loaned by the Hall of Fame, having been
won by such bygone luminaries as Bill Tilden and Helen Wills Moody,
Alice Marble and Titanic survivor Dick Williams. You almost could
hear Armstrong tooting, ``As the Saints Go Marchin' In.''
</P>
<P>
   If Draper, a young Australian lefthander, had any familiarity
with the works of the singing horn player, the dirge, ``St. James
Infirmary,'' might have run through his mind. And Louis rasping:
``Went down to St. James Infirmary/To see my baby there,/Stretched
out on a long white table,/So young so clean so fair . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Opening day was closing day for Draper, as it was for all the
first-round losers. No tragedy in that. The hardest part for him
was merely showing up because his tragedy had occurred July 19, the
death of his 23-year-old wife, Kellie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe me, I didn't want to come,'' Draper said after an
obviously dispirited loss to an ex-NCAA champ out of Stanford, Paul
Goldstein, 6-3, 6-1, 6-0. ``My heart didn't want to come here.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think you can't walk away. You're not going to get
anywhere in life just walking away from things.''
</P>
<P>
   And Draper, 25, a very good player who made the last 16 of the
US Open two years ago, didn't walk away from the woman he loved
even though her life expectancy wasn't terrific. Afflicted with
cystic fibrosis from childhood, she was a long shot to go past her
teens. Nevertheless, he married her almost two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had five years together _ and now I have that,'' he said.
``That's really something for me to have.''
</P>
<P>
   Kellie Grieg Draper was always ``rugged-out,'' said an Aussie
friend, using a homeland expression for somebody wearing a heavy
coat.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had trouble keeping warm,'' said Scotty. ``Her illness.
The breathing could be tough, and we had plans for a lung
transplant. We thought that would help a lot. She was doing all
right, and we didn't expect her to die . . . now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was at Wimbledon, and she was home. She caught a cold.
Didn't seem like much, but suddenly she was very sick.''
</P>
<P>
   Draper had the bad luck to draw Sampras in the first round at
Wimbledon. Much worse luck was in the wings, at home in Brisbane.
He got there for Kellie's last days.
</P>
<P>
   She died the day Australia clinched the Davis Cup quarterfinal
over the US, 3-2, at Boston. Aussie captain John Newcombe was
notified, but Draper asked that the awful news be kept from his
Queensland mate, Patrick Rafter, and the others. He wanted nothing
to deter them.
</P>
<P>
   His US Open lasted 81 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, I knew three weeks ago when I left home to come over
here that it was going to be difficult,'' he said. ``It's just
difficult to concentrate on the court. It's going to take some time
to get through this period. But I wanted to play when there was no
pressure on myself to perform. Just to get over, get a lot out of
the way, see all the guys. Maybe next time, when I start full-on,
all this behind, and I can concentrate.''
</P>
<P>
   His foe, Goldstein, said, ``It's a match you play with heavy
heart because you feel for Scotty.'' Goldstein shares the general
feeling of these nomads: ``Scotty is one of the most liked, most
respected people on tour. For him to step out there and play . . .
he's all class.''
</P>
<P>
   Draper apologized to Goldstein for a poor performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want Paul to think I disrespected him, like I wasn't
trying,'' said Draper.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me, `My head just wasn't in it, mate,' '' said
Goldstein.
</P>
<P>
   It was hard, but it was also the Aussie code. If you're not
hurt, you play. Draper was hurt where it didn't show, but he
carried on. He knew from the beginning Kellie was sick, and he
carried on.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, it wasn't hard to go into marriage,'' he said. ``You say
for better or worse _ you're marrying the person. Whatever they
bring, they bring. Whatever problems. You marry because you love
that person. The quality of time you spend with her is the most
important. I'd do it again.''
</P>
<P>
   He took her to Paris in 1996, and took her up her high, looking
at the city from the top of the Eiffel Tower. A year later they
went back, same place, and another high: Scotty gave her an
engagement ring. This terrible low doesn't negate the highs, he
feels.
</P>
<P>
   The show goes on without Scotty, but he didn't walk away from it
or Kellie.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
