<HEADLINE>
RAMON MARTINEZ TO PITCH THURSDAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- At long last, Pedro the Younger will be joined by
Ramon the Elder. In the Martinez brothers, the Red Sox will have
siblings pitching together on the same team for the first time in
the 99-year history of the Olde Towne Team.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Jimy Williams summoned reporters into his office Monday
to announce that Ramon Martinez, who has not pitched in the big
leagues in 14 1/2 months because of shoulder surgery, will make his
Boston debut Thursday, when he is scheduled to start against the
Kansas City Royals.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, who won 123 games in 11 seasons for the Los Angeles
Dodgers and whose career that includes a 20-win season (1990), an
18-strikeout game (1990), and a no-hitter (1995), will be on an
85-pitch count and will be followed to the mound by knuckleballer
Tim Wakefield, who has served as the staff starter, closer, and
Band-Aid this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's best in our minds to do it in that sequence,'' Williams
said. ``Ramon first, Wakefield second. That's what we're going to
do. Give it a shot. Especially when the kid came into my office
(Sunday) and said he's ready to pitch, he wants to pitch and help
this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Wakefield, who made 14 saves when he replaced Tom Gordon as the
closer, was just recently returned to the rotation and made two
starts, losing 6-0 to the Texas Rangers and getting no decision in
a 7-6 win over the Angels on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   He accepted this new change in assignment in his usual stoic
fashion.
</P>
<P>
   ``No big deal,'' said Wakefield, whose won-lost record (4-9)
belies his value to the club this season, one in which he not only
bailed out the bullpen but performed a similar service for Bret
Saberhagen when the sore-shouldered pitcher was able to go just two
innings in his last start.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think about it,'' Wakefield said. ``This is the best way to
try and do it. My understanding of it is they're going to give
Ramon a shot, see if he can pitch here, instead of giving him
another minor league rehab start. What's the sense of sending him
on another rehab start? He's got to start here sooner or later.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's logical for me to back him up out of the pen, because
it's my day to throw and it's easier for me to get loose, because
I've done it (relieved). And what if he can only go two innings?
Why deplete the bullpen?''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, without elaborating, insisted that Wakefield will
remain in the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not my decision,'' Wakefield said. ``But they told me I'm
definitely a starter. Will we go to six starters? I don't know. But
I'm not worried about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams ruled out a six-man rotation. A likely scenario, if
Martinez proves he can contribute: Wakefield could come back Sunday
on two days' rest and take the place of the ineffective Mark
Portugal in the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Ramon Martinez, 31, will serve as the bookend to a series in
which Pedro Martinez, 28, pitched the opener. The elder Martinez
last pitched for the Dodgers on June 14, 1998, and 16 days later
underwent rotator cuff surgery on his right shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   After signing with the Red Sox as a free agent in March,
Martinez made 10 rehabilitation assignments in the minor leagues,
the last one coming last Thursday for Triple A Pawtucket. In all,
he threw 36 innings and had a 2-1 record with a 3.73 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   After throwing a side session in the Sox bullpen on Sunday,
Martinez told Williams he was ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a very long time,'' said Martinez, who is the
taller, more reserved, and more mature of the brothers (or, as one
press box observer noted, Wally to Pedro's more excitable Beaver).
</P>
<P>
   Once known for a fastball that topped out around 95 miles an
hour, Martinez estimates that his velocity is around 86-88.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're young, what do you think? You're going to blow
everybody away,'' Martinez said. ``Ten years later, you don't have
a 95 mile-an-hour fastball. What do you do? You use your mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez said he is pleased with the way he has recaptured
command of his pitches but warned against great expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't expect to pitch a shutout or go nine innings,'' he
said. ``I just want to go out there and do the best I can, get some
innings for the team and help them out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
