<HEADLINE>
WORRIES OF A 3RD RATE INCREASE PULL STOCKS DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stock prices fell for the third consecutive session
Monday, pulled down by worries that in early October the Federal
Reserve may increase short-term interest rates for a third time
this year.
</P>
<P>
   A stronger-than-expected report on new-home sales for July and
an earnings warning from a big personal automobile insurer combined
to raise anxiety during morning trading. A selloff in the bond
market, which pushed yields on long-term Treasury bonds to 6.05
percent, compounded the worries.
</P>
<P>
   The result was a broad decline in equity prices, one that sent
the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index to its biggest loss in nearly
six weeks and battered financial service and transportation stocks.
The S&AMP;P 500 fell 24.25 points, or 1.8 percent, to 1,324.02.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average dropped 176.04 points, or 1.6
percent, to 10,914.13. Financial stocks like American Express and
J.P. Morgan accounted for much of the drop.
</P>
<P>
   Big losses in American International Group, the multinational
insurance company, Bank of America and America Online generated the
biggest loss in the S&AMP;P 500 index since July 20.
</P>
<P>
   The technology-heavy NASDAQ composite shed 46.21 points, or 1.7
percent, to 2,712.69.
</P>
<P>
   With many investors on vacation, trading volume was light: On
the New York Stock Exchange, about 610 million shares changed
hands.
</P>
<P>
   Still, traders and analysts were not willing to say the lack of
activity was a positive sign for the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people will say that because volume is light this
selloff doesn't mean anything,'' said William Meehan, chief market
analyst at Cantor Fitzgerald. ``I am not so sure. I told our
clients this morning that this week is important.''
</P>
<P>
   Meehan and others are concerned that if reports later in the
week _ particularly the August employment data, due on Friday _
portray an economy that is showing few signs of slowing down, the
Federal Reserve Board will be forced to raise short-term interest
rates again in early October.
</P>
<P>
   The shift in sentiment, which the new-home sales numbers helped
to promote, comes only days after most traders seemed convinced
that last week's rate increase by the Fed was the last of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, this is just a replay of the cycle we played out in
June, the last time the Fed bumped rates,'' said Michael Clarm,
head of U.S. stock trading at Credit Suisse First Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went into that increase with tremendous negative sentiment,
and we did the same thing going in to last week. Now the
anticipation is gone and we are still wondering if there is another
hike down the road.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the threat posed by higher interest rates,
insurance and financial service company stocks were hurt by an
announcement late Friday from Progressive Corp., the nation's
fourth-largest personal automobile insurer, that it would miss
earnings estimates for the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Progressive, an S&AMP;P component, fell 16 1/4, to 102 3/4.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement dragged down other insurance company stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Allstate, the largest publicly traded car insurer, fell 1 13/16,
to 33 11/16. And Safeco Corp. lost 1 9/16, to 34 5/8.
</P>
<P>
   Diversified financial service company stocks also slumped. The
Standard &AMP; Poor's financial stock index fell 5.34 points, or 3.9
percent, to 130.36. Citigroup fell 2 1/4 to 44 3/4. American
Express dropped 4 15/16, to 139 11/16. General Electric, parent of
GE Capital, fell 2 5/16, to 114 1/4. And J.P. Morgan lost 3, to 130
3/4.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, it was a pretty good day for drug stocks.
Bristol-Myers Squibb gained 5/8, to 72 1/4. Eli Lilly rose 1 1/8,
to 76 3/8. Pfizer rose 1/4, to 38 7/8.
</P>
<P>
   Technology shares, including many Internet companies, fell after
AT&AMP;T, following similar moves by MCI WorldCom and Sprint, announced
the introduction of a discount long-distance rate. AT&AMP;T fell 1 1/2,
to 46. MCI/Worldcom dropped 2 7/16, to 76 1/16.
</P>
</TEXT>
