<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATTERNS-FASHION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BALMAIN DESIGNER MAKES U.S. DEBUT; STORE DESIGNER WEARS MILLENNIUM
ON HIS SLEEVE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Calif., France)   By CATHY HORYN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Gilles Dufour, the new ready-to-wear designer at
Balmain, was in town recently to go over details for his first
American store appearance, at Saks Fifth Avenue on Sept. 9. Dufour,
who has the swept-back demeanor of a 1970s French film star, was
Karl Lagerfeld's assistant at Chanel for 15 years, and it's no
exaggeration to say that his rapid style of speech is oddly
familiar. ``It's Karl,'' Dufour conceded. ``If I don't talk fast,
I'm afraid I'll sound stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   Dufour is too modest. His first Balmain show, in Paris last
March, drew a throng of admirers, including Catherine Deneuve, Lee
Radziwill Ross and Claudia Schiffer. The clothes were young with a
knowing French accent _ tweed blazers with tiny flowers embroidered
on the cuffs; snappy broadcloth shirts with white, oversize
collars, and the occasional gamine town coat.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Balmain, I wanted a change from the old, jolie madame look
to one that is more wearable and hip, for the woman who moves,''
Dufour said. He suddenly looked nonplused. ``Maybe I'm repeating
the stuff I said before.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe. But given Oscar de la Renta's success in designing
Balmain haute couture and the fact that Saks will carry the
ready-to-wear line at five other branches, including Dallas and
Beverly Hills, Dufour is eager to make his own mark. One thing he
has done that should make a difference with American customers, he
said, is to combine the easy fit of Italian sportswear with the
insouciant details of French fashion. ``It's a little bit _ how do
you say _ `twisted,''' he said. When it was suggested to Dufour
that his clothes looked sophisticated but not (yawn) overly
elegant, he beamed. ``Write that,'' he demanded. ``That's it
exactly.''
</P>
<P>
   Dufour, who is to be the guest of honor at a private dinner at
La Grenouille the night before he attempts to razzle-dazzle
customers, added that he had received a number of congratulatory
notes from American designers in Paris, including Marc Jacobs and
Michael Kors. ``All the American designers have been very
supportive,'' Dufour said. ``But not the French.'' He shrugged and
smiled. ``I'm not naive.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BETTING ON 01-01-00
</P>
<P>
   For years, as a store designer, Kenneth H. Walker was more
elaborate stage manager than show-stopping personality. It was
Walker's firm, Walker Group/CNI, that helped to give Burdine's a
youthful look in the early 1970s and that later in the decade
created Henri Bendel's Shoe Biz, probably the swingiest shoe salon
in town. Nowadays, though, Walker is kind of an advance man for the
new millennium, his picture popping up in publications like People
and Forbes. All because he had the foresight in 1994 to apply for a
trademark for the numbers 01-01-00.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all honesty,'' he said, ``I liked the way it looked. It
also wasn't language-dependent. You know what it means whether you
speak Chinese, French or English.''
</P>
<P>
   What's interesting about Walker's venture is not that the
trademark process cost him $500,000 in attorney fees or that the
logo appears on 1,000 different products in 14 categories (from
clocks to caps) or even that he and his partners could see sales
``go north of $100 million,'' as he put it. The intriguing thing is
how poorly fashion merchandise with the numbers has fared.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, when he began opening 01-01-00 boutiques in
department stores like Bloomingdale's and J.C. Penney, he predicted
that fashion would account for 60 percent of sales, with items like
mugs and picture frames taking up the slack. But by the end of
1998, he said, ``There was a ton of apparel left over.'' Apparently
he was ahead of consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Now that there are only 122 days left before the corks fly,
Walker says he expects to see more demand for millennium fun wear,
like evening bags and black stretch sheaths studded with
``01-01-00'' in rhinestones. But are fabric suppliers and clothing
manufacturers willing to gamble now with inventories to meet
last-minute party demands in December? To put it another way, what
do you do with a couple thousand millennial frocks on Jan. 2?
</P>
<P>
   As Walker said, ``My biggest problem has been taking on a whole
industry that is risk-averse, and getting it to take a chance on
something.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
