<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-CRENSHAW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRENSHAW SAVORS THE COUNTRY CLUB EXPERIENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE _ Monday's restful interlude on the way to the 33d
Ryder Cup at The Country Club may have been Ben Crenshaw's calm
after the storm. Or was it merely the calm before the storm that
may kick up when his players take on the Europeans Sept. 24-26?
</P>
<P>
   Crenshaw, who became upset when certain players talked more
about sharing the wealth than the joy of victory, showed up Monday
for a practice round with eight members of the team that will seek
to win Sam Ryder's cup for the first time since a 15-13 triumph at
The Belfry in Sutton Coldfield, England, in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods, Mark O'Meara, and Tom Lehman had prior commitments
and Davis Love was getting medical attention for a nerve problem in
his neck, but the group on hand in bright breezy conditions was
headed by David Duval, one of those singled out for criticism by
Crenshaw. Also on hand were Payne Stewart, Hal Sutton, Justin
Leonard, Jim Furyk, Phil Mickelson, Jeff Maggert, and captain's
pick Steve Pate.
</P>
<P>
   Crenshaw got in the eye of the storm following remarks by Woods,
Duval, O'Meara, and Mickelson over the PGA of America's
distribution of money from this event, but he was completely at
ease in a location he loves and on a course where he advanced to
the quarterfinals of the US Juniors in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the greatest honor for an American professional golfer to
be captain,'' said Crenshaw. ``I'm very emotional about it. It's a
great honor.''
</P>
<P>
   Only Pate, Love, Sutton, O'Meara, and Stewart have played this
course, which was restored by architect Rees Jones prior to the US
Open in 1988. Ten of the first 20 players in the world rankings are
on the US team; just four of the first 20 are on the European
roster. Crenshaw's major assignment is to guard against
overconfidence, make sure the storm warnings are in place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted them to go out, relax, have a little fun, but really
study it,'' said Crenshaw.
</P>
<P>
   ``The person getting here for the first time has to understand
what a special place this is. There are very few places in golf
that have atmosphere like this. I wanted them to experience this.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a day of learning for us, and a day to be together.
It's important for us to be together. It's a golf course that takes
a long time to learn, and you can't see it enough. This is a large
part of preparation.''
</P>
<P>
   The first glitch could be Love. He was scheduled to see Dr.
Frank Jobe Monday in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was having trouble with it at the PGA,'' said Crenshaw.
``He's played a lot and he's playing well. He's having it looked
at.''
</P>
<P>
   Should Love be unable to play, the replacement would be the No.
11 man on the points list, Bob Estes.
</P>
<P>
   Once the competition approaches, Crenshaw must piece together
the pairings for the first two days of foursomes and alternate-shot
matches and determining the playing order.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to put all of your thoughts into the one week
of practice,'' he said. ``It's still important to consider how
they're playing at the moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be talking to all of them. That's my job. Some captains
want the steadiest players to go into the alternate-shot
competition. It's a rudimentary procedure at this point. When I
look at my team, there aren't a lot of holes. There's nobody who's
appreciably shorter. That's important, because you're not playing
too many different shots into the greens. You still have to have
your thinking cap on when you go out to play any of these holes.''
</P>
<P>
   The great known/unknown is Woods, who is playing a different
game, as evidenced by his victories in the PGA Championship at
Medinah and the $5 million NEC Invitational that ended Sunday in
Akron, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very tough thing,'' said Crenshaw, ``because nobody
plays like him. They're all at the top of their game, but it's very
difficult to find someone who plays a game like Tiger. There's a
lot of interchangeable parts, but there's not a lot of holes in
there.''
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is the course, where the rough will not be US
Open length.
</P>
<P>
   ``The course doesn't favor one team or the other,'' said
Crenshaw. ``There's definitely the flavor of the British Isles. It
reflects something that's beautifully natural. It's not heavily
manicured, so you do feel you're playing against a piece of ground
and piece of art. The great thing is it's a great test for
everybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel every moment we can spend together is golden. That's
why I enjoyed today so much. They were together. I told them before
they left, `I want you to know what the other guy's thinking.'
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't fall out on this golf course and expect to learn it.
On the other side of the column is team, camaraderie, and being
together. They know they're favored, but that doesn't mean a thing
Ryder Cup week.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-99 2156EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
