<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5098 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BBDO-AD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      08-30 1101
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBDO-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BBDO NEW YORK ENTERS CYBERSPACE IN A BIG WAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds., in (at)mosphere, the (at) should be replaced by the symbol) 
(DW) 
 By PATRICIA WINTERS LAURO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BBDO NEW YORK, known for its television commercials for longtime
clients like Pepsi-Cola, Visa and Frito-Lay, is making a big push
into the exploding business of Internet marketing with the opening
of a new agency dedicated to interactive marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Called (at)tmosphere, the new shop is BBDO New York's vision of
a hybrid agency that marries the technical ability of Internet
marketing with traditional advertising techniques. To fulfill that
vision, the firm is bringing in the top BBDO senior creative
director, Mike Campbell, as its managing director. Campbell has
worked on virtually all of BBDO's top accounts, creating memorable
TV spots that have included the comical Donald and Ivana Trump spot
for Pizza Hut and the much-publicized Mario Cuomo-Ann Richards spot
for Doritos.
</P>
<P>
   The new shop opens with capitalized billings of about $25
million from BBDO clients like Visa USA and General Electric and
assignments for Federal Express, Frito-Lay, M&AMP;M/Mars and Pepsi One.
That places (at)tmosphere squarely in the middle of the pack of the
top 100 interactive ad agencies compiled by Advertising Age, the
trade publication. In comparison, the nation's top interactive shop
USWeb/CKS in Santa Clara, Calif., had $125.3 million in revenue
last year, up from $54 million.
</P>
<P>
   BBDO's move may foreshadow a coming consolidation in the
interactive agency world as the Web has evolved from a hip, young
medium into mainstream big business. Last year, $1.03 billion was
spent on Internet advertising, up from $544 million in 1997,
according to Intermedia Advertising Solutions, a unit of the Dutch
conglomerate VNU Marketing Information Services.
</P>
<P>
   BBDO's new agency is late to the field. Many of the big Madison
Avenue agencies have prominent interactive shops, like Ogilvy
Interactive and Grey Interactive. ``They're late to market,'' said
Marissa Gluck, an analyst with Jupiter Communications in New York,
an online research firm ``I think they're going to have a tough
time of it.''
</P>
<P>
   But BBDO said it believed its timing was actually opportune
because the interactive business is now out of its infancy and
ready for the skills of top-notch creatives. BBDO New York is part
of BBDO Worldwide, which is ranked by Advertising Age as the
world's third-largest ad agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen the engineering, the strategic planning and the
placement, but we haven't seen breakthrough ways of interacting
with consumers on the Internet _ no one is doing world-class
creative,'' said Bill Katz, BBDO New York's president and chief
operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Sann, BBDO's co-chief executive and chief creative officer,
said: ``When you talk about building brands, that's not happening
yet on the Internet. No one has cracked that code _ we're still in
the very early stages of development.''
</P>
<P>
   BBDO Interactive, an in-house department that was mainly a media
buying unit. The new agency will be involved in all aspects of
Internet marketing _ from advertising to Web site development to
strategy _ and will operate independently in its own offices apart
from BBDO headquarters. The new agency, which will report to BBDO
New York, will also seek its own new accounts.
</P>
<P>
   BBDO's parent company, Omnicom Group, has also been intricately
involved in the Internet and was one of the early investors in the
fledgling interactive business via its Communicade unit, a
portfolio of investments in interactive, E-commerce, digital design
and technology companies. Omnicom has a stake in several
independent interactive shops, including Organic, Razorfish, Red
Sky and agency.com.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, (at)tmosphere will be headed by a Communicade senior
consultant, Susan Pinkwater, who becomes the new agency's president
and chief executive. Earlier, Ms. Pinkwater worked at agency.com,
and even earlier, ``in another life'' she was a social worker.
</P>
<P>
   In her work for Communicade, Ms. Pinkwater said she was
delighted by the technical abilities of interactive shops, but was
frustrated by the limited understanding of brand strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to create a new kind of agency that addresses branding,
quality of creative and the big picture, and works with ad agencies
instead of against them,'' said Ms. Pinkwater, who added that the
staff of 25 was from both traditional advertising and Internet
shops
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Gluck of Jupiter said advertising agencies had not made
an easy transition to the Internet. BBDO's stellar creative
reputation may have less meaning in the interactive ad world, where
the hottest shops started as fledgling independents that have grown
up with the Internet, she said.
</P>
<P>
   `A lot of the traditional agencies are very stuck in their ways
and not really open to the pace and flexibility that the Internet
requires,'' Ms. Gluck said. ``They haven't shifted their mindset.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Ms. Gluck noted that it might be more economical to start
up a shop and take talent from the field than to buy a shop
outright because the valuations of many interactive shops ``are
astronomical.'' Several shops have gone public and there are rumors
about more initial public offerings ahead, she said.
</P>
<P>
   For Campbell _ who said joining (at)tmosphere felt a little like
``being Joe Kennedy before the Court of St. James's'' _
(at)tmosphere has an edge because as interactive communications
have evolved, they demand classic branding techniques. In their
early experimental stages, interactive ads often had a completely
different image than traditional (i.e. off-line) advertising and
that diffused the message, he said. Interactive advertising _ like
all advertising _ must go back to the core image of the brand, and
that puts a big creative powerhouse like BBDO at an advantage, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tools are different, the medium is different, but what's
the same is how you bring a brand to life in a creative powerful
way with a big idea,'' Campbell said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gluck likened the situation to the 1980s when the big shops
gobbled up specialized medical agencies en masse with the growth of
consumer health care marketing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there will be more consolidation among the larger
agencies _ I think the traditional agencies are playing catch-up,''
Ms. Gluck said.
</P>
<P>
   Katz agreed that consolidation was coming, but said it was
premature to discuss. Still, he said, BBDO New York will succeed in
the business.
</P>
<P>
   ``However it happens, it happens,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
