<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SCHULTZ-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHULTZ TO QUIT OLYMPIC JOB 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dick Schultz will step down as the executive director of the
U.S. Olympic Committee next year as part of an organizational
restructuring.
</P>
<P>
   The USOC's executive committee adopted the preliminary
recommendations of a report by a management consulting firm and a
public-sector task force that will make the USOC operate more like
a private corporation.
</P>
<P>
   One of the main changes is to eliminate the executive director
post and replace it with a president and chief executive officer.
The volunteer president, who is now William Hybl, will become a
more ceremonial chairman.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is exactly what I've pushed for,'' Schultz said. ``It's
being able to do more things that you couldn't do under the current
structure, to be more in control of strategy and direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Schultz said that while it would be tempting to apply for the
new, more powerful job as president and chief executive, he would
not seek the position.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I looked at what was needed, it's a five- to six-year
commitment,'' said Schultz, who became executive director in 1995.
``I was encouraged to do it, but my wife and grandkids would kill
me. I'll be 70 years old next week. We have to get the right person
to make that commitment, a younger person who can look at 5 to 10
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Schultz's contract expires in 2002 but gives him the option to
decide to leave at the end of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   As the USOC has grown in size, so has the need to make it
operate more like a major corporation than a nonprofit
organization. The budget has grown from $13 million for the 1976-80
quadrennium to the current $441 million. Since 1979, the number of
employees has swelled from 40 to 527.
</P>
<P>
   The final report of the proposed restructuring, made by McKinsey
&AMP; Co. and the USOC Public Sector Task Force, is to be presented to
the Olympic committee's board of directors in October and is
expected to be approved in January. Hybl is expected to appoint a
search committee for a president in several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Schultz said he would serve his term through the Summer Olympics
in Sydney, Australia, next year and focus most of his remaining
tenure to USOC fund-raising for Sydney and the 2002 Winter Games in
Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   He said many of his day-to-day responsibilities would be handled
by Scott Blackmun, the USOC's general counsel until the new
president is appointed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to raise $20 million a month for the next 12 months,''
he said. Fund-raising is going well in the aftermath of the Olympic
bribery scandal involving improper gift-giving by former Salt Lake
City Olympic officials, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see the market loosening up, as we go after corporations
that have never done business with the Olympics before,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The effort to reorganize the USOC began about two years ago,
before criticism was leveled at the organization regarding the Salt
Lake City bid. The scandal erupted late last year, and the USOC's
lack of oversight of the Salt Lake Olympic Organizing Committee was
harshly criticized by a commission headed by George Mitchell, the
former U.S. senator from Maine. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
