<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-BERG-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BERG FINALLY AGREES TO KINGS' TERMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By   ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Defenseman Aki Berg said Monday he has decided to
end his year-long salary dispute with the Los Angeles Kings and has
agreed to terms on a one-year contract pending the resolution of
minor details.
</P>
<P>
   There is the possibility Berg, a 22-year-old native of Finland
who was the third player chosen in the 1995 NHL draft, could sign
today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to play in the NHL, everybody knows that,'' Berg said
Monday. ``It's going to be nice to come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Kings general manager Dave Taylor said a contract could be
finalized by today.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're down to talking about bonuses,'' Taylor said. ``I think
both sides would like to get this done.''
</P>
<P>
   An NHL source said Berg acquiesced to the Kings' terms.
</P>
<P>
   Last week _ through an associate of his Ottawa-based agent,
Larry Kelly _ Berg said he was willing to sign a one-year deal
worth $900,000. At the same time, the source said the Kings were
offering a one-year deal worth about $750,000.
</P>
<P>
   The contract Berg appears ready to sign is for a salary much
closer to the one offered by the Kings than to the amount he was
seeking.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings hold all the cards, because if they wished to do so,
terms of the NHL's collective-bargaining agreement give them
complete control of Berg's rights until he is 31. Thus, his option
is to sign with the Kings or play in Europe, as he did last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll sign, and that's it,'' said Berg, who has been in Ottawa
since flying there Saturday from Finland. ``I'll come back and show
the people.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Petri Lehto, a friend of Berg's and an associate of
Kelly's, ``He could be in Europe until he's 31. If that's the
choice, I guess you do what you have to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Berg said he is prepared to put the contentiousness of the past
12 months behind him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I make a deal and I'm part of the team, and of course I've
forgotten what happened last year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Berg has appeared in 164 games in three seasons with the Kings,
scoring two goals and assisting on 21 others. Two other key Kings,
defenseman Mattias Norstrom and right wing Glen Murray, remain
unsigned. Players report for training camp Saturday and step on the
ice for the first time Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Belanger has surgery: Center Eric Belanger, suffering from
Thoracic Outlet Syndrome, a circulatory disorder, underwent surgery
Monday at USC University Hospital to remove a rib and resolve the
problem, which had caused a blood clot in his right arm.
</P>
<P>
   Belanger, 22, is considered one of the Kings' top prospects but
has been plagued by injuries in the past year. He will be sidelined
indefinitely and his status will be reviewed over the next month as
he recuperates from the operation. Taylor said there's a
possibility Belanger could be playing within three months.
</P>
<P>
   Belanger, a fourth-round draft choice in 1996, had 26 points in
33 games last season with Springfield of the American Hockey
League.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-99 2216EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
