<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CLINTONS-CAMPAIGN-ART-775&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST LADY SEEKS BLUE RIBBON FOR CAMPAIGNING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYRACUSE, N.Y. _ Wading into a sea of candied apples, broiled
sausages and fried dough, Hillary Rodham Clinton campaigned elbow
to elbow with President Clinton at the state fair here Monday _ the
first time that this husband has campaigned on behalf of this wife.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons shook hands, hoisted toddlers into the air and
addressed a Democratic luncheon in a day filled with reminders that
a passing of the family torch was at hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, it's pretty nice to go to a lunch like this when you
know you're the only one not running for anything,'' Clinton said
with a sheepish grin after he ambled up to the microphone,
following his wife, at the annual luncheon sponsored by the state
comptroller, H. Carl McCall, the highest-ranking elected Democrat
in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, even with a president in town _ people lined Route 5 for
hours for a glance at the presidential motorcade _ it was Mrs.
Clinton who kept snatching the spotlight. And the state fair, a
sprawling two-week confluence of food, culture and art held every
year in Syracuse, turned out to be particularly friendly territory
for a trip that was as much about the 2000 race for U.S. Senate as
about rest and relaxation for the first family.
</P>
<P>
   John Avery, a retired tool factory executive, pulled Mrs.
Clinton aside to urge her to move to the Finger Lakes area rather
than to Westchester County. A few moments later, outside the
International Horse Show exhibition, Robert Lentz of Warners
greeted the first lady by taking out his wallet and offering her
two $50 bills if she announced to him that she would run for the
Senate, as she seems likely to do.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton demurred, summoning her press secretary, Howard
Wolfson, to politely decline the potentially illegal offer of a
cash donation. ``I think she'd do a lot better for this state than
the other guy,'' said Lentz, referring to Mayor Rudolph Giuliani of
New York City, her presumed opponent, as the Clintons moved into
the crowd. ``And if she doesn't run, I want her to turn it over to
the Clinton defense fund.''
</P>
<P>
   The flurry of events came on the third phase of what is, at
least ostensibly, the Clintons' vacation, complete with their
daughter, Chelsea, and their dog, Buddy. (Chelsea, wearing a pair
of sunglasses, came to the fair; Buddy did not.)
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is counting off the months until the end of his term,
and this was his first vacation in New York since becoming
president. Nonetheless, after spending 10 days in the Hamptons on
Long Island, N.Y., and Martha's Vineyard, Mass., he looked anything
but unhappy at the demands of putting on a shirt and tie and
spending a beautiful if slightly cool late August afternoon shaking
hands under the upstate sun.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's what I've done all my life,'' Clinton told reporters, a
bit wistfully, as he headed back to his motorcade. ``It's how I
think it should be done.''
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton was trying to offer his wife some pointers on how the
game should be played, the first lady seemed the eager student.
Upon arrival in Syracuse, where a crowd of 2,300 was waiting,
according to the Secret Service, Mrs. Clinton kept shaking hands
long after even Clinton had stopped.
</P>
<P>
   Later, at the fair, when the Clintons stopped for iced tea, Mrs.
Clinton again seemed the experienced politician as she politely
turned down an offer of a chicken lunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably not,'' she said, glancing at the photographers who
were circling the table. ``Actually, I'd love to take some with me
because I don't want to eat it in front of 9 million people. I'd
love some.'' The Clintons left with containers of chickens and
apples.
</P>
<P>
   The state fair, which was on the way from the airport to
Skaneateles, provided an ideal foray for anyone looking for fun, a
quick lesson in New York culture or campaigning opportunities. The
fair is one of New York's largest upstate tourist attractions, and
even at midday, it was packed with people.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons did not take in all the attractions at the fair _
they skipped the Freakathon, for example, which from the outside
appeared to be a late-20th-century version of a circus ``freak
show'' _ but they did see an exhibition of American quilts.
</P>
<P>
   People lined up eight deep at some spots just for a chance at a
handshake, an autograph or, in some cases, the political trifecta:
a piece of paper signed by Clinton, Mrs. Clinton and Chelsea.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so excited!'' Richard Ferris of Syracuse exclaimed as he
kissed Mrs. Clinton's right hand. ``This is the most exciting thing
that has ever happened to me.''
</P>
<P>
   As the first lady began to move on, Ferris, a hairstylist,
called out, ``And I want to do her hair!''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Later, as the Clintons moved through the fair _ to the sounds of
``Louie Louie'' and other famous 1960s songs _ they made their way
to the Dairy Building. There, Mrs. Clinton handed out containers of
milk and even indulged in a soft ice cream cone.
</P>
<P>
   At McCall's lunch, Clinton sat with his hands clasped and his
head tilted as he listened to his wife speak.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton discussed funding for education and health care,
the issues that she expects to raise in a campaign against
Giuliani. ``People are asking me what I am learning,'' said Mrs.
Clinton, referring to the so-called listening tour that she has
been conducting in New York for two months. ``I am learning about
the diversity of New York.''
</P>
<P>
   The president, in his remarks, mixed humor and reminiscences of
trips to other state fairs with what has become his standard
refrain these days: the need for the nation to take advantage of
its prosperity to plan for the future.
</P>
<P>
   On the way from the fair to the home of Thomas McDonald, a
supporter who is the Clintons' host this week, they encountered
another cluster of people and stopped again to shake more hands.
Clinton, in an aside to reporters, brushed off the suggestion that
he needed to teach Mrs. Clinton anything about campaigning. ``I
think she's doing pretty well without any help from me,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
