<SLUG> BC-COULTER-COULTER </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Coulter's Cancer Drug Is Delayed by FDA
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By Tom Abate &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Shares in Coulter Pharmaceutical Inc. plunged 32 percent yesterday
after the company disclosed that the Food and Drug Administration
wants it to revise its application to sell a cancer drug called
Bexxar.
</P>
<P>
   The South San Francisco biotech company said the FDA wanted it
to reformat parts of its massive application and reanalyze some of
the data it has already submitted.
</P>
<P>
   Coulter spokeswoman Sylvia Wheeler estimated it would take six
to eight weeks to resubmit the application and emphasized that the
FDA has not asked for any new studies, which would take much longer
to satisfy. The company did not release the FDA letter.
</P>
<P>
   The news sent Coulter stock plunging $10.94 to close at $23.50
yesterday on a volume of 6.3 million shares, nearly 20 times the
company's daily average over the past three months.
</P>
<P>
   Bexxar is intended to treat non-Hodgkin's lymphoma, a cancer of
the blood and lymph tissues that affects 300,000 Americans. Bexxar
consists of a monoclonal antibody attached to a radioactive
isotope. The antibody is designed to find the cancer cell, while
the radioactive payload is supposed to kill the cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Jim McCamant of the Medical Technology Stock Letter in Berkeley
that a delay in winning FDA approval for Bexxar _ if the setback
proves to be just that _ would diminish Coulter's lead over Idec
Pharmaceuticals Corp.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego's Idec is testing a drug called Zevalin that would be
very similar to Bexxar, joining a radioactive particle to an
antibody. Idec is still about a year away from asking the FDA for
permission to sell Zevalin.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA action took analysts by surprise. Only last week,
Coulter Chief Executive Officer Michael Bigham said in a magazine
interview that his company had provided the FDA all the information
it needed when Coulter submitted its application to sell Bexxar on
June 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``They lost some credibility,'' said Curtis Hogue, an analyst at
Volpe Brown Whelan &AMP; Co., who has a ``neutral'' rating on Coulter
shares.
</P>
<P>
   Pending FDA approval, Coulter plans to market Bexxar in
conjunction with SmithKline Beecham Plc., which is based in the
United Kingdom. Shares in SmithKline dropped fell $1.63 to close at
$64.31.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
