<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG-DISTANCE RATE WAR HEATS UP AFTER AT&AMP;T CUTS
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T has introduced lower long-distance rates, reluctantly
joining a price war with large and small phone carriers that has
brought bargains for consumers but threatens to add to already
intense pressure on profits.
</P>
<P>
   The new plan, which has a $5.95 monthly fee, offers calls at 7
cents a minute any time. That represents a 30 percent cut in the
per-minute rate from AT&AMP;T's previous main offering, 10 cents a
minute with a $4.95 monthly fee. Customers must request the new
plan, otherwise they will remain with their older, more expensive
ones. Shares of AT&AMP;T declined $1.50 a share, or 3 percent, to $46,
on the news.
</P>
<P>
   HOME SALES REMAINED BRISK IN JULY
</P>
<P>
   The number of new single-family homes sold in July reached a
seasonally adjusted annual rate of 980,000, the Commerce Department
said. Although that was up only slightly from June, it was the
highest sales pace since the record high of 985,000 in November
1998.
</P>
<P>
   CIGARETTE PRICES UP 18 CENTS A PACK
</P>
<P>
   The country's leading cigarette manufacturers raised wholesale
prices 18 cents a pack over the weekend, anticipating a tax
increase and more expenses from a settlement with the states over
health care costs.
</P>
<P>
   DOW FALLS ON CONCERN ABOUT RATES
</P>
<P>
   Stock prices fell for the third consecutive session, pulled down
by worries that in early October the Federal Reserve may increase
short-term interest rates for a third time this year. The Dow Jones
industrial average dropped 176.04 points, or 1.6 percent, to
10,914.13. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 stock index fell 24.25 points,
or 1.8 percent, to 1,324.02. The technology-heavy NASDAQ composite
shed 46.21 points, or 1.7 percent, to 2,712.69.
</P>
<P>
   Bond yields rose sharply, reflecting investors' fears that the
Federal Reserve would increase short-term rates again because of
continuing evidence that the economy is strong. The yield on the
30-year Treasury bond rose to 6.05 percent, from 5.97 percent on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   OFFICE DEPOT TO MISS ESTIMATES
</P>
<P>
   Office Depot, the office-supply superstore chain, said that it
would miss earnings estimates for the rest of the year because of
lower-than-expected sales and tighter profit margins. The company
also said it would take third-quarter charges and buy back $500
million of its stock.
</P>
<P>
   SEC SEES DEAL WITH BIG BOARD
</P>
<P>
   Securities and Exchange Commission officials expect to work out
an agreement with the New York Stock Exchange on the thorniest
issue involved in its going public _ what happens to the exchange's
self-policing unit, which would face the possibility of
investigating and disciplining its own shareholders. Arthur Levitt,
the SEC chairman, has warned that approval for the exchange to
convert to public ownership would be contingent on ``investors'
interests taking precedence over all others.''
</P>
<P>
   SHARES OF REPUBLIC SERVICES PLUNGE
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Republic Services, the waste collection company, fell
$5.375, or 32.6 percent, to $11.125, after the company said that
1999 earnings would fall below analysts' estimates. Republic cited
a lag in integrating assets bought from Waste Management.
</P>
<P>
   A NEW SHOP FOR INTERNET MARKETING
</P>
<P>
   BBDO New York, known for its television commercials for longtime
clients like Pepsi-Cola, Frito-Lay and Visa, is making a big push
into Internet marketing with the opening of a new agency dedicated
to interactive marketing. The new shop is BBDO New York's vision of
a hybrid agency that marries the technical ability of Internet
marketing with traditional advertising techniques.
</P>
<P>
   PRADA TO BUY JIL SANDER'S SHARES
</P>
<P>
   The Italian fashion house Prada said that it planned to buy 75
percent of the common shares of Jil Sander AG of Germany and 15
percent of its publicly traded preferred stock, adding to its
designer-clothing brands.
</P>
</TEXT>
