<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLUBS-CLUBS </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Investment Clubbing on the Net  
 By Arthur M. Louis 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Investment clubs date back to before that rusted-out Hudson in
grandpa's barn, but they are beginning to take on a slick, modern
look thanks to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 100 investment clubs now operate exclusively online,
experts estimate. Their members, scattered throughout the country,
may never meet face-to-face.
</P>
<P>
   They don't hold their monthly strategy meetings in somebody's
living room over coffee and finger food, as the nation's 50,000
conventional investment clubs do. Instead, they share their ideas
and make their buy-and-sell decisions via chat rooms, bulletin
boards and e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the more popular financial Web sites, such as Motley
Fool and Yahoo, are catering to this new trend, offering the clubs
private Web pages, bulletin boards and portfolio tracking.
</P>
<P>
   They do this free of charge, though the club members who use the
sites must endure an endless stream of advertisements for brokerage
houses and other financial service providers.
</P>
<P>
   Communicating online lets the club members break out of the
conventional, rigid investment-club structure and carry on a
perpetual dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will set up a message board for any club,'' says Selena
Maranjian, a senior writer with Motley Fool. ``You not only can
post messages, but if you notice an article you want other members
to share, you can post a link.''
</P>
<P>
   In one recent bulletin board posting on Motley Fool, a club
member plaintively inquired: ``When is our next meeting? I noticed
ORCL (Oracle Corp.) is stuck around $37 lately. Do we want to take
any action (like selling it to gain some profit????).''
</P>
<P>
   Not only does the Internet let clubs with geographically
dispersed members operate more efficiently, but it also makes it
more practical to recruit large numbers of members and amass large
amounts of capital. That gives the funds more flexibility in their
investments.
</P>
<P>
   John Conley, a paralegal based in Nicasio in Marin County, is
organizing an online club that will invest in stocks, mortgages and
deeds of trust. He says he can think of a dozen friends and
relatives who might sign up, but like Blanche DuBois, he will
depend heavily on the kindness of strangers.
</P>
<P>
   He plans to set up a Web page to attract members. He hopes to
corral as many as 75 and to build an initial investment pool of
$200,000 so that the club can diversify its investments adequately.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the average investment club has fewer than 20
members.
</P>
<P>
   While the number of strictly online clubs is still small, a
substantial minority of traditional clubs can be classed as
semionline. They use the Internet to enhance communications among
their members _ mainly with e-mail and to do investment research.
</P>
<P>
   ``More and more investment clubs are doing business online,''
says Kenneth Janke, president of the National Association of
Investors Corp. ``It is more convenient, especially if people are
vacationing out of town and can't attend a meeting.''
</P>
<P>
   NAIC, whose members include about three-fourths of all U.S.
investment clubs, was founded in 1951, a few years after investment
clubs began to proliferate.
</P>
<P>
   Devin Holmes, a network administrator with the state Department
of Corrections in Sacramento, is president of a conventional,
3-year-old investment club with 12 members and $23,000 in assets,
as well as a 1-year-old, $2,300, semionline club limited to a
half-dozen members of his family, including one in Utah.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone in the family club has a computer,'' he says. ``We
have a Web site that is updated every month. We discuss possible
investments and vote on them.''
</P>
<P>
   Holmes sends each member a list of stocks the club might want to
buy or sell, and the members respond by e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Once Holmes receives a majority vote for or against a stock, the
order is placed by his mother, the club treasurer, with Waterhouse
Securities, where the club has its brokerage account.
</P>
<P>
   Holmes says he will follow the standard procedure recommended by
NAIC if any members want to quit and withdraw their share of the
club assets. The member must give 60 days' notice so that the club
has plenty of time to liquidate securities with minimal harm to the
portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   As convenient and efficient as they may be, online clubs have
potentially bothersome drawbacks, some experts say.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Robertson, senior contributing editor of NAIC publications,
contends that face-to-face discussions help investment clubs
perform better _ that crucial nuances get lost when club members
only interact electronically.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no substitute for the one-room schoolhouse atmosphere
of the conventional face-to-face club,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Terrance Odean, a professor of finance at the University of
California at Davis, worries that online investment clubs will
trade too actively _ ``because the online environment encourages
more active trading.''
</P>
<P>
   Odean co-authored a recent study of investment clubs, which
indicated that the clubs that trade most actively perform
relatively poorly, while those that hold stocks for the long term
do best.
</P>
<P>
   Another potential drawback is fraud _ a real possibility when
the club members are far-flung strangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The notion of opening a joint brokerage account with a bunch
of strangers and hoping for the best seems frivolous to me,''
remarks Elizabeth Rowe, a senior consultant with Find/SVP Emerging
Technologies Research Group in New York.
</P>
<P>
   NAIC's Janke acknowledges that ``any time you are dealing with
money, there is a potential that someone will try and con you.''
But he insists that fraud has been extremely rare among the clubs
that belong to his organization.
</P>
<P>
   He points out that the opportunities for rank-and-file members
to defraud an investment club are limited. A crooked officer, on
the other hand _ particularly a crooked treasurer, who handles the
flow of money in and out of investments _ can inflict serious
financial damage.
</P>
<P>
   Janke cites the case of a woman who gave club members copies of
authentic-looking but phony brokerage statements that indicated she
was buying and selling exactly the securities on which the members
had voted. In fact, she was keeping the club's money for herself.
</P>
<P>
   The scam didn't get detected until after the woman died.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone in the club went to the broker to say they needed to
change the administration of the account to someone else,'' Janke
says. ``The broker didn't know what they were talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   The fraud might have been avoided if the club had taken the
precaution of assigning more than one person to monitor the
brokerage account. The members were too naive and too trustful.
</P>
<P>
   But not entirely trustful. Fortunately, they got back all their
money because they did have the foresight to get the treasurer
bonded by an insurance company. If the loss hadn't been insured,
they might have had to hire a lawyer to sue the treasurer's estate.
</P>
<P>
   Or they might have gotten relief through the regulators that
oversee investment clubs _ the Securities and Exchange Commission
and the state agency that administers securities laws. (In
California, that would be the Department of Corporations.)
</P>
<P>
   Janke emphasizes that this particular fraud was perpetrated
entirely offline. He concludes: ``If someone wants to cheat you,
they can find a way, and it doesn't necessarily have to be
online.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
