<SLUG> BC-DETROIT-TEACHERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DETROIT TEACHERS CALL A STRIKE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., Ill., Ohio, N.J.)   (jw) 
 By ROBYN MEREDITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Against the recommendation of their union leaders,
teachers here voted Monday to strike, just one day before Detroit's
172,000 public school students were due to return to school.
</P>
<P>
   The strike will test not only a new school board appointed this
year by Mayor Dennis Archer and Gov. John Engler but also a 1994
state law that makes the strike illegal and punishes teachers with
fines of a day's pay for every day on strike. The last teachers
strike in Detroit was in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The union, the Detroit Federation of Teachers, has been in
negotiations since February over terms of a contract to replace the
one that expired Monday. The union's leadership recommended that
teachers accept a 10-day extension of the talks with the Detroit
public schools, but teachers rebelled, voting to strike by an 80
percent majority.
</P>
<P>
   ``They voted not to return without a contract,'' said Janna K.
Garrison, executive vice president of the Detroit Federation of
Teachers.
</P>
<P>
   The union leadership had recommended the extension, Ms. Garrison
said, because ``we were at the table and we were getting pretty
close.''
</P>
<P>
   Teachers apparently felt that returning to the classrooms and
extending the talks would cost them leverage at the negotiating
table.
</P>
<P>
   Archer urged the union and the school board to continue
negotiations until they reach a deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remain optimistic and encourage the negotiators to return to
the table forthwith,'' Archer said.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's office is also hoping for a quick end to the
strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reform must move forward, and a key to that is having teachers
in the classrooms,'' said John Truscott, a spokesman for Engler.
``We're just hoping for a speedy resolution.''
</P>
<P>
   Half the students in Detroit's public schools do not graduate
from high school, and half of those who do graduate struggle to
meet state standards. Fourth-graders approach state averages on
standardized tests, but by the seventh grade just a third can read
or do math at their grade level.
</P>
<P>
   The state Legislature, which is controlled by Republicans, voted
in March to transfer control of Detroit's schools from an elected
school board to the mayor and the governor, who appointed a new
school board. The Detroit Federation of Teachers supported that
reform effort. State legislatures have similarly restructured
school boards in Chicago and Cleveland and in five school districts
in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   All summer, the Detroit school board has been racing to complete
school repairs before students return, hiring scores of contractors
to refinish floors, refurbish dilapidated restrooms and repair
broken windows. The board also recruited local businesses to
monitor the progress, and many have donated school supplies and
expertise to their adopted schools.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's developments are likely to leave parents confused.
David Adamany, the chief executive of the Detroit public schools,
said that schools were open and that teachers were expected to
report to their posts. But Adamany also said parents should not
take their children to school until the board could ensure that
there were enough teachers.
</P>
<P>
   The union has called for teachers to head for the picket lines
instead of their classrooms on Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``No teacher ever wants to go on strike,'' said John Elliott,
the union president. ``But when the school system tries to
undermine the teachers, it winds up hurting students.''
</P>
<P>
   Teacher strikes are rare in large cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been little strikes, but it has been a long time
since we had a really big strike,'' said Janet Bass, a spokeswoman
for the American Federation of Teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Others concurred. ``They have been very few and far between in
recent years,'' said John Butler, a spokesman for the National
School Boards Association, based in Alexandria, Va.
</P>
<P>
   In Detroit, the 11,500-member teachers union was seeking a
raise, a reduction in class sizes and the elimination of certain
policies, including what teachers called too-rigid attendance
requirements. The union had asked that wages for Detroit's teachers
be brought up to the median of those in the three-county
metropolitan area, which would have meant raises of 2 percent to 10
percent, depending on seniority.
</P>
<P>
   The board had proposed giving the teachers 95 percent of the
raises they had asked for, said Ms. Garrison, the union's executive
vice president. And it had agreed to study whether to reduce class
sizes, which reached 41 students in one first-grade class last
year, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Mario Morrow, a political consultant in Detroit who is also an
assistant principal in the school system, said teachers felt that
although they were on the front lines of improving the city's
schools, the board was asking a lot without giving enough in
return.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers say that ``even though the strike is illegal, at some
point in time, you've got to stand up for what you believe in,''
Morrow said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
