<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 22:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5120 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-MARCH-ART-600&AMP;ADD-     08-30 0995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MARCH-ART-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK CITY CLAIMS THAT HATE SPEECH JUSTIFIES DENYING RALLY
PERMIT
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By DAVID BARSTOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The city's lawyer argued in court Monday that the
incendiary words of Khallid Abdul Muhammad are so filled with
hatred toward Jews and whites _ and are so likely to incite
violence against the police _ that he and his compatriots should be
prevented from staging a youth rally in Harlem on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The argument was not received warmly by U.S. District Judge
Denny Chin.
</P>
<P>
   In sharp, persistent questioning of Michael Hess, the city's
corporation counsel, Chin wondered whether Mayor Rudolph Giuliani
arbitrarily denied a permit for the rally simply because he
detested Muhammad's political views. He called the city's response
to Muhammad's permit request ``problematic.''
</P>
<P>
   Chin criticized the city's procedures for reviewing parade
permits, saying, ``There still do not appear to be any standards.''
And he observed that the city's abrupt decision last week to deny a
permit ``would seem to contradict'' efforts by city lawyers to
negotiate with organizers of the rally, called the Million Youth
March.
</P>
<P>
   Only last week, Giuliani said the permit was denied because a
proper application was not made in time _ the same sort of narrow
legal grounds his lawyers employed unsuccessfully to try to block
last year's rally. Such technical reasons were largely abandoned
Monday, as Hess instead framed the city's denial as a lawful
restraint on demagogic, hate-filled speech.
</P>
<P>
   In an emotional defense of the city's position, Hess urged the
judge to consider ``the reality'' of last year's Million Youth
March, in which hundreds of participants clashed with police
officers after Muhammad urged them to ``beat the hell'' out of the
advancing line of officers in riot gear if they were attacked by
the police.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no joke,'' Hess said. ``Twenty cops were hurt.'' One
officer, he said, had been out of work for a year because of a neck
injury. Others, he said, were knocked unconscious by chairs and
other objects hurled at them by rally participants.
</P>
<P>
   With one rally organizer talking of inviting armed gang members
to this year's rally, Hess argued, and with Muhammad vowing to
march with or without a permit, the city is justified in denying a
permit because of the content of Muhammad's words.
</P>
<P>
   The usual test for upholding restrictions on demonstrations is
whether they are neutral, and are imposed for valid logistical
reasons, rather than because of the speech's content.
</P>
<P>
   At times Chin appeared impatient with Hess' arguments. At one
point he rubbed his head in frustration, and at another he cut Hess
short with ``You didn't answer my question.'' When Hess said the
heavy police presence at last year's rally was ``relatively
normal,'' Chin again interrupted. ``Cattle chutes are relatively
normal?'' he asked acidly, referring to the hundreds of steel
barricades that the rally organizers likened to cattle pens.
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad did not attend Monday's hearing, but his lawyers were
clearly encouraged by Chin's questions and comments. ``His
questions seemed to indicate he was in favor of our position,''
said Roger Wareham, a lawyer for the rally organizers.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Chin also expressed reservations about allowing Muhammad to
stage a rally on Malcolm X Boulevard in Harlem. Taking note of
several prominent politicians in Harlem who have called on
residents to boycott the rally, Chin asked, ``Do the residents of
Harlem really want this rally?''
</P>
<P>
   Chin said he expected to give a decision Tuesday. His ruling is
likely to be appealed, lawyers in the case said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Giuliani clearly anticipated an unfavorable ruling. In response
to a reporter's question Monday evening, he said he feared that
Chin had failed to appreciate the difference between what the mayor
called the ``Million Teen Hate March'' and traditional events like
the St. Patrick's Day Parade.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can't figure out that difference there is nothing in
the world that I can do to educate the judge as to the difference
between those two things,'' he said, his expression one of
incredulity.
</P>
<P>
   The limits of the First Amendment _ and specifically whether it
protects Muhammad's most inflammatory statements _ were at the
heart of Monday's hearing. On the one hand, as Chin noted, the U.S.
Supreme Court has ruled that the Constitution protects the speech
of those who advocate the violent overthrow of the government. Yet
in an important 1969 case, Brandenburg vs. Ohio, the court also
held that the First Amendment does not protect speech aimed at
``inciting or producing imminent lawless action.''
</P>
<P>
   Hess argued that Muhammad and other rally organizers did just
that last year, and plan to do the same this year. He submitted
videotapes of last year's rally, and transcripts of speeches by
Muhammad and other rally participants.
</P>
<P>
   But Wareham said that Muhammad only called for violence as a
means of self-defense. During his brief remarks, Muhammad spoke of
self-defense or ``the right to defend ourselves'' nine times. In
Muhammad's final instructions to the crowd, he urged them to leave
in ``peace,'' and to ``go home to your families, brothers and
sisters.''
</P>
<P>
   Wareham argued that it was the Police Department that caused the
violence with a series of provocative tactics, such as flying
helicopters low over the crowd. He noted that there were no arrests
or reported incidents of violence until the police moved in to
clear the area minutes after the rally was scheduled to end. What's
more, he asked, if Muhammad's words sparked the violence, then why
was he not indicted by a grand jury that spent months investigating
the melee?
</P>
<P>
   Chin appeared troubled by aspects of the Police Department's
conduct last year. ``Certainly some of it appears excessive _
helicopters swooping in at 4 o'clock,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
