<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 22:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5121 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-EXP-HURRICANE-DENNIS-     08-30 0363
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXP-HURRICANE-DENNIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HURRICANE GIVES PECK TO THE CAROLINA COAST BEFORE DRIFTING OUT TO
SEA
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By EMILY YELLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, N.C. _ Hurricane Dennis began peeling away from the
coast of North Carolina on Monday afternoon, apparently sparing the
state the kind of damage it had suffered in three other hurricanes
since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Officials here along the state's southern coast began reopening
barrier islands that were evacuated on Sunday night. And although
northern coastal communities remained hunkered down Monday evening
against heavy rain, sustained winds of nearly 90 mph and gusts of
up to 112 mph, they also seemed to have avoided a direct hit.
</P>
<P>
   But even as the eye of the storm continued moving away from the
coast, officials cautioned that the hurricane remained a threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``These things are so unpredictable,'' said Bill Furney of the
North Carolina Division of Emergency Management. ``It could stay
off the coast for a day or two and gather strength and come back
in. We hope that doesn't happen. What we need is a good front to
come in from the coast and push Dennis back out to sea.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Jarrell, director of the National Hurricane Center in
Miami, predicted that the storm would ``come to a screeching halt
out there'' in the Atlantic by early Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, heaven only knows what it's going to do,'' Jarrell said.
``But we think it'll probably sit there for one, two or three days,
and then almost anything is possible after that.''
</P>
<P>
   No deaths were attributed to the storm directly, although a
head-on collision that killed two people Monday morning north of
Wilmington was laid to 60 mph winds and heavy rain associated with
it.
</P>
<P>
   The storm did not appear to have caused any major structural
damage in southern North Carolina. To the north, it appeared that
Dennis had not brought the destruction inflicted by three other
hurricanes in the last three years: Bertha, Bonnie and Fran.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like Dennis said, `How close can I get to land and not
cause any damage?''' said Bill Clontz of the New Hanover County
Emergency Management Agency, here in Wilmington.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-99 2229EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990830.0461 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 22:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5122 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-HURRICANE-DENNIS-1STL     08-30 1262
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-DENNIS-1STLD-WRITETHRU(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HURRICANE GIVES PECK TO THE CAROLINA COAST BEFORE DRIFTING OUT TO
SEA
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Updates throughout, ADDS quotes from residents, that VP Gore
cut short family vacation; adds optional trims.) 
 (nk) 
 By EMILY YELLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, N.C. _ Hurricane Dennis began peeling away from the
coast of North Carolina on Monday afternoon, apparently sparing the
state the kind of damage it had suffered in three other hurricanes
since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Officials here along the state's southern coast began reopening
barrier islands that were evacuated on Sunday night. And although
northern coastal communities remained hunkered down Monday evening
against heavy rain, sustained winds of nearly 90 mph and gusts of
up to 112 mph, they also seemed to have avoided a direct hit.
</P>
<P>
   But even as the eye of the storm continued moving
east-northeast, away from the coast, officials cautioned that the
hurricane remained a threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``These things are so unpredictable,'' said Bill Furney of the
North Carolina Division of Emergency Management. ``It could stay
off the coast for a day or two and gather strength and come back
in. We hope that doesn't happen. What we need is a good front to
come in from the coast and push Dennis back out to sea.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Jarrell, director of the National Hurricane Center in
Miami, predicted that the storm would ``come to a screeching halt
out there'' in the Atlantic by early Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, heaven only knows what it's going to do,'' Jarrell said.
``But we think it'll probably sit there for one, two or three days,
and then almost anything is possible after that.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Todd Miner, a meteorologist at Pennsylvania State University,
explained that the hurricane was being pushed away from the coast
by the same southward dip of jet-stream winds that brought cool
weather to the Northeast on Monday. The jet stream is now expected
to move back to the north, Miner said, a shift that, in the absence
of any other strong weather pattern, will most likely leave the
storm to stall at sea.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   At 8 o'clock Monday night, the eye of the hurricane was about
120 miles east of Cape Hatteras, and was continuing on a path that
had brought it close to the coast, but without making landfall, all
along the Southeastern seaboard. A hurricane warning remained in
effect for most of the North Carolina coast to the Virginia state
line.
</P>
<P>
   No deaths were attributed to the storm directly, although a
head-on collision that killed two people Monday morning in Onslow
County, north of Wilmington, was laid to 60 mph winds and heavy
rain associated with it. The storm did not appear to have caused
any major structural damage in southern North Carolina. To the
north, it was still too early Monday evening for much of a damage
assessment, although there, too, it appeared that Dennis had not
brought the destruction inflicted by three other hurricanes in the
last three years: Bertha, Bonnie and Fran.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clontz of the New Hanover County Emergency Management
Agency, here in Wilmington, said: ``We're thinking we're very lucky
we only got a glancing blow, compared to the three storms we've had
in the past few years. The rest of the state seems to be faring
very well just like we are.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems the whole country made out. It's like Dennis said,
`How close can I get to land and not cause any damage?'''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The storm did cut electrical power to 60,000 people, the North
Carolina Division of Emergency Management reported, and those
disruptions stretched as far inland as 140 miles, all the way to
the Raleigh area, where at one point about 10,000 customers were
without power.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, ``as far as damage in the state,'' ``we have a few
roads out, and bridges closed,'' said Furney, of the state's
emergency management division.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Although the punishment to the state as a whole appeared light,
there were pockets of almost puzzling damage. On Hatteras Island,
two gasoline pumps embedded in concrete were blown over at the
service station owned by Danny Couch, who sat out the storm on the
island. (Although the island was under an evacuation order,
residents were allowed to stay if they remained on their own
property.)
</P>
<P>
   Valerie Tucker, 39, from Michigan, also stayed on the island,
with 24 of her relatives, who were making their annual visit to the
Outer Banks Motel on the beachfront. The motel owner let the
gathered clan stay at her house, farther from the beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were here for Hurricane Emily in 1993,'' Ms. Tucker said,
``but we evacuated for that. This one didn't seem like it would be
as bad. We haven't been out yet, but I don't think there will be
too much damage. We're still hoping to get a good week out of our
vacation.''
</P>
<P>
   At a mooring on the Cape Fear River in downtown Wilmington on
Monday morning, Mike Brit, 55, cleared some leaves off his 55-foot
charter boat, which he moved there from Carolina Beach, a barrier
island south of the city, after that island was evacuated on
Sunday. Brit spent the night with his wife in a nearby hotel with a
view of the river, and his assistant, Dean Holt, stayed on board
the boat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't sleep much,'' Brit said. ``Dean had a phone, I had a
phone, so we kept in touch through the storm. I came down here
about 4:30 in the morning to check on the boat.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, neither the boat nor Holt suffered any damage, and
when the first sunlight of the morning appeared, and Brit decided
that the worst was over, he declared the hurricane not so bad as
those he had weathered in the past.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Already, hopes for a big Labor Day weekend were spreading among
many whose work is dependent on the busy tourist industry all along
the Southeastern coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call Labor Day weekend the last big hurrah of the season,''
said Shayna Anderson, a front-desk manager at the Blockade Runner
Beach Resort on Wrightsville Beach, a barrier island near
Wilmington that was evacuated on Sunday night but reopened Monday.
Ms. Anderson said the hotel was just about fully booked for the
Labor Day weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we came in this morning,'' she said, ``the phone was
ringing off the wall with booked guests for this weekend checking
to see if we were still here. I spent much of the morning assuring
them that we were, in fact, still standing, had had minimal damage
and that everything would be fine for this weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   But one family that evacuated the area on Sunday apparently has
no plans to return this season. Vice President Al Gore cut short
his family beach vacation on Figure Eight Island near Wilmington on
Sunday afternoon, after state officials issued evacuation orders
for that and other islands.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore family was nearing the end of a 12-day vacation at a
private home on the four-mile-long resort island just north of
Wrightsville Beach, said Thomas F. Taft, a family friend from
Greenville, N.C., who planned the trip. The private home, where the
Gores also stayed for two weeks in 1997, is owned by V. Parker
Overton, founder of a large water sports equipment retailer.
</P>
<P>
   Gore had intended to stay until Tuesday, but after monitoring
the hurricane's progress on television and through military
channels, decided to leave early, Taft said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once they started having evacuations,'' Taft said, ``he felt
it best to take normal precautions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
