<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR TUESDAY, AUGUST 31
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Tuesday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-MADAMOISELLE-EDITOR-NYT (moved on Thursday, Aug. 26)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Thursday, Aug. 26,
about the resignation of Elizabeth Crow, editor in chief of
Mademoiselle, misstated a comparison in the magazine's advertising
pages. According to estimates by the Publishers Information Bureau,
advertising pages rose to 582 for the first six months of this
year, compared with 438 in that period in 1994. They did not
decline; 960 was the figure for all of 1994.
</P>
<P>
   BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS (moved on Saturday, Aug. 28)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Saturday, Aug. 28,
about the coming special election in the 42d Congressional District
of California misstated the reason that one candidate, Marta Macias
Brown, was endorsed by Emily's List, a national organization that
supports Democratic women who favor abortion rights. It was because
of Mrs. Brown's stand on abortion, not her support of stricter
controls on guns. Emily's List takes no position on any issue
except abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-NYT (moved on Wednesday, Aug. 25)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, Aug.
25, about the Startac Clip-On Organizer, describing the dexterity
needed to enter information into it, misstated the name of the
Dickens character who knitted as the guillotine blade fell on
victims of the French Revolution. She was Madame Defarge, not
LaFarge.
</P>
</TEXT>
