</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PANAMA-IMMIG-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-OFFICIAL ACCUSES PANAMA'S LEADER IN VISA-SELLING SCHEME
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By DAVID GONZALEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PANAMA _ Panama dismissed its intelligence chief in June after
the United States made allegations that she was selling visas to
Chinese seeking a back-door entrance to the United States. Now she
is charging that Panama's president insisted that she authorize
visas that he was selling.
</P>
<P>
   The official, Samantha Smith, said in an interview that she
approved visas specifically requested by President Ernesto Perez
Balladares. She said she had warned the president on several
occasions that she had serious doubts about the visas. She said
that they clearly were being used by poor rural Chinese to get to
Panama en route to the United States, and said that the Chinese had
no intention of returning to their homeland.
</P>
<P>
   As head of intelligence from September 1998 to June of this
year, Ms. Smith was in charge of approving visas from countries
like Cuba and China. She said that the president's personal
secretary delivered to her office some 140 visas for her approval
during her nine months in office. She said she confronted the
president in early May to voice her objections to authorizing the
latest batch of 32 suspect visas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president said that I had to give the visas because they
were already committed to giving them, because he had obligations,
because people were after him and he had things to pay, expenses to
cover,'' she said. ``He put it this way, `These visas have been
promised. They have to be issued.'''
</P>
<P>
   The president, whose five-year term in office ends Wednesday,
said through a spokeswoman that he ``categorically denies''
benefiting from any visa scheme. Previously, he said he had asked
Ms. Smith to approve certain visas for Chinese merchants and their
relatives who worked in the nation's free-trade zone. His office
provided no further comment, but a statement issued late Monday by
the Ministry of Government and Justice insisted that the president
had ``never promoted, nor allowed illegal immigration to any
country.''
</P>
<P>
   It also accused Ms. Smith of making politically motivated
accusations that could be seized upon by American critics of the
hand over of the Panama Canal, set for Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview on Sunday, Ms. Smith portrayed herself as a
skeptical official who reluctantly obeyed her president. Ms. Smith,
a lawyer who started with the intelligence service as an analyst,
said she still did not know the full extent of whatever scheme
there was to sell visas.
</P>
<P>
   She said she was disclosing her conversation with the president
to ensure her safety and because she feared that the scheme might
go uninvestigated by Panamanian authorities.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. official said: ``A whole lot of senior Panamanian
officials appear to be guilty, complicit in the scheme or
participants in it. It's a mess.''
</P>
<P>
   Illegal traffic in visas is not new to Panama, dating back at
least to the rule of Gen. Manuel Noriega, who in the 1980s was
accused of selling visas to Cubans.
</P>
<P>
   The latest scandal erupted when Ms. Smith discovered that she
had visa problems of her own in June after State Department
officials revoked her visa to travel to the United States. She said
American Embassy officials in Panama told her that they suspected
her involvement in an immigrant smuggling ring that used Panama as
an entry point for Chinese aliens headed clandestinely by land to
the United States. The fallout from that decision cost her her job,
as well as those of several other mid-level officials.
</P>
<P>
   But the State Department's revocation of her visa has also drawn
the ire of officials at the Justice Department, who said the move
damaged an investigation that could have resulted in charges
against more senior Panamanian officials.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the U.S. Embassy said there would be no comment
on the revocation of Ms. Smith's visa or any of her allegations.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ms. Smith said she had had doubts about the visa requests from
the beginning of her tenure. She said the requests arrived at her
office after bypassing regular immigration channels and appeared to
be for people who clearly had no intention of returning to their
homeland.
</P>
<P>
   American officials have said that smugglers later took the
Chinese immigrants through Costa Rica and into Mexico, where they
illegally entered the United States. It has been estimated that the
visas were sold for $15,000 apiece.
</P>
<P>
   ``When these packets arrived for visas for people from
Guangdong, I immediately thought something was wrong,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, she said, she wrote a letter to the president
outlining her objections. She said he returned the letter with a
notation to not issue the visas. Soon afterward, she said, Romulo
Abad, the president's personal secretary, came to her office
seeking that month's package of approved visas. When she showed him
the president's reply to her letter, she said he took his cellular
phone, called up the president and passed the phone to her.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president told me to give the visas to Romulo Abad,'' she
said. ``Romulo Abad then told me, `You know the president cannot
leave anything in writing.'''
</P>
<P>
   Her doubts grew as the visa requests continued, she said,
especially when several presidential aides told her she needed to
approve some visas quickly because ``the budget is short.''
</P>
<P>
   In the interview, Ms. Smith said: ``I want to restore my
reputation. I did nothing wrong. Why should I have to pay for
someone else?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
