<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 23:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5216 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-AMERICAS-RETAIL-NYT &LR;      08-30 0645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICAS-RETAIL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A STRONG LATIN RETAIL PRESENCE IS ABOUT TO GET STRONGER
</HEADLINE>
   (See also CARREFOUR-PROMODES) 
(jw) 
 By SIMON ROMERO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAO PAULO, Brazil _ Geraldo Ferregetti was overjoyed when his
company, a prominent fruit producer, signed a contract last week to
supply 100 tons of papayas each month to Carrefour S.A., Brazil's
largest retailer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Selling to Carrefour is like securing our future,''
Ferregetti, the produce director at Caliman Agricola, said in a
telephone interview from the company's headquarters in the
southeastern state of Espirito Santo. Ferregetti said the next step
was to use Carrefour's global reach to sell papayas in Europe, Asia
and Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   At least in the Spanish- and Portuguese-speaking countries of
Latin America, Ferregetti's goal is likely to get a boost after
Carrefour's agreement Monday to buy its rival, Promodes S.A.
</P>
<P>
   Just as U.S. companies like McDonald's Corp. have carved out a
leading presence in Latin America's fast-food business, French
retailers have emerged as some of the region's largest supermarket
operators. So it is small wonder that the combined operations of
Carrefour and Promodes provide a Latin giant with the power to
compete in markets where they are not already leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``The global consolidation of the retail industry arrived late
in Latin America, but it's here to stay,'' said Percio de Souza, a
managing director at Banco BBA-Creditanstalt, an investment bank in
Sao Paulo that has worked as an adviser on several takeovers in the
Brazilian supermarket sector. ``The fight to dominate retailing in
areas which are until today untouched by global players like
Carrefour should be a fierce one,'' de Souza said.
</P>
<P>
   A look at how the old Carrefour grew into the largest retailer
in Brazil and Argentina, South America's two largest economies,
provides some insight into how the new Carrefour might start to
flex its muscle in countries like Mexico, Chile and Colombia, where
other companies are leading supermarket retailers.
</P>
<P>
   In Brazil, Carrefour's influence comes from a string of
acquisitions of smaller chains in the last few years, giving it 13
percent of the retailing market. The buying binge, undaunted by an
economy that shrank in 1998 and is expected to register no growth
this year, has picked up pace only in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, for instance, Carrefour said it would buy three
supermarket chains that operate in Rio de Janeiro, some of them in
the city's gritty, working-class suburbs. The purchase comes after
similar acquisitions in places like Belo Horizonte, Brazil's
third-largest city, and in Brasilia, the capital. In fact,
Carrefour has sought opportunities far from Sao Paulo and Rio de
Janeiro, the two largest cities.
</P>
<P>
   In neighboring Argentina, Carrefour's share of the market should
be even larger than it is in Brazil, about 30 percent, after its
purchase of Promodes. This is because Carrefour's leading position
will be combined with Promodes' recent move into the country.
Earlier this year, Promodes bought a 49 percent stake in
Supermercados Norte, the country's third-largest supermarket chain,
and announced plans to buy a controlling stake by the end of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   Such expansion has not caught some of Latin America's more
nimble supermarket companies off guard. Companhia Brasileira de
Distribuicao Pao de Acucar, which competes with Carrefour for
customers in big cities, decided this month to sell a 26 percent
stake to Casino Guicard Perrachon S.A. of France in a transaction
that should provide the company with about $1 billion of cash to go
on its own acquisition spree.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the deal also benefits Casino, France's third-largest
retailer, which would like to complement the operations it already
has in Argentina, Colombia, Uruguay and the United States.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
