<SLUG> BC-TEN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: LIGHT-YEARS AND A BRIDGE OF SEPARATION  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Britain, The Netherlands)   By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The young ones are coming bigger, hitting harder,
learning faster. From one end of the summer to another, London to
New York, Mirjana Lucic schooled a former Harvard student on the
existential differences between plucky challengers and aspiring
champions, between opposite ends of the Whitestone Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Erika de Lone had pushed Lucic deep into a third Wimbledon set
just two months ago in the first round of the tall Croatian
teen-ager's run to her semifinal defeat by Steffi Graf. De Lone
returned home to her best tennis summer ever, to become authentic
queen of a gritty Bronx court. Then she walked onto Court 11 Monday
at the National Tennis Center, and it was all too clear that she
was in the wrong borough, half a foot smaller than her opponent, in
over her head at the U.S. Open. Against all reasonable laws of
main-draw probability, Lucic was waiting for de Lone again, more
poised, better prepared, still growing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing how much the tour has changed,'' de Lone said
after Lucic had hammered out a 6-3, 6-3 victory. ``When I first
came on eight years ago, it was pretty much Seles and Capriati. Now
you have so much depth, so many players, all these Europeans, so
many big, strong players who are really cracking the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   It can be enough to send a woman who stands under 5 feet 7
inches tall and weights 135 pounds to places where she can find
someone her own size, where Darwin doesn't always dole out the
prize money and computer ranking points. This is how 26-year-old
Erika de Lone of Lincoln, Mass., recently discovered another side
of the tennis city, how she came to conquer the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't luxury like this, what you get used to,'' she said,
making a sweeping gesture outside Court 11. ``But the fans came
out. The tennis was good.''
</P>
<P>
   Her pre-Open tuneup was the GHI Bronx Challenger, a satellite
event in what is the tennis equivalent of the minor leagues. The
site was Crotona Park, a short drive from the Third Avenue exit of
the Cross Bronx Expressway. Here there were no fancy food courts,
no parking lot full of luxury cars. The fans came in from the
neighborhood on foot, for free. The kids came from all over town,
courtesy of the New York Junior Tennis League. The players were
bused up from Manhattan, on a yellow school bus that de Lone didn't
have to ride because she'd brought her car.
</P>
<P>
   She found a room at the Roosevelt Hotel in Manhattan for $133, a
bargain compared to the $350 they wanted at the Parker-Meridian,
which refused to extend her the Open player rate until the Open
actually began. This is not a consideration for Venus Williams, but
de Lone had to hustle everywhere she could to earn $53,137 in 1998.
When Els Callens of the Netherlands retired from their Bronx
Challenger final, it was worth $8,800 to her 1999 bank account, and
a qualifier's place in the Open draw.
</P>
<P>
   She had nine break points Monday against Lucic and converted
none. The match came and went, like the smell of hamburger wafting
from close by. Still, it was the Open. It was another chance to
step into a fantasy before it slips through her fingers, like sand
at the beach. Her run from the Bronx was worth this one afternoon
in Queens, against a 17-year-old who is supposed to be going all
the places that Erika de Lone is not.
</P>
<P>
   She dropped out of Harvard after her freshman year, with the
support of her parents, who agreed that tennis was ``now or
never.'' Her older sister, Amy, played briefly on the tour. She has
a younger half sister and half brother who are nationally ranked
juniors. She's ``taking this where it goes,'' though to reach her
career-best ranking of 85, de Lone has had to win four Challenger
events this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm playing better than I ever have,'' she said, ``but the
players are so much stronger now, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The day she can't stand to wake up in a hotel room will be the
day she starts thinking about returning to Harvard, about an
economics degree. She realizes that day is coming, because more and
more, the early round opponents are 6-foot sluggers, whether they
are named Lucic or not.
</P>
<P>
   While de Lone told her story outside Court 11, Amelie Mauresmo
was powering forehands, impressively warming up for her first-round
match. Venus Williams was about to bring her special athleticism
into Arthur Ashe Stadium. Little sister Serena and Alexandra
Stevenson will be out there belting winners Tuesday night. It
doesn't take a Harvard study to recognize what is happening in
women's tennis, to know where the bridge to the future goes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
