<SLUG> BC-BBO-UMPS-COURT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UMPIRES' BID TO SAVE JOBS NEEDS HELP FROM COURT  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa.)   By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nearly reduced to grasping at flimsy foul lines, the umpires
union went to court again Monday in a late effort to save the jobs
of 22 major league umpires.
</P>
<P>
   Without waiting for a ruling from the National Labor Relations
Board, the union asked U.S. District Court in Philadelphia to issue
an injunction blocking the National and American leagues from
letting the umpires go after Wednesday's games.
</P>
<P>
   The union acted after the leagues rejected a request to retain
the umpires pending the outcome of a union grievance filed with the
American Arbitration Association last Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Richie Phillips, the union leader, did not return a telephone
call seeking comment on the union's action, but he clearly is
trying every conceivable avenue to rescue the umpires who are
losing their jobs as a result of his mass resignation strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips has spoken with Major League Baseball officials, the
union has filed unfair labor practice charges against the leagues
and now the union has gone to court a second time in five weeks.
But nothing has worked.
</P>
<P>
   The labor board's New York office is expected to rule on the
union's allegations before Thursday, but the decision most likely
will go against the union.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the union, which withdrew its first lawsuit three
weeks after it was filed, are expected to argue at a hearing
Tuesday before Judge Curtis Joyner that the umpires will suffer
irreparable harm if the leagues are allowed to accept their
resignations. Irreparable harm is one element that has to be
established for an injunction to be granted.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the leagues, however, are expected to argue that the
22 umpires will suffer no irreparable harm if they lose their jobs
Wednesday and the union subsequently prevails in court or the labor
board's proceedings. In that event, the lawyers will argue, the
umpires' jobs can be restored and back pay ordered.
</P>
<P>
   The union also said in its suit that if the injunction was
granted, neither the leagues nor baseball would suffer irreparable
harm.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit further contends that baseball and its integrity
will suffer harm if the leagues are permitted to proceed with their
plans.
</P>
<P>
   The union, maintaining that it is the umpires who protect the
integrity of the game, even invoked the view of former President
Nixon on that issue.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon said in his 1985 arbitration decision: ``The leagues
should recognize that umpires have a special relationship to the
game, which is different from that of players. Umpires should not
be treated as employees but as judges who are independent of both
players and owners and whose primary responsibility is to maintain
the integrity of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   On July 14, more than 50 umpires signed letters of resignation,
which were faxed to the league offices the next day. The leagues
subsequently hired 25 new umpires and accepted the resignations
nine American League umpires and 13 National League umpires. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
