<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEANING COWBOYS' IMAGE DOESN'T REQUIRE MORE SOAP OPERA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
FORT WORTH, Texas _ Going totally out of character, I'm refusing to
overreact after the latest episode of ``All My Cowboys.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   But who was originally driving that Suburban, anyway? Al
Cowlings?
</P>
<P>
   It has often been suggested the inhabitants of Valley Ranch long
ago reached soap-opera status. This is false. The soaps seek more
realism.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Jones arrested on a Sunday morning while on his way to
church? Yes, and Barry Switzer has been accepted to grad school at
MIT.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about another national embarrassment for the Cowboys
organization _ and no, I don't necessarily mean Jerry's arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Jones may have upgraded the team image by insisting
nothing delay his visit to a place of worship. In doing so, he had
to be bonded out of jail, but what was more shocking _ Jerry going
to church or being busted by the cops?
</P>
<P>
   If, however, Jerry stumbled into a `goodwill'' gesture for the
Cowboys, it was erased later Sunday evening when the Fox TV cameras
honed in for a sideline shot of Cowboys defensive tackle Nathan
Davis.
</P>
<P>
   This was a bit more than any of us needed to see. Davis stuck
out his tongue to reveal double stud piercings, matching twin
eyebrow piercings. Real class. The only thing Nathan didn't do was
drop his pants and display what else is rumored _ I stress rumored,
because I swear I haven't looked _ to be pierced.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Gailey, you might need to do something. A member of the
Cowboys could have been mistaken for a grunge band act on MTV. It's
harmless, except for the perception. But for the Cowboys, hasn't
perception become everything. Chan, it just didn't look
footballish.
</P>
<P>
   Again, however, there will be no personal overreaction, or
piercings. And that includes reaction to the results of an
exhibition game that was played Sunday night. Somehow, the game
became almost secondary to Jones' arrest, but since it was the best
Cowboys' preseason showing in several years, well...
</P>
<P>
   Place about the same amount of importance on the dismantling of
Denver as in the three previous misadventures of this month. The
one upside for the Cowboys is both teams used the game as a final
tuneup for the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   But the same suspects who did a full-tilt panic over the team's
poor play will now be glorifying the meaningless dominance of
Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, judge nothing on the field about the Cowboys until
Sept. 12 in Washington. The one and only verdict begins then, and
stretches through December.
</P>
<P>
   Off the field, however, what can happen next to the Cowboys?
Image disasters are nothing new, but how can this team possibly top
Jerry Jones being arrested on a Sunday morning while riding to
church?
</P>
<P>
   Even worse, I confess to actually being sympathetic toward Jones
in this particular case.
</P>
<P>
   With all due respect to the officer of the Highland Park Police
Department who made the original traffic stop, was all this
necessary?
</P>
<P>
   Jones released several statements Sunday night, and then didn't
want to discuss the situation yesterday. It has often been said
Jones is immune to public embarrassment, but apparently not this
time.
</P>
<P>
   What began as a private and joyful family event for Jones _ the
christening of a grandson _ ended up as another Jethro joke. The
usual national ridicule was heaped upon Jones, and in many past
incidents I've either joined in or led that parade.
</P>
<P>
   But this...
</P>
<P>
   Who knows, maybe Jerry tried to big-time the cop. Maybe he
became verbally pushy. Whatever, Jones had a valid reason for not
wanting to be late for this church service, and there were two
carloads of family with him.
</P>
<P>
   It does seem like the police could have cut him a break, but in
saying so, I have no idea what went on after the traffic stop.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, Jones has now done personal damage to his own
``clean up the Cowboys'' campaign. And much of that campaign has
centered around players and coaches never placing themselves in a
position to be arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Remember the college draft of 1998, when the Cowboys skipped a
particular player because they feared the possible image impact?
</P>
<P>
   Since coming into the NFL, however, Randy Moss has now been
arrested one less time _ meaning none _ than Jerry Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry, it doesn't matter why. Just go ahead and fine yourself
$50,000 and donate the money to a local charity. And for penance,
also have many body parts pierced. See Nathan Davis for references.
</P>
<P>
   There is no soap opera like this soap opera. Except this one
never seems real. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-99 2325EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
