<HEADER>
A5276 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-TEN-GOLDSTEIN-DRAPER-     08-30 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-GOLDSTEIN-DRAPER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO APOLOGIES NEEDED,   JUST COMFORTING WORDS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Scott Draper shuffled around the lines of Court 7
Monday, but he could not find solace in its boundaries. This was
not an escape but another dip into a tennis life that seems as
empty and as fragile as a soap bubble.
</P>
<P>
   A simpler life seems much more appealing to Draper now, just six
weeks after his wife, Kellie, died from cystic fibrosis.
</P>
<P>
   Once a steadily rising star in the world ranking, Draper, 25, is
wondering where he can find happiness. Right now, it is not on the
court.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of his 6-3, 6-1, 6-0 first-round loss to Paul
Goldstein at the U.S. Open, Draper resisted the impulse to walk out
on his first-round match.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a struggle,'' Draper said. ``But that would have been
weak and unnecessary.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet understandable, too. You could see his mind drifting with
every stroke. His forehands landed like darts flung wide of the
board, and simple volleys crashed into the net. At the end,
Goldstein hardly felt like celebrating a match point against an
opponent going through so much.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you go out there, you just play every point and put your
head down after every point,'' said Goldstein, a 23-year-old
Stanford graduate whose ranking has risen from No. 189 to No. 80
this year. ``It's a match you play with a heavy heart because you
feel for Scotty and because he's really one of the most well-liked
and most well-respected people on the tour.''
</P>
<P>
   Draper respects the game, too. Maybe he could not have beaten
Goldstein _ a bright young player coming off a gold-medal
performance at the Pan American Games _ but Draper wanted to give
him a tougher match, wanted to prepare him for the Open
competition. But as the two met at the net, they lingered for a
while as Draper put his arm around Goldstein and apologized.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came up and said: `Mate' _ in typical Scott Draper fashion
_ `Mate, it was nothing against you. My head wasn't into it
today,''' Goldstein said. ``He started the conversation before I
could say anything. I said: `I don't take it bad at all. You're
class.' I said to him, `I admire you for being out here.'''
</P>
<P>
   Draper has been a familiar face on the tour since 1993. But he
is not like a lot of the other players. Although his ranking was up
to No. 51 in 1998 before tumbling to No. 151 during a difficult
season this year, Draper never enjoyed the sport's fast track.
</P>
<P>
   There were too many moments at home lost to the travel, too many
times when he felt the lifestyle promoted selfishness and
indifference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need time to figure out if this is what I want to do for the
next five, six, seven years,'' Draper said. ``Like right now, yes,
I could walk away and say, `I've had enough.' But that would be a
stupid decision because in six or seven or 12 months' time, that
urge, that feeling of wanting to compete may come back. I'm not
making any decisions right now because they're just clouded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess what I'm saying, if I found a job right now at home
that paid pretty well and I enjoyed it, it sounds good. But tennis
is a great sport. It brings a lot of great things, but it may not
bring happiness.''
</P>
<P>
   He had that with Kellie. The disease did not stop him from
falling in love, proposing and embracing the 19 months he was given
as her husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the person you're marrying, the person you love,'' Draper
said. ``I think the quality of time you spend with somebody is more
important than anything else. She was still the same person
regardless of whatever problems she had. I'd do it all over
again.''
</P>
<P>
   While it has helped the grieving process to be around some of
his friends on the tour this week, he is not sure he wants this
life anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe in my thought process right now,'' Draper
said. ``It's just all over the place. That just takes time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
