<HEADER>
A5278 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-BOATERS-FOUND31-COX     08-30 1181
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOATERS-FOUND31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Lost' boaters didn't fear for their safety
 &HT;    By Angela Townsend
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Richard Stewart's desire to sail his 65-foot
sailboat through the stormy Atlantic and back to shore safely was
the uppermost goal in his mind.
</P>
<P>
   After managing to bring the Jolly Joyce close enough to land
Saturday night to allow Stewart and his family to use their
cellular phone, it was then that they called home to Ludlow Falls.
They hadn't checked in since July 26.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Stewart was beginning to sense what that connection to
his daughter, Beth, would mean to him, his wife Debra, 47, their
children Chad, 16, and Mischa, 12, and the family pets _ a mixed
breed dog named JJ and a calico named Hannah.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never had any consideration of the boat sinking or anything
like that,'' Richard Stewart said Monday from the Jolly Joyce,
which for now is docked at Ocean City Fisherman's Marina at Ocean
City, Md. ``We've got to do some repairs to the boat before we can
go anywhere,'' he said. ``No, I wasn't really worried about losing
the boat.''
</P>
<P>
   He also wasn't worried about being lost, because that phone call
to Beth was the first time Richard Stewart found out that he and
his family had been classified as ``missing.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Coast Guard, which had been searching for the Jolly
Joyce since Aug. 16, got wind of that Saturday night phone call
from Beth. Sunday, the Coast Guard towed the boat to the marina.
</P>
<P>
   It was Aug. 15 when a family friend, Mike Candella, called the
Coast Guard to report that the Stewart family was missing.
</P>
<P>
   The Stewarts, who had been living in Fort Lauderdale, Fla., on
their boat intermittently since November, were last seen July 23 in
Newport, R.I. They had docked there for more than a month after
having engine trouble. Relatives last heard from them on July 26.
Harbor authorities in Rhode Island recorded the family's actual
departure Aug. 2.
</P>
<P>
   By Aug. 17, the Coast Guard had launched two C-130 planes to
scour the Eastern seaboard for the Jolly Joyce.
</P>
<P>
   By Aug. 23, the Coast Guard had suspended its search but had
used substantial resources:
</P>
<P>
   _ Two C-130 planes were flown for slightly more than 13 hours at
a cost of $4,081 per hour.
</P>
<P>
   _ The HU-25 falcon jet launched from Cape Cod, Mass., was flown
for one, six-hour mission at a cost of $3,700 per hour, according
to Coast Guard Lt. Cmdr. John Fitzgerald.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of the planes alone _ more than $75,000 for three days'
use _ and other costs incurred will not be passed on to the
Stewarts, the Coast Guard said. Reimbursements happen only when the
Coast Guard responds to hoax calls, determined as such after an
investigation by the Department of Interior.
</P>
<P>
   By Monday afternoon, the Stewarts had spoken to Beth; Debra
Stewart's mother, Joyce McManus; and Candella.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're kind of peeved,'' Richard Stewart said of them
and other family members who for weeks anxiously awaited word about
the Jolly Joyce.
</P>
<P>
   But now the questions begin.
</P>
<P>
   How could the Stewarts not have known about the six-day, 85,000
nautical square mile search for the Jolly Joyce? Were they lost or
simply out of touch? Why didn't they call family sooner?
</P>
<P>
   Stewart said he was never seriously worried about their safety.
After all, they had a 30-day supply of food and water and plenty of
emergency supplies, he said. Food, however, was running out.
</P>
<P>
   Until their first venture into Ocean City to stock up on
groceries, the family's food supply included a few packages of
noodles, some cans of tuna fish and corned beef, bread, juice and
water, Debra Stewart said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were getting down pretty sparse,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   When the Stewarts left Rhode Island, they planned to sail
directly south to Cape Hatteras, N.C., on the way back to Fort
Lauderdale for boat repairs. While attempting to sail along the
outside of Cape Hatteras, the Jolly Joyce ran into a storm on Aug.
6.
</P>
<P>
   ``The storm knocked us 30 miles further east, and then back
north,'' Stewart said. By the time they recovered from that storm,
they drifted another 15 miles east and hit another storm Aug. 7.
The Jolly Joyce lost its mizzenmast (the back sail) and mainsail.
</P>
<P>
   Ten days later, a hydraulic leak caused them to lose steering.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 18, the Stewarts began drifting east in the Gulf Stream
and made some repairs to the sails and the steering.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 22 while heading to Cape Henry, Va., they saw some
merchant vessels but couldn't communicate with them because of weak
radio signals.
</P>
<P>
   The winds were not kind, Stewart said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd gain 10 miles west, then end up going the opposite
direction,'' he said. ``Over the course of the time we were out
there, we slotted several different courses to go because of the
wind,'' Stewart said.
</P>
<P>
   At one point they were within 300 miles of Bermuda, he said.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, after spending more than two hours locating the the
Stewarts, the Coast Guard used a 47-foot motor lifeboat to tow the
Jolly Joyce. By then the Jolly Joyce had lost all steering and the
use of its engines.
</P>
<P>
   The Coast Guard had asked the family to call them every 30
minutes during the day Sunday until they could find them; Richard
Stewart, however, was determined to come in on his own power.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd gone 900 miles on our own. If we would get to shore we're
gonna do it on our own,'' his wife quoted him as saying.
</P>
<P>
   The Coast Guard is now conducting a ``survivor debriefing,''
standard operating procedure in a successful search and rescue
case, Fitzgerald said. The debriefing includes interviews with the
family and the compilation of additional data.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next couple of weeks the Coast Guard will review copies
of Stewart's logs to compare the Jolly Joyce trip with the Coast
Guard's search patterns.
</P>
<P>
   Fitzgerald conceded its two-week involvement with the search for
the Jolly Joyce departs from Coast Guard norms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Typically we will search until we're pretty certain that we've
exhausted all possibilities,'' Fitzgerald said. ``Obviously this is
a wonderful thing. The most obvious lesson that anyone can learn
from this is that people have to file a float plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Had the Stewarts done that, the Coast Guard may have found them
sooner, Fitzgerald said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were lucky. Almost 30 days at sea is a long time,''
Fitzgerald said. ``Had they incurred a little more trouble and been
delayed in going back to shore, they would have been affected by
the hurricane (Dennis). Who knows what would have happened then.''
</P>
<P>
   Son Carter Stewart, 27, the family's unofficial spokesman, on
Monday expressed his relief that the Jolly Joyce had been located.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The Coast Guard) was absolutely fabulous and professional,''
he said. ``We're very relieved to know that this potentially tragic
story has a happy ending.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter Stewart deferred all other comments about the matter to
his father and stepmother, but not before adding, ``This is their
drama, let them act in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
