<HEADER>
A5281 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-RUN-MITCHELL-2TAKES-N     08-30 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-MITCHELL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TRACK STAR'S BURDEN 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Fla.) (jt) 
 By JAMES C. McKINLEY JR.    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAINESVILLE, Fla. _ When the world's best sprinters met in
Seville, Spain, last week to test the limits of human speed, Dennis
Mitchell was not among them. The veteran American sprinter instead
worked out at the University of Florida track, helping younger
athletes with their running technique while keeping an eye on his
two small children.
</P>
<P>
   But his mind, and part of his heart, were two thousand miles
away at the world track and field championships, where he had hoped
to at last win a gold medal and break his personal record in the
100 meters.
</P>
<P>
   That hope was destroyed in August, when a three-member panel
from the International Amateur Athletic Federation, the sport's
international governing body, suspended Mitchell for two years. The
arbitrators ruled that a test of Mitchell's urine had proved he was
taking banned steroids, even though a United States panel had
cleared him of the same charge in December. His ban will end on
April 1, 2000, two years after the positive test.
</P>
<P>
   The world championships ended on Sunday, but for Mitchell the
distress continues. For years he had spoken out against doping in
track and field and was seen as a role model by many younger
athletes. At 33, he has only a few more years of competition left.
His reputation is hopelessly tarnished, he says. His livelihood,
which he said brought him a half-million dollars a year, has been
temporarily taken from him. And he angrily maintains, as he has all
along, that there is a natural explanation for the test results.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing else for me to do except accept this thing,''
he said, looking wistfully down at the track. ``I feel terribly
wronged. I feel like this sport owed me more than this.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell, a four-time national champion who has competed in
three Olympics, is one of several athletes suspended recently not
because banned substances were found in their bodies, but because
the ratio of various hormones in their urine was so unusual that
the International Amateur Athletic Federation ruled it could only
have been caused by taking illicit steroids.
</P>
<P>
   Once a Positive Test, A Presumption of Guilt
</P>
<P>
   Whether Mitchell is telling the truth, his case illustrates the
difficulties inherent in trying to catch athletes who ingest
hormones already found naturally in the body. It also raises
troubling questions about how the sport's main governing body
adjudicates such cases. Athletes going before IAAF arbitrators must
do more than simply create a reasonable doubt about the evidence
against them. They are presumed to be guilty unless they can prove
that the hormonal imbalance in their bodies has a natural cause, a
nearly impossible burden, lawyers say, since there is little
research on the subject outside of studies done by the very same
laboratories testing the athletes.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell's case may also reflect another problem: the growing
use among top athletes of unregulated dietary supplements, from
amino acids to plant sterols, bought over the counter in
health-food stores. The effect of these supplements on the body are
largely a matter of conjecture, scientists say. What's worse, some
products have been found to be mislabeled.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are hundreds of different things sold in food-supplement
stores,'' Dr. Don H. Catlin, who operates the Olympic drug-testing
laboratory at the University of California at Los Angeles and is a
member of the International Olympic Committee's medical committee
on doping. ``Many of them have amino acids on the label, but this
is not a regulated industry, so it's buyer beware.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many modern sprinters, Mitchell's cupboard looks like a
new-age apothecary shop. There are bottles of Symbiotropin,
Triboxin, arginine, glutamine, B-complex, Creotine Xtreme and whey
protein.
</P>
<P>
   But while Mitchell admits he has experimented with these
supplements to try to keep his strength from declining with age, he
does not think he took a banned substance by accident. Instead, he
has argued at his hearings, the testosterone level found in his
urine resulted from two stressful nights without sleep, including a
night of drinking and lovemaking to celebrate his fiancee's
birthday, coupled with the effect of amino acids he was taking to
shore up his aging muscles. The acids _ arginine and glutamine _
might have stimulated his adrenal gland to produce more
testosterone than normal, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My testosterone level rose naturally,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the case is a test that Olympic drug-testing
laboratories have used since 1983 to catch athletes who are taking
testosterone and other steroids that allow their bodies to put on
extra muscle during training, scientists say.
</P>
<P>
   The test measures the ratio between two hormones excreted in the
urine in a metabolized form _ testosterone and epitestosterone,
scientists say. When testosterone, or another anabolic steroid
closely related to it, is taken as a supplement, the production of
epitestosterone is suppressed and the gap between the two hormones
in the urine widens.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last two decades, Olympic labs have tested tens of
thousands of athletes. Those results show 90 percent of athletes
have a ratio of about 1-to-1 and that more than 99 percent fall
under 5-to-1. Only one in every 2,000 athletes has a naturally
elevated level, and those tend to remain constant.
</P>
<P>
   In 1983, officials at the International Olympic Committee set a
limit of 6-to-1 as the acceptable upper ratio. Even that limit left
room for cheating, scientists say, since most people have much
lower ratios. Anything above that level was deemed to be evidence
of taking steroids, unless the athlete had a history of elevated
testosterone, scientists at several Olympic labs said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Six was the speed limit,'' Catlin explained.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Violating The Speed Limit
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell was tested on April 1, 1998, when lab technicians hired
by the IAAF showed up without warning at the track in Gainesville
to conduct a urine test.
</P>
<P>
   Unannounced tests have been routine since 1996 to fight a
widespread perception of cheating. Before that, athletes were
tested only during competitions, and some athletes beat the testers
with gels, creams, patches and injections that deliver drugs
quickly flushed from the system.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell's urine was sent to a Montreal laboratory accredited by
the International Olympic Committee, where scientists found it
contained a testosterone-to-epitestosterone ratio of 7.3-to-1. He
had been tested 21 times before and had never had a ratio above
2.2-to-1, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell was not told about the test results until three months
later, at a meet in Norway on July 8. He was stunned. He rushed
home and had a battery of blood tests by an independent doctor to
prove he was clean. ``I turned myself inside out for them,'' he
said. It was to no avail. Just after the Goodwill Games in August,
officials from USA Track and Field informed him he had been
suspended.
</P>
<P>
   But at a hearing in December, Mitchell mounted a surprisingly
formidable defense, calling Wylie C. Hembree, a respected
endocrinologist from Columbia University, as a witness.
</P>
<P>
   Hembree testified that the elevated testosterone level might
well have been caused by Mitchell's sleepless weekend, coupled with
drinking alcohol and the effect of other dietary supplements he was
taking.
</P>
<P>
   Two nights before the test, Mitchell had driven for 10 hours
from a meet in Raleigh, N.C., to Florida, pushing on through the
night and arriving home late in the morning. He then went to the
track after two hours' sleep and worked out. That night, instead of
sleeping, he had stayed up until dawn for a second night with his
fiancee to celebrate her birthday, drinking eight beers and having
sex several times, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Hembree said that sleep deprivation causes the
adrenal gland to work overtime, pumping out three times more
cortisone and other hormones than normal. The gland produces only a
small amount of testosterone, but it produces other hormones that
can be quickly converted to testosterone in the bodies tissues,
thus boosting the amount of metabolized testosterone in the urine,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Hembree pointed out that alcohol has been shown to
increase testosterone levels, since the enzymes that usually break
down testosterone are kept busy attacking the alcohol molecules.
Studies at Olympic labs have also shown moderate increases in the
testosterone level in men's urine after heavy drinking and fairly
large increases among female athletes, scientists at three labs
said.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Hembree pointed out that the amino acids Mitchell had
been taking can cause the body to produce more human growth
hormone, which in turn would have stimulated the adrenal gland to
secrete even more products that could increase the amount of
metabolized testosterone in the urine. ``It was highly likely that
was the explanation,'' Hembree said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   But testing experts from Olympic labs argued there were no
scientific studies that specifically proved Hembree's theory. They
noted that in addition to the high ratio, Mitchell also had twice
as much testosterone in his urine as his past tests had shown _
about 300 nanograms per milliliter. Christiane Ayotte, who heads
the University of Quebec lab that did the test, said the only
possible explanation was that he took steroids. ``I am 100 percent
convinced that this elevated ratio was not attributable to natural
factors,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The American panel _ composed of two lawyers and an athlete _
disagreed. They ruled that Mitchell had created enough doubt about
the validity of the test to be exonerated. The IAAF appealed the
decision to arbitrators at the organization's headquarters in Monte
Carlo, Monaco.
</P>
<P>
   It was not the first time an American panel had questioned the
world body's tests. Another U.S. panel had cleared Mary Decker
Slaney, the former world champion distance runner, in 1997 after
her lawyers presented evidence that the testosterone ratio in women
could rise dramatically because of birth control pills and
menopausal changes.
</P>
<P>
   But earlier this year both rulings were overruled by panels of
arbitrators in Monte Carlo. In both cases, the IAAF officials ruled
that the prosecution had proved a doping violation ``beyond a
reasonable doubt'' simply by showing the athlete had a
testosterone-to-epitestosterone ratio and raw testosterone level
far above the athlete's previous test results.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Arne Ljungqvist, the chairman of the IAAF medical
commission, said sports officials have so much confidence in the
testing method that it is up to the athletes to provide scientific
evidence of their claims. He noted the 25 labs employed by the
International Olympic Committee draw their conclusions from more
than 100,000 tests each year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are enough data available to show that cases like the
one we are talking about have been the result of the ingestion of a
banned substance,'' he said. ``It is not for us to prove that they
are wrong, because they can come up with any claim. It is for them
to prove that they are right. And they couldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Olympic Labs' Studies Are Questioned
</P>
<P>
   But some critics have questioned the studies done by Olympic
labs because they often do not include control groups to compare
against the athletes. No one has ever studied, for instance, the
effect of sleep deprivation on the testosterone-to-epitestosterone
ratio, Hembree said.
</P>
<P>
   In Mitchell's eyes, the hearing was a farce. He said the IAAF
panel sacrificed him because it did not want to not set a precedent
that dietary supplements and sleep deprivation may skew the test
results.
</P>
<P>
   The rulings at the international body have also infuriated U.S.
track officials, who are questioning why they should go to the
expense of holding hearings if the decisions of their panels are
ignored by the IAAF. Some have even argued an independent
arbitration court relying on outside labs should be set up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's go to a system where any doping case in the world is
adjudicated in exactly the same way, with a hearing and an appeals
process, that are external to any sports organization,'' Craig
Masback, the chief executive officer of USA Track and Field, said
this week in Seville.
</P>
<P>
   For Mitchell, the bottom line is that he did not run the 100
meters in Seville this year, though he will be allowed to compete
in next year's Olympics in Sydney, Australia. The loss is still
significant, he said. He had hoped to break his personal record of
9.91, set in 1991, and his times had been coming down this fall.
His career has been notable: He was the 100-meter bronze medalist
in the 1992 Olympics and part of two teams that share the world
record for the 400-meter relay. Still, he had harbored hopes of
someday winning a world championship. And he still dreams of
running a 9.8 before his career is finished. Those hopes are now
dimming rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two years they were trying to take away from me were the
only two years I wanted,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
