<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-30 23:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5285 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT-EMAIL-BREAC     08-30 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-EMAIL-BREACH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT SHUTS SECURITY BREACH IN E-MAIL SYSTEM
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By   SARA ROBINSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Microsoft Corp. scrambled Monday to close a
security breach that had left tens of millions of personal e-mail
accounts freely accessible through Web sites that were created to
exploit the vulnerability.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear how much private information might have been
compromised and for what length of time. And while Microsoft said
it had solved the problem, after shutting down the service for
several hours, it was not clear whether other vulnerabilities in
the e-mail service, known as Hotmail, might still exist.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't go into specifics'' about Hotmail security issues
``because we don't want to enable people to do this all the time,''
said Rob Bennett, director of marketing for MSN, Microsoft's online
division, which includes Hotmail.
</P>
<P>
   Hotmail is a free service that allows any Internet user to
create an account and send and receive e-mail from any location
with Internet access. Microsoft says 40 million people worldwide
have signed up for the service, but it is not clear how many use
it.
</P>
<P>
   Although it was clear from messages circulating on the Internet
on Monday that unauthorized users had gained access to e-mail
accounts, Microsoft said it had received no reports of tampering
with e-mail content.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft said it was alerted to the problem at 2 a.m., Pacific
time, by a Swedish newspaper that ran an article about it.
</P>
<P>
   The company responded by immediately shutting down the Hotmail
service. Microsoft said it restored service after about eight
hours, but a cat-and-mouse game ensued as new instructions were
circulated on the Internet routing would-be intruders around the
initial fix and Microsoft scrambled to block them.
</P>
<P>
   By 2 p.m., Pacific time, Bennett declared the problem solved.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going manually now from server to server to make sure
the fix has been propagated, but we're quite confident that it has
been,'' he said. The HotMail servers, the computers that operate
the service, are scattered around the world, but the ones initially
attacked were in San Jose, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Smith, a computer security expert, said the program that
allowed illicit access to Hotmail appeared to be derived from the
work of a programmer named Michael Nobilio, whose Internet postings
say the software was intended to allow users to store their Hotmail
login information as a convenience so it would not have to be
entered each time they used the service. Nobilio made his program
available through an Internet discussion group in June 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But what was apparently intended to be innocent code could be
manipulated to allow people to gain access to Hotmail accounts
without a password, so long as they knew the user's e-mail address.
The code has been posted on at least 20 sites scattered around the
Internet, probably for months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Enjoy, and I hope other folks find it as useful as I have!''
he said in one Internet posting.
</P>
<P>
   In an e-mail exchange Monday with Smith, president of Phar Lap
Software in Cambridge, Mass., Nobilio said he knew nothing of the
Hotmail vulnerability and had not intended for his program to be
used maliciously.
</P>
<P>
   MSNBC.com, an Internet news service in which Microsoft is a
partner, quoted Jon Thompson, administrator of one of the Web sites
that posted instructions on exploiting the Hotmail flaw, as saying
that associates had known about the vulnerability of Hotmail
accounts for about eight weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Christian Carrwik, the reporter who wrote for the Swedish
newspaper Expressen, said he was tipped off to the vulnerability by
a hacker over the weekend, and was told that a member of the
computer underground discovered the hole late last week, MSNBC.com
reported.
</P>
<P>
   The episode was one of several recently in which the security of
Microsoft software was found to be compromised. A flaw affecting
the Office 97 and Office 2000 programs allowed a user's data,
software or hardware to be damaged via e-mail or commands sent from
a malicious Web site. The company also said this month that it was
repairing a bug in its new Internet chat software, MSN Messenger,
that could allow anyone with access to an individual's computer to
see that person's Hotmail password.
</P>
<P>
   The incident raised eyebrows among the community of well-meaning
hackers who probe software for security flaws but immediately
report them to the vendor. Bennett said that whoever made the
Hotmail vulnerability known on the Internet had not reported it to
Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a good relationship with white-hat hackers,'' he said.
``It's unfortunate that the person or people responsible chose to
put people's privacy at risk in such a public way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
