<SLUG> BC-BKL-LIBERTY-STING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK LIBERTY DEFEAT CHARLOTTE STING 69-54  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.C., Texas, Calif.)   By STEVE POPPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The celebration started early Monday night, the crowd
realizing from the opening minutes what became a reality to the
Charlotte Sting in the final minutes. In the final minute, after a
steal and a foul stopped the clock, Teresa Weatherspoon finally let
loose, whirling her arms at the crowd or the sky and then hopping
frantically into the air.
</P>
<P>
   There was no need to get the crowd of 12,929 at Madison Square
Garden out of its seats. The emotional outpouring was for herself,
celebrating the Liberty's 69-54 victory in Game 3 of the
best-of-3-game Eastern Conference finals and releasing a season of
waiting for a chance that the Liberty now possess, heading to the
Women's National Basketball Association championship series
beginning on Thursday night in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberty, which missed the playoffs on the final game of the
regular season last year, will face the winner of the Western
Conference finals series between the Houston Comets and the Los
Angeles Sparks that was played Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   As the Sting slumped off the floor, the Liberty celebrated
wildly, with Weatherspoon racing to every corner of the floor, then
hopping onto the press table, as rookie Tamika Whitmore danced into
the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberty had earned the home-court advantage in the Eastern
Conference finals with its first-place finish in the regular
season, an advantage that seemed precariously close to going to
waste after the Liberty lost Game 1 in Charlotte. But after
surviving Game 2, it never trailed once in this game.
</P>
<P>
   By the time that the final minutes arrived Monday night, a
celebration followed almost every basket, whether it was a
fist-pump by Weatherspoon, the hand thrust in the air by Vickie
Johnson after a jumper, or a taunting glare by Whitmore when the
dagger had been twisted in the Sting for good.
</P>
<P>
   But this time the Liberty knew that there would be no comebacks,
no furious rushes to the finish. The only drama down the stretch
was whether the Liberty could contain itself until the final buzzer
sounded. Weatherspoon assured that by spearheading a defensive
effort that would be the envy of the Liberty's Garden-mates, the
Knicks, and by handing out 11 assists as she controlled the tempo,
keeping the Liberty from squandering any of its lead.
</P>
<P>
   For the third consecutive game, the Liberty controlled play for
most of the first half, building leads of as large as 11 points and
never trailing in the opening 20 minutes. But after seeing that
lead evaporate in a Game 1 loss and then disappear in Game 2 before
the Liberty was able to regroup in the final minutes, New York was
well aware it was in for a fight in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   While the two sides nearly did come to an actual fight on the
floor, something that would have come as little surprise with the
constant trash-talk on the floor and in the locker rooms, the fight
that the Liberty displayed was the sort that drove the Madison
Square Garden crowd into a frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   Leading by 40-34 on a pair of 3-point field goals by Crystal
Robinson, who had a team-high 18 points, in the opening minutes of
the second half, the Liberty seemingly opened the door as Robinson
turned the ball over. But as Andrea Stinson, who had a game-high 24
points, raced the other way, Robinson chased her down from behind.
She caught her, deflected the ball into the stands and then bounded
into the seats behind the basket herself.
</P>
<P>
   If the hustle sparked the crowd, it also provided a lift to the
Liberty, which responded on the other end. With the Sting unable to
score when it inbounded the ball, Johnson buried a 3-point field
goal, starting a stretch in which the Liberty opened the lead back
up to 56-43 with just over seven minutes to play, prompting a
celebration that had even the front-row observer Dick Vitale
dancing on the floor. After the timeout, the Liberty continued to
build on the lead, capping out at 60-43 on a jumper by Kym Hampton.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton, again playing with the fear that the game might be her
last with retirement awaiting at season's end, played a steady
first half Monday night after a manic second half on Sunday. She
finished the first half with six points and eight rebounds, helping
the Liberty to a 32-26 advantage.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
