<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-RAINES </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN EMPTY BOX OVERFLOWS WITH AFFECTION FOR TIM RAINES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
 - NYT  
 (ATTN: Calif., Canada, Ore.)   By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Tim Raines of the Oakland Athletics was the center of
attention in the Yankees' clubhouse Monday night before the game.
He was standing in the middle of the room, engulfed by the opposing
team.
</P>
<P>
   Raines spent almost an hour with his former Yankee teammates,
catching up on news, teasing them, laughing with them.
</P>
<P>
   Bernie Williams gave him a bearhug. It was a powerful reminder
of how popular Raines was during his three-year stay in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Raines was at Yankee Stadium Monday night for an on-field
ceremony during which he was presented with his 1998 World Series
championship ring. It was Raines' first time in New York since the
victory parade in Manhattan last October.
</P>
<P>
   It was also the first time Raines had traveled with the A's
since he learned last month that he had lupus, an incurable but
treatable connective tissue disease in which the immune system
turns against the body.
</P>
<P>
   The switch-hitting outfielder, who turns 40 on Sept. 16, won't
play again this season, but he vowed Monday night to be ready for
spring training.
</P>
<P>
   During the emotion-charged ceremony, Raines went from the
Oakland dugout to home plate, where he was met by manager Joe
Torre, who handed him a box that had no ring in it. The entire
Yankee team then gathered around Raines, and Williams presented him
the ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was emotional,'' Raines said before the game. ``I haven't
seen those guys in a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to play. I know that. I could probably play five or
six more years. I feel like a rookie. Who knows, maybe I could play
another 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Raines said he was feeling better than he had in months. Three
weeks ago, when the Yankees were in Oakland, he was too weak to
make the short drive to visit his former teammates at the park.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the swelling and the weight he gained from the illness
are gone, although, at one point Monday he pulled up his jeans and
showed David Cone how his ankles were still thicker than usual.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looks good,'' Torre said. ``He says he feels great. If
there's one person we miss, not for his at-bats but for his
presence, it's Rock. You remember his infectious laugh. He's a good
guy with great leadership qualities.''
</P>
<P>
   For most of his career, Raines, who carried a .296 batting
average into this season, was an outstanding leadoff batter and
base stealer. But his role as a Yankee was more pronounced in the
clubhouse than on the field. He was the joker, the guy with the
high-pitched cackle who always seemed to keep things loose. He was
even able to get a smile out of the combustible Paul O'Neill.
</P>
<P>
   ``We miss him around here,'' Derek Jeter said. ``What can I say?
He was a great teammate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey Rock, come over here,'' Jeter yelled moments later. ``Hey
Rock, come on, you old man.''
</P>
<P>
   Raines said that winning the championships with the Yankees in
1996 and 1998 were the highlights of his career, which began in
Montreal in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the greatest feeling I've ever had in my life,'' he
said. ``For years I watched Michael Jordan win championship after
championship and wondered what it felt like to put on one of those
rings. Now I've had that feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Raines is undergoing intensive treatment for lupus. His friend
and lawyer, Randy Grossman, said the disease, which Raines might
have had for years before the diagnosis, could have contributed to
the injuries that forced Raines to miss considerable time as a
Yankee with hamstring and knee ailments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who knows Tim knows that he was never one to make
excuses,'' Grossman said. ``But lupus may have very well affected
his hamstrings.''
</P>
<P>
   With this season over for Raines, he is focusing on preparing
for next year. Nine years after Ken Griffey Jr. and Sr. became the
first father-son teammates to play in a game, Raines said that his
dream is to be able to hang around long enough to play with his
oldest son, Tim Jr., who was Baltimore's sixth-round pick last year
and is working his way through the ranks.
</P>
<P>
   ``That the one thing I want to do,'' Raines said. `` I want to
do the Griffey thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-99 2356EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
